<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO TESTIFY IN LEWINSKY INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout; adds statement by White House press
secretary Mike McCurry in 12th graf.) (Eds.: See also CLINTON-TRIPP, CLINTON-MOOD,
CLINTON-TALKINGPOINTS) 
(ART ADV: Photos of Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton agreed on Wednesday to submit to
questioning at the White House by federal prosecutors in the
Lewinsky investigation after the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, withdrew an unprecedented subpoena to compel his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be permitted the unusual courtesy of having his
lawyers at his side, unlike other grand jury witnesses, when he
gives his videotaped testimony on the agreed-upon date of Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was willing to agree to many of Clinton's conditions in
exchange for the president's decision not to challenge the subpoena
on constitutional grounds and further delay the lengthy
investigation, lawyers said. Clinton will be the first sitting
president to testify under oath in a grand jury investigation in
which he is a potential target.
</P>
<P>
   As the arrangement to secure Clinton's testimony was announced,
new details emerged about the testimony and evidence that Monica
Lewinsky is prepared to provide to grand jurors under the broad
immunity deal she reached with prosecutors on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky met with prosecutors on Wednesday and turned over
evidence, including a dress as well as several taped phone messages
from Clinton, lawyers familiar with Ms. Lewinsky's case said. They
said that the dress had been sought under subpoena since late last
year and that Ms. Lewinsky had shipped it to her mother for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   The dress became a bargaining chip used by prosecutors to wield
pressure against Ms. Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, and
ultimately was part of the reason Ms. Lewis was granted immunity
along with her daughter, lawyers familiar with the immunity
agreement said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with Ms. Lewinsky's account said that the
25-year-old former White House intern told prosecutors on Monday
that she had expressed concern to Clinton in December about a
number of gifts he had given her, including a T-shirt, a brooch and
a hat pin, that had been subpoenaed by lawyers in the sexual
misconduct case brought by Paula Jones against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky said that the president had made the hypothetical
suggestion to her that ``If you don't have them you can't turn them
over'' to Ms. Jones' lawyers, lawyers familiar with her immunity
deal said. Clinton's personal secretary, Betty Currie, retrieved
the gifts and gave them to investigators in January, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   That account closely tracks with Ms. Lewinsky's original
proposed testimony, or ``proffer,'' given to investigators last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's agreement to testify allows him to avoid the
humiliating spectacle of being led under subpoena into a federal
courthouse to appear personally before the 23-member grand jury and
becoming the first president to be compelled to do so. But it gives
Starr something important as well _ the chance to confront the
president in person and question him extensively on matters ranging
from his relationship to Ms. Lewinsky to alleged efforts to buy her
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has now secured the testimony of the two central and final
witnesses in the Lewinsky inquiry, after Ms. Lewinsky accepted an
immunity agreement that requires her to provide ``full and
truthful'' testimony about her relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, said that Clinton
did not intend to alter his earlier statements about the Lewinsky
matter. The president in January emphatically denied a sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and said he did not tell her or
anyone else to lie.
</P>
<P>
   The president's account was contradicted this week by Ms.
Lewinsky, who told prosecutors that she and Clinton did have a
sexual relationship and they agreed to deny it, according to
lawyers. They discussed hypothetical explanations to try to keep it
private, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   In turning over evidence on Wednesday, Ms. Lewinsky also
provided several taped messages left for her by the president on
her answering machine at her apartment at the Watergate, lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky scheduled to tell their stories in
the next few weeks, the independent counsel will soon have the
final pieces of a complex mosaic that may or may not constitute
crimes or impeachable offenses. Starr is expected to quickly
conclude the Lewinsky investigation and prepare a report on his
findings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor has said he was investigating possible charges of
perjury, witness tampering and obstruction of justice arising from
accusations that Clinton carried on a sexual relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky and directed a conspiracy to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal lawyer, David Kendall, announced the
arrangement for the president's testimony in a brief statement in
the White House driveway on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to achieve a prompt resolution of this entire
matter,'' Kendall said, ``the president will voluntarily provide
his testimony on Aug. 17, 1998, to the office of independent
counsel as he has on prior occasions. The president's testimony
will be videotaped at the White House with lawyers present. No
further statement will be issued.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough in a week of negotiations over Clinton's
testimony came Tuesday, when Starr agreed to withdraw the subpoena
that he issued on July 17, allowing Kendall to characterize the
President's prospective testimony as ``voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials acknowledged for the first time on
Wednesday that a subpoena had in fact been issued and served on
Kendall last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, had sought to delay the testimony until late September,
but the federal judge supervising the case, Norma Holloway Johnson,
admonished both sides to schedule it sooner.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the response to the subpoena was the subject of intense
debate within the White House and among the president's official
and private lawyers. Several of the president's political and media
advisers wanted Clinton to comply quickly to avoid the appearance
of stonewalling, but some members of the president's legal team
believed the subpoena was unenforceable and an affront to the
presidency and urged the president to resist it.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Clinton decided to make himself available for
questioning, but only under favorable conditions and not under
compulsion of a subpoena. In another of the odd twists that have
marked this investigation since it began in January, Linda Tripp
emerged from the federal courthouse 10 blocks from the White House
a few minutes after Kendall spoke and read a statement of her own.
She had just completed her eighth and final day before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp brought her former friend, Ms. Lewinsky, to the
attention of Starr's office on Jan. 12, saying that Ms. Lewinsky
had confided in her details of a long-running sexual relationship
with the president. She provided tape recordings of their
conversations and documents that appeared to point to a conspiracy
to obstruct justice involving the president and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation has never been, quote, `just about sex,'''
Mrs. Tripp said in a breaking voice under a sweltering sun. ``It
has been about telling the truth; the truth matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who chairs the Judiciary Committee,
welcomed news of the president's impending testimony as a sign that
Starr's inquiry was in its ``closing throes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be more than just alleged sexual peccadilloes in
the White House,'' Hatch said at a news conference, ``and frankly
all of us would like to get this over with. I'd be surprised if Ken
Starr would allow this to go well into September.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the ranking Democrat on the
committee, was more blunt, calling on Starr to conclude his
investigation and ``give us a report on what he's done to date. Let
the American people, let the Congress do it and let the Congress
act whichever way they want. But wrap this sucker up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
