<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE HAM FOR BROOKLYN'S MORNING RUSH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard to describe exactly what Roland Joseph does
every morning in the middle of Flatbush and Fourth avenues in
Brooklyn, a confluence of screaming traffic that seems as vast as
the Nile delta.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons are easy, though: sometimes he is like a
bullfighter, planting his legs and twisting his pelvis as a van
veers through a turn inches from his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Or a baseball pitcher, glancing over his shoulder as if toward
first base, making sure pedestrians don't crowd off the curb and
into the grille of a truck. Sam Schwartz, who writes the Gridlock
Sam column for The Daily News, calls him the Beethoven of traffic
cops.
</P>
<P>
   All this suggests that Joseph, 51 years old and 5 feet 2 inches
tall, stands in one place. But during a shift last week that began
at 6:45 a.m. and ended for lunch 3 1/2 hours later, when the
temperature had already climbed to 87, he stopped moving for about
10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK! That's it. Whoop! Whoop! Whoop!'' he yelled, setting a
Manhattan-bound lane of Flatbush into motion. He whistled. He
pounded his chest with his white-gloved fists. He made a gesture
like tooting a horn. Sometimes he did a disco move or dropped to
one knee like an early-70s Elvis. When drivers heeded his commands,
he put his hands together and bowed his head in a kind of
respectful prayer pose.
</P>
<P>
   When traffic began to flow, Joseph acted as if it were a
personal victory. Bouncing on his toes, he yelled: ``Yes! Go, baby,
go!''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to a driver's excitement, he routinely keeps a sharp eye
out for tiny national flags dangling from rear-view mirrors and
tries to address drivers accordingly, as in ``Good mornin',
Jamaica!'' or ``Hello, countryman!'' when he sees the flag of his
native Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the obvious question for a man who has been doing
this around the city for 16 years and on Flatbush, at one of the
city's busiest intersections, for the last two, all for $31,000 a
year, is: why?
</P>
<P>
   Joseph shrugged his shoulders. ``I don't like to be bored,'' he
said during his lunch break. ``The day would never go by.'' He also
said he loves to keep in shape and often cannot believe he is being
paid to exercise and to practice his calypso dancing for the West
Indian Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also something of the relentless ham about Joseph.
He thrives on the attention he gets working the intersection, his
stage. ``The people need a little bit of me in the morning,'' he
said. ``I am making a donation to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The public eats it up. Bryan France, a 32-year-old van driver,
always rolls down his window so he can give Joseph a shout and a 20
mph tap on the hand. ``When he's not here, everybody wants to know
where he is,'' France said last week. ``It's like not having your
coffee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
