<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY POLICY IN SAN FRANCISCO DRAWS PENALTY IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Wednesday night narrowly passed a
measure that would deny federal housing money to San Francisco
because of that city's policies supporting live-in homosexual
partners.
</P>
<P>
   By a two-vote margin, the House unexpectedly adopted the measure
after an unusually pointed debate in which the author, Rep. Frank
Riggs, R-Calif., appeared to be virtually alone in his support.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was specifically intended for San Francisco, the
only city that requires the groups it does business with to provide
benefits to the unmarried partners of their employees. Riggs'
measure would deny San Francisco about $265 million in federal
housing money because of this policy, which he said forced the
private sector to adhere to a morally objectionable policy.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs said the policy wrongly elevated unmarried homosexuals to
the same status as married heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic opponents were aghast after the measure passed, 214
to 212. Twenty-five Democrats joined 189 Republicans in voting for
it, while 178 Democrats, 33 Republicans and 1 independent opposed
it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California, one of two Democrats
representing San Francisco, said afterward that the measure
reflected the homophobia of House Republicans. She said Republicans
pretended that the issue was protecting the private sector, but
that she knew from conversations with colleagues that it was
motivated by anti-gay and anti-lesbian sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The House also passed another measure perceived as
anti-homosexual. Proposed by Rep. Van Hilleary, R-Tenn., it would
take away $21 million from housing programs for people with AIDS
and give it to veterans. The measure was adopted 231-200.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the Riggs measure was particularly pointed, with
virtually no one rising to advocate Riggs' cause except himself.
Many opponents said it violated the prerogatives of local autonomy.
But others were more harsh. Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., branded
it a witch hunt and called it ``mean-spirited, bigoted, bigoted.''
Rep. Tom Lantos, the other Democrat representing San Francisco,
called it ``a poorly disguised assault on a persecuted minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pelosi said that the passage of the two measures added to
evidence of a crusade by conservatives against homosexuals. The
measures come as conservatives have coordinated a national
campaign, including newspaper advertisements encouraging gays to go
straight, geared toward drawing their supporters to the polls in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But one Republican lawmaker worried privately that the votes
could benefit the Democrats by painting the Republicans as
extremists.
</P>
<P>
   The House is to consider within a week a measure that would deny
federal money for the implementation of an executive order by
President Clinton to bar discrimination against federal employees
based on sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The two measures that passed on Wednesday night were part of a
larger, $94 billion spending bill that would finance veterans
affairs and housing matters in the next fiscal year, which begins
Oct. 1. That bill, which contains a host of unrelated measures,
passed on Wednesday night by a vote of 259 to 164.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the two measures is uncertain. The Senate has no
corresponding legislation, and they could easily be dropped when
the House and Senate negotiate the final spending bill they send to
the President. Clinton, who has largely supported homosexuals, is
certain to oppose the measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
