<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYAN LOSES TO REAL, LIVE HERO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Bryan's first-round match at the Mercedes-Benz Cup was more
like a scene out of some kind of Disney children's fantasy. It was
as if he woke up one day in his Camarillo bedroom and a poster of
his idol, Andre Agassi, came to life and leaped off the wall to
play a couple of sets.
</P>
<P>
   But fantasy and reality merged for a while Tuesday night at the
Los Angeles Tennis Center, as Bryan faced his childhood hero on
Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really nervous,'' the 20-year-old Bryan said after
losing 6-4, 6-3. ``I didn't know what to expect. I couldn't believe
I was even on the same court with the guy.... I tried not to look
over there too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before, Bryan was sitting in ``the Agassi room'' _
his old bedroom at his parents' Camarillo home _ looking up at the
20-plus posters of Agassi, whom he's followed since age 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting in my room looking and I saw Andre Agassi
everywhere. So it's pretty weird,'' said Bryan, who turned pro,
along with brother and doubles partner Mike, in June.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Bryan played Agassi in singles (they faced
off in doubles last year), so you could forgive the tour rookie for
being a bit awestruck. But he actually held up well, breaking
Agassi's serve in the fourth game of the first set and generally
matching the veteran's energy throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan seemed to savor every point, pumping his fists at times
and firing up the exceedingly supportive crowd, which included
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome, all the support,'' he said. ``It was like a
circus out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi had kind words for his opponent, whose game he called ``a
little deceptive'' and said, ``I enjoyed playing against him
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Goran's pain: Third-seed Goran Ivanisevic, who left the court
frustrated after being upset Tuesday by Guillame Raoux, came back
to win his doubles match in the evening. He and partner Paul
Kilderry defeated Doug Flach and Michael Tebbutt.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ivanisevic acknowledged he'd only picked up a racket
a few days before the tournament after spending most of his
post-Wimbledon time on a boat. And he said the devastating loss to
Pete Sampras in the Wimbledon final was still on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me four years to get (over losing the Wimbledon final
in) 1994, and four years before that for (losing in) 92,'' he said.
This loss was the most painful, though, ``because it was the
closest one and the best tennis ever I have played.''
</P>
<P>
   Laver update: Rod Laver, the only tennis player to win two Grand
Slams, remained in serious condition, two days after a stroke that
impaired his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Laver, who turns 60 on Aug. 9, was in the intensive-care unit at
UCLA Medical Center, where he is expected to remain for a week to
10 days. The stroke caused Laver to become weak on his right side,
but he is not paralyzed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
