<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES FEELING GREAT, PLAYING GREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is late on a sweltering afternoon, but the New York Yankees
coolly emerge from their Edison Field clubhouse and walk onto the
field to warm up for their pre-game batting and fielding drills.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is an unmistakable swagger to these Joe Torre
Yankees, who have been winning games at a pace not even matched by
the storied Yankees of Miller Huggins in the 1920s and of Joe
McCarthy in the 1930s and of Casey Stengel in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel great, great, great,'' says Darryl Strawberry, as he
shuffles past a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   There might not be a future Hall of Fame entrant among this
Yankee group, but there are a lot of exceptional players with
experience who know how to hit, run and field and a lot of pitchers
who know how to retire opposing batsmen.
</P>
<P>
   They are cool, these Yankees, even on a stiflingly hot Orange
County day, going through their calisthenics routine with a casual
haughtiness.
</P>
<P>
   They are tranquil, these Yankees, even though they draw their
paychecks from a notoriously meddlesome owner and Bronx Zoo curator
named George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   They are subdued, these Yankees, even though they've been
turning the summer of 1998 into an epic showcase of their wonderful
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``A throwback team,'' says the Yankees' venerable bench coach,
Don Zimmer, in his 50th year of professional baseball. ``They just
go out and do the job without making a big deal out of it. They
just do the job like teams from the past did.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, standing near the batting cage, takes a moment's
break from hitting infield fungoes to talk about a team that has
been winning games at a greater rate than any other in all the
summers of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely one of the best teams I've ever seen,'' says
Zimmer, a member of the world champion Dodgers in Brooklyn in 1955
and Los Angeles in 1959. ``And, believe me, I've seen a few over
the years. Our pitching has been terrific. We just don't give up
many runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our guys care about is winning. They're very unselfish.
They don't care about personal statistics. We get a runner on
second base with no outs, and a guy will give himself up to hit the
ball to the right side to get the runner over to third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys get along as well as any team I've ever seen. Spend
some time in our clubhouse. There's a great camaraderie on this
team. Of course, winning certainly helps create such an atmosphere.
But these guys really like one another. They root for one another.
Just a wonderful team to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, ol' Popeye, one-time manager of the Chicago Cubs,
Boston Red Sox, Texas Rangers and San Diego Padres, Joe Torre's top
lieutenant since 1996, a man who has seen, heard and lived baseball
his entire adult life, is shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really burns me when I hear people say what the team has
done so far doesn't mean a thing,'' says Zimmer. ``What're they
talking about? Here we are, what, 15 games ahead of the Boston Red
Sox in our division, and that doesn't count? What if we were behind
by 15 games? What this team has done so far has been absolutely
amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know anything can happen in a short playoff series. We can
catch some hot pitcher, and get shut out. I know we aren't a cinch
to make it to the World Series. There are no cinches in baseball.
I've been around long enough to realize that. But we're still
having an amazing season. And it's really been a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In a corner of the Yankee dugout, Joe Torre is holding court
with reporters, telling them what a luxury it is to have five
quality starting pitchers, David Cone, David Wells, Andy Pettitte,
Hideki Irabu and Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez, to go with a
dependable reliever, Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry is now in the outfield shagging fly balls.
Derek Jeter is playing catch on the sidelines. Tino Martinez is
taking his batting practice swings. So is Tim Raines. So is Scott
Brosius. Paul O'Neill is stretching near the cage.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees go about their business quietly, efficiently and
professionally.
</P>
<P>
   No horeseplay.
</P>
<P>
   No loud banter.
</P>
<P>
   No goofing around.
</P>
<P>
   No frills.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys amaze me a little more every day,'' says Zimmer.
``We're down near where I live in Tampa Bay recently, and we wind
up winning four games and each night I'd go home to my house and
think to myself, `How'd we win that game?' Tampa Bay got some good
pitching, but somehow we won every game. This team just knows how
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would go on to win on this evening, too, as David
Cone's pitching and 14 New York hits would be enough to squelch the
Anaheim Angels by a 9-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer is right, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen in a brief playoff series, and has across
the fickle seasons of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But at this juncture, these New York Yankees are on a merry romp
in a dream season of constant glory and applause.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
