u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMAS-SPEECH-2NDLD-W     07-30 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-SPEECH-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARENCE THOMAS RESPONDS ANGRILY TO HIS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd graf to fix quote and for rewriting) (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. _ In an explosion of pent-up resentment, Justice
Clarence Thomas on Wednesday vigorously attacked his critics, both
black and white, saying they had racist views because they had been
unable to accept the notion that he was able to think for himself.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would ``refuse to have my ideas assigned to me as
though I was an intellectual slave because I'm black.'' He spoke to
an audience of nearly 2,000 black judges and lawyers. His critics,
he said, have subjected him to particularly ``bilious and venomous
assaults'' because his conservative views and judicial opinions
since he joined the Supreme Court in 1991 do not conform to what is
expected of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   His critics, Thomas said, have engaged in what he called silly
speculation that he must be taking his cues and ideas from other
conservative justices who are white.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else could be the explanation when I fail to follow their
ideology or anti-intellectual prescription,'' he said. ``The stench
of racial inferiority still confounds my olfactory nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that such views were racist because they were based
on the idea that he would be unable to formulate such views for
himself and that he did not have a right to such opinions, because
he is black.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' deeply complicated and troubled relationship with his
fellow black Americans was on vivid public display in his
appearance before the annual convention of the National Bar
Association, the nation's largest group of black lawyers. It was an
event to which he had been invited months ago, only to have a large
and prominent group of members try to have the invitation
rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   In the end he accepted the invitation with alacrity, even though
he knew he would confront an audience with many critics.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Thomas generally confined his public speeches
to small and friendly audiences.
</P>
<P>
   He told the audience of nearly 2,000 that it had become a
wearisome ritual that when he is invited to speak publicly, people
seek to deny him that opportunity. But he suggested his acceptance
of Wednesday's invitation was like when he was younger and ``tired
of turning the other cheek.'' As for those who have said he has
forgotten his black roots, he said they were engaging in
``psychosilliness'' and probably had too much time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Although his delivery was calm, his words Wednesday were harsher
than ever before. At one point he said his critics were
``illiterate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his speech, Thomas said, ``Despite some of the
nonsense that has been said about me, I am a man, I am a black man,
I am an American.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Isn't it time to move on? To be angry with me solves
no problems.'' About half of the audience applauded, some standing,
while the other half remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the speech, several hundred lawyers and judges
went into an adjoining room to hear Thomas' critics analyze his
work and compare him unfavorably to the man he replaced on the
court, Thurgood Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Judge A. Leon Higginbotham, former chief judge of the 3rd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in Philadelphia, and one of Thomas' most
consistent critics, said Thomas was deceptive in his speech
Wednesday. He had said his critics purposely misinterpreted his
dissent in a 1992 case in which he wrote that it was not a
violation of the Constitution's proscription against ``cruel and
unusual punishment'' when a black prisoner was beaten by guards. He
described the injuries as minor, but Higginbotham said the shackled
prisoner was beaten so badly his dental plate was broken, his lips
were burst and some teeth were loosened.
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham had argued before Wednesday's event that it was a
mistake to have Thomas be the bar association's keynote speaker
because that would bestow an undeserved honor on someone whose
rulings on the court ``have done more to turn back the clock of
racial progress than any other African-American public official in
the history of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Bernette Johnson, a member of the Louisiana Supreme
Court and chairwoman of the association's judicial council, who had
first invited Thomas, said she knew the selection would be
controversial. But Ms. Johnson said she did not view extending the
invitation as an honor to Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she said, ``it gives us a chance to interact with a
Supreme Court justice and dialogue is always good.''
</P>
<P>
   But like most of those who supported the invitation, Ms. Johnson
said she disagreed strongly with Thomas' views and his writings on
the Supreme Court. ``I'm not an apologist for him,'' she said.
``I'm just saying he has a right to say what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Bar Association opposed Thomas' confirmation to the
court when he was nominated in 1991, largely over his conservative
views and outspoken opposition to affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas offered a fervent defense of his views against
affirmative action programs Wednesday, saying such programs are
inevitably based on black inferiority and are ``non-starters in my
view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe kneeling is a position of strength,'' he
said, ``and I do not believe that begging is an effective tactic.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' opponents have said his views on affirmative action are
particularly galling since he was a major beneficiary of such
programs, including his admission to Yale Law School under a
program in which a number of places were set aside for minority
students. Keith Watters, a Washington lawyer and a former president
of the National Bar Association, said he decided at the last minute
to picket the speech outside the hotel because he found Thomas'
views so hypocritical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
