<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Last season, Gary Sheffield watched the Florida
Marlins grow into a World Series champion. He's not quite sure what
he's seeing in this year's Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   One night after an impressive victory to open this long East
Coast road trip, Sheffield was left to count the Dodger mistakes
that led to Wednesday's 8-3 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies in
front of 20,127 at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, the team's only All-Star, wasn't so bothered that the
Dodgers had a chance to move ahead of the Phillies in the wild card
race. There still are two months left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   He is more concerned that the team on the field might not have
the character to make a late-season surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not something you build; that is something you have,''
said Sheffield, who hit his 19th homer in the fourth. ``I don't
know all the young guys that we have here. But tonight was a
frustrating loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield never mentioned them by name, but he was speaking
about rookie third baseman Adrian Beltre, second-year shortstop
Juan Castro and second-year second baseman Wilton Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, promoted from Double-A last month, had a single and
double in his first two at-bats, but also had three defensive
lapses that kept Phillies rallies alive.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero had two hits, but was thrown out at the plate in the
third inning when he failed to slide and touch home after being
blocked off by rookie catcher Bobby Estalella.
</P>
<P>
   Castro misplayed a third-inning grounder into the Phillies first
run.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero killed a Dodger rally and Beltre helped keep alive the
Phillies four-run fourth and three-run sixth that decided the game.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't help that the Dodgers were overmatched by rookie
right-hander Carlton Loewer (5-3), who has been in the big leagues
less than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Beltre, Castro and Guerrero raised the question whether the
team now is putting the kids in a position to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I don't know the youngsters here that well,''
Sheffield said. ``They have stepped up to help, but we seem to be
lacking the concentration in the middle of the game to get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The job of getting to the post-season has been the focus of new
general manager Tom Lasorda, who continues to search for pitching
in the final days before Friday's trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The same Toronto media outlet that said Eric Young had been
traded to Toronto for right-hander Juan Guzman said Wednesday the
Dodgers had completed a deal for Montreal left-hander Carlos Perez.
That also didn't happen, but the clubs are still talking.
</P>
<P>
   But Lasorda also has to address the rest of the team. Beltre's
blunders came after the man he replaced, Bobby Bonilla, said early
Wednesday it might be best to take off the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla is eligible to return from the disabled list today, but
his surgically repaired left wrist hurts more than it has in weeks.
(See related story.)
</P>
<P>
   In some corners of the clubhouse there are concerns the team is
rushing Beltre, who entered the game batting .202 (19 for 94) with
two homers and 10 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman met with Beltre before the game to
make sure the 20-year-old's confidence hasn't wavered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team still is pretty banged up, but we may be getting
some help,'' said Young, who will test his strained left thigh
today and hopes to come off the DL on Friday in New York. ``These
kids have gotten us back in this thing. But now we need to give
them some help.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't get it from right-hander Dave Mlicki (5-5), who lost
for the first time as a Dodger. Bobby Abreu opened Mlicki's fourth
and final inning with a home run, and Doug Glanville later had a
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   The inning was kept alive on a wild throw by Beltre on Gregg
Jefferies that the official scorer ruled a hit.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Beltre bobbled Estalella's grounder helping two
more runs to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job protecting these guys,'' Sheffield
said. ``Last year we had (Edgar) Renteria and (Craig) Counsell.
(Manager) Jim Leyland told them just to take care of the defense
and the older guys would do the rest. He drummed it into them so
much that when the season was on the line they were ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
