<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO WHEEL AND DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They came in bragging about the left side of their infield. They
will leave talking about the right side.
</P>
<P>
   They came in comfortable with their top two starters. That duo -
Andy Benes and Willie Blair - has produced 26 losses in 46 starts.
</P>
<P>
   They came in with illusions of becoming the prototype for all
expansion teams. In the end, they will settle for baby steps.
</P>
<P>
   And that just about sums up the plight of the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever brings fans out to the ballpark, that's what's
important,`' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``As we grow as an
organization, hopefully we'll give them a little more to cheer
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. And because contention must wait until the next
millennium, because Rupert Murdoch will throw around crazy money to
win in Los Angeles, because the trading deadline is less than 48
hours away, some more unsolicited advice: Make some moves. Find
some kids who might blossom in a few years. Take advantage of
organizations that have spent decades stocking their farm systems.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Gregg Olson. The veteran has been a wonderful surprise,
converting 17 of 20 save opportunities. But his market value will
never be this high. Closers are in demand, especially in Atlanta,
where Mark Wohlers requires two catchers. Wohlers couldn't pitch
for the now-defunct Peppers, and the Braves are getting worried.
Deal Olson now or be like the Suns, a team that waited too long to
peddle Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Talk Benes out of his no-trade clause and trade him to the
Giants or the Cubs. Benes is a nice guy. Too nice, in fact. A guy
who often makes that one pitch to lose a game. The Cubs were
interested in Benes in the off-season, but only for a one-year
deal. Now, Jeremi Gonzalez is done for the season. The Cubs need
another quality starter if they're going anywhere. And Wednesday's
trade for Matt Karchner will be met with a yawn in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Devon White. He's the perfect hired assassin, a guy who
collects World Series jewelry. He has three rings and is enjoying
his best season in seven years. Not many contending teams need a
center fielder, but someone has to be interested. Besides, he's
only keeping the grass warm until Bernie Williams arrives next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Trade Jorge Fabregas, if possible. Damian Miller and Kelly
Stinnett can get it done. Besides, a mysterious fungus has once
again eaten a hole in the bat of Fabregas, a guy who will earn $1.8
million next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're evaluating a lot of scenarios,'' Showalter said. ''I'll
leave that in Joe (Garagiola Jr.'s) hands. He's been pretty busy.
Obviously, since we haven't done anything so far, it hasn't been
anything that's been in our long-term interest. But we'll see what
the next two days bring.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't believe for a moment that the future of the
organization rests in the hands of Joe Junior. He, too, is a very
nice man, but a guy who has been out of the game for a long time, a
guy who is more general than manager.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, Showalter is playing Whitey Herzog, an
arduous and dangerous task. As good a field boss as Showalter is -
easily among the top five in the game - no manager should serve as
his own GM.
</P>
<P>
   A manager needs a foil, someone to play devil's advocate,
someone to study other organizations on a daily basis. But that is
a story for another day.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of hope have emerged at BOB. If not the next Rusty Greer,
David Dellucci has become an overachieving fan favorite. Travis Lee
is a stud with training wheels. While currently enduring his first
freshman hazing, Danny Klassen will soon be a fixture at shortstop.
Matt Williams is a wonderful leader. Brian Anderson is a keeper.
Andy Fox might be the team's MVP. Even Karim Garcia is showing some
patience at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Time to add more pieces for the future. Which is the only thing
left to accomplish this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
