<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS EXPECTS UNEXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The rumors have been rampant, but the big
trades in baseball have not happened. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   The non-waiver trading deadline is 9 p.m. Friday, leaving teams
like the Angels only hours to get what they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around enough teams to know that on the night of the
31st, some things will happen that you don't expect,'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``And there may be deals that fall
through. I don't worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a good example. Texas thought (Ivan) Rodriguez
was going to go and they needed a catcher. So we got Kenny Hill (in
exchange for Jim Leyritz). We had no idea that was going to happen,
it just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Angels need is a starting pitcher, and their best bets
now are the Cardinals' Todd Stottlemyre and the Royals' Tim
Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   Unexiting streak: Outfielder Garret Anderson broke Rod Carew's
club record for longest hitting streak, getting a double in the
second inning Wednesday night against the Yankees and extending his
streak to 26 games. Carew set the previous record of 25 in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson said before the game he wasn't overly excited about
the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing it says is that I'm more consistent,'' said
Anderson, who graduated from Kennedy High. ``But over a period of
time, you can hit the ball hard and they may not fall your way. Or
you can hit little chinks that fall in. You can't explain it, so I
try not to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admitted he didn't expect to have a streak go this
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time about a week, week-and-a-half ago that I
thought it would end sooner or later,'' he said. ``Now I'm at the
point where if it happens, it happens. It's nice to do some things
in your career. But for the most part it wears on you.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, Hill rehabs: Pitcher Jack McDowell (elbow) will make a
rehab start for Single-A Lake Elsinore at High Desert tonight. He
has been given a 60-pitch limit.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (elbow) will pitch two simulated games before making a
rehab assignment of his own sometime next week. If the Angels can't
make a deal for a starting pitcher, the return of Hill becomes
vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be big for us, a big lift,'' Collins said. ``We sit
here and talk about all the possibilities, and Kenny Hill would be
a good deal for us again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' condition: The Yankees' Chili Davis has begun a rehab
assignment in the minor leagues, and when he is ready to come back,
he'll get most of the at-bats at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   That means fewer at-bats for current DH Darryl Strawberry, who
hit his team-leading 17th homer in the second inning Wednesday.
Yankees manager Joe Torre said he anticipates no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Straw came here in '96, he's never been anything but
`When you need me, I'll be ready,' '' Torre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
