r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-AUTOGRAPHINDUSTRY     07-30 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-AUTOGRAPH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SIGN FOR TRUE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
 INDUSTRY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On more than one occasion, New York Yankees shortstop Derek
Jeter has found himself darting in and out of traffic on the
heavily congested FDR Drive that loops around Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter does not fancy himself any kind of Speed Racer. It's just
that fans have been known to follow the star shortstop to his
Manhattan apartment, wanting to chase down an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can definitely be a scary situation,'' Jeter said. ``The
FDR is not an easy road to maneuver in and out of. But I have no
way of knowing what those people's intentions are. You have to be
careful, and that not only goes for New York but anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The world of autograph hunting is both impressive and scary.
</P>
<P>
   What could easily be described 25 years ago as a cute hobby for
children has evolved into a $100 million industry in which the
proverbial ugly head is rearing with more frequency.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon to see fans screaming, veins popping out in
their necks, as they try to get the attention of a player before
the start of any major league baseball game. Many players are
accommodating to many fans. But leave one out and the player is
likely to be called all sorts of names, most of them obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams signed autographs for
nearly 20 minutes before a recent game, putting his name on trading
cards, balls or slips of paper at least 100 times. But when
Williams had to walk away to warm up before the game, he left
several fans disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   One of those went so far as to send a terse letter up the
Diamondbacks' chain of command, starting with Manager Buck
Showalter and heading up the ladder to General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr. and managing general partner Jerry Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players tend to feel like it's never enough,'' Showalter said.
``As a player, it's not a battle you can win.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' worst scenarios exist when their clubs are on the
road, leaving them more vulnerable. The autograph hounds somehow
find out which hotels house the visiting clubs in every city.
</P>
<P>
   Even though nearly all of the hotels now prohibit autograph
signing on the premises, they cannot stop the seekers from huddling
outside the hotel's doors, where sometimes hundreds camp out as
long as 16 hours a day waiting for the chance to get a player's
signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't always sign for everybody,'' Chicago Cubs All-Star
Sammy Sosa said. ``I do as much as possible. In situations that get
out of hand, I try to control them as much as possible. I sign for
everyone, especially if I know it's for a personal collection. You
can tell which ones want it for themselves and which ones want it
to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where one of the players' biggest problems lies. Almost
universally, they agree that they do not mind signing for the fan,
young or old, who truly wants to add the signature to a prized
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're older or more mature, they can ask me just as
easily as a kid can,'' Baltimore Orioles All-Star second baseman
Roberto Alomar said. ``I realize it's not only kids who collect
autographs. Young fans grow up to be old fans. They should be able
to ask for our autographs, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I've always enjoyed meeting and talking to people,
so I don't mind signing for anyone. The only request I make is, if
I'm having dinner, they wait until after I finish. There's a time
for asking. The problem is, it hasn't always been polite fans who
ask. We're human beings, even though we are celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest objection players have is with the dealers who
deceive in trying to acquire an autograph. With the growing sales
in the autographed memorabilia business has come the obvious side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers, who can peddle superstar autographs for hundreds
and sometimes thousands of dollars, go to great lengths to get
players to sign. In a disturbingly growing trend, dealers now hire
children, as young as 7 or 8, to plead with a player for a
signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it where I sign a baseball card and see a kid walk
over to a grown-up and exchange it for a $5 or $10 bill,'' Anaheim
Angels closer Troy Percival said. ``It's really sad to see that
happen because I really enjoy signing for kids, especially the ones
who get really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are also the children who line up at a hotel's
doors at 3 or 4 in the morning, waiting for the incoming club to
check in after a late-night flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sign in hotels anymore,'' said San Diego's perennial
All-Star right fielder Tony Gwynn. ``I'll sign before and after
games at the stadium only. I get people knocking on my hotel doors,
sliding things under the door with a note to leave them at the
front desk. I've had people yell at me, `You fat so and so, who do
you think you are?' It's a no-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn recalled a scenario where a teenage boy wearing an old New
York Yankees cap got Gwynn's autograph on a card. Ten minutes
later, after a quick makeover that included flipping the cap
backwards and the addition of sunglasses, the boy was back asking
for another autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I already signed for you,' '' Gwynn said. ``He
insisted he hadn't gotten an autograph. I'm older, but I remember
faces, especially a old Yankees cap. You never see those.''
</P>
<P>
   Autograph hunting will not go away soon. If anything, it's
become much more aggressive. Where it's headed, no one knows for
sure, but it seems as if players have been forced to be on the
defensive more than at any other time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just have to say no,'' said Seattle center
fielder Ken Griffey Jr., whose autograph can command hundreds of
dollars. ``I hate to do it, but I'd be there forever if I started
signing while I'm out in public. You wouldn't believe the names
I've been called. I know you couldn't print them in a newspaper.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0114EDT &QL; 
