</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FANTASY-BASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING STARS' STATISTICS FAR FROM GOLDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for Cal Ripken to quit. And Wade Boggs, too, for that
matter. I wonder if they could even land a job in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   Both play third base, a position that teams rely on for home
runs and RBIs, or if not either of those, a very high batting
average. You have to bring something more than just your glove and
guile to the park. And they don't. They have outlived their
usefulness, and that is tarnishing their status as the
standard-bearers for that position that they once were.
</P>
<P>
   And if they do go, they can take Paul Molitor, Joe Carter and
Harold Baines with them. Since that bunch can't become left-handed
pitchers, then it's time for them to depart while they still enjoy
star status.
</P>
<P>
   As a fan, it almost hurts to say all this. But as a fantasy
owner, hey, it's good riddance. Nobody wants Ripken's 600 at-bats,
.250 average, 12 homers and 60 RBIs. And those marks will only
diminish next season _ except for the at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken has had his run. He's broken his records. Now, he should
step aside. &QL;  &QL; 
Don't believe 'em &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With everyone so involved in all the trade talk, it looks as if
somebody forgot to let the trade genie out of the lamp.
</P>
<P>
   If Estaban Loaiza, Doug Jones, Joe Carter and Jose Mesa are the
biggest and only deals to happen since the breakup of the Marlins,
then baseball insiders everywhere have been way off track. (I'm no
insider, I'm just off track.)
</P>
<P>
   And all that fretting over all those other future free agents
went for nothing, because nobody could pull the trigger. Either
that, or the insiders were wrong all along. (Imagine that.)
</P>
<P>
   There could be an 11th-hour trading frenzy. The Devil Rays would
be nuts not to find a new home for Boggs, Fred McGriff or David
Martinez, all of whom have some stretch-run value and are too old
to keep. Ditto for Todd Zeile and John Cangelosi in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn seems intent on being a Blue Jay next season. And get
a load of this reaction _ ``I can't see where he'd fit in, what
with (Carlos) Delgado, (Jose) Canseco and myself here,'' said
Toronto DH Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say, ``So long, Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   A few new blips on the trade radar screen has the Rangers
getting Royce Clayton and Todd Stottlemyre from the Cardinals.
Heaven knows what the Rangers have to deal in return. It'd take a
bit more than Darren Oliver, I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious place for Stottlemyre is with the Yankees, where he
could join his dad, Mel, who is the pitching coach. That could
allow the Yankees to put Orlando Hernandez into the setup role. But
Stottlemyre has not pitched effectively for weeks now. &QL;  &QL; 
Set in stone &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In any event, by now you have either made your move or you
haven't. The trade deadline is tomorrow in real baseball. Your
league's deadline may vary, but for the most part your team is set
in stone. &QL;  &QL; 
Love that loophole &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week passed its bill to ban betting on the
Internet but luckily left a little loophole for Rotisserie and
fantasy league players to take advantage of the stat services that
are available online. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
