<HEADLINE>
TEAM PATIENT WITH KLASSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rookie second baseman, as baseball folks say, is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   And that might be putting it mildly, considering that Danny
Klassen has only four hits in his past 29 at bats and has struck
out in 11 straight games while committing two of his five errors in
21 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter is reluctant to sit him
down for a mental adjustment, although he did replace Klassen with
veteran Andy Stankiewicz on Wednesday night as part of a
sixth-inning double switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I told him in Houston when he first came up, this
isn't a tryout camp or something,'' Showalter said. ``He's someone
we think highly of and we're going to give him an opportunity. All
young players go through periods where they struggle and look bad
at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about resting him, but right now the advantages
of him playing, growing and seeing situations, ballparks and
pitchers outweigh it. If he started making the same mistakes over
and over, it's one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he's overmatched at the plate. He's hit some
balls hard the last two or three nights, but right at people. It
takes a lot for a young player to get into the flow where he
relaxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for Showalter's patience is he wants to see how
Klassen handles the adversity. He hit .345 in his first 10 games
but has seen his average drop to .215 in the past 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night he made an error and came back and turned a
tough double play on the next hitter,'' Showalter said. ``That's an
encouraging thing to see. A lot of young players will wallow around
in self-pity.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Setup man &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, who are expected to finalize another trade today,
dealt promising minor league starter John Garland, 18, across town
to the Chicago White Sox in exchange for veteran relief pitcher
Matt Karchner.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, the Cubs' first selection in the 1997 draft, was 4-7
with a 5.03 ERA in 19 starts at Class-A Rockford this year, while
Karchner, 30, was 2-4 with 11 saves in 15 chances and a 5.15 ERA
for the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably an area that was our Number 1 concern,
to get some help down there to set up (closer) Rod Beck,'' Cubs
Manager Jim Riggleman said. &QL; 
Extra bases &QL; 
Showalter said the Diamondbacks will be without reliever Bobby
Chouinard for today's series-ending game against Chicago. Chouinard
and his wife, Erica, were to have their first child after doctors
induced labor late Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Relief pitcher Clint Sodowsky underwent a magnetic resonance
image Wednesday for possible tendinitis in the shoulder of his
throwing arm but will be available today.
</P>
<P>
   The team changed its rehabilitation timetable for third baseman
Matt Williams. Instead of playing in Tucson tonight and Friday, he
will workout with the Diamondbacks today and play in Tucson on
Friday and Saturday before rejoining the team Sunday in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   When Sammy Sosa hit the first grand slam of his career Monday
night, he dispatched a dugout attendant to the center-field seats
to negotiate the return of the ball. The price he paid was an
autographed bat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
