<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-PLUMME     07-30 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSTEVENS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CLASS, PLUMMER AC CEPTS ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ A Cardinals fan showed up at training camp one day
carrying a life-size likeness of Troy Aikman. He lay the cardboard
cutout on the practice field, with written instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stomp Dallas,'' the sign read.
</P>
<P>
   Several Cardinals did, some with glee.
</P>
<P>
   Not Jake Plummer. When Jake saw Troy at his feet, smiling up at
him, he sidestepped the cardboard effigy. The courtesy spoke of his
respect for a fellow quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer knows how it feels to be flat on your back, outnumbered
by the enemy. Last year in Texas Stadium, the Cowboys sacked the
Cardinals rookie eight times.
</P>
<P>
   A week later against New York, he went down eight times again.
</P>
<P>
   But Plummer kept getting up, and if you ask him at what point
last season he realized he can do it _ when he told himself, ``I
can play in this league'' _ he will tell you that the dawning began
that gray November day in Giants Stadium when he kept pulling
himself off the turf and threw for 388 yards, an NFL rookie record.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, the critical letters stopped arriving at the
newspaper. The ones that said Plummer is a media creation. The ones
that said Plummer is overrated. The ones that argued Kent Graham
should be the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   I kept one letter. The author berated the Cardinals for putting
in a ``boy to do a man's job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals can be faulted. They should have played Jake
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he made mistakes. Plenty of them. ``For every good moment,
I'd make a bonehead play that brought me back to earth,'' Plummer
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Third down was an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head would be spinning sometimes,'' Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had no running game. The offensive line leaked.
Often times, when the quarterback peered across the line, the
defenders looked like movie Indians on a ridge. Seven, eight.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers sacked him 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept getting up. If his psyche was bruised, he didn't
show it. Plummer looks relaxed and confident going into his second
season. Sounds confident, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about the sophomore jinx?'' a radio guy asked.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer fixed him with a flat gaze. ``You think that's a good
question?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't,'' Jake replied.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Trestman likes what he sees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake has tremendous leadership qualities,'' said the new
offensive coordinator, who coached Bernie Kosar and Steve Young.
Trestman talks about his Young-like ``escapability'' and Kosar-like
intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   He is still learning the new offense. The other part of the job
_ public relations _ he has down pat.
</P>
<P>
   They wait for him, patiently, merchandise in hand. Practice
over, the crowd engulfs him. He begins signing whatever they hold
out to him.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man edged next to Plummer. Jake draped an arm around
him, as if they are old friends. They smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two best-looking guys on the field,'' the man's wife said, as
she snapped the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Is it like this every day?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day,'' Plummer said, patiently, head down, scribbling
away.
</P>
<P>
   Do you get tired of it? Of course he does. I asked the question
anyway, to see what he would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. The fans are great. We're glad they're here. We really
need their support.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches have left the field. His teammates are gone, headed
for the dining hall. No. 16 stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for him are high. Perhaps unrealistically high. But
it's fun watching him grow into the job. The Cardinals haven't had
a player this popular since they moved to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer looked up. ``More'' new faces.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's biggest tourist attraction south of the Grand Canyon
gave a playful smile and asked, ``Is there a bus that keeps
dropping people off here?'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
