<SLUG> BC-CAR-UNSER-IROC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE AL'S BACK AT INDY  
 FORMER 500 WINNER SETTLES FOR IROC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Little Al is not so little anymore. And not
nearly as young.
</P>
<P>
   At age 36, Al Unser Jr. no longer is the skinny pipsqueak that
20 years ago needed two telephone books to see over the hoods of
his midget and sprint cars.
</P>
<P>
   He is an adult. And he now sees things more clearly.
</P>
<P>
   What Unser sees most is a dream that may never come true again.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Unser won his first Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he won again.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1995, a year after Unser's second greatest triumph, he
unceremoniously failed to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the feud separating the Championship Auto Racing
Teams circuit and the rival Indy Racing League, formed three years
ago by Indianapolis Motor Speedway President Tony George, Unser
hasn't been back. Not in a race car, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In May, during qualifying for the Indy 500, Unser returned to
offer support to cousins Johnny and Robby Unser. When the crowd
near Gasoline Alley and along pit road spotted Little Al, they
roared, begging him to return.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly three months later, Unser has returned. He, along
with 11 other drivers, will compete Friday in the first-ever
International Race of Champions event at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway, which a day later will be the site of the NASCAR Winston
Cup Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   But the IROC series is not even close to what those Indy-car
fans in May had in mind when they stood and cheered for one of
racing's most heralded drivers.
</P>
<P>
   And, really, the IROC circuit is not what Unser had in mind,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was there in May, the overwhelming response the fans
gave me meant a lot,'' Unser said. ``It got me emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather be coming back in the open wheelers. The last
time I drove a race around that place, it was a long time ago. And
I missed the show. I just wish I could be going back in a champ
(Indy) car.''
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, it likely won't happen soon, thanks to the CART
vs. IRL rift, which keeps growing wider by the minute.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been rumors that Unser and his dad,
four-time Indy 500 winner Al Unser, who, ironically, is an IRL
driver coach, might form an IRL team, Little Al scoffs at the
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no validity to it,'' Unser said.
</P>
<P>
   So for the moment, Unser must be satisfied with driving a
Pontiac Firebird IROC car. And nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back to Indianapolis, but I don't think I want
it as bad as say, Michael Andretti, who's never won, or Scott
Pruett or Jimmy Vasser,'' Unser said. ``These guys grew up in
America and their whole life dream was to get to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They earned the right to drive the top cars in the top series
in the nation and whammo, all of a sudden, they don't get to drive
in the Indy 500. It's a real shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had I not won it, I'd be really heartbroken right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there remains an emptiness inside Unser. He believes the
Indy 500 has lost its lustre and its magic, denigrated to the point
where he almost pities what it's become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Mears put it really good,'' Unser said. ``He wears the
Indy 500 ring on his finger, and so do I. We're proud of it because
when we won the race. It was a race. It was something. Now it's
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something missing at the Speedway during the month of
May. It's Alex Zanardi, Jimmy Vasser, Bobby Rahal, Michael
(Andretti). All the teams and the big major sponsors weren't there.
You could definitely notice something was missing. It's a real
shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, we (raced in it) when it was a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Unser dare utter those words to George, a longtime friend?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to tell him,'' Unser said. ``He knows (what the
Indy 500 has become). He wants us back bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Unser, Little Al's wife, says it would be impossible for
her husband to let go of Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it really does play on his mind an awful lot,'' said
Shelley, who attended Camelback High School and met her husband at
Manzanita Speedway. ``I think it's because the whole (Unser) family
heritage, aside from Pikes Peak (annual hill climb), came from
their success at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   `I mean, it's like you weren't anybody in the family unless you
won Indy. When Al finally won, it's like he finally got respect
from his Uncle Bobby (Unser, who won three times), who used to
tease him. All his childhood memories are about Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think it's been real hard for him because of that. And
it's like he's caught in the middle because he finally got a job
driving for the man (Roger Penske) he always wanted to drive for
and Tony being his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank, God, he won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley also believes her husband's return to Indy in the IROC
series won't be near the tonic some might think it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be emotional for him, but not as emotional as it would
be if he were in a champ car,'' she said. ``It's a different kind
of emotion. It's almost like it will make it worse. I think he
might feel awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Unser feels, it surely won't be near the emotion he
would feel should he one day again line up on the starting grid in
an Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Indianapolis 500 wants to have (CART's) top
drivers and their top sponsors,'' Unser said. ``It's the most
popular series in the world. Who wouldn't want to be part of that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we'll just have to wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Unser concedes it likely will be a long wait. Too long,
maybe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
