<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OLIVER RECOVERS HIS FORM IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ General manager Doug Melvin acknowledged Wednesday
that his attempts to strengthen the Rangers' rotation appear to be
losing steam.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, left-hander Darren Oliver, the rotation's caboose and
subject of trade speculation with tomorrow's deadline approaching,
returned his off-the-tracks season between the rails.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who recorded an out in the seventh inning for only the
sixth time in 19 starts this season, helped the Rangers right their
four-game losing streak in Wednesday night's 9-6 victory against
the Toronto Blue Jays at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver (6-7) allowed only two earned runs in his 61/3 innings
and departed with an 8-3 lead after inducing a ground-ball
fielder's choice from Blue Jays center fielder Shannon Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The performance was long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's there,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``There's no doubt in my mind about that. I've seen him do it
before, and I know he can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' expectations for an American League West title
demand it, and the left-hander responded to the challenge by
minimizing the Blue Jays' first-inning threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big inning there,'' said Oliver, who entered
Wednesday night's appearance with a 6.77 earned-run average. ``That
could have been a three-run inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart drew a one-out walk and advanced to second on the first
of the Blue Jays' three stolen bases in the inning. Stewart scored
the game's first run on a single by Jose Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Delgado advanced Canseco 90 feet with an infield single,
and both runners moved up another base through a successful double
steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my fault,'' Oliver said of the three first-inning
stolen bases, ``for not paying them enough attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, though, caught the attention of designated hitter Mike
Stanley by recording the first of only two strikeouts with a 3-2
fastball. Oliver later induced an inning-ending ground ball from
Tony Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Oliver later overcame a second-inning throwing
error by shortstop Kevin Elster that led to two unearned runs and a
3-1 deficit. Blue Jays right-hander Chris Carpenter (6-5) issued
four walks in the third inning, and catcher Ivan Rodriguez made it
costly with a three-run double that made the score 4-3, giving the
Rangers a lead that never would be relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Dave Stieb, whom Melvin expressed interest in
before the Rangers purchased right-hander Todd Van Poppel from
Triple-A Oklahoma, replaced Carpenter for the fourth inning and
surrendered three consecutive run-scoring hits to Luis Alicea,
Rusty Greer and Roberto Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who responded to the five-run advantage by allowing only
two hits and two walks in the next four innings, utilized all three
pitches _ fastball, curveball and changeup _ effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched even better than his line,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Oates replaced Oliver after Stewart's seventh-inning at-bat with
Canseco scheduled to bat. Oliver's pitch count and the potential
matchup made it a wise choice. Oliver's pitch count stood at 121,
and Canseco entered the at-bat hitting .375 (6-for-16) with three
home runs against the left-hander during his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want Canseco hitting against a tired left-hander,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who expressed dissatisfaction about being removed after
42/3 innings during his previous start Thursday in Kansas City,
complained of nothing this evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a quality start,'' Oliver said, ``and a big win for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' AL West title hopes require more of those during
the season's remaining two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
