<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PUNTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE CARDS PUNTERS TRY NOT TO BOOT CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ Scott Player was working as a dispatcher for a
trucking company last winter, the reluctant first step into a
second career that he really wasn't ready for.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped he'd hear from another NFL team that was looking for a
punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd had some good camps,'' Player said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Williams clung to hope, too, that he somehow would get
into an NFL camp after an impressive collegiate punting career at
Arizona State. The NFL draft came and went. His name was not
called.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have had excellent punters. Rich Camarillo. Then
Valley native Jeff Feagles. Both were Pro Bowl players.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Cardinals are staking their hopes on these two young
candidates who, at this stage of their careers, are among the NFL
fringe at their craft.
</P>
<P>
   When Feagles' contract expired after last season, Seattle
Seahawks owner Paul Allen opened his sizable wallet. Feagles jumped
at his seven-figure offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals quickly were on the phone to Player, who has yet
to make an NFL roster, and later to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a call from the team in my hometown was like a dream
come true,'' said Williams, who grew up in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   The dream hasn't come true entirely, yet, for either.
</P>
<P>
   Both have had their moments in the rarefied air here, but
neither has shown consistently that he's ready to be the successor
to Feagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not completely satisfied,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
``We're very, very inexperienced there. Scott Player is having a
good camp, with good hang time and distance on his punts. Marcus
Williams has a strong leg but he's more erratic. That goes with
being young.''
</P>
<P>
   If neither is dazzling in preseason games, the Cardinals'
opening-day punter might not be on the roster yet.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do NFL clubs use a draft pick on a punter, nor, until
Allen dug in, did they pay them highly, giving the perception that
punters are not critical.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a punter can change a game faster than almost any other
player. A well-placed punt can pin a foe in lousy field position.
Feagles was a master at placing punts inside the opponent's 20-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   Or a boomer that hangs long enough for the coverage to get
downfield can negate a return, leaving the offense with a long
field to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   But a bobbled snap or a blocked punt can put the defense in
horrible position.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize how important the punter is,'' Player
said. ``You talk about field position, or losing field position,
it's a lot of responsibility, and only 30 guys in the world get to
do it in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Player calls the competition ``neck and neck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is a good punter, with a strong leg,'' Player said.
</P>
<P>
   Player, who was in the Cardinals' camp two years ago and with
New York last year, has taken some razzing from teammates because
he has gone to a single-bar face mask, the kind old-timers wore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was developing bad habits looking through the old mask,
moving the ball over the bar where I could see it,'' Player said.
``That was too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Even through his conventional face mask, Williams, an excitable
lad, could see that he was succumbing to rookie jitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time out here at this level, and I wasn't in
my rhythm,'' Williams said. ``It was typical rookie things. I was
taking too long to get it off. I talked to everyone for advice, and
the bottom line is I just had to calm myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, also getting a look as the kickoff man, regained
confidence after blasting a few kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really striking it well, and that began to carry over to
my punts,'' Williams said. ``Scott is an excellent punter. He's
been in a lot of pro camps. I came in here and I was all over the
place. I didn't know what to expect. This is a great opportunity, a
great experience for my first year out. Now I'm getting a feel for
it. If this first week taught me anything it's that I need to
settle down and just be myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
