<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9720 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-30 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Elarton convincing in save
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Scott Elarton is starting to act like a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   He's starting to think like a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he looked like a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, still regarded as one of the Astros' top
starting-pitcher prospects, is turning out to be one of their top
relievers. The 22-year-old rookie shut the door on the Florida
Marlins over the final three innings for his first major-league
save in the Astros' 10-6 victory in front of 21,870 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable,'' Elarton said. ``I don't know what it is.
I've felt comfortable in the bullpen all along. It's good to come
into a situation where I could get a save, because you kind of feel
like there's something on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true reliever. Only in Elarton's case, his first
save came on the one-month anniversary of his move to the Astros'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton relieved starter Pete Schourek (7-6) in the seventh
inning with the Astros holding a 9-6 lead. Elarton retired the
first six batters he faced before giving up consecutive singles to
pinch hitters Craig Counsell and Gregg Zaun to start the ninth. The
6-7 righthander, whose fastball tops out around 93 mph, got out of
the jam with a pair of grounders and a flyout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big. They had some momentum,'' said Astros manager
Larry Dierker, whose club built a 5-1 first-inning lead before
Florida rallied to tie the score in the third. ``Sometimes, it's
hard to stop them. (Coming back in a game) can be contagious. It is
for us when we hit. To get Pete out of the game, you don't know
what you're going to get in the bullpen. Sometimes it's good;
sometimes it isn't. It was very timely.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for the Astros' offense, which pounded a
Marlins rookie starter for the third consecutive night. This time,
it was Andy Larkin's turn. The righthander didn't make it past the
third inning, and for the second time in three days the first five
Astros to bat scored during a five-run first inning. The big blow
was a three-run home run by ex-Marlin Moises Alou, who has homered
in four consecutive games, one shy of Cliff Johnson's 1975 club
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have the swing down,'' said Alou, who is batting
.556 (10-for-18) this season against the Marlins. ``I haven't been
hitting that many home runs in consecutive days since 1993-94. It's
a good feeling when you can go out there and drive the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the Astros' nine starters had a hit, with Craig Biggio
and Derek Bell each contributing three hits and two RBIs. Bill
Spiers went 2-for-5 with two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida manager Jim Leyland isn't surprised with the Astros'
offense, which ranks first in the National League with 592 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the better lineups in the league, without
question,'' Leyland said. ``That's a pretty tough lineup for any
pitcher, let alone a young pitcher. To be honest, we're overmatched
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The early run support was almost not enough for Schourek, who
ran into trouble in the third inning. The Marlins scored four runs
off him, with Derrek Lee accounting for three with a bases-loaded
double that tied the score at 5. Lee, who extended his hitting
streak to nine games, also hit a bases-empty home run in the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, coming off a strong seven-inning outing against San
Diego five days earlier, allowed six runs and eight hits in six
innings in winning for the second time in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My control wasn't real sharp. The balls they hit _ some were
good pitches; some were bad pitches,'' said Schourek, who helped
his cause with two hits and a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros knocked Larkin (2-6) out of the game with three runs
in the third to go back in front 8-5. Larkin allowed eight runs, 10
hits and three walks in 2 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
