<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIVEAWAYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Traditional giveaway items give way to chic beanies 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giveaways at the ballpark used to be a traditional,
unsophisticated thing.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a baseball game, get your kids a bat, a ball, a cap or a
glove. Something that said baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams have tried giving away something different. The
Indians, for instance, once gave away cans of deodorant _ on
Mother's Day. And who can forget that June night in 1974 when they
sold beer for a nickel in Cleveland?
</P>
<P>
   Bat day, however, may no longer be the pinnacle of giveaways. On
July 7, crazed fans and memorabilia brokers stormed Coors Field in
Denver to grab one of the hot new giveaway items. Major League
Baseball added to its all-star luster by passing out something that
had nothing to do with the game:
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   50,000 of them, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   And now Beanie Ball seems to be changing the way sports teams
are playing the giveaway game. Seizing the moment, the Rangers and
the Cowboys plan to distribute the toy industry's latest phenomenon
at upcoming games. In a doff of the helmet to fullback Daryl
``Moose'' Johnston, the Dallas Cowboys intend to give away the
``Chocolate Moose'' Beanie Baby at the regular-season opener Sept.
6. The Texas Rangers are giving out ``Pugsley,'' a bean-stuffed pug
dog, on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Rangers announced the Beanie Baby giveaway, ``We
were getting a ton of calls,'' said Sherry Flow, the Rangers'
promotions manager. ``I never thought it would be a big promotion.
I guess I'm still trying to figure out what the craze is with
regard to sports teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Ball, sports-marketing experts say, reflects not only
changing consumer tastes but the growing sophistication of sports
franchises who recognize the benefits of jumping on a promotional
bandwagon as it passes by the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With competition for the sports entertainment dollar increasing,
marketing experts say teams are searching for unique,
higher-quality items to give away to fans. Bats, balls and T-shirts
haven't exactly been replaced, but they've had to make room for
Mattel Hot Wheels, Barbies, Duncan Yo-yos and Beanie Babies _ toys
with name recognition and value far beyond the ballfield, rink or
court.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular promotional items of today didn't exist or were
unknown to the public not long ago. Who knew what a screensaver or
a mousepad was back in the days of the Big Red Machine? Yet, both
are common giveaway items at ballparks and arenas today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all trying to tap into what's hot,'' says Sean
Brenner, editor of Team Marketing Report, a Chicago-based,
sports-business trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed a lot lately,'' adds Ben Creed, director of
marketing partnerships for the Florida Marlins. ``Of course, we
still want the item to be somehow baseball-related, or if it's not,
to have something saying `Marlins' on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Marlins are giving away bean-bag dolls
featuring team mascot Billy the Marlin, not Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs, however, are featuring two Beanie Baby
giveaway days this season. One, ``Daisy the Cow,'' was tied to
legendary broadcaster Harry Caray through his signature call,
``Holy Cow.'' A second giveaway, of ``Gracie the Swan,'' is being
nominally connected to Cubs first baseman Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for ballpark giveaways hasn't changed much
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to put more people in the seats,'' Creed
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely see a jump in attendance on a giveaway night,''
Dallas Stars spokesman Larry Kelly says.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, Kelly adds, are considering a Beanie Baby giveaway
for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey and basketball clubs have increased their number of
giveaway promotions in recent years, but baseball still leads the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot more seats to fill,'' Brenner explains. ``A
giveaway in baseball can make a real difference when you're trying
to fill 50,000 seats 81 times a season.''
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the reason behind the Rangers' long list of
giveaway nights, which include items such as magnetic schedules,
mugs, calendars, cups, umbrellas, caps, tote bags, jerseys,
sunglasses, commemorative pins, batting helmets, binders,
backpacks, growth charts, posters and seat cushions. Flow said the
biggest giveaways prior to Beanies have been the traditional ones:
bats, hats and replica shirts or jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of group sales with boy scouts and girl scouts,''
Flow said. ``And the day they usually pick is bat day.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling seats isn't the only reason for promotional giveaways,
though, or the Dallas Cowboys probably wouldn't be handing out
Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giveaways aren't that common in football,'' says Joel
Finglass, director of sales and promotions for the Cowboys.
``Ninety percent of your tickets in the NFL are pre-sold. Most of
the time they're just a bonus for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving away Beanie Babies, Finglass adds, provides loyal fans
with an item of considerable value _ some brokers reportedly
offered up to $500 to buy Beanie Babies given to fans at the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Hosting such a hot promotion doesn't hurt a team's image,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Finglass says, ``for teams like us to stay
on top of trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams rarely do promotions anymore unless they have a corporate
sponsor underwriting the cost to purchase the giveaway item.
Dallas-based Southwest Airlines sponsors giveaways for the
Mavericks and Stars as well as the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good will and exposure for us,'' says Christy Hall,
manager of sports marketing for Southwest. ``We want to promote our
partnership with the teams and give folks something they can take
back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has given away screensavers, baggage tags and
miniature binoculars _ more adult-oriented items since airline
customers tend to be adults.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of sports giveaways, however, still go to kids.
Team officials say the promotional item lures the whole family to
the ballpark, resulting in more tickets sold, as well as
concessions, souvenirs and parking.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to sponsor a giveaway is not small. While screensavers
can go for $2 or less each, bats cost $3.75 apiece and baseballs
even more. Multiply that by 20,000 or more fans, and it is an
investment in marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Hot as Beanie Babies are, some companies shy away from
sponsoring their giveaway. That's because it is difficult to
associate the sponsor's name with the dolls. Still, Southwest's
Hall says, they are likely to remain a better draw than bat day or
ball day for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just not a better traffic builder out there,'' Halls
says. ``This is not going away any time soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
