<HEADLINE>
LINEMEN TO BATTLE FOR SPOTS AT CAMP  
 DEVILS LOOKING FOR RIGHT TACKLE 
</HEADLINE>
 LINE -AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hog feeds are alive and well, and that's a good sign for the
status of Arizona State's offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The linemen, firm believers in bonding off the field, have met
several times this summer for barbecues, affectionately known by
the group as ``hog feeds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get along well,'' sophomore Marvel Smith said. ``And I
think we feel we can even be better than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That's encouraging for the Sun Devils, whose line may have been
the most unappreciated aspect of the offense last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the offensive line started doing better, the defenses
weren't blitzing Ryan (Kealy) as much,'' wide receiver Lenzie
Jackson said. ``That not only helped Ryan but the receivers, too.
It made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit will benefit from offensive line coach Dan Cozzetto's
decision last season to go with freshmen Smith (left tackle) and
Victor Leyva (right guard), who combined for 17 starts. They'll
join senior Grey Ruegamer, who Coach Bruce Snyder has suggested may
be the best center in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman Scott Peters, the heaviest of the linemen at
321 pounds, will replace Kyle Murphy at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I see about him is all good,'' Smith said. ``The
only thing he needs is to get to know plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into this program already as strong as me and
Victor.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters will need to keep on his toes. Senior Randy Leaphart, a
backup at center and guard, had a strong spring.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such clarity at right tackle. Glen Gable, who
started the final nine games there last season, is gone. The
position will be won at Camp Tontozona, which starts Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Troy Davis, who started the first three games of last
season at right tackle before backing up Smith on the left side,
will square off with junior Thomas Schmidt and sophomore Dane Beem
for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a heated battle,'' Cozzetto said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils were hoping to have Tucson High School standout
Ralph Zarate in the mix, but he hasn't reached the necessary ACT
score and may end up going to a junior college.
</P>
<P>
   Damien Niko, a standout recruit from Mesa Mountain View, also
did not qualify and won't be eligible this season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith thinks the line will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking forward to the season starting for a long
time,'' he said. ``It feels different going into camp not really
competing for a position, but I still have a lot of work to do,
focusing on technique and everything. I can't wait.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
