<SLUG> BC-BKC-UTAHSTATE-NAU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH STATE MAY PURSUE NAU BASKETBALL COACH 
</HEADLINE>
 COACH-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aftershocks of Phil Jackson's departure from the Chicago
Bulls might be felt in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been replaced by former Iowa State Coach Tim Floyd.
Iowa State replaced Tim Floyd with Utah State's Larry Eustachy. And
a Utah State official called Northern Arizona Athletic Director
Steve Holton on Tuesday, expressing interest in Coach Ben Howland.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Van De Velde, who became Utah State athletic director 10
days ago, didn't ask for permission to interview Howland but told
NAU of his interest.
</P>
<P>
   If things progress, Van De Velde said he will call for formal
permission to talk to Howland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing would not be real good,'' Holton said. ``But if
it's much better financially and all those things . . . The feeling
at mid-level schools is that if you leave a place better than when
you came in, you can't argue with people (leaving).''
</P>
<P>
   Howland, reached on a recruiting trip in Las Vegas, said he had
not been contacted and declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, the job could be attractive to Howland, who has several
ties to Utah. He played at Weber State in Ogden, and his wife is
from nearby Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Howland has guided NAU to one of the biggest improvements in
college basketball history. Taking over one of the nation's worst
programs, he has gone 58-51 in four seasons, 42-15 over the past
two.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks won the Big Sky championship last season and
earned the school's first NCAA Tournament berth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
