<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-SCHOOLS-SITE-LADN     07-30 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOLS-SITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT RIPS DISTRICT SOUTH CENTRAL
</HEADLINE>
 (With BC-LA-SCHOOLS-HAZARD-LADN, both for use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jefferson Middle School is a prime example of what
can go wrong when a school district builds a campus on toxic land,
according to a critical report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Students will attend classes at the South Central Los Angeles
school even though workers will still be extracting contaminants
from the soil, which contained the carcinogen chromium-6 at initial
levels 540 times the limit allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   When the land was bought in 1990, district officials didn't know
the extent of the contamination. Once the land was acquired,
environmental analysis was deficient, and cleanup was only done
after the school was built, according to a report by the Joint
Legislative Audit Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every indication that the district not only failed to
properly assess the contaminants at the Jefferson site, but may
have withheld what they did know from state officials in a rush to
receive $11,834,812 in state land purchase funding,'' the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the Los Angeles Unified School District,
however, contends that the district handled everything at the site
correctly. He said he could not comment on the report because he
had not read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, issues at this site were properly
investigated and remediated, received appropriate agency
approvals,'' said Barry Groveman.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 assessment by the district, with state oversight,
concluded that there is no health threat to students, although the
state committee report questions whether the remediation efforts
will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminated site was found by coincidence _ an EPA
scientist visiting a Superfund site ``strolled across the street to
the Jefferson site and was shocked to find it was a school,'' the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   Toxic problems at the 15-acre site would have been hard to
overlook, according to state officials' testimony. It once held a
World War II defense plant, furniture manufacturers, metal plating
operations and a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Once the land was acquired, the district's two phases of
environmental reports were deficient in their size and scope,
according to testimony by Jesse Huff, director of toxic substances
control for the California Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Huff chides the district for failing to
adequately follow the law. ``Local school districts, particularly
the largest one in the state, should be able to read the law,'' he
testified.
</P>
<P>
   James Wakefield, an attorney for the district, testified that
the LAUSD was impeded in its efforts to find out past uses of the
site because of a national security blackout surrounding defense
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The report said it was still unclear why the site was approved
by an inspector for the California Department of Education in 1989.
The department's approval process is also under examination.
</P>
<P>
   Huff said Cal-EPA's oversight failed at Jefferson because the
agency was not informed about problems there until 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A thorough environmental assessment wasn't conducted until after
the school was substantially completed and the California EPA
forced the LAUSD to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Melodie Dove, environmental organizer for Concerned Citizens of
South Central, said the organization began fighting the
construction of Jefferson Middle School two years ago, after a
neighbor received notice that Cal-EPA would test his property for
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   She said the school district failed to properly protect the
mostly African-American and Latino students from that hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an environmental justice issue,'' Dove said. ``It
says if they're building a school in South Central or East L.A.,
they don't go through all the steps of determining what the
contaminants are and doing possible cleanup and mitigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
