A9733 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-DIAMONDBACKS     07-30 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS END IT EARLY  
 D-BACKS CAN'T DIG OUT FROM 6-RUN DEFICIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Amaury Telemaco had toweled off after his night's
work, the Diamondbacks found themselves in a six-run hole. The
worst part? The third inning wasn't even over yet.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Diamondbacks managed to chip away at the Chicago
Cubs' lead, they were never really in a position to seriously
threaten during Wednesday night's 7-3 loss at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks blew a chance to surpass the Florida Marlins
for the worst record in the majors, but Telemaco's awful evening
gave the Diamondbacks virtually no chance to escape baseball's
overall cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't locating my pitches,'' Telemaco said. ``In addition,
they were swinging the bats well. I needed to get ahead in the
count and I didn't do that. During the course of a season a pitcher
will go through games like I did tonight. It's just no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of spring training, Manager Buck Showalter
has been preaching how the Diamondbacks would be a work in progress
during this inaugural season, with players receiving chances and
needing to seize the opportunities when they're given in order to
make a mark.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the club has languished in last place in the
National League West and has had one of the worst records in ball
season, the Diamondbacks players are under pressure to perform in
order to keep their job.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco, claimed off waivers from these very same Cubs, was
picked up with the intention of getting a first-hand look at a
24-year-old right-hander who has shown promise in short glimpses.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco is not immune to losing his spot in the rotation. Many
more night like Wednesday, when he allowed six runs on eight hits
while facing just 15 batters before being lifted with no outs in
the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco's ERA in his last three starts is 7.47. He has won just
once in his seven starts and the Diamondbacks are 2-5 in games
Telemaco has started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amaury has pitched well for us,'' Manager Buck Showalter said.
``He'll get the ball again in five days.''
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco breezed through the first inning, retiring Lance
Johnson, Mickey Morandini and Sammy Sosa, who failed to his a grand
slam or a home run, consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   But the second inning offered a precursor to Telemaco's evening.
Mark Grace and Henry Rodriguez blasted a pair of solo home runs to
lead off the inning, Grace's splashing down in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The first six batters Telemaco faced in the third inning all
reached and Showalter made the quick jog to the mound to summon
help from the bullpen in the form of the suddenly dependable Willie
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher most likely to take Telemaco's place in the rotation
is Banks, who inherited a pair of runners on base with no outs in
the third from Telemaco but got out of the inning without either
runner advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Banks went on to three innings, retiring nine of the 10 batters
he faced while allowing a meaningless two-out single to Tyler
Houston in the fifth. Houston's single snapped a string of 22
consecutive batters retired by Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Banks, a former first-round draft pick of the Minnesota Twins,
has pitched brilliantly since utilizing an arm-flapping,
double-pump windup that seems to have taken him back to his most
successful period, as a high school senior in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie has pitched well in situations given to him,''
Showalter said. ``How you pitch in those situations dictates if you
are elevated to other situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter admitted the Diamondbacks have talked about giving
Banks a start or two at some point.
</P>
<P>
   For right now, we'll see,'' Showalter said. ``It's a two-edged
sword. You hate to change someone who's doing so well in his
role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
