landscape history at Harvard, is part of a new flowering of
interest in looking at how culture shapes the wide, mundane world
around us. His evocative new book, ``Outside Lies Magic: Regaining
History and Awareness in Everyday Places'' (Walker), is a clarion
call to what he calls, almost mystically, ``exploration'' _
wandering on foot or bike, in search not of cardiovascular fitness
but of mental agility. Ultimately, it's about becoming the
proverbial person on whom nothing is lost. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-KITCHEN (Undated) _ Ten years ago, I brought my family to
rural Nebraska and built a farmstead from scratch. We bought an
abandoned house for $350 and moved it onto the land, but some
things we had to build: a machine shed, a garage and _ a summer
kitchen. The reason our little building in the backyard is called a
summer kitchen is that it's the perfect place to make tomato sauce
and at the same time enjoy the rattle of cottonwood leaves while
dozing in a hammock. By Robert Welsch.
</P>
