<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENMAN UNFAZED BY TARANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Tarango lost, in order, his cool, a racket and his match
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Beach resident snapped during his second-round
match vs. England's Tim Henman _ and snapped his racket over his
knee _ during a 7-6 (8-6), 7-5 loss in the Mercedes-Benz Cup at Los
Angeles Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Henman, the tournament's second seed and a Wimbledon
semifinalist, was unfazed by Tarango's sideshows, coming back from
a 4-1 deficit in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's probably one of my good points, is I'm able to
stay positive and turn things around,'' Henman said.
</P>
<P>
   Even while his opponent is self-combusting.
</P>
<P>
   Tarango began verbal volleying with chair umpire Norm Chryst and
the linesmen in the first set and escalated his antics in the
second. He broke his racket and tossed it into the first row of the
crowd after Henman broke his serve to cut the lead to 4-3.
Tarango's outburst drew a warning from the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just disappointed with myself for losing my serve when I
was ahead like that,'' he said. ``I think it was just a little
machismo racket break. I just wanted to clear my head.''
</P>
<P>
   After going down 30-love in the next game, Tarango decided to
take a unscheduled water break, drawing a time-violation warning.
He also drew boos from the home crowd on his way back to the
baseline as one fan yelled ``Head case!''
</P>
<P>
   Henman tuned it all out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it upset my rhythm at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the world's 11th-ranked player said he was grateful
for the tough match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is my first tournament since Wimbledon, and
I'm really pleased with the way I'm playing,'' he said. ``It's
ideal to have a tough match like this as long as you win. You don't
want to have a tough match and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a calmer Tarango blasted tennis officiating in
general, calling it ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of line calls and when officials overrule is not
good,'' he said. ``The same people have been doing it since I was 7
years old. I mean !ital!literally!off! the same people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balls are hitting half on the line and they're calling them
out. It brings the quality of tennis down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarango also complained of dizziness, which he said affects his
serves. He plans to see a specialist in Beverly Hills today to
examine his neck and spine.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the L.A. tournament for the first time, Henman now
finds himself in the quarterfinals. His opponent is seventh-seed
Byron Black of Zimbabwe and USC, who defeated Gianluca Pozzi 6-3,
6-2 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   In other singles matches Wednesday, Santa Monica's Michael Joyce
defeated Armenia's Sargis Sargsian 6-3, 4-6, 6-2, and Guillame
Raoux _ coming off Tuesday's upset of third seed Goran Ivanisevic _
defeated Kenneth Carlsen in a 2-hour, 47-minute marathon that took
three tiebreakers, 7-6 (9-7), 6-7 (1-7), 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday doubles, Grant Stafford and Kevin Ullyett defeated
Brandon Coupe and Kent Kinnear 6-3, 6-3; No.2 Martin Damm and Jim
Grabb defeated Jan-Michael Gambill and Vince Spadea 6-4, 6-2;
third-seeded Patrick Rafter and Sandon Stolle defeated Tuomas
Ketola and David Roditi 7-6 (6-5), 7-6 (6-4); and Eric Taino and
Adam Peterson defeated brothers Luke and Murphy Jensen 4-6, 6-3,
6-2; and Marcos Ondruska defeated Byron Black and Pat Galbraith 7-6
(6-2), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's late match, No. 1 seed Patrick Rafter won his
first-round match, defeating Ramon Delgado 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
