<HEADER>
A9739 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CROUSE-LADN     07-30 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ LEFT BEHIND FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Everybody assumes the hardest leg of Orlando
Hernandez' incredible journey ended when a low-flying U.S. Coast
Guard chopper happened upon a cluster of eight castaways on a spit
of land called the Anguilla Cay one day late last December.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed pitcher and his wife, Norris Bosch, were among
the Cuban refugees who flit for freedom on a 20-foot boat that was
constructed from scrap wood and guided by a compass composed of
household magnets.
</P>
<P>
   The leaky boat somehow supported its occupants for 10 hours
before sinking and Hernandez and the others managed to swim a mile
to the cay, where they stayed and prayed for deliverance. On the
fourth day, the whirlybird came. It might as well have plunked
Hernandez down in a whirlpool; ever since then he has been tugged
this way and that by the highest highs and the lowest lows.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year, $6.6-million contract that Hernandez signed with
the New York Yankees is a matter of public record and, thanks to
his sterling start, no longer a topic of public debate. The
28-year-old rookie carried a record of 5-2 and an earned-run
average of 2.43 into his eighth start Wednesday night against the
Angels at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   What few people know are the hardships Hernandez continues to
endure even as the Yankees challenge the all-time single-season win
record.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, Hernandez' heart is like the boat that carried
him from Cuba, away from his two daughters, ages 7 and 3. It's
leaking and no amount of shipbuilding magnate George Steinbrenner's
money or resources can render it buoyant.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first-base coach, understands better
than most what makes Hernandez' heart sink, and not just because he
lives in the same mid-Manhattan hotel as the player.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenal was one of the last Cuban-born players to enter the
U.S. legally, in the early 1960s, before Cuban Communist leader
Fidel Castro _ himself a former pitcher of some renown _ bolted the
door shut.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old Cardenal signed with the Giants at the age of
16. He didn't see either of his parents again until he was 35 and
in the ebbing stages of an 18-year major-league career. The longing
for family that Cardenal felt all those years now permeates from
Hernandez' pores in the quiet moments they spend together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he's struggling a little bit,'' Cardenal said of the
pitcher known as ``El Duque.'' ``I'm not talking on the field. He's
pitching great, he's got great money, he's got the glamour of
pitching for the Yankees. But there's something missing in his life
that's important and that's the daughters he left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez never thought he'd leave Cuba right up until the week
he did. A longtime national team member, Hernandez had
opportunities to defect but he never did, explaining to would-be
go-betweens that he'd rather have 5 million Cuban fans cheering his
name than $5 million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, though, his younger half-brother, Livan, did defect. A
year later, Orlando was unceremoniously dropped from the national
team, lest he follow Livan's footsteps to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Hernandez petitioned for reinstatement. On Dec. 15,
two months after Livan had earned World Series MVP honors for his
pitching in Florida's title run, Hernandez was summoned by
state-security agents and told in no uncertain terms that his
playing days were over.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was crushed. If there was one thing he loved more than
his flesh and blood, it was the game that coarses through his
veins. Ten days after the meeting with Cuban officials, Hernandez
made his escape, leaving a large chunk of his life behind.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenal can't imagine how he did it. ``I don't think I'd have
the nerve,'' he said. ``All you need is a 3-foot tall wave to flip
the boat. I don't think I could have risked my life like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of Hernandez' desire to play baseball is dizzying to
his new teammates. It also has been instructive. When Hernandez
walked into the clubhouse the first day and saw two pairs of new
shoes sitting there for him, his first reaction was there had been
a mistake and he needed to give one pair back.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the ballplayer's standard $68 per diem, which is
almost as much as Hernandez was drawing in a YEAR at his job as a
rehabilitation therapist in a psychiatric hospital in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   His childlike joy at all the perks of being a professional has
been mildly contagious, which is saying something considering he is
among players whose salaries form the highest payroll in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think his attitude has rubbed off,'' said catcher
Joe Girardi. ``When you see how much he appreciates everything and
you think about what he went through to get to this level, it's
inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez' pitching has been a revelation. He has shown no rust
from his two-year layoff. With his high-leg kick (he nearly bumps
his chin with his knee), chameleon delivery and stubborn
competitiveness, Hernandez reminds many people of Cuban
right-hander an former major-leaguer Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   Count among them Tiant, who spent a leisurely afternoon
conversing with Hernandez in Spanish last weekend during Old
Timers' Day festivities at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a smart pitcher,'' Tiant said from his home in Savannah,
Ga. ``When he's on the mound he makes you feel like he's in command
of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because off the mound there's so much he can't
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
