<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TROUNCE YANKEES, 10-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The New York Yankees win so often that their
losses are generally forgotten. But Joe Torre will no doubt
remember how Anaheim embarrassed the Yankees on Wednesday night,
10-5, how his team embarrassed itself, for perhaps the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   After performing with unusual energy Tuesday, the Yankees
sleepwalked through this game, like a second-division club playing
out its schedule. They didn't execute properly, they didn't make
adjustments, and in a couple of instances, they simply did not
hustle.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez gave up 13 hits and 10 runs in three and
one-third innings, the most runs and hits allowed by a Yankees
pitcher this year, and confirmed once more that unless he starts to
pitch inside more aggressively against left-handed hitters, they
are going to hammer him.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels' Tim Salmon finished off Hernandez with a
titanic two-run homer that almost cleared the bullpens that rest
beyond the left-center field fence, Hernandez began stepping off
the mound even before Torre arrived and was already en route to the
dugout when he handed the ball to his manager. Hernandez wore the
slight smirk that erupted on his face in the midst of the fourth
inning, as Anaheim blooped in a couple of hits.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole, awful fourth inning was no laughing matter. It
began when Garret Anderson hit a liner to right field, where Paul
O'Neill twisted and turned awkwardly before it went over his head
for a double. With a better route, O'Neill may or may not have been
able to make the catch; the ball was scorched, no doubt
contributing to the difficultly of the play.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was no gray area about O'Neill's effort on the
next play. Dave Hollins rolled a single through the right side of
the infield, and O'Neill, assuming Anderson would score and Hollins
would stop at first, loped in slowly. But Hollins, watching
O'Neill, suddenly charged around first and easily beat O'Neill's
belated throw into second base.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out Phil Nevin, and then the parade started.
Jason Baughman, a line single. Gary DiSarcina, a bloop hit over the
infield, scoring Hollins. Orlando Palmeiro ripped a two-run double,
and when the relay came back to the infield, Palmeiro was halfway
between second and third; Tino Martinez, the cutoff man, flipped to
Scott Brosius to begin the rundown.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way the play came together, however, the Yankees
were left with nobody covering third base, after Brosius initially
flipped to second, and Palmeiro scampered into the bag. Any number
of Yankees, from left fielder Chad Curtis to catcher Jorge Posada,
might have been responsible for the blown rundown, but in general,
the Yankees simply reacted slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds singled home Palmeiro and then immediately stole
second base. Darin Erstad, the eighth batter of the inning, dumped
a single over shortstop, and Hernandez, moving to back up home
plate, grinned as he ran home, disgusted by his bad luck on this
and several other hits. Posada patted him on the side,
commiserating.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez got ahead in the count to Salmon, no balls and two
strikes, and threw a changeup that hardly moved as it reached home
plate, thigh high. Salmon utterly killed it, and there was
Hernandez, smirking, Angels 10, Yankees 2.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson followed that with a single off the reliever
Darren Holmes, the seventh straight hit in the inning, the Angels
tied a club record. In all, Anaheim sent 11 batters to the plate in
the fourth, scoring eight runs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre met
with Hernandez and told him he needed to throw inside more, and in
his next outing, against Toronto, Hernandez did this diligently.
But pitching last week and again on Wednesday night, Hernandez once
again remained focused on the outside part of the plate,
particularly when pitching to left-handed batters. The result is
that the left-handers, well aware of this trend, hang over the
plate fearlessly, not concerned whatsoever about Hernandez pumping
a fastball near their chest.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, left-handed batters had 9 hits in 13 at-bats
against Hernandez, helping to propel his earned run average upward
by more than a run, from 2.43 to 3.66, and reduce his won-lost
record to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   The night had started so promisingly, Darryl Strawberry giving
the Yankees a 1-0 lead in the top of the second, with his 17th home
run, against the knuckleballer Steve Sparks. When the Angels scored
twice in the bottom of the second, Derek Jeter unloaded a home run
into the right field stands, tying the game. The Yankees, it
seemed, had the same energy and efficiency they displayed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
