<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING NEEDS TO SHOW ITS TEETH TO TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Here we are worrying about where Randy Johnson will be
in three days. We should be worrying about where Mike Tyson will be
in three months, since he already has shown us Vincent Van Gogh
wasn't the only lobe-lopping nut to walk the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In boxing, the fate of one psychologically troubled man _ for
whom no amount of boxing or money ever will fill the void of his
self-proclaimed darkness _ is secondary to the fate of a gigantic,
smarmy industry.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a betting person, as so many boxing fans are, better
put your money down on Tyson making a comeback in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   On the boardwalk, you'll be having some fists.
</P>
<P>
   On the boardwalk, people will be cheering for blood.
</P>
<P>
   On the boardwalk, the purse will be $50 million, most of which
will line the bottomless pockets of the irrepressible and now
unconvictable Don King.
</P>
<P>
   There is little reason to doubt that a Tyson rematch with
Evander Holyfield is coming to a pay-per-view screen near you,
probably just in time for the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   You can only begin to imagine the forthcoming froth of hype:
</P>
<P>
   Ear ye. Ear ye. Step right up, folks. A Christmas special with
``Jaws-of-Life'' Mike.
</P>
<P>
   When the big bout is about to happen, the whole
sports-entertainment world will start to get jiggy with it, as if
on a super-sized dose of Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a big-time heavyweight fight that gets
everyone all giddy and jittery. NBA stars fly into town on rented
jets. Hollywood stars make the scene. Glamour and glory surround
one of society's sick little addictions.
</P>
<P>
   We all understand that boxing needs Mike Tyson, the steamroller
of fury who has prompted every person who has ever watched him
fight to wonder where such rage and brutality come from in a single
human being.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing needs Tyson because there was no real heavyweight action
for the three years he was in prison serving time on a rape
conviction, nor has there been a compelling heavyweight bout since
Tyson's license was revoked a year ago, right after the June 28,
1997 fight in which Tyson viciously knawed off pieces of
Holyfield's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who knows the economics of boxing and gambling
understands that the great Garden State of New Jersey also needs
Mike Tyson, regardless of that bloody act of carnivorous horror he
committed in full view of every pay-per-view and MGM Grand Casino
ringside customer.
</P>
<P>
   That is why it will be extremely difficult for state regulators
in New Jersey to turn down Tyson's request for a license to once
again do his work with his sledgehammer fists that like to drill
nose bones through brains.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the story is that New Jersey should deny Tyson
entry to the ring. They should uphold the decision of the Nevada
State Athletic Commission that revoked Tyson's license. And any
other state before which Tyson and his handlers appeal also should
deny Tyson the chance to fight.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Tyson and his people should be forced to
return to Vegas. Let Nevada finish its business on this matter.
</P>
<P>
   The loopholes in boxing are many, which is why Tyson has sought
a new start in New Jersey. But even without codified rules, the
decision whether Tyson should ever fight again should be left to
the state where he committed his own, ugly undoing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the very grounds for Tyson's return to the ring in New
Jersey are whether, according to the three-member panel, Tyson has
the ``good character, honesty, integrity and responsibility'' to
box in that state.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey panel has 45 days to find a way to make palatable
(pardon the expression) an excuse for his re-admittance to the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   And with as much as $200 million in tickets, pay-per-view and
casino receipts riding on another Tyson fight, it might not take
New Jersey regulators long to overlook what's criminal and what's
not.
</P>
<P>
   One question, though: How can a man who does not merely bite an
opponent's ear, but bites off a piece of his ear ever be deemed
responsible or to possess integrity?
</P>
<P>
   That alone should be enough of a question for the New Jersey
regulators to dismiss Tyson's request.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson snapped last June, when he was in trouble early in the
bout and Holyfield's head-butting had put Tyson into an
instinctively animalistic panic, it is safe to assume he would
resort to a similar tactic again.
</P>
<P>
   But that sort of logic is not likely with this impending ruling.
It should be easy enough for New Jersey regulators to cop a
position that it is not up to them to terminally condemn a fighter
such as Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   It will be easy enough to say Tyson has served his sentence,
paid his $3 million fine. The wiggle room is more than there for
this panel to give Tyson another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will be off to the boxing ring again, where the drama
surrounding and infesting boxing is almost as ugly and animalistic
as the horrible stuff that goes on inside the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
