<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9756 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      07-30 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG DOG' CORTEZ KENNEDY GETS BORING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Shhhh. The Big Dog is napping.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping? Cortez Kennedy? In the middle of the day?
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was once the scourge of Seahawks training camps,
stalking the halls of the players' dormitory in the middle of the
night because he had too much nervous energy to sleep. Whenever
there was a prank to be pulled, the rotund one was the primary
tugger. When laughter would erupt during pre-practice stretching,
the Pro Bowl defensive tackle was almost always the instigator.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Kennedy naps for an hour between practices and is
doing his best to blend into the Eastern Washington University
landscape. He doesn't even wear the customized practice jerseys
with his nicknames _ ``Big Dog'' and ``Tez'' _ across the
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten boring,'' he offers with a rumbling belly laugh.
``I'm even boring myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kennedy calls boredom, defensive line coach Tommy Brasher
calls acting his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you write that off to maturity,'' Brasher said.
``Cortez is right up against 30. He's still got a little of that
kid in him, but not as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this kinder, gentler Kennedy is rooted in what has been an
offseason-long love fest.
</P>
<P>
   In April, they renamed Main Street in his hometown of Wilson,
Ark., Cortez Kennedy Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the club signed him to a three-year, $17 million
contract extension, all but guaranteeing that Kennedy will play his
entire career with the team that made him the third pick overall in
the 1990 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's his realization that this game he still loves to
play has become serious business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win. We haven't got time to be playing around,''
Kennedy said. ``It's a do-or-die situation for a lot of people. We
want to keep everyone around.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it was the reality slap that was missing eight games
last year because of injuries _ the first of Kennedy's NFL career
in which he had started a club-record 100 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when you've made your last play or played your
last game,'' Kennedy said. ``You don't want to think about it. But
when I first got hurt I felt as low as I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason _ or reasons _ a change has come over
Kennedy from the days when two of his more memorable escapades
involved videotape and closets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Brasher was looking to make a good impression on the
players he had just been hired to coach. But during one of the
first defensive line meetings at training camp, he couldn't find
the videotape of that day's practice.
</P>
<P>
   As Brasher searched in vain, Kennedy shook in silent laughter in
the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Brasher did get even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made them watch the same tape over again, and the other
guys got on Cortez pretty good,'' he said with a smile of
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Kennedy's teammates, they didn't have the
authority to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite pranks in the dorm was to wait for another
player to get up and use the bathroom in the middle of the night.
Kennedy then would sneak into the room and hide in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd wait 'til you were back in bed, all comfy, then come
bounding out at you,'' defensive end Michael Sinclair said. ``And I
mean, that's intimidating _ a big ol' guy coming out of your closet
at midnight going, `Ahhhhhh.' Then he'd go down the hallway
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cortez is the real bogeyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair appreciates the serious side of Kennedy, and admires
what he feels is the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes with the expectations, the sense of urgency
that is here to win,'' Sinclair said. ``He doesn't have time to
fool around anymore. There are a lot of blitz packages we're
putting in. I find myself with my nose in the playbook at night. I
barely have time to even look at television.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've thrown so much at us, that even Cortez has had to get
in there and study.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dean Wells, for one, isn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't changed. He's just been a little more quiet than
usual this first week and a half,'' Wells said. ``Cortez is still
Cortez. He may take a few days off from joking around, but he lives
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming. Just wait. When the guys get a little flat,
Cortez is always there to say something goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day when Wells was asking Kennedy why he was being so
quiet during warmups, strength and conditioning coach Dana LeDuc
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dana told Dean, `Cortez is being so good because he's getting
ready to move into the front office after he retires,''' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a good laugh, Kennedy added: ``I guess it's only fair.
I've always been messin' with the guys and they're messin' with me
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
