<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMERS CARRY RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ If baseball weren't a series of endless
tomorrows, Scott Hatteberg said, failure would be that much harder
to accept.
</P>
<P>
   But why worry about striking out four times in a game, Hatteberg
said, when you know that in the span of a single spin cycle, you
may have the chance to hit a home run?
</P>
<P>
   That's how it played out for the catcher, who hit one of three
Red Sox home runs Wednesday night in a 10-2 rout of the Oakland
A's, making it two wins in a row at the start of the team's longest
trip of the season, five in their last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Former A's pitcher John Wasdin, in his second start since
replacing the Korean Kid, Jin Ho Cho, in the Sox rotation, held his
former mates to two runs and six hits in six innings for his first
win this season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn and Nomar Garciaparra also homered for the Red Sox,
who broke a 2-2 tie with four runs in the sixth. Garciaparra, who
has nine hits in his last four games, including three home runs,
hit his seventh homer since the All-Star break and 20th of the
season and seems as comfortable hitting cleanup as he did leadoff,
in the third spot, and in his backyard playing Wiffle Ball. He's
had three hits in both games here.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who have had 11 extra-base hits in the two games,
have beaten the A's in all seven meetings this season. Oakland has
now lost nine in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jimy Williams shuffled his lineup, installing Garciaparra
in the No. 4 spot with Vaughn sandwiched between the shortstop and
No. 2 hitter John Valentin, the Sox have scored no fewer than five
runs in a game and are averaging 6.8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess maybe I just had a gut feeling that was the best way
for us to go,'' the manager said. ``Put 'em in there, let 'em play.
I don't know how many games you use as a barometer, but you just do
what you think is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the biggest difference he sees in Wasdin since his
return from Pawtucket is the use of his split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having that split has helped him a lot,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe, who allowed just two hits in three scoreless
innings, was credited with his third save.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's home run, a low line drive that traveled at
bullet-train speed into the left-field seats, came off A's loser
Mike Oquist and made it 3-2. Two outs later, Mike Benjamin drew a
walk and scored ahead of Hatteberg's ninth home run, one fewer than
he hit as a rookie last season. The Red Sox added another run when
DH Keith Mitchell, playing because Midre Cummings was a late
scratch with a sore right wrist, singled, stole second, and scored
on Darren Lewis's second single.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Hatteberg said he couldn't recall ever striking
out four times in a game, as he did Tuesday night. Hatteberg
whiffed twice against A's starter Jimmy Haynes, once against lefty
reliever Buddy Groom, and once against righty reliever T.J.
Mathews.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that had happened to me when I was in the minor leagues, I
would have really been torn up,'' Hatteberg said. ``Sure, I was
upset, but we won the game and I realize, especially as a catcher,
that a lot of great hitters get punched out. It happened to me last
night, but baseball is just too difficult because it's
day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   With his right hamstring packed in more ice nightly than the
fish peddled back home on Atlantic Avenue, Vaughn was no threat to
add to the Red Sox' string of inside-the-park home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Vaughn made the same circuit as teammates
Garciaparra and Lewis on their inside-the-park jobs in the previous
two games, but at a more leisurely pace. Vaughn was credited with
his 26th home run of the season and first in 10 games when his
opposite-field drive in the fourth hit the glove of leaping left
fielder Rickey Henderson and struck the base of a TV camera set on
a platform just above the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ball came back to the field, Vaughn stopped at
second with what he assumed was a double. But third-base umpire Tim
Welke spun his right index finger, the signal that it was a home
run, the first extra-base hit of the night for the Red Sox after
six the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox added another run in the inning on singles by
Garciaparra, Darren Bragg, and Benjamin to tie the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   After their uprising in the sixth, they iced the A's with a
four-run, five-hit ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a Bay area native, had three singles Wednesday night,
giving him five hits in the last two games here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
