A9780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-RAPIDS     07-30 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-RAPIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION'S RAPID DOWNFALL CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The ``Fort'' section behind the goal was
difficult to ignore Wednesday night during the Revolution's 3-1
loss to the Colorado Rapids at Foxboro Stadium. The fans chanted,
``Resig-nation,'' in place of ``Revo-lution,'' and ``Dead Man
Walking,'' referring to coach Thomas Rongen, who guided New England
to its eighth successive home defeat, extending its Major League
Soccer record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even heard it before the game started,'' Rongen said. ``I've
said the last five days that I am extremely disappointed in what
the team has done and extremely disappointed in my performance.
These fans deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the team in a position to win. We had more chances and
we didn't execute. We created more chances but we walk away with a
loss. The game plan was sound; unfortunately, we didn't pull the
trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have won twice, in Dallas and Tampa, since their
last home victory May 10. They have 16 points in 22 games, the
worst record in the league, but remain in contention for the final
playoff place with 10 games left.
</P>
<P>
   But though Rongen has been able to analyze the Revolution's
defeats, he has been unable to break the losing pattern. The
Revolution failed to control the midfield, partially a function of
having to move Dutchman Edwin Gorter to sweeper as the defense
faltered.
</P>
<P>
   And the defense failed again against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Balboa converted a free kick in the third minute as the
Revolution started slowly for the second successive time on a
three-game homestand. The Rapids had chances to increase their lead
before the Revolution tied the score as Raul Diaz Arce headed in
his 14th goal of the season on an Imad Baba cross in the 37th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution displayed little offensive cohesiveness,
they continued to threaten.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rapids broke the tie as Ross Paule fed Paul Bravo, who
chipped over goalkeeper Jeff Causey in the 21st minute of the
second half. Jamaican striker Wolde Harris, who replaced Waldir at
halftime, clinched the win in the 84th minute as the Revolution
made a desperate attempt to rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Revolution is struggling a little bit,'' Colorado coach
Glenn Myernick said. ``We never let them settle into their
formation, didn't let them get their rhythm, and put them back on
their heels early.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good players on the Revolution. They have
leaders within the team. I believe Thomas has enough leaders to
pull them out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, those leaders have been unable to change the Revolution's
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lack of execution in the final third is obvious,'' Rongen
said. ``We gave a goal and got down early, but it was not because
we defended poorly. To be put in that position is tough, especially
when everyone is playing for playoff positions. Every player is
pushing so hard to help the team that we have become our own worst
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado went to Adrian Paz on the right side early, and Paz
went past Janusz Michallik to cross, setting up the first goal.
Mike Burns failed to clear the cross, and Balboa was fouled by
Oscar Pareja 25 yards from the goal. Balboa then sent the free kick
low past the defensive wall and into the left side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, who host San Jose next Wednesday, attracted
13,074 fans, their lowest attendance since their May 10 win over
Tampa in a rainstorm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
