<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-REACTI     07-30 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION PLAYERS GET FANS' MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Their stretch of home futility now stands at
eight straight losses, a Major League Soccer record, but Wednesday
night at Foxboro Stadium, the Revolution got a graphic indication
of their sorry state that transcended mere statistics.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in their three-year existence, they heard
boos. At home. From the people renowned for being the most
supportive fans in the league.
</P>
<P>
   As they left the field following a 3-1 loss to the Colorado
Rapids, the Revolution heard undeniable evidence of the discord on
the home front as the crowd of 13,074 hooted them.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, these folks _ who are coming to the games in ever
dwindling numbers _ aren't happy. But neither are the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel sorry for the crowd,'' said sweeper Edwin Gorter. ``We
were talking about that before the game. This time they boo you.
That's normal. We give these people nothing and they get frustrated
just like us, but they have to pay for it and we get paid for it.
That's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction surprised Joe-Max Moore, but he could understand
it. ``I noticed it immediately because you usually don't hear it in
Foxboro,'' the third-year veteran forward said. ``They pay their
hard-earned money to come out and see us lose. It's disappointing
for them. It's normal across the world in terms of soccer teams
that don't do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Team captain Mike Burns echoed those sentiments. ``It's to be
expected,'' he said. ``You look at our home games and the record we
have (3-8 in Foxborough). We don't like it but it's part of it, and
they had the right to boo us. If I knew what we should do, we'd do
it. I don't know what we should do. I'm at a loss for words right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Revolution can make amends by not falling behind
early. Wednesday night the Rapids took a 1-0 lead three minutes
into the game. ``What we need to do is go ahead sometimes, make it
1-0 for us and not always run behind a goal,'' said Gorter. ``Then
we had to play 30 minutes to make it 1-1. It costs a lot of energy.
It costs a lot of power. And then 10 minutes later, they score
again and you have to get a goal again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the same old story _ the Revolution were forced to
gamble, and the next thing they knew, the Rapids were up, 3-1. ``If
it's 1-0 for us, they have to come and we can play counterattack,''
Gorter said. ``Now it's us who have to attack, attack, attack, and
you have to be afraid for the counterattack. We knew before the
game that this (Colorado) is a very good counter team.''
</P>
<P>
   With the All-Star break here, the Revolution don't play again
until next Wednesday when they face the San Jose Clash in their
third consecutive home game. No meetings are planned during the
hiatus. Everything's already been said. Several times, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say this is a big mistake, this is a big mistake,''
Gorter said. ``We all know that, but at this particular moment,
we're not able to resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Burns, ``Three years I've been in this situation, and
we've had players-only meetings and we've had coaches-and-players
meetings. We've had it all. The bottom line is we're not getting it
done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-30 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TRADE TALKS HEAT UP AS MARINERS GO COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As of Wednesday night, the Mariners still hadn't let
Randy Johnson slip through their fingers. But their grip is
loosening.
</P>
<P>
   With an 8-7 loss to Cleveland a secondary issue, Seattle
appeared ready to pull the trigger on a multi-player trade
involving their disgruntled pitching ace, possibly as soon as
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours into Wednesday night's game, the Madison Square Garden
sportswire reported and retracted that the Mariners had traded
Johnson and reliever Mike Timlin to the Yankees for starting
pitcher Hideki Irabu, closer Ramiro Mendoza and second baseman
Homer Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in the Kingdome pressbox, Mariner president Chuck
Armstrong said no deal had been struck with New York Wednesday
night, acknowledging only that Seattle officials were talking with
several teams _ the club's first confirmation that Johnson was,
indeed, back on the trading block. On June 2, the Mariners
announced in a terse statement that the lefty would remain with the
team for the rest of the season and not be dealt.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also cautioned Wednesday night that a trade wouldn't
necessarily be made with the Yankees, apparently suggesting that
the Mariners were now receiving several offers for their pitching
ace and waiting to see who comes in with the best offer.
</P>
<P>
   With all this going on, a stone-faced Johnson was spotted by a
television camera peeking out of the clubhouse tunnel while Timlin
was seated in the bullpen, laughing. Timlin later would pitch to
three batters in the ninth, and come up with three outs.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, manager Lou Piniella was in no mood to talk about
possible transactions involving his club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to talk to Woody about trades,'' he said, referring
to Woody Woodward, vice president of baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin was surprised to hear about the latest rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I've heard of it. Tell me about it,'' Timlin
said. ``I'm still here and they haven't called me or told me
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman David Segui called the trade rumors ``just part of
the game.'' But he said he hadn't ``seen anything so far that
seemed worth the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering what happened Wednesday night, a deal couldn't come
soon enough. Shoddy defense and inconsistent relief pitching fueled
the Mariners' second straight defeat to Cleveland at home.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 7, the Indians' Jim Thome decided things
in the eighth inning, belting his 29th homer into the right-field
seats off reliever Greg McCarthy. The defeat dropped the Mariners
10 games behind AL West-leading Anaheim, which was a 10-5 winner
over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella didn't hide his desire for some much-needed relief
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland has a good bullpen and we're losing a lot of close
games to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle entered the contest with the third-highest error total
in the big leagues, 97, and added two more _ on the same play. That
effectively killed another efficient offensive output, one that
included a three-run homer by Jay Buhner to erase a 7-4 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner miscues were hard to overlook.
</P>
<P>
   Normally steady Ken Griffey Jr. had a first-inning fly ball
deflect off his glove in center for what initially was ruled an
error, leading to the Indians' first run. An inning later, after
much consultation, the play was ruled a single.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reversing the next two Mariner bumbles, both coming
on the same, bizarre play.
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle clinging to a 4-3 lead, and the Indians' Jeff
Branson on first, Kenny Lofton dropped a bunt down the third-base
line. There to greet it was Mariner third baseman Russ Davis and
his team-high 27 errors.
</P>
<P>
   He threw the ball into the Indian bullpen for No. 28.
</P>
<P>
   As Lofton sped around the bases, the play was far from done.
Buhner tracked the ball down near the bench behind the practice
mound and came up firing. Third base was his target. Unfortunately,
no one except Lofton was there when the ball arrived, with Davis
still lingering near the plate. Lofton was awarded home when the
ball skipped into the stands. Buhner was awarded the error, his
first of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When the inning was mercifully over, Cleveland had sent 10 men
to the plate and scored six runs, and Seattle's starting pitcher,
Ken Cloude, had taken a seat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cloude wasn't too sharp,'' Piniella said. ``We got him four
runs real quick and gave them back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third, the Mariners batted around for four runs, plating
them on RBI singles by Alex Rodriguez, Buhner and Davis, and a
run-scoring double by Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Buhner lunged at a Jaret Wright delivery and
swatted it to right-center for a homer, scoring Edgar Martinez, who
had walked, and David Segui, who had singled. The Mariners now have
a major league-best 162 homers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 0244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9790 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-30 0828
