u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-IMPACT-HNS &LR;      07-30 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-IMPACT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL FALLOUT FROM LEWINSKY SCANDAL IN PUBLIC'S HANDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again, President Clinton stands on familiar
territory _ a precipice _ and few people seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the political ramifications of the Monica Lewinsky
scandal seem few for the president, experts say. Many citizens
already have made up their minds about the alleged dalliance and
the alleged cover-up and have moved on to other issues more
important to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `Perils of Pauline.' He's always tied to the train tracks
and always escapes, or up to this point,'' said Stephen Hess, a
presidential expert with the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospect of presidential perjury and obstruction of
justice, if it is a clear-cut and sustained pattern, could rouse
some public ire and force Congress to do what few lawmakers want to
do before the November elections _ hold hearings.
</P>
<P>
   But independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of charges
the president had an affair with Lewinsky when she was a
21-year-old intern and urged her to lie about it appears to be
nearing an end. Lewinsky will testify under immunity and on Aug. 17
Clinton will answer prosecutors' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, the American people have shrugged their
shoulders and if they continue to shrug their shoulders all it is
is another embarrassment for the president. If they start to turn
against him so everyone will be reading those poll figures as if
they are Holy Grail around here, then Congress may have no choice
but to follow up,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   The political impact on the president depends on whether the
public pulse quickens over any revelations in the next few weeks.
``This is in the hands of the people and the people's court,'' Hess
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a California political commentator, said,
``I don't get the sense that anybody outside the beltway gives a
whiff at this point in time. As long as the focus remains on the
Lewinsky matter, as long as the issue under debate is did he have
sex, this is not going to capture the attention of the American
public. This is not a constitutional crisis. If it becomes a debate
on a constitutional crisis then this may change.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts say the main reason for this national yawn: money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a case of much ado about nothing. People often vote
their pocketbooks and the president is keeping people's pocketbooks
filled,'' said Robert Stein, a Rice University pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the economy falls, I think the president will be victim to
anything and everything. If the economy holds up, I just doubt
there will be moral indignation. A substantial majority believe the
president had an affair and they are not greatly distressed by
that,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Stein also said Republicans could face a backlash if the
investigations into Clinton start spooking the stock market and
prompt even more declines. ``There are a lot of baby boomers
looking at their retirement accounts grow, and grow wildly, and if
anything threatens it, they're going to say why did you have to
impeach a president whose economy was roaring because he couldn't
keep his zipper zipped,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Howard Baker, the former Senate Majority Leader who
served on the Watergate committee, said he doubted the case would
lead to impeachment, a murky procedure steeped in politics by its
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to tell. My guess is no it won't. My guess is
the president will be severely embarrassed. My guess is there will
be ample grounds for impeachment inquiry by the House of
Representatives, which must go first. It probably will never reach
the Senate,'' Baker said on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Baker added, ``that's not based so much on the law, which is
murky on impeachment by any measure, but the politics. In fairness,
I don't think anybody wants to handle this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Starr's investigation began in January, Clinton
consistently has garnered 60 percent or greater support in polls
for his job performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people so far have said that his job performance
counts for a lot more than the `he said, she said' argument which
most people don't care about. I think the person who ultimately has
suffered in terms of professional reputation is Mr. Starr,''
contended Lanny Davis, a former White House lawyer, appearing on
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr's probe is reaching a critical point just 100 days
before the Nov. 3 elections that determine the party majority
controlling Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats contend they have a good shot at regaining the House
and Clinton is the main attraction in party plans to raise $18
million for its candidates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were reports that Democrats warned the White
House they would not spring to the president's defense, another
said most members, awed by Clinton's survival abilities, want to
wait and see what happens before pronouncing Clinton as politically
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans since January have planned for a short congressional
session so they could return to the campaign trial and defend their
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incumbents don't want to rock the boat,'' Jeffe said. Still,
she noted Clinton's appearance in California at mid-month to raise
money for Democratic Sen. Barbara Boxer and gubernatorial candidate
Gray Davis will be interesting to watch for signs of a political
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Republicans run a
political risk by fanning the impeachment flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republicans want to be known as the party of
investigation instead of legislation; the party of partisanship
instead of progress, then I believe the voters will punish them.
That's the risk they run,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official signaled that Clinton will maintain there was no
sexual relationship with Lewinsky. ``The truth is the truth. I
believe the president told the truth. I don't doubt him. I believe
him,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jeffe noted, many people have a different take: ``If you
can't lie about sex, what can you lie about?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
