<SLUG> BC-BLACKGAINS-CENSUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINS FOR BLACK MARRIED COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAMON G. MCLEOD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   African American married couples have made progress toward
income equality with whites in the 1990s, but such gains have been
modest or nonexistent for millions of other blacks, according to a
report to be released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Census Bureau also found that blacks now number
34.2 million, or almost 13 percent of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Any study that tries to identify trends in such a large segment
of the nation has to be approached with care, and census officials
were at pains to point out that using a wide brush to paint a
picture of this group would be as foolhardy as doing so with
whites, Latinos or Asians.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are some clear patterns in the data, which
is based on an annual survey of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   The most encouraging is the narrowing of the income gap between
black and white married couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the brightest spot, the area where the most rapid
gains are being made,'' said census bureau demographer Claudette
Bennett, author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the median income for a black married couple was
$41,963, roughly 83 percent of the median income of a white married
couple, which was determined to be $50,190. In 1990, black couples
made 80 percent of what white couples made.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, only 46 percent of black families are headed
by a married couple versus 80 percent of white families.
Single-parent families headed by a black woman had an income of
only $15,530 in 1996. White women who were single parents had
significantly more: $24,700.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underlying problem of families and incomes can be tied
right back to what's happened in our cities for the last 30 years
with the disappearance of manufacturing,'' said Maria Casey,
president of Urban Strategies Council in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are no jobs, people don't get married,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Education levels have continued to rise for African Americans,
with nearly 75 percent of those over age 25 having completed high
school and more than 13 percent earning at least a bachelor's
degree. In 1990, only 66 percent had a high school diploma and 11
percent had a bachelor's.
</P>
<P>
   About 86 percent of whites over age 25 have finished high
school, and roughly one-quarter have a bachelor's.
</P>
<P>
   Casey said the improvement in education is positive, but is
still not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids may be graduating from high school, but what kind of high
school?'' she said. ``They're doing their part, but we have not
upgraded our schools nor have we provided the level of investment
in education that is necessary for them to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Poverty rates continue to be stubbornly high. In 1996, about 26
percent of black families had income below the official federal
poverty lines. This is down a bit from 1993 when 31 percent were
poor, the worst time in this decade. However, black family poverty
rates have bounced between 26 and 33 percent since the 1970s. White
family poverty rates have been between 6 and 11 percent during the
same period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
