A9823 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCERSTUDY-BLOOD-SFC     07-30 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCERSTUDY-BLOOD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD TESTS ADD TO CANCER STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sixteen years ago, more than a million Americans
agreed to reveal nearly every detail of their lives and family
histories _ their health and illnesses, their smoking and drinking,
the medicines they used, the foods they ate, and their environment
from infancy to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   It was all in the interests of cancer research: one of the
largest efforts ever undertaken to ferret out the risk factors in
cancer and find new clues to prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the participants have been followed up regularly
with fresh questionnaires, and although more than 135,000 have
died, the rest remain in the continuing survey.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in an attempt to take the research a critical step
further, the first of more than 1,200 men and women from the San
Francisco Bay area from the original study bared their arms and
added samples of their blood to the long and intimate records of
their lives _ records maintained by researchers since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide study, initiated by the American Cancer Society,
has already yielded vital information on cancer and human
lifestyles; now, with the addition of blood samples to the data,
new scientific information will emerge on the roles that genetics
and molecular biology play in the many forms of cancer, which will
kill an estimated 565,000 Americans this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of 40 volunteer blood donors in the study lined
up Wednesday at a pathology laboratory next to the Mount Diablo
Medical Center in Concord, Calif., and more will soon do the same
at other Bay Area medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the immense project, 77,000 American Cancer
Society volunteers throughout the country helped enroll the 1.2
million participants: people willing to answer highly confidential
questionnaires covering nearly 400 aspects of their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of survey data, analyzed by epidemiologists at major
research centers, has long been mined for detailed lifestyle data,
but the blood of the participants will open new lodes.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 who gave blood samples in Concord were all veterans of
questionnaires, which they have filled out every year or two. They
filled out more as they waited their turn to donate.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid bias in the ultimate analysis of the samples, all the
donors remained anonymous, but most were remarkably similar:
Elderly or close to it, veterans of previous blood donor drives,
eager to help push research forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing something like this is the only way they're ever going
to find a cure,'' said a Concord woman, who confessed she had
fainted many years ago as a first-time blood donor, but never
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given 100 pints to the Alameda-Contra Costa Blood Bank,
so this is nothing new for me,'' said a healthy, upright
74-year-old Walnut Creek man who worked for 34 years at the Alameda
Naval Air Station, has been married for 56 years, and counts four
granddaughters and eight great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have a buddy from our working days who's in hospice care
with pancreatic cancer,'' he said. ``Answering all these questions
and giving a little blood today won't help my friend, but maybe
it'll help our great-grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey has already yielded important preventive information.
Results have shown that in many people, the moderate use of aspirin
and similar nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs significantly
reduces the risk of cancers of the colon, rectum, esophagus and
stomach, which are expected to strike more than 165,000 Americans
this year, the cancer society estimates.
</P>
<P>
   And among the post-menopausal women in the survey, the use of
estrogen replacement therapy also appeared to reduce the risk of
colorectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, more than 60 scientific reports have been published
in medical journals as a result of the cancer society's large-scale
survey, according to Dr. Donald Beerline, a Concord pathologist and
board member of the cancer society's California division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned an enormous amount from our prevention study
already,'' Beerline said, ``but what's exciting now is that because
of all the advances in genetics and molecular biology over the past
15 years, having very large numbers of blood samples will allow us
to link the behavioral and lifestyle data to biology for the first
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, the cancer society plans to collect samples
from 40,000 to 60,000 of the study's volunteer subjects. Each
sample should yield at least 100 sub-samples that will be made
available to cancer researchers for molecular and genetic analysis,
Beerline said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
