<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9957 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-C     07-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WANT TO TAKE IT WITH YOU?
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 2.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When our son Sam was born 21 years ago, we got him
a Social Security number that he'll keep for life. Someday, Sam's
kids are likely to have personal phone numbers that they can keep
for life no matter where they live or how often they move.
</P>
<P>
   The initial phase of the telecom technology upgrade, known as
local number portability (LNP), should be in place in the nation's
top 100 markets by the end of the year. In due course, number
portability should expand from current capabilities _ to keep a
number when you change local providers _ to span services in any of
the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   By next June, LNP should also be in place for wireless phones,
along with nationwide roaming. To keep track of ported numbers,
U.S. telecoms tap a huge database at the Number Portability
Administration Center.
</P>
<P>
   We are a mobile society. Mindful that each year one in every
four phone customers moves, Congress wrote the LNP rules into the
1996 Telecom Act. (An added benefit: improved digit ecology. Too
many moving days, fax machines and cell phones are chewing up
stocks of available numbers.)
</P>
<P>
   But it could cost as much as $4 billion in extra computer power
to turn what Congress wants into a universal reality. And someone
has got to pay for it all.
</P>
<P>
   So, after Feb. 1, 1999, both business and residential users will
be charged an extra monthly fee, for five years, to let phone
companies recover their costs. While the fee has yet to be set,
it's likely to be between 50 and 75 cents a month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict that eventual full geographic portability,
boundless fiber capacity and Internet-based phone services could
spawn what economists call ``distance-insensitive pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will only be one pricing scheme for telephony,'' writes
Jerry Lucas in his TeleStrategies Insight newsletter. ``Customers
will pay a flat rate for unlimited calls anywhere in the United
States, but will pay on a per-call basis for terminating on
wireless or international networks,'' Lucas adds.
</P>
<P>
   With portability, demand for 800 numbers and other toll-free
services should recede. Using related intelligent network
technology, marketers could snatch up useful seven-digit numbers
uniformly in every area code. (All local phone calls from anywhere
to ``CANDIES'' could be routed to, say, a given Florida-based
business. The actual candies would then be sent from local shops to
local sites.)
</P>
<P>
   LNP minders worry that, while we'll all pony up, not all of us
will benefit, at least at first. Says Federal Communications
Commission chairman William Kennard: ``We should not ask consumers
to pay for number portability before they are able to enjoy the
benefits of the competitive options that number portability is
designed to facilitate.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people need to have a Social Security number. But LNP will
roll out as an optional feature. Unless it catches on quickly,
telephone rates will go up for the many to lend a helping hand to
the portable few.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most folks won't mind seeing that extra 50 cents or so
on their monthly phone bills come early next year. But if they do,
the feds could find they've dialed the wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
