<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2467- JULY 30, 1998   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2467 -- July 30, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SOUND AND SCIENCE : LEARNING TO TUNE OUT THE NOISE
</P>
<P>
   AND HEAR THE WORLD We listen to the world selectively,
subjectively. The sound of a thundering waterfall puts us in a good
mood ; a dripping tap can irritate us to the point of rage. But we
simply tune out many sounds. We (wrongly) think of woods and fields
as silent places. And we ignore the fact that every mountain, every
market, every voice creates its own sound-aura. The world is an
orchestra, with man creating most of the false notes. A growing
brotherhood of ``sound-scapers,'' armed with microphones and
recorders, has been trying to document the world's sounds -- before
fast-encroaching noice pollution drowns out the very sounds of the
Earth. By Dirk Lehmann. From GEO magazine. 1,500 words. (English
translation available.) 2. WOMEN SHOW THE WORLD ABOUT GRACE UNDER
PRESSURE Life delivers no end of opportunities to show grace under
pressure and behave with dignity and style when something is
greatly upsetting us. What does it take to be a Jacqueline Kennedy
or a Hillary Rodham Clinton? Sherry Suib Cohen offers advice on
where to find outside support and inner strength. From McCall's
magazine. 1,100 words. 3. CAFFEINE : DEBATE STILL BREWS OVER ITS
PROS AND CONS Because it's a drug that can cause a mild dependency,
caffeine has gained a bad reputation. But warnings about mental
illness and birth defects are groundless, experts say. Athletes do,
however, report improved performance. By Ken McAlpine. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
WHERE IS DIANA? As the first anniversary of the death of Princess
Diana approaches, theologian Philip Nobile asks whether she is in
heaven or hell. From Prospect magazine. 1,300 words. (N/A UK)
________________________________________________________ 5. AN EVEN
BRIEFER HISTORY OF TIME Stephen Hawking retraces the genesis of his
Brief History of Time and considers what has happened in cosmology
since the book was published. From Prospect magazine. (N/A UK.)
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. LOOK BEFORE TAKING THE PLUNGE WITH A POOL It's hot and you'd
love to have a pool in the backyard ... Here are some decisions to
make before you become a pool owner. By Kathy Sena. 1,000 words
plus 300-word sidebar. 7. BLIND PHOTOGRAPHER PROVES EYESIGHT ISN'T
ALL YOU NEED A former fashion photographer who has lost more than
90 per cent of his eyesight continues to practice his art, with
even greater success. By Ben Widdicombe. 1,200 words + photo. (N/A
Britain and Australia.)
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   A. Water Gets Weird : Forget taps, pumps and cocktail shakers.
To control the tiniest droplets you need bubbles, waves and clever
corridors (microfluidics) B. All About Adam : Men may come out on
