<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS31-TAKE     07-30 1915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS31-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have any update on an accident in New York City when
some scaffolding fell in or near Times Square? I haven't seen any
later news.
</P>
<P>
   A. The accident occurred July 21 when the 700-foot scaffolding
partially collapsed at the 48-story Conde Nast building, under
construction on 43rd Street just off Broadway, forcing the closing
of sections of Sixth Avenue, Seventh Avenue and Broadway, as well
as 41st, 42nd and 43rd streets. Theresa Feliconio, a resident of
the Woodstock Hotel near the accident site, was killed instantly
last Tuesday morning by a piece of metal that fell into the living
room of her 12th-floor apartment. Debris rained onto buildings and
the street below. At least 12 injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   As of July 29, some streets were reported to have reopened.
Parts of Sixth Avenue and several other streets remained closed.
Workers were continuing to cover the damaged, unstable scaffold and
construction elevator with a curtain of netting to hold remaining
debris in place.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The Marines have a Latin motto, Semper Fidelis, meaning
``always faithful.'' The Coast Guard uses Semper Paratus, meaning
``always prepared.'' Are there similar mottoes for the Army, Air
Force and Navy?
</P>
<P>
   A. Representatives of each of the other branches report no Latin
mottoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How is the latest version of the movie ``Gone With the Wind''
doing at the box office?
</P>
<P>
   A. In limited release since June 26 _ it's currently showing in
about 200 theaters nationwide _ the reissue of ``GWTW'' has taken
in between $2 million and $3 million, said Elizabeth Guider of
Variety, the show-biz publication. In the week ending July 23, it
grossed $620,255, a dropoff of about 30 percent from the previous
week, she said. The cumulative box office take from all its
releases since 1939 totals about $197 million (domestic) and $202
million (foreign) for a worldwide total of about $399 million. In
comparison, as of July 20, the cumulative domestic box office for
``Titanic,'' in the 213 days since it was released, was $590.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   If figures are adjusted for inflation, and to reflect real
ticket sales, 1939's ``Gone With the Wind'' would be the top
money-earning film of all time, with the equivalent of an estimated
$1.2 billion in box-office receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few weeks ago, I heard that an experiment would be done
with Wall Street computers to test for the year 2000 bug. The
computers would be set for the end of Dec. 31, 1999, to see what
would happen. What did? I never saw any results.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Securities Industry Association's test turned computer
clocks at 29 brokerage firms and 13 exchanges and clearing and
settlement firms ahead to Jan. 3, 2000, the first trading day of
the next century. It then ran simulated trades to see if they would
work.
</P>
<P>
   Based on preliminary feedback, the trades were successful, with
no major glitches. ``It's gone much better than we anticipated,''
said John Panchery, Year 2000 project manager for the association.
The only problem reported in the project involved miscommunication
_ not related to the date _ between the various computers set up
for the testing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent success of the test, securities officials
aren't yet claiming that no problems will occur when midnight Dec.
31, 1999, arrives. The testing so far is preliminary only, and was
done using a small volume of trades.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have read that antibacterial soap can harm a septic tank.
Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A. Septic systems are rich bacterial environments that could be
adversely affected only by very large quantities of such products,
said Tony Tyson, Extension Service engineer in Statesboro.
Antibacterial soap won't damage a septic system, he added. There's
not enough disinfectant in the soap to affect the bacteria. If that
were a concern, stronger products would be much more worrisome,
such as the chlorine-based cleansers often introduced into such
systems. In some cases even the laundry, with all its bleaches and
other products, empties into septic systems. In the typically small
quantities used they're still not a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Considering all the rough weather we've been having, is there
any list of, say, the 10 places in the United States with the best
climate?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you're looking for weather as good as it gets in North
America, go west. Places Rated Almanac lists these cities and metro
areas as North America's top 10 for climate: San Francisco;
Honolulu; Los Angeles-Long Beach; Ventura, Calif.; San Luis
Obispo-Atascadero-Paso Robles, Calif.; San Diego; Orange County,
Calif.; Oakland, Calif.; Santa Barbara-Santa Maria-Lompoc, Calif.;
and Salinas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To assess climate, the almanac assigns scores to locations based
on three factors: mildness, which takes in everything from winter
temperatures influenced by wind chill to summer temperatures
influenced by humidity; brightness, which embraces the number of
clear days and wet days, plus latitude, an indicator of potential
sunlight; and stability, which takes in thunderstorms, snow, and
the difference between January's mean low temperature and July's
mean high.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale with 100 being the top, San Francisco got a score of
98.12.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the significance of the copper bracelets that we see
golfers wearing during televised tournaments?
</P>
<P>
   A. Some people think the wearing of copper bracelets helps
relieve arthritis pain, while others dismiss it as a folk belief
along the lines of such other ``cures'' as bee venom and various
diets and balms. While the Arthritis Foundation says the benefits
are unproven, it also says the wearing of copper bracelets is
considered harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have any information on a Van Gogh exhibit coming to
Washington?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs: Masterpieces from the Van Gogh
Museum, Amsterdam'' will be on view at the National Gallery of
Art's West Building from Oct. 4 to Jan. 3. It will include 70
paintings. After Washington, it will move to the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art Jan. 17 to April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Entrance to the exhibition at the National Gallery of Art will
be free, but passes will be required for entry. Beginning Aug. 30,
advance passes (no more than six per order) may be obtained through
Ticketmaster locations for a service charge of $2 per pass, and
through Ticketmaster PhoneCharge for $2.75 per pass plus a $1.25
handling fee per order. Also starting Aug. 30, passes can be
obtained in person at the Gallery's East Building pass desk, Fourth
Street and Constitution Avenue N.W. in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster PhoneCharge: 1-800-551-7328. Exhibit information on
the Internet is available at the National Gallery of Art's
exhibition site: www.nga.gov/exhibitions/exhibits.htm
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently read that sugar water, if left in the sun, becomes
poisonous to hummingbirds. Does that same thing happen to
commercial solutions for hummingbirds sold at nurseries and pet
stores?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's likely, because after a period in the hot sun, the
solution ferments, with bacteria and fungi (usually yeasts)
producing compounds that are toxic to the hummingbirds. You should
check the solution _ whether it's one you make, or a product you
buy _ every few days in hot weather, and change it if you're
suspicious, said Jeff Jackson, extension wildlife specialist at the
University of Georgia Warnell School of Forestry. You can tell by
the odor if it's fermenting, but you shouldn't take a chance. If
you have a lot of hummingbirds, they probably will drain the
solution before it ferments, Jackson said. When the weather is
cooler, the solution doesn't need to be changed as frequently.
``The trick is to use your judgment,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial solutions are no more effective than sugar water
combinations you can make in attracting hummingbirds,, Jackson
said, because it's the sugar in the water that attracts them.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When is next year's Westminster Dog Show? How can we get
tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Westminster Kennel Club says its next annual show will be
Feb. 8-9, 1999, at Madison Square Garden in New York. Tickets won't
go on sale until the fall, said club spokesman Tom Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   You can call the club at 212-682-6852 after Labor Day to request
a mail-order ticket order form; or, nearer the date of the show,
call the Madison Square Garden box office, 212-465-6741.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Now that Alan Shepard has died, how many of the original
Mercury astronauts are still alive? What are their ages and where
are they now?
</P>
<P>
   A. Of the seven test pilots introduced as the first group of
astronauts for the Mercury program on April 9, 1959, four are
living:
</P>
<P>
   Scott Carpenter, 73, who made three orbits around Earth on
Mercury 7 in May 1962, retired from the Navy with the rank of
commander. He lives in New York and in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Cooper Jr., 77, who orbited Earth on Mercury 9 in 1963
and did onboard experiments on Gemini V in 1965 to prepare for moon
missions, retired from the Air Force as a colonel. He lives in Van
Nuys, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Walter M. ``Wally'' Schirra Jr., 75, flew on Mercury 8 in 1962,
making six orbits of Earth; piloted Gemini 6 in 1965; and was
commander of Apollo 7 in 1968. A retired Navy captain, he lives in
Rancho Santa Fe, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Glenn Jr., 77, who became the first American to orbit
Earth on Feb. 20, 1962, in Mercury 6. A retired Marine Corps
colonel, he is a U.S. senator from Ohio. He's preparing to go into
space again aboard a shuttle mission in October.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil I. ``Gus'' Grissom, who flew a suborbital flight on
Mercury 4 in 1962 and made three Earth orbits on Gemini 3 in 1965,
died Jan. 27, 1967, in the Apollo spacecraft fire at Cape
Canaveral, Fla. Donald K. ``Deke'' Slayton, whose Mercury mission
was scrubbed but who flew on the Apollo mission that docked with
the Russian Soyuz spaceship in 1975, died June 13, 1993. Shepard,
74, died July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the status of the volcano that erupted last fall in
the Caribbean? Have island residents been allowed to return to
their homes?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Soufriere Hills volcano on Montserrat has been relatively
calm in the months since the eruptions began last September, but a
``burst of activity'' occurred July 3, said Jill Norton of the
Montserrat Volcano Observatory. It was the first significant
activity in ``three or four months,'' she added. Scientistsexpect
to release a report on the outlook in a week or two, she said.
Information is available by calling the Montserrat Observatory,
664-491-5647. Residents of areas evacuated last fall have not been
allowed to return, Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does it mean when someone says ``take it with a grain of
salt''?
</P>
<P>
   A. The idea is that you're approaching some suggestion or
proposal with skepticism bordering on distaste. The basic concept
is that you would take the same approach to an unappetizing meal,
which might be made palatable by the addition of a grain or two of
salt. The expression dates from Roman times, with the Latin cum
grano salis, according to Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase
Origins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
