<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS31-TAKE     07-30 1828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS31-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on the news
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q. What does it mean when someone says ``take it with a
grain of salt''?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Eric Robert Rudolph, the fugitive bombing suspect, has eluded
capture for months. A massive manhunt has been under way, with
hundreds of FBI and other law enforcement people searching for him.
Is any estimate available on the cost, say, per day or per week,
for the manhunt?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not yet, but an FBI spokesman said it wouldn't be as high as
one might think. Most of the search cost is personnel related, he
said, but most of the personnel involved already are on the payroll
and have just been reassigned temporarily to this mission.
Additional costs would be for equipment brought into the search
area, but no tally is yet available on that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I haven't seen anything lately about the fires in Florida.
Are they all out? What was the final acreage and dollar-figure
damage?
</P>
<P>
   A. All the fires are contained and most are controlled, said
George Cooper, fire resource manager in the Florida Department of
Forestry. ``Contained means we've got suppression lines around
them, controlled means they're out,'' he explained. The fires that
are continuing are burning in organic fuel or muck, and they're
relatively minor. The typical summertime pattern of localized heavy
rains and thunderstorms has returned to Florida, Cooper said,
helping prevent a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   Officials haven't finished computing the dollar cost of the
damage or of the firefighting mission, but some statistics are
known: 499,477 acres burned between June 1 and July 21; 126 homes
destroyed, 211 homes damaged; 25 businesses destroyed, eight
businesses damaged; and 86 vehicles damaged or destroyed.
Miraculously, considering that up to 10,000 firefighters were
involved and 150 aircraft flew 2,080 ``aircraft days,'' only 124
fire-related injuries to firefighters were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The only Florida area still considered in the tinderbox stage is
Panama City, Cooper said, because it hasn't seen a return of rain.
The two or three counties in that area still are considered in
critical fire stage.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I didn't see any report about casualties on ships associated
with the tsunami that struck Papua New Guinea July 17. Does a
tsunami not cause any damage until it reaches land?
</P>
<P>
   A. A tsunami is a series of traveling ocean waves of great
length and long duration. As it crosses the deep ocean, its length,
from end to end, may be 100 miles or more, its height from trough
to crest only a few feet. It cannot be felt aboard ships in deep
water, which explains why you didn't hear about any shipboard
problems or casualties.
</P>
<P>
   As the tsunami enters the shoaling waters of coastlines in its
path, the velocity of its waves diminishes and wave height
increases. It is in these shallow waters that tsunamis become a
threat to life and property, striking with devastating force.
</P>
<P>
   The three waves striking Papua New Guinea claimed at least 1,200
lives, officials reported, but the toll is expected to climb much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've read several times lately about something being shown on
TV in ``letterbox format.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. Think of the shape of a movie screen: wider than it is high.
Think of the shape of a TV screen: usually about the same height
and width. Letterbox format refers to showing a wide-screen image
on TV in its original proportion, allowing viewers to see it in its
full width, not just the portion in the middle. You'll see it on TV
with a black band across the top and bottom of the image.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a recent column, Miss Manners suggests that the word
``staff'' has to do with diseases and infections. Isn't she
mistaken in her spelling?
</P>
<P>
   A. We wouldn't be ill-mannered enough to presume to speak for
someone else, but let's be generous and politely assume Miss
Manners _ who often injects humor into her recommendations for
proper behavior _ knows the difference between ``staff'' and
``staph.'' She was responding to a reader asking whether a manager
should refer to the people who work for him as ``employees'' or
``co-workers.'' She recommended using the word ``staff,'' adding
that she hoped people associated it more with competence than with
infections.
</P>
<P>
   You're right, of course, to point out that ``staff'' is not the
medical word. That is staphylococcus, or staph for short.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our family recently was at a beach near Destin, Fla., and
observed a strange phenomenon. At night, the breaking surf glowed
with a bright, fluorescent light. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a fairly common occurrence created by bioluminescent
planktonic organisms in the water, said Wade Jeffrey of the biology
department at the University of West Florida in Pensacola. The
organisms usually give off light when they're disturbed, such as
when a boat is passing by, and sometimes the effect appears in the
surf as it approaches the beach. Think of the light given off by
fireflies, but imagine it in the sea water, and you have the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any connection between the name of the drug Viagra
and the Sanskrit word for tiger?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Sanskrit Dictionary says the word for tiger in English is
transliterated as vyaaghraH or shaardulaH; the word for ``a tiger
among human beings,'' purushhavyaaghra. A Sanskrit connection to
the word Viagra would be colorful but incorrect, said Pamela Gemmel
of Pfizer Inc. in New York, developer of the product. The name
Viagra was created years ago for a urology drug Pfizer was
developing, but that drug eventually was named something else, she
said. However, the company liked the name, so it was applied later
when sildenafil citrate was developed. Gemmel said other theories
about the name Viagra _ also incorrect _ have linked it to the
words vigor, vitality, virility and even Niagara (as in Falls).
</P>
<P>
   Q. News reports about a passenger jet forced to make an
emergency landing said it had to dump fuel before attempting the
landing. Where is fuel dumped? Is there a special zone or altitude,
or can it be done anywhere?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are no hard-and-fast rules, said Anne Eldridge of the
Federal Aviation Administration, because dumping of fuel usually is
associated with a potential problem or emergency, or with a flight
that is diverted to an airport far short of its intended
destination. Dumping is done to reduce the weight of the airplane
and to slow the landing speed, as well as to reduce the risk of
fire in an emergency, she added. In general, pilots try to dump
fuel at altitudes above 1,500-2,000 feet, where it will vaporize
before it reaches the ground, and they try to avoid doing it over
populated areas, Eldridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It was reported recently that an American tourist was found
hacked to death in a hotel room in Kenya. Do you have any more
details for those who may be considering a trip there?
</P>
<P>
   A. Although some published accounts decribed the victim,
identified as Luzzola Heriot, as a tourist, a British newspaper
said she had moved into a house she was renovating in Timau, 30
miles from Nairobi. In any case, her body was found in a room at a
hotel at Nanyuki, about 80 miles north of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Few details are available, but whatever the circumstances, the
death probably will add to Kenya's already declining state of
tourism, which has been blamed on rampant crime and recurring
politically motivated violence. Earlier this year, Nairobi's
expatriate community voiced anger in the face of chronic violence
in Kenya after the murder of a German technician. Two people are
being tried for the murder in February of a British tourist at the
Aberdare County Club near Nanyuki. And at the end of January,
heavily armed bandits attacked and robbed nine tourists in the
Masai Mara game reserve, one of Kenya's most popular areas for game
viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department reports a high rate of street crime against
tourists in Nairobi, Mombasa and elsewhere in Kenya, as well as
robberies of tourists drugged with food and drinks laced with
sedatives. For recorded information, call the State Department's
Citizens Emergency Center at 202-647-5225 and follow the prompts
for Kenya or any other country. On the Internet, you'll find
information on the State Department's home page (www.state.gov).
Click first on Information and Services; and, under Travel, on
Travel Warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've noticed an increasing number of programs on Discovery
Channel and elsewhere being shown in letterbox format. Does this
have anything to do with the new digital technology?
</P>
<P>
   A. Only about 5 percent of Discovery Channel's programming is in
letterbox format, said Discovery spokeswoman Karen Beimdiek, and
it's done only because the film was shot on Super 16 format film.
She cited two advantages: ``an appealing look visually, and as a
means of preparing for the future, when TV sets are designed to be
more wide-screen or higher definition.'' What has been shot on
Super 16 film will match proportionally the newer TV sets without
having to reformat the picture to fit current sets, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q. An article about Saratoga Springs, N.Y., used the term
``giddyup.'' Where did such a curious word originate?
</P>
<P>
   A. Also spelled giddyap and giddap, it's simply an informal
pronunciation of ``get up.'' As any fan of westerns knows, it is a
command to a horse to speed up.
</P>
<P>
   Q. After visiting Arlington National Cemetery, I'm curious about
Fort Myer. Where did it get its name? What is its history?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Military District of Washington reports that the site
currently occupied by Fort Myer traces its ownership to George
Washington Parke Custis, who owned the land where Arlington
National Cemetery now stands. Part of the Arlington estate became a
cemetery for war dead and the remainder became Fort Whipple, named
in honor of Brevet Maj. Gen. Amiel Weeks Whipple.
</P>
<P>
   In 1881, Fort Whipple was redesignated Fort Myer in honor of
Brig. Gen. Albert J. Myer. A secondary benefit in the renaming was
to avoid confusion raised by the existence of a Fort Whipple in
Arizona. During his career, Myer served as commanding officer of
Fort Whipple and was appointed the Army's first chief signal
officer in 1866, a position he held until his death in 1880.
Quarters One at Fort Myer, completed in 1899, has been home to the
U.S. Army chief of staff since 1908.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Fort Myer served as a military
in-processing and out-processing station. Defense troops also were
stationed there throughout the war. The U.S. Army Band,
``Pershing's Own,'' moved to Fort Myer in 1942, and in 1948 two
battalions of the 3rd Infantry Regiment were reactivated and
assigned to Fort Myer and Fort McNair. Today, Fort Myer is under
the jurisdiction of the commanding general, U.S. Army Military
District of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
