<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-SPORT31-COX     07-30 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-SPORT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dance Sport stepping to a different tune
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH _ Come Sunday, August 2, they will have danced all
week.
</P>
<P>
   For the 18th consecutive year, The Triple Crown DanceSport
Championships are waltzing and swinging, mamboing and boleroing,
fox-trotting and quick-stepping their way around the Gulfstream
Ballroom of The Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 700 dancers signed up, and I expect around 1,200
spectators,'' said Larry Dean, owner of Dance Consultants
Unlimited, the event's producer.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent competition, paired professionals and amateurs _
mostly teachers and their students _ took to the floor while a team
of judges and a young woman named Laurie Frederik watched.
</P>
<P>
   The judges were evaluating the dancers' timing, posture and
showmanship. Frederik was nursing a broken baby toe on her left
foot and wishing she could be out there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke it in an Indianapolis competition two weeks ago,'' she
sighed, ``and I'm real disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Ph.D. candidate in anthropology at the University of Chicago,
Frederik, 30, said ballroom dancing is the perfect respite from an
academic life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend my days in front of a computer, studying Cuban
culture,'' she explained. ``Then at night, I get to put on
rhinestones and bright red lipstick and be a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Her instructor, Gregory Day, is a former ballet dancer who came
to ballroom styles when the ballet studio he frequented in New York
City was sold and turned into a ballroom studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing is dancing,'' he figured. ``You have the waltz and
swing in both country-western and ballroom dancing, and the
two-step and fox trot are similar, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One winner was Nancy Lowenstein, ``over 60,'' who appeared on
the dance floor in a baby's nightgown, nightcap, bib and pacifier _
until the loudspeakers blasted I'm Just A Baby In This Business Of
Love, and the toddler togs fell away to reveal a skimpy and
shocking red flapper dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a first place this morning,'' Lowenstein boasted. ``It's
not a career on the Broadway stage, but it makes me feel good about
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, about $175,000 in prizes and scholarships will be
awarded by week's end, Dean said, and greater glory may be ahead
for ballroom dancing.
</P>
<P>
   It's been accepted as a full exhibition event at the 2000
Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
