A0154 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN31-COX     07-30 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officers deserve justice, not vengeance
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My dad was a Fort Worth cop for almost 40 years, most of that as
a
</P>
<P>
   detective in the homicide division.
</P>
<P>
   Working the homicide detail isn't exactly easy duty -- the hours
can be
</P>
<P>
   brutal for one thing -- but he would tell me plainly that it was
nothing
</P>
<P>
   compared to the 10 years or so he spent patrolling the streets
of Cowtown.
</P>
<P>
   Uniform officers take the frontline of danger in the police
business. Twice
</P>
<P>
   in that 10 years criminals made direct attempts on his life. In
that era
</P>
<P>
   before police officers had to watch how they treated prisoners,
it was a
</P>
<P>
   mistake that both men paid for.
</P>
<P>
   I won't say that a detective's job doesn't have elements of risk
but,
</P>
<P>
   generally, they arrive when the danger is over to investigate
the crime
</P>
<P>
   already occurred.
</P>
<P>
   When my father was a patrolman, my mother did not sleep while he
was on
</P>
<P>
   duty, no matter what his work hours might have been. She lived
with the
</P>
<P>
   fear, barely submerged in her mind, that, one day, she would get
the dreaded
</P>
<P>
   visit from a police chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   As cop's kids, my brother, sister and I lived with that fear,
too. It did
</P>
<P>
   not affect us a keenly as it did my mother, but it was still
there.
</P>
<P>
   So I think I understand a bit of what the families of Jacob J.
Chestnut and
</P>
<P>
   John Gibson are feeling this week. How horrible it must have
been to hear
</P>
<P>
   the news of a Capitol shooting knowing that was where your
husband or father
</P>
<P>
   worked. The dreadful waiting of minutes until you heard the
worst news
</P>
<P>
   confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   No one should ever have to hear that news, but police officers
all over the
</P>
<P>
   nation (and the world) take the job knowing the risk. Chestnut
and Gibson
</P>
<P>
   willingly gave their lives for their country. They deserve the
highest
</P>
<P>
   honors we can bestow upon them.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Chestnut and Gibson families are not alone in
tragedy. They
</P>
<P>
   are not the only innocent victims.
</P>
<P>
   Two others live all the way in Florida: Mr. and Mrs. Russell E.
Weston Sr.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to suggest that the Westons are feeling loss like
the
</P>
<P>
   families of Chestnut and Gibson, but when you make national
statements
</P>
<P>
   apologizing for the actions of your son, you are feeling
considerable pain.
</P>
<P>
   How could Weston the father known what was going to happen? How
could the
</P>
<P>
   mother have stopped it. They apparently raised their son as best
they could,
</P>
<P>
   then watched helplessly when, after he was already an adult, he
began to
</P>
<P>
   experience mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the record suggests that they tried to help their
son. Certainly
</P>
<P>
   they encouraged him to take the medication that might have
helped him lead
</P>
<P>
   an ordinary life. They practiced the theory of ``tough love,''
ordering him
</P>
<P>
   out of their Florida house after he took a pistol and shot 14
cats.
</P>
<P>
   What could they have done? How would they have known that Weston
would turn
</P>
<P>
   from shooting cats to shooting police officers? He was an adult
and they had
</P>
<P>
   no standing to commit him, then and there, to a mental
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as horrible as the news that your father has been killed
in the
</P>
<P>
   Capitol is the news that your son was the one to do the deed.
</P>
<P>
   By overwhelming numbers, the mentally ill are not violent
people. They work
</P>
<P>
   in your office and you'll never know. They go to school with
your children
</P>
<P>
   and sleep over at your house. Yes, some of them are even police
officers and
</P>
<P>
   do fine jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Like disorders from ulcers to high blood pressure, most mental
illness can
</P>
<P>
   be corrected or controlled with medication. The cases of the
violently
</P>
<P>
   mental ill are rare but, admittedly, it makes big news when such
a person
</P>
<P>
   takes his acts in the community.
</P>
<P>
   For parents like the Westons, there is little to do but watch in
horror
</P>
<P>
   like the rest of us. No psychiatrist or counselor could have
told them how
</P>
<P>
   to do anything different. They were powerless to prevent this
crime, but the
</P>
<P>
   perpetrator carries their name. Russell Jr. is still their son.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Weston Jr. needs to be put away to protect society.
It is just
</P>
<P>
   as clear that this nation should move with all deliberate speed
in honoring
</P>
<P>
   the memories of Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   But it does those two fallen officers no honor to put a mentally
ill person
</P>
<P>
   to death.
</P>
<P>
   It would, in fact, be an insult to their service of justice.
</P>
<P>
   (Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
