<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A question of taste
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If society shrugs as standards decline, we're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   An old friend who has seen the calendar turn about as many times
as I have was on the phone. ``I think I've lived too long,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe both of us have,'' I replied. ``What's bothering you
today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen the cigarette billboard in Atlanta?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I replied. ``I haven't had to go to Atlanta this
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Winston billboard. It says, `Finally, a butt worth
kissing.' Can you imagine such bad taste on a billboard in downtown
Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly where is it?'' I asked. ``I don't think we have
billboards like that on our side of town. We're still pretty
old-fashioned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on the Connector going north,'' he said. ``What do you
think it means?''
</P>
<P>
   I had to admit I had no idea. When I was foolish enough to smoke
Winstons myself I never considered kissing what was left of a
cigarette before snubbing it out and throwing it away.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being in poor taste, the billboard doesn't make sense.
If they're trying to sell cigarettes, whatever happened to
``Winstons taste good, like a cigarette should?'' As an example of
how things have changed, remember when purists were upset because
that advertisement, being grammatically incorrect, was corrupting
the language? They wanted to change it to ``as a cigarette
should.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think with all the trouble the tobacco companies are in
they'd at least try to have dignified advertising,'' my friend
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably can't find any,'' I explained. ``The people who
make the ads are either old hippies or young smart alecks who get
their kicks by shocking old folks like you and me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he said, ``but who's bossing the shop? Who approves
the ads at the tobacco company?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're the same people who own and manage radio
stations and allow all that garbage on the air,'' I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear Guy Millner's radio interview?'' my friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't. I was in the garden picking tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about his relationship with Mrs. Millner,'' he
explained. ``He was being questioned about rumors saying he and
Mrs. Millner weren't getting along.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he say to that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said they were getting along great. Then he gave an
example. He said, `I patted her on the butt before I left home this
morning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a nice thing for him to do,'' I replied, ``but if I
patted my wife on her butt and broadcast it on the radio, I
wouldn't be going home that night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me either,'' he said. ``I might not be going home that
month.''
</P>
<P>
   While my friend thought it untoward for a gubernatorial
candidate to tell a radio audience about patting his wife on the
butt, he was particularly surprised to hear it from Guy Millner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't he after the religious right vote?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I read it. Guy's the traditional values,
motherhood, God and Country candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Won't talk like that on the radio upset religious right
folks?'' my friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' I replied. ``Nothing upsets anyone any more. Bad taste
has become so common we're like the old man in north Georgia who
lived in a room above his chicken house. After a while he got to
where he thought chicken manure didn't stink.''
</P>
<P>
   We talked about the two 18-year-old virgins who were supposed to
make love for the first time on the Internet. Thank goodness that
turned out to be a prankster's hoax, but not before everybody
believed it was going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The really scary thing about that episode, as national columnist
Mona Charen pointed out, is that while everybody was believing
copulation was actually going to take place in full view of
strangers all over the world, none of the news reports about it
reflected disapproval, or even concern. Like the north Georgia
chicken farmer, we've lived with manure so long we don't notice the
smell.
</P>
<P>
   This is a free country. Every citizen, high or low, enjoys
freedom of speech and expression, guaranteed by the Constitution. A
billboard can say whatever some advertising agency adolescent, or
tasteless company CEO, wants it to say. It's a First Amendment
thing.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange how we've come to use the right of free speech and
expression. It would be a violation of the First Amendment to
prohibit billboards on the Downtown Connector merely because they
rot the fabric of society and offend those who retain a modicum of
propriety. However, it is not a violation to prohibit billboards
beside an interstate highway in south Georgia merely because they
are offensive to the eye and sometimes cause trees to be cut down.
</P>
<P>
   I will have to call my friend back and apologize for slandering
the northside. Eventually, I had to go into Atlanta. Right there
south of the stadium was a duplicate Winston billboard. Not far
away was another, touting a radio station and informing me that
rock music, sex, and beer are the three essentials of life.
</P>
<P>
   We are in trouble. Churches can teach, preachers can preach,
philosophers can philosophize, authors can write great books,
editors can publish responsible newspapers, but advertising and
entertainment decide standards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
