</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The loonies-with-guns lesson _ again
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two Capitol Police officers who died doing their duty have
been given the honored burial they deserve in Arlington Cemetery. A
week of national drama over the deaths played out as if scripted _
as, indeed, by now such occasions are.
</P>
<P>
   The breaking news is followed by catch-as-catch-can interviews
in which shock and disappointment are exercised. Flowers and other
tokens of remembrance and of caring appear at the scene. Sentiment
is spilled, in this case largely in the form of congressional
speeches often canted toward a Heavenly outcome. (House Majority
Whip Tom DeLay seemed almost delighted at the victims' prospects.)
</P>
<P>
   Solemn funerals end the public spectacle, and the lingering,
hellish private grief is left to its own devices. The rest of us
have by then had all the vicarious involvement we care for.
</P>
<P>
   We then proceed to do nothing very useful nor germane, because
in most instances anything germane or useful would cost either
money or political will and we have declared ourselves impoverished
of both.
</P>
<P>
   Congress now talks about extending or otherwise shifting its
perimeter. The next crazy person with a gun would still be crazy
and would still be armed, but the new deaths would be at some more
discreet remove from congressional chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress does not wonder whether it might knit up a seamless
system to care for, and about, the mentally ill. And it insists
upon a slovenliness in firearms management that makes it no trick
for a man who has been delusional for years to pick up a gun and go
hunting his devils.
</P>
<P>
   With the development of antipsychotic drugs in the 1970s, we
began closing, with just relief, our often horrid old warehouses
for the mentally ill. A network of outpatient clinics and programs
was to be put in its place. It was not, and what passes for a
system now is spotty and incoherent. Many patients stop taking
their medication and few states allow the outpatient commitment
that would mitigate that and incidentally would spare city streets
the pathetic and corrosive human litter of untreated illness.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Eugene Weston Jr., charged in the Capitol shootings, was
classified paranoid schizophrenic for Social Security benefits in
1984. In 1996, the Secret Service investigated his threats toward
the president. (Among his delusions: Clinton planned the Kennedy
assassination in jealousy over Marilyn Monroe. Even Ken Starr
didn't think of that one.) Weston was committed to a Montana mental
hospital later that year but was released with a prescription and a
bus ticket to his native Illinois. ``Greyhound therapy,'' as they
say.
</P>
<P>
   He got a gun permit there early this year _ Brady law background
checks often miss mental illness because there's no national
recordkeeping _ and then simply lifted a .38 from his parents'
house. We won't require firearms owners to store their weapons
under lock.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, absolutely none, is beyond substantial social
repair, as other nations have shown, but we have convinced
ourselves we are helpless. Communal sentimentality and mourning,
however sincere at the moment, are finally just cheaper and easier
than common effort.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail:teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
