<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASTPITCH-ONLINE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fastpitch online reaching world
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ A great experiment in cyber softball is being
conducted in a small room at the town hall.
</P>
<P>
   From here, a 1,000-game tournament is being transmitted to the
world, one score at a time, one computer keystroke at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing quite like this has been tried before,'' said Melinda
Miller, the town's director of information services. ``We have had
to develop our own software. The response we've gotten has been
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter, host city for the ongoing NSA Girls Youth Fastpitch
World Series, expanded its Internet Web site to provide tournament
results, highlights and features on participating teams. Under
Miller's direction, www.nsa-worldseries.com was born _ and to a
reception that was enthusiastic beyond expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the World Series began this week, the site has been
bombarded by more than 1,500 hits per day from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic has been more than we can handle,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County tech companies have rallied to donate services
to deal with the surprising demand: Yonder Technology developed the
Web site, Klear Technologies created software for tournament
brackets, and Citywalk.net Inc. helped expand Internet capacity.
</P>
<P>
   At restaurants in north county _ Pizza Hut, McDonald's, R.J.
Gators, the Blarney Pub &AMP; Brewery _ computer terminals were
installed so players and their families could follow the series,
which they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail messages have come to Miller's screen from more than 40
states. Players who couldn't make the trip to Jupiter have sent
thanks for the chance to follow the games with the click of a
computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite e-mail came from Mark Grcevich, who coaches the
18-and-under Nighthawks from Lowell, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   It reads: ``I can't thank you enough for what you are doing on
the Internet. Our team was going to play in the tournament but had
to withdraw ... because of a serious car accident involving three
kids from our team, including my daughter. So I have been following
the teams from our area.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller believes Jupiter has set a standard on how future
tournaments will transmit information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed the focus of communication from paper to the Web
site,'' she said. ``Cyber softball. I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
