</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURE-CALLS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 25 years, nature calls
 &HT;    By Ian Trontz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ When it finally happened, Emma Goldwire
couldn't use her bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carpet was wet, it even ran out into the hallway,'' said
Goldwire, 75, who lives at 1961 W. 13th St. ``I had to go to my
daughter's house to take a shower.''
</P>
<P>
   The leak was caused by roots from a neighbor's ficus tree. They
had penetrated the bathroom floor, reaching underneath the tub and
around Goldwire's toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Ficus trees _ and their cousins, rubber and banyan trees _ can
send roots more than 100 feet from their bases in search of water
to nourish their splendid canopies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ficus is probably the most invasive plant we have for
roots,'' said Latimer Farr, a master gardener with the Palm Beach
County Extension Service. ``It's not recommended at all to put next
to a house or water pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, after plumbers and her son-in-law gave up
trying to stop her bathtub from leaking, Goldwire finally pulled up
the bathroom carpet. She found the root of her problem.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 years ago, she said, her neighbors planted the tree
about 50 feet from her bathroom. The tree was at least 40 feet tall
when the property owner, Forest Parson, sent two men this week to
chainsaw it to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'll pay to repair Goldwire's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwire also blames the roots for water damage in the adjacent
den, but Parson said he won't fix that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even sure it was my tree that did it,'' he said,
adding another tree on the block may have been guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwire isn't relieved yet. ``It's got to be done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
