<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUR-STORY31-COX     07-30 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUR-STORY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet Lindsay: singer, poet, social critic
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Editor's note: For the next few weeks, Ron
Wiggins will be picking names at random from the phone book for
What's Your Story?, a column based on the premise that everyone has
a story to tell. This week, he found Lindsay Porter, a Jupiter,
Florida teenager ready to take on the world if she could just skip
the high school portion.
</P>
<P>
   If Lindsay Porter, almost 17, could get a note from her mother
excusing her from her senior year at Jupiter Community High School,
that would be fine with her.
</P>
<P>
   Except that she would miss chorus. She loves chorus. Especially
her chorus teacher, the only teacher who seemed to notice when she
dropped out of school for eight weeks near the end of her sophomore
year. That was the time her mom and stepdad packed her off to live
with her dad in Port St. Lucie for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Lindsay, what you see is what you get,'' says her mother,
Janni Bland, an accountant. Bland says this with a good deal of
affection, considering that her daughter _ the future
singer/songwriter _ can be a royal pain in the household.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's sister, Stephanie, 12, is standing by, ready to
contribute to the big-deal newspaper story being done on her
sister. ``You're so annoying,'' little sister says to big sister.
``She claws me when we wrestle. I can hardly wait until she moves
out and I have the house to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, this critique is also laden with affection. Maybe the
poem Lindsay wrote about her little sister helps explain. Love,
Tea, and Soup
</P>
<P>
   I painfully scrunch my legs
</P>
<P>
   under my little sister's tiny table.
</P>
<P>
   Because I love her
</P>
<P>
   While she pours me
</P>
<P>
   a cup of imaginary
</P>
<P>
   tea and cooks me soup
</P>
<P>
   on her ``play'' stove . . .
</P>
<P>
   Because she loves me
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay surrenders a sheaf of her poetry, explaining that it may
one day find its way into song lyrics. ``I've spared you all of my
I-want-to-kill-myself poetry,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay is far from suicidal. Homicidal, maybe, if you count the
times she'd like to drown some of the nitwit boys in her classes.
Sometimes school is so tedious that it practically makes her teeth
ache.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, today's little scene in the English class she
is taking in summer school. Yes, she flunked English, even after
acing her assignments, because she wouldn't ``participate'' in
class.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to participate when you don't attend. ``English
was last period, after all,'' she says, the implication being that
last period should be optional. On her rare appearances, the
teacher liked to make a big deal of her deigning to honor the class
with her presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe I flunked,'' she says. ``I thought I would
get a C.''
</P>
<P>
   As for today's outburst in class, it seems that the teacher was
trying to lead an intelligent discussion of the novel Ordinary
People when this jerk kid started going on and on about the book's
earthy language.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a typical male adolescent mind-set, Lindsay says.
It is so insufferably, insipidly, obnoxiously childish, and people
wonder why some students feel suffocated by high school! So she
turns on this twit, and, with a contempt that soars beyond
infinity, she explains, ``They allow the language in a novel
because they expect you to be mature enough to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   As if.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the crux of Lindsay Porter's problem with school. She
could probably stand it if the other students would just pretend to
be interested in learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in college, people are there because they want to
be,'' she huffs. ``How can you learn anything in high school with
these adolescent boys laughing because they find sexual meaning in
everything the teachers say?''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay is not so much alienated from her contemporaries as she
is in tune with adults. ``I have more in common with my mom's
friends than people my age,'' she says. ``One of my best friends is
my 28-year-old cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay does have friends her age, but she can count them on two
fingers: Her chorus pal who got her over her singing shyness and
her friend who moved to Minnesota and will always be a part of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay's brother, Christopher, 14, admits under direct
examination that his big sister is pretty cool in her own weird
way, and leaves it at that. After all, she will have her driver
license soon, and a fellow may need a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay is reconciled to serving out her last year of high
school. She will bring her grades up. She will continue to get math
tutoring. She will participate in class.``I'm trying to build study
habits,'' she says. ``When you get to college, they aren't
interested in your excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   And, no matter how hideous high school may be, chorus, and her
piano and guitar studies, restoreth her soul.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her writing. Before he leaves, the interviewer
glances down at one of Lindsay Porter's poems, intending to read a
verse. But once he begins, he can't stop:
</P>
<P>
   Generations
</P>
<P>
   Mom _ Can we trade?
</P>
<P>
   Your Beatles
</P>
<P>
   For my Guns-n-Roses?
</P>
<P>
   Your Volkswagen bus
</P>
<P>
   For my 4x4 Blazer:
</P>
<P>
   Your marijuana
</P>
<P>
   For my
</P>
<P>
   Crack
</P>
<P>
   Your pregnancy
</P>
<P>
   For my AIDS?
</P>
<P>
   Your father and mother
</P>
<P>
   For my
</P>
<P>
   Father, his new wife, and my half-sister?
</P>
<P>
   Your generation
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for mine?
</P>
<P>
   What do you say Mom . . .
</P>
<P>
   Can we trade?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
