<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMERS-BOOK31-COX     07-30 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-BOOK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Alzheimer proof'' home to comfort, protect loved one
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Imagine that you are 75 years old but you
picture yourself the way you looked at 25. Gentlemen admired you
then, the way you swept your long locks up above your slender neck,
where you would fasten that first strand of cultured pearls.
</P>
<P>
   You peer into the mirror, and . . . who's that? You see a
wrinkled face, a stranger's face. ``Go away!'' you holler. ``Help!
There's a strange woman in the house!''
</P>
<P>
   You shuffle away from the stranger, down an unfamiliar hallway
into an unfamiliar living room. How did I get here? you wonder. Who
lives here? When can I go home?
</P>
<P>
   Home is the brick apartment building on the Grand Concourse in
the Bronx, where you and your husband lived after the first baby
came. Oh, no! you think. Where's the baby? I must find my baby!
</P>
<P>
   You try to leave this strange house to find the baby, but the
front door is locked. So, with all your might, you climb through a
window. And suddenly you find yourself sprawled on the grass,
aching and wondering how you got there.
</P>
<P>
   Then you remember: You're supposed to meet Betty at the steps of
the Astor Hotel in just an hour. You collect all the shiny, round
objects you can find in the neighbor's trash (you need a subway
token, after all) and amble past one palm tree after another in
your South Florida subdivision, looking for the subway that will
take you from the Bronx to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   You have just entered the confused world inhabited by people
with Alzheimer's disease. This world follows a certain logic, even
if the details vary from person to person and the reasoning is
obvious only to those who live inside.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Warner, an architect and gerontologist from Jupiter,
explains this logic in a new book, ``The Complete Guide to
Alzheimer's-Proofing Your Home,'' published this month by Purdue
University Press, (800) 933-9637.
</P>
<P>
   The 470-page book gives caregivers room-by-room _ and
symptom-by-symptom _ advice on how to make a loved one feel more
comfortable and independent at home.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggests home adjustments that can help behavioral
problems common to people with Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Like seeing ghosts or strangers in the mirror. Or rummaging for
objects _ cardboard, buttons, scrap pieces of metal so precious
during the Great Depression. Or wandering, even ``escaping,'' from
a home they do not recognize as their own.
</P>
<P>
   And it explains why these things happen: For instance, people
with Alzheimer's lose their short-term memory and often believe
they are living 50 years ago. (If they learned English since that
time, they may not even recognize the word bathroom but will recall
the word bano.) They will also hoard and hide strange objects
because they have symbolic meaning. The act of collecting makes
them feel more in control.
</P>
<P>
   Several books have been written already about designing homes
for people with Alzheimer's, but never in terms the general public
can understand, says Alzheimer's Association spokeswoman Nicolle
Gajda. She calls the book, with its 28-page directory of
Alzheimer-proofing products, a ``much-needed resource.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips from the book:
</P>
<P>
   BATHING AND SHOWERING
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a hand-held shower head with an on-off button.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change door handles that lock from the inside. Otherwise,
Grandma may lock herself in, then forget how to get out. Consider
replacing the bathroom door with a shower curtain or folding door.
They afford privacy yet allow you to enter quickly in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   _ Simplify your loved one's wardrobe. Too much clothing means
too many choices, which is confusing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Label drawers with pictures of what's inside: shirts, socks,
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Mom has a favorite red dress that she won't take off _ even
to wash it _ buy a second red dress that looks just like it. Switch
dresses when it's time to wash.
</P>
<P>
   USING THE TOILET
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, people with Alzheimer's would use the commode _ if
only they could find it, or recognize it, or weren't afraid of
sitting on it. So . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure the pathway from your loved one's room or favorite
chair to the bathroom is free of obstacles. Encountering a
footstool or TV set on the way may be enough to cause confusion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decorate the bathroom in different colors, so that the toilet
bowl may be distinguished from the floor tiles and the tub. Beige
on beige and other chic, one-color decorating schemes may look good
in House Beautiful, but for a person with Alzheimer's, Mark Warner
says, it makes finding the commode ``like looking for a polar bear
in a snow storm.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hampers and wastepaper baskets may look like a toilet to a
person with Alzheimer's. Add decorations to lessen the resemblance,
buy a childproof hamper, or one that requires some skill to open,
and label the bathroom and toilet in big, bold letters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attach a ``bidet device'' to your toilet. It will spray water
to clean your loved one. Some come with heated toilet seats and
drying fans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
