<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0164 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMERS-SIDE31-COX     07-30 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-SIDE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did you know . . . ?
 &HT;    By Dale Fuchs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 4 million Americans have Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   One in 10 people age 65 or older _ and nearly half of those age
85 or older _ have Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Seven out of 10 people with Alzheimer's disease live at home.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends take on almost 75 percent of the work needed
to care for their loved one at home. The rest of the work is done
by paid help, at an average of $12,500 a year, most of which isn't
covered by Medicare or private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A person with Alzheimer's will live an average of eight years
after symptoms appear. Some people live as long as 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: The Alzheimer's Association.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DO WHEN YOUR LOVED ONE WANDERS:
</P>
<P>
   Camouflage closets that are off-limits with wallpaper that looks
like a book shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Camouflage sliding glass doors with decals that make them look
like picture windows or murals.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure windows can't open far enough to climb through. Many
people with Alzheimer's don't recognize their own home and will try
to ``escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Install motion detectors and other alarms that make pleasant
sounds, like the ring of a cow bell or the tinkle of chimes.
</P>
<P>
   If Mom wanders at night, place a ``sofa saver'' (normally used
to keep Rover off the couch) on the floor around her bed. That way,
when she steps down, an alarm will sound and wake her caregiver.
</P>
<P>
   Build a doorway between Dad's room and his caregiver's room,
then hide the original doorway behind a piece of furniture. That
way, to leave his room, Dad must first pass the through his
caregiver's room.
</P>
<P>
   DEVICES THAT EASE LIFE:
</P>
<P>
   Photo Dial Phone (Polyconcept USA, (203) 358-8100). If Dad can't
remember a name or phone number, he can just press the button with
the picture of the person he wants to call.
</P>
<P>
   Bathtub with doors (BathEase, (888) 747-7845) so your loved one
doesn't have to balance on one leg and lift the other over a tub
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Waterwand (International Environmental Solutions, 800-972-8834).
This faucet control shuts off the water automatically in case Mom
forgets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safe return'' bracelet with your loved one's name and address.
Available through the Alzheimer's Association, (888) 572-8566.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES:
</P>
<P>
   The national Alzheimer's Association in Chicago, (800) 272-3900.
Local chapter, (561) 740-1180.
</P>
<P>
   COMMON PROBLEMS IN THE HOME
</P>
<P>
   Mirrors. Many people with Alzheimer's disease do not
recognizetheir reflection in a mirror and think it is a stranger or
a ghost.While mirrors are a good idea in the early stages of
Alzheimer's -they encourage proper grooming - it's best to cover
them, removethem, or disguise them with murals as the disease
advances.
</P>
<P>
   Black or dark-colored floor tiles and throw rugs. These
sometimeslook like ``holes'' to people with Alzheimer's and cause
terror everytime they walk across a checkered kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   Balconies. Grandma may no longer realize she lives on the
fifthfloor. Make the balcony off limits with a combination of locks
andalarms. That way, if Grandma figures out the lock, an alarm will
warnher caregiver that she stepped outside.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinets containing sharp utensils, medications. Use
child-prooflocks, and place locks above or below your loved one's
line of sight.Hang signs on doors and drawers that are off limits.
</P>
<P>
   The refrigerator. Keep medications in a small refrigerator in
thecaregiver's room. That way Dad can rummage through the frige in
thekitchen all he wants - without the risk of taking too much
medicineby accident.
</P>
<P>
   Some household plants, such as dieffenbachia, are harmful if
eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Bright lights and abrupt changes in lighting can be
disorienting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
