<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARASITES-VICTIMS31-C     07-30 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARASITES-VICTIMS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parasite claiming more spill victims
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Rita Fuentes knew she was going to be in for a long
day. Fuentes, the communicable disease nurse for the Williamson
County and Cities Health District, had scores of calls to return
from the day before _ all to people who had reported stomach
ailments that officials believe is caused by a July 14 spill of raw
sewage from a City of Austin pumping station into Brushy Creek.
</P>
<P>
   But when she got to the office, she had a whole new stack of
calls to make: 47 messages from people reporting symptoms that
varied from diarrhea and vomiting to nausea and headaches.
</P>
<P>
   By lunch, she and her assistant had 63 more messages. And
Fuentes' neck was still sore from cradling the phone the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   The spill of 170,000 gallons of raw sewage into Brushy Creek
came after the pumping station lost power during a thunderstorm.
Since then, 13 wells have been contaminated _ four of which belong
to the Brushy Creek Municipal Utility District. Nine people have
tested positive for a rare parasitic infection called
Cryptosporidium.
</P>
<P>
   The generator that lost power in the storm did not have a
back-up generator, and the phone line that the alarm system depends
on was also knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 300 people had called Williamson County health
officials to report illnesses. Fuentes' job was to return their
calls, record their symptoms and addresses, and question them about
the water they have been drinking in the days following the spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been swamped,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said they got five more tests back Wednesday,
but they showed no signs of the parasite.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't necessarily mean they weren't infected with
crypto,'' said Doug McBride, spokesman for the Texas Department of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   In all, nine of 17 Brushy Creek MUD residents have tested
positive.
</P>
<P>
   A 35-year old Brushy Creek woman, who did not want her name
published, said she was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in bed for days,'' she said. On Friday, July , she said
she told her husband, ``I've had enough,'' and he called the family
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if we lived in the Brushy Creek MUD, and then told us
to go to the hospital right away,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital took a stool sample, she said. By Tuesday, she got
the news that she was infected. The hospital would not identify
people treated in the outbreak, citing patient privacy
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Schumacher, 66, of the 16500 block of Denise Drive in
the Brushy Creek MUD, said his was one of the messages Fuentes
received over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He said he, his wife and son all started feeling sick July 21,
the day the MUD closed four of its five drinking wells because of
they were contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Schumacher called the health district number he saw
in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all sure it was from the water,'' he said. ``We just
don't get diarrhea in our household.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher said he was upset with the MUD officials for their
delay in testing the wells. The district did not test the water
going into its wells until three days after the spill. And by the
time it closed the wells, a week had passed since the spill,
allowing for contaminants like Cryptosporidium to slip into the
public water supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute they learned of that spill they should have shut
those wells down, even before the testing,'' Schumacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of illnesses aren't just being reported to the health
district, said Lisa Quay, a MUD resident and former board member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I go _ swimming lessons, the grocery store, the
women's club _ everyone comes up to me and says, 'My family is
sick,' `` she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandee Sykes, the president of the Woods of Brushy Creek
Neighborhood Association, said she had not heard of such widespread
illness from her neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes, who went door to door Tuesday evening to make sure her
neighbors had all the information they needed, said, ``People
aren't dropping like flies, but they should be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   $S:US/PRIu;/CATa;/KEYAUS-BRUSHY;
</P>
<P>
   Parasite claiming more spill victims
</P>
<P>
   By Christian Davenport
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Rita Fuentes knew she was going to be in for a long day
yesterday, Fuentes, the communicable disease nurse for the
