<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISC-XRAYS31-COX     07-30 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-XRAYS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    X-RAYS via computer disc saving time, lives
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Three minutes in a hospital room can seem longer
than an hour in the pediatrician's waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an emergency, says Dr. Kathleen Bohanon, it takes at
least three minutes for a doctor to see her patient's X-rays after
the pictures have been shot. Someone has to develop and print the
film, then someone else has to run the hospital-hall dash to
deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes is a lot of time for doctors and nurses to spend
drumming their fingers and watching the clock and wondering if they
did all the right things a few moments earlier when the patient's
heart stopped beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to see that X-ray immediately so you can decide the
next thing to do for this critically ill patient,'' says Bohanon, a
colonel and the chief of medical staff at Wright-Patterson Medical
Center. She'd hate to spend most of her time in a hospital where
that's still not possible, which would be most other hospitals in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two years, nearly all the X-rays and many other
diagnostic images at Wright-Pat have been captured on computer
disks instead of film. As soon as the X-rays are taken, they can be
seen on any of 60 monitors throughout the hospital. Through the Air
Force's Medical Diagnostic Imaging Support System (MDIS), a doctor
often can look at the X-ray before the patient is wheeled back from
radiology.
</P>
<P>
   Besides boosting emergency response to the speed of light,
picture archiving and communications systems (PACS) such as MDIS
have the advantage of turning out X-rays that never disappear in
long-forgotten folders. That availability often spares patients
from repetitious tests or unnecessary biopsies. The digital X-rays
require fewer exposures to radiation, and might someday lead to
more definite diagnoses and 3-inch disks on which people can carry
their complete medical histories.
</P>
<P>
   An outgrowth of satellite technology and battlefield urgency,
PACS have caught the attention of most big civilian hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in 10 years, the only people doing X-rays on
film are going to be Third World countries,'' said Dr. Kevin Voss,
the colonel who directs the Wright-Pat Medical Center radiology
department. At an international convention of radiologists last
November, he said PACS were the hottest topic of discussion since
magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) started producing sharp pictures
of soft tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Wright-Pat has every kind of picture on its PACS network except
mammograms, which require such intense sharpness that the
government hasn't approved a digital medium for them. Besides
X-rays, it has CAT scans, MRIs, ultrasound and gastrointestinal
pictures and, after ironing out the final wrinkles last week,
angiography (heart) images.
</P>
<P>
   The system has 2 trillion bytes of storage capacity _ enough for
250,000 chest X-rays _ and plenty of shelf space for archived disks
when that fills up. It needs 28 square feet to store images that
used to take up 2,800 square feet, Voss said. The former darkroom
for developing X-ray film has been turned into an office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every health-care decision depends on transferring
information out of and into the radiology department,'' said Bilal
Ezzeddine, who has spent three years developing a PACS as imaging
project director at Kettering Medical Center. He said hospitals
cannot tolerate backlogs in imaging departments, which slow down
the rest of a hospital as surely as a highway accident downtown
backs traffic up to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering already uses its PACS for one thing still in the
planning stage at Wright-Pat: transmission of images between
distant hospitals. Cardiologists at Kettering can view images from
Middletown Regional Hospital, which has a diagnostic heart lab but
no surgical program, and discuss a patient's treatment while he's
on his way in an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   The military first did that more than seven years ago during the
Gulf War, said Chuck Beverly, who oversees Wright-Pat's PACS for
its manufacturer, GE Medical Systems. A radiologist in Virginia
read a CAT scan that was beamed off a satellite from the
battlefield in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   With its unique battlefield needs and its network of military
hospitals, the Department of Defense was in a better position than
individual hospitals to sink a huge investment into digital imaging
and archiving _ $8.5 million up front in Wright-Pat's case. It was
the second military hospital on line in the fall of 1992 and phased
in the system until it stopped using film internally in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the system has progressed to the point where people at the
medical center can work with community hospitals looking for
archiving networks. With the military's new Tricare health plan
farming more and more business out to civilian doctors,
transmitting images between hospitals is becoming essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's exciting here is technology has fixed a problem and
made it better,'' said Ed Quillan of the med center's computer
systems department.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was to accommodate the growing field of medical
imaging without hiring a platoon to file and distribute the
pictures. A study at Brooke Army Medical Center outside San Antonio
showed that two weeks after X-rays were taken, 30 percent couldn't
be found and about 10 percent hadn't been read. ``I'm sure that's
true at most teaching hospitals,'' Voss said.
</P>
<P>
   The technology evolved from the snapping and storing of large
volumes of pictures from spy satellites. ``If you can get a
detailed image from miles above the Earth, imagine what you can get
up-close and personal with somebody's anatomy,'' said Master Sgt.
Tom Monroe, the non-commissioned officer in charge of MDIS.
</P>
<P>
   The military's system wasn't the first network for storing and
transmitting images, Beverly said. It was just the first to
transfer images of different manufacturers _ say from a Siemens CAT
scanner through a Merge modem to a GE network on Imation disks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things doctors noticed was that they no longer
had to spend as much as half an hour a day looking for X-rays that
were piled in wire baskets or in transit between departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when we create an image, the physician can see it down the
hall and he's happy,'' Monroe said. ``And we still have it filed,
so we're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The system took a little longer to grow on radiologists, Voss
said. They knew how to read film. Screens are a little different.
``It was like going to England and driving on the opposite side of
the road.'' The docs were afraid they'd miss something.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they learned the screen lets them do something film
never allowed: They could adjust for brightness and contrast.
Instead of calling the patient back to reshoot a bad image, they
could fix it themselves. Instead of using separate exposures for,
say, a hip and a thigh, they only needed one. They could even tweak
a single chest X-ray to focus on the lungs, the ribs, the spine and
the liver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's particularly helpful with kids because they're all
different sizes,'' Bohanon said. ``You might be getting film every
day of a baby with lung disease, and each one's a little different
darkness. So you're trying to decide if the disease is changing or
the X-ray technique is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing current and previous X-rays is the best way to
diagnose many illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a nodule on somebody's chest, we've got the
person's X-rays going back to 1992,'' Voss said. If it hasn't
changed in six years, it can't be cancer. ``Now we don't have to do
a biopsy. We don't have to do surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, the Wright-Pat doctor can even show both pictures
to his patient on his office desktop computer. A link with the
hospital's appointment system will put the right pictures on the
desktop just when the patient arrives. If the patient can see a
picture of his own pneumonia, Voss said, he might be more inclined
to take his medicine as directed.
</P>
<P>
   The technology will soon put images together with lab reports
and doctors' comments, Monroe said. Properly encrypted, a chest
X-ray can be e-mailed to a California specialist. Or a neck X-ray
can be sent from the emergency room to a neurosurgeon's home, where
he can decide if he needs to rush to the hospital or if surgery can
wait till the morning.
</P>
<P>
   As huge databases grow, doctors can compare similar disorders to
see what subtleties they have in common. They're already learning
more about the characteristics of Alzheimer's disease that way.
Some day, computers probably will be able to look for those
characteristics and help doctors make a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just getting started,'' Voss said. With chest X-rays
and mammograms, some computers are programmed to highlight areas
where the radiologist should pay close attention.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, the computers are flagging too many things that
don't matter. ``But that's coming. Computer-assisted diagnosis is a
natural progression. Predicting what's going to occur based on past
information _ people are just scratching the surface on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
