A0168 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HEAT31-COX     07-30 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas thirsts for hint of relief
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    and Rebeca Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin _ It's hot. It's dry. And nobody knows when it's going to
rain.
</P>
<P>
   That was the consensus at a legislative hearing on Texas'
deepening drought. Lack of rainfall and triple-digit temperatures
are producing wide-ranging effects statewide:
</P>
<P>
   Texas' share of water in the two international reservoirs
supplying the Lower Rio Grande Valley is at a combined 21percent of
capacity, the lowest level since the storage system was completed
nearly 30 years ago. (Mexico's storage is at 14 percent.) State
officials foresee no immediate problems meeting the needs of
household and municipal uses, but crop losses are mounting.
</P>
<P>
   Flow at Comal Springs in New Braunfels, the largest spring in
the southwestern United States, is dropping daily and could soon
hit the level where the existence of spring-dependent endangered
fish would be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   More ranchers are selling off cattle because pastures are
withering and feed is expensive. U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman, winding up a two-day tour of Texas and Oklahoma, said
last year's farm bill ended a program allowing the federal
government to assist farmers with feed costs and compensate them
for dead animals during natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental officials have put 213 of the state's 4,201
community water systems on a ``watch list'' because their pumps and
pipes are under strain or supplies are being depleted. The human
toll is mounting, with 96 deaths since June 1. The latest victim
was Tommy McDeane, 48, of Dallas, who died recently at a hospital
after an apparent heat stroke about two weeks ago. In Central
Texas, temperatures have broken the century mark in 16 of the last
19 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken a whuppin,''' said Travis Miller, a professor and
extension agronomist with Texas A&AMP;M University, about the state's
estimated agricultural losses of $1.5 billion. But his comment also
spoke volumes about the broader effects of the searing weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature enacted a landmark water law last year that
requires cities, water-supply companies, irrigation districts and
other suppliers to conserve more, plan for droughts and work out
regional water-supply arrangements. State Sen. Buster Brown, R-Lake
Jackson, said it was unfortunate that thelegislation was not passed
a few years ago. It's too soon for all of the plans and
conservation measures to be in place, he said at the hearing, held
by a House-Senate panel examining water issues.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, cities across the state can provide residents
with water, said Carolyn Brittin, director of special projects for
the Texas Water Development Board, a planning and financing agency.
</P>
<P>
   But if the drought worsens, many small and medium-size cities
could be hard-pressed for cash to drill new wells, replace broken
equipment and make other improvements, said state Rep. Ron Lewis,
D-Mauriceville. He said many such communities might hesitate to
apply to the development board for loans.
</P>
<P>
   As in most droughts, farmers and ranchers have been the first to
feel the impact. Ranchers are selling 30 percent more cattle than
last summer in the East Texas town of Navasota, said Curtis Burlin,
who runs the local auction barn. ``If you have to sell them all,
it'll take you five years to grow new cows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry said some auction
houses are selling cattle at 10 times last year's rate. ``We're
sitting on what could be one of the worst natural disasters in
Texas history,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton already has declared Texas and 10 other states
in the South and Southwest disaster areas because of heat and
drought, triggering $100 million in federal aid. Texas is expected
to receive $32.7 million of that, primarily for helping low-income
people pay utility bills and buy air-conditioning units, said Tom
Millwee, state coordinator of emergency management.
</P>
<P>
   The current drought differs from the 1996 drought, said James
Kowis, a senior technical specialist for the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission. The 1996 drought began in the fall of the
previous year, while this one began after a wet spring. Therefore,
most areas of the state have more ample supplies now than they did
at the same time two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there are notable exceptions. The watershed supplying the
Lower Rio Grande Valley never received sufficient rainfall to
recover from the '96 drought, Kowis said. And stream flows in
scattered parts of the state are approaching the levels of two
years ago. That spells trouble for some of the state's endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the fountain darter, a 2-inch fish that lives in
the cool waters of Comal Springs. Normally, water flows from the
Edwards Aquifer into the springs at 125,000 gallons per minute.
</P>
<P>
   This week, flow was about 80,000 gallons _ the lowest all year.
Increased draw on the aquifer prompted the Legislature in 1993 to
form the Edwards Aquifer Authority. The agency is supposed to
regulate aquifer pumping and monitor aquifer levels to keep them
from dropping below federally mandated levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, an environmental group, is considering stepping
up its pending federal lawsuit against 1,000 of the largest aquifer
pumpers, including San Antonio and several military bases, said
Myron Hess, a lawyer for the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been lucky in the past, the last two times that the
aquifer dropped to dangerously low levels, that we got rain,'' Hess
said. ``But we're not going to get lucky every time.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
