<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ My dad was a Fort Worth cop for almost 40 years,
most of that as adetective in the homicide division. Working the
homicide detail isn't exactly easy duty -- the hours can be brutal
for one thing -- but he would tell me plainly that it was nothing
compared to the 10 years or so he spent patrolling the streets of
Cowtown. Uniform officers take the frontline of danger in the
police business. Twice in that 10 years criminals made direct
attempts on his life. In that era before police officers had to
watch how they treated prisoners, it was a mistake that both men
paid for. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CSIBLEY-COLUMN _ It's almost camp meeting time in Georgia. Those
crops that the heat and drought haven't burned up are, in the
poetic phrase, laid by. It's almost time to put the chairs in the
wagon, hitch the milk cow to the tailgate and head for Old Salem or
New Hope or blessed Shiloh campground. But until camp meeting
starts, there are decoration days at small churches all over the
state. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ If society shrugs as standards decline, we're in
trouble. An old friend who has seen the calendar turn about as many
times as I have was on the phone. ``I think I've lived too long,''
he said. ``Maybe both of us have,'' I replied. ``What's bothering
you today?'' `` ``It's a Winston billboard. It says, `Finally, a
butt worth kissing.' Can you imagine such bad taste on a billboard
in downtown Atlanta?'' (Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
