<P>
   DANCE-SPORT _ PALM BEACH _ Come Sunday, August 2, they will have
danced all week. For the 18th consecutive year, The Triple Crown
DanceSport Championships are waltzing and swinging, mamboing and
boleroing, fox-trotting and quick-stepping their way around the
Gulfstream Ballroom of The Breakers. ``We have about 700 dancers
signed up, and I expect around 1,200 spectators,'' said Larry Dean,
owner of Dance Consultants Unlimited, the event's producer. It's
been accepted as a full exhibition event at the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, Australia. (Hayes, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   FASTPITCH-ONLINE _ JUPITER, Fla. _ A great experiment in cyber
softball is being conducted in a small room at the town hall.
``Nothing quite like this has been tried before,'' said Melinda
Miller, the town's director of information services. ``We have had
to develop our own software. The response we've gotten has been
overwhelming.'' Jupiter, host city for the ongoing NSA Girls Youth
Fastpitch World Series, expanded its Internet Web site to provide
tournament results, highlights and features on participating teams.
Under Miller's direction, www.nsa-worldseries.com was born _ and to
a reception that was enthusiastic beyond expectation. (Moffett,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE-CALLS _ RIVIERA BEACH _ When it finally happened, Emma
Goldwire couldn't use her bathroom. ``The carpet was wet, it even
ran out into the hallway,'' said Goldwire, 75, who lives at 1961 W.
13th St. ``I had to go to my daughter's house to take a shower.''
The leak was caused by roots from a neighbor's ficus tree. They had
penetrated the bathroom floor, reaching underneath the tub and
around Goldwire's toilet. Ficus trees _ and their cousins, rubber
and banyan trees _ can send roots more than 100 feet from their
bases in search of water to nourish their splendid canopies.
(Trontz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR-STORY _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Editor's note: For the next few
weeks, Ron Wiggins will be picking names at random from the phone
book for What's Your Story?, a column based on the premise that
everyone has a story to tell. This week, he found Lindsay Porter, a
Jupiter, Florida teenager ready to take on the world if she could
just skip the high school portion. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ALZHEIMERS-BOOK _ Mark Warner, an architect and gerontologist
from Jupiter, explains Alzheimer's logic in a new book, ``The
Complete Guide to Alzheimer's-Proofing Your Home,'' published this
month by Purdue University Press, (800) 933-9637. The 470-page book
gives caregivers room-by-room _ and symptom-by-symptom _ advice on
how to make a loved one feel more comfortable and independent at
home. (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ALZHEIMERS-SIDE _ About 4 million Americans have Alzheimer's
disease. One in 10 people age 65 or older _ and nearly half of
those age 85 or older _ have Alzheimer's. Seven out of 10 people
with Alzheimer's disease live at home. (And other Alzheimer's
facts.) (Fuchs, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   PARASITES-VICTIMS _ AUSTIN _ Rita Fuentes knew she was going to
be in for a long day. Fuentes, the communicable disease nurse for
the Williamson County and Cities Health District, had scores of
calls to return from the day before _ all to people who had
reported stomach ailments that officials believe is caused by a
July 14 spill of raw sewage from a City of Austin pumping station
into Brushy Creek. But when she got to the office, she had a whole
new stack of calls to make: 47 messages from people reporting
symptoms that varied from diarrhea and vomiting to nausea and
headaches. (Davenport, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISC-XRAYS _ Three minutes in a hospital room can seem longer
than an hour in the pediatrician's waiting room. Even in an
emergency, says Dr. Kathleen Bohanon, it takes at least three
minutes for a doctor to see her patient's X-rays after the pictures
have been shot. Someone has to develop and print the film, then
someone else has to run the hospital-hall dash to deliver it. ``You
need to see that X-ray immediately so you can decide the next thing
to do for this critically ill patient,'' says Bohanon, a colonel
and the chief of medical staff at Wright-Patterson Medical Center.
For more than two years, nearly all the X-rays and many other
diagnostic images at Wright-Pat have been captured on computer
disks instead of film. As soon as the X-rays are taken, they can be
seen on any of 60 monitors throughout the hospital. (Lamb, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-FLYJESUS _ (w/photos) Harold Martin of Hobe Sound is a
student at Moody aviation learning to do airplane maintenance for
mission planes. They fly to strange places taking the word of God
and supplies. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-CARRINGTON _ HBO wants to talk about a sitcom. Album sales
are climbing. Comedy club gigs have him rolling in the dough.
Rodney Carrington can feel it. He's on the verge of something
big.``I can feel a rumble,'' says Carrington, who brings his at the
Comedy Corner in West Palm Beach the next two weekends. (Houck,
Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
