   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   FASTPITCH-ONLINE _ JUPITER, Fla. _ A great experiment in cyber
softball is being conducted in a small room at the town hall.
``Nothing quite like this has been tried before,'' said Melinda
Miller, the town's director of information services. ``We have had
to develop our own software. The response we've gotten has been
overwhelming.'' Jupiter, host city for the ongoing NSA Girls Youth
Fastpitch World Series, expanded its Internet Web site to provide
tournament results, highlights and features on participating teams.
Under Miller's direction, www.nsa-worldseries.com was born _ and to
a reception that was enthusiastic beyond expectation. (Moffett,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE-CALLS _ RIVIERA BEACH _ When it finally happened, Emma
Goldwire couldn't use her bathroom. ``The carpet was wet, it even
ran out into the hallway,'' said Goldwire, 75, who lives at 1961 W.
13th St. ``I had to go to my daughter's house to take a shower.''
The leak was caused by roots from a neighbor's ficus tree. They had
penetrated the bathroom floor, reaching underneath the tub and
around Goldwire's toilet. Ficus trees _ and their cousins, rubber
and banyan trees _ can send roots more than 100 feet from their
bases in search of water to nourish their splendid canopies.
(Trontz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR-STORY _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Editor's note: For the next few
weeks, Ron Wiggins will be picking names at random from the phone
book for What's Your Story?, a column based on the premise that
everyone has a story to tell. This week, he found Lindsay Porter, a
Jupiter, Florida teenager ready to take on the world if she could
just skip the high school portion. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
