<P>
   PARASITES-VICTIMS _ AUSTIN _ Rita Fuentes knew she was going to
be in for a long day. Fuentes, the communicable disease nurse for
the Williamson County and Cities Health District, had scores of
calls to return from the day before _ all to people who had
reported stomach ailments that officials believe is caused by a
July 14 spill of raw sewage from a City of Austin pumping station
into Brushy Creek. But when she got to the office, she had a whole
new stack of calls to make: 47 messages from people reporting
symptoms that varied from diarrhea and vomiting to nausea and
headaches. (Davenport, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DISC-XRAYS _ Three minutes in a hospital room can seem longer
than an hour in the pediatrician's waiting room. Even in an
emergency, says Dr. Kathleen Bohanon, it takes at least three
minutes for a doctor to see her patient's X-rays after the pictures
have been shot. Someone has to develop and print the film, then
someone else has to run the hospital-hall dash to deliver it. ``You
need to see that X-ray immediately so you can decide the next thing
to do for this critically ill patient,'' says Bohanon, a colonel
and the chief of medical staff at Wright-Patterson Medical Center.
For more than two years, nearly all the X-rays and many other
diagnostic images at Wright-Pat have been captured on computer
disks instead of film. As soon as the X-rays are taken, they can be
seen on any of 60 monitors throughout the hospital. (Lamb, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
