<P>
   POLL-CALIF (Sacramento) _ In the first voter survey since the
raucous June primary, a San Francisco Examiner poll shows Lt. Gov.
Gray Davis is favored over Attorney General Dan Lungren,
particularly among women and independent voters, in the race for
governor. Davis leads Lungren 48 to 39 percent. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CYCLISTS (San Francisco) _ On Friday thousands of bicyclists
will mark the one-year anniversary of the infamous Critical Mass
that paralyzed car traffic here for several hours and jump-started
bike politics in San Francisco. Some participants say they hope to
make a strong political statement for cycling but do not seek
another confrontation with police. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   SF-LABOR (San Francisco) _ An interest group considered to be
the strongest and most effective at getting its way with local
government here _ organized labor _ doesn't disclose its lobbying
of city officials, despite a 10-year-old law aimed at eliminating
back-room deal-making. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-UNIVERSITY (San Francisco) _ Ten months after the
California Virtual University popped up on the World Wide Web,
making the audacious claim it could link students worldwide with
unrivaled educational opportunities, CVU looks like the team to
beat. In the past six months, it has more than doubled the number
of courses it offers electronically. Now it has been turned over to
a nonprofit foundation formed by educators. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
