upper-class fairy tale about the problems of the rich and lovelorn.
And parents can take heart in knowing that it's a movie they can
safely let their kids see. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-NEGOTIATOR (Undated) _ ``The Negotiator'' is
probably one of the least offensive of the summer's goofy and
contrived movies. It may be difficult to swallow that a police
hostage negotiator, framed for his partner's murder, resorts to
taking hostages himself in order to clear his name. But at least as
directed by L. Gary Gray and acted by Samuel L. Jackson, it is
watchable. By BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE-RYAN (San Antonio) _ Linda Lopez never understood why
her father, Remigio Cobarruvias, was so reluctant to talk about
World War II, especially his role in the tide-turning D-Day
invasion. After seeing the film ``Saving Private Ryan,'' three
generations of Cobarruviases understood what the veteran of Utah
Beach experienced. By DANIEL J. VARGAS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACING (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ When Victory Gallop goes to
the races early next month, Elliot Walden, his trainer, has
absolutely no doubts that Gary Stevens will be the jockey on his
colt's back. Victory Gallop, who hasn't raced since depriving Real
Quiet of winning the Triple Crown by edging out his rival in the
Belmont Stakes last month, is scheduled to run next in the $1
million Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park in New Jersey. By TIM
WILKIN.
</P>
