   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Kenneth Starr could have saved
Monica Lewinsky a lot of headaches, and us a lot of money, by
nailing the president years ago on the Whitewater deal. Now we
learn that Monica's parents ``are relieved their daughter is out of
harm's way.'' Right. What was Starr going to do? Send a 25-year-old
to jail for falling for our president? She still has a life
sentence as the woman who launched a billion jokes. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Despite insistence to the
contrary by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Tuesday's Capitol
Rotunda ``tribute'' to policemen Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson
was inappropriate excess that nearly cheapened the deaths of both
men. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MANAGED-CARE (Oakland, Calif.) _ Smithy, a kidney patient, has
learned, as have other Americans, that Catch-22 has arrived in
American health care. Die, or pay twice: once to maintain managed
care coverage, then again out-of-pocket when the prepaid
managed-care plan bosses deny benefits. That is why the battle in
Congress over patients' rights is crucial. By ROBERT L. WEINMANN.
</P>
