<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-RYAN-HNS &LR;      07-30 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-RYAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMANDY VETERANS RELIVE INVASION THROUGH TALE OF PVT. RYAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIEL J. VARGAS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Linda Lopez never understood why her father,
Remigio Cobarruvias, was so reluctant to talk about World War II,
especially his role in the tide-turning D-Day invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobarruvias was a 19-year-old medic with the Fourth Infantry
Division, which stormed Utah beach. He was drafted just after
graduating from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Three generations of Cobarruviases saw the new Steven Spielberg
film last weekend. When the credits rolled and moviegoers filed
out, Cobarruvias sat still, staring at the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to him and thanked him for what he did, and most
importantly for coming home,'' Lopez says.
</P>
<P>
   She says experiencing the film as a family was healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bridges the generational gaps,'' she says. ``The horrors my
father experienced at such a young age, it explains why he didn't
want to talk about it. Now, I really understand what he went
through. It's a part of my father's history so it becomes my
history, and I want it to be part of my children's history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' strips away any glamour attached to
combat and shines a harsh light on ``the good war,'' the bloodiest
conflict in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   The film, starring Tom Hanks, follows eight infantrymen who land
at Normandy on D-Day and end up searching for Pvt. Ryan (Matt
Damon), whose three brothers have been killed in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Spears had heard some of her grandfather's war stories
and rummaged through his military photos and records, but she
couldn't comprehend what he went through, the hellish nature of
combat.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hear a story, but not all the gunfire, the screams,''
Spears, 27, said after seeing the film with her 74-year-old
grandfather, World War II veteran Charles W. Armstrong, who took
part in the Normandy invasion. ``I never pictured it quite like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, 1944, Armstrong was a 20-year-old paratrooper (like
the character Pvt. Ryan) with the 82nd Airborne Division. Armstrong
and 35 other men aboard a C-47 were dropped 35 miles inland just
hours before the Allied invasion of Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few minutes into ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the tears
began. During the grisly, 24-minute re-enactment of the Omaha beach
landing that opens the film, Armstrong clenched his 82nd Airborne
camouflage cap. He took deep breaths. His legs twitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly like it,'' the three-time Purple Heart
recipient says of the film. ``It was so real. While I sat there, I
couldn't stop from crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong says he was lucky to be so far inland that day. He had
volunteered for airborne duty because paratroopers made $50 more
per month. He was pulled out of Italy and then stationed in
Nottingham, England, for three months in preparation for D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a lot of friends over there,'' Armstrong says. ``We
were scared. Everyone was afraid, but you had to go. I wasn't a
coward. Even now, some days I wake up crying.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Lisa Armstrong, 37, says the film has given her a
newfound gratitude for World War II veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives would be different today if it wasn't for them,''
she says. ``I'm so proud of him and glad he made it through. It was
hard to watch, but I think it's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears says she didn't want to see the movie without her
``papa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to experience it with him,'' she says. ``I just
wanted to be with him holding his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, says Cobarruvias, who as a medic saw the horrors of
combat up close, was ``real, real tough.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ryan's'' realism is important, he says, so younger
generations can understand that World War II was just as terrible
as the Vietnam conflict, so often chronicled on film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad people can get an idea of what happened over there,''
he says. ``War is hell. It takes a lot of our young people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
