<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Tinkering with the legend of Atlantis
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 2, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am a devoted reader of the Sunday New York Times Book Review
section. Often it saves me the trouble of reading the books
themselves, which allows me to talk about more books than I
actually read, which is helpful at cocktail parties.
</P>
<P>
   A recent New York Times review of the Richard Ellis book
``Imagining Atlantis'' caught my attention, and inasmuch as I have
not been invited to many cocktail parties lately, this is my only
outlet for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   According to reviewer Robert Eisner, a professor of classics and
humanities at San Diego State University, Ellis claims that
Atlantis did not and does not exist. It was invented by Plato,
writes Ellis, for one of his literary dialogues, just as Lilliput
and Brobdingnag were creations of Jonathan Swift for ``Gulliver's
Travels.''
</P>
<P>
   I never have met anyone who sent out a search party for either
Lilliput or Brobdingnag, but scores have been in pursuit of
Atlantis, that formerly powerful civilization that legend says
apparently sank into the sea because of a huge sinkhole, or
something similar.
</P>
<P>
   According to the review, upwards of 2,000 books have been
written about Atlantis, none of them proving there ever was an
Atlantis. People have looked everywhere for the place, in the
Mediterranean, the Atlantic, the Straits of Florida, the Caribbean,
maybe even in the Gowanus Canal.
</P>
<P>
   But no Atlantis. And, now, the definitive disclaimer by Ellis:
Atlantis never was. Plato made it up.
</P>
<P>
   What the author and reviewer fail to recognize, in their
literary efforts to be academically correct, is that Atlantis does
exist in the minds of every adventurer and dreamer who ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist I once worked with, the late John Keasler, once
wrote a most profound statement about Atlantis. ``That which you
can find is never Atlantis,'' he wrote, ``but that which you can
never find always will be Atlantis.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis, therefore, is what the Chicago Cubs have been
searching for since 1908, the Boston Red Sox since 1918. Atlantis
is what soap opera star Susan Lucci has been seeking for more than
18 years. Atlantis is what Amelia Earhart sought, and Judge Crater,
too. Atlantis is where Harold Stassen wanted to go, where Bob Dole
is planning a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis may be a literary myth but it is a very real state of
mind. Atlantis is that one thing that is just beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I should read the Ellis book but I won't. With all
those hard-to-say and even harder-to-recall Athenian names, I'd
never make it through the book. For me, ``Imagining Atlantis'' may
be an Atlantis in itself; just beyond my ken.
</P>
<P>
   Keasler's observation about Atlantis always has stayed with me,
particularly because that was a trip he talked me into when I was
managing editor of the Miami News. Handing in his expense account
and receipt BEFORE leaving, he and two buddies set sail from Fort
Lauderdale in a fishing boat. They returned in about a week,
proclaiming the discovery of Atlantis in the region of some known
Bahamian turtle kraals.
</P>
<P>
   I recall another thing he said about Atlantis. ``It's partly off
Bimini and partly off Andros Island. So is some good snapper
fishing,'' he wrote for the Miami News many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's something else I've never been able to find _ some good
snapper fishing.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
