<SLUG> BC-GOVERNESS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXY `GOVERNESS' PIVOTS ON EXPOSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the sensuous, visually astute British period
piece ``The Governess,'' Minnie Driver plays Rosina, a young London
Jewish woman who, to provide for her family after her father is
killed, pretends to be a Protestant in order to secure a position
in a dour, isolated Scottish household.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which is the feature writing and directing debut of
Sandra Goldbacher, doesn't make much of its threat to explore 1840s
anti-Semitism. Rather, it uses Rosina's deception as a central
motif for a story about people who are not what they seem, and how,
perhaps, a new technology of artifice can help expose the truth.
Call it ``Isle of Skye Confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving on the windswept, North Sea rock, Rosina discovers
that the wealthy Cavendish clan is made up of an affected,
borderline hysterical mom (Harriet Walter), a distracted dad (Tom
Wilkinson), a dissolute adult son (Jonathan Rhys Meyers) and a
misbehaved little girl (Florence Hoath) whom her new nanny
describes as ``a rodent in petticoats.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun, resourceful Rosina quickly brings the child around. It
takes a little longer to get to the Mister, who is obsessed with
discovering a fixing solution for the newfangled craft of
photography. Rosina figures it out for him, then provides more by
posing for a series of ``art'' pictures (Salome's a favorite
theme). Their inevitable affair brings Cavendish out of his uptight
shell but of course threatens the very foundation of Christian
Victorian propriety.
</P>
<P>
   The movie eventually lurches into soapy complications while it
becomes another female empowerment parable that uncomfortably
imposes 1990s attitudes on 1840s sensibilities. Still, for its
cunning interplay of image and illusion; its genuine, exultant
eroticism; and the opportunity it gives the versatile Driver to
break out of supportive-girlfriend purgatory, ``The Governess''
deserves our indulgence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-IVOR-BASSETT-ART     07-30 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-IVOR-BASSETT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 WHEN AN OLDER WOMAN ROMANCES A YOUNGER MAN   World rights except
Great Britain and Australia  Color slides and black and white
photos of Angela Bassett and of Bassett and Whoopi Goldberg in
scenes from ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back.''
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's no big deal when Warren Beatty, Jack Nicholson, Michael
Douglas, Clint Eastwood or Harrison Ford romance and win the hearts
of their leading ladies _ most of whom are young enough to be their
daughters.
 &HT;    But what happens when the tables are turned, and the woman is 40
and the object of her desire is 20? Add to the mix the fact that
the couple are black and you have a story perfect for Hollywood.
 &HT;    The movie is ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' (opening Aug.
14.) It stars Angela Bassett as a gorgeous, single stockbroker who
lives in San Francisco, with an adorable son.
 &HT;    All she is missing is a man to share her lifestyle. With pal
Delilah (Whoopi Goldberg) she takes off for a vacation to Jamaica
and falls for Winston Shakespeare (newcomer Taye Diggs, who comes
to the screen from Broadway's ``Rent''). Winston, just out of his
teens, is the son of a wealthy surgeon, but a hunk _ and an
aspiring medical student.
 &HT;    The movie is shot with what could be an intriguing story, but
director Kevin Rodney Sullivan hammers us into a near coma with a
barrage of one liners about age.
 &HT;    Stella (Bassett) is called a cradle-robber. ``I'm old enough to
be your mother,'' she tells the man courting her. He's labeled
jailbait. Get the picture?
 &HT;    While Eastwood and Beatty are obviously decades older than their
leading ladies, Bassett, at 40, looks anything but. Diggs, in his
mid-20s, could pass for 30 so the point seems lost.
 &HT;    But why quibble? That's not what's happening here. When late in
the movie, Stella is taken by the sight of Winston taking a shower
and steps in with him, the audience gasped at the shots of Diggs'
naked torso. He's the Bo Derek of the 1990's.
 &HT;    I haven't seen moviegoers react like that since Robert Redford
took his shirt off in 1973 for Barbra Streisand in ``The Way We
Were.'' Of course, Bassett, best known for her 1993 role as Tina
Turner in ``What's Love Got to Do With It,'' is no chopped liver in
the body department.
 &HT;    The scenario isn't pure Hollywood fiction. It's based on Terry
McMillan's book about her affair with a much younger man. But you
can bet neither of them looked like Bassett or Diggs. McMillan's
last work on screen was in 1995 with ``Waiting to Exhale,'' and the
author, capitalizing on the popular new black ``chick flick''
genre, wrote ``Stella.''
 &HT;    The producer protests that she has a serious aim here:
``Hollywood is uncomfortable with the woman being older,'' declares
Deborah Schindler. ``It goes against the Hollywood grain. Maybe our
film will help crack that stereotype.''
 &HT;    But Bassett certainly doesn't need help. At The Four Seasons
Hotel in Beverly Hills she enters the room in a body-hugging
scarlet dress, black and red clogs, no jewelry or makeup, and
admits that she, too, has dated a much younger man.
 &HT;    ``I once had a boyfriend who was pretty young. I think it can
work. I've dated guys who have been 10 years younger than I _ but
10 years is a significant amount of time. And they were very mature
guys. It was fun but I didn't get as far as thinking of marrying
them.''
 &HT;    So does she approve of older women-younger men relationships?
``If the guy loves and appreciates and admires you _ and he's
mature enough then go for it,'' she says.
 &HT;    Married herself (a year in October) to actor Courtney Vance, (he
appeared in the 1997 TV remake of ``Twelve Angry Men''), Bassett is
off the market. But she has a good memory.
 &HT;    ``I know this girl,'' she says. ``Stella has dealt with so many
disappointments in matters of the heart that she puts romance in a
place where her expectations are zero. I think audiences can really
open themselves up to this piece.'''
 &HT;    Bassett, who came to Hollywood after growing up in projects in
St. Petersburg, Fla., got the acting bug at l6 on a student trip to
Washington, D.C., where she was overwhelmed by James Earl Jones'
performance in John Steinbeck's ``Of Mice and Men.''
 &HT;    On several scholarships, she earned an undergraduate degree from
Yale and went on for a master's in fine arts from the univeristy's
School of Drama. After several Off-Broadway roles, she landed on
Broadway in two August Wilson plays, the 1984 ``Ma Rainey's Black
Bottom'' and the 1986 ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone.''
 &HT;    In l990, John Singleton cast her as a single mother trying to
raise a son in ``Boyz N the Hood.'' She was Betty Shabazz, wife of
Malcolm X (opposite Denzel Washington) in Spike Lee's 1992 movie
about the black leader. But it was her performance as Turner that
earned her a Hollywood Foreign Press best actress Golden Globe and
a best actress Oscar nomination.
 &HT;    The new film may seem small after that kind of performance but
Bassett insists, ``I like Stella. Like many women she's a nurturer,
friend, mother, aunt and worker. She's just plain busy with life.
She has put off nurturing herself, giving herself the freedom to
really love somebody and let him love her _ regardless of a big age
difference.''
 &HT;    She grabbed the part, she says, because, ``The story deals with
universal themes while asking some important questions. Can you
live your own life? Is finding love possible, and if so, what does
it take?''
 &HT;    And maybe she and the film makers hope this story might change
things in Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``This theme hasn't been done very often,'' notes Sullivan.
``This is a male-driven industry so the folks who make the
decisions probably prefer to see an an older actor with a younger
woman,'' he says. ``But as Hollywood evolves more women are in
decision making positions.''
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
