<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYAGE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VOYAGE' A FINE FAREWELL FOR MASTROIANNI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At one point in Manoel de Oliveira's melancholy,
charming film ``Voyage to the Beginning of the World,'' the
resonant Portuguese word saudade is translated to mean ``nostalgia
when you lose your sense of irony.'' Spoken by the great Marcello
Mastroianni in his last movie appearance, it sums up the delicate
feeling, if not the complexity, of this bittersweet memory film.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's world-class director for the better part of the
century, Oliveira, now 89, is clearly reflecting on his own life in
``Voyage.'' Mastroianni plays an aging Portuguese filmmaker named
Manoel who road-trips through the locations of his youth regaling
three accompanying actors like a character out of Proust, with the
memories evoked by sights both changed and remarkably preserved.
</P>
<P>
   But Oliveira isn't just looking back in this film. Rather, he
examines the past as prelude to both the present and future _ and
ultimately views it all as a kind of circle where the elusive
concept of home resides.
</P>
<P>
   With Manoel are two French-speaking Portuguese actors, the
intelligent, impudent Judite (Leonor Silveira) and the fun-loving
Duarte (Diogo Doria). The most significant fellow traveler, though,
is Afonso (Jean Yves Gautier), a Frenchman of Portuguese descent
who doesn't speak his father's tongue but is determined to make
contact with his Iberian relatives for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   As the focus of the film shifts from Manoel's memories to
Afonso's encounter with a suspicious aunt (the wonderful,
rhino-hided Isabel de Castro), questions of where blood ties and
cultural identity belong in modern, cosmopolitan Europe emerge. The
answers, which incorporate the conforming effects of urbanization
and mass media and the specter of nationalism gone horribly wrong
in the Balkans, are not simple.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Oliveira's cinematic plan is simple, but
elegantly so. Much of the movie consists of four people talking in
a moving van and more pseudo-intellectual conversations framed
against picturesque destinations. Yet the film, which opens with a
long shot of lines speeding by on a highway, gradually shifts into
an exquisite collection of visual rhythms, with tempos that change
to fit the emotional mood of a scene much as the film's
well-tempered musical score graduates from dissonance to more
contemplative, if not more comforting melodies.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about this understatedly unsettling piece is pure
pleasure, though: watching Mastroianni being every bit the
sophisticated imp of international cinema he always was to the very
end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
