</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-NEGOTIATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD POLICE WORK IN `THE NEGOTIATOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the goofy and contrived dramatic/action situations
thought up for this summer's crop of movies, the premise for ``The
Negotiator'' is probably one of the least offensive.
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult to swallow that a police hostage negotiator
who finds himself framed for his partner's murder resorts to taking
hostages himself in order to clear his name. But at least as
directed by L. Gary Gray (``Set it Off'') and acted by Samuel L.
Jackson, the thing is watchable.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson plays Danny Roman, famed in Chicago police circles for
his golden tongue and steely courage in life-and-death
circumstances. But when his partner is assassinated and papers
indicating that Danny has been siphoning pension funds to off-shore
accounts are found in his house, Danny demands to face his accuser.
</P>
<P>
   That man is an ethically ambiguous internal affairs investigator
named Niebaum (the late J.T. Walsh). When Danny gets no
satisfaction, he loses his head and takes Niebaum, his assistant
and a petty informer hostage. His intention is to hold them until
he can interrogate Niebaum and learn who framed him.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Chris Sabian (Kevin Spacey), another well-known police
negotiator from across town. Danny will only talk to him because he
knows that the real perpetrators of the crime are fellows in his
own precinct. Danny can't trust his friends because exonerating
Danny will implicate them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the two-hours-plus movie is spent shifting between the
command center occupied by Danny's colleagues and the federal
office building where Danny is trying to get the truth out of
Niebaum and his computer system. In all the back and forth, the one
thing the audience knows is that Danny is innocent. What we don't
know is which of the cops played by John Spencer, Ron Rifkin and
David Morse are trying to kill Danny for their own nasty reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that the movie doesn't have much comprehensible plot.
We know that Sabian will do the right thing and help Danny in the
end, but when the mystery is unraveled and the frame-up is
revealed, I, personally, had no idea what anyone was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many things about this movie that stretched credulity
was the fact that Danny was accused of stealing from the pension
fund based solely on incriminating papers found in his house. I
never heard anyone wondering if these papers had Danny's
fingerprints on them. If not, how did he get them into the house?
With pincers? And when the rubber gloves worn by the killer were
found, no one checked to see if Danny's fingerprints were inside
the gloves' fingers. This is shoddy police work, if you ask me.
</P>
<P>
   I also wondered about the urgency of getting Sabian, who was
stuck in traffic, to the hostage-taking site when he easily could
have started talking to Danny by cellular phone the minute the
police brought him onto the case. Couldn't the filmmakers dream up
another way of creating dramatic tension?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in these big-budget action movies it's always dismaying
when the makeup and wigs look bad. Poor Spacey shouldn't be reduced
to wearing a toupee that is a different color from the rest of his
hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1228EDT &QL; 
