A0250 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEKET-REVIEW-LADN     07-30 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEKET-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CONFUSE `BASEKETBALL' WITH ANYTHING BY WOODY ALLEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2   Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``BASEketball'' is the kind of movie where if two
people walk into a room that has a chute marked ``soiled laundry,''
you know with complete certainty that one of them will fall through
_ and 10 seconds later, you'll see every yucky detail of the
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has been billed as a melding of David Zucker's wacky
``Naked Gun'' sensibilities with the crude satire of ``South Park''
creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone, who star in the film.
Unfortunately, most of the time, ``BASEketball'' just gives us
vulgarity without any of the biting wit. The generational comic
graft simply doesn't work, although the movie isn't without some
funny moments, especially for those in the audience who like their
genital humor in rapid-fire doses.
</P>
<P>
   When ``BASEketball'' begins, it looks like Zucker is going pull
one of his trademark spoofs, this time skewering the professional
sports scene. In a few dead-on minutes, Zucker and his writing team
hit every target _ the commercialization, the franchise relocation,
the lack of loyalty of both players and team owners. There's some
great stuff here that takes the games' greed to the next logical
level _ stadiums named after a hemorrhoid ointment and blimps owned
by the makers of tampons (a great way, no doubt, to make inroads
with that coveted female demographic).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a couple of dimwits (Parker and Stone, naturally) are
spinning their wheels, wondering if they'll have to get jobs and
buy a pair of khakis to finally score with the babes. It turns out
there will be no need for that. The hybrid sports game they play in
their driveway, ``baseketball,'' has caught the eye of a wealthy
Texas oilman (Ernest Borgnine) who decides to promote it as the
alternative national pastime. And to make it a true alternative, he
lays down a couple of ground rules. Teams can't move and players
(who are paid a flat rate) can't switch teams.
</P>
<P>
   The movie spends an inordinate amount of time on the game
itself, perhaps because Zucker and his friends really did invent
it. It's kind of like the basketball shooting contest ``horse,''
only in ``baseketball'' you get singles, doubles and home runs
depending on where you shoot the ball. You miss a basket and you
record an out. You can also ``psyche'' the shooter out by employing
such varied and cunning strategies as pulling down your pants,
calling out the opponent's mother or squirting milk into his face
through a nipple apparatus. (Don't ask.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of it is as dumb as it sounds. There are only so many times
you can watch these guys try to psyche each other out before it
becomes even more boring than an American League baseball game.
Almost all the humor comes from the toilet, and after the first
shock wave wears off, you're left with a bunch of doofuses talking
about chicken poop and vomit. It's all irony, virtually
substance-free. And as anyone who has recently followed David
Letterman's career will tell you, that kind of comic sensibility
wears thin after a while.
</P>
<P>
   There are some funny bits, though, including costume designer
Catherine Adair's inspired team uniforms for the ``baseketball''
league (the Roswell Aliens, L.A. Riots, San Francisco Fairies,
etc). Broadcasters Bob Costas and Al Michaels share the announcing
duties and spoof their own serious images. There are also the
requisite stadium giveaways _ free-range chicken night, dozen-egg
night _ that are good for a laugh or two.
</P>
<P>
   As actors, Parker and Stone are great writers, but they have a
genial enough presence and can hold their own opposite Jenny
McCarthy and Yasmine Bleeth. Also on hand are the ``baseketball''
cheerleaders, whose uniforms come courtesy of Frederick's of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It's all geared toward 17-year-old adolescents or guys who shop
for bed linens at the ESPN Store. For this audience, you can't have
too many shots of people getting kicked in the groin. Others might
start to feel their pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1229EDT &QL; 
