<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVER-REVIEW-LADN     07-30 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRYMORE-BUOYED `EVER AFTER' STILL A CINDERELLA STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Attitude is everything in ``Ever After,'' a
Cinderella story minus the fairy-tale trappings but drenched in
'90s-style romantic fantasy. It's the kind of thing where Cindy
sometimes saves the prince, and the stepmother is a figure of
ridicule as well as malice, but no one's going to dare take the
happily out of ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the illusion of realism director Andy Tennant and his
first-class design team (production designer Michael Howells,
Merchant-Ivory's Oscar-winning costumer Jenny Beavan) get on screen
is nicely complemented by a set of natural, witty performances. If
the script, by Tennant, Susannah Grant (``Pocahontas'') and Rick
Parks, wasn't so fundamentally dream-wishy, the film might be
mistaken for something like social history.
</P>
<P>
   Or a good farce, which it occasionally turns into.
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens sometime in the 19th century, when an aging
survivor of the French royal family (Jeanne Moreau, exquisitely
imperious) summons the Brothers Grimm to her palace. She has a bone
to pick with their version of ``Cinderella,'' and she has the
actual glass slipper to prove her point.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back about three centuries to a rustic manor home where a
bright little tomboy named Danielle is the apple of her widowed
father Auguste's (Jeroen Krabbe) eye. But shortly after he
remarries the snooty if penniless noblewoman Rodmilla (Anjelica
Huston), Auguste has a heart attack. His last thoughts are of his
daughter, which provides at least a semblance of emotional
justification for the stepmother's future wickedness.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or so years later, Danielle has grown into robust Drew
Barrymore. Though reduced to servant status by Rodmilla and her
daughters, the pretty but hateful Marguerite (Megan Dodds) and the
porky, resentful Jacqueline (Melanie Lynskey, who played the
magnificently psycho sourpuss in ``Heavenly Creatures''), Danielle
accepts her degraded position by choice. Her efforts are all that's
keeping the mismanaged family estate solvent, and she's covered
with ashes because she stays up all night reading Thomas More by
firelight.
</P>
<P>
   In short, she ain't no victim, she's just pursuing a slightly
downscale self-improvement strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle and handsome Prince Henry (Dougray Scott) meet cute:
She beans the heir to the French throne with well-pitched apples
when he steals her father's horse. He's just trying to run away
from an arranged marriage to some Spanish princess he's never met,
but no matter. Henry admires the peasant girl's spunk.
</P>
<P>
   When she disguises herself as a noblewoman and meets the prince
again, he doesn't recognize Danielle but is intrigued by her
stubborn commitment to the plight of the working folk. Infatuation
grows through a series of convenient encounters, sometimes abetted
by the Renaissance equivalent of a fairy godmother: Leonardo da
Vinci (Patrick Godfrey), visiting scholar and matchmaker
extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   Rodmilla has other plans, however. The French king gives his son
until the big masked ball to find a mate he really loves, after
which the Spanish gambit goes into effect. Sexy Marguerite is a
perfect candidate, and that scruffy Danielle better not get in the
way. Without the aid of a magic pumpkin, can the good-hearted girl
prevail?
</P>
<P>
   Huston has a fabulous time playing the calculating, grasping
Rodmilla; she knows just how to deliver a pretension-puncturing
gesture in a way everyone but the character can laugh at. Barrymore
and newcomer Scott make a wonderful couple, of course; it would be
hard for them not to, since they're both playing people whose flaws
are even attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Lynskey, no surprise, is the supporting-cast standout as the
disrespected duckling who refuses to toe the evil stepsister line.
She's a comic vision of rebellion in puffy sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in France's Dordogne region, ``Ever After'' is visually
sumptuous without getting too fussy about it. It's not any more
believable than the fantastic versions of the ``Cinderella'' fable,
and it's hardly the subversion that the filmmakers may wish to
believe.
</P>
<P>
   And, as ever, a change in style has little impact on anything as
powerful as the wish to believe in happily ever after.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
