<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DREW-MOVIE-LADN     07-30 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREW-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE DREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Drew Barrymore certainly didn't have a fairy-tale
childhood. But she knows a thing or two about happy endings, and
that made her a pretty good choice to play the Cinderella-type
character in ``Ever After,'' a charming, romantic update of the the
classic children's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one thing I've learned,'' the 23-year-old Barrymore
says, ``is that fairy tales get darkest right before the light.
That's one of the reasons I wanted to be in this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever After'' manages to put a modern twist on the story while
retaining a wonderfully old-fashioned feel. Cinderella no longer
waits for Prince Charming to rescue her; in fact, she saves the
prince's life with her quick thinking _ and strong back muscles _
on one occasion. The girl loves to read, can hold her own with a
sword and would be just as happy without the prince, as long as she
could somehow move her stepmother and stepsisters off her late
father's land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be doing this kind of movie at a time when there
are so many films being made about tough, evil subjects,'' says
Angelica Huston, who plays the (still) wicked stepmother with
delicious gusto. ``Being involved with something sweet and tender
was a delight.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Andy Tennant (``Fools Rush In'') came upon the Susannah
Grant's original script two years ago and, with the help of writing
partner Rick Parks, polished it, adding comic elements and beefing
up the role of the prince (who never actually speaks in the Disney
animated feature).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had recently become a parent, and I was starting to notice
the kind of influence these stories and cartoons had,'' Tennant
says. ``I didn't want my daughters to grow up believing they have
to marry a rich guy with a big house in order to live happily ever
after.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore came attached to the project, and while Tennant admits
she wasn't everyone's choice to play Danielle, the film's
Cinderella, he believed she would be perfect for the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Drew, and I can tell you that she has lived
Cinderella's story,'' says Tennant, who five years ago directed
Barrymore in ``The Amy Fisher Story,'' one of the actress' first
significant comeback projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has lived through a lot,'' Tennant continues. ``She didn't
have an easy childhood, and I think this project appealed to her to
a certain extent because it could let her exorcise those demons.
There were many times on the set where I would see her going into a
black hole and tap into some things that I think she's done a good
job of avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew, too, that the movie rested upon her shoulders, which
I think both psyched her up and terrified her.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore's troubled past should be familiar even to people who
don't tune into ``Hard Copy'' or read the gossip sheets, perhaps
because she made such a point of going public with the ups and
downs of her life. Her autobiography (yes, she has already written
one) contained the famous line: ``I had my first drink at age 9,
began smoking marijuana at 10, and at 12 took up cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting was in her bloodstream as well, being the granddaughter
of the legendary John Barrymore and goddaughter of Steven
Spielberg, who cast her at age 6 in her first movie, ``E.T.'' After
teen years that began in a mental health facility and ended with a
cover spread in Playboy, Barrymore took control of her life _ and
career _ by winning legal proceedings against her mother, who was
then her manager, too.
</P>
<P>
   So when Barrymore speaks of fairy tales, she certainly has in
mind the fractured kind as told by the Brothers Grimm attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of see this movie as an abolition of cliches,'' she
says. ``Cinderella doesn't have to be this girly, helpless
creature. She can be strong. She can be smart. She can be
vulnerable, but she can learn to make it on her own, too. I think a
lot of young women will be able to relate to this story and see
that it's what is in your mind and heart that's important. You take
care of that and the other things will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever After'' also explains the motivations of the story's
other characters, showing the prince to be something of a prisoner
of his title. (``He learns that power is the ability to change the
world for the better,'' Barrymore says. ``I really like that. It's
something I'm trying to learn, too.'') Huston's stepmother isn't a
cartoon character, either. She's a baddie, all right, but part of
the reason she despises Cinderella is that the girl's presence is a
painful reminder of her late husband's untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   This thoughtful grounding gives the scenes between Barrymore and
Huston an interesting, emotional resonance that expands on the
fairy tale's universal themes.
</P>
<P>
   ```Cinderella' has always had some pretty powerful things going
on,'' Tennant says. ``There's the sibling rivalry, mother-daughter
rivalry and issues of self-worth. Those are all reasons the story
has been around for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore was thrilled to work with Huston, daughter of
directing great John Huston, and not for simply the obvious
reasons. She saw it as a linking of two great dramatic traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the idea of both of our families coming together,''
Barrymore says. ``It's kind of cool to think of honoring the legacy
of the Hustons and Barrymores in one movie.''
</P>
<P>
   As for their potent scenes together, Barrymore admits there are
some obvious mother-daughter correlations to her own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there were some times when it got kind of hard,''
Barrymore says. ``But that's part of acting and part of what makes
it great. You should be willing to go to those places for all your
roles. I love having that cathartic channel and being able to give
a sense of myself in my movies. I don't think you ever need to
create any drama. Life provides it.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, for Barrymore, the drama is coming in smaller
doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good girl, and she's really pulled her life
together,'' says Charles Shyer, the producer-writer of ``The Parent
Trap'' who directed a young Barrymore in the 1984 comedy,
``Irreconcilable Differences'' and has since kept in touch. ``She
is a real success story, the kind of which this town needs.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Barrymore is basking in the light of a happy ending, she
is making sure to keep her feet firmly grounded, from the dirt she
sprinkled in her shoes when she attended the Oscars (``With the
daisies in my hair, I was a human flower pot,'' she says with a
laugh) to the kinds of slippers she really prefers to wear. Hint:
They're not of the glass variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' she says, giggling. ``I'm an Isotoner girl. I didn't
even get one of those glass slippers Salvatore Ferragamo made for
the movie. Too fussy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cinderella for the '90s indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
