<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-30 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM VIETNAM, PHOTOS WORTH THOUSANDS OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I wasn't there. ``There'' is Vietnam, and that's
the word so many use.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors to ``Requiem,'' an exhibition of war photographs
by photographers killed in the Vietnam War, also weren't there.
Others were, and all kinds left comments in a guest book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried here today. I was there. It was as horrible as these
images.'' So wrote a man who served in a helicopter unit in Vietnam
from 1967 to 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been there. Done that. Have the steel plate in my head to
prove it,'' wrote another visitor. ``The memories are still too
powerful to look at the pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Photos never speak of the real pains endured,'' wrote a former
Marine.
</P>
<P>
   The messages in the book speak of real pain, and therefore I
omit the names of those who wrote them. Many are private
communications between authors and their souls.
</P>
<P>
   Some messages were left like names on rocks. ``I was there, Aug.
'65 _ July '66,'' wrote a veteran, adding only his name and former
rank.
</P>
<P>
   Many writers left no name at all. One left the kind of message
that carries the bleak cynicism of the '60s: ``War is a great photo
opp.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, based on the book ``Requiem,'' edited by famed
war photographers Tim Page and Horst Faas, is sponsored by the
Freedom Forum, a foundation dedicated to a free press.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition runs through Aug. 22 at the One Market office
complex in San Francisco, where the Freedom Forum has its West
Coast headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The late Larry Burrows' famous 1965 photo of a crying Marine
helicopter crew chief hangs opposite polished elevators. A picture
of the legendary photographer Dickey Chapelle lying mortally
wounded near Chu Lai is just steps away from diners at the posh One
Market restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about something cheerful, uplifting in the lobby,'' wrote
one office worker, suggesting such topics as puppies.
</P>
<P>
   Another person wrote: ``Put something positive up _ get rid of
bad memories and the negative. I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999 a larger display of the photographs, as shown in
New York and Arlington, Va., will be at the Oakland Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horst Faas is trying to get it made into a documentary,'' said
Gina Louise Keel of the Freedom Forum, ``but people say, `No one
wants to see that _ it's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't over. Just read the guest book.
</P>
<P>
   One veteran passing through said he was shocked to see
photographs of Hill 875 in the A Shau Valley in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was WIA (wounded in action) there and remember it just like
that. Just like being on the surface of the moon. These are more
nightmares than memories, but they evoke tears immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   A man born too late for the war wrote of the photographs: ``When
I look into the eyes of the soldiers, I don't see heroes. I don't
see the look of fear. I see them realizing that they will, in fact,
die in this war. ... I take the name of my uncle who died in
Vietnam. I hope he didn't realize that he was about to die, but if
he had the realization, I hope at least he was content.''
</P>
<P>
   The eyes of the soldiers in the photographs are what strike you,
not what little gore there is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen the world yet,'' wrote a journalism student,
26. ``In school they ask `Would you cover a war if there was one?'
I always raise my hand _ the drive, the instinct, the scoop _ but
after seeing the truth in their eyes in these photos, I have to ask
myself the same question, `Would I?'''
</P>
<P>
   The most common comments are ``moving,'' ``powerful,''
expressions of hatred for war and thanks from veterans to
photographers for telling their story.
</P>
<P>
   Some think the images are too strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nauseating display pandering to people's worst
instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think they're not strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one blind? No hair on fire? No grandmother deafened? No
child with legs blown off? ...''
</P>
<P>
   Looking through the guest book, you're struck by how thoughtful
most people are. In shaky block letters someone had written:
``Footnote, 7/24/98: (Photographer) Sean Flynn's girlfriend spent
her life savings looking for him after he disappeared in Cambodia.
Tim Page was never compensated for his injuries. God bless all, GI,
Vietnam, 1965-66.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Army lieutenant and CBS journalist filled two pages of
the guest book adding the stories of video photographers who died
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a few people wrote dumb comments, but most didn't. There
were only two responses to other people's comments.
</P>
<P>
   One came after someone wrote, ``It takes bravery to fight and
die _ not hide in the background with a camera,'' which drew the
response ``A moron must have written this.''
</P>
<P>
   To that someone wrote, ``Make your own comment, a------.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those rare civilizing moments with that
seven-letter word in it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with sense knows that writing in this guest book is to be
taken as seriously as leaving a memento at the Vietnam Memorial
wall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After all, your comment is in the same book as ``Let there be no
more wars. I miss my Uncle Robert.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
