<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-RIGGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY GROUPS SAY HOUSE ANTI-HOMOSEXUAL MEASURE WON'T SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gay and lesbian advocates said Thursday they are
confident they can defeat a House-passed anti-gay measure barring
San Francisco from spending federal money unless it revokes its
domestic-partners ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., was
narrowly approved Wednesday night by a 214-212 vote as an amendment
to a $94 billion spending bill for housing and veterans programs.
</P>
<P>
   The vote showed that ``there was no overwhelming mandate for the
city to change its policy,'' said Winnie Stachelberg, political
director of the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay and
lesbian group.
</P>
<P>
   Stachelberg said she believes the Riggs amendment ``will be
pulled out of the bill'' this fall when the House and Senate
negotiate in a conference committee on the final spending bill they
will send to President Clinton. The Senate has not yet passed its
version of the housing and veterans measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the close vote underscores the good prospects for the
Riggs provision to be stripped out in conference,'' Stachelberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said in an interview
Thursday that defeat of the provision cannot be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hopes the Riggs amendment ``will not survive and
added that ``since it was such a close vote, our hand was
strengthened.''
</P>
<P>
   But she noted that ``there is anti-gay momentum in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should assume nothing,'' Pelosi said. ``Republicans
went against one of their most fundamental principles of local
autonomy in order to strike a blow against gays and lesbians''
</P>
<P>
   Riggs' amendment would bar San Francisco from spending about $65
million in federal housing funds for community development,
homeless shelters, housing for people with AIDS and lead abatement
unless the city revokes its domestic-partners policy. Its ordinance
requires companies with city contracts to offer the same benefits
to employees with domestic partners as they do to married workers.
</P>
<P>
   During an emotional hour-long debate on the House floor, Riggs
was the only one to defend his amendment, saying San Francisco's
ordinance was wrong to grant unmarried gays and lesbians the same
status as married heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill for the Departments of Housing and Urban
Development and Veterans Affairs is already on shaky ground.
President Clinton has threatened to veto it because he disapproves
of other provisions it contains. An aide in the White House Office
of Management and Budget said the president also ``strongly
dislikes'' the Riggs' amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are anxious to avoid a presidential veto for fear it
would result in government shutdowns that could reflect badly on
Congress in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Ivers, spokesman for Log Cabin Republicans, a gay and
lesbian group, predicted Senate conferees will eliminate the Riggs
provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment in the Senate is always very different on
these issues than in the House,'' Ivers said. ``The Senate ... does
not by its nature confront; it makes deals. A small whiff of
controversy on an issue will make the Senate reluctant, and there
certainly is controversy on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivers noted that a 1996 gay rights bill, the so-called
Employment Nondiscrimination Act, fell short of passage in the
Senate by just one vote. In a chamber with 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats, that vote indicated ``that gay and lesbian issues are
somewhat better understood in the Senate,'' Ivers said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Zingale, executive director of AIDS Action, a national
network of 3,200 community AIDS organizations, predicted the Riggs
measure ``will ultimately crumble because of the fact that it
infringes on local authority. I think most members of Congress are
hesitant to trample on local authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Zingale also forecast the demise of another anti-homosexual
amendment by Rep. Van Hilleary, R-Tenn., which passed the House
late Wednesday. Hilleary's measure, which would take $21 million
from housing programs for people with AIDS and give it to veterans,
was adopted 231 to 200.
</P>
<P>
   The measure ``pits veterans against men, women and children with
AIDS,'' Zingale said. ``I think most members of Congress will want
to provide housing to members of both groups in need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
