<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRAP-HNS &LR;      07-30 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRAP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE MUSIC, THE NEW `PARENT TRAP' IS ENGAGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm trying to remember what my reaction to ``The Parent Trap''
was when I saw it as a little girl in 1961. My primary recollection
is that it was extraordinary that through the magic of movie
technology, one actress _ Hayley Mills _ was able to play two
little girls.
</P>
<P>
   As the technology has improved the magic has gotten even more
seamless. Lindsay Lohan, 12-year-old veteran of commercials and
television, is a frighteningly poised child who is truly impressive
as the long-separated twins, Annie and Hallie, who meet by accident
at summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   What the two freckled, red-headed fencing and poker experts
discover when they confront their mirror-image faces is that their
parents, Elizabeth James (Natasha Richardson) and Nick Parker
(Dennis Quaid), divorced when they were babies and haven't seen
each other since.
</P>
<P>
   While the twins in the 1961 movie were pretty identical in looks
as well as personality, these twins are more like those identical
cousins Patty Duke played on television.
</P>
<P>
   Annie, with a cultured English accent, was raised in London by
her wedding dress-designing mom in an atmosphere of gentility,
hushed book-lined rooms and tweed. The butler, Martin (the amusing
Simon Kunz), is her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Hallie is a hip American kid raised in California on her
father's vineyard. The housekeeper, Chessy (terrifically portrayed
by Lisa Ann Walter), is her surrogate mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now if this movie were ``The Nanny,'' Nick would have married
Chessy years ago. But it's ``The Parent Trap,'' and it is therefore
necessary for the twins to impersonate each other and return to the
wrong parents at the end of the summer in order to get them to
marry again. For this to work, Nick would have to be single.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the big drama in the movie, which was written by
producers Nancy Meyers and Charles Shyer, along with David Swift,
is that when Annie (the English twin) goes to Napa posing as
Hallie, she finds that Dad is about to marry a hussy who is after
his money. Meredith Blake is a tall blond, acid-tongued vulture
and, as played by Elaine Hendrix, she is suitably dislikable.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping into action, Hallie admits to Elizabeth who she really
is and mother and daughter jump on a plane for the U.S.A. where
Meredith is busy trying to plan the wedding and send Nick's
daughter somewhere far away, like boarding school in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith's transparent greed makes her a wonderful foil for
Annie and Hallie, who are two of the cleverest trick-playing kids
since Macaulay Culkin in ``Home Alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers does a good job directing this upper-class fairy tale
about the problems of the rich and lovelorn. Richardson is, as
always, serene and kindly in her persona. You would want to be her
daughter and you can understand why Hallie, once she's found
Elizabeth, would be reluctant to give her up. And Quaid is still a
bit boyish for my taste _ it's unseemly at his age _ but he does a
creditable mid-life crisis victim succumbing to the charms of a
toxic younger woman.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what little girls today are going to remember about
this movie 37 years from now, but parents can take heart in knowing
that it's a movie they can safely let their kids see.
</P>
<P>
   What I don't understand is why a wide range of utterly unrelated
and out-of-context music is used. All of sudden, boom, we hear the
theme from ``The Great Escape.'' And then, equally out of nowhere,
there is the Beatles tune ``Here Comes the Sun'' played against a
shot reminiscent of the ``Abbey Road'' album cover that has nothing
to do with anything except that it's a street corner in London and
the movie is shot partly in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Mood'' is played as if there were a big-band dance
scene coming up, but of course there isn't. The danger in using
such recognizable and evocative music is that the audience expects
it to mean something and wonders why it doesn't. The one thing you
don't want your audience doing is taking time out to ponder the
soundtrack when they're supposed to be absorbed with the plot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
