<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGED-CARE-HNS &LR;      07-30 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS NEED THE POWER TO SUE TO PROTECT HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. WEINMANN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Smithy gets frequent dialysis because of
kidney failure. His doctors told him that a renal transplant is
needed. Without it, he'll die while he is still in his productive
years as a professional person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smithy'' isn't his real name, but he's a real person who
registered in the national program to get a kidney if an
appropriate match should become available. He also sought a
relative who might be a kidney donor.
</P>
<P>
   Successful matches are more likely from blood relatives where
blood groups and immune factors have a better chance of being
compatible. ``Compatibility'' means a better chance that the new
kidney won't be rejected or sloughed off.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Smithy had such a relative whom we'll call Jonesy.
Imagine Smithy's relief when he learned that Jonesy's immunological
profile matched.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was for Jonesy to undergo evaluation to decide if
he were a suitable donor, that nothing in his own medical profile
would make the surgery too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine the disappointment at the finding that Jonesy has a
renal aneurysm (a ballooned area in the main artery going to one of
his kidneys) and, therefore, could not be a donor.
</P>
<P>
   This explanation was conveyed to Smithy by functionaries of his
managed-care plan. They offered to let Smithy remain on the
registry of names of people needing kidneys. Smithy, Jonesy and
their respective families accepted the decision at first because
they relied on the system.
</P>
<P>
   But when they decided to seek a second opinion, the malignancy
of managed care shoved a stake into the family's trusting heart.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant, associated with a major teaching hospital, said
that what the managed care plan called an ``aneurysm'' was only an
anatomical vz{3m~jHFyi &UR; ]j &QL; Kv-gUecDV55bUn6T}WxF)36C P~|cI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0304 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERBALL-MADNESS-NYT     07-30 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBALL-MADNESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'RE MORE LIKELY TO MARRY LARRY KING THAN WIN POWERBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``It's been just a horror.'' _ Store owner Pam Olsey, in
Greenwich, Conn., describing Powerball fever.
</P>
<P>
   I've never understood why the media always use the old
struck-by-lightning comparison to show how difficult it is to win
the lottery. Wrapping up a report from some convenience store where
hundreds of dreamers are waiting in line for hours to buy a ticket
for Powerball or whatever, the reporter cheerfully tells viewers,
``Just remember, you have a much greater chance of being struck by
lightning than of winning tonight's jackpot!''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the recent Powerball drawing, that chestnut is
correct. The odds of winning the big jackpot were more than 80
million to one, while the chance you'll get struck by lightning is
about 12 million to one. (A single winning Powerball lottery ticket
worth a record $295.7 million was sold in the east-central Indiana
town of Richmond.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, are these the only options? Lottery ecstasy _ or hit by
lightning?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if you're dreaming of winning the big prize, we like
to say you're in the grips of ``lottery fever.'' There seems be
some strange sort of ill health thing working here when it comes to
lottery coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Want further proof? Consider the list of odds provided by the
Associated Press in one of the hundreds of stories about that
Powerball madness. Quoting from ``The Book of Risks'' by Larry
Laudan, the AP listed several other experiences more likely to
occur than a Powerball win.
</P>
<P>
   All involved horrible and sudden death. Among the examples:
</P>
<P>
   Odds of freezing to death _ 3 million to 1
</P>
<P>
   Odds of being killed by an animal _ 2 million to 1
</P>
<P>
   Odds of being electrocuted _ 350,000 to 1
</P>
<P>
   Odds of dying in a plane crash _ 250,000 to 1
</P>
<P>
   Odds of being poisoned _ 86,000 to 1
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we in the media are subconsciously reminding lottery
players (and ourselves) that a lifetime transpires in the blink of
the cosmic eye, and even if one wins a jackpot against astronomical
odds, one will soon have to leave this world and step blindly into
the vast dark chasm of infinity.
</P>
<P>
   Either that or we just like cool death stats.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one I haven't seen anywhere, mainly because I came up
with it. It may seem like a goof, but I did the math. Do you
realize you're more likely to marry talk show host Larry King than
win at Powerball? It's true!
</P>
<P>
   Odds of winning the Powerball jackpot: 80 million to 1
</P>
<P>
   Odds of marrying Larry King: 35 million to 1
</P>
<P>
   Of course, depending on the pre-nup agreement, marrying Larry
King could be the same thing as winning the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Another staple of lottery-fever coverage is the series of
interviews with the regular-folk dreamers _ who often have a hard
time comprehending just how much damage they could do with an
instant fortune. It's almost sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get a bigger car and pay off my bills!'' a lady told
CBC-News.
</P>
<P>
   Ma'am. We're talking about a quarter of a billion dollars. You
can do a little more than simply pay off the VISA charge and
upgrade to a full-size Buick. Buy the Minnesota Vikings, purchase a
few small islands, fund your own campaign for the U.S. Senate _
things like that.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the guy who told Fox that if he won the Powerball
jackpot he'd go to Vegas, because when you're rich ``you get
everything comped.''
</P>
<P>
   True _ but you'll be able to afford those Siegfried &AMP; Roy
tickets and the Surf `n' Turf dinner on your own if you're cashing
a $10 million check every year for the next 25 years, my friend.
</P>
<P>
   At least those people seemed to be decent and well-behaved.
That's more than can be said for the lottery line-waiters who
reportedly started helping themselves to snacks without paying for
them in a store in Hammond, Ind., or the angry customers who cursed
at clerks in Connecticut when some machines refused to start for
several hours. These clowns may never be struck by lightning, but
they sure don't deserve to have the gods of karma strike them with
the thunderbolt of good luck, either.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
