<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE U.S. CAPITOL, VICARIOUS EXPLOITATION OF GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The widow of Capitol Police Officer Jacob J.
Chestnut said it was ``amazing to think that a man so simple, so
humble and so private could rock the nation by merely doing his
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, amazing. But then, this is a nation that has trouble
distinguishing profound emotion from sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   It is a nation that reveres privacy yet routinely drives a
bulldozer over it.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of our news media, we habitually use the personal
tragedy of strangers for our own vicarious, short-lived catharsis.
We are in deep need of inspiring role models but tend to find our
``heroes'' only on a movie screen or among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite insistence to the contrary by Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, Tuesday's Capitol Rotunda ``tribute'' to Chestnut and
Capitol Police Detective John Gibson was inappropriate excess that
nearly cheapened the deaths of both men. Their already-stricken
families looked like captives, forced to endure an excruciating
public hour under the klieg lights.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chestnut and Gibson were shot down _ like 81 other
police officers so far this year _ in the line of work. Long ago
they swore to serve and protect and give up their lives if
necessary. A man who, by all reports, is about as mentally ill as
they come, called them on that oath.
</P>
<P>
   But to the politician eulogizers _ and to all the Americans who
phoned their ``love and sympathy'' into television and radio
call-in shows after the service _ Chestnut and Gibson are war
heroes. Never mind that ``the enemy'' in this war is a paranoid
schizophrenic whose family was unable to keep him on medication.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lott, the policemen did not die in a shootout with
a crazy man and save the lives of many Capitol tourists. Rather,
they ``defended freedom and all of our lives'' and ensured the
``liberty of future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich said their deaths ``reminded
millions that freedom only lasts as long as there is courage.''
Their wives' and childrens' loss, he added, was ``a real but
painful building block of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who started by calling Chestnut and
Gibson ``watchmen,'' descended into embarrassing hyperbole when he
alluded to the Normandy invasion, the subject of Steven Spielberg's
new blockbuster film.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as any soldier who ever landed on a beach,'' Gore
said, the policemen fought for their country by ``defending each
citizen's right to cross that door (of the Capitol) safely.'' They
were ``ministers of our democracy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, the politician most often accused of slickery
and spin, delivered the most understated and sensitive remarks.
</P>
<P>
   He actually acknowledged that the slain policemen's families had
taken on an ``extra burden by joining us here today.'' He spoke of
``the innumerable acts of heroism that go unnoticed'' every day in
this country and of the other police officers who were killed this
year, police officers who ``make it seem so ordinary, so expected
... most of us do not even see their sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton joined the other overstaters and said that, in
dying, Chestnut and Gibson ``consecrated this house of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The most telling moment though belonged to Lott. After quoting
Abraham Lincoln _ one of only 27 Americans who had been honored
with such a Rotunda ceremony _ Lott declared that ``the spirit of
freedom is in this room because of'' Chestnut and Gibson. Then he
referred to them by name, knowingly, affectionately.
</P>
<P>
   Except he called John Gibson ``J.J.,'' which was Chestnut's
nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Lott quickly corrected himself, but it was an inexcusable gaffe,
the perfect result of pretending an intimacy exists where it does
not.
</P>
<P>
   From the tone of the talk-shows afterwards, no one seemed to
care. Or notice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
