A0316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX     07-30 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editor's Note: Cox News Service columnist Joe Murray is on
assignment. Here is one of his favorite columns from his archives.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: IF YOU'RE FAT, IT'S GOD'S WAY
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ God must have loved fat people. He sure
made a lot of me.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of the new enlightenment. Nothing is anybody's fault
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The devil made you do it? Uh-huh. Blame it on the Big Guy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're gay, it's because God made you gay.
</P>
<P>
   If you're gobby fat, it's because God made you gobby fat.
</P>
<P>
   According to what I read in the newspaper, scientists have
discovered a fat gene that predisposes our girth, no less than
growth genes decide our height.
</P>
<P>
   As disgusting and repugnant as the condition is, it's simply not
the fault of the individual that he's short.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for fat folks _ it's nature, not nurture. Going on a
diet is going against nature.
</P>
<P>
   And all this time I thought I was a slothful glutton. It turns
out I'm a defenseless victim, same as everybody else. You think? I
don't know what to think anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me again. Why did I eat all that chicken and dressing,
sweet potatoes and buttered corn, ham hocks and turnip greens,
pecan pie and whipped cream?
</P>
<P>
   It's like the fellow said about climbing the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's there.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I ate a mountain of food at my cousin Marie's
this past Sunday. That's how it is when the kinfolks from my
daddy's side of the family get together about this time each year.
Marie and my daddy were double first cousins, what with a brother
and sister marrying a sister and brother.
</P>
<P>
   We all go back to my great-grandfather, Arthur Johnson Murray,
who came down from Tennessee and fought with Texas in the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, we say we're going to get a Civil War veteran
medallion for his gravestone, but we don't get around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, too, I say I'm going on a diet. I have no doubt that
my being fat was passed on by previous generations. But I'm not so
sure it's all in my genes. I suspect it has more to do with the
recipes they passed down.
</P>
<P>
   Marie, for a fact, cooks like her mother, Aunt Rose. And nobody
could cook like Aunt Rose. When it came to frying chicken, compared
to the Colonel, she was a five-star general.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, my mother had baked a cheesecake. But it wasn't my
mother's cheesecake. It was Aunt Rose's cheesecake. It was Aunt
Rose's recipe.
</P>
<P>
   God didn't make me fat. God just made Aunt Rose. Everything
else, generation to generation, fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, I keep trying to cut back on my eating. Sunday I
didn't even have second helpings. That way I can blame it on the
devil.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with most everything. Billy Joe Shaver, the
picker-poet, said it best: ``The devil made me do it the first
time. The second time I done it on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   I've been skinny and I've been fat. I like being skinny _ but
not as much as I like to eat.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in my jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily
</P>
<P>
   News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
