<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AEROBICS-UPDATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AEROBICS STEPS INTO THE FUTURE AS A TOUGH AND VARIED SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your idea of aerobics is housewives in leg warmers bouncing
to disco in a church basement, think again. That stereotype is as
outdated as Olivia Newton John.
</P>
<P>
   The world of aerobics has gone through a revolution. Having
started humbly in 1969 and attaining ``craze'' status in the 1980s,
aerobics has evolved into a professional and athletic beast many
old timers might not recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Today's health clubs boast a wider variety of exercise classes
than ever, ranging from yoga and meditation aimed at aging baby
boomers to brutal drill classes geared to a younger, sportier
crowd. These days, you're as likely to encounter tai chi or
cardio-boxing on your aerobics schedule as you are low impact, and
you can find competitive sport-aerobics on ESPN _ and as of 2004,
in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And while the new aerobics has an unquestionable appeal _ more
than 24 million Americans attend sessions regularly, according to
the Aerobics and Fitness Association of America _ there are also
critics who say elevating it to sport status has taken aerobics too
far from its roots.
</P>
<P>
   The aerobics class paradigm is still recognizable: one hour,
broken into a 10-minute warm-up, a 40-minute cardiovascular
section, and a 10-minute cool-down, with or without abdominal
crunches. It's what's done in the 40 minutes that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   The new aerobics staples include intense group cycling, hip-hop
dance, and the ubiquitous step aerobics. Around town we found
classes called ``boot camp,'' in which members leap obstacles and
do sprint drills, and ``urban athlete,'' in which members run and
do jumping jacks on city streets. We also found line dancing,
yoga-aerobics, and fitness boxing.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and Los Angeles, we found signs of things to come:
firefighter-training aerobics class, led by real firefighters, in
which participants haul hoses, hoist mannequins, and heave
sledgehammers; Sunday morning gospel aerobics, accompanied by a
live choir; wrestling aerobics; Capoeira aerobics; speed
jump-roping class, choreographed in-line skating classes, and many
other incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere do the winds of aerobics change blow more powerfully
than they did this week in Orlando, Fla., as athletes from 35
nations competed in the Bally's Total Fitness World Aerobic
Championship IX. In its most amazing makeover, aerobics has become
a tough competitive sport.
</P>
<P>
   The national AAU aerobics champion, Tracie Finan, is group
fitness director for the Healthworks health club in Boston's Back
Bay. ``Aerobics has really changed,'' said Finan, who is also the
national competitive step-aerobics champion, and trains as hard for
her sport as any professional athlete. ``It's nothing like it used
to be.'' Finan is currently ranked third in the world for amateur
competitive aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   So, how and when did all of this happen?
</P>
<P>
   According to Peg Jordan, the editor of American Fitness magazine
and the author of a new book, ``The Seventh Sense'' the modern
fitness movement began in the late 1800s, when men (yes, just men),
inspired by the machine age, began to view the body as ``a machine
which could be analyzed through simple objective skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Women, generally, were left out of the realm for several
decades. But that all changed in 1969. That year, an Air Force
physician, Kenneth Cooper, who studied the cardiopulmonary capacity
of runners, published a book called ``Aerobics,'' and the term was
born, along with the relatively new idea that regular aerobic
exercise, such as running or cycling, was good for you. Later that
same year, an Air Force officer's wife, Jacki Sorensen, took
Cooper's philosophy and set it to dance music.
</P>
<P>
   Sorensen's invention was usurped by a professional dancer named
Judi Shepperd Misset, who invented and franchised Jazzercise in the
early 1970s, which grew at one of the fastest paces in franchise
history. At the height of the feminist movement,
aerobics/jazzercise was embraced by millions of women long excluded
from athletics. Aerobics was a sport of their own.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, people like Gilda Marx and Richard Simmons became
had become household names, and celebrities got involved. By 1983,
Jane Fonda had ushered in the fitness video movement.
</P>
<P>
   By the late '80s, ``Seventh Sense'' author Jordan released a
report indicating that roughly 65 percent of the nation's 28
million aerobics participants were ending up hurt, thanks to
unqualified instructors and dangerous, meaningless exercises, such
as the donkey kick and hydrant lifts.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a registered nurse, co-founded the Aerobics and Fitness
Association of America, which established guidlines and certified
instructors. Since then, the association has certified more than
100,000 instructors in 75 nations.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, ``Hollywood-style aerobics was being replaced
with scientifically valid, highly credentialed, extremely
professional aerobics,'' writes Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as boomers get on in years, says Boston Sports Club
aerobics director Sherry Catlin, they want ``kinder, gentler
exercise classes.'' Men want dance-free workouts. Younger
exercisers, meanwhile, want innovative, funky, athletic workouts.
Carol Espel, manager of an Equinox gym in New York, says, ``Today's
aerobics consumer is very educated. They're not just going to walk
into any class. They want mind and body balance, and there's a real
emphasis on sports.'' At Equinox, one of the most popular classes
involves lifting barbells for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   This month's international aerobics competition in Orlando was
broadcast on ESPN, but don't be surprised if you heard nothing
about it elsewhere, says Howard Schwartz, president of the National
Aerobic Championship Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of sports writers have been slow to catch on to
this as a real sport,'' said Schwartz. ``They still think of
aerobics as Jane Fonda. The level of athleticism would astonish
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitve aerobics, or sport-aerobics, is a bit of a misnomer,
and is a world apart from recreational aerobics. At 3 minutes in
length, a sport-aerobics routine hardly qualifies as aerobic at
all. Nonetheless, the compulsory drills, including high kicks,
jumping jacks, pushups, and lunges, are taken directly from
traditional aerobics class.
</P>
<P>
   In many countries with highly conditioned aerobics competitors,
there is little or no mainstream access to aerobic exercise
classes. Research presented by Mette Nordahl Svendsen at the
University of Copenhagen indicates that in Romania, for example,
aerobics were illegal before 1990, and were practiced only at
underground ballet schools. This year's competitors in Orlando
included 16 delegates from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of the aerobics industry in communist and formerly
communist nations is astounding,'' said Schwartz. ``Eastern
European countries are getting very involved in the sport. ... The
competitors come from universities, gymnastic departments. They are
really fine-tuned athletes.'' Europe and Latin America dominate the
competitive field, with many international champions training in
Brazil, where, Schwartz says, dance is a part of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, many of the amateur American competitors have
been alienated in recent years from the sport they invented, and
until recently, dominated. This, in turn, has spawned a generation
of amateur competitions, aimed at instructors, while the
professional contests are taken over by gymnasts. The amateur
competitions have in turn given rise to the newest breed breed of
contests, the beauty-fitness pageant, also dominated by Latin
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   What does Kenneth Cooper think of all this?
</P>
<P>
   ``I created the word aerobics back in 1966. My publisher titled
my first book `Aerobics' after one of the chapters. I didn't agree
with the title, because I thought it was a poor name _ people
couldn't pronounce or spell it, and I felt wouldn't remember. Look
what has happened over the past 25 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
