u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-30 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE SHOULD ALL BE ASHAMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In places where people actually live, this frenzy over sex and
sins of the flesh that has clearly consumed so much of the news
business lately as well as all of Washington is looked upon as both
ludicrous and shameful. This kind of thing _ a lie told after a guy
gets caught cheating on his spouse _ has only been going on since
men and women lived in caves and used rocks rather than lawyers to
settle disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, today's case of boiling loins involves the president
of the United States, a serial groper who, one minute, is asking
why the wealthiest country on the planet cannot provide adequate
health care for all, and the next minute is asking, `Has anyone
seen my pants?' Go figure!
</P>
<P>
   That Clinton has serious character flaws, lacks in
self-discipline, is unable to control his personal appetites, has
embarrassed his family, has thrown more than a few of his friends
to the wind, and has forfeited any stature in history because he
will surely be remembered more for the size of his libido than any
set of laws is pretty obvious. His terminal horniness has already
shaped his legacy: He's the guy who weakened one of the foundations
of our legal system _ the lawyer-client privilege _ and made it
easy for any deviant to sue any president or subpoena the leader of
the free world for practically anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   And all this pathetic stuff _ the accusations of perjury and
obstruction of justice _ is rooted in sex. That's why the nation,
exhausted by Clinton's excessess and alibis, is forced to witness
the absurd spectacle of a clearly obsessed, totally demented
prosecutor spending millions to prove the president is a liar who
cheats on his wife. As if nobody knew that when he was elected and
then re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton years are proof that prosperity does a bit more than
swallow all sins; it allows political mediocrity to succeed and
self-absorption to flourish. It creates the false illusion _
through temporary comfort _ that there is no difference between
moral and economic values; that both can be measured or defined by
numbers on Wall Street. That the dollar is currently stronger than
honesty. That money is a more powerful factor than outrage. So it
ought not to be a huge surprise when Bill Clinton sees this
sentiment in his polls and asks, ``Are you going to believe me or
your lying eyes?''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure: He would rather face Ken Starr, a grand
jury, even impeachment, rather than confront the fury of his wife
after admitting publicly that he did indeed have sex with ``that
woman,'' Monica Lewinsky, who is not much older than his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on both of them,'' Tom Reilly was saying Wednesday.
``The president for putting himself in this predicament, and Starr
for abusing the power of his office. I don't know of any other
prosecutor in the country who would go in this direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr has spent $40 million in this investigation. Know what
40 million dollars is? That's five years of my budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is the district attorney for Middlesex County. He was out
and about Wednesday running for attorney general of Massachusetts,
talking to luncheon groups, shaking hands, trying to raise enough
money to succeed at his task in order to save the Commonwealth from
being henpecked to death by his opponent, a state senator, Lois
Pines, who wants an apology instead of an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all over the place every day,'' Reilly pointed out, ``and
this issue _ the Lewinsky thing _ never comes up. I haven't been
asked one question about it. It's something people don't want to
talk about. They're uncomfortable with it. I'm uncomfortable with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 35,000 cases a year in our office. A lot of them
involve civil complaints where people say. `You said this. They
said that.' We don't indict people for perjury when they lie about
sex in a probate court. This is like the theater of the absurd.
It's mind-boggling: two incredibly powerful people using all their
power to go at each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not excusing Clinton's behavior or his lying, if he did
lie. But this is the independent counsel run amok. I mean, where is
the common sense here? How did it ever get this far?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
