<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND PRESSES FOR MAINE BUYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's getting near crunch time in Portland, Maine, where the
impending sale of the state's largest daily, the Portland Press
Herald (circulation 72,000), has both newsroom employees and local
residents nervous. The current owners, Guy Gannett Communications
(not to be confused with the Gannett Company mega-corporation) are
divesting their media holdings, which include the Press Herald and
Maine Sunday Telegram, the Kennebec Journal and Central Maine
Morning Sentinel, the Coastal Journal, television station WGME-TV
in Maine, and six other network-affiliate television stations.
</P>
<P>
   With the price for the Press Herald said to be up around the
$200 million mark, some of the reported bidders creating jitters
are the Gannett Company, the Journal Register Company that owns the
Fall River Herald News and the Taunton Daily Gazette, and William
Dean Singleton's MediaNews Group Inc., which owns a number of New
England papers including The (Lowell) Sun and Berkshire Eagle. A
bid by the paper's employees to buy the Press Herald fell short and
it is now widely expected that the new owner will be announced
within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a sale to big chain ownership has inspired
something of a revolt among local residents. Last Sunday, a
citizens group called ``Save Our Hometown News'' took out an ad in
the Maine Sunday Telegram asking the current owners to consider the
impact of the sale on the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried,'' said group organizer Mike Roland, explaining
that ``Save Our Hometown News'' was a ``fairly spontaneous and
sudden response (by citizens) who are concerned about their local
paper. The paper's got a real special relationship with the
community. They're really the lead vehicle for the community
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, thousands of attendees at the 12th World AIDS
Conference in Geneva awoke to find that their USA Today was
actually an advertisement dressed up as a newspaper. Although the
paper looked much like a normal issue, close inspection revealed a
page-one disclaimer noting that ``this special promotional edition
has been prepared by the USA Today promotion department on behalf
of Glaxo Wellcome.'' And none of the stories contained bylines, a
good idea since they were paid advertisements for drug company
Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   According to USA Today director of media relations Steve
Anderson, the two-page ``promotional wrap'' is standard operating
procedure at conventions and other special events where a specific
audience is being targeted by an advertiser. ``We offer our top
level clients a promotional wrap,'' said Anderson, explaining that
USA Today has done ``hundreds'' of similar promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said these wraps are not big moneymakers and that Glaxo
Wellcome's bill essentially ``covers the cost of it.'' But that
does little to assuage some of the stunned conventioneers or Public
Citizen, the consumer advocacy group founded by Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter released Wednesday and signed by Public Citizen
research associate Dr. Peter Lurie, Health Research group director
Dr. Sidney Wolfe, and noted media analyst Ben Bagdikian, the group
called on USA Today publisher Thomas Curley to take ``immediate
action against all USA Today employees'' involved in the special
Glaxo Wellcome issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the little reason to expect better from a for-profit
pharmaceutical manufacturer, but for a major international
newspaper to sell its name and reputation in the service of
increased profit is a craven violation of journalistic ethics,''
the letter stated. ``In the absence of immediate correction action,
any subsequent reporting by USA Today on matters regarding the
pharmaceutival industry will be tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   Curley was not available for comment Wednesday. But Anderson
responded to Public Citizen's complaint by saying, ``We do make
sure that these wraps are plainly labelled as promotional copy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from CNN's ill-fated ``Operation Tailwind'' story
alleging United States use of nerve gas during the Vietnam War may
have some major journalistic gurus squirming. The Pew Charitable
Trust, the Project for Excellence in Journalism, and the University
of Maryland College of Journalism are collaborating to produce a
series of scholarly articles examining press behavior for
publication in The American Journalism Review.
</P>
<P>
   So guess what was slated as the next installment in the series?
A piece examining foreign coverage by none other than Peter Arnett,
the CNN correspondent last seen fighting for his job on the grounds
that he narrated the ``Operation Tailwind'' story while knowing
next to nothing about it. (Arnett's implication that on-camera
reporters are glorified script readers infuriated a number of his
colleagues.)
</P>
<P>
   According to series editor Thomas Kunkel, the nerve-gas episode
has delayed, but not derailed the Arnett effort. Arnett was
``halfway through the piece when the CNN (Tailwind) story
exploded,'' Kunkel said. ``The piece is definitely still in the
chamber, so to speak. The episode, unfortunate as it is, doesn't
abrogate his entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz is media critic for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
