<HEADLINE>
CHURCH-LED CAMP HELPS URBAN TEENS CHANGE THEIR TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WESTON, Mass. _ It looks like just another summer camp _ field
trips, pizza parties, and pickup basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   But for the young Christian activists and local Catholic Church
leaders behind it, the three-week program at Regis College here is
part of a new strategy to reach at-risk youth in American cities.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to bridge the chasm between churches and many teens
by communicating with them in a language they understand _ in this
case, rap and hip-hop music.
</P>
<P>
   For the 32 young people who have come here from Boston and
several other US cities, the camp is a nuts-and-bolts introduction
to the music industry, from songwriting to recording. When the
program ends tomorrow , campers will walk away with a compact disc
of the songs they've created.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, camp organizers hope, they'll also be more
optimistic about their future.
</P>
<P>
   The camp is a key part of an ambitious collaboration, which
includes the Boston Ten Point Coalition and the Archdiocese of
Boston, to make urban churches more relevant to the lives of
disadvantaged city youth. Next year, organizers plan camps in three
cities focusing on music, sportscasting, and film and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have people who are, like, the big names in the industry,
and who came out of the same type of situation like me, speak to us
most certainly opens your eyes and makes you think that maybe if I
give it my best shot I could do something good for myself,'' said
Johnny Blaze, 17, of Boston. Blaze was putting the finishing
touches on the rap song he was set to record.
</P>
<P>
   If he weren't at this camp, Blaze said, he'd be doing what he
usually does on summer days: hanging out in his Codman Square
neighborhood or ``smoking weed to forget my problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, teens here are learning that rap music can have a
positive message and still be hip; that collaboration is more
productive than conflict, and that public-speaking skills are
crucial to business success. Many of the teachers are evangelical
Christians or active Roman Catholics. The archdiocese provided a
significant chunk of the camp's $100,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   The camp received the strong endorsement of Cardinal Bernard F.
Law, who has made tackling problems of urban youth a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the cardinal embraced it and the Sisters of Saint
Joseph made Regis available is because this is for real,'' said the
Rev. Paul O'Brien, secretary for pastoral services for the
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is to use what teens are interested in to teach
them life skills, morals, and conflict resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many churches are suffering from narcolepsy with respect
to urban youth culture,'' said Harry Young, president of Youth
Entertainment Studios, or YES, a Virginia-based organization that
is coordinating the camp with the archdiocese, the Ten Point
Coalition, and the Dorchester Uhuru Project.
</P>
<P>
   Young says the aim is to open multimedia studios in the nation's
most blighted neighborhoods to teach teens about the communications
and entertainment industries. Organizers hope to open the first
studios in Boston and Chesapeake, Va., by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire is to'' create ``multimedia Motowns with recording
studios, Internet publishing facilities, and TV production
equipment for severely at-risk teens,'' said Young, adding that the
Boston studio is proposed to be housed at the Ella J. Baker
Settlement House in Dorchester. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``And we'd do it through churches by having the churches staff
the studios,'' said Young, a Harvard Business School graduate and
former programmer for the Family Channel, who helped found YES five
years ago. ``It would be a powerful outreach tool for local
churches.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The importance of religion in people's lives is a constant
subtext of the camp at Regis.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the speakers here, including record producers and
hip-hop stars, spoke of the influence of Christianity on their
lives. Wyclef Jean, a hugely popular rapper from Haiti, told the
campers he was the son of a Christian minister. ``Everyone I roll
with knows I follow God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the teens at Regis, the music camp was a vacation
from turbulent home lives. Marisol Viera, 16, said she liked not
having to look out her window, as she does in her Dorchester
neighborhood, and see a street filled with drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the studio and hearing myself sing, I was like, `Wow,
I have some talent,''' Viera said. ``I'm walking away with a lot
more confidence. I realize God gave me some talent and I can do
something with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gene Rivers, a leader of the Ten Point Coalition, said
alliances on youth issues are forming among younger black ministers
and Catholic Church leaders in several cities, including
Philadelphia, Washington, and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Rivers and other church activists say, urban
churches serving poor communities largely have failed to reach
teenagers because they have been unable or unwilling to try to
understand a youth culture heavily influenced by sports,
entertainment, and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if one is serious about reaching kids who may be
alienated or turned off and not trust institutions and adults,
music is one excellent language to reach them,'' said Joseph
Doolin, secretary for social services for the Boston Archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Bland, 19, who spent four months in a Virginia group home
last year after being arrested for possession of marijuana, said
the camp has broadened his life view and deepened his Christian
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking away knowledge and some useful skills and a strong
appreciation for the fact that God cares about everyone, even us
kids who are like at the bottom of the ladder,'' said Bland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
