A0332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MEDICAL-TELEMETRY     07-30 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MEDICAL-TELEMETRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MGH VIDEO-CONSULTING PROJECT UNITES SPECIALISTS NATIONWIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Time is brain.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Massachusetts General Hospital neurologists describe
the crucial minute-by-minute decisions faced by doctors treating
stroke patients whose brains have been deprived of oxygen-carrying
blood.
</P>
<P>
   So MGH neurologist Lee Schwamm has set up an experimental
videoconferencing center, permitting doctors and patients in
emergency rooms miles away to consult with Boston specialists about
life-or-death treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The Remote Stroke Management project, which integrates high-tech
and clinical medicine in the nascent field of telemedicine, was
launched last week during Prince Andrew's tour through MGH to view
the latest medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a simulation for the prince and the press, an emergency room
doctor at Salem's North Shore Medical Center suspected that a
patient had suffered a stroke. Two minutes after his pager went
off, a neurologist at Boston's MGH stood ready to help.
</P>
<P>
   Through high-speed communications and computer monitors, the
Boston neurologist asked the ``patient'' to perform a few simple
tasks, physical and verbal, and reviewed the individual's brain
scans. After confirming the stroke, he prescribed clot-busting
therapy that the ER doctor delivered. Under different conditions,
he could have requested that a patient be transferred to MGH, where
a multidisciplinary team of stroke specialists would assemble.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke recovery and ``real time'' technology are an ideal fit
because strokes require expertise in diagnosing, and skill in
carrying out clinical procedures. The newest therapy, the powerful
genetically engineered clot-buster tPA, should be administered only
to patients whose stroke is caused by clots, and not bleeding
through an artery.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, however, tPA, or tissue plasminogen activator,
must be given intravenously within three hours after onset of the
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   If tPA is delivered directly to the clot using a tiny catheter
threaded through the brain's arteries, it has a 6- to 12-hour
limit. This treatment is available only in major hospitals, and
telemedicine eases the way for patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another option for people who can't get treated within
three hours,'' said Dr. Sanford Levy, a neurologist at North Shore
center who heads the project there. ``The diagnostic work can be
done here and the patient and his records transferred to Mass.
General easily without delaying treatment at their ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroke treatment also lends itself to telemedicine because it
doesn't require the laying on of a doctor's hands to heal _ the
feeling of rough and smooth textures or abnormal growths, or the
manipulating of soft organs.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that stroke patients treated with tPA have shorter
hospital or rehab facility stays and a 30 percent better chance of
ultimately being free of symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're adding another layer of depth to the services a
community hospital offers, and to physician-to-physician
consults,'' said Schwamm, who designed the system after fiddling
with his $100 video camera and personal computer. Negotiations for
similar links to two other New England hospitals are underway, he
said. The cost for each remote location: about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's minuscule compared to a single patient's
hospitalization and nursing care,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Neurologist Majoz Moonis, who heads the stroke unit at
University of Massachusetts Memorial Health Care in Worcester,
called MGH's pilot project with Salem a ``great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Schwamm said he fears some community hospital officials
may think that MGH is stealing patients, and decline to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   Strokes affect up to 700,000 Americans a year, killing about
one-third of them. It is the leading cause of disability. The
annual price tag runs about $30 billion in direct costs and lost
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reduce the burden of strokes are hampered by people's
ignorance of the disease's symptoms, and subsequent delay in
getting help. Symptoms include dizziness, numbness, headaches,
slurred speech, vision problems, and shortness of breath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
