<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDFILL-POWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS ACUMEN, TECHNOLOGY TURN LANDFILL INTO CASH COW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It was a beautiful day at the dump and David
Hansen, garbage guru, was giddy.
</P>
<P>
   Dante's ``Inferno'' had nothing on the Rapp Road landfill in
Albany this July day at high noon. Temperatures hovered around 90,
the sky was the color of dirty dishwater and the humidity hung as
heavy as a woolen blanket.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of weather that tries the souls _ and noses _ of
landfill operators.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen is president of Landfill Technologies Inc., which has
developed an array of landfill improvements using the Albany dump
as its laboratory since 1981. The dump has drawn landfill engineers
from across the country and abroad, including representatives from
Israel, Argentina, Hong Kong, Taiwan and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming from all over the world to see what Albany
is doing with its garbage,'' said Hansen, a bear of a man who
sweated profusely and grinned like a child when tramping with
visitors over the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the technologies in use are a state-of-the-art plant for
extracting methane gas from the landfill, burning it and converting
that energy into electricity. Another is a system for improved
compacting of solid waste and covering it with a thin coating
called Posi-Shell that has proved more efficient than dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albany landfill is on the cutting edge of technologies. It
has become a leader in several areas,'' said Thomas Reynolds,
environmental engineer for the New York Department of Environmental
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The praise is tempered by the city's checkered history of
handling its solid waste. In 1990, an explosion of methane gas
leaking from another Albany dump caused damage to homes and
required $4.4 million to relocate residences and alleviate the gas
danger.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Gov. George Pataki announced a $1.4 million
settlement of a federal lawsuit brought by a neighborhood group for
pollution caused by the ANSWERS plant, a waste-to-energy facility
developed jointly by Albany and the state.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the dump is a fire-breathing cash cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel the power of those engines?'' Don Mazzarello, who
wore headphones to protect his ears, shouted over the rumble of two
truck-sized engines.
</P>
<P>
   The air in the engine room was a wall of sound and fury, with
intense heat rolling off the red-hot, 1,400 Fahrenheit burn zone.
The engines suck out methane gas from pipes buried deep in the gut
of the landfill, burn the gas and convert it into electricity that
is purchased by Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzarello operated the brand-new electric generating plant,
which recently went on line at the landfill. Known as Minnesota
Methane, the plant is owned by NEO Corp. of Minneapolis and is
capable of extracting enough methane from the buried garbage to
produce 1.9 megawatts of power _ the equivalent of lighting 19,000
100-watt light bulbs. Eventually, the landfill might be able to
produce 3.2 megawatts of power.
</P>
<P>
   Methane is a colorless, odorless and highly flammable gas. It is
produced when organic matter decomposes. Naturally occurring
bacteria essentially eat the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a giant compost pile.
</P>
<P>
   Methane production is altered by rainwater, heat and other
factors. By pumping in air through the piping under the landfill,
the bacteria can be stimulated to work harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a living entity out there,'' Hansen said. ``I'm
fixated by garbage. There's a lot going on under the ground. I've
spent most days out here for the past 17 years and it changes every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Methane has invested about $2.5 million so far in the
Albany landfill. The city paid nothing, and it avoids about $20,000
per month in upkeep costs on the methane gas extraction it would
have to do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city stands to benefit to the tune of $6 million over the
next six years, said Gregg Nolte, deputy commissioner of the city's
Department of General Services..
</P>
<P>
   Nolte's dream would be to use the electricity generated by
burning methane gas from the landfill to power the city's street
lighting, saving millions of dollars every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not far-fetched,'' Nolte said. ``The technology is
improving all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the microscopic bacteria churning through the
decades of garbage are the equivalent of the bunny in the Energizer
battery ads. They just keep going and going and going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process starts right away, but peak methane production is
eight or nine years after the garbage was covered,'' Hansen said.
``Production is good for about 20 years. That takes us well into
the 21st century here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
