<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWING BABY OUT WITH THE SMUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those of us with monitor tans start getting nervous whenever
Congress takes up Internet legislation. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the latest effort to protect kids from on-line smut.
Last year the Communications Decency Act was gutted by the Supreme
Court, so Congress is trying to be a bit more creative this time
around. Last week, the Senate passed an appropriations bill with a
rider that will force schools and public libraries to use Internet
filtering software or lose their federal funding. Another part of
the bill will require that commercial Web sites with material
deemed ``harmful to minors'' must prevent minors from getting into
the sites.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sympathetic to the goal of this bill. There's some appalling
stuff on line, material that children have no business seeing. But
these proposals are a lousy way to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The mandatory filtering idea was proposed by Arizona Senator
John McCain, a conservative Republican who for some reason wants to
impose a sweeping federal mandate on thousands of classrooms and
libraries across the land. I favor blocking porn and violence on
school computers, and I think libraries should set limits on how
kids use their Internet terminals. But these institutions are
perfectly capable of working out for themselves the best ways of
doing this. The feds should butt out.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the plan to force Web sites to hide their seamier
material from youngsters. There's just one little problem: How?
Consider the on-line magazine Salon, a lively site with excellent
writing on politics and the arts. And yes, sex. Salon won't let a
week go by without a thoughtful but raunchy consideration of the
world's favorite pastime, written in a form that is definitely not
suitable for the kiddies.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's advertiser-supported, Salon is a commercial site,
subject to the new law. But there's no practical way to seal off
the naughty articles from the rest of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, an effort to protect our children is going too far.
The Supreme Court should knock this one down, if the House of
Representatives doesn't scrap it first.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the House can be trusted to do right by the Internet.
Consider pending legislation that's supposed to fight the plague of
spam _ those unsolicited ads for porn and get-rich-quick schemes
that flood our e-mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an area that's ripe for federal legislation. It's already
illegal for businesses to send ads to your fax machine. Republican
Chris Smith of New Jersey proposes to extend the ban to e-mail.
This wouldn't do much to stop spam from other countries, but for
now it mostly originates in the United States anyhow. I think the
Smith bill is the best approach to spambusting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet thurda (July 30)the House is supposed to vote on a bill that
would effectively legalize spam. The legislation, drafted in the
Senate, would simply bar the common practice of using phony return
e-mail addresses in these obnoxious mailings. Spammers would have
to include a name, street address, phone number, and correct e-mail
address. Recipients of spam would thus be able to write back to the
sender asking them to stop, with stiff civil penalties if the
mailings continue.
</P>
<P>
   A fat lot of good that'll do. Even if spammers comply, they're
free to keep clogging the Internet with tens of millions of useless
messages. But we don't want to know who these guys are. We just
want them to stop. Bring on the Smith bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every now and then, Congress gets it right. On Tuesday,
the Senate Finance Committee approved a two-year moratorium on new
state and local Internet taxes. And the House backed a three-year
Internet tax moratorium last month. Everyone agrees that taxation
of Internet activity is coming. But there's a consensus that taxes
on this new industry should be delayed, until lawmakers know enough
to do it right.
</P>
<P>
   It's an outbreak of prudence and common sense, in the last place
you'd expect. Maybe I've been too hard on these guys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
