<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOWIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BOWIE: WEALTHY WEB WIZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprisingly few people scoffed when rocker David Bowie, known
more for his high-heeled antics in the '70s than his high-tech
forays in the '90s, announced recently that he was leaping further
into the digital ether.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie was one of the first celebrities to leverage his name and
sonic appeal into the wide-open Web with davidbowie.com, and
expands that foothold with the anticipated August launch of
BowieNet, an Internet service provider that will enable fans to
become citizens of a Bowie-focused cybercommunity. If successful,
Bowie could be at the forefront of a new kind of Web gathering, a
collective driven by the personality at its center.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest shift for rock's reigning master of reinvention,
yet another permutation of the Bowie persona that has mutated
through Ziggy Stardust, the Thin White Duke, various glam rock
incarnations and now, to its current state, the Omniscient Elder
Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   At 50, Bowie is one of the world's richest musicians, with a
personal wealth estimated in excess of $200 million. He plans to
add to that with this new venture, likely to finance a few more
palatial villas in warm places.
</P>
<P>
   At $20 per month, the price is comparable with AOL and other
major ISPs and online services, but with full internet access
customized for Bowie fans. E-mail will be routed to
subscriber(AT)davidbowie.com, and a national scattering of points
of presence will allow users local-call dialup service.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the hook is Bowie himself, and the site intends to
feature exclusive Bowie content that should satisfy the most rabid
Bowiephile. The service's Web browser will be customized with
pictures, sounds, and graphics, likely similar in some ways to the
artistic use of simple design elements on the davidbowie.com site.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie shrewdly allied himself with industry players with the
tools to make such a venture work smoothly. The network
infrastructure is provided by Concentric Network Corp., of
Cupertino, Calif., with the whole deal orchestrated by a management
and technology partnetship called UltraStar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.33l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Behind the name are two of the people most responsible for
Bowie's financial success: Robert Goodale, executive vice president
of Bowie's management company for six years; and William Zysblat,
co-owner of RZO, the firm that coordinated the innovative $55
million sale of bonds based on future royalties from Bowie's songs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of BowieNet's partners is N2K, the online music
entertainment firm that established jazzcentralstation.com as a
major jazz content provider. Definitely worth clicking is the link
to milesdavis.com, which, as one might deduce from the URL, intends
to be a comprehensive and official Miles resource.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With each month, Yahoo! Internet Life extends its lead over the
chaotic field of Web-focused print magazines. It also proves
there's a substantial crossover between Web users who prefer to
retrieve their information on line, and diehards who swear by the
infinitely more portable dead-tree editions.
</P>
<P>
   The well-designed glossy anticipates boosting its guaranteed
circulation base to 600,000 by February, double the initial
circulation after its first year of operation. There's space to
grow within the genre, although two good-looking competitors folded
within a year: The Web Magazine, a promising venture that never
caught on; and NetGuide, which attempted to chronicle the Web's
spread and was bowled over instead.
</P>
<P>
   Like new growth springing up where old trees fall, several
ambitious magazines have joined the race to catch Yahoo! Internet
Life. Worth searching for is Upside, an excellent new-media
chronicle that also seems poised to fish the waters patrolled by
Wired, the now-mainstream mag that is part of the Conde Nast
empire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kodak.com is mustering support for PhotoQuilt 2000, a Web-wide
project that arranges submitted pictures into a virtual patchwork
quilt. The site is desperately seeking submissions, which can be
sent directly from a digital camera, traditional photos scanned in
.jpg or .gif formats, or a transferred Web image. Each picture,
however, should be accompanied by a brief story that gives it some
context. This will also enable visitors to use the site's indexing
software to search for keywords.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers can zoom into pictures with surprising magnification;
this is just one of the benefits of the FlashPix formatting that
each picture undergoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total Annihilation freaks have a new reason to cackle as they
rampage through the core, an expansion pack that enables players to
choose 100 quick scenarios. The battle tactics add-on also has a
long-awaited feature allowing players to select the length of
desired missions. The shortest can be played in the time needed to,
say, run out for a carton of milk. The longest is a several-hour
siege perfect for developing bleary eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
