<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_DRUG CUTS RELAPSE IN HERPES STUDY   
 _OSTEOPOROSIS RISK LESSENED BY DRUG   
 _MS FOUND TO FLARE LESS IN PREGNANCY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Drug cuts relapse in herpes study
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current New England Journal of Medicine shows
that a commonly used antiviral drug, acyclovir, can prevent
recurrences of herpes infections in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 400,000 Americans are infected with herpes Simplex
I, which causes fever blisters on the mouth and infections in the
eye, some serious enough to cause blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Both the ocular herpes virus and the genital herpes virus
(Simplex II) are notorious for recurrences because the viruses can
hide in nerve tissue. Once you get ocular herpes, for instance, you
have up to a 50 percent chance of relapse.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, led by Dr. Kirk Wilhelmus, a professor of
ophthalmology at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, 703
patients who had had ocular herpes were given either acyclovir or a
placebo to prevent recurrences. Those who took 400 milligrams of
acyclovir twice a day had a 41 percent reduction in recurrences,
said Wilhelmus in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was even more pronounced _ a 50 percent reduction in
risk _ for those with the most serious form of ocular herpes,
stromal keratitis. There was no rebound in recurrence rates for at
least six months after patients stopped taking the drug, nor were
there any serious side effects associated with the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drug is the first treatment that helps prevent herpes of
the eye from returning. The results of this study should change
medical practice,'' said Dr. Carl Kupfer, director of the National
Eye Institute, in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial, Dr. Douglas A. Jabs of the Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine in Baltimore, agreed, calling the
findings ``robust.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Osteoporosis risk lessened by drug
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One million Americans routinely take steroid drugs like
prednisone to combat rheumatoid arthritis, asthma, inflammatory
bowel disease, and other conditions. But a major side effect of
steroid treatment is an increased risk of osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the New England Journal of Medicine by researchers
from the University of Iowa and elsewhere shows that the drug
Fosamax (alendronate) offers significant protection against this
bone loss, at doses of 5 or 10 milligrams a day.
</P>
<P>
   While previous research had shown Fosamax can prevent and treat
post-menopausal osteoporosis, this is the first large study to show
it works in steroid-induced osteoporosis, too.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by Dr. Kenneth Saag, an assistant professor
of internal medicine at the university, studied nearly 500 men and
women ages 17 to 83 for 48 weeks. All the patients were taking at
least 7.5 milligrams a day of prednisone.
</P>
<P>
   All patients also took 800 to 1,000 milligrams a day of calcium,
as well as 250 to 500 International Units of vitamin D daily to
help protect their bones. The patients also received either
Fosamax, at one of the two doses, or a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, those who took Fosamax had a nearly 3 percent increase
in bone density and a 40 percent reduction in risk of spinal
fractures, regardless of age or sex, said Saag in a telephone
interview. For post-menopausal women not taking estrogen
replacement therapy, the higher dose was more effective; for
everyone else, the low dose worked just as well. The study was
sponsored by Merck and Co., which makes Fosamax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MS found to flare less in pregnancy
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have long known that women have more auto-immune
diseases like multiple sclerosis than men and that pregnancy
sometimes makes such diseases worse, and sometimes, better.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from 12 European countries report in the New England
Journal of Medicine on 254 women with MS. Compared to the year
before pregnancy, the women were 70 percent less likely to have an
MS flare-up in the last three months of pregnancy. In the three
months after delivery, they were 70 percent more likely to have
one.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that during pregnancy, a woman's immune
system shifts from a preponderance of pro-inflammatory (TH1) cells
to a preponderance of anti-inflammatory (TH2) cells, said Dr. John
N. Whitaker, head of neurology at the University of Alabama at
Birmingham and author of an editorial on the study.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the resurgence of MS after childbirth, Whitaker said
in a telephone interview, women with MS should be offered one of
three commonly used drugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
