<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0340 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WATER-SPI &LR;      07-30 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WATER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WATER' IS A CLEVER COMEDY ABOUT HOMOSEXUAL PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first half hour, this gay soap opera runs amok as far as
tone and technique. The acting is so amateurish and over the top,
we initially wonder if we'll ever be able to engage with the
caricatured characters who inhabit the upscale and elite Southern
town, Azalea Springs.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the film comes back down to Earth and transforms
itself into a clever, spry comedy about homosexual panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the Water'' is like watching ``Steel Magnolias'' on
speed. But fortunately, the core couple-to-be in the movie move
center stage and ground the story within its overblown peripheral
chaos and camp.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Stratton (Keri Jo Chapman) is in an unhappy marriage with a
too-busy husband. Worse, her society mother, Lily (Barbara
Lasater), intrudes in her life _ and her wardrobe _ on a
too-regular basis. Alex stoicly goes about her business despite
their constant carping and disapproval. Only her friends at the
town's new AIDS facility, gay Spencer (John Hallum), and old high
school chum, Grace Miller (Teresa Garrett), keep her spirits
afloat.
</P>
<P>
   When the town's country club-like Women's League surprisingly
votes to do its volunteer work at the hospice, the decision upsets
several of the snooty women and causes controversy when Spencer
drunkenly jokes at the Azalea Ball that he became gay ``after
drinking the town's water.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the whole burg turns upside down and is in a frenzy; Alex
falls in love with Grace, and newspaper reporter Mark Anderson
(Derrick Sanders) defies his old-school dad and announces that he,
too, is gay. Even Brother Daniel (John Addington), who runs a
``Homo-No-Mo'' support group, inadvertently gets caught in the
craziness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the Water'' features two attractive lead characters.
Chapman and Garrett inhabit their parts with quiet assurance and
gravity and they hold our attention by offering welcome relief from
the rest of the insanity. Unfortunately, most of the other actors
push the envelope as far as perpetuating old stereotypes _ both of
gays and Southern belles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, director and writer Kelli Herd has made a pleasant and
moving comedy that sprung from her astonishment over ``the lack of
films about gays and lesbians.''
</P>
<P>
   She manages to poke fun at conservative, right-wing factions yet
isn't vicious or mean in her humor. That allows the film to
transcend being pigeon-holed. It has a more universal appeal. In
fact, ``It's in the Water'' played two years ago at the Seattle
International Film Festival, where it packed the house and was
well-received.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's not perfect _ the look of the film has no real style
or originality _ it does have an eclectic charm. And Chapman, who
has appeared on ``Baywatch,'' is terrific as a society wife who has
been beaten down by marital and parental pressure. She retains a
resilience that is compelling.
</P>
<P>
   As Alex begins to take control of her life, the actress visibly
blooms onscreen. While Patricia Rozema's ``When Night Is Falling''
is still the best film about a woman's coming out, ``It's in the
Water'' is a feel-good addition to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the Water. Directed by Kelli Herd. Written by Kelli
Herd. Cast: Keri Jo Chapman, Teresa Garrett, Derrick Sanders,
Timothy Vahle. Herd Film Co., 100 minutes. Unrated with nudity,
language, gay themes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
