<HEADLINE>
`WHATEVER' COPS AN ATTITUDE EARLY ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This movie about high school girls on the fast track to hell in
1981 cops an attitude early on and maintains its facade of
hopelessness and apathy throughout. Like ``Girls Town'' and ``All
Over Me,'' its main characters are opposites who attract.
</P>
<P>
   Anna (Liza Weil) lives with her mom and bratty little brother.
She's up for admittance to art school _ Cooper Union in Manhattan _
and has genuine artistic talent. Brenda comes from an abusive
household and she's full of rage and self-loathing. She doesn't
care about anything but having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever'' opens with a distasteful scene of three boys
``running a train'' on Brenda as she lies drunkenly in a field.
It's an unsettling and revolting moment that sets the tone for
things to come.
</P>
<P>
   But Anna is the film's real protagonist. She's shy and unsure
and mouths off to everyone in authority in an effort to be
accepted. Only in art class under the guidance of Mr. Chaminsky (an
over-the-top Frederic Forrest) does she find her footing. Deep down
she desperately wants to be admitted to college. She's fragile,
ackward and at the age where any rejection could break her in half.
</P>
<P>
   The girls slum from party to party; Brenda grows continually
more reckless, picking up older boys, and Anna follows behind,
picking up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The unfocused world of teenagers at a breaking point is captured
beautifully in ``Whatever.'' Anna admits she's ``afraid of being
ordinary'' and writer/director Susan Skoog and Liza Weil, the young
actress who astonishingly inhabits Anna, ensure she's anything but.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad the same can't be said for Skoog's script, which
relies upon banalities, overused trademarks of teenage angst and
rebellion and that old red herring, abuse, as the impetus for
Brenda's sullen rage.
</P>
<P>
   The party scenes are perfectly recreated, with the miasma and
lethargy of youth wasting their lives and brain cells with too much
alcohol and drugs, and not having a very good time in the process.
It almost feels like a documentary in some instances, which would
have been a fascinating premise, but Skoog forces her narrative
into conventional dramatic structures and it hurts the film.
</P>
<P>
   Had she just let the camera roll and not pushed the story into
such convenient, cliched and obvious slots, the film might have
been revelatory. But it opts to follow a more traditional path and
despite two exceptionally fine performances from Weil and Morgan,
``Whatever'' is, well, just whatever itself.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and written by Susan Skoog. Cast: Liza Weil, Chad
Morgan, Mark Riffon. Sony Pictures Classics. 112 minutes. Rated R
for language, sexual content, nudity, scenes with drugs and
alcohol, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
