<SLUG> BC-PROBE-LEWINSKYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LEWINSKY AND MOTHER, THE ORDEAL GOES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They hunkered together like frightened prey as
prosecutors stalked their secrets.
</P>
<P>
   For Monica S. Lewinsky and her mother, Marcia K. Lewis, time
passed slowly in the six months that independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr tightened the prosecutorial circle around them before they
agreed on Tuesday to cooperate in his investigation of President
Clinton in exchange for full immunity from criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, a mother and daughter accustomed to many of the
finer things money can buy lived in fear that they could land
behind bars for their roles in Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lewinsky and Lewis are starting over, free from prosecution
as long as they tell grand jurors all they know about Lewinsky's
alleged affair with Clinton and any efforts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   But with much to tell _ and so much upheaval behind them _ the
lives of the mother and daughter from Beverly Hills will never be
the same.
</P>
<P>
   According to news accounts, taped conversations between
Lewinsky, a 25-year-old former White House intern, and her former
co-worker, Linda R. Tripp, show Lewinsky confided details of her
alleged sexual relationship with Clinton to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes also reportedly indicate Lewis, 50, was scheming to
try to conceal her daughter's relationship with Clinton when
Lewinsky and Tripp were subpoenaed in the sexual harassment case
that Paula Corbin Jones brought against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In one taped exchange, Lewinsky told Tripp her mother had
offered to help pay expenses if Tripp would follow through on her
idea to fake a ``foot accident'' to avoid testifying, according to
Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was quoted as saying her mother described Tripp's idea
for the foot injury as ``brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ploy was never used.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, in an affidavit, denied having sex with Clinton. The
president also denied under oath that he and Lewinsky had a sexual
relationship, a denial he has repeated publicly.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis's part, Starr has also investigated whether she helped
Lewinsky develop a mysterious list of ``talking points'' for Tripp
to use if she testified in the Jones case. The talking points are
considered possible evidence of an effort to have Tripp lie about
Clinton's alleged encounter with a White House volunteer, Kathleen
Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Starr, in the end, would have considered Lewis complicit
in a criminal case involving Lewinsky or Clinton, all that mattered
to the mother and daughter was the possibility raised by Starr's
staff that he might.
</P>
<P>
   None of the estimated 70 witnesses who have testified before
Starr's grand jury since January became more distraught than Lewis
did during two appearances in February. At one point, the judge
halted questioning and summoned a nurse for Lewis. The judge later
excused her because she was too upset to continue.
</P>
<P>
   The episode marked a low point in the lengthy ordeal the mother
and daughter have endured since Lewinsky burst from obscurity with
the first news reports on Jan. 21, a week after Starr's
investigators confronted Lewinsky after she and Tripp discussed her
alleged affair with Clinton over drinks at a Ritz-Carlton hotel in
suburban Washington. Investigators were monitoring a hidden
recording device worn by Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   The first call Lewinsky made while the investigators detained
her was to her mother _ who has been her daughter's housemate,
closest friend, and confidante.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who shared Lewinsky's passion for the social circuit,
became a freelancer for the Hollywood Reporter while she lived a
millionaire's life in Beverly Hills during her 19-year marriage to
Dr. Bernard S. Lewinsky, a prominent oncologist.
</P>
<P>
   At one social event, Lewis, which is her pen name, befriended
the singer Placido Domingo. She later wrote a book, ``Three
Tenors'' about Domingo, Jose Carrera, and Luciano Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign she harbored little naivete about the public appetite
for sexual intrigue, Lewis reportedly encouraged her publishers to
promote the book by leaking rumors that she had slept with Domingo,
which she would deny.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lewis reportedly told Starr's investigators after they
detained Lewinsky at the Ritz-Carlton: ``What's the big deal? So
she lied and tried to convince someone else to lie?''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Lewis accompanied Lewinsky home to the duplex
apartment they were sharing in the Watergate complex next to the
John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in Washington. Lewis
moved there after she and Dr. Lewinsky divorced in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed the episode at the Ritz-Carlton,
Lewis and Lewinsky faced a battery of television cameras whenever
they left the Watergate. They grew increasingly reclusive, although
Lewinsky occasionally attended social events with her former
lawyer, William H. Ginsburg, and Lewis sometimes escaped to New
York to visit her then fiance and now husband, R. Peter Straus, 75,
a communications executive who has stood by Lewis and Lewinsky
throughout the experience.
</P>
<P>
   But the mother and daughter mostly were alone with their secrets
and their fears. Now, they have something more to share: an
uncertain future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
