<SLUG> BC-FILM-BASEKETBALL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASEKETBALL' IS LOW AND DUMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are this summer's Hollywood comedies aiming lower than ever
before in terms of bathroom humor, cruelty jokes, insensitivity to
minorities and all-around bad taste?
</P>
<P>
   That's the argument several critics have made recently, and
based on the evidence of such films as ``Mafia!,'' ``There's
Something About Mary,'' and even ``Dr. Doolittle,'' it's hard to
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   And there's still more evidence for the prosecution in
``BASEketball,'' a harrowingly dumb comedy that combines the
talents of writer-director David Zucker (``Airplane!'' ``The Naked
Gun'') with the creators of trash-TV's ``South Park,'' Trey Parker
and Matt Stone.
</P>
<P>
   This one is about two Milwaukee underachievers (Parker and
Stone), who inadvertently invent a backyard game that combines
elements of both basketball and baseball, with an added ``psyche
out'' factor in which opponents deliberately try to rattle each
other's concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to five years later, and the sport is the rage of America,
largely because it has forbidden all the things we hate about
professional sports in the '90s _ players aren't highly paid, they
can't change teams and corporate money is kept out.
</P>
<P>
   It's rather a clever idea for a sports satire, on the basis of
which sports-enthusiast Zuker apparently managed to recruit a slew
of famous sports announcers (Bob Costas, Tim McCarver, Curt Gowdy
and Al Michaels), and such sports legends as Reggie Jackson, Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Dale Earnhardt to take part.
</P>
<P>
   But, not content to make merely a clever satire, he's junked up
the movie far beyond anything he's ever dared in the past. It's one
flatulence, urination and vomit gag after another; juvenile attacks
on gays (the San Francisco team is ``the Ferries''), Hispanics and
the blind; cruelty jokes that go on for agonizing lengths of screen
time.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, despite his successful track record as a comedy
director, Zuker proves himself not especially adept at
low-low-humor _ not half as imaginative as, say, the Farrelly
Brothers (``Kingpin,'' ``Dumb and Dumber''). At least three-fourths
of his gags fell absolutely flat with the audience Universal
recruited for the Seattle preview showing. Barely a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   But the real tragedy is that, by spending so much of its time
heaping up the most abysmal kind of adolescent humor,
``BASEketball'' fails to live up to whatever small potential it has
as a sports comedy. The script doesn't even have time to tell us,
for instance, how this game is played. We're forced to keep staring
at these numbskulls throwing basketballs and running around some
weird shaped court without ever really knowing what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   BASEketball. Directed by David Zucker. Cast: Trey Parker, Matt
Stone, Yasmine Bleeth, Robert Vaughn. Universal. 100 minutes. Rated
R for gross humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-30 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... she says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What she didn't know was that an entire family had been waiting
_ and literally praying _ for her arrival for decades. She didn't
know that the grandmother she'd never met had pasted a halo of
Brock's baby pictures on her bedroom mirror, or that an aunt
carried a faded photograph of her in her wallet. (More people who
knew the secret.) ``It was really strange, like being famous and
not knowing you're famous,'' Brock says.
</P>
<P>
   She knew none of this, of course, when she arrived by chance at
a convention in Dorado Beach four months after her mother's death.
Or when she asked a hotel desk clerk how she might track down
someone in the area and he suggested she try any number of old
restaurants where locals hang out. Or when, in the first restaurant
she entered, the cook announced that he knew the brother of one
Clemente Morales Torres. Or when the cook fetched a young man named
Rafi, who said he was related to Clemente Morales Torres and that
Torres had indeed been in Japan after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Brock got a pretty good idea what was coming when she told
Rafi that Torres might be her father and he nonchalantly replied:
``Yeah, I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The next few hours were chaos. She was taken to meet her uncle,
the proprietor of a nearby store. She was whisked to an elegant
neighborhood home where she met her two aunts, one of them weeping
as she pulled Brock's baby picture from her wallet. She was hurried
to another, more modest, home where her elderly paternal
grandparents _ Miquel and Maria, no longer living at the address to
which Brock had sent her letter _ were waiting. ``My grandfather
embraced me and cried and mumbled things in Spanish,'' Brock says.
``Then I sat between the two of them on a couch while they held my
hand and talked in Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing was, they all knew. They all knew of the young man who
had joined the Army, gone to Japan, fallen in love, fathered a
child, and come home alone. They had prayed for the child's arrival
in their midst, and the prayers had finally been answered. Even as
the father of the little girl had gone away to live on the US
mainland, even as he was now working as a cab driver in New York,
they had waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing thing,'' says Brock, ``that they had loved
me dearly but had never known me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rita Brock talked to her father for the first time on the
telephone from Puerto Rico the next morning. He told her that he'd
met her mother in a US hospital in Japan where he was an orderly
and she was a nurse. He explained that he and Ayako had lived
together for six months after Rita was born, and that he'd been
shipped to Korea. He told her she'd been named after actress Rita
Hayworth, who was part Hispanic. And he admitted that he hadn't
kept in touch with Ayako, finally receiving a letter from her
announcing that she'd gotten married and that he should never try
to contact her or their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried a lot,'' Brock says of that first conversation with
her father. ``He said several times that he had wanted to find me
but had wanted to respect my mother's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brock did not, she recalls, have any strong feelings about
this voice at the other end of the line. To her, it seemed she was
simply having a polite conversation with a kind of stranger. ``He
just seemed like some guy that I was supposed to know but didn't
feel any connection to,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Later they would meet face-to-face in New York. Torres would cry
again, but Brock still didn't know what to feel. ``It was a numbing
experience in some ways,'' she recalls. ``Many of my assumptions
around the experience had been shattered. I'd thought it would be
hard to find him. I thought people might be unhappy to see me. So I
couldn't connect to the intense euphoria in Puerto Rico. More than
anything, it was bewildering.''
</P>
<P>
   It still is. Four times divorced, Torres, now in his early 70s,
lives in Chattanooga, where he is a part-time security guard.
Brock, herself divorced with no children, sees him only about once
a year. He signs his cards, ``Dad.'' She calls him ``Clemente.''
``He really doesn't know me in the way a father would know me,''
says Brock. ``We don't have those shared experiences. He's not
someone I would go to for help. ... It's hard to imagine him as my
father. Mostly he's this person who connects me to this very
interesting family in Puerto Rico.'' Describing herself as ``half
Puerto Rican but not culturally Puerto Rican,'' Brock says she'd
eventually like to live on the island, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she still wonders why her mother never told her the
secret. And she wishes she had. She muses aloud about the
difficulties her mother must have faced in raising a mixed-race
child within a xenophobic culture. And hadn't Ayako Brock written
in longhand to Clemente Torres in March 1953, when she told him not
to contact her, ``If necessary to tell (Rita) I will tell her about
you?'' But she never did tell her, except by leaving a document in
a metal box as she was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably had some intent to tell me, but the longer she
waited the harder it got,'' Brock theorizes.
</P>
<P>
   After she had learned the secret and found her birth father,
Rita Brock visited her adoptive father's family in rural
Mississippi. When she told her Aunt Pearl Gilmore that she'd
discovered she wasn't Roy Brock's daughter and that her father was
really Puerto Rican, the older woman didn't blink. Yes: she knew,
too. Heck, Aunt Pearl allowed as how just about everyone knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way to do it,'' she declared, laughing. ``You tell
people something but don't tell them it's a secret. That way they
won't talk about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1326EDT &QL; 
