<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHILDREN OF FAST FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I still remember how shocked I was when I first read that girls
were beginning to diet in the fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   I blamed the families, especially the superficial, empty-headed
mothers who taught their daughters to care too much about their
appearance. I blamed the media and a corporate culture that
presented girls with unattainable models of slimness as a way of
inducing them to spend more money. I saw this premature concern
with weight as a way of distracting girls from their real purposes
in life, turning would-be astronomers and aspiring physicians into
obsessive fat gram counters. I thought that having so many young
girls dieting was appalling.
</P>
<P>
   I take it all back. They have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Today's kids are under assault by a multibillion-dollar fast
food industry intent on cramming fried foods, snack foods, and
sweet foods down their throats. I now think that one of the most
important skills we can teach our children, male or female, is how
to avoid getting hooked on food that is dangerous to their health.
</P>
<P>
   Today's kids face too many temptations. A birthday party, which
used to be an unusual event, comes up every week. Once you invited
a few friends and that was that. Today, in an attempt to be more
inclusive, children invite every classmate to every birthday party,
which results in a hectic, and very fattening, social calendar for
all.
</P>
<P>
   My grandaughter and I went to a roller-skating party the other
day, and it was lots of fun, especially when I discovered I could
still skate backward. As Jessie and I passed the food table,
however, we snacked on potato chips, M&AMP;Ms, cheese puffs, pretzels.
Then came lunch: cheese-drenched pizza and sugar-filled soda. And
dessert: rich chocolate cake, creamy ice cream. At the end of the
party, the two of us waddled to the car.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not blaming anyone. This is the same menu Jessie served at
her birthday party. This is the food that's on every children's
menu in every restaurant in America. This is the food they serve
when the gym team wins a match or the Girl Scouts have a picnic.
This is the food the baby sitter orders when she's asked to give
the kids dinner, the food a family eats when it stops on the road
for a meal. This is the food for sale at movie theaters, in bowling
alleys, at ball games. This is the food many schools are now
serving in their cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it fattening, the portions are getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Most ice cream stores these days start their cones at $1.89 or
more. Several scoops fill even the smallest container to
overflowing. If you ask for a single scoop, the kid behind the
counter informs you that small is not an option. When I've offered
to pay top price for one tiny scoop, I usually get one the size of
a bloated softball. And don't forget the sprinkles: oreo cookies,
M&AMP;Ms, chunks of chocolate peanut-butter cups, rainbow jimmies
shoveled on with a trowel. The ``smallest'' dish of ice cream in
these places could hold any kid for a month. Have you seen a muffin
lately? Eating one is like lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   The results are everywhere you look. In the past 30 years, the
proportion of US children who are overweight has doubled, from 5 to
11 percent, but getting fat is only one of the problems that comes
from eating this stuff. Pediatricians are increasingly concerned
about the incidence of high blood pressure in boys 10 to 18, who,
upon examination, are found to already have a thickening of the
heart muscle that has been linked to heart failure in adults.
Excess weight is also a contributing factor to adult-onset
diabetes. In addition, because we live in a fat-hating culture,
being heavy puts a child under significant psychological strain.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents discover, to their dismay, that after their child
hits school, they have no control over what she eats. How else can
a family fight back except by placing the responsibility for her
diet within the child? What else can parents do but explain the
principles of good nutrition and hope they've succeeded in walking
the fine line between raising a healthy child and creating fertile
ground for bulimia or anorexia?
</P>
<P>
   This is a culture that is deeply at odds with our children's
well-being. As long as money changes hands, advertisers don't care
what they push on our kids: cigarettes, caffeine-laden soda, or
clogged arteries and a blighted life, it's all the same to them. As
the only voice of reason around, the conscientious parent walks
this minefield with caution. One misstep and the child is hiding
candy bars under the bed or subsisting on one small apple for
dinner, slice by slice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
