<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-GROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST HOW THE GARDEN GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardeners are a curious lot (you can take that two ways, and
probably should), and lately this gardener has been curious about
just how his garden does grow.
</P>
<P>
   My idle summer thoughts ran thusly: In the front yard, awash in
sunshine, the grass grows and must be mowed (though not so much in
the heat waves of July, which may be of some relief to us as we
swelter). In the back, where I have the vegetable garden, there is
too much shade, and corn will not grow. Grass and corn are both
monocots, and what do we really know about monocots? This is how my
interest was piqued (and this is how my mind works, a process well
understood by my long-suffering wife).
</P>
<P>
   The plants we are familiar with are gymnosperms (conifers, which
have no flowers and whose so-called naked seeds are not encased
inside ovaries) and angiosperms (the flowering plants, with seeds
in ovaries). Angiosperms (division Anthophyta) constitute the
largest classification of plants and are divided into two classes:
monocotyledons (monocots) and dicotyledons (dicots).
</P>
<P>
   The classes are named for the number of cotyledons each has.
Cotyledons are the ``seed leaves,'' those small fleshy appendages
(one on monocots, such as grass and corn; two on a dicot, such as a
rose and marigold) that appear as a seed sprouts. They provide
storage for nutrients from the seeds and, in some cases, may
generate food through photosynthesis.
</P>
<P>
   It is not so simple, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Dicots greatly outnumber monocots, and they are quite different
in many ways. But many plants have a mix of monocot and dicot
characteristics, attributable in part to a shared ancestry. Tracing
the morphology of angiosperms, which would help us understand the
differences, and just where each species fits, is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Monocots evolved from dicots so early in the development of
flowering plants that there are large gaps in the fossil record.
There are plenty of flower fossils from the mid-Cretaceous, but by
then the split was well under way. Monocots may have branched off
from a Magnoliidae-like lineage, perhaps sharing ancestry with
Magnoliales, an order that now comprises several primitive dicots.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the number of cotyledons (and even that is not
definitive in every case), the differences between monocots and
dicots are both external and internal, obvious and obscure.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, monocots have leaf veins that are parallel, and the
base of a leaf sheathes the stem; dicot leaf veins are reticulate,
or netlike, and the flat part is usually connected to the stem by a
petiole, or stalk.
</P>
<P>
   Monocots can have modified structures underground for storage
and anchoring, such as bulbs (fleshy leaves, as in onions and
tulips), corms (dry leaves and stem) and rhizomes (stems).
</P>
<P>
   The parts of monocot flowers typically occur in multiples of
three; the floral parts of dicots come in multiples of four and
five.
</P>
<P>
   Monocot roots are adventitious, arising from nodes along stems,
and fibrous; dicot roots develop from the radicle at the base of
the seed and often have taproots.
</P>
<P>
   None of these by itself is definitive.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, monocots have vascular bundles (the xylem and phloem,
which carry nutrients and moisture) scattered inside the stem. In
dicots, these are arranged in a ring around the edge of the stems.
</P>
<P>
   Monocots do not form wood, lacking the vascular cambium that
forms the annual rings in woody dicots as new xylem is created and
pushes outward, though bamboos and palms and agaves can take on
woody characteristics. Palms, for example, use overlapping leaf
bases, thickened enlarged cells, and prop roots.
</P>
<P>
   Monocots have pollen with single furrows or pores; dicots have
pollen with three furrows or pores.
</P>
<P>
   None of these is itself definitive.
</P>
<P>
   There is a single definitive characteristic, though.
</P>
<P>
   Plastids, small structures inside cells, are found in all
plants. Inside the phloem, they contain crystalloid proteins, and
the shape of those is distinctive. In monocots, they have a
triangular shape; in dicots, all dicots, they do not.
</P>
<P>
   So, aside from passing the time on a hot summer afternoon, who
cares? Well, monocots compose a quarter of the flowering plant
species, and economically those may be the most valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Corn, rice, wheat and barley are derived from monocots. Bamboo
and palms are key building materials in many countries, and sugar
cane, pineapples, dates, bananas and many tropical fruits also come
from monocots. They also give us lilies and orchids, grasses and
sedges, rushes and cattails. Not surprisingly, monocots are
primarily tropical.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me back to my hot afternoon, and reality. Got to
mow the monocots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-ROSENBAUM-BOS &LR;      07-30 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-ROSENBAUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR REFOCUSES ON WHO LED THE HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the Hardy Boys had gone on to Yale and studied
English literature, they might have ended up a lot like Ron
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, by his own account, is a writer obsessed with
mysteries. He investigates investigations, immerses himself in
``clandestine subcultures'' and ``esoteric controversies,'' and
reads deep between the lines of the darkest puzzles, in search of
the hidden meanings that might unravel the great conundrums of our
time _ yet suspecting they'll never be solved.
</P>
<P>
   His new book, ``Explaining Hitler'' (Random House), grapples
with what may be the most enormous conundrum of all _ the true
nature of Western civilization's emblematic mass murderer and,
ultimately, of evil itself.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum adopts the role of literary critic-turned-gumshoe _
analyzing the texts of the historians, philosophers, and
theologians who have addressed the riddle, and then interviewing
them, probing their underlying methods and motives, stacking up
their stories and theories against one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a scholar, I'm an educated consumer of scholarship,''
Rosenbaum said over coffee at the Oyster Bar in Grand Central
Station, not far from his Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I read the literature,'' he said, ``the more I became
struck by how divisive _ how intriguingly divisive _ the
controversy about every facet of Hitler's biography, every facet of
his psychology, was. These were brilliant, deeply learned scholars
who were at loggerheads a half-century after Hitler's death, still
arguing over the origins of his anti-Semitism and `Was he
sincere?'''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of characters in Rosenbaum's tale is every bit as
motley and fascinating as the witnesses cross-examined in a
top-notch murder mystery.
</P>
<P>
   There's the first generation of dueling Hitler-explainers _ H.R.
Trevor-Roper, who argued that Hitler was ``convinced of his own
rectitude,'' versus Alan Bullock, who saw Hitler as cynically
manipulating popular German anti-Semitism for his own political
ends.
</P>
<P>
   There are the Freudians, who explain the Holocaust as the
product of Hitler's sexual perversities or as a reaction to
sublimated self-hatred stemming from his own possible Jewish
ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   There's Daniel Goldhagen, who sees the death camps as the
culmination of tendencies in German culture _ and Hyam Maccoby, who
sees them as the legacy of Christianity itself. There's Claude
Lanzmann, director of the nearly nine-hour documentary ``Shoah,''
who finds it sinful even to seek a ``why'' for the Holocaust,
arguing that explanation leads to exculpation; and Louis Micheels,
an Auschwitz survivor, who declares we must find a why, to prevent
the Holocaust from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum may be uniquely trained to sift through this mountain
of evidence and clues _ which is where the Hardy Boys and Yale come
in.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Bayshore, Long Island _ ``an uneventful place,''
as he calls it _ and found refuge in books as ``a way of escaping
to a more adventurous realm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hardy Boys detective books, he said, ``may have been my
biggest influence as a young kid. I got fixated on the idea of
solving mysteries. Maybe I was envious. I wished there were a lot
more skulduggery going on in my town.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rosenbaum went to Yale (class of '68), the English lit
department still revolved around the New Criticism, which preached
that the meaning of all literature was to be found through keen
examination of the text.
</P>
<P>
   ``I escaped from the academic world,'' he said, ``but one of the
things I brought to journalism from it was close reading _ not just
of literature, but of court documents, memoranda between
politicians and generals, the stenographic records of Hitler's
table talks.''
</P>
<P>
   As a freelance writer for numerous magazines for 25 years,
Rosenbaum has applied close reading _ and his obsession with
skulduggery _ to the CIA mole-hunters, the residual puzzles of
Watergate, JFK's assassination, and the subterranean world of the
Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The past three years, as a columnist for the weekly New York
Observer, he has resharpened his literary tools, probing less-trod
passages to illuminate unsolved mysteries in the life and work of
Shakespeare, Salinger, Nabokov, Pynchon, even the pop lyrics of
Rosanne Cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do read incessantly,'' Rosenbaum said. ``I always have a
stack of books that I'm reading simultaneously.'' His tastes tend
toward the grim. One of his favorite tomes is Robert Burton's
17th-century ``The Anatomy of Melancholy.'' His sense of identity
as a Jew is shaped mainly by his passion for such Jewish writers as
Kafka and the darker works of Isaac Bashevis Singer.
</P>
<P>
   He ends his book with the mystery of Hitler unsolved _ possibly
unsolvable. ``The deeper I looked into things,'' he said, ``the
less certain I became.'' In a sense, this makes his tale all the
more profound and scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to cling to the one theory, the one book, the one
rumor, to make them think it's nailed down,'' he observed. ``It's
pretty frightening to conclude that you don't really understand
where this evil comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum sees many theories as distractions from this
discomfort, as intellectual constructs to fit Hitler into some
scheme of normal human conduct and, thus, make staring into the
abyss more bearable.
</P>
<P>
   He especially distrusts the recent historians and political
scientists, such as Christopher Browning, who see the Holocaust as
the result of impersonal, almost inevitable forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to believe that great events don't happen without
great causes,'' Rosenbaum said. ``Contemporary historians want to
believe in great abstractions because it's considered a more
sophisticated way of looking at things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum may heap particular scorn on this school of thought
because he once endorsed it himself.
</P>
<P>
   He traces the genesis of ``Explaining Hitler'' to a conversation
in 1983 with a group of Jewish militants. ``They were talking about
building pipe bombs and attacking neo-Nazis,'' he recalled, ``and I
got into an argument with them about taking the law into one's own
hands. I took the liberal position that if you do this, others will
take the law into their hands and retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them said, `Wouldn't you have taken the law into your
own hands in Weimar Germany in the 1920s, when Hitler was on the
rise? Wouldn't it have been a good idea then to assassinate
Hitler?' I replied, `How do you know that would have made a
difference? There were powerful forces of history that would have
brought about a Hitler anyway.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I believed this even when I said it,''
Rosenbaum said. ``Certainly, I wasn't satisfied with my answer. It
made me wonder about the decisiveness of Hitler. Would
assassinating him have made a difference? It became a question I
wanted to investigate. I thought I'd write a novel, set in the
period, about an attempt by Jews to assassinate Hitler. I spent
four or five years researching it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more he delved into the controversies, the more he
favored the idea of a nonfiction book. He was particularly taken
with his discovery in German archives of the Munich Post, a
long-forgotten newspaper of the 1920s whose journalists were the
first to see Hitler as a murderer while so many other observers
were dismissing him as a clown or the tool of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me,'' he said, ``that some postwar scholarship,
which downplayed or dismissed the centrality of Hitler's role, was
replicating the common prewar view of Hitler _ the view that
underrated him, that saw him as a pawn of larger forces.''
</P>
<P>
   In this light, Rosenbaum came to see reestablishing Hitler's
central role as not only a factual responsibility but also a moral
one. The scholars who do otherwise, he writes at the end of his
book, permit Hitler ``to escape.'' They ``grant him the posthumous
victory of a last laugh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
