<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ALONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN TO THE SEA WITH JOSHUA SLOCUM, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
ALONE AT SEA 
The Adventures of Joshua Slocum 
By Ann Spencer 
Doubleday, 321 pp., illustrated, $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I read ``Alone at Sea'' on a cruising sailboat in Katama Bay off
Martha's Vineyard, not 5 miles from where an Edgartown fisherman
made the last positive sighting of Joshua Slocum's yawl Spray as it
sailed south, bound for the Caribbean, 90 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The few dozen sailboats that lie here at anchor boast aluminum
masts that fairly bristle with electronic sensors _ VHF radio,
single sideband, TV, Loran, GPS, radar, anemometer _ all to aid and
protect the humanity on the decks below. For modern sailors, every
revisit to the world of Joshua Slocum is as much rebuke as it once
was inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between Slocum's sailing conditions on Spray _ with
a compass, sextant, and inoperable clock _ and those on any modern
36-foot fiberglass cruiser scarcely needs mention. And yet his
towering abilities as a navigator, sailor, ship-wright, and
quick-witted adventurer are _ as many times as one comes upon
accounts of them _ awesome to behold. Spencer's book, an
appreciation of the man who sailed alone around the world from
April 1895 to July 1898, may not much advance our knowledge beyond
the earlier biographies, but it does repaint a wonderful old
seascape with loving care and some new detail.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time he spent cruising and navigating the world ``in
solitude supreme'' Slocum ironically was a very public man. After
his circumnavigation on a boat he rebuilt from a derelict oyster
dragger he found sitting in a Fairhaven cow pasture, Slocum wrote
and lectured extensively for the rest of his life. Spinning his
yarns to an amazed and, by Spencer's account, affectionate audience
(the old sea captain looked, spoke, and acted the part to a fault),
he made spellbinding his livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   The only real mystery of Slocum's life remains the circumstances
of his death. Was he lost in the fierce November gale that swept up
the Atlantic shortly after he left the Vineyard in 1908? Did Spray,
now in near-derelict condition, come apart in the autumn storms off
Hatteras? Or was Spray run down one night by a mail boat in the
lesser Antilles? Spencer explores the theories, seeming to favor
the last one, which came to light 50 years after Slocum and Spray
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Slocum's many scrapes and escapes, his struggles
against nature at its fiercest and most elemental, became the
metaphor of the man's life long before Spencer arrived at the
subject, though she finds something of a new beginning. She sees
Slocum as a man out of his time. At the end of the 19th century, as
he was coming of age as modern history's greatest sailor, the world
was turning away from sail to steam power, which he detested. His
early glory days as captain and part-owner of the magnificent
clipper Northern Light gave way to several reversals of fortune
that struck as suddenly as running aground on a bar, which he did
in one of his few miscalculations as navigator. Midlife found
Slocum penniless, depressed at the death of his first wife,
Victoria, and without a ship or prospect of another command.
</P>
<P>
   At this low point a friend offered Slocum the 36-foot sloop that
``needs some repair.'' Slocum was in Fairhaven next day, only to
find Spray such a derelict _ high, dry, and half-rotted _ that what
had seemed like a new prospect looked like a derisive joke. So
preposterous was the idea of restoring such a wreck that villagers
of Fairhaven often came to watch in wonderment as Slocum labored.
</P>
<P>
   But Slocum was stubborn, obsessively optimistic, and visionary.
He ``no doubt gave villagers their first intimation of how
determined and resourceful the old captain could be in heavy seas.
The crowd gathered in the pasture shared the assumption that Slocum
would be breaking up the Spray for scrap. His reply was quick and
to the point: `No, going to rebuild her.'''
</P>
<P>
   The best parts of Spencer's book are the pure shots of Slocum,
either his own poetic language or many of his time-polished tales
of pirates, storms, mutinies, hostile natives, and treacherous
reefs. Slocum's stories are, as Spencer notes in echoing his
publishers, a blend of ``Walden'' and ``Treasure Island.'' They are
always wonderful to read, even in retold form. The element of
Thoureau is in Slocum's quest to confront the essentials of life as
they are found not only in nature but in solitude. And though
Spencer treats this well and with care, no biography has ever
improved on Slocum's own ruminations, which she includes: ``The
loneliness of my state wore off when the gale was high and I found
much work to do,'' wrote the old captain. ``When fine weather
returned, then came the sense of solitude, which I could not shake
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when asleep, as Spray sailed along in perfect balance with
the tiller lashed, Slocum knew by instinct where the boat was, as
if he had an inner GPS attuned both to heaven and sea. It mattered
not, when he was sailing Spray, that no one was aboard to witness
his magnificent navigational skills. Says Spencer: ``He tested and
stretched his abilities, which were considerable, and in doing so
discovered where his limits were to be found. With no one to
witness his astonishing feats of seamanship, Slocum took comfort in
the knowledge that he had one constant companion at all times,
besides the Spray. As Slocum told it, `I sailed alone with God.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
