<HEADLINE>
STATES BET ON A LEGION OF SUCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend never plays the lottery unless the prize is over $10
million because, he says, if you win $1 million, or even a few
million more, it's not worth it. What have you got after taxes? he
asks.
</P>
<P>
   A lot more money than you had before?
</P>
<P>
   The lottery tends to cloud minds. Naturally my friend has been
buying fistfuls of Powerball tickets and has mentally spent the
$250 million he's sure he'll win, this time. He was angry when he
didn't win last week, actually angry. He took it personally.
</P>
<P>
   I almost never bet on anything because I know I'll lose. So I'm
fascinated by people who are sure they're going to win every time
they place a bet, even when they're betting on a state-run lottery,
where the odds of winning are infinitesimal.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this thinking come from? Whatever its source, it's
epidemic, and nothing, even years of losing, does much to
discourage it. Yesterday, throngs of Massachusetts residents
continued to storm the borders of neighboring states to buy
Powerball tickets, even as the executive director of the New
Hampshire Lottery _ the director of the lottery! _ was advising
bettors on Page1 of the Globe to save their money, that Powerball
is, in effect, a fool's game.
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against taking a chance. As my mother, an avid
lottery player, always says: Somebody's got to win. But when the
odds are 80 million to 1, you don't have to be a mathemetician to
figure out that it won't be you.
</P>
<P>
   Lotteries are a lousy bet. When state lotteries started up, a
lot of people assumed that they would drive the numbers game out of
business. That hasn't happened because organized crime gives
bettors much better odds than the state does. There are plenty of
seasoned gamblers who won't buy a lottery ticket because the odds
are so high. Some gamblers refuse to play the state lottery on
moral/political grounds, because they see it as a regressive tax
that moves money from poor communities, where the lottery is
popular, to richer towns, where it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the Massachusetts Department of Public Health has aired
radio commercials about problemgambling. I've heard two or three of
them and none of them mentions the lottery. In one a man babbles on
about how he has a sure-fire system for winning at the race track.
In another a desperate-sounding woman talks about her husband's
gambling addiction, how he spent the grocery money, how even stole
money from their kid's piggy bank to squander at the track. You
might think horse players were the only people with gambling
problems.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I should note here that I own one-10th of a racehorse,
the fabulous Fly McGrew, whose earnings currently stand at $135,
against expenses of $8,200, and rising daily, unlike my hopes for
him. But that's another story. I may be a fool, squandering my
money on horse feed, but I'm having fun, and even with that
pathetic return on my investment, I'm still doing better than I
would playing the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   I mention Fly only to make the point that I have spent some time
at Suffolk Downs and Rockingham Park. Of course there are
compulsive gamblers at the track, but there are many more people
with gambling problems playing the lottery simply because so many
more people play the lottery than the horses.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery addiction is a serious, growing problem, as a Globe
series on the Massachusetts lottery pointed out last year. Isn't it
a little hypocritical for the state to wring its hands about
problem gambling at the race track in those radio ads while
ignoring the elephant in its own living room?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
