<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY REF STEWART WAGING HIS TOUGHEST FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Stewart has been in tough situations before.
</P>
<P>
   Like Thanksgiving night in 1979 when he came back home to Boston
for the first time as a professional hockey player to play in front
of his mother, father, and friends.
</P>
<P>
   He had a straightforward assignment from his team, the Quebec
Nordiques, who had brought him up from the minors to do a fistic
number against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time the two teams played, Robbie Ftorek (now coach
of the New Jersey Devils) had hit Bobby Schmautz in the throat with
his stick and the Bruins put out the word they were going after
Ftorek the next time they met,'' recalled Stewart. ``(Quebec)
called me up to protect Ftorek. And I was happy to do it. I would
have done anything to come home and play in Boston Garden. It had
always been a dream of mine since I was a little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart remembers walking briskly across the concourse in North
Station and meeting a surprised Bobby Miller, an old friend who was
playing for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing here?'' asked Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to keep you guys off Ftorek,'' said Stewart. ``Tell
(Terry) O'Reilly to be ready to drop the gloves the first time I
come on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly obliged. Stan Jonathan obliged. Al Secord obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart battled the building and survived.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has another battle going, and surviving this one is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had cancer surgery back in June, and they took out 2 feet of
my colon,'' said Stewart, who just finished up his 14th season as a
National Hockey League referee after eight seasons as a player in
the World Hockey Association, the minors, and that NHL cameo.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Stewart is one of the best-liked guys in the hockey world.
Players like him because he is no-nonsense and can't be
intimidated. Coaches and general managers like him because they
know he will not be a homer and will call the game as he sees it,
no matter who's beefing at him or where the game is being played.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he knows, he is going to find out how tough he really is.
He hopes he will be as sturdy as he has been in
non-life-threatening situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this happens to you, your whole perspective changes,''
said Stewart, who's in the midst of ongoing chemotherapy and hopes
to return to officiating in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not angry anymore,'' he said. ``It seems I was angry my
whole life, and I don't know why. Each day I get up and look at my
wife and 5-month-old son (McCauley John Stewart), I am thankful.
Part of my rehabilitation after surgery has been listening to
motivational tapes. I don't need them anymore. I just look into my
son's face, and that's all the motivation to do what I have to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has been a horse when it comes to officating. No one has
called more games than he has, both NHL and American Hockey League,
during the regular season in the past decade. He remembers calling
more games in 1989 than anyone else in hockey _ almost 90 between
the two leagues, when the average is in the area of 60.
</P>
<P>
   Always strong, well-conditioned, and seemingly indestructible,
Stewart missed just six games in 14 seasons. ``I tore my hamstring
and had to sit out for a couple of weeks,'' he said. ``But that was
the only time I missed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart remembers feeling punk for the first time during the
NHL's Olympic break in February. ``My stomach didn't feel good,''
he recalled, ``and then I was watching TV the morning that Katie
Couric's husband died and I said to myself, `Maybe I should have
this checked out.' As it was, this saved me life.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was given a series of tests, and in the beginning, there
didn't seem to be any real problem. Then a colonoscopy turned his
life upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little groggy coming out of the anesthesia, but when I
looked up, I could see the concern on the faces of the doctors,''
said Stewart. ``I told them to give it to me straight. Don't kid a
kidder. They didn't. They told me I was in serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, he had the cancerous section of his colon removed.
``The doctors told me there are four stages and I was about 2
1/2,'' he said. ``I feel very lucky. A little bit longer and I
wouldn't have the chance I have now. And it's a very good chance.
I'm going to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart hopes to be back on skates in three weeks, even though
he still acknowledges being weak on his feet. He doubts he can go
to training camp with the rest of the NHL officials Sept. 10, but
he has his sights set on being ready for the opening games in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to call off the golf tournament my brother Bill and
myself run in memory of my father,'' he said. ``We hated to do it,
but my father always said when he was alive, `If you can't do
something the right way, don't to it at all.' We'll definitely be
back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul and brother Bill, without fanfare, would take the proceeds
from the tourney and purchase sporting equipment for kids
throughout Boston. This year, with some money left over from 1997,
the Stewarts are sponsoring junior golf at Franklin Park and paying
for all the equipment used by the kids in a youth hockey program,
the gear to be cleaned and refurbished by the Riddell Co. of
Somerville.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of nice things have happened,'' said Stewart. ``With the
golf tourney, some of the people told us to keep the checks (for
the tourney slated for Aug. 7), and others said they would send in
a contribution to the Bill Stewart Foundation. But something that
has really hit me is the way so many people have responded just in
the past 24 hours when the news (of the cancer) got out. One of the
first calls I got was from Vancouver from a rookie in the league
last year. I called his first game in the NHL. Now he was telling
me how concerned he was about me. I told him, `Don't worry. I'll be
back. And it won't be any easier for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, battling again, in the face of his greatest
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
