<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US'S ALEXIS CAN BE CALLED FOR TRAVELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ Back in those glory days when you're kicking butt in
high school and college, you just don't see yourself bouncing
around the world. No, no, no. The only thing on your mind is the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Alexis can tell you all about it.
</P>
<P>
   He never saw himself playing in five countries. When he left
Syracuse 12 years ago, he never remotely imagined that one of the
big things on his resume would be his selection as Player of the
Year in Germany's first division. He surely never thought that he
would be spending his 34th birthday (tomorrow) representing the
United States of America in the World Basketball Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea about what was ahead of me,'' he says. ``I just
knew I wanted to play basketball. I didn't know where it was going
to take me.''
</P>
<P>
   It has taken him to teams in Italy, France, Spain, Israel, and
Germany. And now it has taken him to Athens, where he is the oldest
and savviest of the 12 players Rudy Tomjanovich is trying to direct
to the very necessary gold in place of the seven- and eight-figure
NBA stars who opted out of this tournament when the Great Lockout
deteriorated in status from probable to inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   If the sport's elite choose to stay home over a dubious
principle, that is quite all right with Wendell Alexis. He is very
happy to put on the red, white, and blue uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to do something I never thought I'd
have a chance to do,'' says the 6-foot-7-inch forward. ``When I
found out that I was going to be invited to try out, my only
questions were, `When do the tryouts start, and where do I have to
go?'''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis was home in Bridgewater, N.J., when he got a call from
USA Basketball representative Jim Tooley asking him if he'd be
interested in trying out for this team. ``The first talk was of
getting a team together of ex-NBA players (Dominique Wilkins,
etc.),'' Alexis points out. ``Then I heard they were talking about
CBA and European players and I was very happy to get the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to refresh some memories: Wendell Alexis was a very
reliable four-year player for Jim Boeheim back in the early to
mid-'80s. He was one of those guys who just kept getting better,
peaking as a senior when he scored 15 points a game while shooting
54 percent from the floor. He was the team captain and MVP, and he
made the all-tournament team at the Portsmouth Invitational. The
Warriors took him in the third round, and at that point, Phase II
of the Alexis career began. He was the last man cut.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, he would keep trying and trying. He
twice went to camp with the Knicks. He went to camp with the
Pacers. He went to camp with the Clippers. He went to camp with the
76ers. By 1991, he sat himself down and delivered the sad, bad
news, the gist of which was, ``Son, they just don't want you.
Accept the fact that you are a European ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an acceptable life for the right person, and Wendell Alexis
is clearly the right person. ``It's not easy,'' he reports. ``You
come in somewhere alone. You don't know anyone. They always expect
you to carry the ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   You need patience. You need a facility for language. You need a
strong sense of self-worth, because sooner or later, you're going
to hear some ridiculous stuff from people who have no idea what
they're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexis has mastered the system as well as any American ever
has. He is a mature professional, and that is why it came as no
surprise Wednesday that the game against Brazil sort of changed
direction when he entered it. He helped settle down a jumpy
American team, and before the afternoon was over, he had
contributed 13 points (on everything from driving 3-point plays to
soft 3-point shots) and eight rebounds as the US rolled to an 83-59
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy hasn't really set down a role for me,'' Alexis says. ``I
think he just wants me to come off the bench and be consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis is the personification of this European- and CBA-laden
team, which must win the gold in order to save the US from the
aggravation of somehow having to qualify for the Sydney Olympics
two years up the road. ``There is a lot of individual pride here,''
Alexis explains. ``We know we're capable of winning the gold. I
think a lot of guys were taken aback by the reaction back home,
with people thinking the only team capable of doing it was the
Dream Team. A lot of guys wouldn't say so publicly, but they really
were upset. So this is a team that is going to play with a lot of
emotion and extra oomph.''
</P>
<P>
   His many triumphs haven't even made the newspapers back home.
But if the US wins the gold, people will not be able to ignore this
one. He and his teammates will have saved the USA's hide, big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would consider it the highlight of my career,'' Alexis says,
``but it's not going to be the end.'' Of course. The birthday in
question is 34, not 44.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Alexis is proud of his career. ``I've persevered,'' he
says. ``I've stayed determined. It would have been easy for me to
quit and take another job, but I've been able to make a living
doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any team, they've all got stories. But nobody's going to
top his. Nobody on this team has paid more dues than Wendell
Alexis, and nobody deserves a gold medal more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
