<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MILLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLOY IS MAKING A MAJOR IMPACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Uh-oh, thought Patriots safety Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   He had just put a licking on wide receiver Terry Glenn coming
across the middle, and on the next play, he'd done the same to
running back Sedrick Shaw breaking through the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   His blue-shirted mates on defense whooped it up. The fans
ringing the practice field came alive.
</P>
<P>
   And here came the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete came over to me in a hurry,'' Milloy said. ``I thought he
was going to get in my ear and chew me out a little bit about my
hitting. I was ready to plead my case.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to plead.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll came to praise, not upbraid. He wasn't here to give
Milloy a hard time about dumping the team's highest-profile
receiver as he chased a high pass from Drew Bledsoe. He wasn't
about to get on him about belting the guy who is scheduled to line
up as the starting halfback in Sunday's exhibition opener at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought I was coming up to dog him for being too physical,
but it was just the opposite,'' Carroll said. ``I thought that was
a tremendous indication or example of leadership on the field. One
guy with his effort and performance lit up not only our football
team but people watching practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy got them going early in Wednesday's morning session at
Bryant College.
</P>
<P>
   And just think what he might have done if he had been out of the
lineup a week or more.
</P>
<P>
   The strong safety hasn't missed a game with the Patriots and
said he was a little antsy after missing a day and a half of
practice after twisting his ankle Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a competitor, and the way I see it, when I'm sitting on
the sidelines, someone else is moving in on my position,'' Milloy
said. ``I came out here today, my first day back, and I was ready
to go out there and rock-and-roll a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   He rocked and socked.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn came through on an early play, and Bledsoe's pass was up
and the receiver never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't throw that, Drew; don't throw that, Drew,'' said Milloy
as he got back in position for the next play.
</P>
<P>
   The offense then tried a different tack. Shaw carried to the
left side, found a little running room, and Milloy quickly _ and
crunchingly _ took it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young running back with a lot of potential,'' Milloy
said. ``He broke through the hole and he was looking sweet. But in
the NFL, you're not really free untl you cross the goal line. He
was running a little high and I had a chance to make a hit on him,
and that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is his game. Last year Milloy was second on the team in
tackles with 112, behind Ted Johnson. In the postseason, he had 14
more.
</P>
<P>
   He came out of the University of Washington and was third on the
Patriots in tackles with 85 as a rookie in 1996. He started the
final 13 games of the regular season that year and the three
playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, he played three years of baseball, too, and in
1995, he was in the NCAA regionals against the Georgia Tech team of
Red Sox Nomar Garciaparra and Jason Varitek. He was drafted out of
high school and then college in baseball. The Patriots took him in
the second round in 1996, and soon he had established himself in
the secondary _ hitting running backs and receivers rather than
fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hitter,'' Milloy said. ``I love to hit. There's nothing
fancy about my game. I love to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That suits Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just played the plays full speed all out and represented
what he believes about the game,'' the coach said. ``You hit the
crud out of everything you can hit and and give great effort and be
a tough nut.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy is looking forward to hitting someone other than
teammates when the Patriots take on San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   With a full year of defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell's system
behind them and coming off a season in which the defense was
getting better and better as it ended, Milloy sees no reason that
the unit should not start at a high level this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll be flawless,'' he said. ``But we should be
somewhere close.''
</P>
<P>
   High expectations? Sure. Milloy takes the same approach to
training camp. He takes it seriously. He thinks everyone else
should, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is fighting for a position,'' he said. ``I don't care
if it's Drew Bledsoe, Lawyer Milloy, or anyone else. That's the way
they should take this. That's the only way we're going to be a
championship team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
