<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TROPICAL LOOK IS HOT, HOT, HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer's hot look in home gardening would have been
nominated for a Bad Taste Award by most homeowners only a short
time ago. Gardens with tropical foliage plants, unruly vines, and
perennials that are bigger than you are can leave you disoriented.
So does this look really translate into a garden, or is it the set
for a theatrical production of ``Alice in Wonderland Lost in the
Rain Forest''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tropicalismo'' gardening is one term for the sudden revival of
passion for tropical plants that aren't supposed to be grown here.
Others call it ``zonal denial.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``the banana-canna garden'' by Horticulture
magazine's Nan Sinton, who told gardening professionals at the
Perennial Plant Association Symposium in Boston last month that
it's ``the newest, most exciting trend in gardening today.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's just something intrinsically fin de siecle about
cannas and coleus, whose last wave of popularity was a century ago.
Coleus varieties were the big seller this season at Avant Gardens
in North Dartmouth. ``A few years ago nobody would have a coleus in
their garden. They used to be ditzy small plants but now there's a
whole new line available that grows bigger,'' said owner Kathy
Tracey.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly bigger is better. Especially big leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Cannas, big plants with big leaves, are enjoying the biggest
career comeback since John Travolta made ``Pulp Fiction.'' Catalog
companies like White Flower Farm have suddenly found their sales of
cannas far outstripping expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sinton, who is always on the road scoping out other people's
gardens as the director of Horticulture magazine's tours and
educational programs, said she first noticed the style in the
Northwest five years ago, where African banana trees and Tasmanian
tree ferns and ginger lilies were becoming landscape linchpins.
</P>
<P>
   Any zone-conscious local gardener's first response is going to
be, ``Well, you can't do that here!''
</P>
<P>
   But indeed you can, says Kevin Doyle, a designer whose Dover,
Mass. garden looks as lush as a Hawaiian hideaway, with a back-yard
terrace bedecked with pots of variegated oleander, black sugar
cane, tropical vines, and 8-foot palms.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle uses his new greenhouse to winter these over. But he also
grows tropical-looking plants that are hardy here, such as aralia,
a tree with thorns so sharp it's called ``the devil's walking
stick,'' and big-leafed magnolias with 16-inch flowers. Some other
tropical plants, such as cannas, dahlias, banana plants, daturas,
and brugmansias can be cut to the ground, dug up, and wintered over
in the basement, he said. Others that require lower light levels,
such as tropical hibiscus, double as houseplants in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   So, with a lot of effort, you can do it here. But why would you
want to? Doesn't a tropical look clash with the whole English
Colonial aesthetic of much of our New England landscape and
architecture?
</P>
<P>
   ``You would probably feel more comfortable designing with more
traditional plants with a Colonial style home, but if you have a
modern architectural home, bolder color and foliage go well,'' said
Tracey.
</P>
<P>
   One motivation seems to be consumer boredom with the status quo.
``For a long time everything was pink and blue and white and very
sedate,'' said Tracey. ``Last year we saw orange becoming more
popular. It's a reaction. You couldn't sell orange before.''
</P>
<P>
   If the term ``tropicalismo'' gardening sounds a bit like a
guerrilla assault, the term does challenge the traditional northern
European plant lists and design concepts that have guided the
flower gardening resurgence in New England. Tropical foliage plants
from equatorial Asia, South America, and Africa bring aesthetic
diversity to gardens while throwing out the old rule book. They are
to gardens what curry is to cuisine, what world music is to pop.
</P>
<P>
   Horticulture magazine editor Tom Cooper embraces the
vegetational giganticism of a 10-foot Canna musafolia in his
Watertown, Mass. garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of English-style borders tend to be finished by the
middle of the summer,'' Cooper explained. ``With tropical plants,
people are making gardens that are exciting throughout the summer.
It's a trend that is hitting throughout the US wherever there's
enough heat and enough creative gardeners who are becoming more
confident and less bound by the notion of making little
Sissinghursts,'' Cooper said, citing a much-visited British garden.
``England doesn't get enough heat to make a lot of these things
splashy. We do have hot summers here, so why not grow plants that
love that?''
</P>
<P>
   Shade gardeners in particular are taking notice because many
tropical plants are foliage plants that are native to forest
understories.
</P>
<P>
   Though a walk through the Doyle garden suggests an instant trip
to an exotic resort, the designer says he's motivated by his
eclectic love of plants, not a need to disguise his New England
locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 2,000 types of plant in this garden, and only
about 25 are tropical,'' Doyle said. But the addition of even a few
well-chosen tropicals has a strange way of transforming everything
around them.
</P>
<P>
   The pesty pokeweed in Doyle's front yard looks mysteriously
gothic growing next to the over-the-top white trumpets of a
tropical datura. A ho-hum apple tree invites a second look when
Spanish moss dangles from a branch. The ruby-red leaves of a tender
banana tree planted in Doyle's perennial border highlight day
lilies and phlox like a flashlight in a darkened room. When
captured by unexpected forms, the eye looks anew even on familiar
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Though Doyle maintains you don't need a greenhouse to have a
garden with a tropical flavor, winter is the bete noir for this
kind of gardening. At the end of each year, Doyle finds himself the
recipient of gift plants from people who have enjoyed them all
summer and have no idea what to do with them once Jack Frost
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   One anonymous would-be gardener even left two palms and several
poinsettias at the foot of Doyle's driveway one fall, like a litter
of abandoned kittens. Doyle still has the palms.
</P>
<P>
   People who don't want to bother wintering over tropicals can buy
new ones in the spring, giving the garden a different look each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy is to find hardy analogs, frost-proof plants
that look tropical. There are many of these.
</P>
<P>
   Since we can't winter over Portuguese Senna didymobotrya,
Westwood, Mass. designer Gary Koller suggests the northern
look-alike relative, Senna marilandica. Hibiscus moscheutos has
both the big leaves and big flowers of its tropical cousin, yet is
native to New England. Petasites Japonica is a giant-leaved
substitute for gunnera.
</P>
<P>
   Other hardy plants that look tropical, according to Koller,
include old-fashioned orange trumpet vine and kiwi vine (you might
even get some fruit). Persicaria polymorpha, now becoming a hot
perennial, is a well-behaved Japanese knotweed with a long
flowering period. Sinton has trimmed the lower branches from
cut-leaf staghorn sumac in her South Shore garden to make it
resemble a New Zealand tree fern.
</P>
<P>
   Houseplants are another resource. Koller suggests integrating
them in the garden during the summer instead of parking them in an
out-of-the-way corner of the yard, as is often done.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are not going to rip out their old rose garden and
fill it with cannas and other flashy tropicals, as English
gardening guru Christopher Lloyd did a few years ago, to the shock
of the horticultural establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But there are more bright-orange potted cannas perched on Boston
terraces this summer. And fewer garden lovers who wince when they
see them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCES FOR TROPICAL PLANTS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garden centers, and even supermarkets, are good sources for
potted exotics, which are often sold as houseplants. Here are some
other sources for tropical plants and information about them:
</P>
<P>
   _Avant Gardens, 710 High Hill Road, North Dartmouth, MA 02748;
508-998-8819.
</P>
<P>
   _The Banana Tree, 715 North Hampton St., Easton, PA 18042;
610-253-9589. Catalog $3. Rare tropical seeds and bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   _Blue Meadow Farm, 184 Meadow Road, Montague Center, MA 01351;
413-367-2394. Catalog $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   _Dutch Gardens, Box 200, Adelphia, NJ 07710-0200; 800-818-3861.
Free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   _``Exotic Gardening in Cool Climates'' (1993) by Myles Challis,
Trafalgar Square, North Pomfret, VT 05053.
</P>
<P>
   _Kartuz Greenhouses, 1408 Sunset Drive, Vista, CA 92083-6531;
760-941-3613. Catalog $2.
</P>
<P>
   _Logee's Greenhouses, 141 North St., Danielson, CT 06239;
860-774-8038. Catalog $3.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Subtropical Garden'' (1996) by Jacqueline Walker, Timber
Press.
</P>
<P>
   _Gossler Farms Nursery, 1200 Weaver Road, Springfield, OR
97478-9691; 541-746-3922. Catalog $2. Source for Aralia elata
Variegata.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
