<SLUG> BC-CAPE-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELIST JACQUELYN MITCHARD FINDS A SECOND HOME ON THE CAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Wis.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARWICH, Mass. _ It took novelist Jacquelyn Mitchard much longer
than she expected to find a vacation home on Cape Cod: three days.
She saw the house she wanted on the evening of the third day of
hunting and bought it the following morning.
</P>
<P>
   She likes making quick decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Such decisiveness served her well after the sudden death of her
husband in 1993. She knew she couldn't support her family of three
young boys and a stepdaughter on a freelancer's income. So she
picked herself up, headed to an artists colony and wrote the first
100 pages of ``Deep End of the Ocean'' _ her best-selling 1996
novel and Oprah Winfrey's first selection for her television book
club.
</P>
<P>
   She then decided to adopt a daughter from an agency in Texas.
Bought the house on the Cape. Is moving to a larger, six-bedroom
home in Madison, Wis., next month after her stepdaughter's wedding.
Awaits the movie premiere of ``Deep End'' in September. And has
just completed a 17-city book tour for her latest novel, ``The Most
Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as if her life wasn't busy enough, she met a man on March
13 and married him on May 13. He's 32. She's 45.
</P>
<P>
   Some may call her impulsive. But she says she's just a ``T-type
personality.'' A thrill seeker. And thrill seekers, she says, fear
tedium and boredom. But they do not fear taking risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a risk taker,'' says Mitchard, a Susan
Sarandon look-alike with more flesh on her bones. ``You can't be 40
years old and become a first-time novelist or single mother who
adopts a baby if you aren't a risk taker. My husband's early death
reinforced my beliefs _ act now, not tomorrow. And I understand
that by taking risks there's a 50/50 chance that things won't work
out. But I don't ever again want to make a decision based on fear.
An excess of caution is what douses most people's dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she bought the three-bedroom house on a cul-de-sac here
with great alacrity, she admits she did entertain the negatives.
Was it too far from Madison? Too expensive to fly her large family
to the East Coast several times a year?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to buy a second home, it was going to be on the
Cape or nowhere,'' says Mitchard, talking to a visitor in the
dining area of her kitchen. ``This house was the first splurge
after my book became so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard received $500,000 for a two-book contract with Viking
based on the 100 pages she wrote while at Ragdale, the artists
colony in Lake Forest, Ill. After its release, ``Deep End'' sat
comfortably at the top of the New York Times bestseller list for
seven months. Close to 3 million copies have been sold to date. She
got another $300,000 for the movie rights _ a film that stars
Michelle Pfeiffer, Whoopi Goldberg, and Treat Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being a million-dollar jewel on the water, however, the
Cape house is a modest, compact home that Mitchard has made
virtually childproof. The kitchen/dining room and the living room
comprise the first floor _ hardwood floors, unadorned furniture, no
frills or knickknacks. There are three small bedrooms upstairs and
the boys bunk in the basement recreation room.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the interview, Mitchard's 23-year-old
stepdaughter was back home preparing for her July wedding and her
oldest boy, Robert, 14, was at camp. So that left Martin, 9, and
Dan, 11, who flew in and out of the front door and straddled the
railing of the small deck outside until Mitchard's new husband,
Chris Sornberger, took them on an adventure to the local hardware
store. Francie, 2, was being cared for by two ``assistants,'' Pam
and Kerry, who take care of the house and the kids both here and in
Madison. There are no television sets in this house so the children
rely on board games, going to the beach, reading, listening to
music, and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Cape Cod for several reasons,'' says Mitchard. ``My
best friend, who I met five years ago at Ragdale, lives in Chatham.
I chose this house because I'm only seven minutes away from Ann
(Dickinson Le Claire). I think the Cape is the most beautiful place
on earth _ I spent a summer working in Provincetown after
graduation and I loved it here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Cape, she sets aside time to write, usually in the
afternoons, at a small desk in her bedroom; back home she writes in
her office from 9 to 5. After her stepdaughter's wedding, she'll
return to the Cape for a few weeks and then come back in the fall,
after Christmas, and again in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Her children, Mitchard says, were surprised at how swiftly she
married Sornberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really knocked my children off their pins. My older boy's
comment was, `Oh sure, and hell freezes over next week.' But I
spent five years as a widow. I served my time. I'd come close to
falling in love but something always stopped me, perhaps it was my
agent's advice to always settle for more,'' says Mitchard. ``I was
certain about Chris in about one day.''
</P>
<P>
   A carpenter and landscaper, Sornberger had come to her Wisconsin
home to lay tile in a bathroom. They ended the day by talking about
books. After a week, they knew they were attracted to each other.
Two weeks after they met they knew it was more than that. Their
experience mirrors a relationship in Mitchard's new book, where a
younger, blue-collar worker revitalizes an older woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a spiritual person but it wasn't lost on me that what
was happening to me was very similar to what I wrote about in my
book,'' says Mitchard. ``Chris is the most peaceful human being
I've ever met. He balances me. He has such character and patience.
He approaches life as an art form _ every day is different. Oh my,
I'm sounding like a newlywed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard still writes a column once a week for the Milwaukee
Journal Sentinel &UR;  &LR; but has cut back on her speaking engagements,
``unless they are ridiculously lucrative,'' and essays and features
for magazines. She remains a contributing editor to Ladies Home
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't do the column for money,'' says Mitchard,
whose columns were syndicated 18 months ago and now appear in more
than 200 papers. ``The emotional demands of fiction are so great
that writing the column is like mind oxygen. Plus I don't want to
forget where I came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchard grew up in Chicago, the daughter of a plumber. She
graduated from the University of Illinois and became a newspaper
reporter for several weeklies before working for the Capital Times
in Madison. From 1984 to 1988 she was a metro reporter for the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel. From 1989 to 1993 she was the speech
writer for Donna Shalala, chancellor of the University of Wisconsin
before becoming US secretary of Health and Human Services. Her
husband, Dan Allegretti, was editorial page editor of the Madison
paper before his death from colon cancer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that she was encouraged by writer and friend Jane
Hamilton to apply for a writing fellowship at Ragdale. That is
where she began ``Deep End.'' Both that book and her most recent
novel took shape from dreams _ the first was about a kidnapped
child and the second about a young girl who falls in love with an
older man who is in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Her next book? Either ``a contemporary story about the
conversion from cynicism'' or one that ``is almost like a ghost
story.'' These days, the downside to her busy life is that she does
not have enough time for her close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends say I married Chris because I didn't have time to date
him,'' says Mitchard with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   But she has made time to come to the Cape, to her ``tribal
house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to rent it out,'' says Mitchard. ``I want it to
be here for family and friends and their children. I want everyone
to come here and relax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
