<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2TAKE     07-30 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-SECRET-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITA BROCK LEARNS THE SECRET EVERYONE KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Everyone, it seems, knew the secret except
the little girl. The family in Japan knew. The family in
Mississippi knew. Even the family in Puerto Rico knew. In fact, so
many people knew that it really wasn't a secret at all. Except to
the little girl.
</P>
<P>
   But the little girl grew up, eventually becoming a highly
regarded feminist and theologian who now, at the age of 48, runs
the Bunting Institute at Radcliffe College. She's been a high
school cheerleader and prom queen, earned a PhD, served as a
college instructor, gotten married and divorced, and landed here as
the director of a prestigious think tank for women. But probably
nothing Rita Nakashima Brock has done has changed her self-image as
much as the document she found in a small metal box in a small
bedroom of a small house in Barstow, Calif., 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God!'' Brock remembers saying loudly as she stared at
the paper that contained the secret everyone else knew. ``I'm
adopted!''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, as Brock struggles to write her memoir of that day and
what she calls the ``massive mystery'' that it revealed, she still
seems startled by the discovery that her mother's husband, the man
who had taught her how to tune the engine of a car and had taken
her fishing and camping so many times, was not her biological
father. When former US Army enlisted man Roy Grady Brock had passed
away seven years earlier, not even Rita Brock's Japanese mother,
Ayako, had whispered the secret. ``I thought my father had died
that day,'' Rita Brock recalls. ``No one at his funeral said
anything to me that would have led me to believe he wasn't my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   But when she was dying &UR;  &LR; of cancer in 1983, Ayako Brock clearly
had a change of heart. Inside the metal box of documents she knew
that her three children would open shortly after her death, she
placed an official document headed FAMILY REGISTER. And indeed, on
the day before her mother's funeral, the 33-year-old Rita Brock
found herself staring at the typewritten piece of paper. Translated
into English from Japanese and dated July 3, 1954, it named her as
the person ``to become an adopted child of an American citizen
named Roy Grady Brock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're what?'' Rita's younger sister, Jo Ann, asked her on
that day in Barstow as they sat on their mother's bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm adopted!'' Rita Brock repeated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Brock sits in her large corner office at Radcliffe on an
early summer afternoon today, there is still a tremor of
astonishment in her voice. In a heartbeat, she recalls of that late
summer's day in 1983, she had been redefined. But as whom? There
were the practical implications of the discovery, of course,
matters such as her medical history. ``But mostly I was just very
curious,'' she recalls. ``Did my mother not know she was pregnant
when my father left her? And then maybe she couldn't find him? Or
did he know about me and disown me? Had he been disgraced? Had
there been a falling out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, it was like my mother wasn't who I'd thought she was. I
mean, my image of my mother was as a rather conventional Japanese
housewife. It turns out she had this whole other life she didn't
tell us about.''
</P>
<P>
   And what to think about Roy Brock? True, father and daughter had
had a parting of the ways when the latter was in college, even
coming to blows at one point. (``I won,'' Rita Brock points out
impassively.) But the fight was a typical coming-of-age
confrontation, inflamed by the times: Offspring of a World War II
POW and Vietnam veteran becomes involved in the antiwar movement.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brock clearly has a great deal of respect for her
adoptive father's accomplishments and for what he gave her. ``He
invested a lot in me,'' she says. ``He grew up in rural Mississippi
and had an eighth-grade formal education. He joined the Army,
fought in World War II, was in a Nazi POW camp, joined the Army
again, went to Japan, married my mother, and did a good job raising
me.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, she still refers to Roy Brock as ``My father.''
</P>
<P>
   But now there was another father to be found. Adopted kids often
search for years for their biological parents, chasing down false
leads and wandering through mazes that lead only to dead ends. But
a few hours after her mother's funeral, Brock not only got her
first clue to her father's identity, but also an indication of the
fact she was clearly among the last to know the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a picnic table in her mother's back yard, chatting
with an ex-GI and his Japanese wife who were old family friends,
Brock mentioned her discovery. Almost as casually, the couple
explained that they'd always known she was adopted. They told her
that her father was Puerto Rican, but that they didn't know much
more. The only thing that seemed to surprise them was the fact Rita
Brock herself hadn't known about her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean your mother didn't tell you?'' they asked
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now she had a new nationality _ ``I always knew I wasn't half
white,'' she muses today _ but not a name to go with it. That came
within weeks, when her sister found among their mother's belongings
what appeared to be a Japanese birth certificate on which three
words were written in English characters: Clemente Morales Torres.
More digging produced an address book with an entry for a Maria and
Miguel Torres in Dorado Beach, Puerto Rico. Brock wrote to the
address, but her letter was returned unopened. ``I thought my
father had died or didn't want to see me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
