<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Keizo Obuchi is formally installed as
Japan's 23d prime minister in the postwar period and names his
Cabinet, which largely reflects the loyalty he owes to various
factions within the governing Liberal Democratic Party that insured
his election to the country's top political job. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MURDER (London) _ The conviction against Derek Bentley,
a 19-year-old hanged for the murder of a police officer in 1952, is
overturned. Bentley was the mildly retarded man who allegedly told
a friend with a gun to ``let him have it'' when the two were
confronted by police as they broke into a candy factory. The friend
killed the officer, but was only 16 and got 10 years in prison;
Bentley was hanged. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM-DRUG (Undated) _ A drug widely available in Europe
that may reduce the urge to drink is being tested in the United
States, which has 13.7 million alcoholics. Its French maker hopes
to have it on the American market in 2000. Many experts on
dependency say the drug _ acamprosate, which would be sold in the
United States as Campral _ is badly needed. Only two other
medications can treat alcoholism, and both can have unpleasant or
potentially dangerous side effects. But others in the medical
community argue that alcoholics should be treated with counseling
alone.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-COSTS (Undated) _ Labor costs for businesses registered a
restrained increase in the second quarter, as both wage and benefit
costs crept higher. The employment cost index, the broadest measure
of wage, salary and benefit costs, rose a seasonally adjusted 0.9
percent, faster than the first quarter's increase of 0.7 percent.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN-CHARTER (Undated) _ The Microsoft billionaire Paul Allen
purchases privately held Charter Communications in a transaction
valued at $4.5 billion, becoming a major player in the cable
business in Los Angeles and moving closer to his goal of building a
high-tech cable empire. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
