<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES-     07-30 0276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Turning reform into abuse
 &HT;    (A bonus Short Takes column for use at will.)
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two U.S. Capitol cops are gunned down by a man so deranged that
it's considered in doubtful taste to mention gun control. The
responsibility for mental health care rested with the states until
the mid-1970s, when the states figured a way to get out from under.
This is one reason we have a federal government, to do things
correctly when states can't be bothered.
</P>
<P>
   The opening wedge was benign. I remember it well. The idea was
to protect the civil and legal rights of the mentally ill. Mental
health treatment should not be used as a form of law enforcement
and the mangling of sick people's rights. Sounded good to me. I
commissioned a depthy newspaper series on the legal rights of the
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   State governments were overjoyed. Return mental health care to
the local community, where it belonged, went the cry. Great idea
except it didn't happen. States closed down a raft of mental
hospitals, kicked a lot of mental patients out on the streets and
turned them into the homeless. Then they cut their state budgets.
The previously flawed system was replaced with precisely nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions caught up with us the other day at the Capitol
when two cops were gunned down by an abuse posing as a reform. A
grateful Congress is naming a door for the cops.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
