<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0405 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYPSY-SWEETHEARTS-SPI     07-30 2059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYPSY-SWEETHEARTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEETHEART SCAMS' FLEECE THE ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some lonely old men in the Tacoma, Wash., area, what seemed
like true May-December love has turned to heartbreak, leaving them
financially drained and alienated from their families.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a Bellevue, Wash., dentist is fighting to overturn
his late father's will, which left an estate worth up to three
quarters of a million dollars to a bride in Lakewood, Wash.,
roughly 50 years his junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a very generous man who was taken advantage
of,'' said Dr. Lester Peterson. ``It was so well-orchestrated, this
whole scenario. When I look back on it, it was so smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a Kentucky woman named Suzanne Cheaney says her
lovestruck elderly father, who lives in Lakewood, has been bled
financially by a family. She's furious at the lack of police
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they sit back and watch all these old people go down
the tube and not do anything?'' Cheaney said. ``As far as I'm
concerned, it's just as bad as child abuse, because these men
become like children.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say they know of about half a dozen
sweetheart scams in the Tacoma-Lakewood area in the past few years.
In each case, the elderly person was involved with a member or
members of an extended Gypsy family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been aware of those for a long time,'' said Pierce
County, Wash. Deputy Prosecutor Tom Moore, ``but we can't prove
anything because the victims willingly go along. It's been a
problem in my office for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee Police Lt. Dennis Marlock, who founded an
international group called Professionals Against Confidence Crime,
said no one knows the extent of these crimes nationally.
</P>
<P>
   However, news reports on con games, especially those perpetrated
by families of Gypsies, have earned national headlines in recent
years and been featured on TV newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetheart scams _ typically nonviolent, predatory crimes _
often go unreported because of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll do what they do very quietly, very methodically, and
they'll make a lot of money in the process,'' Marlock said.
``Unless you look for it, you're not going to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle's King County, officials say most allegations of
financial elder abuse involve relatives or neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the Tacoma-Lakewood area, sweetheart scams involving
Gypsies ``just has not been something that we've seen a lot of in
King County,'' said Patrick Sainsbury, chief deputy prosecuting
attorney in the fraud division.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police detective John Lewitt, who has investigated
fortune-telling scams, noted that elder scams are an
equal-opportunity crime. ``There's scams going on by other people,
not just the Gypsies,'' he said. ``It's unbelievable to me, there's
just so much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Lester Peterson, the Bellevue dentist, he and his
half-sister, Betty Iannicelli, have filed a petition in Thurston
County Superior Court to nullify the latest in a string of wills
made by their father, Clarence L. Peterson, who died last October
at age 76.
</P>
<P>
   They also are trying to overturn their father's 1995 marriage to
a young woman named Victoria Steve, saying it was a sham union she
entered into as part of a fraudulent scheme, according to court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said his father's troubles began six months after his
first wife died of cancer in 1989, leaving him lonely and
distraught.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father mentioned that he'd met somebody,'' he said, ``but
he was really unspecific about who this somebody was.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition identifies this new friend as Lisa Steve, a woman
about 40 years younger than Clarence Petersen. At one point in the
relationship, according to the petition, she stood to inherit
$100,000 from him. However, Lester Peterson's attorney said the
elder Peterson later dropped her from his will.
</P>
<P>
   After that relationship soured in 1993, the petition says, Lisa
Steve passed the elderly man on to her niece, Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Peterson says his father, who lived in Olympia, Wash.,
met Lisa at a shop or restaurant in Lakewood. Later, Peterson says,
his father moved to an apartment in Lakewood to be closer to
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   His father's final will, executed in August 1996 with a February
1997 codicil, left his Olympia home to his son William. But most of
the remainder of the estate _ which Lester Peterson values at
$500,000 to $750,000 _ was earmarked for Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   The court petition says Victoria Steve was about 25 at the time
of the marriage, never spent a night with her elderly husband and
continued to live with her parents in Lakewood.
</P>
<P>
   It also alleges that Victoria and some of her relatives
fraudulently claimed to have cancer, then persuaded Clarence
Peterson to give each of them $10,000 for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And it claims they bought several cars with the elderly man's
money, then sold them and kept the cash.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Steve Peterson's lawyer, Dale B. Sawyer of Federal Way,
Wash., wants the petition dismissed on grounds the filing came
after the four-month statute of limitations for probate challenges.
His motion is scheduled for hearing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer declined to discuss the particulars in the petition but
said, ``My client's position is there was no fraud, that it was a
valid and good marriage that was consummated.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Victoria Steve Peterson would speak with a reporter, he
said, ``I doubt she wants to be bugged at this point. Her life's
been made unpleasant enough by their inaccurate allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Lisa Steve for comment were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The petition identifies Victoria Steve Peterson _ ``alias
Samantha Perry and Anne West''_ and Lisa Steve as members of the
Steve Gypsy family in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   The petition also notes that some of those family members are
awaiting trial in Pierce County on charges of running an organized
welfare-fraud ring. Lisa Steve and Victoria Steve Peterson were not
among those charged, and Sawyer said his client, Victoria, is being
tarred by guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Peterson said that after his father died, he and other
family members paid for a private autopsy because they suspected
foul play might have been involved in his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion of the pathology report was he had died of a
heart attack,'' Peterson said, adding that indications of
Alzheimer's disease also were found.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations in the Clarence Peterson case have similarities
to other cases familiar to law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Moore, the Pierce County deputy prosecutor, said police
often are reluctant to pursue cases involving Gypsy suspects
because the cases are time-consuming. There's often a convoluted
paper trail and many of the suspects have multiple aliases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to pin these people down,'' he said, adding
that police tend to get discouraged after handling one or two cases
and say, ``I don't do them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Rob Floberg, of the Lakewood branch of the Pierce
County Sheriff's Department, said suspects often have a keen sense
of the limits of the law and can afford talented attorneys who can
easily outclass overworked prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any person with money can take a criminal case and stretch it
out to where it's unbearable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Floberg rationalizes that in some cases, the elderly victims are
at least getting some attention and companionship.
</P>
<P>
   He said one 84-year-old man, now bedridden and hooked up to
oxygen and a urinary catheter, had been taking his Gypsy sweetheart
out to dinner three times a week and paying her about $100 a shot
for her time. He said the man also paid for her sports car and cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he added, when the old man fell one day, his
Gypsy girlfriend helped him to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got no relatives _ nothing,'' the detective said.
</P>
<P>
   The man is now being looked after by caregivers from the
Catholic church, which will inherit his house when he dies. When
Floberg and a newspaper reporter visited him recently, the old man
said his girlfriend is now out of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dropped her about six months ago,'' he said weakly.
</P>
<P>
   But some old men cling to the relationships despite warnings
from relatives and police. That's the case with 88-year-old
Theodore Newell of Lakewood.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, Newell's daughter, Suzanne Cheaney, flew from
her home in Louisville, Ky., in hope of ending Newell's
relationship with a local Gypsy family. She and her sister, Judith
Conway of Portland, Ore., have stuck a For Sale sign on his home,
which they legally own. They hope to persuade him to move out of
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney said her father was first approached by a young woman
named Lisa Marie Stevens at a local supermarket around Thanksgiving
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy talks to everybody, like a lot of old people do,'' she
said. ``They were talking about turkeys, and one thing led to
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney said she and her family tried to warn Newell away from
his new friend. But she said her father, a retired teacher,
replied, ``She doesn't know how to read and write and I'm going to
teach her.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, 1996, Newell married Lisa Marie Stevens in Washoe
County, Nev. Four months later, at the urging of his daughters, he
filed a petition in Pierce County Superior Court asking to have the
marriage declared invalid. The petition said Newell was
fraudulently induced to marry Lisa Marie Stevens and that the
couple had never lived together.
</P>
<P>
   Newell's attorney, Gary Wallis, says he told the court in oral
arguments that Lisa Marie had drained Newell financially. He says
he never had an exact accounting but he believes Newell's loss
exceeded $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wallis also says he told the court that Lisa Marie ``had no
intention of consumating the marriage and basically married him to
take advantage of an old man financially.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 28, 1997, the court overturned the marriage in a default
judgment. The court said Lisa Marie had committed fraud against
Newell's personal property and in inducing him to marry her.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Marie was not present at the 10-minute proceeding. Earlier,
she had filed a handwritten response in which she denied everything
in the petition _ including matters of fact, such as names,
addresses, date of marriage and the lack of dependent children in
the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Her handwritten note said, ``I dont want a Divorce. I am very
much in love with my husband and I feel I need him very much, so
for my sake (and) his dont grant this decree. Reason for this
request is We have changed our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Newell's family told police that Lisa Marie had claimed to have
ovarian cancer and said the only doctor who could treat her was in
Las Vegas. Newell paid for air fare to Las Vegas, plus food and
hotel charges, for Lisa Marie and four others, according to a
police report based on conversations with Newell and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney said her father's new friends also took out a
half-million-dollar insurance policy on his life, but the paperwork
was returned, she said, because it ``wasn't up to snuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month Cheaney and her sister secured a new, unlisted
phone number for their father, but they still worry that he'll be
talked into giving it out, as he has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Newell says he hasn't seen his Gypsy friends lately and doesn't
know where they are.
</P>
<P>
   With his two dogs nestled by his side, the old man vowed
recently that he was through with Lisa Marie and her family,
especially since his credit card bill for June _ a year after the
marriage was overturned _ showed the unauthorized purchase of six
airline tickets, including one in the name of Lisa Newell.
</P>
<P>
   Conway is dubious that her father will make a complete split
from the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really believes that he's in love with this girl,'' she
said. ``Every time we say anything about her, he protects her. When
we were (visiting him), he got real upset. He said he was tired of
us snooping into his business. We gave him an ultimatum _ the
Gypsies or us.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking slowly and heavily, Newell said he isn't sure anymore
what to think about Lisa Marie and her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they're friends or enemies,'' he said
gloomily. ``Sometimes I wonder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
