<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GRAVE-OLSEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF GYPSIES, SCAMS AND DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rigor mortis had already set in when 83-year-old Hope Victoria
Beesley was found dead in her bed, apparently of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The irascible San Francisco dowager looked both eerie and
pathetic _ eyes open, scalp naked without its wig, arm pointed
defiantly toward the ceiling in a clenched-fist salute.
</P>
<P>
   Her death left a number of loose ends _ one being private eye
Fay Faron of the Rat Dog Dick Detective Agency.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Beesley's attorney had hired Faron to trace a
handyman named Danny Tene, who abruptly disappeared after allegedly
sweet-talking his way into co-ownership of Beesley's
half-million-dollar home.
</P>
<P>
   With Beesley dead, the case was moot. But Faron, nicknamed ``Rat
Dog'' for her persistence as an investigator, couldn't stop
wondering ... Who was this Danny Tene?
</P>
<P>
   Thus began Faron's five-year quest to halt a byzantine series of
alleged ``sweetheart scams'' against the elderly _ an old game that
may have taken a murderous twist within one Gypsy family suspected
of poisoning its ``clients.''
</P>
<P>
   While Faron was tailing suspects in her neon-green junker called
the Frog Prince, crime journalist Jack Olsen was tailing her. The
Bainbridge Island writer, an Edgar Award-winner, knew he had a
great story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw right away,'' said Olsen, 73, words spilling out
rapid-fire in his enthusiasm. ``The combination of Gypsies and Rat
Dog _ holy moley! My kid could have written it.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is detailed in Olsen's newest true-crime saga,
``Hastened to the Grave: The Gypsy Murder Investigation'' (St.
Martin's Press, 276 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Tene and others were suspected of cozying up to elderly people
and bleeding them dry financially. In some cases their deaths may
have been hastened by sprinkling their food with the heart medicine
digitalis, which can be fatal in high doses, producing what appears
to be a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust cleared, the bodies of four alleged victims had
been exhumed and tested for traces of digitalis. Beesley's remains
were not tested, however. She had already been cremated, with the
ashes and bone fragments scattered at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Last November four suspects were indicted on charges of
conspiracy to commit murder. Danny Tene (pronounced ``TEE-ney'')
faced lesser charges of grand theft and stealing from a dependent
adult.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen says most of the suspects, who are awaiting trial, are
relatives of the Tene Bimbo family featured in Peter Maas' 1975
book, ``King of the Gypsies.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen's book grew out of a Vanity Fair story that ran in May.
The article was greeted by protesters outside Vanity Fair's New
York office, who distributed fliers headlined: ``Vanity Fair! Stop
`Gypsy' bashing!!!'' Over a photo of Gypsies in a Nazi
concentration camp were the boldfaced words, ``We will not be
gassed again!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Auntie's bookstore in Spokane hired security
last month after being warned that a prominent local Gypsy planned
to attend Olsen's book signing and be ``in his face.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Olsen defused the protest by reading passages
detailing the Gypsies' long history of persecution. According to a
newspaper account, it was enough to wring tears from his would-be
antagonist. Olsen said they later had a few friendly drinks
together.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, a New York Times review of his book
accuses Olsen of too much ethnic sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly reminded that Gypsies are an oppressed
people,'' wrote critic Judith Newman. ``Olsen sometimes feels
compelled to equivocate by making politically correct excuses for
their behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen's book describes Gypsies, or Rom, as descendants of a
nomadic people in the Punjab region of India who left their
homeland around 1,000 A.D. and faced discrimination and cruelty
wherever they went.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen has been informed that Gypsies unhappy with the book have
placed a curse, or ramya, on him. He laughs it off. ``I do know
that I bought a lottery ticket and didn't win, so it's working
already,'' he said. ``If you take these things seriously, you'll
never get any work done.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen may chortle about the curse, but he's dead serious about
the skulduggery detailed in ``Hastened to the Grave.'' No one could
dream up a case this complex and bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the least imagination of anybody I've ever met,'' Olsen
said. ``That's why I write non-fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero is Faron, a sweet-but-spunky private eye whose previous
careers include driving an ice-cream truck, filming a travelogue on
the River Kwai and selling vacuum cleaners in a part of Appalachia
without electrical power.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's by far the most fascinating character I've ever written
about _ bar none,'' said Olsen. ``She's also just about the most
noble person I've ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   Faron, 49, who donated five years of unpaid labor to the case,
said she was motivated by a desire for justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elders have been discovered as the perfect victims,'' said
Faron, who flew to Seattle recently to discuss the a local TV
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're piggy banks walking around waiting to be smashed.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Faron founded a non-profit advocacy group called
ElderAngels in an effort to prevent such scams. She said Olsen's
book has given her the clout to lobby for legal change and has
alerted the public to similar cons around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's important,'' Faron said, ``is we're hearing
from people all over the United States. The suspects are different
from here but the M.O. is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the elderly are prey to all kinds of cons, the
sweetheart scam is especially cruel and lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sweetheart scam is the lottery,'' Faron said. ``When you
do a sweetheart scam, you can get half a million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Hastened to the Grave'' spotlights a case involving one
family, it also suggests there's a well-entrenched criminal
subculture within the Gypsy community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a Gypsy mafia and it's all over the country and it's
just as together as the Italian Mafia ever was,'' Olsen said.
``They have their own territories, just like the Mafia. They have
safe houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen's comment is seconded by Lt. Dennis Marlock of the
Milwaukee Police Department, who founded an international group
called Professionals Against Confidence Crime. Marlock, who has
worked with the Gypsy community for 30 years, is author of a 1994
book, ``License to Steal: The Traveling Con Artist'' (Paladin
Press, 403 pages, $30).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's organized crime _ bottom line,'' Marlock said, adding
that most of the crimes are non-violent. ``It's a
multibillion-dollar enterprise. They're so cocky. For so many years
they have gone unchallenged and there's no serious law-enforcement
attempt to stop them from doing what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlock noted that there are many honest Romani people who don't
have ties with the criminal subculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken it to the Sicilian Mafia in the sense that all Mafia
members are Sicilian, but not all Sicilians are criminals,''
Marlock said. ``It's identical with the Gypsies.''
</P>
<P>
   Olsen said San Francisco police ignored evidence and dragged
their feet on the case detailed in his book, resulting in
interdepartmental charges. Given the alleged missteps by police,
Olsen said, ``I don't think the case is going to be won. It's
probably going to die on a technicality.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the elderly are sitting ducks for financial schemers
of all stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A doddering 90-year-old man is every bit as vulnerable as a
5-year-old child,'' Olsen said. ``The only difference is the
90-year-old man has an estate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
