r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THING-SPI &LR;      07-30 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVERY LITTLE THING' IS A BIT LIKE WATCHING GRASS GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Every Little Thing,'' the new film by noted French
documentarian Nicolas Philibert (``In the Land of the Deaf''), is
set in La Borde, a stunning chateau in the Loire Valley that was
converted into a minimum security mental institution back in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   His camera is a roving fly-on-the-wall as the staff and inmates
of the institution go through a laborious rehearsal process and
finally perform their annual musical revue for 1995, a performance
of Witold Gombrowicz' ``Operetta.''
</P>
<P>
   If the viewer is very, very patient, the film modestly pays off
by ultimately communicating some of the sense of pride and
self-worth the patients get from having a focus, and engaging in a
creative act. We also gradually feel some of the sense of community
both the patients and the staff achieve in this unique environment.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience of this worthy movie is a bit like watching
the grass grow. Philibert's camera lingers endlessly on people and
scenes that never seem particularly interesting, significant or in
any way revealing: a man walking across the lawn, a woman
struggling to memorize a song, a cat sitting at the side of the
rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   We never really get to know any of these characters on a
personal level, never know what their particular problems are, and
never learn the answers to any of the natural questions that arise.
Such as: who pays to incarcerate these handicapped people in this
Five Star Loire Valley chateau without bars? And where do you sign
up?
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it stubbornly refuses to ``tell'' its audience anything
about what it's seeing along the way, apparently relying on
reviewers who've read the press notes to inform viewers where and
what the institution is, how it operates, just what is going on
with this rehearsal and play, and even what the title means.
</P>
<P>
   (According to the notes: When asked to explain the unique brand
of ``institutional psychotherapy'' practiced at La Borde, the
institution's founder, Jean Oury, replied that it is not a
punishment: it is ``every little thing.'' If that makes any sense
to you.)
</P>
<P>
   Philibert had much more success using his enigmatic, stand-back
method with his multi-award-winning 1992 documentary, ``In the Land
of the Deaf,'' an extremely touching journey into the world of the
deaf. This film will also be playing at the Grand Illusion as a
double-bill with ``Every Little Thing'' through Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Every Little Thing. Directed by Nicolas Philibert. Photographed
by Philibert and Katell Djian. Documentary. International Film
Circuit. Grand Illusion Cinema. In French with English subtitles.
105 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1411EDT &QL; 
