<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, July 31, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   SWEETHEART-SCAM (Undated). Law authorities and families are
struggling to deal with so-called ``sweetheart'' scams in which
young Gypsy women find vulnerable old men, become their
sweethearts, financees or wives and clean out their bank accounts
and other assets. A Bellevue, Wash., dentist and his sister have
petitioned Thurston County, Wash., Superior Court to overturn the
will of their late father, who died at 76 after after marrying a
20-something Gypsy woman from the Steve family (the one involved in
a massive welfare fraud case). He changed his will several times,
with the final one leaving the woman something between $500,000 and
$750,000.
</P>
<P>
   By Cecelia Goodnow. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-GRAVE (Undated) Jack Olsen's new book, ``Hastened to the
Grave,'' tells of a Gypsy crime ring in San Francisco that bilked
vulnerable old men out of their money and homes and hastened their
deaths by spiking their food with digitalis. One of the heroes of
the book is private investigator Fay Faron, who donated nearly five
years of her life trying to bring the perps to justice. The larger
story is that Gypsy crime rings are operating across the country
with almost identical MO's. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   By Cecelia Goodnow. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EVER (Undated) The one thing you can say about ``Ever
After,'' the movies' latest and umpteenth retelling of the
Cinderella story, is that it's not lacking in audacity.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BASE (Undated) Are this summer's Hollywood comedies aiming
lower than ever before in terms of bathroom humor, cruelty jokes,
insensitivity to minorities and all-around bad taste? There's more
evidence for the prosecution in ``BASEketball,'' a harrowingly dumb
comedy that combines the talents of writer-director David Zucker
(``Airplane!'' ``The Naked Gun'') with the creators of trash-TV's
``South Park,'' Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THIEF (Undated) ``The Thief'' is a joyless, dour and
relentlessly sad movie metaphor for life during Stalin's reign over
post-war Russia in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WHATEVER (Undated) ``Whatever,'' a movie about high school
girls on the fast track to hell in 1981 cops an attitude early on
and maintains its facade of hopelessness and apathy throughout.
Like ``Girls Town'' and ``All Over Me,'' its main characters are
opposites who attract.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WATER (Undated) For the first half hour, this gay soap
opera runs amok as far as tone and technique. The acting is so
amateurish and over the top, we initially wonder if we'll ever be
able to engage with the caricatured characters who inhabit the
upscale and elite Southern town, Azalea Springs.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the film comes back down to Earth and transforms
itself into a clever, spry comedy about homosexual panic.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WEDDING (Undated) pOLQ: Arnold reviews ``Polish Wedding''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-THING (Undated) ``Every Little Thing,'' the new film by
noted French documentarian Nicolas Philibert (``In the Land of the
Deaf''), is set in La Borde, a stunning chateau in the Loire Valley
that was converted into a minimum security mental institution back
in 1953. His camera is a roving fly-on-the-wall as the staff and
inmates of the institution go through a laborious rehearsal process
and finally perform their annual musical revue for 1995, a
performance of Witold Gombrowicz' ``Operetta.''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
