<HEADLINE>
`POLISH WEDDING' WASTES A GOOD CAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good cast is wasted in ``Polish Wedding,'' the latest
low-budget American indie to try _ and fail _ to come up with that
same distinct mixture of ethnic charm, whimsical characters and
subtle romance as 1987's ``Moonstruck.''
</P>
<P>
   The setting is Hamtramck, the working-class, Polish American
community of Detroit, which is depicted in the film as much more
than just another Motown neighborhood, rather as literally a
self-contained Polish village within the huge American city.
</P>
<P>
   The Pzoniak family is led by its matriarch, the hot-blooded and
beautiful Jadzia (Lena Olin), who works as a cleaning woman by day
and spends many of her evenings having clandestine assignations
with her wealthy businessman lover (Rade Serbedzija).
</P>
<P>
   Her patient, long-suffering husband, Kris (Gabriel Byrne), is a
baker who looks the other way at his wife's persistent infidelity
and apparent lack of respect for him, and mopes through his days
muttering bits of philosophy and chain-smoking cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Jadzia also has four sons and an equally hot-blooded teenage
daughter, Hala (Claire Danes), who has dropped out of high school,
spends her days taking care of her older brother's baby, and is
having her own sexual affair with a rookie cop (Adam Trese).
</P>
<P>
   The ambience and the ethnic eccentricities of these characters
are presumably highly authentic, since the film's writer-director,
Theresa Connelly, grew up in the same Detroit neighborhood where
the film was shot, and hails from a family much like this one.
</P>
<P>
   And presumably her script makes a remarkably good read, since it
won her the financial and moral support of the prestigious Sundance
Institute, attracted an impressive cast, and earned her a shot at
directing _ no small feat for a first script.
</P>
<P>
   But _ even though Olin and Danes each sparkle in several of
their scenes _ the elements don't add up to anything especially
interesting, charming, humorous or believable. Like so many in
today's glut of mediocre independent films, this one simply never
clicks into place.
</P>
<P>
   Polish Wedding. Directed and written by Theresa Connelly. Cast:
Lena Olin, Claire Danes, Gabriel Byrne, Adam Trese. Fox
Searchlight. Seven Gables. 101 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
