<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
DREW-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ Drew Barrymore certainly didn't have a
fairy tale childhood. But she knows a thing or two about happy
endings and that made her a pretty good choice to play Cinderella
in ``Ever After,'' a charming, romantic update of the the classic
children's story. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
FESTIVAL-FILM (Los Angeles) _ So many films, so little time. UCLA
Film and Television Archive's annual Festival of Preservation,
which opens Saturday night, not only brings to light the artful
restoration of reels, but also exhibits some notable films that
haven't been seen in a long while _ at least not like this. By Bob
McCarthy. 
. 
BASEKETBALL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``BASEketball'' gives us
vulgarity without any biting wit. The generational comic graft
simply doesn't work, although the movie isn't without some funny
moments. But, it's all geared toward 17-year-old adolescents or
guys who shop for bed linens at the ESPN Store and don't believe
you can have TOO MANY shots of people getting kicked in the groin.
2 Stars. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
GOVERNESS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``The Governess,'' a sensuous,
visually astute British period piece, uses a Jewish woman's
deception to secure her a job in a Scottish household as a central
motif for a story about people who are not what they seem. And it
gives Minnie Driver the opportunity to break out of supportive
girlfriend purgatory. 3 Stars. Bob Strauss. 
. 
JOURNEY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Portugal's world-class director
Manoel de Oliveira reflects on his life and the search for home in
this melancholy, charming film ``Voyage to the Beginning of the
World,'' with the great Marcello Mastroianni in his last movie
appearance. 3{ Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
EVER-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Ever After'' is a Cinderella story
minus the fairy tale trappings but drenched in '90s style romantic
fantasy. A set of natural, witty performances complement the
illusion of realism created by director Andy Tennant and his
first-class design team. 3 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
PRESENT-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ Garry Essendine, the bad-boy hero of
Noel Coward's ``Present Laughter,'' is a good example of what today
we'd call the Peter Pan syndrome. Handsome, charming, effortlessly
witty and on the wrong side of 40, he's a West End idol and
man-about-London who'd just as soon never grow up. By Reed
Johnson. 
. 
COHEN-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Some say Adam Cohen only got his record
deal because he's the son of rock icon and poet Leonard Cohen.
Surprisingly, though, the 25-year-old Cohen doesn't really mind
that perception. ``You don't get a record deal until the company
feels it can make a buck off you,'' he said. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ It's hard to believe Atlanta-born r&AMP;b diva
N'dea Davenport has just released her first solo album. That's
because Davenport's voice is so familiar. As a session singer, she
collaborated with everyone from Natalie Merchant to Malcolm McLaren
to hip-hop icon Guru. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC _ Yes, we know ``Backstreet Boys'' has been on the
charts for a year. But that's no reason why we can't take a second
look, especially since this Florida r&AMP;b harmony quintet's
self-titled debut just rocketed straight back into the top 10. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 

