<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECOND LOOK AT THE `BOYS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BACKSTREET BOYS/``Backstreet Boys'' (Jive)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we know it's been on the charts for a year. But that's no
reason why we can't take a second look, especially since this
Florida r&AMP;b harmony quintet's self-titled debut just rocketed
straight back into the top 10. It's state-of-the-art stuff, full of
first-class, well-produced material that ranges from solid funk to
sturdy ballads and soulful hip-hop cuts. Best moments here are
numerous, including ``Quit Playing Games (With My Heart),'' ``We've
Got It Goin' On,'' ``All I Have to Give,'' the uplifting current
smash ``Everybody (Backstreet's Back)'' and a wonderful cover of PM
Dawn's ``Set Adrift on Memory Bliss.'' Backstreet Boys will be
around for a while. 3{ Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
KANE &AMP; ABEL/``Am I My Brothers Keeper'' (No Limit/Priority)
</P>
<P>
   Rap mogul Master P has never made a good album and all his CD
covers look the same. Yet, he keeps churning 'em out under his or
other names and they inexplicably sell millions. This one, full of
the usual shoot-'em-up scenerios and predictable odes to the hood,
resembles everything else on the label, which follows a strict but
terribly dull gangsta-rap formula. Cameos from new signing Snoop
Dogg don't help matters. True to form, the album recently reached
No. 5. Who buys these things? 1 Star. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUBLIME/``Stand by Your Van _ Live'' (Gasoline Alley/MCA)
</P>
<P>
   As the Sublime trough runs dry, here's the dreaded and sometimes
even dreadful live album, recorded almost entirely at a 1994 date.
While the Sublime record to get is still ``40 Oz. to Freedom,''
this disc has a couple of reasons to exist, such as the tracks
``Poolshark'' and ``DJs.'' On the whole, however, avoid it unless
you're a fan, completist or bug collector. 2 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHERRY POPPIN' DADDIES/``Zoot Suit Riot'' (Mojo)
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's Daddies insist they don't do retro even though the band
plays horn-fueled swing and jump blues in the style of Cab Calloway
and Louis Jordan. This 14-track collection compiles the best of the
group's three previous indie releases and adds four new songs,
including the title song which is a staple at radio stations like
KROQ. It's a thoroughly entertaining disc that benefits from loads
of extra players who stretch the band's horn section to almost a
cast of thousands. The familiar ``Zoot Suit Riot'' isn't the only
good cut here by any means. Other strong swingers: ``Master and
Slave,'' ``Dr. Bones'' and ``Brown Derby Jump.'' 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUEEN LATIFAH/``Order in the Court'' (Motown)
</P>
<P>
   Although she divides her time between acting and making music,
the Queen hasn't lost her microphone or street smarts. This bold
new release features the sort of raps that made her famous almost
10 years ago and she even tries singing with mixed results on a
couple of tracks. She's best on the strong hip-hop cuts such as
``Bananas (Who You Gonna Call?)'' and the perfectly realized old
school/new school hybrid ``Paper.'' 2 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ETTA JAMES/``Life, Love &AMP; the Blues'' (Private)
</P>
<P>
   The title sums it all up. Etta's best album in ages offers a
wealth of pungent blues and convincing Southern soul gems,
including marvelous covers of the late Johnny ``Guitar'' Watson's
``I Want to Ta Ta You, Baby,'' Al Green's ``Here I Am (Come and
Take Me),'' Willie Dixon's ``Spoonful'' and Marvin Gaye's ``Inner
City Blues (Make Me Wanna Holler)'' with Leo Nocentelli from the
Meters on guitar. The best cut here is also the most obscure _
Perry Jordan's ``Running Out of Lies'' _ but the entire album is
worth investigating. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUNTRACK/``Saving Private Ryan'' (DreamWorks)
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual approach to the use of music in film, the first
notes heard during this movie come some 15 minutes into the
narrative. Oscar-winning composer John Williams' lyrical score,
recorded by the Boston Symphony Orchestra, is sweeping and grand
but also ominous in places. Taken apart from the film, the mood
here is reflective, even during segments featuring the Tanglewood
Festival Chorus, one of the country's most renowned vocal
ensembles. Clearly one of Williams' most memorable works. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOUNDTRACK/``BASEketball'' (Mojo)
</P>
<P>
   Fans of slacker-rock and ska-punk can chalk up another winner in
this 13-track sampler tied to the current comedy about a fictional
sport which combines baseball and basketball. The best tracks
include Cherry Poppin' Daddies' cover of Harry Belafonte's ``Jump
in the Line,'' the Supersuckers' ``Psyched Out'' and, best of all,
Plastiscene's ``Lemon Yellow.'' Ultimately, the soundtrack is
bogged down by less-than-stellar offerings from Reel Big Fish,
Goldfinger and Smash Mouth. 2 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NICHOLAS PAYTON/``Payton's Place'' (Verve)
</P>
<P>
   Payton's best work has come with challenge. Last year's
collaboration with the late Doc Cheatam was marvelous, as was his
trio recording with Christian McBride and Mark Whitfield that
celebrated the music of Herbie Hancock. Here he shines with fellow
trumpeters Roy Hargrove and Wynton Marsalis on a swinging ``The
Three Trumpeters'' and with saxophonist Joshua Redman on the
energetic ``A Touch of Silver.'' Elsewhere, Patyon plays with his
regular quintet on his compositions that loosely tie together funk,
blues and swing with occasionally memorable results. 2{ Stars. _
Glenn Whipp &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ELIANE ELIAS/``Sings Jobim'' (Blue Note)
</P>
<P>
   Pianist Elias has been paying tribute to fellow Brazilian Jobim
throughout her career, frequently playing his songs in concert and
on albums. This is her second album completely devoted to the
brilliant composer's music, and although the results are pleasant
enough, they won't make you forget the brilliant source material.
Elias uses her voice more or less as another instrument to deliver
the melody. She's limited in range, much like ``Ipanema''
standard-bearer Astrud Gilberto. But unlike Gilberto, Elias'
singing never manages to be memorable. But her piano work does do
justice to Jobim's incomparable melodies, making this a worthwhile
disc for bossa nova diehards. 2{ Stars. _ Glenn Whipp &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
