<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESENT-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COWARD-LY PETER PAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Garry Essendine, the bad-boy hero of Noel
Coward's ``Present Laughter,'' is a good example of what today we'd
call the Peter Pan syndrome. Handsome, charming, effortlessly witty
and on the wrong side of 40, he's a West End idol and
man-about-London who'd just as soon never grow up.
</P>
<P>
   So he hides behind his suave stage persona. He keeps dangerous
emotions at bay by affecting a world-weary, self-dramatizing
attitude. When friends or his ex-wife drop by his London studio,
they usually find Garry in a silk smoking jacket, tickling the
ivories or fixing a drink, his latest nubile conquest stashed
safely away in a spare bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   As long as he's acting _ which is always _ Garry can be the star
of his life, reciting his own best lines to a supporting cast of
co-dependents that includes his astute ex-wife Liz, his blustery
business associates, a faithful Cockney valet and a chain-smoking
housekeeper with a bent for spiritualism.
</P>
<P>
   Garry, of course, is Coward's midlife self-portrait (or maybe
Hugh Hefner's airbrushed one). And as played by Robert Curtis Brown
at the Pasadena Playhouse it's a portrait of a lively, engaging
fellow, though not quite the irresistibly rakish bon vivant Coward
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   One difficulty with this role is that while Garry is constantly
performing, the actor playing him somehow needs to let the mask
slip now and then so we can glimpse the real man underneath. Brown
finds a certain wistful melancholy and a dash of anger behind
Garry's coolly amusing facade, but not much of genuine emotional
insight.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, director Richard Seyd's production offers a pleasant
summer divertissement with no particular edge _ a wine cooler
instead of a full head of champagne. While one recent,
controversial New York production of ``Present Laughter'' attempted
to spice things up by ``outing'' Garry _ and, by implication, the
famously closeted Coward _ Seyd prefers to play things straight, so
to speak. He emphasizes the play's farcical side, an approach that
works rippingly well in the Act 2 scene in which various ingenues,
cuckolded husbands and jealous lovers converge on Garry's studio in
a door-slamming frenzy of romantic recrimination.
</P>
<P>
   It's less effective in providing an emotional context for
Coward's droll ripostes, which here too often come across as mere
icy put-downs. Actors gesticulate, wag fingers at each other and
leap onto furniture to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   But these antics, combined with several wobbly British accents,
prove more distracting than fun. The first place Seyd needs to turn
down the volume is Scott Lowell, who tears up the stage in the role
of a ``serious'' playwright who comes to berate Garry for selling
out, then ends by fawning all over him.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the supporting cast are Keith Langsdale, as Garry's
flustered, straight-man manager Morris, and Kaitlin Hopkins, whose
performance as the wickedly seductive Joanna puts some much needed
bite into this fizzy affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
