<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, July 31, 1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June
20, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WHY _ WASHINGTON _ Why did President Clinton choose the
perilous course of voluntarily testifying before Ken Starr's grand
jury? If he has been truthful in denying an affair with Monica
Lewinsky, the answer is that he has nothing to fear from Starr. If
he has been untruthful, the answer may be that he has made a
political calculation that his transgressions won't prove
impeachable. We ask legal and political experts for their views.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NC-CLINTON _ President Clinton travels to Boone and Raleigh,
N.C. Catching up with him in Boone, a talk of the town on reaction
to the visit by the embattled leader. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DATE-RAPE _ WASHINGTON _ A House Judiciary subcommittee holds a
hearing on the use of controlled substances used to commit date
rape. Texas and Florida witnesses testify. (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION _ WASHINGTON _ A House Judiciary subcommittee meets
to mark up a bill to establish the Bureau of Enforcement and Border
Affairs within the Justice Department. The new agency would take
over prevention of illegal immigration from the Border Patrol and
elements of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. (Harlan,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DEAF-BLIND-COMPUTERS _ WASHINGTON _ Gary Strong, the National
Science Foundation's Coordinator for Computing, discusses an
NSF-funded project to design a portable computer interface for deaf
and blind people. (Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION _ WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee is expected to
vote Thursday to split the immigration service, creating an agency
that would deal solely with new citizens and a separate law
enforcement bureau that would be responsible for guarding U.S.
borders. The Justice Department today reiterated its opposition to
the plan, but some Democratic lawmakers find the division of labor
attractive. ``The agency has become too big,'' says Rep. Silvestre
Reyes, D-Texas, a former Border Patrol chief. (Harlan, Cox News
Service 600).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SKOLVIOLENCE-HOTLINE _ It appears that Georgia may be the only
state that has a statewide school system hotline that allows
students, parents, etc., to anonymously call in tips about
potential campus violence. Typically, individual schools or school
districts usually have these kinds of lines. They are another
measure to curb school violence in light of recent schools at
schools nationwide. National safety experts, as well as some local
educators applaud the hotline idea, but say the mechanics of how it
works should be well thought out. (Badie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 14-16.
</P>
<P>
   STAMP _ DAYTON, Ohio _Postal Service put 200 million stamps on
sale Thursday to raise money for breast cancer research. The
32-cent stamps sell for 40 cents, with the extra 8 cents going to
research. We check on local sales, opinions. (Moss, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   GA-POWERBALL _ Checking with state officials on what the loss of
Powerball has meant to Georgia. The state dropped out of the
lottery in favor of the Big Game because Powerball jackpots were
too small. Shortly after that the odds were changed in Powerball,
and the jackpots began climbing.
</P>
<P>
   SINCLAIR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Sinclair Community College is in the
early stages of a collaboration with seven other similar colleges
across the country to offer distance-learning courses to students
anywhere. This would make full use of the college's
computer-integrated learning center that is nearing completion in
the heart of campus. (Fisher, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT _ AUSTIN _ It's hot. It's dry. And nobody knows when
it's going to rain. Environmental officials have put 213 of the
state's 4,201 community water systems on a ``watch list'' because
their pumps and pipes are under strain or supplies are being
depleted. The human toll is mounting, with 96 deaths since June 1.
The latest victim was Tommy McDeane, 48, of Dallas, who died
recently at a hospital after an apparent heat stroke about two
weeks ago. In Central Texas, temperatures have broken the century
mark in 16 of the last 19 days. (Haurwitz/Rodriguez, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-FLYJESUS _ Harold Martin of Hobe Sound is a student at
Moody aviation learning to do airplane maintenance for mission
planes. They fly to strange places taking the word of God and
supplies. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COMIC-CARRINGTON _ HBO wants to talk about a sitcom. Album sales
are climbing. Comedy club gigs have him rolling in the dough.
Rodney Carrington can feel it. He's on the verge of something
big.``I can feel a rumble,'' says Carrington, who brings his at the
Comedy Corner in West Palm Beach the next two weekends. (Houck,
Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
