<SLUG> BC-FILM-THIEF-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE THIEF' IS JOYLESS, RELENTLESSLY SAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admittedly, there are some buoyant Russian movies. ``Burnt By
The Sun'' brimmed with vitality and ``The Ascent'' evoked the
austere beauty and extreme closeups of a Carl Dreyer classic.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, recent Russian cinema still thrives on
the belief that life is bleak. Efforts like ``Mother and Son,''
which admittedly have been visually astounding, dramatize the
ordeal of living in an economically beleagured Russia before and
after Perestroika and the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thief,'' which was nominated in 1997 for an Oscar in the
best foreign film category and won top honors at the 1997 NIKAs
(the Russian equivalent to the Academy Awards), is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   It's a joyless, dour and relentlessly sad movie metaphor for
life during Stalin's reign over post-war Russia in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   That life is seen through the eyes of a young boy, Sanya (Misha
Philipchuk), as his beautiful young mother, Katya (Ekaterina
Rednikova) falls instantly in love with a dashing, renegade
military officer named Tolyan (Vladimir Mashkov), who she meets on
a train.
</P>
<P>
   Tolyan turns out to be a fraud; in truth he's nothing but a
common thief (who sports a tattoo of Stalin on his chest and a
panther on his shoulder) and who alternately dotes on and abuses
both mother and boy. He's even stolen his uniform from an unknown
soldier in order to acquire lodging and the opportunity to ravage
his neighbor's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dismal life but, because living is a trial in itself
under Comrade Stalin, Katya stays with Tolyan. Ultimately the woman
pays a terrible price for her loyalty. As their relationship
deteriorates, it's inevitably 6-year-old Sanya who comes to adore
and worship Tolyan and think of him as ``daddy.'' Just when Katya
has had enough of pain and crime and is intent upon leaving her
lover, Tolyan suffers a surprising fate _ one that will tear the
``family'' apart.
</P>
<P>
   Chukhrai ultimately beats us to death with the downbeat crisis
that prevail over the character's lives. There's no relief in ``The
Thief'' and more, the ending betrays everything that is interesting
in the story. Who wants to watch a depressing film about life in a
bygone era that has no resolution and redemption? Perhaps that's
precisely the point Chukhrai is trying to make _ there is no point.
</P>
<P>
   The Thief. Directed and written by Pavel Chukhrai. Cast:
Vladimir Mashkov, Ekaterina Rednikova, Misha Philipchuk.
Stratosphere Entertainment. 90 minutes. Rated R for language,
violence, sexual content. In Russian with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
