r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BASEKETBALL-SPI &LR;      07-30 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BASEKETBALL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASEKETBALL' IS LOW AND DUMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are this summer's Hollywood comedies aiming lower than ever
before in terms of bathroom humor, cruelty jokes, insensitivity to
minorities and all-around bad taste?
</P>
<P>
   That's the argument several critics have made recently, and
based on the evidence of such films as ``Mafia!,'' ``There's
Something About Mary,'' and even ``Dr. Doolittle,'' it's hard to
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   And there's still more evidence for the prosecution in
``BASEketball,'' a harrowingly dumb comedy that combines the
talents of writer-director David Zucker (``Airplane!'' ``The Naked
Gun'') with the creators of trash-TV's ``South Park,'' Trey Parker
and Matt Stone.
</P>
<P>
   This one is about two Milwaukee underachievers (Parker and
Stone), who inadvertently invent a backyard game that combines
elements of both basketball and baseball, with an added ``psyche
out'' factor in which opponents deliberately try to rattle each
other's concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to five years later, and the sport is the rage of America,
largely because it has forbidden all the things we hate about
professional sports in the '90s _ players aren't highly paid, they
can't change teams and corporate money is kept out.
</P>
<P>
   It's rather a clever idea for a sports satire, on the basis of
which sports-enthusiast Zuker apparently managed to recruit a slew
of famous sports announcers (Bob Costas, Tim McCarver, Curt Gowdy
and Al Michaels), and such sports legends as Reggie Jackson, Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Dale Earnhardt to take part.
</P>
<P>
   But, not content to make merely a clever satire, he's junked up
the movie far beyond anything he's ever dared in the past. It's one
flatulence, urination and vomit gag after another; juvenile attacks
on gays (the San Francisco team is ``the Ferries''), Hispanics and
the blind; cruelty jokes that go on for agonizing lengths of screen
time.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, despite his successful track record as a comedy
director, Zuker proves himself not especially adept at
low-low-humor _ not half as imaginative as, say, the Farrelly
Brothers (``Kingpin,'' ``Dumb and Dumber''). At least three-fourths
of his gags fell absolutely flat with the audience Universal
recruited for the Seattle preview showing. Barely a giggle.
</P>
<P>
   But the real tragedy is that, by spending so much of its time
heaping up the most abysmal kind of adolescent humor,
``BASEketball'' fails to live up to whatever small potential it has
as a sports comedy. The script doesn't even have time to tell us,
for instance, how this game is played. We're forced to keep staring
at these numbskulls throwing basketballs and running around some
weird shaped court without ever really knowing what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   BASEketball. Directed by David Zucker. Cast: Trey Parker, Matt
Stone, Yasmine Bleeth, Robert Vaughn. Universal. 100 minutes. Rated
R for gross humor.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
