r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EVER-SPI &LR;      07-30 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EVER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVER AFTER' DOESN'T LACK AUDACITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one thing you can say about ``Ever After,'' the movies'
latest and umpteenth retelling of the Cinderella story, is that
it's not lacking in audacity.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it strip the story of its magical elements and
rework the character into a take-charge feminist, it casts the
dramatically questionable Drew Barrymore in the part, and throws in
Leonardo da Vinci as the Fairy Godmother figure.
</P>
<P>
   It's so bizarre that it almost works, though a grumpy critic
could certainly have a field day with it, and especially with the
performance of Barrymore, who often seems to doing ``Scream 3'' and
speaks throughout with a glaringly fake English accent, even though
the story is set in France.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with a prologue in which an aged French countess
(Jeanne Moreau) calls the Brothers Grimm to her chateau and takes
them to task for getting the Cinderella story all wrong. Producing
a glass-studded slipper, she tells them it's a true story, and she
wants ``to set the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to a few hundred years earlier, and we met Danielle
(Barrymore), whose happy life with her beloved father (Jeroen
Krabbe) comes to a halt when he remarries a countess (Anjelica
Huston) with two daughters, and promptly drops dead of a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle becomes a servant in her own house, and the rest of the
movie follows the outline of the myth, except that this Cinderella
is both rebellious and highly capable, the prince falls in love
with her keen mind more than her buxom beauty, and the visiting Da
Vinci plays cupid.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, obviously, was to modernize the myth for modern
audiences, removing what feminists have long charged is an
abhorrent central theme (that women should wait around for a Prince
Charming to come along and change their lives for the better) and
otherwise portraying the cardboard characters as more recognizable
human beings.
</P>
<P>
   However, no one appears to have told Anjelica Huston what was
going on in the humanizing of characters department, because she
plays the Evil Stepmother with nostrils flaring and no holds
barred. She's such a portrait of menopausal meanness that she makes
Glenn Close's recent turn as Cruella De Vil look like Melanie
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's hard to ever know for sure when this film is being
deliberately tongue-in-cheek and when it's being straight.
Barrymore is so contemporary in manner and the script is so
littered with modernisms (``Un-bee-lieveable!'' Danielle exclaims
at one point of frustration) that it often plays more like a
``Airplane!''-style parody of ``Cinderella'' than an affectionate
re-interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Ever After. Directed by Andy Tennant. Screenplay by Susannah
Grant, Tennant and Rick Parks. Cast: Drew Barrymore, Anjelica
Huston, Dougray Scott. 20th Century-Fox. 121 minutes. Rated PG-13
for no obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
