<P>
   Weekend Section stories in sight at this hour from The New York
Times News Service for Friday, July 31.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other entertainment stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MET-UNICORN (New York) _ The branch of the Metropolitan Museum
known as the Cloisters is, in every sense, one of the high points
of art in New York City. An impressive jumble of Romanesque scraps
and American prewar masonry, and a monument to American
philanthropy, it sits atop a rocky outcrop over the Hudson near the
upper tip of Manhattan. If location is one of the Cloisters'
outstanding attractions, the magnificent trove of medieval art it
houses is another. Burgundian carvings, illuminated manuscripts and
one of the greatest of all early Netherlandish paintings are among
the treasures. But surely the most famous work is the set of
tapestries long known as ``The Hunt of the Unicorn.'' By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SHAKERS (Undated) _ The peninsula encompassing the
downtown area of Portland, Maine., is a pleasantly compact place,
with neighborhoods that invite strolling and a harbor full of
islands reached by a ferry ride that can feel like a vacation in
itself. The chance to visit such a manageable maritime city and do
a little exploring along the coast nearby lured my wife, Margaret,
and me on a recent weekend. But we also went out of curiosity about
a living link to an unusual chapter in American religious history.
For more than two centuries, a Shaker community has made its home
on a farmstead less than an hour's drive away from Portland, and
the six believers living there now are the last remnant of this
sect in the United States. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-OUTDOOR-DANCE (New York) _ A young girl dressed in a
scalloped tunic and kerchief jumps awkwardly on a makeshift outdoor
stage beneath the Queensborough Bridge in the late 1960s. Seven
shambling young avant-gardists spread the 1970s gospel of
fashionably untutored and untheatrical dance performance on a city
sidewalk. Ballroom dancers spin and fly through countless nights in
the parks of New York City in the 1940s and '50s. Charming
photographs from ``Stepping Out: A Century of Dance in New York
City Parks,'' an exhibition at the Central Park Arsenal Building,
suggest that outdoor dance performances have long been with us. But
those performances have changed a great deal, to judge by the
attractions offered by festivals this summer in the city and
beyond. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
