<HEADLINE>
STEVENS STICKS WITH VICTORY GALLOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for RACING)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM WILKIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ When Victory Gallop goes to the races
early next month, Elliot Walden, his trainer, has absolutely no
doubts that Gary Stevens will be the jockey on his colt's back. And
Stevens backs the trainer up on that.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, who hasn't raced since depriving Real Quiet of
winning the Triple Crown by edging out his rival in the Belmont
Stakes last month, is scheduled to run next in the $1 million
Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park in New Jersey on Aug. 9. The
Jim Dandy, the traditional Travers prep at Saratoga Race Course, is
scheduled for the same day.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, Victory Gallop, second in the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness, will go from the Haskell to the
Travers.
</P>
<P>
   Walden, who has Victory Gallop stabled at Saratoga, said he was
never concerned that Stevens might jump off his colt. Stevens, who
is based at Del Mar near San Diego, decided to bypass Saratoga and
remain on the Left Coast. That decision came after Bob Baffert, who
trains Real Quiet, gave Stevens an offer he couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert told the jockey that if stayed at Del Mar for the
summer, he would give Stevens first call on all of his horses,
including Real Quiet. Seeing as Real Quiet is scheduled to face
Victory Gallop in the Haskell, Walden may have been staring at a
problem. Speculation was running high about just who would pick up
the mount.
</P>
<P>
   `I am not concerned now,'' Walden said Wednesday. ``Gary told me
he was going to be on Victory Gallop on Haskell Day.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walden heard that Stevens was going to bypass Saratoga and
stay as Baffert's No. 1 guy in California, he did raise his
eyebrows. He knew that Stevens would have his choice of riding his
colt or Real Quiet, who has been being rode by Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, speaking by phone from the jockey room at Del Mar
Wednesday, said the option was there to ride Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an issue,'' Stevens said. ``But after a lot of
thought and consideration, I decided to stay on Victory Gallop.
Those people (Victory Gallop's owners Art, Jack and J.R. Preston)
have been so good to me over the years and I have had a good
working relationship with Elliot Walden. I felt fortunate to be
chosen to ride their horse in the Preakness and then the Belmont
Stakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens rode Indian Charlie to a third place finish in the
Kentucky Derby. After that colt was declared out of the Preakness,
Stevens picked up Victory Gallop and has been there since and
apparently will stay there.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Stevens wants to make sure people know is that he is
not staying on Victory Gallop because of the sentimental hogwash it
seems to reek of. He said he did not talk to Desormeaux about this
and he and Baffert are apparently OK with this decision.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens did work Real Quiet in California earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't keep the mount because I thought I was obligated
to,'' Stevens said. ``I really think Victory Gallop is a very good
racehorse; I am confident he is one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary won the Belmont, a Grade I race, with Victory Gallop,''
Walden said. ``It wasn't like I had to ask him what he was going to
do. We did have some discussion because we obviously wanted to make
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he was not sure when he would be making an
appearance at Saratoga; the first time could be when and if Victory
Gallop runs in the $750,000 Travers here on Aug. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
