<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT PORKER AND THE SLEAZE PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This week Monica Lewinsky and her mom got
immunity. Columnists lost it. We have to write about this stuff
whether we like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like it, and until this week have been avoiding the
subject for months. But the whole country is asking the question:
``Huh? Aren't people supposed to lie about sex?''
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago I gave Clinton the first break I've given him in
this column since a month after his inauguration, asking why we'd
destroy a president because he couldn't keep his zipper up and his
lip zipped afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Can't we get this guy on bigger stuff, like being a
sanctimonious shyster who doesn't solve problems but just starts
national conversations about them?
</P>
<P>
   A woman friend immediately accused me of giving Clinton a free
pass. ``He may have done good things for women,'' she said. ``But
he's a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't respond without feeling like part of the piggie club.
This is despite the fact that, according to surveys and overheard
conversations, men have been tougher on Clinton for his
peccadilloes than women have.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because men are envious of Clinton's attractiveness
to women. As a female I know once said: ``He's a babe.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the name of a pig, too. A cuter and straighter-talking
one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can be described with a slew of ``sl-'' words like
``slick,'' ``slimy,'' ``sleazy'' and ``slippery,'' as shown by how
he wriggled out of the draft in the '60s to how he dodged taking a
position on affirmative action in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   He's been trying to wriggle out of this one too, ever since that
bit about oral sex not being adultery. OK, he's a greased pig, or a
member of that all-male species known as the horn dog.
</P>
<P>
   But so were many presidents. Recent accounts by former Secret
Service officers show that our most revered recent president, John
F. Kennedy, turned the White House into a bordello with himself as
the only john.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Lyndon Johnson was envious and bragged, ``I've had
more women by accident than he's had on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Or something to that effect. If Clinton is a pig, he's living in
a big white sty with porticos.
</P>
<P>
   My friend is genuinely offended that Clinton, a married man with
a child, would have sex with a then-21-year-old intern in the house
the American people rent to their highest public servant.
</P>
<P>
   If it's true, as all the leaks and sources assure us, it does
make Clinton a pig of a different stench. Monica Lewinsky seems
like a nice young woman, but insecure and impressionable.
</P>
<P>
   At least Kennedy had the good taste to bed mobster molls. What
the hell was Clinton thinking? This intern was barely older than
his daughter, and a woman you couldn't exactly ditch. She worked in
the next office.
</P>
<P>
   Does Clinton toss back Stoly with Boris Yeltsin and then play
Russian roulette with the nuclear button, too?
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is a young woman who, if all reports are accurate,
regularly talked with her own mother about her affair with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   For the life of me, I don't know what Monica Lewinsky needs
immunity from, but I wish her mother didn't have it.
</P>
<P>
   Even at my age, if I told my mom I was having an affair with the
first lady, she'd never let me sleep in my old room again.
</P>
<P>
   The other night David Letterman's Top 10 List were the questions
special prosecutor Ken Starr plans to ask Monica Lewinsky. They
included the usual puerile jokes, but No. 3 was ``Are you mad at me
for ruining your entire adult life?''
</P>
<P>
   How does she maintain her sanity, now that she's keeping five
networks and the entire Internet in business?
</P>
<P>
   My wife, ever the realist, says: ``One word: Theresabookinit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the best-seller will come dozens of made-for-TV movies,
and then an entire life known as Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   I'm looking at a color picture of Lewinsky in the Los Angeles
Times. She is surrounded by gawkers and cameramen, yet she stands
apart like a serene Renaissance beauty.
</P>
<P>
   What are all these jokes about Lewinsky's appearance? Maybe this
is some kind of guy thing _ putting down a woman who did it with
another guy.
</P>
<P>
   Below the picture of Monica with the Mona Lisa smile is a
picture of Ken Starr with his Mr. Toad smile. One line comes to
mind, the kind always spoken by neighbors: ``He always seemed like
a nice, quiet guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice quiet guy who has spent $50 million trying to get the
president. As Gerald Seib of the Wall Street Journal has pointed
out, Starr was appointed four years ago _ when Monica Lewinsky was
still in college _ to investigate a real-estate deal in backwater
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   He could have saved her a lot of headaches, and us a lot of
money, by nailing the president back then.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky family now has a spokeswoman. Every family needs a
spokeswoman, especially hers. After the immunity deal, the
spokeswoman said that Monica's parents ``are relieved their
daughter is out of harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. What was Ken Starr going to do? Send a 25-year-old to
jail for falling for our babe of a president? She still has a life
sentence as the woman who launched a billion jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton started a national conversation all right. What a
porker, and we've all followed him and Ken Starr into the mud.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
