<HEADLINE>
INTERIM 49ERS BOSS FOCUSES ON FINDING A SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ It was in 1992 that Larry Thrailkill made his
first serious connection with the DeBartolo family.
</P>
<P>
   He started out handling financial dealings, working closely with
Edward DeBartolo Sr. until DeBartolo's death in 1994. Shortly after
that, 49ers owners Eddie DeBartolo Jr. and Denise DeBartolo York
invited Thrailkill to Super Bowl XXIX in 1995 in Miami, offering
him the job of chief operating officer of the Edward J. DeBartolo
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time of adjustment and Thrailkill was the man for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill finds himself in the same position today, only this
time it is with the 49ers and his title is interim president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie and Denise invited me to be COO of the corporation in
order to help them get through a transition period,'' Thrailkill
said. ``That was my role then, to work through that period, and
that's what I'll be doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill held a news conference Wednesday, a week after Carmen
Policy resigned as president of the San Francisco team. Now
Thrailkill is in charge and must face most of the questions about
the uncertainty of the 49ers' ownership.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he will be doing that Policy didn't in his last months
on the job is keeping Eddie DeBartolo Jr. more apprised of the
organization's operations. DeBartolo removed himself from team
management in December after becoming the subject of a federal
probe into gambling in Louisiana. Policy started answering directly
to York at that time and also stopped talking to DeBartolo about
team business.
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill will still answer to York, but he also will be
talking to her brother regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie stepped away from management of the team, but he's still
an owner of the organization,'' he said. ``I'll talk to him as much
as I talk to Denise because he's a shareholder in the organization
that owns the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill's attitude toward his input into the daily operations
of the team hasn't changed. That responsibility still falls on
executive vice president of football operations Dwight Clark, coach
Steve Mariucci and chief financial officer Bill Duffy. Thrailkill
apparently plans on ensuring that things run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest tasks will be monitoring the progress of plans for
the team's new stadium and finding a permanent successor for
Policy.
</P>
<P>
   No one argues that Policy, who is now part of an ownership group
bidding for control of the expansion Cleveland Browns, supplied all
the attributes the team could covet in a top executive.
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill and Policy are good friends, and saw each other early
Wednesday in Youngstown, Ohio, where Policy was cleaning out his
office at the DeBartolo Corp. headquarters. The company's business
holdings include shopping centers and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Policy pointed out that his name had been removed from his
parking space, replaced by Thrailkill's.
</P>
<P>
   Thrailkill currently wears three hats _ his titles with the
49ers and the DeBartolo Corp. as well his role as a partner in a
Nashville law firm. He harbors no plans to turn this job into a
permanent one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
