<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTIRON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAST-IRON: HEAVY-METAL MEALS  
 (PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SEND TO NYTNS PHOTO CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - All you need to cook, all you really, really need, is
a cast-iron skillet. And maybe a knife and a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, you inherited a piece of cast-iron cookware
from a grandmother. Be proud of it. Martha Washington left some to
her descendants, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cast iron has many uses around the home kitchen, but it's also
especially wonderful for camping and outdoor use. Chef Robert
McGrath of the Roaring Fork in Scottsdale, Ariz., serves Green
Chile Pork at the restaurant in individual cast-iron cauldrons, but
he's also had vast experience with cast iron around campfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up camping,'' McGrath said as he poked the fire for a
photo shoot. ``I've been going to Colorado (for an annual rafting
trip) since 1972. That's how the restaurant got its name.''
</P>
<P>
   He piled rosemary on the fire to scent the food, and seasoned
boneless trout fillets with kosher salt, cracked black pepper and
yellow cornmeal. He set them to sizzle in a cast-iron skillet in
hot shortening, his preferred frying medium for camping purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to transport. When we're out rafting and so on, we
use shortening,'' McGrath said. ``And when I'm cooking in cast
iron, when I'm doing chicken, that's what I use.''
</P>
<P>
   Fried chicken cooked in a cast-iron skillet _ is there anything
else that qualifies quite so readily as nectar of the gods?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. McGrath's Green Chile Pork is way up there, too. He uses
three kinds of chiles, including roasted dried green chiles. If you
can't get them or don't want to dry your own in a dehydrator,
substitute fresh or canned roasted chiles.
</P>
<P>
   The pork is made into a stew, which is a classic use of a
cast-iron Dutch oven. ``Dutch oven'' is a term used to describe two
different kinds of pots, so pay attention here.
</P>
<P>
   Many cooks call their large covered pot a ``Dutch oven.'' It has
a flat bottom and a domed lid.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dutch oven'' also refers to a cast-iron pot that actually
will cook like an oven, with heat from above and below. This kind
of Dutch oven has short legs to sit over coals, and a flat lid with
a flanged top so hot coals or charcoal briquettes can be held on
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner Cast Iron calls this a ``cowboy pot.'' Lodge, another
maker of cast iron, calls it a Dutch oven.
</P>
<P>
   We liked McGrath's biscuits baked in a cast-iron skillet. (He
put it in the oven, not over coals or on a grill.) He put balls of
dough in the skillet and when they baked, they grew together into
one mass. It was easy to break off the biscuits and eat them. You
can use your favorite biscuit recipe or biscuit mix to duplicate
this.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath uses smoked red and yellow onions and leeks in Barbecued
Onion Soup, another delectable creation served in cast-iron
cauldrons at the Roaring Fork. You can use any kind of smoker for
the onions, or, if you're in camp, McGrath suggests that you cut
the onions into thick slices, put them on the grill, and put a
cast-iron lid or inverted cast-iron pot over them to trap the smoke
and infuse them with flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The soup is topped with fine slices of onion tossed with chili
powder and flour, and fried until crisp.
</P>
<P>
   You can cook almost anything in a Dutch oven. At the World
Championship Dutch Oven Cookoff on Aug. 8 at the Festival of the
American West in Logan, Utah, contestants will prepare three
entrees in three Dutch ovens: one a meat dish, one a bread with
yeast or sourdough, and one dessert. The winning team of two gets
$500.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a cornbread baking tip that your grandmother knew: Put a
small amount of butter or fat in a cast-iron skillet and preheat it
in the oven before adding cornbread batter. The hot skillet will
make a crisper crust.
</P>
<P>
   Carol McClain of Wagner Manufacturing, makers of cast-iron
cookware since 1891, said the company still makes several of its
original pieces. Newest are fat-free fryers, with raised grids in
the bottom of the pan to sear the food and cook it above the
drippings.
</P>
<P>
   You can find cast-iron skillets in all sizes, round and square,
with grids in the bottom or not; Dutch ovens in medium and huge
sizes; cornbread pans in interesting shapes, including the
ever-popular one shaped like ears of corn; griddles that fit across
one or two burners. Cast-iron pans also are made for unusual
specialties such as Swedish pancakes and the puffy round Dutch
balls of dough called ableskivers.
</P>
<P>
   One new cast-iron pan even has a lid with grids underneath,
which is made to be heated separately from the skillet, which also
has grids. It is used on the stove top or on a grill, and the
heated lid is pressed onto the meat to give it those grill marks
and make it cook faster.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Clark, who listed their Dutch oven as one of the most
important pieces of equipment they had on their westward
exploration trek, would be proud. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Green Chile Pork &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From chef Robert McGrath) &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 pounds coarse-cut boneless country style pork ribs
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 cups roasted, peeled, pureed poblano pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup seeded, stemmed, coarse-cut dried New Mexico green chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons corn oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated pepper Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   24 grilled flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound butter
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy saute pan or Dutch oven, saute the pork (seasoned
with salt and pepper) with the onions, jalapeno and garlic until
the pork is tender. Add the poblano puree and the New Mexico dried
chiles. Simmer for 35 to 45 minutes and adjust seasoning to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the green chile pork in a small crock, or kettle, topped
with the cheese. Grill the tortillas and brush on the butter. Serve
the kettle on a folded napkin with the tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 833 calories, 44 g fat, 122 mg
cholesterol, 66 g carbohydrates, 889 mg sodium, 48 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pan-Fried Canyon Trout with Salad of Spring Melons, Green Onions &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From chef Robert McGrath) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Salad: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced watermelon
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cantaloupe balls
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced honeydew
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bias-cut green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup 1-inch chive sections
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped garlic chives
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raspberry vinegar &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trout and garnishes:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   4 boneless rainbow trout
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable shortening, or corn oil spray
</P>
<P>
   20 whole chives
</P>
<P>
   4 lime wedges
</P>
<P>
   Mix all of the ingredients of the salad together in a medium
bowl and let sit for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Combine salt, pepper and cornmeal in a shallow dish. Dip trout
fillets into it to coat well on each side. Heat a cast iron skillet
with the shortening and fry trout in it briefly on each side until
cooked. (Alternatively, omit cornmeal and season trout with salt
and pepper. Spray a hot cast iron grilling skillet lightly with
corn oil. Place the trout cut side down on the grill for 2 1/2
minutes then turn 90 degrees for 1 1/2 minutes. Turn over carefully
and allow to cook for 2 1/2 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   To serve, set the salad into the center of the plate and place
the trout on top of the salad. Spoon some of the liquid from the
salad around the perimeter of the plate. Squeeze the lime wedge
over the trout and garnish with the whole chives.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 316 calories, 13 g fat, 97 mg
cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 63 mg sodium, 35 percent calories
from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barbecued Onion Soup with Jalapeno Jack Cheese &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From chef Robert McGrath) &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 cup thin strips of smoked yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thin strips of smoked red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped and smoked leeks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup roasted chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark chile powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef stock (the chef uses veal demi-glace)
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fine strips of onion for garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark chile powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   4 round sourdough croutons
</P>
<P>
   4 1/4-inch slices jalapeno jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Caramelize the onions, leeks, shallot and garlic by cooking them
slowly in a little oil in a heavy pot or Dutch oven until they are
dark brown. Add the chile powder, sugar and barbecue sauce. Add the
beef and chicken stocks and simmer until mixture is reduced by
one-third. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Just before ready to serve, make the garnishes. Mix a teaspoon
of chile powder with the flour in a bowl or in a plastic bag, and
toss the fine onion strips in the mixture. Fry the strips in a cast
iron skillet in the hot vegetable oil until crisp. Drain on paper
towels and keep hot.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the soup into fireproof serving bowls. Place the crouton
on the surface of the soup. Place the slice of cheese on top of the
crouton and carefully run it under a preheated broiler. Broil
briefly, until brown. Keep an eye on it at all times. (You may also
melt the cheese atop the crouton separately, keep it hot, then add
it to the soup.)
</P>
<P>
   Serve the soup topped with the fried onions and sprinkled with
the chopped chives.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke the onions in your smoker or cut onions into thick slices,
put them on a barbecue grill, and cover them with a cast-iron lid
or an inverted cast-iron skillet or Dutch oven to capture smoke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 414 calories, 17 g fat, 30 mg
cholesterol, 49 g carbohydrates, 1,708 mg sodium (or use homemade
beef stock and lower the sodium count significantly), 36 percent
calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cast Iron-Cooked Beef Tenderloin Mashed Potatoes &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From chef Robert McGrath) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mashed Potatoes:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
4 peeled, cubed russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped, sauteed yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons roasted chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup beef stock (the chef uses veal demi-glace)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared horseradish
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
Tenderloin:
</P>
<P>
   4 pieces beef tenderloin, 5 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   16 steamed asparagus spears
</P>
<P>
   16 potato chips (purchased or homemade by frying thin slices of
potato in hot oil in a Dutch oven)
</P>
<P>
   Boil the potatoes until thoroughly cooked, then drain and roast
in the oven for 5 minutes to remove excess moisture. In a mixing
bowl, put the potatoes, onions, garlic, sour cream, milk and
cilantro, and mix thoroughly. Add the butter and season to taste
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, make the sauce. Whip the beef stock (or
demi-glace), barbecue sauce, red wine and the horseradish together
and season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Season the beef tenderloin with salt and pepper and grill to the
desired temperature.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place a mound of the mashed potatoes in the center of
an individual serving-size cast iron skillet and stick the potato
chips in the mashed potatoes. Place the filet on the mashed
potatoes and chips. Spoon the sauce around the perimeter of the
skillet and arrange the asparagus around the perimeter on the
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 685 calories, 50 g fat, 137 mg
cholesterol, 29 g carbohydrates, 487 mg sodium, 65 percent calories
from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
