<HEADLINE>
IRON WARE NEEDS CARE, SEASONING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Cast iron cookware has many advantages. It wears like,
well, cast iron. And it's inexpensive. You can buy a skillet for
$15 or so and use it throughout the rest of your culinary life. The
handle will never fall off.
</P>
<P>
   A properly seasoned cast iron skillet will become non-stick
through use. But there's the rub, so to speak. How do you season
cast iron? It's not mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   New pans are dark gray in color and will eventually darken to
black with use. Pans are shipped with a coating of wax sealant to
keep them from rusting in transit, explained Carol McClain, manager
of consumer services for Wagner Manufacturing, an Ohio company that
has made cast iron cookware since 1891.
</P>
<P>
   The wax coating should first be scrubbed off the entire surface
of the pan with hot water and a soapy steel-wool pad. Now, you have
to seal the porous surface of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, apply a thin coat of fat over all the pan, inside
and out, with a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to use solid vegetable shortening, such as Crisco.
Your grandmother probably used lard or bacon grease to season pans.
Now, it's not recommended because it might become rancid over time.
</P>
<P>
   Lodge Manufacturing, a Tennessee cast iron cookware company,
recommends a good grade of olive or vegetable oil for this purpose.
McClain tells consumers she doesn't advocate using peanut oil.
Whatever you choose, don't use a lot of it because overseasoning
can make a pan sticky instead of slick.
</P>
<P>
   Sources recommend varying times for heating the pans for
seasoning, but the consensus is to stick the coated skillet in an
oven heated to 250 to 350 degrees. Either turn the pan upside down
to let the excess fat drip off (put something underneath to catch
it) or take the pan out after 15 minutes and pour off the excess.
Then put it back in.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the pan in the oven to bake for at least an hour. Two to
three hours is fine. Then turn off the oven and remove the pan, or
leave it in there until it's cool.
</P>
<P>
   Your pan is seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   New pans will probably smell while cooking in your oven. It is
not unpleasant, but you might want to turn on an exhaust fan.
</P>
<P>
   Don't store cast iron pieces with the lids on, because it might
trap moisture that causes rust.
</P>
<P>
   One ``rule'' about cast iron cookware is that you're never
supposed to wash it with soap. As with all rules, this one is meant
to be broken. Chef Robert McGrath of Roaring Fork in Scottsdale
always uses soap and water to clean cast iron, and then rubs it
down with oil and salt, which he wipes out with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   If you make cornbread in your skillet or Dutch oven, it will pop
out easily and you can simply wipe out the pan with paper towels.
If you make stew, that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape out all the food residue, then use hot water (never cold)
and a plastic scrubber or stiff natural fiber brush to remove the
rest. If you use steel wool or a metal brush, you'll have to
reseason. Rinse well in hot water and dry thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Drying is important because of the rust risk.
</P>
<P>
   Many cooks put their cast iron, at this point, back into a warm
oven or on a warm burner to make sure it's completely dry.
</P>
<P>
   Some sources say not to use cast iron cookware to prepare
recipes with high-acid foods, such as tomatoes, because this will
take off the coating. Nutritionists have said for years that this
very thing can be a good source of iron in the diet.
</P>
<P>
   If your cast iron rusts, McClain said, scrub it off with steel
wool or run it through a self-cleaning oven cycle. Then reseason.
</P>
<P>
   You can do the same thing if you find old cast iron that has
black crusty flakes. In the old days, pioneers would stick it right
into the fire. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
