<HEADLINE>
BAKINGIN A DUTCH OVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED- Lodge Manufacturing gives these directions for baking
in a Dutch oven. As with anything else, it gets easier with
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ignite briquettes 15 to 20 minutes before you need them, or get
a fire going 30 to 45 minutes before if using hot coals. Prepare
food and ovens for cooking. If your dish takes longer, you will
need additional coals or briquettes to replenish those used.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange briquettes under oven bottom in a circular pattern at
least { inch inside the oven's edge. Put briquettes on top of the
lid in a checkerboard pattern. Bunching briquettes can cause hot
spots and burn the contents. To prevent small hot-spot problems,
lift and rotate the oven one-quarter turn every 10 to 15 minutes
and then rotate the lid one-quarter turn in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Check food occasionally, but be careful when removing the lid.
If adding briquettes, do so in equal portions to top and bottom. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Baking temperature chart for 10-in Dutch oven
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
325 degrees: 19 briquets, 13 on bottom, 6 on top
</P>
<P>
   350 degrees: 21 briquets, 14 on bottom, 7 on top
</P>
<P>
   375 degrees: 23 briquettes, 16 on bottom, 7 on top
</P>
<P>
   400 degrees: 25 briquets, 17 on bottom, 8 on top
</P>
<P>
   425 degrees: 27 briquets, 18 on bottom, 9 on top
</P>
<P>
   450 degrees: 29 briquets, 19 on bottom, 10 on top
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
