<HEADLINE>
GROUP TO MARK ANNIVERSARY OF PEDAL-POWER PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bicyclists who advocate two-wheeled commuting
plan to mark the first anniversary Friday of a disruptive
pedal-powered protest for improved biking conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But organizers and the police say this year's action should be
quieter than a year ago, when 105 people were arrested in an event
that paralyzed vehicular traffic during the afternoon rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say as many as 5,000 bicyclists are expected to mark
the one-year anniversary of Critical Mass, which launched bicycle
politics in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to be big,'' said Leah Shahum of the San
Francisco Bicycle Coalition. ``I think there is a lot of anger out
there ... We expect to see a lot of creative energy on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Ackerson, a spokesman for the police, said the bicycle
ride might slow traffic, but he expected no confrontations. The
department in recent months has tried not to antagonize the cycling
community but promises to arrest anyone who goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate it will be peaceful,'' Ackerson said. ``There
are no special preparations. We don't plan to throw lots of troops
at this thing. ... They've been behaving themselves. We hope it
stays that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bicyclists are seeking more accommodations, including bike lanes
on busy streets, to encourage people to leave their cars and pedal
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Some anger lingers at the way cyclists took over downtown on
July 27, 1997. Also, many bike riders remain bitter over actions by
the police last July and in subsequent rides. Although 105 people
were arrested last year, charges were dropped against all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycle advocates are far from satisfied, but they as well as
city officials agree that Critical Mass has given bike riders
political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the chaotic last year, Mayor Willie Brown vowed to
make ``San Francisco the nation's most bicycle-friendly city.''
</P>
<P>
   But cyclists are disappointed with a number of policy decisions
by the city, especially the rejection of most of their Bicycle
Route Network plan designed to encourage more people to ride bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really noticing that the mayor hasn't followed through
on what he promised a year ago,'' Shahum said. ``We're seeing a
lack of commitment from a year ago. The rejection of improvements
to eight of the 10 streets in our proposed bicycle route shows that
there is no commitment to true accessibility for bicyclists in San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyclists did praise the installation of hundreds of new bicycle
racks in the city. They also have praised efforts to add bicycle
lanes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
