<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LOLITA-AZR &LR;      07-30 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOLITA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOLITA' FINALLY FINDS A WILLING PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. - Cable television has also become a home for
projects that the mainstream movie industry can't accommodate. On
Sunday, Showtime will premiere director Adrian Lyne's adaptation of
Vladimir Nobokov's 1954 novel, ``Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobokov's story is about a middle-age college professor's
obsessive romantic relationship with a teenage girl. Made as a
feature film two years ago, it failed to find a distributor that
would play it in theaters. (Lyne's deal with Showtime allows for a
limited theatrical release).
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Irons (``Reversal of Fortune,'' '`The Man in the Iron
Mask``) plays the professor, Humbert Humbert. Newcomer Dominique
Swain, a Malibu High School senior, plays the title character.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Stanley Kubrick directed an earlier adaptation,
starring James Mason and Sue Lyon, but Lyne's directing credits _
which include such slick, sexually charged movies as ``Fatal
Attraction'' and ``Indecent Proposal'' _ made this version suspect
from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   There are many interpretations of Nabokov's book, of course. Not
all of them say it's just about titillation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's about many things, like any great work,'' said
Irons, who was interviewed via satellite by members of the
Television Critics Association, meeting here recently for their
twice annual TV publicity tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tragedy. I think it's a love story. I think
it's a portrait of America at a certain time. It has many levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any great work, you can take it for what you want. For
me, because I was the protagonist, it is a love story, and a
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little wary of playing Humbert Humbert because I felt
I played enough oddballs for one career. And so I fought against it
for a while. Adrian was very passionate that I should do it, which
is very flattering, and then accused me of being politically
correct by turning it down, which made me think because I felt that
one of the functions of the arts is to stir up debate, to make
people question things in life, and standards, and make people see
situations from a different viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I felt, `This is a film that should be made.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Making it might've been as difficult as getting it distributed.
Swain was 15 during filming. Accompanied on the set at all times by
her mother, Swain couldn't directly participate in many of the more
intimate scenes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's technically illegal to portray some such scenes
with an adult body double standing in for a minor. Lyne told the
critics that he spent six weeks in an editing room, with an
attorney at his side, to deliver a legally releasable film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, from my point of view, incredibly difficult, but
incredibly useful, that difficulty, in that I was supposed to be
obsessed with somebody, who, of course, I couldn't be obsessed
with,'' said Irons.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you're acting, it's a strange sort of thing. You play
with reality. And this was a reality I couldn't play with, so I
felt like somebody said to me, `Try and do ``Raging Bull,'' but
don't hit the guy, and certainly don't hurt the guy, and really
don't even touch the guy. Don't even think about touching the guy.
But make it look as if you're killing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite difficult, but, of course, useful because
Humbert was aware that what he was doing was damaging, that what he
was doing was wrong. And so I was able to use that difficulty. But
it wasn't an easy shoot.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dave Walker is the television critic for The Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
