<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTIONS-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICAN ELECTIONS TEST PRI'S GRIP ON FAITHFUL, LEFT'S STRENGTH
AMONG INDIANS
</P>
<P>
   With photo placed in the International folder on the Cox Server.
</P>
<P>
   For purposes of a locator map: Oaxaca, the capital of the state
of Oaxaca, is 321 miles southeast of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Contains optional add.
</P>
<P>
   For Use Saturday, Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   By SUSAN FERRISS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   c1998 Cox News Service &QC;
</P>
<P>
   OAXACA, Mexico _ On the eve of Mexico's gubernatorial elections
here, it was business as usual down at the offices of the
Revolutionary Institutional Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   Three old farmers in weather-worn hats sat patiently waiting for
their turn to talk to party representatives. They needed an
electric water pump for their town, and they were turning to those
who they believed knew best how to get it for them.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the men will do what they do every election day:
They will vote for the candidate of the PRI, the same political
party that has dominated life here for the last 70 years and, for
many, is still synonymous with government and country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other parties say they don't have the money to help us,''
shrugged Celso Moreno, 75, who views the PRI -- not an impartial
public sector -- as the generous entity that built a high school in
his town and is now paving roads.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's political landscape is shifting dramatically and
becoming more pluralistic with each election. Yet for many Mexicans
a vote against the PRI is still unfathomable, even unpatriotic.
Sunday's showdown in the southern state of Oaxaca (pronounced
Wa-HA-ka), will test the PRI's strength -- and its grip on the
party faithful -- as its candidate for governor competes with a
strong challenger from Mexico's burgeoning left-center movement,
the Party of the Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   PRI contender Jose Murat is a party loyalist and senator who has
an edge in the polls. The PRD's Hector Sanchez is also a senator
and a full-blooded Zapotec Indian, a heritage that matters in a
state of extreme poverty where 40 percent of three million
residents speak an Indian language.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez views his candidacy as the result of 25 years of fierce
grassroots Indian struggle against the PRI, whose patronage he
believes has failed miserably to meet the needs of Oaxaca's poorest
Indians. Sanchez was one of the original leaders of a militant
anti-PRI organization, the Worker, Peasant, Student Coalition of
the Isthmus (COSEI), which fights for basic services and political
plurality.
</P>
<P>
   The group claims that 50 of its members have been assassinated
and more than 600 jailed on various bogus charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation only began to change with the birth of the PRD
in 1989,'' said Sanchez, who was himself jailed and forced to leave
the state to save his life in the late 1970s. The party, Sanchez
said, has given many disgruntled Indians whose living conditions
have deteriorated a vehicle for political expression.
</P>
<P>
   When Oaxacans went to the polls in 1992 to select federal
deputies, for example, the PRD captured only 10 percent of the
vote. Last year that figure leaped to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a great civic awakening among people who are
tired of lies and abandonment,'' Sanchez said in an interview with
the Cox News Service. He said poverty has become so grinding some
Oaxacans have chosen ``the wrong path'' and joined the armed
Popular Revolutionary Army (EPR), a mysterious Marxist guerrilla
group that has skirmished with the Mexican Army in Oaxaca and
neighboring Guerrero state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has only created more repression, and less democracy,''
Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   And bad publicity for the PRD, which the PRI has sought to link
to the guerrillas. In a PRI election ad aired on local radio
stations, listeners are treated to fiery PRD speeches designed to
portray the leftist opposition as irresponsible and violent.
``Don't get burned by the sun,'' a voice warns, referring to the
party's Aztec sun symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the PRD imported some of its top national leaders to
attend a closing rally and boost Sanchez's profile. Many in a
throng of supporters were Indians who wore traditional Zapotec
clothing, and Sanchez offered part of a campaign speech in Zapotec,
which is his native language.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI doesn't work anymore. We need a change,'' said
supporter Ignacio Morales, a 68-year-old peasant wearing leather
sandals.
</P>
<P>
   He said PRI officials in his hometown of Salina Cruz(CQ) used to
``sell'' water to residents. He grew weary of the corrupt practice
and supported the COSEI, which he credits with fighting for basic
water delivery to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Morales said, he receives water twice a week. But he still
only makes about 25 pesos -- less than $3 -- a day, and he doesn't
feel the PRI cares about his plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of hope that Hector will win, although people
believe the PRI is ready to unleash fraud on Sunday,'' added Aurora
Pineda, a COSEI loyalist for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The PRD has complained that the PRI is up to old tricks, out
buying votes by offering bundles of money while also engaging in
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he was barred from entering San Agustin Loxicha, a
rural town, by masked PRI supporters who gave him a letter
declaring that ``we do not want any incursions from any other party
than the Official Party'' because the other parties ``only come to
provoke problems and divisiveness among our Indian brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he doesn't believe fair elections can be held under
such circumstances, and that fraud is sure to occur.
</P>
<P>
   PRI campaign spokesman Carlos Velasco dismissed the allegations
as sour grapes because the PRI is ahead in the polls. ``When the
PRD won in Mexico City last year, nobody complained there was
fraud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Velasco also said the PRD has been hurt by its association with
the COSEI, which many Oaxacans view as too radical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the triumph of the PRI this Sunday will be very
clear,'' Velasco said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, during a separate round of gubernatorial races, the
PRI proved it can make a comeback from where it previously lost
ground. In the border state of Chihuahua, its candidate recaptured
the governor's seat from the more conservative Party of National
Action (PAN).
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, it is expected to win the governor's race in
Veracruz, but it is fighting a close race in Aguascalientes state
against a popular PAN candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Also on July 5, the PRI lost a governor's seat in Zacatecas
state to the PRD. But the PRD's candidate had only recently
defected to the PRD from the PRI because he was angry that the
party brass failed to select him as their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A victory for Sanchez in Oaxaca would be a much greater triumph
for the PRD's peasant supporters. But even if Sanchez loses the PRD
stands to pick up more local deputies on Sunday and gain more
experience in the electoral arena in a critical state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember that if the coin falls on one side it doesn't
mean that the other one disappears,'' warned the generally pro-PRI
columnist Juan Ruiz Healy, writing in Novedades, a Mexico City
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
