<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNEY-SUIT-TEX     07-30 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEY-SUIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNEY'S VERY, VERY, VERY BAD WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA and TERRY LEE GOODRICH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For a dinosaur who lifted his theme song
from ``This Old Man,'' you could say it's a case of The Chicken
coming home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   Barney, TV's purplest and most litigious Tyrannosaurus rex, lost
a copyright suit on Wednesday to a feathered foe.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any barnyard bird, mind you, but The Famous San Diego
Chicken, a celebrity fowl known to pummel a Barney look-alike as
part of his comedy routines at professional sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Even before a Fort Worth federal judge threw out the suit, it
was a bad week for Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity was slipped into a news release touting his new
sing-along cassettes as ``perfect for a short or long car trip
anywhere!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having those little s---- clamoring to stop at the
next McDonald's, or those interminable whines of `When we gonna get
there?' or `I really gotta go, Mommy,' plug their ears with these
latest banalities ... and you're guaranteed to arrive free of
stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Barney says computer hackers targeted his Los Angeles-based PR
firm, Nina Stern Public Relations Co., and inserted the naughty
language into the news release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're too close to it to think it's funny,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Barney didn't think The Chicken was funny either when, in 1994,
he added a purple-and-green reptile to the antics he'd been
performing for two decades at professional sports matches.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-minute act _ one of more than 100 routines The Chicken
hatches at an average game _ the Barney clone joins him for a rap
dance. After a clumsy start, the dinosaur outdances ]The Chicken.
The bested bird turns him into a prehistoric punching bag, but not
before Mr. I-Love-You-You-Love-Me throws a few punches himself.
</P>
<P>
   The free-lance _ make that free-range _ mascot has performed the
routine all over the country, including at Texas Rangers games.
</P>
<P>
   The Richardson, Texas, company behind Barney, Lyons Partnership,
sued The Chicken, a k a Ted Giannoulas. The company alleged that
the routine violated its copyright and trademark on the ``purple,
highly stylized Tyrannosaurus rex-type dinosaur character with a
friendly mien, a swath of green down his chest and stomach, and
green spots on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern has always been that young children in an
audience at a sporting event don't realize it's not the real Barney
and some of those children become visibly upset when they see
Barney beaten up,'' said Kelly Lane, public relations director for
Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge John McBryde said the routine is clearly
parody and is not likely to cause trademark confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``By placing the putative Barney character in an ego-driven,
urban-style rap dance competition and wrestling match, he portrays
the character in an original and unexpected light,'' McBryde wrote.
`` ... Spectators at sporting events would not normally expect to
see the real Barney and the Chicken performing together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken could not be reached to comment. He was performing
at a minor-league baseball game on the East Coast, where, his
lawyer said, he was likely doing the Barney routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will continue to do so, so long as it makes people laugh,''
said Kenneth Fitzgerald, The Chicken's San Diego attorney. ``The
show must go on.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
