<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX     07-30 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROY DISNEY: THE MAN BEHIND WALT AND MICKEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney could have attributed much of his amazing career and
business success to one character _ and it wasn't Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Roy Disney, was the financial genius behind the
entertainment mogul.
</P>
<P>
   From the day in 1923 when he left the Midwest to join his
brother in California, Walt was dreaming big expensive dreams. Roy
went looking for money for his little brother while trying to keep
Walt's creative perfectionism in check with accounting realities.
</P>
<P>
   Roy ``was the bookkeeping man, the money man, the man trying to
keep Walt under control,'' an early Disney art director said.
``Walt was like a spinning flywheel, spinning revolutions that kept
the thing going. When Walt wanted to spend everything on the next
picture, Roy would say, `Let's keep a little sinking fund _ in case
we sink.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And sink they often did. It is hard to imagine, considering the
company's golden touch today, that Disney classics such as
``Bambi'' and ``Fantasia'' were originally box office flops.
Start-up financing problems, a garage-based workplace and
stress-related illnesses made the business look like most typical
entrepreneurial efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Later, union strikes, budget overruns and World War II would
create major headaches for the struggling studio.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney story is chronicled in a fascinating new book,
``Building a Company: Roy O. Disney and the Creation of an
Entertainment Empire'' (Hyperion, 359 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned Hollywood author Bob Thomas, who also wrote a biography
of Walt, uses sources including friends, relatives, co-workers and
the Disney Archives, a collection begun in 1970 by UCLA
bibliographer David Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a candid, close look at the other pillar of the
Disney empire, a man few knew was so integral to the success of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy O. Disney's life was as private as his younger brother's
was public,'' Thomas writes.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only dichotomy between the two brothers, who
were 8 1/2 years apart in age. Their differences led to countless
arguments, even times of estrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``During one basic disagreement late in their lives, they did
not speak to each other for more than two years, communicating only
through emissaries,'' Thomas writes. ``The Disney family was Irish
and subject to stubborn temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   But dispite the friction and business fluctuations, the two
brothers worked magic.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas documents the creation of the first Mickey Mouse cartoon;
the first feature-length cartoon, ``Snow White;'' and the
Disneyland theme park. He has an eye for story and detail, making
readers feel as if they are in on the real moments.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thomas chronicles Roy Disney's pivotal role for perhaps
the first time, he concentrates more on each brother's influences
on the company, as well as those of their wives, parents and
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Roy's family ties that got him into his brother's
business so much as his health. Roy had a bout with tuberculosis,
and at 30 could not get a job because of the stigma the disease
carried at that time, Thomas writes.
</P>
<P>
   Then Walt showed up.
</P>
<P>
   As Roy recalls in the book: ``I was in the hospital at Sawtelle.
By correspondence (Walt) sold somebody in New York on a series of
pictures. One night he found his way to my bed, which was on a row
of beds on a screened porch. It was eleven or twelve o'clock at
night, and he shaked me awake and showed me a telegram of
acceptance of his offers. He said `What can I do now? Can you come
out of here and help me to get this started?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Roy left the next day, against medical advice, and spent the
next 48 years helping his brother create the magic of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
