<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0625 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SITCOMS-AZR &LR;      07-30 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SITCOMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE, JERRY; HELLO SHOWS ABOUT SOMETHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The legacy of ``Seinfeld'' is the pursuit of
nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   The recently retired sitcom, which emphasized the sub-trivial
pursuits of young, urban singles, spawned a generation of
broadcast-network comedies targeted at the young, urban audience
that seemed to share the ``Seinfeld'' world-view.
</P>
<P>
   That audience is greatly desired by advertisers, and,
accordingly, big broadcast networks, who've mostly abandoned older
viewers to cable in pursuit of ever more specific younger
demographics. But the field of topics for most current comedies _
dating, dining out and dead-end jobs _ leaves a lot of life
experience untouched. If those topics aren't nothing, they're
nothing much.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, a comedy sameness has come over the big networks,
and grown-up comedy makers have begun to turn elsewhere for
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, two cable nets not known for original
comedies will debut four shows that appear to be about something.
The premium network Showtime goes first, with ``Linc's'' and ``Rude
Awakening,'' which debut on Saturday. Lifetime rolls out its new
comedies, ``Maggie'' and ``Oh, Baby'' on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I think is the definition of `cutting edge'
right now?'' asked Diane English, the creator of ``Murphy Brown,''
speaking here recently with TV critics. ``It's a show about
something. It's a show that has a point of view, that has a voice.
Do you know how rare that is?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to cable, maybe not so rare. The four new shows:
</P>
<P>
   - ``Linc's``: Set in a bar in Washington, D.C., Showtime's
``Linc's'' casts Pam Grier (``Jackie Brown''), Steven Williams
(``The X-Files``) and Georg (cq ) Stanford Brown (Tyson) in an
African-American ensemble comedy that promises to address grown-up
concerns, including politics.
</P>
<P>
   The series creator is Tim Reid, known to most as Venus Flytrap
in the classic sitcom WKRP in Cincinnati, and remembered by many as
one of the creative forces behind ``Frank's Place,'' which aired
briefly in the 1987-88 TV season and was one of the best little
shows that ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Rude Awakening``: Sherilyn Fenn (``Twin Peaks``) stars as
Billie Frank, a sobriety-challenged actress just beginning to deal
with recovery. Lynn Redgrave (``Georgy Girl,`` ``Shine``) plays her
mother, whose own capacity for drink explains a lot about her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The show is based largely on the life of its creator and
executive producer, Claudia Lonow (``Knot's Landing``), the product
of a show-business family (her father Mark, co-owns Hollywood's
famed Improvisation comedy club).
</P>
<P>
   Here's an indication of where this one might go: Frank's boss,
the least-neurotic character in the cast, is played by Richard
Lewis. (Who, it was revealed at the show's session at the
Television Critics Association (TCA) Summer publicity Tour,
actually once baby-sat Lonow, then later dated her.)
</P>
<P>
   - `` Maggie``: Ann Cusack plays Maggie Day, a seemingly happily
married woman about to turn 40. She's got a successful husband of
19 years, a teenage daughter who doesn't appear to be too troubled,
and enough ambition to want to return to school to become a
veterinarian. She's also got very vivid fantasies about soap stud
Jack Wagner, and is showing symptoms of approaching midlife crisis.
</P>
<P>
   This series will display zany daydream sequences that will seem
familiar to Ally McBeal fans, but Cusack (out of the fabled Cusack
acting family, she's worked in ``From the Earth to the Moon'' and
``The Jeff Foxworthy Show'') seems highly likable.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Oh, Baby``: Cynthia Stevenson plays Tracy, who's single and
successful but thirtysomething and childless. Her otherwise fine
boyfriend has commitment problems, so a discussion with pal
Charlotte (Joanne Gleason) leads Tracy to the local sperm bank.
</P>
<P>
   The single-momhood premise will be a challenge to sustain, but
Stevenson (``Hope &AMP; Gloria, ``Bob``) and Gleason (``Love and War)''
should be terrific together.
</P>
<P>
   (Lifetime also debuts an original hourlong drama Aug. 18.
Starring Annie Potts (``Designing Women,'' ``Dangerous Minds'') and
Lorraine Toussaint (``Law and Order,`` ``Leaving LA``), the series
observes, via the relationship of two lifelong friends, the
evolution of race relations in the South.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
An old argument &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the quality's-on-cable conversation began long ago,
especially on the topic of original movies and miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks' ``From the Earth to the Moon'' recently got more Emmy
nominations for HBO than any program from the 1997-98 season.
Overall, cable's recent Emmy nominations increased - thanks to
prestige projects from TNT (``George Wallace''), USA (``Moby
Dick``) and Showtime (``Armistead Maupin's More Tales of the
City``) - during a year in which HBO's numbers fell.
</P>
<P>
   And an early contender for a big Emmy haul next season is sure
to be ``The Baby Dance,'' a Showtime film based on the play by Jane
Anderson. Starring Stockard Channing and Laura Dern - and
co-produced by new mom Jody Foster - ``The Baby Dance'' debuts Aug.
23.
</P>
<P>
   When Hanks and Foster - perhaps the two most powerful
actor-director-producer hyphenates in Hollywood - are taking
passion projects to cable, the medium's standing as a prestige
destination appears secure.
</P>
<P>
   With a few rare exceptions, however - HBO's ``Dream On,'' say,
or ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' which a couple of weeks ago won
another best-comedy award from the Television Critics Association -
cable hasn't made episodic comedy much of a priority.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast networks' pursuit of young viewers isn't the only
factor driving studios and their producers to cable. Networks have
shown favoritism to shows they ``own'' _ and will profit from in
syndication - over series owned by other production entities, such
as big Hollywood studios, who deficit-finance most shows betting on
the prospects of huge back-end profits in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   Networks pursuing a specific young-demographics business plan
also are more likely to meddle in the creative details of show
production. Some cable networks, especially pay services, also
offer writers and producers more freedom to explore adult
situations. Rough language and even a little tame nudity _ both
features of Showtime's ``Rude Awakening,'' for example - sometimes
allow a script to escape the three-jokes-per-page rhythms of
mainstream network fare.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, cable networks generate revenue in ways other than
selling ad time, which allows them to be less dependent on
assembling the largest possible audience.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave believes the intrusion of network executives in the
day-to-day composition of a series is one of the nuisances of
working for a broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them restraints-and-practices police, who live in some
curious room and send down edicts to the floor _ when you're
rehearsing very hard and working a scene - very often based on a
table reading that somebody's heard or a memo from some mysterious,
never-identified person,'' she said. ``And it is the most
frustrating thing for performers.''
</P>
<P>
   At Showtime, she added, ``We don't get that sense of being
policed by people who probably haven't seen us bring a scene to
life.'' And, aside from a crack about Bill Clinton's personal life,
when was the last time you heard a network comedy even mention
politics?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a network would be the place for this show,''
said Reid of ``Linc's``. ``It is really a show that would find a
home on cable. About five years ago, I realized that if ``Frank's
Place'' had been on Showtime that it would probably have stayed on
about five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ``Linc's'' is too political for network. God, the
first show, the sponsor would be calling: `I mean, you've got a guy
coming in saying, `There's too much persecution of the tobacco
industry. Don't they know that they've employed more people than
they've killed?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would create a problem for a network.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A focus on youth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even producers of successful mainstream comedies have begun to
grouse about the constraints of getting a comedy that's not a
permutation of the ``Seinfeld/Friends'' model on one of the larger
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Finestra, supervising producer on ``The Cosby Show'' and
co-creator of ``Home Improvement, ``Soul Man'' and the new Fox
comedy ``Costello,'' told the TCA members that his mother had
called him to protest ABC's cancellation of ``Soul Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I called (ABC programing chief) Jamie Tarses and told her
that my mother, a 78-year-old woman, was upset that she canceled a
show, she'd be thrilled,'' he said. ``The networks are choosing to
lose that audience'' while ``going to that which is profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   (The 20-second explanation of why young demographics are so
important: According to Madison Avenue, your product-selection
glands dry up at age 50, freezing until death the brand of auto
tire you will buy. In theory, consumers age 12-34 can still be
wooed to make the big switch from Mountain Dew to RC. Accordingly,
advertisers pay a premium to reach that demo. True, the population
is aging, and folks in the upper demographics have the most
disposable cash. CBS has claimed it is having some success in
selling its older audience to ad buyers, who are, according to
legend, all twentysomething women.)
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lorre, creator and executive producer of ``Grace Under
Fire,'' ``Cybill'' and ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' said cable's comedy
emergence is ``wonderful, great for TV,'' he said. ``There'll be
more of a Sundance mentality, where television is developed with
less stringent controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monopoly is over. That's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   For producers, some drawbacks remain. The audiences for
individual cable programs remain minuscule compared with even the
lesser-rated efforts of broadcast networks, and budgets for cable
shows generally are correspondingly lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to the trouble of creating a show, you want a lot
of people to see it,'' said Peter Casey, a writer and supervising
producer for ``Cheers,'' co-creator of ``Wings,'' ``Frasier'' and
``Encore! Encore!``, a new-for-fall NBC sitcom starring Nathan
Lane. ``There's nothing more frustrating than going through all of
that sweat, and nobody came to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dean Valentine, CEO and president of the fledgling UPN
network, said the narrowcasting approach of his broadcast
competitors is ultimately ``doomed to failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences have been shrinking for years, and, of all the big
networks, only NBC made money last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the sameness of network programing is driven by
narrowcasting, by targeting the same 18- to 35-year-old audience,
and doing one show after another where there's somebody working at
a magazine office or an advertising office or some glamorous job,''
said Valentine, whose network is offering a new fall schedule
targeted at a wider audience than its startup competitor, the WB,
which has evidently targeted suburban teen girls as its core
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, shows like ``Roseanne'' and ``Home Improvement''
are getting harder for people to find on network television as it
abandons the adult audience and family audience and every au dience
that's not that one audience.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dave Walker is the movie critic for The Arizona Republic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
