<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-EVERAFTER-TEX     07-30 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EVERAFTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVER AFTER' LEAVES A NUTRA SWEET TASTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Set in 16th-century France, ``Ever After'' is such a politically
correct rendering of the Cinderella story that the stepmother isn't
even evil anymore. She's just snippy. Fortunately, she is played by
Anjelica Huston, who cruises through ``Ever After'' like a slumming
diva; her insouciance is such that the movie achieves a state of
grace when she is onscreen. As Danielle, the Cinderella figure,
Drew Barrymore is such a contemporary embodiment of Girl Power that
she might as well be working at the Gap. Director and co-scripter
Andy Tennant did make a funny movie. Sometimes, it's even funny on
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle is thrilled when her father brings home his new wife
(Huston) and a pair of stepsisters. Daddy dotes on young Danielle.
Having taught his little girl to read, he gives her a copy of
``Utopia.'' It's not exactly the most suitable reading for an
8-year-old, but he doesn't have long to live, so who's gonna hold
it against him? He tumbles off his horse, after grasping his left
arm in pain for his entire time onscreen. He doesn't get to shout,
``Elizabeth, I'm comin' to join ya, honey,'' but he might as well;
his heart attack is as underimagined as almost everything else.
</P>
<P>
   A flash-forward shows a young adult Danielle (Barrymore) going
at her chores, and winning over the servants with her charm and
guilelessness. Meanwhile, the pouty Prince (Dougray Scott) has fled
the palace in a fit of pique over being forced into a marriage of
convenience. The two meet when he tries to steal the horse that
belonged to Danielle's father _ and she knocks him off with a
well-flung apple. Danielle falls in love with the prince anyway,
even though he's so dim and self-involved he doesn't recognize her
when she masquerades as a noblewoman. Maybe it's the absence of the
carefully applied soot from her face that throws him off; it's the
only thing that's the slightest bit different about her appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore is a bold good sport. She may be the first actress to
gain baby fat in her early 20s instead of losing it _ the planes of
her face have disappeared _ but she is a charming dumpling. She's
spunky and self-assured, a straightforward answer to the waifish,
victimized Cinderella of most fairy tales. Barrymore's
groundedness, and Huston's brittle theatricality, give ``Ever
After'' a lilt, even though the movie doesn't deserve them. This
story is all business, debunking the fairy godmothers and
dreaminess, and determined to add egalitarianism to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Such an updating makes sense. What doesn't make sense is ``Ever
After's'' trailer, which positions the movie as an overwrought
romantic fantasy of the ``Great Expectations'' variety, complete
with a loamy low-fi alt-rock song scoring the flash-cut images. In
fact, sense is the order of the day _ so much common sense has been
packed into the story that it doesn't quite hold together anymore.
Danielle seems to have been transported to the locale from another
time, or cobbled together by an Action for Children's Television
subcommittee. All this meddling to make the story palatable, and
inspire a young girl audience, gives it a Nutra Sweet aftertaste.
With all of the current references and attitudes _ at one point,
the King growls, ``It's not about love!'' to his overprivileged son
_ ``Ever After'' loses a fairy tale's ability to enchant, as well
as the streak of cruelty that makes a fairy tale stick with you. If
you rob a magic trick of its mystique, it's not magic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ever After''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Drew Barrymore, Anjelica Huston
</P>
<P>
   Director: Andy Tennant
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ mild violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
