a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV06-     07-30 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIME, SECDOND-TIME PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday Aug. 6)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Diaper Genie. The black-and-white developmental mobile. The
battery-powered baby swing that goes through a six-pack of size D
batteries each week. The six-generation family genealogy tree
chart.
</P>
<P>
   Some baby accessories are destined to be purchased only by
first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   It's like that diaper commercial on television, where the mother
and babe are in soft focus, with classical lullabies playing in the
background. Then, with the second and third child, the stark light
of day falls on a family running around the back yard, kids yelling
and rolling around laughing and parents trying to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the fantasy and the reality is often
bridged by taking seconds at the parenting picnic.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Unisar Inc. came out with Bebe Sounds, a prenatal
listening kit that allows pregnant women to ``have the excitement
and thrill of hearing and recording a baby's heartbeat prior to
birth,'' I thought immediately: first-time parent product.
</P>
<P>
   Bebe Sounds ($29.99, at Babies R Us or Toys R Us, or calling
800-430-0222) is an amplifier similar to ones obstetricians use to
check the baby's heartbeat during prenatal exams.
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit to being thrilled the first time I heard both my
children's rapid heartbeats. But once was plenty. To sit at home
and listen would have been an exercise in paranoia. Is the rate
faster today? Slower? What if the baby turned and I couldn't find a
beat at all? Doctors should be thankful more pregnant women don't
own home monitoring devices.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I'm sure Bebe Sounds will find its niche among
those first-timers who crave more prenatal contact with their
baby-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bebe Sounds ... by the end of the second trimester,
hiccups, kicks and even the heartbeat can be heard,'' says the
Unisar Inc. press release. ``These precious sounds will help bring
the mother and family even closer to their coming baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The device won the U.S. Consumer Electronics Show Innovations
Design and Engineering Award and Great Britain's Child and Nursery
Fair Top Gold Award.
</P>
<P>
   To gauge Bebe Sounds' appeal to new parents, I showed the
release to a colleague who has a 3-month-old daughter. Now, this
dad had been a bit cynical about the whole baby marketing trend
before he and his wife had a child, and I thought he would dismiss
the Bebe Sounds monitor as a techno-gadget for overly involved
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Quite the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would have been great,'' he said enthusiastically. ``I
tried to rewire my computer microphone to use it as a listening
device, and I bought a stethoscope, but neither was sensitive
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   He reminded me that, being the one who was pregnant, I never had
the ``outsider'' experience that expectant fathers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife could feel the baby kicking and moving and doing
stuff, and I couldn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, he's getting plenty of contact hours with baby
Riley.
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's the reason I think second-time parents wouldn't
be nearly as interested in Bebe Sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Amplification just doesn't hold the same appeal it once did.
After the infant comes out, the sounds he makes are quite loud
enough, thank you. Especially the ones that mean, ``I'm hungry;''
``I'm wet;'' ``I'm overly tired;'' or ``It's 3 a.m. and I'm
bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine months of blissful silence seems like a pretty good deal.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
