<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEGOTIATOR-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTAGE DRAMA NOT MUCH OF A BARGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``The Negotiator'' must have sounded like a hot idea
when it was first pitched to the movie studio: Two hostage
negotiators engage in a battle of wits when one of them switches
sides and becomes a hostage taker.
</P>
<P>
   But as the writers and director F. Gary Gray labored to
construct a scenario in which that idea would make sense, they must
have used a shovel instead of a pen. They dug themselves an
ever-deeper hole as the plot implodes.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, you're going to reach the point where you
think: Yeah, right, like that could actually happen.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Roman (Samuel L. Jackson) is the first hostage negotiator,
a dedicated hero working for the Chicago police.
</P>
<P>
   But when Danny's partner uncovers a major criminal scandal
within the police department and is murdered, Danny is framed for
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone turns against Danny so quickly that he feels his only
recourse is to take the chief investigator and several other people
hostage within the city administration high-rise.
</P>
<P>
   The story plummets down the believability scale right there _
especially when his lawyer says, ``There's nothing I can do for
you,'' even before Danny is arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The plot machinations get more convoluted and less believable as
the long hostage night wears on.
</P>
<P>
   Danny's plan is to hold the hostages long enough to prove his
innocence. Exactly how he's going to do that, he has no idea.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the second police negotiator, Chris Sabian (Kevin
Spacey), shows up to persuade Danny to release the hostages. But
Chris has an even tougher job: trying to keep dozens of rabid SWAT
cops from blasting into the office and killing Danny.
</P>
<P>
   Do they want to kill him because they're the real bad guys? Or
just because that's their passion in life?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an implausible plot, ``The Negotiator'' digs itself
into dramatic trouble from the beginning. We know Danny is
innocent, so we know he's not going to kill any of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, we spend most of the movie watching him run bluffs on
Chris and the other cops, bluffs we don't believe for a second.
</P>
<P>
   Director Gray ``(Set It Off)'' tries to smooth off the rough
edges of the story with psychological insights into the work of
police negotiators, who try to defuse violent situations using
their minds instead of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those insights are interesting, but not interesting
enough to keep you from picking the story apart as you watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Gray does maintain some on-screen tension once the bullets start
to fly, and the final showdown has its moments. Jackson is sweaty
and tense throughout, but his performance has none of the subtlety
he brought to ``Eve's Bayou'' or ``Pulp Fiction.'' Jackson's Danny
is more of a plot device than a real character.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey ``(L.A. Confidential``) remains unexpressively enigmatic
for most of the movie, which works in contrast to Jackson's heated
performance. But it's also a plot device, to keep us unsure about
who's side he's on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator'' would have worked better as an hourlong
episode on ``NYPD Blue'' or one of the other cop shows. Stretching
it over two hours exposes the holes in the plot and the dramatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator'' is rated R for profanity and violence. 2
stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
