r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BUFFALO66-TEX     07-30 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BUFFALO66-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET YOUR KICKS FROM `BUFFALO 66'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can you not be fascinated with a movie that features a tap
dance musical number staged in a bowling alley? Especially when
it's done by the kittenish Christina Ricci, who plays the
saucer-eyed but loving dimwit kidnapped by Billy Brown (Vincent
Gallo) to impress his folks in ``Buffalo 66.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy's an angry loser _ he vibrates with rage like a tuning
fork _ who seems in danger of exploding on his first day out of
prison. Not only was he in for a crime he didn't commit, he was
extorted into doing the crime because he lost a bet. A bet he made
to, yep, impress his parents, who wouldn't notice him if he were
set on fire and flung out of a moving plane into their house.
Probably the only thing that could make his mother (Anjelica
Huston) pay attention to him is if he hit the field as a member of
the Buffalo Bills; she still blames Billy because his birth made
her miss an important game. She's obsessed with the Bills, whose
pathetic NFL streak could make them the subject of a Verdi opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is about anger and obsession. Gallo, who wrote,
directed, and stars in the film, in addition to composing its
music, plays it all for comedy. So, even when the volume level is
jacked all the way up _ which is almost all the time _ ``Buffalo
66'' is funny.
</P>
<P>
   His Billy is an infant, who stomps and snarls when he isn't the
center of attention. He's also quite a naif, despite his tough-guy
act. When he snatches Layla _ whom he renames Wendy, after the love
of his life who got away _ he bellows at her, occasionally toning
the derision down to a mere bark. He drags her to his folks' house,
where initially he makes her pretend to be his wife, and she
sweetly warms to the task, bragging outrageously and unbelievably
about him. And here we see that he just treats her the way they
treat him.
</P>
<P>
   It's a modest spectacle, ``Buffalo 66,'' but it IS a spectacle.
The movie's all of a piece as well; it benefits Gallo's own
obsession with detail of every sort. He gets a soft, winning
performance from Ricci, dressed in powdery pastels that match her
makeup perfectly. She's a kind of kewpie doll, and she sparkles
under his care. In the movie, he eventually glows under her purity;
she's as devoted to him as a duckling, and clatters clumsily after
him in her 2-story platform tap shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo maintains consistency of tone by crafting the movie as a
series of long takes, so that the characters' behavior is the most
important aspect of the film. Even the musical numbers, such as
they are _ and ``Buffalo 66'' uses as much music as any full-blown
musical _ are one-take wonders. Ben Gazzara, as Billy's father,
gets to sing right into the camera in a scene as silly as it is
touching. ``Buffalo 66'' seems a combination of Dennis Potter,
cinema verite and the Three Stooges. (At a couple of points, when
Rosanna Arquette, Mickey Rourke and Jan Michael Vincent are
produced for cameos, it feels like the Where Are They Now? section
of ``People'' magazine, too.) It's an original combination of
elements, and it helps that Gallo knows exactly what he wants to
achieve. He does it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is unrated. It contains nudity, adult language,
sexuality and scenes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Buffalo 66''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Vincent Gallo, Christina Ricci, Anjelica Huston
</P>
<P>
   Director: Vincent Gallo
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Unrated
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0635 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BASEKETBALL-TEX     07-30 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BASEKETBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `BASEKETBALL,' BEING A GOOD SPORT IS FOUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``BASEketball'' is the type of movie that few people will see
once. They'll either avoid it, driven away by previews and ads that
make it look aggressively stupid (which it often is), or go back
for repeat viewings to catch all the dialogue and cameos they
missed the first time _ and eventually, rent the video so they can
memorize it.
</P>
<P>
   Couples break up over movies like this. If it's early in your
relationship, and you're not laughing and your date is, it's a
pretty good sign that you're not destined for eternal bliss.
</P>
<P>
   Director David Zucker and his co-writers certainly have their
target audience firmly in mind. Any movie that mixes sports,
``South Park,'' Yasmine Bleeth and Jenny McCarthy isn't going to be
fighting ``Hope Floats'' for fans. (Although you don't have to be
male to enjoy it, as evidenced by the two young women at the
preview screening who laughed loudly at every joke that's been
spoiled by the trailers.)
</P>
<P>
   In a summer when theaters could promote the Lowbrow Comedy of
the Week, ``BASEketball'' falls somewhere between the Farrelly
Brothers' ``There's Something About Mary'' and ``Mafia!,'' which
was directed by Jim Abrahams, Zucker's former partner. Like
``Mary,'' it's politically incorrect and sometimes mean-spirited,
featuring gags at the expense of gays and terminally ill children.
Like ``Mafia!,'' it takes an anything-for-a-laugh approach, and how
much it succeeds depends on how much you share its sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   It's the closest thing we've had in a while to a true slob
comedy, that anarchic genre that ``Animal House'' all but invented
20 years ago. ``Mary,'' for all its flouting of convention, doesn't
aim at any establishment targets. ``BASEketball'' takes a direct
bead on the increasingly corrupt and greedy world of professional
sports, with the help of an amazing number of real-life
sportscasters and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The title refers to a nonsensical combination of baseball and
basketball concocted by two slackers ``(South Park'' creators Trey
Parker and Matt Stone; Parker's the blond guy) as a way of showing
up some Dockers-clad neighborhood jocks. It's a noncontact sport,
but players are allowed to do ``psych-outs'' _ which are anything
the player can think of to mess up his opponent's shot, and which
make for many of the movie's funniest gags.
</P>
<P>
   After BASEketball becomes a neighborhood sensation, a
Stetson-wearing millionaire (Ernest Borgnine) persuades the guys to
turn it into a professional sport. Although anything goes on the _
field? court? _ the league is a model of integrity, in which teams
aren't allowed to move between cities and players aren't allowed to
sell out, refreshing bylaws in a business where real-life teams
have been known to move out of their hometowns overnight.
</P>
<P>
   But then another millionaire (Robert Vaughn) comes into the
picture, threatening to split up the duo with a Faustian deal;
their partnership is also threatened by a pretty charity worker.
Bleeth plays the good-hearted woman with good-natured humor.
McCarthy is wasted _ if, as an actress, she ``can'' be wasted _ as
the woman who hooks up with both millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Sports fans have a head start on everyone else here; the movie
is so loaded with cameos and in-jokes that you practically have to
be an ESPN junkie to get them all. Respected sportscaster Bob
Costas and Al Michaels deliver many funny moments with some fairly
demented play-by-plays; you have to wonder how many takes it took
before they stopped cracking up.
</P>
<P>
   For guys not known as actors, Parker and Stone do a decent
enough job, and they play off of each other well (although in slow
moments you're tempted to tally how many times they say ``Dude!'').
Even though they were cast before ``South Park'' became a
phenomenon, there still are a couple of ``Park''ish moments that
had the show's fans hooting and hollering at the preview screening.
The movie even features a hard-luck supporting character named
Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   Like his crony Abrahams, Zucker often runs out of momentum;
there are a lot of dead spots between the laughs, and the ratio of
successes to flops could generously be put at 50-50. At nearly an
hour and 40 minutes, the movie is too long for this kind of goofy
material, but people with the patience to sit througl`:he clo.Z7
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
