<HEADER>
A0636 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVENGERS-AZR &LR;      07-30 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVENGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AVENGERS' STILL HIP ON THESE SHORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON RENFROE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - By March 1966, the Beatles had forever changed pop
music and hairstyles. Miniskirts and knee-high boots were the rage.
And America was about to get hit by yet another British invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Enter ``The Avengers,'' an unlikely import that shortly would
have grown-ups captivated and adolescent boys in a swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Americans quickly fell for the attractive pair of spies: John
Steed, who was very British, very polite, and always wore a bowler
and trim Pierre Cardin suit; and his partner, Mrs. Emma Peel, who
was young, smart, kittenishly sexy and always ready with a karate
chop for some evildoer.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to hear a lot about ``The Avengers'' in the next few
weeks. The big-screen, updated version opens in theaters nationwide
on Aug. 14 and stars Uma Thurman and Ralph Fiennes. A&AMP;E Home Video
is releasing, for the first time Friday, 12 episodes from 1967. And
the cable network also will present ``The Avengers: The Journey
Back,'' hosted by one of the original stars, Patrick Macnee, on
Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a brief history of this tongue-in-cheek, kooky spy spoof
for those who missed this camp classic the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avengers'' began in Britain in 1961. Initially broadcast
live, it starred Ian Hendry and Macnee as top-secret agents. Their
mission was to ``avenge'' evil deeds committed against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The series continued, virtually unknown here, until 1966, when
ABC brought it to American prime time. By then Hendry was out, and
Macnee had assumed the starring role. Joining him was Diana Rigg,
playing ``talented amateur'' Emma Peel to Macnee's ``top
professional'' John Steed.
</P>
<P>
   Together they made quite a charming pair. Their chemistry made
the series work, and it's for them American fans have been eagerly
awaiting the video releases. The show hasn't been seen in the
United States since 1990, when the Arts and Entertainment cable
network ran some episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Like many series from the 1960s, it's the ``furniture'' that
would come around every week that's memorable:
</P>
<P>
   _The theme music. Laurie Anderson's bouncy-yet-elegant opening
and closing tune is hard to get out of your head. It's not often
you hear bongos, horns and violins all blended dramatically in one
minute.
</P>
<P>
   _The fashions. Steed's swagger was one part self-confidence, two
parts smart Edwardian dressing. But it was Mrs. Peel's outfits that
got adolescent boys' blood stirring. They included hip-hugging
pantsuits and of course, The Leather Suit, which will be updated by
Thurman in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   While it's the leather one remembers, it was used only
occasionally, as the outfit tended to tear during the action
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mrs. Peel _ we're needed.'' For 16 episodes (beginning in
fall 1967), Steed would find novel ways to let Mrs. Peel know they
were to be required on a case. These included a dashed line painted
on her floor, which led to the front door, which led to Steed
sticking his trademark umbrella through the door with an
invitationlike note attached: ``Mrs. Peel _ we're needed!''
</P>
<P>
   In the episode ``The See-Through Man,'' Mrs. Peel looks into a
microscope and finds the usual message.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lots of drinking. Hitting the booze was still exotic in the
late '60s. Emma and Steed did lots of it. Champagne flowed.
</P>
<P>
   _ The cars. Emma preferred a cute Lotus Elan (there would be an
auto chase scene in almost every episode). Steed had a stable of
classic roadsters from the 1920s and '30s. After the denouement,
the two would climb aboard one of Steed's favorites and do a bit of
silent comedy as a way of saying goodnight to the viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   These bits from 30 years ago are still fun. But to those viewing
the tapes for the first time, be forewarned: This is not James
Bond. That is, all is low-key. The series moves along at its own
pace, thank you very much. Remember, this was before MTV, and most
TV series moved slower than what we expect today.
</P>
<P>
   Violence is there, but it's mannerly and short-lived. The
villains and their henchmen get knocked out remarkably fast and
with relative ease. And not much blood.
</P>
<P>
   Sex is there, too, but very tame by today's standards. Often the
villain lusts in some kinky way for Mrs. Peel, who is often put in
bondage _ tied to railroad tracks and chairs. In one episode, her
hands and feet are put in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   There was no romance between Steed and Mrs. Peel; rather a
mutual affection. She was married, after all, although the hubby
doesn't figure until Diana Rigg, and our beloved Emma, left the
show at the end of the 1967 season.
</P>
<P>
   Dame Rigg usually tries to opt out when it comes to reevaluating
the series. In previous interviews, she makes it clear that while
``The Avengers'' was a good career move and one that she enjoyed,
she doesn't have much to say on the subject. She has returned to
her first love, the stage, and also has hosted ``Mystery'' on PBS,
along with authoring books on the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Macnee is more eager to ride ``The Avengers'' publicity train.
He has written a book, ``The Avengers and Me,'' and is helping push
the videos. According to press reports, he will be seen in a cameo
role in the new movie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`The Avengers' &QL; 
WHERE: Cyberspace. &QL; 
WHAT: Hundreds of Web sites relating to the 1960s British series.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best sites is www.ee.ualberta.ca/dawe/avengers.html.
It includes an extensive photo gallery and theme-song downloads.
</P>
<P>
   Newly released videos from the 1967 season may be ordered from
www.OriginalAvengers.com.
</P>
<P>
   One may also order an Emma Peel T-shirt. Of course, Emma would
never be caught dead in a T-shirt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
