<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAGAN-RANCH-ART-650(     07-30 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-RANCH-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION FINDS A CORNERSTONE IN REAGAN RANCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By MARK VAN DE KAMP   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ A dusty tankard of jelly beans sits on a
corner table in the den of Rancho Del Cielo, near a window
overlooking the pond where Ronald and Nancy Reagan used to unwind
from Washington by paddling about in a canoe, sharing laughs and
kisses.
</P>
<P>
   The home looks as if the former president could walk in at any
moment, sore from chopping wood by the barn, although he hasn't set
foot at the ranch since late 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It's quiet and peaceful at the rustic mountaintop retreat about
30 miles northwest of Santa Barbara. Because it's fully furnished,
the home makes the rare visitor feel a sense of walking in on
Reagan's private life.
</P>
<P>
   His riding boots are in the closet, next to White House jackets
and monogrammed shirts. There's his favorite Ralph Lauren Polo
shirt that he often wore while horseback riding, its navy blue
threads with horizontal white pinstripes worn thin.
</P>
<P>
   Still in the lemon-yellow master bedroom are sheepskin rugs, a
bedspread with the initials ``NRR,'' for Nancy and Ronald Reagan,
and two leather-bound Bibles gracing a wooden side table adorned
with cowboy statues.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the nation has seen little of Reagan's ranch, except
for television footage and newspaper photos of press conferences,
and of him riding horseback and doing chores 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners, who bought the ranch April 21, want to
eventually give visitors unprecedented access to the ranch, to
offer insights about Reagan's lifestyle. So far, they have invited
a few reporters to take a peek.
</P>
<P>
   The decor is modest. The bookshelves in the living room are not
lined with the classics but with Westerns, paperbacks, copies of
Arizona Highways magazines and a hardcover of Larry McMurtry's
``Lonesome Dove.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the kitchen stands a bumper-pool table. Paintings of the
couple's favorite horses hang on the walls. The kitchen spice rack
is well stocked with seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   This 1,200-square-foot house and its furnishings don't meet
one's expectations of a presidential home. It's just so plain,
ordinary and simple.
</P>
<P>
   No plush pile carpeting, only cracked faux-brick red linoleum
and Indian-style throw rugs. No framed portraits of the Oval Office
or handshakes with foreign leaders, just macrame and numerous
paintings of cowboys and Western landscapes above bright orange
Naugahyde wingbacked chairs straight out of the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   A SIMPLE LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   The house has a Spartan feel with its aluminum-framed windows.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Reagans lived. It's a world apart from the
formality and exhibits under glass at the Reagan Library a couple
of hours south in Simi Valley that opened in November 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And it's going to stay this way. No ropes and posts to keep
visitors shuffling in single file from room to room.
</P>
<P>
   The 688-acre spread, owned by the Reagans since 1974, is now
owned by the Young America's Foundation, a conservative outreach
group for college-age students. The ranch was listed for $5.95
million but the purchase price is a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reagans really put a lot of themselves into this place,''
said 28-year-old Marc Short, foundation executive director. ``This
really was their spot. You really get a feeling for who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation intends to use the ranch as an inspirational,
educational and historic backdrop, making it the focal point of its
new Ronald Reagan Leadership Development Program. It hopes to
obtain conference facilities nearby and begin bringing students
there in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, it must buy more land, secure county approval and
permits, and will likely be asked to help repair the crumbling,
winding road that snakes up the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tremendously excited to share President Reagan's
vision,'' said Kristen Short, foundation conference director and
Marc's wife. Two weeks ago the Young America's Foundation opened a
West Coast office in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A VISIT FROM NANCY
</P>
<P>
   Ten days after the purchase _ done with Nancy Reagan's direct
approval _ the former first lady paid a visit and met the Shorts at
the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brought a lot of knickknacks and paintings and saddles
from storage, and spent hours going through each room with us,
sharing stories and adjusting the pictures on the walls and the
statues and plates on the tables,'' Kristen Short said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so fortunate to have Mrs. Reagan assisting us,'' she
said. ``She took it upon herself to gather more from the Reagan
Library and brought it here. She did all this on her own will, and
we learned so much from her. It's really wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Such inside knowledge is incomparable. After all, Mrs. Thomas
Jefferson wasn't around to tell stories to the caretakers and
docents at Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a look inside the president's personality,'' Marc Short
said. ``And we're meeting people who personally knew the Reagans _
Secret Service agents and Cabinet members who are sharing their
memories and stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Short _ a Wake Forest University graduate _ shows a
visitor through the house and around the grounds like a pro,
relating endless anecdotes about the furnishings, clothing and how
Reagan hand-built the fences from telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   The Shorts do not pretend to be as famous as the Reagans, though
they represent the next generation of Reaganites. Rather, they
respect their new role as caretakers of this historical property
and pledge not to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranch will offer students a unique opportunity to view the
simple lifestyle and hard-work philosophy that made President
Reagan the great leader that he was,'' Marc Short said.
</P>
<P>
   DETAILS OF THEIR LIVES
</P>
<P>
   The Shorts, children during the Reagan administration, say that
Reagan's legacy has been distorted by academics and the media. The
foundation will bring speakers to the ranch. Former Attorney
General Edwin Meese, former Secretary of Defense Casper Weinberger
and Marine Col. Oliver North are among the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But just as powerful for future generations, they say, is the
opportunity to walk through the house and the horse barn, to absorb
the simplicity and natural surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   On the front porch are the stones that Reagan himself hefted
from around the ranch. A round wooden table out front was used by
Reagan to sign tax cuts into law in August 1981.
</P>
<P>
   To the left of the front door is the bell that Nancy Reagan
would sound to call her husband in for lunch. Up by the barn is an
old train bell that Ron would ring in the mornings to call Nancy
when her horse was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on the hat rack inside the front door, stained with
sweat from chopping wood and building fences, is a worn navy blue
baseball cap embroidered in gold thread: ``United States Mounted
Secret Service.''
</P>
<P>
   The main house, built in the 1890s, has two large rooms, a
master bedroom and bath, a kitchen and a small maid's suite.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttered from view on the bottom shelf of a towering armoire
sits a bulky Zenith ``space command'' TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Mounted on the wall next to the simple bar with its pewter mugs
and glasses are two ``jackalopes'': stuffed heads of jackrabbits
affixed with pairs of antlers. One has fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the master closet is a snazzy white Stetson hat; the
hatband is inscribed with a notation that it was made personally
for the president.
</P>
<P>
   And atop the four-drawer bureau in the closet are Reagan's two
Rancheros Visitadores leather patches, noting his donor membership
of 1984 and honorary membership of 1986. The local horse-riding
group makes annual treks to a camp in the Santa Ynez Valley.
</P>
<P>
   There are reminders of how the remote ranch was once ringed by
cameras, motion sensors, surveillance lights and roving Secret
Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   On the master bedroom's side table are two telephones, one with
a rotary dial and one without any dial or buttons. That white phone
was connected directly to the Secret Service command post on the
knoll above the house, so agents could alert the president in any
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   A few steps from the main house is the two-bedroom guest cottage
used by Queen Elizabeth II, Mikhail Gorbachev and other guests.
</P>
<P>
   Up a hill is a pet cemetery, with headstones Reagan carved. One
is for Nancy Reagan's horse, No Strings.
</P>
<P>
   These are the stuff of memories that visitors to the ranch will
take home.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Van de Kamp writes for the Santa Barbara (Calif.)
News-Press. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News
Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
