<SLUG> BC-BUSEY-SALVATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GARY BUSEY, IT'S GOOD TO BE ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Anything good?''
</P>
<P>
   You hear this while you're skimming a newspaper article about a
17-year-old stabbed to death in summer school, and the answer is
obvious. No. Life basically stinks, our kids are cold-blooded
killers, our adults are innately corrupt, our society is too
materialistic and intolerant, and it's difficult to flip to the
next page for fear of delving even deeper into depression.
</P>
<P>
   When the voice quips, ``You're alive, aren't you? Isn't THAT
good?'' it's time to look up and connect a scratchy voice with a
face. Standing in the corner of the elevator is Gary Busey, actor
and drug rehab poster boy.
</P>
<P>
   He's wearing this goofy, crooked grin, knowing that he'd said
the right thing and was the right person to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Being stuck with Gary Busey on even a moving elevator counts as
an intriguing experience, but there's more. Because we were going
to the same place as interviewer and interviewee, we walk down the
hotel corridor together. He says hello and looks deep into the eyes
of everyone he encounters: the surprised young man painting a door,
a maid carrying a vacuum cleaner, a hotel executive wearing an
expensive double-breasted suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless,'' he says. Or ``Are we good today?'' Or ``Wonderful
day, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful, sure, for Busey. By most accounts he should be dead,
a statistic, a member of the celebrity drug overdose club. Three
years ago in May, he was found slumped in a chair at his home,
filled with steroids, cocaine and tequila. He'd been up and down
through most of his career, one that was filled with promise after
his fine performance in ``The Buddy Holly Story'' and as a heavy in
``Lethal Weapon,'' ``Drop Zone'' and ``Under Siege,'' among others.
But he simply couldn't handle fame.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before Busey appeared at the television critics'
press tour, Burt Reynolds had declared Hollywood a cold,
calculating place that kicks you when you're down and leaves you
for dead. He was talking about his treatment as a has-been, before
``Boogie Nights,'' before he snagged that Oscar nomination, before
he fell into Hollywood's favor again.
</P>
<P>
   Busey makes no such claims, saying he has been welcomed back by
Hollywood, that it is generous and good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's forgiving when somebody gets back up on their
feet, dusts themselves off, and says, `Let's go again, and do it
the right way,' '' Busey says. ``And that's the glory that I'm
having in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   One supposes that Busey considers E! Entertainment, the cable
channel that pushes coverage of sex, drugs and lingerie models as
entertainment, to be generous: It took on his life story in its
popular tabloidish profile series.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. Sunday, Busey will be the latest catch of its
salacious ``E! True Hollywood Story,'' a popular series that
doesn't pretend to be A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' or even Lifetime's
``Intimate Portrait.'' It chronicles the rise and fall of stars,
with or without their input. So it's truly a special moment that
Busey is here, in person, thanking his exploiter.
</P>
<P>
   Once a fluffy, though legitimate, entertainment channel ``(E!
News Daily'' and ``Talk Soup'' are still worth a look), E! has
found its niche in peddling cheesecake TV, a collection of programs
featuring scantily clad women, from models scurrying down runways
to shows involving Victoria's Secret lingerie and specials on
``Playboy'' playmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``E! True Hollywood Story'' is on something of a roll, having
dipped into the turbulent lives of Mackenzie Phillips and Liberace
last month, and with Tommy Lee, Brett Butler and that wayward
``Diff'rent Strokes'' cast set for Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell whether Busey considers this a needed
catharsis or a chance to tell Hollywood that, hey, he's sorry and
he's back. ``It's nice to let people know what a man in the
celebrity position has gone through and come through,'' he says.
``And it will help others to see that it can be done. To heal
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Busey is now ``a full-blooded Christian'' who witnesses to
inmates in juvenile detention halls, viewers of ``The 700 Club''
and Promise Keepers.
</P>
<P>
   And to prove this E! tell-all isn't a plea for sympathy and
work, he points to such accomplishments as his roles in ``Fear &AMP;
Loathing in Las Vegas'' and in an upcoming children's film.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to believe a man who has seen a snapshot of a tortured
life and lived to tell about it, but you have to wonder how and why
he's telling it. One supposes it's also easy for him to trust
others, to think that his best interests are being cared for.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a tape of Sunday's show, I'd say E! got more out of
this than Busey.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
