<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-UNICORN-2TAKES-NY     07-30 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-UNICORN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELUSIVE PREY IN A COURTLY PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The branch of the Metropolitan Museum known as the
Cloisters is, in every sense, one of the high points of art in New
York City. An impressive jumble of Romanesque scraps and American
prewar masonry, and a monument to American philanthropy, it sits
atop a rocky outcrop over the Hudson near the upper tip of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The island's last stand of virgin forest is just to the north
beyond a geological fault line; to the south the terrain gradually
descends toward midtown.
</P>
<P>
   If location is one of the Cloisters' outstanding attractions,
the magnificent trove of medieval art it houses is another.
Burgundian carvings, illuminated manuscripts and one of the
greatest of all early Netherlandish paintings are among the
treasures. But surely the most famous work is the set of tapestries
long known as ``The Hunt of the Unicorn.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember them from my first trip to the Cloisters when I was
10 and visiting New York from Boston with my parents. It was
December, a few weeks before Christmas, and snowing hard. The river
below was ice-gray; inside the museum, decorous stone virgins and
angels leaned stiffly from the walls.
</P>
<P>
   But the tapestries, over 12 feet high and hanging floor to
ceiling in their wood-paneled gallery, seemed to offer a different
vision, one of almost tumultuous vivacity and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   What was the source of this impression? In part, it lay in the
vivid, though somewhat illogical story they seemed to tell in a
succession of cinematically scaled episodes. In the story, a
charismatic and valiant beast was harassed by a passel of
aristocratic hunters, and finally killed, only _ or so it appeared
_ to be brought back to life and enclosed, as docile as a pet,
within a pretty garden fence.
</P>
<P>
   The enigmatic texture of the narrative, with its blend of
pageantry and adventure, harsh facts and a happy ending, was
instantly appealing to a child. So was the eye-catching wealth of
visual details.
</P>
<P>
   A complete miniature world was crowded into these fabrics:
meticulously rendered flowers; birds whirring up from streams;
squirrels and panthers keeping incongruous company in the lush
underbrush, and a fairy tale cast of characters, from knaves and
nobles to gawky, embarrassed-to-be-here everyday folk.
</P>
<P>
   The Unicorn tapestries aren't at the Cloisters this summer. They
have traveled downtown and are now on display at the Met's main
headquarters on Fifth Avenue, in an exhibition organized by Timothy
B. Husband and Mary B. Shepard. Their stay will be brief, lasting
just a few weeks while their uptown room is refurbished. (The rest
of the Cloisters is open as usual.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Met is celebrating the visit with the release of a
freshly researched catalog, written by the art historian Adolfo
Salvatore Cavallo, offering a revised interpretation of the
tapestries' meanings.
</P>
<P>
   The historical information presented isn't, for the most part,
new. Although the seven tapestries are among the most celebrated
surviving examples of their kind, their origins remain elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the costumes depicted, they date from between 1495
and 1505. Their designs were probably produced in a Parisian
workshop and draw on a pool of contemporary images that also turn
up in illustrated books and stained glass. The actual weaving may
have been executed in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tapestries are conspicuously monogrammed with the
initials AE, their patron is unknown. The first mention of them was
in 1680 when they were listed as belonging to La Rochefoucauld,
author of the ``Maxims.''
</P>
<P>
   During the French Revolution, they were looted from the family
estate and vanished. But in the 1850s, six of them turned up on a
farm where they were being used as coverings to protect potatoes
against frost. After some restoration, they were returned to the
family's chateau.
</P>
<P>
   In 1922, the La Rochefoucaulds allowed a Paris art dealer to
ship the works to a New York gallery for exhibition. John D.
Rockefeller Jr. saw them there and snapped them up. Rockefeller
later gave New York City the land the Cloisters stands on, and
financed its building.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he purchased a sizable chunk of the Palisades
across the river to insure an unspoiled view from the museum. He
gave the tapestries to the Met, and they were installed in their
new quarters in 1937, together with two remnants of a seventh
hanging, which the museum had acquired from the la Rochefoucauld
family.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Unicorn tapestries were displayed as a unit,
Cavallo's research confirms that they do not, in fact, form a
sequence, but are parts of two or three separate sets, which differ
in symbolic import.
</P>
<P>
   Two pieces stylistically distinct from the rest, for example,
are of a type known as mille-fleurs, referring to the unbroken
fields of flowers that form their backgrounds. (The other
outstanding example of this type is the ``Lady With the Unicorn''
series at the Cluny Museum in Paris.)
</P>
<P>
   And one of the pair, the renowned image of the unicorn confined
to his tiny pen and leashed to a pomegranate tree, may have been
intended as a self-contained emblem of marriage, with the beast
standing for a bridegroom captivated by love.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cavallo's research, the fragments from the seventh
tapestry seem to illustrate another allegory, the Mystical Hunt of
the Unicorn. The legend was that the creature, independent and
fierce, could be subdued only by a virgin, in whose lap he would
lay his head.
</P>
<P>
   The virgin was often taken to be Mary and the unicorn Christ,
tamed through the Incarnation. In the damaged tapestry, the virgin
is missing; but a hunter crashing in from the left may represent
the angel Gabriel, while the crafty young woman in the blood-red
gown supervising the capture could be the biblical figure of Eve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The four tapestries that unquestionably belong together also
invite religious readings, as depictions of the Passion, framed in
terms of the elaborate etiquette of the courtly chase. In one
scene, the fleeing unicorn plunges his horn into a stream,
miraculously purifying its water for the thirsty woodland creatures
gathered around him.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters permit him to escape, but he is soon cornered and
killed, his body delivered into the hands of a waiting lord and
lady, perhaps the sponsors of the hunt, who here look remorseful at
its outcome
</P>
<P>
   That a bit of fiction like the unicorn myth can yield so many
complex meanings is perfectly plausible in works that lie, as these
tapestries do, so close to the extraordinary spiritual and
intellectual universe of the Middle Ages. It was an environment in
which the supernatural and the natural ceaselessly and almost
casually interacted, in which daily life was a mirror of the
divine, and in which every image, however prosaic, was coded with
moral implications.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, several of the birds and animals shown here carry biblical
references, and plants embody meanings derived both from Christian
thought and from the folklore of pagan Europe. Of the nearly 100
different types of flowers and fruit trees depicted, more than 80
have been identified. Many had special significance to the medieval
eye. Roses and lilies were revered as Marian emblems; pomegranates
and apples spoke of the pleasures and the pitfalls of carnal love.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this multilayered, metaphorical perspective on the
earthly existence gives the tapestries much of their interest for a
modern audience, for whom such thinking is distant but by no means
forgotten. At the same time, the artists who created them did
everything possible to project a charge of theatrical vitality,
with each scene conceived as a kind of tragicomic tableau vivant.
</P>
<P>
   The characters, though drawn from stock types, are carefully,
often hilariously, detailed. Most are hunters who share an
extravagant period style, one which includes cloddish round-toed
Earth Shoes, striped hose, rakish caps and modified Farrah Fawcett
haircuts. But despite the fashion-victim look, personal
distinctions abound: one man has a five o'clock shadow, another a
surplus of chins, yet another is in serious need of orthodontia.
</P>
<P>
   Personalities, too, stand out. The noblewoman who greets the
unicorn's corpse comes across as a sympathetic figure, decorously
doleful as she fingers the thick rosary beads at her waist. And the
chap who delivers the coup de grace at the end of the hunt is a
Judas if ever there was one, with an ostentatious gold coat and a
craven, no-goodnik squint.
</P>
<P>
   The animals depicted are, in many cases, more human than the
humans themselves. The hunting dogs _ greyhounds, mastiffs _ are at
once adamant and deferential, many reacting with an odd, empathetic
probity to the mortal ritual to which they are supporting players.
The unicorn himself has true star presence, projecting a kind of
Billy-Buddlike innocence in life, and in death a seraphic
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the work's appeal is its matchless craftsmanship. The
dyes are still bright and true; the weaving of fine wool, silk,
silver and gilt thread is of surpassing skill, marked by a
painter's eye for modeling forms and for capturing the feel of
surfaces, from the nap of an animal's coat to the sheen of light on
the fold of a silk sleeve. Here and there, see-through slits have
even been incorporated into the weave to enhance an illusionistic
play of shadow and light.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition at the Met may give this visual spectacle a
larger audience in a matter of weeks than it has drawn in years
uptown. But a trip to the Cloisters, either now or after the
tapestries have returned in early September, remains an essential,
and unfailingly delightful, part of any experience of medieval art
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the plants and flowers found in the tapestries are
cultivated in the Cloisters courtyards and terrace gardens; birds
sing in the trees of the surrounding parkland; fountains splash
with cool water. Most important, almost everything in the
collection belongs to the spiritual world of the unicorn
tapestries.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ultra-refined, courtly world, but one saturated with
what the historian Johan Huizinga called ``the extreme excitability
of the medieval soul.'' Here the beautiful and grotesque, the real
and the fanciful, the human and divine dynamically coexist. And
art, as both a category of exquisite worldly objects and as a lens
of perception, reveals a memory of innocence lost and a promise of
final perfection to come.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``The Unicorn Tapestries'' remains at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, 1000 Fifth Avenue, at 82nd Street, through Sept.
6.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
