<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROUP-BIKING-ART-2TAK     07-30 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUP-BIKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDALING PLEASURES, EN MASSE VS. SOLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARC BLOOM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on a sultry summer morning, a caravan of recreational
bicyclists pulls out of a parking lot at Brookdale College in
Lincroft, N.J., for a 25-mile ride through the country lanes of
Monmouth County. We are a dozen people, ages 30 to 60, men and
women _ including one couple on a tandem _ heading out to Holmdel,
Colts Neck, Marlboro and Freehold for a marvelous workout,
camaraderie, tips on bike handling and the consuming power that
comes from riding together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need someone to stay back and watch out for the last
rider,'' summons the group leader, Patty Dyer, of the Jersey Shore
Touring Society, which is sponsoring this ride on what it calls the
Cranberry Sauce Lite Route. Someone immediately volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a friendly contingent. As we briefly hit a main
thoroughfare about 8 a.m., everyone finds a partner the way
schoolchildren on a class trip do. We hug the shoulder riding two
abreast with traffic (bikes are considered ``vehicles''). Up ahead,
Patty checks for cars, announces all is clear, and we snake left
across the road toward miles of pasture.
</P>
<P>
   I recognize another cyclist, Steve, and we ride side by side in
conversation. Invigorated by the fragrant smells of summer filling
the air, Steve and I feel an immediate connection and spill out our
life stories, on work, family, bicycling background, or whatever
comes up. I'm amazed to learn that Steve met his wife through the
personal ads in New York magazine, and he charms me with tales of
their first date.
</P>
<P>
   I've been cycling for more than a decade, but this is my first
group ride in a couple of years and I'm eager to feed off the
energy of the group. I'm also eager to test my new Trek 5200, a
snazzy road bike with an up-to-date carbon-fiber frame, and see how
it responds in tight quarters. While this day's ride is sedate, I
still must be alert to other riders and how the group stops and
starts like an accordion at corners. It's an opportunity to sharpen
my instincts on drafting (positioning myself closely behind another
cyclist to reduce wind resistance), turning, taking hills and
grabbing a bite of the bagel in my back pocket while holding my
bike steady.
</P>
<P>
   In a group, you have a responsibility to keep up, to prize
safety and assist fellow riders and do the right thing. Brazenly
trying to beat a motorist at an intersection _ something I might
foolishly do on my own _ is bad karma. Wearing a hard-shell helmet
is a safety must. I also recommend a side-view mirror that sits on
your handlebars, a bike timer that shows pace and distance, and
authentic, padded bike shorts for support.
</P>
<P>
   Group rides, plentiful on summer and autumn weekends throughout
the New York City area, usually fall into one of two categories:
fast-paced rides of close to 20 miles an hour for racers and others
seeking to emulate the peloton in the Tour de France; and
moderately paced rides of 10 to 15 miles an hour for recreational
riders who want to burn calories and enjoy the scenery without the
fear of being ``dropped'' by those in front.
</P>
<P>
   Novice cyclists, who may consider themselves unathletic or who
are intimidated by riding in traffic, acquire the confidence and
skills to negotiate the open road. These tools expand your
bicycling horizons and, with patient progress, you can eventually
cover distances of 50 miles and more, earning a rare feeling of
freedom. Just get on your bike and . . . go!
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine and his wife, both teachers, participate in an
organized weeklong group ride in a different state every summer.
Typically, the couple are among several hundred riders covering 50
to 75 miles a day, enjoying the best of Iowa or Vermont from top to
bottom. This summer, they're headed for Montana.
</P>
<P>
   It's never too late to get started. A gentleman in his 70s I
often see at the local YMCA told me recently that he had biked
round-trip to his high school reunion at Choate Academy in
Connecticut. Using some public transportation, the man covered over
200 miles in less than a week. He told me he had plotted his course
around the best places to stop for apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   Eating and bicycling do go together. A vigorous ride builds up a
ravenous appetite, and many rides are routed around essential food
stops. Stick-to-your-ribs snacks like a peanut butter sandwich or a
banana fill the bill. In addition to my bagel (and, of course,
water bottle), I've stuffed a Power Bar into my bike jersey. My
take-along meal proves to be insurance. Patty tells us we'll be
stopping at a deli midway.
</P>
<P>
   We travel two-lane back roads past the lush horse farms of Colts
Neck. I work at smoothing out my riding style for comfort and
efficiency. I pedal in a circular motion, lowering my heels, while
aiming for 90 to 100 revolutions a minute. I change hand positions
on the handlebars, setting my elbows at almost a right angle and
relaxing my neck and shoulders. I try to keep my torso still and
let my legs do all the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car back!'' Patty cries every so often, and the alert is
repeated down the line like an echo at a ball park. We move into
single file, then fan out again once the motorist passes. The 13-
to 14-miles-an-hour pace is a little slow for my taste, and I pull
to the front and stay there as we travel through farmland as far as
the eye can see. My shirt is moist, and I take sips of water.
Roadside fruit stands with fresh peaches _ gifts from heaven _ will
pop up later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is a selective list of bicycle clubs in the New York
metropolitan region that organize group rides and can provide
schedules. Always check on speed, hills and the general degree of
difficulty of a ride before showing up.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL JERSEY BICYCLE CLUB, Fords, N.J., (732) 225-HUBS
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY CYCLE CLUB, Mount Kisco, N.Y., (914) 472-8690.
</P>
<P>
   JERSEY SHORE TOURING SOCIETY, Red Bank, N.J., (732) 747-8206.
</P>
<P>
   MASSAPEQUA PARK BICYCLE CLUB, Massapequa Park, N.Y., (516)
942-3727.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CYCLE CLUB, Manhattan, (212) 828-5711.
</P>
</TEXT>
