A0682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CINDERELLA-FILM-REVIE     07-30 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINDERELLA-FILM-REVIEW-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVER AFTER': PART SPOOF, PART SOAP OPERA, PART FEMINIST PEP TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sooner or later Cinderella was bound to be re-invented as a
resourceful young woman whose ascent from rags to riches depended
on her own pluck and not on the magical intercession of a fairy
godmother. Andy Tennant's bland, sappy costume comedy ``Ever After:
A Cinderella Story,'' portrays the most popular of all fairy-tale
characters as a kind of 16th-century Olympic hopeful going for the
gold on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Her happily-ever-after involves a lot more than marriage to a
handsome prince. Once she's got her man, her in-laws promise, per
her desires, to found a university with a library available to all
the people. Hubby even agrees to stop automatically assuming the
worst about Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being delivered from a life of oppression by a bland,
infatuated Prince Charming, this Cinderella, named Danielle (Drew
Barrymore), saves the life of her wimpy future husband, Prince
Henry (Dougray Scott), when the pair, while strolling through the
forest, are menaced by a band of outlaws. Danielle is in such
tiptop physical shape from all her menial chores that at one point
she actually picks up her dreamboat and slings him over her
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they've wed, she has tutored him in the ugly
political realities of the world that his life of privilege has
prevented him from grasping. You see, Danielle's father, who died
when she was a child, used to bring home stacks of books including
Sir Thomas More's ``Utopia,'' which was instrumental in shaping her
vision of 16th-century France as an enlightened monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing the movie offers to a fairy godmother is
kindly Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick Godfrey), who just happens to be
traipsing around in the French forest with a canvas of the ``Mona
Lisa'' under his arm. Old Leonardo (although the movie couldn't get
Leonardo DiCaprio, it at least gets to drop his first name) is
forever spouting icky platitudes about following your heart and
believing in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever After'' might have succeeded had it had a modicum of
historical consistency. But the dialogue (spoken by French
characters with English accents) sounds like a flattened-out
Anglicized version of contemporary teenspeak. Although the
screenplay puts its heroine in mortal peril more than once, the
rescues it contrives are unconvincing and anticlimactic. Veering
wildly between farce and suds, the movie never makes up its mind
whether it's a spoof, a soap opera or a feminist pep talk. The
overbearingly glutinous soundtrack by George Fenton relentlessly
pushes the movie toward mush.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most orthodox characters are Danielle's evil
stepmother, Rodmilla (Anjelica Huston), and two stepsisters, the
cold, conniving Marguerite (Megan Dodds) and the homely, gawky
Jacqueline (Melanie Lynskey). Ms. Huston's Rodmilla could be a
cousin of Morticia Addams. Haughty and poker faced, with a streak
of cruelty, she is chilly and ambitious but a long way from truly
evil.
</P>
<P>
   The most contemporary element is Ms. Barrymore's Danielle.
Twinkly eyed and saucy in a tomboyish way, she is the very model of
a smart, modern college girl who knows how to stand up for herself
and remains resolutely undazzled by the make-over mentality. Ms.
Barrymore's buoyant, unaffected performance is the best thing about
the film. From Danielle's first meeting with the rather slow-witted
prince, it's obvious she's far too good for him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If this weren't the 16th century, you could almost swear that
Danielle had memorized ``The Rules: Time-Tested Secrets for
Capturing the Heart of Mr. Right,'' Ellen Fein and Sherrie
Schneider's best-selling guidebook for snaring men in suits.
Without hurting a man's feelings, this Cinderella knows exactly
when and how to say no.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EVER AFTER: A CINDERELLA STORY''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Andy Tennant; written by Susannah Grant, Tennant and
Rick Parks; director of photography, Andrew Dunn; edited by Roger
Bondelli; music by George Fenton; production designer, Michael
Howells; produced by Mireille Soria and Tracey Trench; released by
20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   With: Drew Barrymore (Danielle), Anjelica Huston (Rodmilla),
Dougray Scott (Prince Henry), Patrick Godfrey (Leonardo), Megan
Dodds (Marguerite), Melanie Lynskey (Jacqueline), Jeanne Moreau
(Grand Dame), Richard O'Brien (Pierre Le Pieu) and Jeroen Krabbe
(Auguste).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever After: A Cinderella Tale'' is rated PG-13 (parents
strongly cautioned). The screenplay includes a single glaring
obscenity.
</P>
</TEXT>
