<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-UNIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL UNIVERSITY JUMPS TO THE TOP OF ITS CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ten months after the California Virtual
University popped up on the World Wide Web, making the audacious
claim it could link students worldwide with unrivaled educational
opportunities, CVU looks like the team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, CVU has more than doubled, to 1,600, the
number of courses available electronically. At launch time, 65
accredited California colleges and universities appeared in the CVU
catalog. Now, there are 95.
</P>
<P>
   This growth, Gov. Pete Wilson said Wednesday, is only the
beginning. He believes there is almost unlimited potential for
long-distance higher education in California.
</P>
<P>
   California Virtual University _ a state-run Web catalog of
college courses offered on-line _ was turned over Wednesday to a
nonprofit foundation formed by educators.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson proposed the virtual university more than a year ago,
selling the project as a marketing tool for colleges and as a
career and skill booster to workers and employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means that when we speak of an information age, that is
not just a glib phrase,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all our wishes are granted, there will be a work force that
is better educated and has better access to higher education _ a
citizenry that can gain the skills to function in the knowledge
society which is upon us,'' said Carol Tomlinson-Keasey, vice
provost of the University of California and chairwoman of the CVU
Foundation Board of Directors.
</P>
<P>
   From the inception of the Web catalog, the state has believed
that its role should be minimal and that CVU should be directed by
educators. In its nascent period, it was given shape by teams of
teachers from the University of California, California State
University, California community colleges and the Association of
Independent California Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   An infusion of money accompanied Wednesday's spinoff from state
control. Redwood Shores-based Oracle Corp., with a $75,000
contribution, joined Sun Microsystems, Cisco Systems, Pacific Bell
and International Thomson Publishing as a founding corporate
sponsor of CVU.
</P>
<P>
   On-line courses have been available for some years, but are
growing rapidly in number and diversity. As many as 240 colleges
are expected to participate in the CVU within three years, said Jim
Highsmith, a CVU planner and immediate past president of the
Academic Senate of the California State University system.
</P>
<P>
   CVU's catalog (at www.california.edu) pulls into one
interactive, searchable forum the many on-line courses available.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The variety is extraordinary:
</P>
<P>
   _ The University of Southern California's Andrus Gerontology
Center (www.usc.edu/go/AgeWorks) is offering the nation's first
graduate gerontology program over the Internet. Topics include
successful aging and death and dying.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beginning this fall, Stanford University will offer courses
that lead to a master's degree in electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allan Hancock College in Santa Maria, a community college, has
three offerings: World Civilization Since 1500, PC Care &AMP; Upgrade,
and Financial Accounting.
</P>
<P>
   The CVU catalog lists more than 100 certificate and degree
programs. Most are in engineering, technology and sciences, but
there also are programs in the humanities, general education,
business, health, education, environmental studies, vocational
education and agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
