<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-LOBBYING-$ADV01-     07-30 3895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LOBBYING-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH-TECH LOBBYING ALLIANCE MAKES BIG IMPACT IN A HURRY
 &HT;    With TECH-GRAPHIC and TEXT-BOX, which moved Tuesday. Cox photos
have been placed in the National folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Saturday, Aug. 1.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last fall, the high-tech industry lost another
battle in its quiet legislative war against the nation's top
crime-fighters and code-busters.
</P>
<P>
   Four House committees had failed to agree on one of the
industry's top priorities: a bill to allow the export of powerful
software to protect electronic data with virtually unbreakable
codes.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the setback, industry lobbyists began exploring a new
approach.
</P>
<P>
   It started with tentative discussions and a few phone calls.
Just 10 months later, it has grown into the biggest, best-funded
lobbying army in the tech industry's history, commanded by a
bipartisan team of political heavyweights and wielding a nationally
televised ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now the coalition, under the market-tested name of Americans for
Computer Privacy, may be on the verge of extracting compromise
language from federal security agencies that could lead to new
legislation or a favorable re-interpretation of existing export
laws.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the effort may someday be cited as a textbook case of how
an interest group can use the traditional levers of Washington
power _ money, lobbying, public opinion and political connections _
to make the system work for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the tech industry has sought federal permission
to export technology that will protect electronic messages and
records with the newest and strongest codes possible.
</P>
<P>
   They watched enviously as foreign software companies threatened
to capture markets around the world with powerful encryption
programs similar to ones that U.S. companies sell at home, but are
forbidden by federal law to sell abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robust foreign encryption is being so widely used that if U.S.
companies can't sell their products with encryption in it, they'll
either move production offshore or export product with a 'hole' in
it, so the user can plug in foreign encryption,'' said Jeffrey
Smith, a leading lawyer for the new coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI and the Defense Department's National Security
Agency have different priorities. They object to widespread sales
of codes so strong that they are unbreakable not just by
competitors, crooks and hackers, but also by law enforcement
agencies and American spies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I'm going to agree to is that American
encryption gets used by terrorists overseas without any effort on
our part to control that,'' Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre
warned Fortune 500 technology officials in Aspen, Colo., last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prosecutors are ``very much concerned about
commercially available encryption products being manufactured for
use in or imported into the United States that do not allow for
access to plain text by law enforcement pursuant to court orders,''
said FBI special agent Barry Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such objections, Congress has consistently rebuffed
the tech industry's pleas to loosen export restrictions, including
the House committees' impasse last September.
</P>
<P>
   After that setback, Ira Rubinstein, a senior Microsoft Corp.
attorney in Redmond, Wash., and his colleagues conceived the idea
of a powerful new coalition to educate public officials on the
issue and put pressure on them to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of phone calls, the lobbyists from the world's
biggest software company refined the idea with their counterparts
at the biggest chip maker, Intel Corp., and the biggest computer
network firm, Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   They were encouraged by calls to and from other giants of the
high-tech industry and their network of allies among senators,
House members and congressional employees.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein was reluctant to claim personal credit for ramping up
the discussions, saying only that ``a lot of the people who staff
this issue know each other and talk to each other on a regular
basis.'' But others said Rubinstein took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Some high-tech firms stayed aloof. They included IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, and other companies with more sympathy for the
views of their government customers or less interest in
mass-marketed encryption.
</P>
<P>
   But the coalition signed up many other high-tech firms whose
leaders see stronger codes as a key selling point for the next
generation of hacker-resistant communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sun Microsystems and Netscape Communications, both among
the fiercest competitors of Microsoft, jumped on board.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition was formally launched March 4 as Americans for
Computer Privacy, after focus groups responded well to the name's
positive connotations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Intel and Cisco agreed to be the coalition's biggest
funders. Representatives of 10 other high-tech companies and the
Business Software Alliance, which represents software manufacturers
in 65 countries, joined them on ACP's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we had in common is, we all were being screamed at by our
customers ... who want us to fix this so that they can have secure
networks.'','' said lobbyist Dan Scheinman at the headquarters of
Cisco Systems in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the customers were eager to join as well. One was the
American Automobile Manufacturers Association. Its member firms
would like to cooperate on a cheap, more efficient system for
communicating with their suppliers around the globe _ but only if
each competitor could be absolutely certain that the other firms
couldn't decode its messages.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-industry trade associations such as the U.S. Chamber and
the National Association of Manufacturers, which together had 23
staff lobbyists working on the issue, joined. So did some smaller
business groups, like the Small Business Survival Committee, where
the only paid lobbyist is its president, Karen Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of small businesses in high-tech, and we're
concerned that government restrictions on entrepreneurs would crimp
job creation, so we agreed'' to join, Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Issue-oriented interest groups also climbed aboard. One early
member was Americans for Tax Reform, a Republican-subsidized
lobbying group whose president, Grover Norquist, has worked as a
part-time lobbyist for Microsoft. ``Our people don't want
government getting into their computers and reading their e-mail,
and they don't want overbearing, intrusive government regulations
destroying their sense of privacy,'' said Audrey Mullen, the
group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Other ACP members include the National Rifle Association and a
pro-gun, antiregulatory group it helped start that bears the
politically useful name of Law Enforcement Alliance of America.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition organizers had a little less luck at the left end of
the political spectrum. The American Civil Liberties Union and two
leading cyber-libertarian groups, the Electronic Frontier
Foundation and the Electronic Privacy Information Center, endorsed
the coalition's efforts but refused to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important to keep an independent voice for the
user community, and we differ with them on some details,'' said
Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the Center for Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit
spin-off started by former EFF and ACLU staffers, overcame similar
misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joined because we agree with their desire to fight against
any domestic controls on encryption and to promote export relief,''
said Alan Davidson, the center's staff counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in ACP has been so intense that the coalition, which
had only 26 potential members as recently as mid-February, has now
grown to embrace 40 associations, more than 90 companies and more
than 2,000 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the deep pockets of its main corporate sponsors, ACP
has spent about $2 million since March, about half of it on cable,
print and Internet ads. It has enough corporate pledges left in its
war chest to spend another $3 million to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ACP has assembled a top-dollar team of lobbyists, consultants,
lawyers, ad agencies, academics, webmasters and cybercasters from
the pool of professionals in the capital who shift smoothly between
government jobs and private for-profit and non-profit posts.
</P>
<P>
   The group's budget is not much by Washington standards _ no more
than half the annual lobbying budget of just one of its members,
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce _ but many of its members are already
well-connected. In addition to supporting ACP, they have given more
than $7 million in federal campaign contributions in the last year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of ACP's organization chart sit a bipartisan pair of
generals, a typical feature of large-scale lobbying campaigns aimed
at both the Republican-controlled Congress and the
Democratic-controlled White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republican operative Ed Gillespie, ACP's executive director,
plays a ``Mr. Outside'' role involving public appearances and work
with sympathetic members of Congress. A veteran House staffer,
Gillespie is president of a public relations firm chaired by former
Republican National Committee Chairman Haley Barbour, a lobbyist
whose clients include Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic attorney Jack Quinn, ACP's general counsel and a
partner in the powerful Washington law firm of Arnold and Porter,
is ``Mr. Inside,'' in charge of executive-branch strategy. His most
recent government jobs include general counsel to President Clinton
and chief of staff for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of its well-connected leadership, ACP has
focused its efforts where they could do the most good.
</P>
<P>
   Its lobbyists have conducted briefings in the offices of 230
House members and 30 senators, and its representatives have held
closed negotiations on a possible encryption compromise with a team
of officials from the White House and the Departments of Commerce,
Justice, Treasury and Defense.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of one session at the headquarters of the
National Security Agency in Maryland, those meetings have been held
in downtown Washington at the Madison Hotel or in the law offices
of Arnold and Porter.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to disclose the contents of the talks because
the government participants were assembled by the Office of
Management and Budget and the National Security Council. As parts
of the White House bureaucracy, OMB and the NSC are exempt from
laws requiring open meetings and disclosure of information.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings are co-chaired by OMB technology chief Bruce
McConnell and Smith, the ACP lawyer who is a colleague of Quinn's
at Arnold and Porter. Smith served as counsel to the Senate Armed
Services Committee when its chairman was Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and
his most recent government job was general counsel of the Central
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the administration's attitude was that they could
block any legislation that didn't like, which was probably true,''
Smith said. ``But the marketplace is putting them under pressure to
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACP submitted its latest compromise offer in early May, and
posted a copy on its World Wide Web page
(http://www.computerprivacy.org). McConnell expects the
administration to respond by announcing a new position in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in intense discussions not only with ACP, but with other
industry groups,'' said an administration official who declined to
be quoted by name. ``They have come up with some creative ideas for
addressing law enforcement's requirements, but we think that there
are are also national security issues left to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   That is consistent with the public comments of Hamre, the second
highest official in the Defense Department, which houses the
National Security Agency's vaunted code-busting machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is working very actively with law enforcement
and with (the) Commerce existing export laws.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the effort may someday be cited as a textbook case of how
an interest group can use the traditional levers of Washington
power _ money, lobbying, public opinion and political connections _
to make the system work for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the tech industry has sought federal permission
to export technology that will protect electronic messages and
records with the newest and strongest codes possible.
</P>
<P>
   They watched enviously as foreign software companies threatened
to capture markets around the world with powerful encryption
programs similar to ones that U.S. companies sell at home, but are
forbidden by federal law to sell abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robust foreign encryption is being so widely used that if U.S.
companies can't sell their products with encryption in it, they'll
either move production offshore or export product with a 'hole' in
it, so the user can plug in foreign encryption,'' said Jeffrey
Smith, a leading lawyer for the new coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI and the Defense Department's National Security
Agency have different priorities. They object to widespread sales
of codes so strong that they are unbreakable not just by
competitors, crooks and hackers, but also by law enforcement
agencies and American spies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I'm going to agree to is that American
encryption gets used by terrorists overseas without any effort on
our part to control that,'' Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre
warned Fortune 500 technology officials in Aspen, Colo., last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prosecutors are ``very much concerned about
commercially available encryption products being manufactured for
use in or imported into the United States that do not allow for
access to plain text by law enforcement pursuant to court orders,''
said FBI special agent Barry Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such objections, Congress has consistently rebuffed
the tech industry's pleas to loosen export restrictions, including
the House committees' impasse last September.
</P>
<P>
   After that setback, Ira Rubinstein, a senior Microsoft Corp.
attorney in Redmond, Wash., and his colleagues conceived the idea
of a powerful new coalition to educate public officials on the
issue and put pressure on them to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of phone calls, the lobbyists from the world's
biggest software company refined the idea with their counterparts
at the biggest chip maker, Intel Corp., and the biggest computer
network firm, Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   They were encouraged by calls to and from other giants of the
high-tech industry and their network of allies among senators,
House members and congressional employees.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein was reluctant to claim personal credit for ramping up
the discussions, saying only that ``a lot of the people who staff
this issue know each other and talk to each other on a regular
basis.'' But others said Rubinstein took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Some high-tech firms stayed aloof. They included IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, and other companies with more sympathy for the
views of their government customers or less interest in
mass-marketed encryption.
</P>
<P>
   But the coalition signed up many other high-tech firms whose
leaders see stronger codes as a key selling point for the next
generation of hacker-resistant communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sun Microsystems and Netscape Communications, both among
the fiercest competitors of Microsoft, jumped on board.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition was formally launched March 4 as Americans for
Computer Privacy, after focus groups responded well to the name's
positive connotations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Intel and Cisco agreed to be the coalition's biggest
funders. Representatives of 10 other high-tech companies and the
Business Software Alliance, which represents software manufacturers
in 65 countries, joined them on ACP's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we had in common is, we all were being screamed at by our
customers ... who want us to fix this so that they can have secure
networks.'','' said lobbyist Dan Scheinman at the headquarters of
Cisco Systems in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the customers were eager to join as well. One was the
American Automobile Manufacturers Association. Its member firms
would like to cooperate on a cheap, more efficient system for
communicating with their suppliers around the globe _ but only if
each competitor could be absolutely certain that the other firms
couldn't decode its messages.
</P>
<P>
   Multi-industry trade associations such as the U.S. Chamber and
the National Association of Manufacturers, which together had 23
staff lobbyists working on the issue, joined. So did some smaller
business groups, like the Small Business Survival Committee, where
the only paid lobbyist is its president, Karen Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of small businesses in high-tech, and we're
concerned that government restrictions on entrepreneurs would crimp
job creation, so we agreed'' to join, Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Issue-oriented interest groups also climbed aboard. One early
member was Americans for Tax Reform, a Republican-subsidized
lobbying group whose president, Grover Norquist, has worked as a
part-time lobbyist for Microsoft. ``Our people don't want
government getting into their computers and reading their e-mail,
and they don't want overbearing, intrusive government regulations
destroying their sense of privacy,'' said Audrey Mullen, the
group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Other ACP members include the National Rifle Association and a
pro-gun, antiregulatory group it helped start that bears the
politically useful name of Law Enforcement Alliance of America.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition organizers had a little less luck at the left end of
the political spectrum. The American Civil Liberties Union and two
leading cyber-libertarian groups, the Electronic Frontier
Foundation and the Electronic Privacy Information Center, endorsed
the coalition's efforts but refused to join.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's important to keep an independent voice for the
user community, and we differ with them on some details,'' said
Marc Rotenberg, director of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But the Center for Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit
spin-off started by former EFF and ACLU staffers, overcame similar
misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joined because we agree with their desire to fight against
any domestic controls on encryption and to promote export relief,''
said Alan Davidson, the center's staff counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in ACP has been so intense that the coalition, which
had only 26 potential members as recently as mid-February, has now
grown to embrace 40 associations, more than 90 companies and more
than 2,000 individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the deep pockets of its main corporate sponsors, ACP
has spent about $2 million since March, about half of it on cable,
print and Internet ads. It has enough corporate pledges left in its
war chest to spend another $3 million to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ACP has assembled a top-dollar team of lobbyists, consultants,
lawyers, ad agencies, academics, webmasters and cybercasters from
the pool of professionals in the capital who shift smoothly between
government jobs and private for-profit and non-profit posts.
</P>
<P>
   The group's budget is not much by Washington standards _ no more
than half the annual lobbying budget of just one of its members,
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce _ but many of its members are already
well-connected. In addition to supporting ACP, they have given more
than $7 million in federal campaign contributions in the last year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of ACP's organization chart sit a bipartisan pair of
generals, a typical feature of large-scale lobbying campaigns aimed
at both the Republican-controlled Congress and the
Democratic-controlled White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republican operative Ed Gillespie, ACP's executive director,
plays a ``Mr. Outside'' role involving public appearances and work
with sympathetic members of Congress. A veteran House staffer,
Gillespie is president of a public relations firm chaired by former
Republican National Committee Chairman Haley Barbour, a lobbyist
whose clients include Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic attorney Jack Quinn, ACP's general counsel and a
partner in the powerful Washington law firm of Arnold and Porter,
is ``Mr. Inside,'' in charge of executive-branch strategy. His most
recent government jobs include general counsel to President Clinton
and chief of staff for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of its well-connected leadership, ACP has
focused its efforts where they could do the most good.
</P>
<P>
   Its lobbyists have conducted briefings in the offices of 230
House members and 30 senators, and its representatives have held
closed negotiations on a possible encryption compromise with a team
of officials from the White House and the Departments of Commerce,
Justice, Treasury and Defense.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of one session at the headquarters of the
National Security Agency in Maryland, those meetings have been held
in downtown Washington at the Madison Hotel or in the law offices
of Arnold and Porter.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to disclose the contents of the talks because
the government participants were assembled by the Office of
Management and Budget and the National Security Council. As parts
of the White House bureaucracy, OMB and the NSC are exempt from
laws requiring open meetings and disclosure of information.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings are co-chaired by OMB technology chief Bruce
McConnell and Smith, the ACP lawyer who is a colleague of Quinn's
at Arnold and Porter. Smith served as counsel to the Senate Armed
Services Committee when its chairman was Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., and
his most recent government job was general counsel of the Central
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the administration's attitude was that they could
block any legislation that didn't like, which was probably true,''
Smith said. ``But the marketplace is putting them under pressure to
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACP submitted its latest compromise offer in early May, and
posted a copy on its World Wide Web page
(http://www.computerprivacy.org). McConnell expects the
administration to respond by announcing a new position in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in intense discussions not only with ACP, but with other
industry groups,'' said an administration official who declined to
be quoted by name. ``They have come up with some creative ideas for
addressing law enforcement's requirements, but we think that there
are are also national security issues left to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   That is consistent with the public comments of Hamre, the second
highest official in the Defense Department, which houses the
National Security Agency's vaunted code-busting machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is working very actively with law enforcement
and with (the) Commerce (Department) on a strategy that we think
will help break through this,'' Hamre said. He dropped hints that
in the administration's internal debates, he has argued that
foreign sales of the stronger encryption technology should be
phased in over several years.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Hamre told the Fortune 500 technology executives:
``I think that in the next several weeks, we'll be able to finally
hammer this out.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
