<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-US-$ADV02-CO     07-30 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-US-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BURST OF OPTIMISM WILL GREET NEW PRESIDENT OF VIOLENCE-RACKED
COLOMBIA
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-BOX-$ADV02.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The South American country of Colombia is a land of
music, emeralds, riotous carnivals, and breathtaking snow-capped
peaks, the exotic land of Nobel laureate Gabriel Garcia Marquez and
his modern classic ``One Hundred Years of Solitude.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a land of murder and violence, where more people are
kidnapped for ransom -- or because they work for foreign oil
companies -- than anywhere else on the planet, the land where a
grinding civil war has killed some 35,000 Colombians in three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But, on Friday(Aug. 7), it will become a land of rare optimism
when Andres Pastrana, the photogenic, blue-eyed former mayor of
Bogota, Colombia's capital, is sworn in as the next president.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana had run a lackluster campaign against Horacio Serpa,
the candidate hand-picked by outgoing President Ernesto Samper. So
much so, that the election easily could have gone either way.
</P>
<P>
   But since his surprising win on June 21, Pastrana, 44, has
rattled his critics and delighted his supporters by improving the
image of his country even before taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Last month(July), when Colombians thought Pastrana was
celebrating his victory in France by watching the World Cup final,
he was traipsing through the jungle for secret talks with leaders
of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), Latin
America's oldest and largest rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   The FARC -- and the smaller Cuban-inspired National Liberation
Army (ELN) -- number nearly 20,000 fighters. Demanding a
more-responsive government and increased social spending, they've
tried to topple the Colombian government since the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But now the FARC and the ELN say they will launch peace talks --
the first in six years -- with Pastrana during his first 90 days in
office, a sign that bloodshed may be nearing an end. Officials with
the Colombian military, which has traditionally wielded great
influence over the government, have not indicated whether they will
participate.
</P>
<P>
   In still another positive sign -- this one indicating a thaw in
icy U.S.-Colombia relations -- Pastrana is scheduled to meet
Monday(Aug. 3) with President Clinton at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, White House press secretary Mike McCurry was asked
whether the meeting signals an improvement in U.S.-Colombia
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it will. It will certainly be a chance for them to
address a broad range of issues on the bilateral agenda, including
narcotics cooperation, as well as President-elect Pastrana's
efforts to begin a peace process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States held such an aversion for Samper, Pastrana's
predecessor, it revoked his tourist visa in 1996 after allegations
surfaced that he knowingly accepted $6 million in campaign
contributions from drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   But how fast and how far Pastrana can go remains to be seen in a
nation so mired in political and economic crises.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is still the cocaine capital of the world, where up to
80 percent of the cocaine sold in the United States -- and a
growing amount of heroin -- is produced.
</P>
<P>
   And it's still a place where violence mars daily life.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, a dozen bombs exploded outside banks in
Medellin, once home to the world's most powerful drug cartel,
shattering windows and blowing off doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the money involved, drug traffickers are able to
corrupt every level of society, and so nothing's going to improve
in Colombia as long as that's the case,'' said Larry Birns, head of
the Council on Hemispheric Affairs, a Washington, D.C.-based
research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for drugs in the United States isn't going away,''
he said. ``There still isn't an alternative for farmers who grow
coca.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an ineffectual Samper administration, the country's rebel
forces expanded their influence, and have taken control of nearly
40 percent of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   These guerrillas have kidnapped hundreds of civilians, among
them four American tourists who were on a bird-watching vacation in
late March.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have clear links to the drug trade, and are thought
to provide protection for airstrips, cultivation fields, and the
processing plants that produce heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its anti-narcotics effort, the United States has
given $100 million to the Colombian military this year, or more
than three times the total two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's military forces are 147,000-members strong -- some
19,500 of whom are properly trained in anti-guerrilla tactics --
but have been ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   This ineffectiveness is why Pastrana's incoming administration,
although working toward peace, announced Thursday a 59-percent
increase in defense and security spending next year, to $4.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But that may only make it harder for the administration to boost
social spending, sure to be one of the rebels' key demands during
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Pastrana inherits a troubled economy, in which the
inflation rate tops 20 percent, the gap between the rich and poor
is widening and the unemployment rate is at an all-time high of
14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters say Pastrana, who comes from a long line of
politicians and is the son of a former president, may have the
background and the determination to turn the tide in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pastrana was kidnapped by the Medellin drug cartel
during his mayoral campaign, then was freed a week later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the fluent English-speaker narrowly lost a bid for
president to Samper. Then, three days later, he blew the whistle on
his opponent by playing a taped phone conversation in which a
leading Cali cartel drug trafficker discussed contributing to the
Samper campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to June's election, which ended the ruling Liberal Party's
12-year lock on the presidency, the Conservative Party's Pastrana
campaigned on an anti-corruption platform. He vowed to improve
U.S.-Colombia relations, engage the rebels in peace talks, and
better the lot of the 18 million Colombians who live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My foreign policy will aim to restore Colombia's lost dignity.
To regain the respect that our people deserve in the international
community so that once again we can be proud to pronounce
Colombia's name in all corners of the world,'' Pastrana said
following the election.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, according to his fans.
</P>
<P>
   Following Pastrana's historic face-to-face meeting with FARC
leaders, Colombian guerrillas and civilian organizations agreed
that they will hold a national convention before Oct. 12 to discuss
economic and social reforms that could pave the way for a permanent
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Equally as important, leaders of the main right-wing
paramilitary groups, which for years have imposed a reign of terror
in rural Colombia, said they would be willing to join peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists say that state abuses have increased in
recent years, with the number of extra-judicial killings and
disappearances climbing from 2,036 in 1996, to 2,416 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And following exploratory peace talks last month in Germany with
Colombian business, social, and church leaders, the ELN, the
country's second-largest rebel group, promised to stop at least
some military activities, most notably against foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana also has vowed to remove security forces from 16,000
square miles of southern Colombia after he takes office. This was a
stumbling block to formal peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Colombian military remains an important wild card in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastrana will need the United States to apply pressure on the
Colombian military to get them involved,'' said Coletta Youngers,
an expert on Colombia at the Washington Office on Latin America, a
liberal think tank. ``Unless the military's involved, the process
won't be successful, and the military's been pretty quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
