<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYL-JONES-TRAGEDY-NY     07-30 3086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYL-JONES-TRAGEDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 CHRONICLE of a TRAGEDY FORETOLD  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By PETER MANSO  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    On the evening of Feb. 20, 1998, less than a week after the
much-heralded publication of her first novel in more than 20 years,
Gayl Jones, 48, was handcuffed and removed from her Lexington, Ky.,
home by the local police.
 &HT;    Inside the two-bedroom bungalow, her husband lay bleeding from a
self-inflicted knife wound.
 &HT;    The confrontation began just after 6 p.m., when police officers
knocked on the door at 440 Locust Ave., to serve a 15-year-old
warrant for the arrest of Bob Higgins, also known as Bob Jones. The
man opened the door a crack, but after a brief exchange with the
cops, he slammed it shut, ran to the rear of the house and
reappeared, holding two knives to his throat.
 &HT;    ``Don't come in,'' he screamed. ``I'll kill myself if you come
in here.''
 &HT;    At 8:45, the SWAT team arrived. The couple had barricaded
themselves inside, and Jones was calling 911. She insisted that she
too would kill herself if the police stormed the house, and then
she announced that they had turned on the gas.
 &HT;    Whether the couple intended to asphyxiate themselves or blow up
the neighborhood, SWAT members couldn't be sure. Having evacuated
surrounding residents to the end of the block, they decided to go
in. Two members of the five-man rapid-entry team managed to throw
themselves across Jones, who was on the couch less than 10 feet
from the door.
 &HT;    But the two assigned to Higgins did not get to him in time. He
thrust one of the knives into his throat with such force that it
lodged in his spine. A geyser of blood sprayed across the room.
 &HT;    Over the next month the outpouring of news articles predictably
focused on the brilliant black writer whose comeback had been
blasted by her husband's death _ and the hideous irony that it was
a flattering full-page article about Jones and her new novel, ``The
Healing,'' in Newsweek that had led the police to discover Higgins'
fugitive status.
 &HT;    Yet beyond the explanation that Jones was simply another victim
of an abusive, controlling husband was a more complex reality, and
the violence surrounding the couple was in fact the culmination of
the legacies that had wedded Gayl and Bob to each other.
 &HT;    If the question was why a woman as smart as Jones could be swept
away by a man like Higgins, then the answer lay not only in her own
lifetime but also in her collective past, in the blood of
generations that coursed through her writing. It was not just life
imitating art; it was that Jones and Higgins were united in the
conviction that a racist society had doomed them to repeat the
violent history of their forebears.
 &HT;    As she wrote in ``Wild Figs and Secret Places,'' a 1983 poem,
``Memory is a mosquito/pregnant again/and out for blood.''
 &HT;    Born Nov. 23, 1949, to Franklin and Lucille Jones, Gayl grew up
in a cramped, dilapidated house with no indoor toilet in Speigle
Heights, one of Lexington's more turbulent black neighborhoods. Her
father worked late hours as a restaurant cook, while her mother, an
aspiring writer, stayed home with Gayl and her younger brother,
Franklin Jr.
 &HT;    Most weekends Lucille took the children to visit her mother, who
lived on a small farm outside town. There the grandmother and
mother shared old family tales in the oral tradition of rural
blacks throughout Kentucky.
 &HT;    In the mid-'60s, the Jones children would have attended the
black high school, but Lucille made sure that Gayl and her brother
were among the handful of African-Americans enrolling at Henry
Clay, the white school known for its academic excellence. Painfully
shy to the point of muteness, Gayl seemed almost invisible to other
students, although several teachers took note of her.
 &HT;    Her Spanish teacher, Anna Dodd, who usually kept her distance
from students, often lent Gayl books and talked to her about her
adventures among the Paris expatriates in the '20s and '30s. Just
as she soaked up her grandmother's and mother's reminiscences, Gayl
absorbed Dodd's.
 &HT;    ``I want to write like Henry James,'' she told Sue Ann Allen,
her junior-year English teacher, and the final story she turned in
was, indeed, written in a Jamesian style.
 &HT;    But when she went to Connecticut College on a scholarship
arranged with the assistance of Dodd's friend Elizabeth Hardwick,
the writer and a Lexington native, Jones discovered a literary
legacy that was more her own.
 &HT;    The disparity between her background and that of white
classmates had been painfully evident in segregated Lexington.
 &HT;    ``She grew up in a town with two statues of Confederate generals
on the courthouse lawn,'' says Don Edwards, a veteran columnist at
The Lexington Herald-Leader who can trace his family to slave
owners. ``And then to go from that to the North, Gayl must have
felt like an astronaut shot into space.''
 &HT;    Connecticut College, then a small, elite women's school, was
another world entirely. Jones landed there during the turbulent
'60s, but while other African-American students were demonstrating
for more minority admissions and an all-black dormitory, she
remained on the periphery, quiet and withdrawn. At the same time,
she became engrossed in African-American literature and studied
with Robert Hayden, the esteemed black poet and literary historian
then visiting from the University of Michigan.
 &HT;    Her reading seemed as much a way of defining herself as protests
were for others, and when she returned home from college the summer
after her freshman year she told her former English teacher of a
new project. ``She said she was starting a `generational novel'
based on her family history,'' Sue Ann Allen says.
 &HT;    Graduating with a stellar record, Jones was accepted in 1971 to
Brown University's graduate writing program. By the end of four
years she had all but completed the manuscripts for two novels,
several collections of short stories and poetry and a play. And she
had been listening to the blues, which now became an affirmation of
her heritage as a black woman.
 &HT;    At Brown, Jones attracted another mentor: Prof. Michael S.
Harper, a prominent African-American poet and critic. Harper had
long been influenced by jazz and the blues and thus had a unique
appreciation of what Jones was attempting in her writing.
 &HT;    When Harper brought Jones' work to the attention of Toni
Morrison, then an editor at Random House, she signed Jones to a
book contract. With the publication of her first novel in mid-1975,
Jones was heralded as a significant, major new author.
 &HT;    In 1975, Jones became a visiting lecturer in English at the
University of Michigan and a year later was hired as an assistant
professor. Jones was the only African-American woman among the
department's 70 or so faculty members (two black female
predecessors had not been tenured), and Hayden, the
African-American poet whom she had met at Connecticut College, was
near retirement.
 &HT;    With her isolation and watchful alienation, she was, apparently,
altogether ripe for the picking by the time Bob Higgins, an
attractive, well-dressed African-American, happened into her life.
She was first seen around campus with him in the late '70s, about
the time of the publication of ``White Rat,'' which had followed
hard on the heels of her second novel, ``Eva's Man.''
 &HT;    Born in Cleveland in 1947, Higgins brought his own legacy of
racism and family suffering to the relationship. Having been
abandoned at a young age by his mother (who eventually died
homeless, a fatality of mental illness and alcoholism), he was
reared by relatives in Detroit as well as by several foster
families, including that of George Breitman, a leading Socialist
and a supporter of black nationalism.
 &HT;    Although he later earned a degree at the University of Michigan,
Higgins hung out in Detroit at Wayne State University, which in the
mid-'60s and early '70s was a hotbed of black activism, even more
so than Berkeley. He routinely proclaimed his own brilliance,
calling himself ``a true Hegelian'' and ``a math genius'' who
should be on the university's faculty. He was also writing a column
for Wayne State's student paper under the byline ``A. Violence.''
 &HT;    Higgins had already been married and divorced when, around 1970,
he began a relationship with Carolyn Ramsey that was a blueprint
for what happened with Jones. ``As a young black woman, I was
totally smitten,'' Ramsey says. ``I felt that he was misunderstood
by everybody but me.''
 &HT;    When his treatise on Hegel was turned down by publishers and
received an unfavorable reading from Breitman, Higgins, then living
on Staten Island, went bananas and sparked a police standoff at his
apartment. When the cops lobbed tear gas inside, Higgins took a
suicidal leap out the window, landing on the frozen ground six
floors below.
 &HT;    Miraculously, he survived and though he was to be sent to
Ypsilanti, Mich., for psychiatric treatment, his case fell through
the cracks, and in 1975 he showed up in Ann Arbor instead. There,
he announced to old acquaintances that his survival was evidence of
his ``godliness,'' even proof that he was the new Messiah.
 &HT;    Many who knew the couple were perplexed by Jones' infatuation
with a man who, by the early '80s, was no longer a Marxist and
black nationalist but was cloaking himself in capitalist dreams and
messianic religiosity. In addition to dressing in silk suits and
driving expensive cars, Higgins opened two Ann Arbor investment
businesses and took over as Jones' agent, which instigated the
withdrawal of Morrison as Jones' editor.
 &HT;    Still, Jones continued to progress in both her academic and
literary careers, and she was rewarded with tenure in 1982. She had
earlier contacted Naomi Long Madgett, a poet and the publisher and
editor of Lotus Press, the small Detroit house known for publishing
African-American poets.
 &HT;    Madgett eventually accepted three of Jones' collections, the
first of which was ``Song for Anninho,'' a rendering in verse of
the plot of her unpublished novel ``Palmares,'' in which two
enslaved lovers escape to northeastern Brazil. Jones' only requests
were that no author's photograph appear on the book cover and that
she not do readings to help sales.
 &HT;    The two communicated by letter or phone except for one brief
meeting in 1980. But after the publication of ``Song for Anninho''
in 1981 and ``The Hermit-Woman'' in 1983, the editor heard almost
nothing from Jones for about two years after the couple abruptly
fled Ann Arbor.
 &HT;    The precipitating event was a gay-rights parade at which Higgins
railed that he was God and that AIDS was a form of divine
punishment. One of the marchers, a woman, had punched him, and the
police refused to file an assault complaint; he returned to the
march with a shotgun and was arrested for felonious assault, a
charge that carried a potential sentence of four years in jail.
 &HT;    Neither Jones nor Higgins appeared in the courtroom to answer
the charges. Two days earlier, Jones had resigned from the
university and given vent to her long-seething rage: ``I reject
your lying racist (expletive), and I call upon God. Do what you
want. God is with Bob and I'm with him.''
 &HT;    Higgins was found guilty in absentia, and a bench warrant was
issued for his arrest.
 &HT;    Although in 1992 Jones emerged for a rare and successful public
reading and discussion of her work at the University of Kentucky,
for the most part the couple remained hidden from the world.
Higgins, in his escalating megalomania, was creating Web sites to
spread a new spiritualism, and by late 1996 Jones had completed
``The Healing'' and was almost finished with a draft of
``Mosquito.''
 &HT;    Professional as ever, in early 1997 she contacted Beacon Press
about reclaiming the paperback rights to ``Corregidora'' and
``Eva's Man,'' which the small Boston-based publisher bought from
Random House in the mid-'80s. To Helene Atwan, Beacon's director,
the novels were backlist gems, and she offered an additional
advance to keep them.
 &HT;    At first Jones refused, explaining that she didn't want those
books to be her only novels in print, presumably because of their
portrayal of black men as violent and abusive, a subject of heated
literary debate then. When Atwan asked if Beacon could publish her
latest writing, Jones seemed less adamant and soon gave Atwan
instructions for downloading the manuscripts of ``The Healing'' and
``Mosquito'' from a Web site.
 &HT;    The contract negotiations by e-mail went smoothly, although
Atwan sometimes suspected that it was Jones' agent, identified by
one of Higgins' many aliases, who was corresponding under Jones'
name.
 &HT;    At the same time, Higgins was taking ever greater risks for a
man dodging a felony warrant. Even though he had been going by the
name Bob Jones, clues to his identity were everywhere in his
cyberspace publishing. With the diagnosis of his mother-in-law
Lucille's throat cancer, he became even more convinced of his
omnipotence. He not only took control of her medical treatment but
used it as the occasion for a full-bore assault on the white
establishment.
 &HT;    During January and February 1997, Jones accompanied her mother
to radiation treatments at the Markey Cancer Center at the
University of Kentucky. On Monday, Feb. 24, 1997, with Lucille's
weight at 68 pounds, the attending physician hospitalized her and
recommended inserting a stomach feeding tube. Higgins objected to
the procedure, and because Lucille seemed so confused, the hospital
ordered a psychiatric evaluation and concluded that she was
``unduly and inappropriately manipulated by family _ especially
son-in-law.''
 &HT;    Banned from visiting, Jones and Higgins were ordered to leave;
when they refused, hospital security was called, and with Higgins'
further resistance, the campus police arrived and charged him with
disorderly conduct.
 &HT;    Higgins and Jones then e-mailed a document entitled
``Kidnapped/Held Incommunicado'' to the national press, and on
Monday morning, March 3, 1997, copies were faxed to the university
and federal, state and local law-enforcement agencies as well as to
President Clinton, the first lady and Vice President Gore.
 &HT;    The next day, Lucille indicated that she wanted to go home, and
again her doctors advised against it. Instead she was transferred
to Central Baptist Hospital, where Higgins and Jones agreed to the
surgery. Sent home on March 13, Lucille developed respiratory
problems and died on March 20.
 &HT;    Higgins' campaign against the medical center then went into high
gear. Jones had been keeping a low profile, but now her name
appeared on a 10-page communique on the Internet listing 50
``changes'' in Lucille after ``one week of U.K. kidnapping.'' The
document described the closeness between the mother and daughter _
undoubtedly Jones' sentiments _ yet the rambling prose was
obviously not hers.
 &HT;    Higgins' onslaught continued with more faxes, phone calls and
mailings to the university. Even Lexington's police chief, Larry
Walsh, had been receiving four or five calls a day, and by early
summer he noticed an increasingly menacing tone.
 &HT;    The police were especially concerned by his Feb. 20, 1998,
letter to the University of Kentucky's president, Charles T.
Wethington Jr.: a reference to ``checking out all the pipes and
fixtures in your system'' implied a bomb threat. Finally figuring
out after the Newsweek article that Bob Jones was Bob Higgins, the
cops had a legal basis for bringing him in.
 &HT;    With the SWAT team surrounding the house and Higgins threatening
to kill himself, Jones called 911. On the tape, she speaks quickly,
with uncharacteristic volume, her voice surprisingly firm.
 &HT;    Gayl Jones: My name is Gayl Jones and I am an author. ... You
killed my mother, Lucille Jones, and now you are trying to kill my
husband.. . .
 &HT;    Police: Ma'am, just try and relax, OK?
 &HT;    Finally, when the police took Jones out of the house, she was
barefoot and wearing sweatpants. Led to the next-door neighbor's
porch, she stood staring at the floor, whispering to herself.
 &HT;    At her side, Sgt. Joan Root asked, ``Who are you talking to?''
 &HT;    ``I'm talking to the spirit of my mother,'' Jones replied, her
eyes vacant and unfocused.
 &HT;    When the paramedics carried Higgins to the ambulance, the knife
still protruding from his neck, Jones lifted her eyes and watched.
She made no move to go to him but asked the policewoman where he
was being taken. When told the University of Kentucky Hospital, she
shook her head, moaning: ``Oh, no. They're going to kill him too.
That's what this is all about. Oh, no, no, no. Don't take him to
U.K.''
 &HT;    In fact, there was nothing that could be done to save him, and
he was pronounced dead later that evening. Jones was committed to
the state mental hospital for 72 hours of observation. Her
confinement was then extended until March 9, when it was deemed
that she was no longer a danger to herself.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Higgins was buried with only four people
present: two reporters, Jones' cousin Cynthia Gentry, and another
woman. Jones sent a eulogy.
 &HT;    Since her release, Jones, who refused several requests to be
interviewed for this article, has spoken only to family members, a
lawyer and Michael Harper, her mentor from Brown, who has managed
to stay her friend despite Higgins' attempt to cut off her ties to
him. Alone in the house, she has remained behind drawn blinds; it
is only at night that neighbors can see her vague form illuminated
by a flickering TV.
 &HT;     c.1998 Peter Manso  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Peter Manso is the author of ``Mailer: His Life and Times''
and ``Brando: The Biography.'') &LR;
