<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASEKETBALL-FILM-REVI     07-30 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEKETBALL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASEKETBALL': ATTENTION, SPORTS FANS _ THESE DUDES GOT GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, through sheer overkill, ``BASEketball,'' will
put an end to the use of the word ``dude'' as an all-purpose comic
term of endearment shouted in each other's faces by hormonally
rampant, eternally adolescent movie pals.
</P>
<P>
   Should it do so, the flourishing genre of acne-challenged,
gonad-driven buddy comedy that came into its own with ``Wayne's
World'' could find itself facing a major identity crisis. What,
after all, could possibly replace ``dude?'' ``Darling?''
</P>
<P>
   This funny, gleefully offensive spoof of professional sports,
written and directed by David Zucker, does suggest a novel
alternative to the question of how overgrown teen-age sidekicks in
a gross-out comedy might better express their affection. Why not
have them actually kiss?
</P>
<P>
   After going through their ups and downs together, Coop (Trey
Parker) and Remer (Matt Stone), the inventors of a driveway game
called BASEketball that becomes a national obsession, kiss and make
up in what may be the slurpiest, most tongue-twisting, but least
erotic osculatory collision to be found in a recent movie. Imagine
two dogs licking each other's faces, and you'll get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The game that Coop and Remer improvise one evening is an
elementary basket-shooting contest in which successful shots landed
from varying distances become the equivalents of singles, doubles,
triples and home runs. The game's primary defense strategy is ``the
psyche out,'' in which you try to shock your opponent into
confusion as he's about to make a shot.
</P>
<P>
   One effective ploy is to pull down your shirt and squirt milk
into his face from concealed bulbs. Or you might suddenly appear in
a tee-shirt on which you've printed a doctored picture of yourself
having sex with his girlfriend. In short, anything goes, the
nastier, smuttier and more humiliating the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``BASEketball'' is essentially two movies stuck together like
chewing gum on a subway platform. One is a dumber-than-dumb teen
comedy crammed with farcical sight-gags and raunchy adolescent
humor, the other a no-holds-barred satire of professional sports,
and the greed, egotism and pomposity surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with a narrator delivering a grandiose
futuristic mini-history of the decline of professional sports
through over-commercialization. By the time the Preparation H Arena
was constructed, we learn, the audience for professional sports had
seriously shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   Enter BASEketball, a new populist sport that anyone can play and
whose by-laws forbid corporate sponsorship, commercial endorsements
and the trading of players. Its teams tend to have down-to-earth
names like the Milwaukee Beers (Coop and Remer's team), the Dallas
Felons and the Los Angeles Riots. Instead of letter-sweaters and
pompoms, The Beers' cheerleaders favor black leather-trimmed
lingerie accessorized with riding crops.
</P>
<P>
   BASEketball's purity is threatened when a sleazy sports
entrepreneur named Cain (Robert Vaughn) hatches an evil scheme to
take control of the sport and make millions. His plan involves
exploiting a charity called the Dream Come True Foundation, which
helps terminally ill children (its president insists on calling
them ``health challenged'' and ``survival impaired'') by gratifying
their dying wishes.
</P>
<P>
   One ailing 8-year-old youth named Joey (Trevor Einhorn), who is
about to have a liver operation, gets to spend a day hanging out
with the Milwaukee Beers. The little tyke eagerly participates in a
drinking contest at a bar showing the Jerry Springer Show. Every
fight that breaks out on the program requires the downing of
another round, and by the time little Joey is wheeled into the
operating room, he is beyond sozzled.
</P>
<P>
   As in his ``Naked Gun'' series, Zucker's comic strategy is to a
fire off a continuous machine-gun volley of jokes of all shapes and
sizes trusting that enough will hit home to keep an audience on the
edge of a giggle. Occasionally, as in a hospital sequence in which
Coop and Remer don surgical gowns and nearly destroy a ward in a
frenzied attempt to save a child's life, the movie tries for a more
sustained slapstick tone.
</P>
<P>
   BASEketball is at its looniest when it is content to be a
scattershot blitz of gags, jokes and insults puncturing the
pretensions of sports stars, sportscasters and fans alike. What are
professional sports anyway but pumped-up ritualized macho fantasies
of eternal youth and physical conquest invested with a
quasi-mystical import?
</P>
<P>
   With its goofy salaciousness and short attention span,
BASEketball illustrates an amusing parallel vision of athletics in
contrast to the one shown on television. Stripped of pomp and
ceremony, it all comes down to a bunch of ``dudes'' scrapping it
out in a driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``BASEketball'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes glimpses of nudity and a lot
of crude humor about sex and body parts.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BASEKETBALL'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Zucker; written by Zucker, Robert LoCash,
Lewis Friedman and Jeff Wright; director of photography, Steve
Mason; edited by Jeffrey Reiner; music by James Ira Newborn;
production designer, Steven Jordan; produced by Zucker, LoCash and
Gil Netter; released by Universal Pictures. Running time: 105
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Trey Parker (Joe Cooper), Matt Stone (Doug Remer), Robert
Vaughn (Baxter Cain), Ernest Borgnine (Ted Denslow) and Trevor
Einhorn (Joey). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
