<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OUTDOOR-DANCE-3TAK     07-30 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OUTDOOR-DANCE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOOR DANCE IN ITS ADULTHOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A young girl dressed in a scalloped tunic and
kerchief jumps awkwardly on a makeshift outdoor stage beneath the
Queensboro Bridge in the late 1960s. Seven shambling young
avant-gardists spread the 1970s gospel of fashionably untutored and
untheatrical dance performance on a city sidewalk. Ballroom dancers
spin and fly through countless nights in the parks of New York City
in the 1940s and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Charming photographs from ``Stepping Out: A Century of Dance in
New York City Parks,'' an exhibition at the Central Park Arsenal
Building, suggest that outdoor dance performances have long been
with us. But those performances have changed a great deal, to judge
by the attractions offered by festivals this summer in the city and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor dance programs have grown more sophisticated and more
varied over the years. The major New York performing arts festivals
_ Lincoln Center Out of Doors, Celebrate Brooklyn and Central Park
Summerstage _ began with programming to draw specific ethnic groups
and provide a forum for local performers.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn festival, which began two decades ago with nine
performances, has more than 40 this year, ranging from works by
what Jack Walsh, the festival's director, called the dance icon
Twyla Tharp to pieces by relatively new choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   Its setting, the Prospect Park Band Shell, is midway through a
$3.4 million upgrading that will improve sightlines and seating and
provide better lighting of the complex sort required for dance
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Successful outdoor programs made their mark on New York dance
history. Modern dance and ballet, a rarity outdoors, could be seen
regularly at Lewisohn Stadium, now the site of City College's Aaron
Davis Hall in Harlem, from the late 1920s through the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   The much-lamented Delacorte Dance Festival in Central Park
presented an astonishing variety of dance from the early 60s into
the 70s. But it is only in the last decade that the idea of outdoor
festivals, once dismissed as second-rate, suspiciously popular
entertainment, has caught on in a big way with donors, audiences,
reviewers and dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences have grown as producers have broadened the programming
and become increasingly willing to take greater risks in their
booking, and sponsors have become more willing to support the
festivals. Major companies seem willing to appear more often
outdoors, too, though that may be in part a response to generally
dwindling performance opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the goals for all of us has been to make this be taken
more seriously,'' Jenneth Webster, program director of the Lincoln
Center festival, said. ``Not `Oh, it's free and it's outdoors so
it's nothing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dance outdoors can present special challenges and rewards to
audiences and performers alike. Some things are irritating, like
the distractions of the world outside the magic circle of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Some are exuberantly liberating, like the sudden rain that
enabled the Pilobolus Dance Theater to skid into unplanned
children's high jinks years ago at the Delacorte, or simply the
size of the stage itself, so much larger than the circumscribed
spaces dancers tend to appear in.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, from dance greats to relative neophytes and from fans
to casual browsers, must come prepared for the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Big-name choreographers and dance companies will perform free
this summer in New York City for audiences that, unused to
attending formal theater or unable to afford the tickets, might
otherwise never see their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now get a lot of dancers coming out to see each other's
work,'' said Bill Bragin, executive producer of the Central Park
Summerstage festival. ``But we also get people who are seeing a
dance concert for the first time, without the intimidation factor
that can happen in other more formal settings.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Moss, vice president for programming at Lincoln Center,
estimates that 75 percent to 80 percent of the audiences for the
festival and the Midsummer Night's Swing summer dance party have
never been there before. ``For a brief two months out of the year,
they change people's perceptions of Lincoln Center,'' Ms. Moss
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados have not been forgotten, though. Friday night, for
example, the modern-dance choreographer Molissa Fenley will present
two new works, intriguingly entitled ``La Muse Menagere'' and ``On
the Other Ocean,'' at the Central Park Summerstage festival. Ms.
Fenley will share the program with the Pascal Rioult Dance Theater,
a company founded by a former Martha Graham principal dancer, which
will also perform a premiere, ``El Mozote,'' based on events in the
civil war in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn Saturday night, two newer choreographers, Arthur
Aviles and Hernando Cortez, will perform new works commissioned by
the Celebrate Brooklyn festival in Prospect Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Merce Cunningham Dance Company will open the Lincoln Center
Out of Doors festival dance series next Friday with a new
``event,'' as Cunningham calls his site-specific works. There will
also be concerts of dance from Africa and the Dominican Republic
and participatory programs of African, American Indian, Korean and
Irish dancing. During the week, the festival will present concerts
by the New York Baroque Dance Company and the Dayton Contemporary
Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Jose Limon Dance Company will perform later in August at
Lincoln Center, as will Dance Alloy of Pittsburgh, a troupe of
aboriginal dancers from Formosa; Noche Flamenca; the Jose Greco II;
the Soweto Street Beat troupe, and Pepatian. There will also be
talks on Donald McKayle and other black contributors to American
modern dance by panels that include McKayle and Joan Myers Brown,
the founder and director of Philadanco.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn festival will present Twyla Tharp and Abdel
Salaam's Forces of Nature company in mid-August. Dance will also be
performed during the week, too, at Bryant Park and Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   In what promises to be the mother of all outdoor dance
performances, audiences will journey through the woods of the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass., with Joanna Haigood
and her San Francisco-based Zaccho Dance Theater in ``Invisible
Wings'' in late August. Created at the Pillow, the multimedia piece
recreates the dangerous northward passage of American slaves along
the underground railroad, which included a stop on what are now
festival grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Open-air settings invariably become a part of outdoor dance. The
sun beats down, enclosing audiences as completely as any theater
walls and ceiling. Stars provide a dazzling nighttime canopy. Birds
dart and butterflies flutter across the line of vision.
</P>
<P>
   And the sounds _ whether of planes, sirens and car horns,
crickets or the mutterings and rustlings of seat-scavengers _ form
the kind of accidental music beloved by John Cage, Cunningham's
longtime collaborator. Such distractions must be endured and even
embraced. But often they suggest or reveal unexpected facets of a
dance or add to the pleasure of spontaneity that comes only with
live performing.
</P>
<P>
   Some things work better than others on an outdoor stage.
Intimate gestures and reclining bodies tend to be lost. Spoken text
in dance is sometimes difficult to follow. Ms. Webster of Lincoln
Center worries about the reverberations from the amplified sounds
of footwork in tap and flamenco.
</P>
<P>
   Live music can present a problem, particularly for dance
performances in the Damrosch Band Shell at Lincoln Center, a more
contained proscenium space than the crannies and open plaza spaces
that also serve as stages. Ms. Webster has a special fondness for
pieces created for those crannies, but how to balance atmospheric
lighting with the very real problem of audience members' tripping
and falling?
</P>
<P>
   But choreographers, even major ones, need little encouragement
to rework dances for these spaces. And dancers tend to love the
large stages and audiences that come with outdoor performing. The
stages are large in comparison to the small theaters where many of
the dancers usually perform. Celebrate Brooklyn, for example, can
accommodate an audience of 7,200 in theater seating and on the
lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Munisteri, who performed with his dancers at Summerstage
this month, talked of the ``thrill of a 1,200-person audience, of
dancing on a 15-foot-high stage, using the San Remo as a spot for
pirouettes and feeling a breeze ripple through costumes that were
designed for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortez said it was profoundly freeing to ``look out at the
audience and beyond, to the trees and horizon,'' from the
Inside/Out stage at Jacob's Pillow, a rustic hillside space that
looks suspended among the trees and sky. Cortez, like Aviles a
resident choreographer at Celebrate Brooklyn this summer, found
himself responding similarly to the large rehearsal space of the
Picnic House at Prospect Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space is huge, unlike any other rehearsal studio,'' Cortez
said of the quaint, light-filled room. ``It allowed me the freedom
to expand, to do a lot of moving and sculpting of space. And the
slipperiness of the floor allowed us to do baseball slides. I'm
hoping they will work at the band shell.''
</P>
<P>
   He will present two new sections of ``Bittersweet Symphony,''
set to music by Simply Red and Sinead O'Connor, that should
contribute, he said, to a ``feel-good outdoor experience.'' He said
it promised to be a high for his company. ``The openness of a space
can enhance performing quality. You move bigger and project
expression more.''
</P>
<P>
   Aviles used the residency to ``go ahead and do something I've
wanted to do.'' His ``Narcissus,'' a replication in movement of the
cacophony of its score by Charles Ives, as Aviles described it, was
developed through separate conversations and improvisations with
two groups of performers whose dancing will be combined with a
mirror-image duet.
</P>
<P>
   Such a concept _ and the ebulliently outspoken messages of
Hispanic and gay pride that inform Aviles' choreography _ would
have been inconceivable in an outdoor festival a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Walsh and Rachel Chanoff, co-producers of the Brooklyn
festival, base their choices on their own extensive concertgoing as
well as advice they and the other festival producers seek from
artists and presenters. In addition, Walsh and Ms. Chanoff ask
artists whom they might commission work from to submit a one-page
treatment for a new piece.
</P>
<P>
   Are the producers aiming at entertainment or education? Both,
they say, in varying degrees. One of Walsh's concerns is that his
performers and audiences have the experience of a professional,
fully produced show. ``We're trying to present things that people
might not otherwise see,'' he said. ``It's been a journey.
Celebrate Brooklyn started with a very definite mission. It was a
time when there were very few performances in the outer boroughs.
The parks were considered unsafe. We were trying to change
attitudes about parks and Brooklyn and create a sense of
community.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Webster, the Lincoln Center festival is ``a wonderful
way for people to get together and see what other people are
thinking.'' For Ms. Moss, such festivals provide the increasingly
rare opportunity for people to do something together.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, it all seems to be working. Bragin said people used to
ask whether there would be a Summerstage the next year. ``Now it's
`What will you be presenting?' '' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a sampling of dance performances this summer at
outdoor festivals. Events are free unless otherwise noted, though
donations are requested for some.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATE BROOKLYN presents Cortez and Company and Arthur Aviles
Typical Theater Saturday; Tharp on Aug. 15, and Forces of Nature on
Aug. 21 at the Prospect Park Band Shell, Ninth Street and Prospect
Park West, Brooklyn. All performances are at 8 p.m. and will be
held rain or shine. Information: (718) 855-7882, ext. 52.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL PARK SUMMERSTAGE presents Molissa Fenley and the Pascal
Rioult Dance Company Friday night at 8:30 at Rumsey Playfield,
Central Park, 72nd Street and Fifth Avenue. The performance will be
held rain or shine. Information: (212) 360-2777.
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN CENTER OUT OF DOORS presents the Merce Cunningham Dance
Company next Friday; the Dayton Contemporary Dance Company and the
Donald McKayle Celebration on Aug. 13 and 14; Jose Greco II
Flamenco Dance Company on Aug. 18, and the Jose Limon Dance Company
and the Donald McKayle Celebration on Aug. 20 and 21 at the
Damrosch Park Band Shell. All performances are at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dance programs at the Fountain Plaza include the Formosa
Aboriginal Song and Dance Troupe on Aug. 12 at 5:30 p.m.; Noche
Flamenca on Aug. 18 at 6 p.m.; Dance Alloy on Aug. 27 at 5:30 p.m.;
Soweto Street Beat on Aug. 28 at 6 p.m., and Merian Soto's Pepatian
on Aug. 30 at 4 p.m. Panel discussions will be held on Aug. 14 and
Aug. 21 at 5 p.m. on the North Plaza. Events are held rain or
shine. Information: (212) 875-5108.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER IN THE SQUARE '98 presents dance on Wednesdays at 5 p.m.
in the center of Union Square Park, Broadway and 14th Street,
featuring Art Bridgman, Myrna Packer, Guta Hedwig and Nami Yamamoto
on Wednesday; Janis Brenner on Aug. 12; seven emerging
choreographers on Aug. 19; Linda Austin and Sandra Botnen on Aug.
26; Victoria Marks and Dan Froot on Sept. 9, and Patricia
Hoffbauer, Paul Langland and Brendan McCall on Sept. 16.
Information: (212) 460-1208.
</P>
<P>
   JACOB'S PILLOW DANCE FESTIVAL presents Zaccho Dance Theater from
Aug. 25 to 29 at 7 p.m. Tickets are $15. The free Inside/Out
series, on Tuesdays and Thursdays at 6:30 p.m. and Fridays and
Saturdays at 7 p.m. at the outdoor theater, includes dance
performances by Aleta Hayes, Friday night; Steve Paxton and the
Improvisation Project, Saturday, Thursday and Aug. 8; Susan
Marshall and Company on Tuesday; the American Indian Dance Theater
on Wednesday; Ann Carlson on Aug. 11; Gotham Group Dance on Aug.
12; Allyson Green and Dancers on Aug. 14; Chuck Davis and Musicians
on Aug. 15; Urban Bush Women on Aug. 18; Reggie Wilson/Fist and
Heel Performance Group on Aug. 19, and Pat Hall and Pam Patrick on
Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Other free events include book signings by David Vaughan,
Saturday, and Robert Tracey on Aug. 22 in the Harriet Freed Tea
Garden at 12:30 p.m., and Pillow/Talk Picnics on Wednesdays at 5
p.m. on the Great Lawn by Susan Marshall and Ralph Lemon next week,
Joanna Haigood on Aug. 12 and Diane Ferlatte on Aug. 19. Jacob's
Pillow is at George Carter Road, off Route 20, Becket, Mass.
Information: (413) 243-0745.
</P>
<P>
   ``STEPPING OUT: A CENTURY OF DANCE IN NEW YORK CITY PARKS'' is a
free exhibition of photographs of dance performances, competitions
and workshops held in city parks, all from the New York City Parks
Photo Archive. The show may be seen through Sept. 10 at the Arsenal
Gallery, Fifth Avenue at 64th Street, Mondays through Fridays from
9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Information: (212) 360-8163.
</P>
</TEXT>
