<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-30 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKER STYLE: AN ELEGANCE BEYOND TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., N.Y., Maine, Mass., Ohio, Ky., N.H.)   (See also BC-MAINE-SHAKERS)  
 (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marybeth Keene, a partner in Wayne Pratt Antiques of
Woodbury, Conn., recently interviewed 60 antiques dealers so she
could compile a list of what's in and what's out of fashion among
collectors. She concluded that Shaker is currently out.
</P>
<P>
   That may surprise the Shaker Museum and Library of Old Chatham,
N.Y. The museum, a 50-acre site with 12 buildings and 15,000
objects, receives 18,000 visitors a year. Saturday its 43rd annual
Antiques Festival opens (the $6 museum admission gets you into the
show), and several dealers there will be selling Shaker antiques.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the museum asked John H. Kirk, author of ``The
Shaker World: Art, Life, Belief'' (Abrams, 1997), to be the curator
for a large exhibition, ``The Shaker World,'' which is on view
through Nov. 1. The show includes what the museum is calling 60
masterpieces of Shaker furniture, textiles (including costumes,
shoes and crazy quilts), tools, printed journals and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Shaker's ``out'' status will probably also come as a surprise to
Shaker collectors, who include Oprah Winfrey, Bill Cosby, Adelaide
de Menil, Leo Castelli, Ellsworth Kelly and David Byrne of the
Talking Heads.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Shaker furniture was never really in, so perhaps Ms.
Keene is right. The Shaker world has always been its own world,
ever since the sect's origins in England in the mid-18th century.
</P>
<P>
   A member who later became a charismatic leader, Ann Lee, was
jailed, and when she got out, she and her followers immigrated to
America in 1774 and settled in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   In time, 19 Shaker communities were established, in New York
State, Maine, Massachusetts, Connecticut, Ohio and Kentucky. They
all produced furniture, but never that much, as there were never
more than 6,000 adherents.
</P>
<P>
   They did, however, produce other things to sell to the outside
world. There are still six Shakers living in a Maine community,
Sabbathday Lake, but they are the last ones.
</P>
<P>
   Shaker furniture was designed to be strictly functional, but of
course it is much more. Its spare lines give it a timeless
elegance. The craftsmanship is superb, and the materials are fine.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the Shaker style is derivative; others consider it a
distinctly American style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shakers didn't create new forms,'' said Richard Russo, a
dealer in East Chatham, N.Y. ``They took vernacular styles and
refined them to the bare minimum. And they kept doing it for a
hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no extra turnings, no enhanced carvings, nothing
extraneous. They took the essence of a chair, for example, and
reduced it to its `chairness.' It was meant to do the job and be
esthetically pleasing, simple but elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Wilkins, a Shaker dealer in Austerlitz, N.Y., for 25
years, disagreed. ``Shaker is a truly indigenous American furniture
form,'' he said. ``It's the first American style.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, who runs his shop with a partner, Suzanne Courcier,
recalled an incident at his booth at the Winter Antiques Show in
Manhattan a few years ago. ``We had a desk on display that was
strongly related to a Federal tambour desk,'' he said. ``It was
superbly organized and wonderfully constructed.''
</P>
<P>
   The antiques dealer Albert Sack, who sells top-of-the-line
American Queen Anne and Chippendale but dismisses Shaker antiques,
``strolled by and stopped dead in his tracks,'' Wilkins continued.
``He looked at the desk and saw something great in it. He turned to
me and asked, `Is that Shaker?' When I responded, `Yes,' he
quipped, `They must have excommunicated that guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins added: ``The Shakers were fond of believing that they
were not style-conscious; what they meant is not fashion-conscious.
Fashion comes from Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamel, a Shaker dealer for 33 years in Chichester, N.H.,
doesn't come down on either side. ``The Shakers probably did
develop a truly indigenous American style, but remember, a lot of
the furniture makers did not grow up as Shakers,'' he said. ``They
adapted what they knew.''
</P>
<P>
   What's clear is that Shaker furniture has wide appeal. ``It
appeals to everybody from schoolteachers to doctors and lawyers,''
Hamel said. ``Celebrities are the exception to the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, the curator of the museum's summer show, said the Shaker
style seemed to have appealed to the Minimalist sculptor Donald
Judd as much as to traditional collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins, discussing collecting, said: ``Unlike the go-go era of
the 1980s, we don't have theatrics in the Shaker market. What
typifies it is the real sincere, dedicated collector. We discourage
people from buying Shaker from an investment point of view. It's
not a liquid investment, though new people are coming in all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Vandall, who owns American Decorative Arts in Canaan,
N.H., and is participating in the fair this weekend, is also a
clinical psychologist who has been collecting Shaker furniture
since he was 12. Its appeal is ``the simplicity and ability to go
with any piece of furniture in any style,'' he said. ``It works in
a dining room with Chippendale or Queen Anne. It's a movable feast
wherever you put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willis Henry, the owner of Willis Henry Auctions of Marshfield,
Mass., is the man who sold Oprah Winfrey $494,000 worth of Shaker
furniture in one day in 1991. People find Shaker appealing because
they can see ``the thought and spirit behind it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a certain quality, like anything that is not made for
money,'' Henry said. ``Most of it was made by the Shakers for their
community, and they cared about each other a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Ingersoll, a skilled cabinetmaker in West Cornwall, Conn.,
has a workshop with 12 people. He has been making precise
reproductions of Shaker beds, chairs, desks and tables for 20
years, using cherry, tiger maple, birch and butternut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected demand for Shaker pieces, new and old, to fade
after the 1980s, but it hasn't,'' he said. ``Now Europeans and
Japanese are going gaga over it. I'm three months behind on my
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaker furniture, Ingersoll added, was made by people who were
instructed to be humble. ``I have a feeling that people who buy
Shaker also have a level of humility,'' he said. ``My customers are
successful, but success hasn't gone to their heads. Otherwise,
they'd want gold leaf on everything. They like the furniture as
much for its lack of pretentiousness as for its fine
craftsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal McKusick, a jazz saxophonist who has been making Shaker
reproductions in Sag Harbor, N.Y., for 20 years, summed it up this
way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaker is organic and graceful. It's beautiful because it's
peaceful. It doesn't need curlicues. The mood is simple. The
joinery is honest, and the pieces are reliable. The Shakers did not
cut steps to save time. They worked like musicians in a band; all
the parts were integrated into the whole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
