<SLUG> BC-BOOGIE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FULL TILT BOOGIE': BEHIND (SOME OF) THE SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The documentary ``Full Tilt Boogie'' may sound like a boon to
anyone with unanswered questions about the making of the
action-sleaze-and-vampire escapade ``From Dusk Till Dawn,'' like
how Salma Hayek did all those erotic dance scenes with the big
snake.
</P>
<P>
   But forget that: Ms. Hayek isn't even here. Instead, this film
is mostly about watching stir-crazy actors and crew members doing
lots of nothing in 120-degree heat. Statements like ``my goal in
the industry is to make a lot of money'' accompany the news that
some members of the group prefer their cookies fat-free.
</P>
<P>
   Horsing around is the main event here, as Juliette Lewis is
heard singing in a karaoke bar after hours, George Clooney
practices the Danny Thomas spitting double-take and Quentin
Tarantino complains about a shortage of beer kegs.
</P>
<P>
   The neophyte director is Sarah Kelly, who was a production
assistant on ``Killing Zoe'' and counts Tarantino as one of her
mentors. Ms. Kelly dutifully watches everyone work without having
anything special to ask her interviewees (though a few, like the
actor Michael Parks, are unexpectedly eloquent anyway). Her film is
a modest, anecdotal look at filmmaking stretched out far beyond its
interest value to feature length.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly fares better at capturing the footloose energy of
young crew members than at finding anything interesting in, say,
the first delivery of lumber to the film's principal outdoor set.
</P>
<P>
   Topics of group interest include the jokey use of ghastly
monster effects in ``From Dusk Till Dawn,'' the question of which
male crew member looks best from the rear and, somewhat jarringly,
the possibility of health benefits for these workers.
</P>
<P>
   While discussing on-the-set romances, what it's like to make
Tarantino's coffee for him and other ephemera, the documentary
touches on a serious dispute between the nonunion film crew and
labor organizers, which has threatened to interfere with the
production. Crew members who began the project without benefits
wind up receiving them as a byproduct of this standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full Tilt Boogie'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes frequent profanity,
grotesque props and makeup, simulated violence and brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FULL TILT BOOGIE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sarah Kelly; director of photography, Chris Gallo;
edited by Lauren Zuckerman; music by Dominic Kelly and Cary Berger;
produced by Rana Joy Glickman; released by Dimension Films. Running
time: 111 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Robert Rodriguez (director), Lawrence Bender and Paul
Hellerman (producers), George Clooney, Juliette Lewis and Quentin
Tarantino (cast).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
