<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0811 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-30 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Predictably, Congress is rushing to reinforce its
own security after the killing of two police guards in a terrifying
shootout inside the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Our elected worthies, shaken by their proximity to senseless
murder, are preparing to put up new barriers to protect the
building and themselves against any future such violence.
</P>
<P>
   This is natural and right. The seat of government in a powerful
nation must not be needlessly vulnerable to random assault.
</P>
<P>
   Although they may nail a few doors shut, the lawmakers insist
that they do not really want to interfere with voters' freedom to
dawdle under the Capitol dome and watch democracy in action. That,
of course, would be a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But they are increasing the number of police on Capitol Hill,
tightening access and studying new methods of controlling traffic.
And officials of both parties were suddenly enamored of an
elaborate plan for a single new entrance area a block away from the
Capitol that all visitors would be initially herded into.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are calling it a ``visitors center'' with educational
facilities, but it is really a holding pen where cops can keep an
eye on folks before granting them entry. It will inevitably be
inconvenient and time-consuming for tourists. And it will never
stop a determined nutcase, who will merely try some other way to
reach his or her target.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another awkwardness here. The new entrance idea
demonstrates that the old double standard is alive and well.
Shamefully, the lawmakers feel no comparable compunction to see
that the president of the United States, the head of the executive
branch, is similarly protected from terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1995 truck-bombing of the Oklahoma City federal
building that killed 168 people, the Secret Service ordered two
blocks of Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the White House closed in
order to keep potentially dangerous vehicles at a distance. For
decades there has been an iron fence around the property, and
concrete barriers were added along the curb years ago.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secret Service Director Eljay Bowron testified that if the
avenue is reopened, ``at some point they (terrorists) will destroy
the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress, however, cavalierly declared the president in no
danger and the newly created pedestrian mall ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers whined about inconvenience to tourists and traffic
jams resulting from closing part of a major city artery. They
scoffed at the possibility of an assault on the White House, even
though a plane had crashed onto the White House lawn in 1994, a
gunman had gone berserk inches from the mansion gate later that
year and President Clinton had frequently received death threats.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that a timid president was being unnecessarily
coddled. During the 1996 presidential campaign, Clinton's GOP
rival, Sen. Bob Dole, even demanded that Pennsylvania Avenue be
reopened after the bombing in an Atlanta park during the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   GOP congressional leaders pushed through a measure to reopen the
avenue but were stymied by a presidential veto. Instead, they have
repeatedly forbidden the National Park Service to spend funds to
transform the avenue into a graceful pedestrian park with walkways
and greenery. Thus, Congress has guaranteed that the White House
remains framed by an ugly, useless strip of asphalt _ petty
politics at its worst.
</P>
<P>
   There is not a penny for beautifying the avenue in the 1999
appropriations bill passed by the House last week. The Senate,
however, still has a chance to act responsibly. When it votes on
the bill, it could approve funds both for a fancy new congressional
entrance and the beautification of Pennsylvania Avenue. This is not
likely, but it would be fair-minded.
</P>
<P>
   The judiciary branch would like more security as well, although
no violence has been reported there. The Supreme Court has asked
Congress for seed money to develop a design for a wall or some
other major security structure around its building, which is
located across a street from the Capitol. There is little
congressional enthusiasm for this project either.
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference a location makes. Congress is going to
give Congress the attention it denies the other branches.
</P>
<P>
   Our lawmakers have always been careful to avoid the appearance
of a hostile fortress. Proposals for a fence around the grounds
have been rejected. But after a bomb exploded in an alcove in 1983,
concrete roadway barriers were erected, vehicular traffic
restricted, delivery trucks searched, metal detectors installed at
all doors, the Capitol Police force expanded and staff and
reporters required to wear badges.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials proposed a visitors center nearly a decade
ago but arguments about its projected cost stalled the plan. House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, then in the GOP minority, denounced it as an
expensive congressional perk.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to raise public funds for it produced only $23 million,
about a fifth of its estimated cost. Newly motivated, congressional
leaders of both parties are now talking about financing that might
come half from taxpayers and half from the private sector. It's not
a done deal, but for want of some better ideas it is moving that
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1714EDT &QL; 
