<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASUAL-DAY01-COX     07-30 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUAL-DAY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banking on a relaxed look
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If employees at Comerica Bank in Austin look
unlike those at any other bank, you're not imagining things.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the dark _ some people say somber _ pinstripe suits
that can be seen soaking up perspiration as bankers stroll down
Congress Avenue at lunch hour in triple-digit heat. Gone are the
skirts and heels, the ties and the stiff-starched, long-sleeve,
white shirts.
</P>
<P>
   For Detroit-based Comerica's 60 Austin-area employees, it's
casual dress day every day _ apparently a first for a big bank. A
golf shirt or short-sleeve collared shirt or blouse and a pair of
nice slacks will do for work.
</P>
<P>
   Austin was chosen in June for a pilot program that will keep
employees at Comerica's five bank offices in light-hearted attire
at least until Labor Day. Officials at the Austin operation _ the
first Comerica affiliate to dress down _ will decide after Labor
Day whether to continue with the casual duds permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what started it (was) our president in Dallas was
listening to our recommendation to change with the culture down
here,'' said Tim Gillespie, manager of the Austin branch offices.
``Austin is typically a little more laid back than the Dallas
business environment,'' he said. ``It's also been pretty hot this
summer, and it's been a morale booster for employees to come in
casually dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to Austin's free-spirit reputation, many local companies
have gone casual _ a few beyond just on Fridays. The Ernst &AMP; Young
accounting firm, for instance, has allowed its 100 employees to
dress casually every day for the past three years. At Ernst &AMP;
Young, men wear either a dress shirt or a golf shirt _ no jeans or
collarless shirts _ and women can exchange suits for slacks and
blouses.
</P>
<P>
   At Dell Computer Corp., 12,000 employees in the Austin area are
free to dress ``to do your job'' on every day of the week, said
spokeswoman Michele Glaze.That includes blue jeans and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, at the University of Texas, 120 employees of the
Administrative Computing Services Department also went casual
full-time last year. It was easy because ``there never has been a
dress code in the academic community,'' said Randy Ebeling,
department director. Ditto for most of the engineers working for
high-tech companies in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Even the bank industry's statewide trade organization in Austin,
the Texas Bankers Association, has casual summers for its
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But most big banks, being banks, have been reluctant to tone
down their threads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a bank per se in Austin,'' that's bucking the
usual dress code, said John Heasley, counsel for the bankers
association. ``Bankers as a rule are pretty conservative folks.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of small community banks around the state do have
casual summers. Some, such as State Bank of Jewett in East Texas,
have given the OK to tennis shoes and blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the bankers association and others, Comerica is
the first big bank in Austin to dress down.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Comerica's policy has its limits. No tennis shoes,
sandals, jeans or T-shirts are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, causal dress is not only OK, it's promoted. As
a business bank, Comerica sells products to middle market and
small-business customers, most of whom dress in professional casual
attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have had some favorable responses from our customers
with comments like, `It's nice to know my banker can come out and
get down to my level in a relaxed atmosphere rather than showing up
in a stiff shirt and a jacket,''' Gillespie said. ``Ninety percent
of the people we are calling on are dressed that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, the banking culture is changing, whether other
Austin banks know it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the guy sitting in the office conservatively waiting
for the business to walk in,'' Gillespie said. ``You('ve) got to go
out and get the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
