u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM31-COX     07-30 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunbeam to keep open plant Dunlap wanted closed
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ In its first public reversal of
cost-cutting plans put in place by fired Chairman Al Dunlap,
Sunbeam Corp. said it will keep open an Ohio Mr. Coffee plant
Dunlap sought to close.
</P>
<P>
   The Delray Beach-based appliance maker said the plant, which was
slated to close Sept. 4, will operate at least until Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new Sunbeam management is giving us time to . . . see if
we can develop a plan to demonstrate that our plant can be
cost-competitive,'' said Daniel Carlson, vice president of
operations for Mr. Coffee maker Signature Brands USA, which Sunbeam
bought this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenwillow, Ohio, plant's largely unionized work force of
about 315 protested the closure and appealed for help this week to
legislators and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who was visiting
the area.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, where workers assemble Mr. Coffee machines, was
among eight plants Dunlap planned to close in the consolidation of
Signature Brands, First Alert and Coleman Co. into Sunbeam.
</P>
<P>
   The board fired Dunlap on June 13, and successor Jerry Levin
said he probably would pull back from Dunlap's plan to centralize
all management at the company's headquarters and would possibly add
workers companywide.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dunlap had no comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam spokeswoman Maureen Bailey said Levin has been touring
plants and meeting with Sunbeam employees as part of an ongoing
review of Sunbeam's businesses. He has not announced plans for the
company, which is struggling to sort out bloated inventories as the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the company itself review
the accuracy of its 1997 results.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect to hear from Levin on the condition of the
troubled company some time after Sunbeam's second-quarter financial
results are released in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to change things in order to get some
positive momentum generated,'' said William Steele, an analyst with
Buckingham Research Group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
