<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORK _AUSTIN _ A group of more than 140 Austin area
physicians has formed a network to contract for the managed care of
patients in hospitals of St. David's Healthcare Partnership. The
QualityCare Network will give the physicians more leverage in
dealing with health maintenance organizations. The HMOs, often
accused of managing health care costs by limiting care, are
delegating more authority to Austin area primary care and
soecialist doctors who are banding together into so-called
independent physician associations. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCHISEFEES _AUSTIN _ Telephone companies press state
regulators for a common franchise fee. As the number of telephone
companies serving communities rises, they don't to negotiate fees
with each municipality. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   REYNOLDS _ DAYTON, Ohio _Dayton-based Reynolds &AMP; Reynolds lands
a $200 million, five-year services contract with Kaiser Permanente,
the largest not-for-profit health maintenance organization in the
U.S. Perhaps this good news will boost Reynolds' stock price, which
has stubbornly refused to climb despite good news from the company.
(Drummond, Dayton Daily News) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CASUAL-DAY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ If employees at Comerica Bank in
Austin look unlike those at any other bank, you're not imagining
things. For Detroit-based Comerica's 60 Austin-area employees, it's
casual dress day every day _ apparently a first for a big bank.
(Golz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ In its first public reversal of
cost-cutting plans put in place by fired Chairman Al Dunlap,
Sunbeam Corp. said it will keep open an Ohio Mr. Coffee plant
Dunlap sought to close. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
