<SLUG> BC-CARTER-BENGALS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Ki-Jana Carter, it's do-or-die time
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Ky. _ Look into Ki-Jana Carter's eyes. Listen to him
speak and watch him run.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you see: Drive, focus, a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 overall pick of the 1995 NFL Draft _ beaten out by
Corey Dillon as the Bengals starting tailback _ knows what's at
stake this year. Either he steps into the spotlight or fades into
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a new attitude on the team this year and
I'm starting with myself,'' Carter said. ``I've had a couple years
that weren't really productive. I didn't do too much. That's not
the kind of person I am. I've got too much pride in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Penn State All-American, whose rookie year was ruined
by torn left knee ligaments in a preseason game at Detroit, showed
great promise in '97 with a 79-yard touchdown run at Denver on
Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   His 104-yard effort that day snapped a Bengals' streak of 67
games without a 100-yard rusher. Afterward, he was diagnosed with a
torn rotator cuff in his left shoulder, but decided to rehabilitate
the injury without surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Carter started through Week 10, but couldn't hold off Dillon,
whose 1,129-yard season was the third-best in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really gives me a sense of urgency is how _ ever since I
hurt my shoulder _ I've been kind of on the back burner,'' he said.
``Corey stepped up. Now I have something to prove. I just don't
want to get forgotten about in this offense. I want to get out
there because I know I can play with a lot of backs in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten? No way. Carter will provide fresh legs when Dillon
needs a break. The two will share the backfield when the Bengals go
to their ``Jet'' package. And with 15 rushing TDs in 32 career
games, Carter should remain the goal-line specialist.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be enough to satisfy his appetite for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're there (in the spotlight) and you get out of it,
you want to get back into it,'' Carter said. ``That's where I am
right now, especially around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to gain the confidence back of the people in
Cincinnati, my teammates, coach (Bruce) Coslet, my running backs
coach (Jim Anderson) and people throughout the nation that I'm a
good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, entering the fourth year of a seven-year, $19.125
million contract, is running hard and fast at training camp in an
attempt to push Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just don't give Ki-Jana credit because to whom
a lot is given, a lot is expected,'' Anderson said. ``Some
unfortunate things have happened to him, but he's come back and
he's working hard. He knows that for him to achieve, he has to get
himself ready, because any snap, he can be called on and he must
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the sad stories in football, what happened at the
beginning of his career,'' said Leigh Steinberg, Carter's agent.
``But Ki-Jana has an incredible competitive desire. He's ready to
take off. He will have an outstanding year and will press (Dillon)
very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter won't reveal his goals, saying only that they have to do
with team and personal success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was being a little knucklehead, taking everything
for granted early in my career,'' he said. ``But I've got too many
things ahead of me that I want to see and I'm too stubborn to let
'em go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people talk bad about me. But (injuries) have
hampered me so far. Now I've got no excuses . . . just go out and
do the best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I'm done with my career, I'm going to have a good
one. It's my fourth year. I know it's getting late. But I'll get
there. I know I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
