</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Johnson's way is a duping incident
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Jimmy Johnson, for all his swagger, knows he
cannot get where he wants alone. He is in a joint venture, with his
players, with the media, all of whom he counts on to be dopes.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the media. Johnson was one of us for two years. He
knows he can use us to motivate players, and he knows what we want.
A story. A story handed to us. Television reporters, who are less
often present, don't even want that much. They want a quote. A
bite. A gimme.
</P>
<P>
   So he gives, even on those days he doesn't call in spin to a
radio show. He bounces off the field, and often before he even
steps upon his little orange box to beam himself into your little
black box, he gives us a name.
</P>
<P>
   A name he either praises or denigrates. No in-between. A name to
which he might have done the opposite a day earlier. The rookie
John Avery slips from Barry Sanders to Barry Manilow, just like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't do my job,'' said a bewildered Avery, who
has a sore hamstring. ``So the praise is cut off right there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm aware of (how it affects players),'' Johnson said.
``But number one, I'm honest. So if you ask me a question, I'm
going to be honest. I may not tell you the full story, but I'll be
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Johnson volunteers names before the questions start, and one
wonders if he doesn't choose them before practice. He cannot have
watched 80 guys at once. He cannot know for sure until he watches
tape.
</P>
<P>
   He's not God.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's just a psychology major who relies on his young
players to think he is God. To not know any better. To read the
newspaper, and watch television, and get his message, if it hasn't
already come to them in waves of cameras and notebooks as soon as
he is done.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dixon was hit by the waves this week. No warning. A
Canadian Football League veteran, suddenly he is being called by
Johnson ``as good a performer as I've seen at (left guard) since
I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon is a performer who admits that ``my confidence is
fragile.'' That he still expects ``to be playing left tackle for
the Montreal Alouettes next week.'' That he has ``had too many
disappointments in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon could use a class with Stuart Smalley, an Al Franken
character on Saturday Night Live. ``I'm good enough, I'm smart
enough, and doggone it, people like me,'' Smalley said into a
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Johnson is the mirror, and Dixon is in the coach's
golden glow. ``This has been a dream, the last couple of days,''
Dixon said. ``It's the biggest thing that has happened to me in the
last four, five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all players enjoy the praise so. When Johnson declared last
July that Derrick Rodgers was having a better camp than Zach Thomas
had as a rookie, Rodgers was uncomfortable. So was Brad Jackson,
when Johnson commended him last month.
</P>
<P>
   That beats the alternative, though. Jeff Buckey has been lauded,
a seventh-rounder made good. Now Johnson dishes out a daily public
insult for the reserved Buckey to swallow, as if it will help him
put on weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about what's said in the media,'' Buckey said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not easy. Jason Taylor talks about taking the positive in
stride and taking heed if Johnson ``comes off and says you're a big
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   But did Taylor, as a 1997 rookie, really know Johnson was
playing mind games? He laughs. ``We're cool now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Most veterans are. Brock Marion played for Johnson as a rookie
in Dallas. He doesn't sweat every word in Miami. Neither does
Robert Jones, another former Cowboy. ``Every time you grab Jimmy,''
Jones said, ``I don't know what he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do we sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Brent Smith, then Smith gets hurt. He likes Avery, then
Avery gets hurt. Wednesday, he liked Bernie Parmalee again. Bernie
Parmalee. How much has he changed since Monday? Since 1996?
</P>
<P>
   How different is Dixon's life than it was Monday? Quite. But he
knows one missed block changes everything again. The cameras leave.
</P>
<P>
   When they left Wednesday, Dixon was smiling. James Brown, the
right tackle, glanced over:
</P>
<P>
   ``What did Jimmy say?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
