<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLINS-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins: Unsigned Ambres holds football option
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The 18-year-old kid who took batting practice with the
Marlins at the Astrodome on Wednesday could be a big part of the
Marlins' future.
</P>
<P>
   He could also be playing quarterback this fall at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Ambres, the Marlins' first-round pick in the 1998 draft, is
still holding out for more money. And, since he has a scholarship
offer from A&AMP;M, he could turn Florida down completely, go to
college and start football practice on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all on them,'' Ambres, a center fielder, said. ``You
still have A&AMP;M in the picture, so if it's not done by Tuesday, I'll
head up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins don't want that, but they're not too keen on meeting
Ambres's asking price, either. He's asking for about $1.8 million,
and the Marlins aren't sure right now if they can make up the
difference by Ambres's self-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd like to get on with his life, it makes sense,'' said
Marlins scouting director Orrin Freeman, who flew to Houston on
Wednesday to meet with Ambres, his parents and his agent. ``We're
hoping to get it done, but we're both going to have to
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman knows Ambres can use football as a bargaining chip _ he
knew it when he drafted him. But the way the Marlins figure it, the
worst that happens is they don't sign Ambres, and they get a
compensatory ``sandwich'' pick between the first and second rounds
of next year's draft. That pick won't be much lower than 27 anyway,
so they won't be losing much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, eventually, things will change,'' said Ambres.
``I've got so many options a lot of guys don't have, and a lot of
people in this state would like to see me go play football. But my
love is baseball, and what better thing is there to do than play
the game you love?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Just resting: Right fielder Mark Kotsay has been out of the
lineup for three days now, and Marlins manager Jim Leyland said
it's because he's worried Kotsay is losing too much weight and
weakening. Kotsay might play this afternoon, but Leyland said
Tuesday he'd likely hold him out of all four games in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Kotsay's batting average has dropped 18 points since the start
of July, to .273 entering Wednesday's game, and Leyland thought
maybe playing everyday in the heat of South Florida and on the
astroturf in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia was wearing on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll take something out of you, sure,'' Kotsay said. ``But
I'm not going to come out and say I'm tired or I'm worn out. I feel
all right to play, and I'll go in when he puts me in. Right now, it
makes sense to have a guy like (Ryan) Jackson in there instead of
me, if I'm not helping the team.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Trade winds: The Boston Red Sox are definitely interested in
Todd Zeile, and have what the Marlins want _ a solid third-base
prospect at a AAA ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   If Boston wants Zeile to bolster their right-handed hitting,
settle their infield situation by moving John Valentin back to
second base and possibly DH or catch in case of emergency, the
Marlins are sure to ask for Cole Liniak, the AAA Pawtucket third
baseman who, though 92 games this season, was hitting .272 with 27
doubles, 14 home runs and 51 RBI. He could step in immediately or
at least soon, because if the Marlins move Zeile, they don't have a
top prospect in their system who could play third at the big-league
level.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston is also talking to Toronto about Mike Stanley, and to
Cincinnati about Reggie Sanders and possibly Bret Boone, so they
could fill their needs elsewhere. The trade deadline is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
