NYT-07-30-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-SHAKERS-2TAKES-     07-30 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-SHAKERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKER SIMPLICITY AND A BAY VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN)  
 (bl)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The peninsula encompassing the downtown area of Portland, Maine,
stretches closely along the mainland like a short left thumb, its
outer margins bounded by the waters of Casco Bay. It is a
pleasantly compact place, with neighborhoods that invite strolling
and a harbor full of islands reached by a ferry ride that can feel
like a vacation in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to visit such a manageable maritime city and do a
little exploring along the coast nearby lured my wife, Margaret,
and me on a recent weekend. But we also went out of curiosity about
a living link to an unusual chapter in American religious history.
For more than two centuries, a Shaker community has made its home
on a farmstead less than an hour's drive away from Portland, and
the six believers living there now are the last remnant of this
sect in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the word Shaker calls to mind the skilled makers of
decorative craft items like ladder-back chairs and elegant wooden
boxes. For others, the name also conjures up an idealized image of
a peaceful, agrarian people, a picture aided by the lyrics of a
well-known Shaker hymn, `` 'Tis a gift to be simple. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Common though such ideas are, they slight the rich and varied
history of the Shakers themselves, a once controversial Christian
sect distinguished by its commitment to celibacy, its practice of
holding all goods in common, its emphasis on personal confession
and on equality between men and women, and its determination to
remain separate from mainstream society, which Shakers call ``the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize the Christ Spirit, the expression of Deity, first
manifested in Jesus of Nazareth,'' declares a tiny pamphlet of the
sect's basic beliefs. ``We also regard Ann Lee as the first to
receive in this latter day the interior realization that the same
Divine Spirit which was in Jesus might dwell within the
consciousness of any man, woman or child.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, born in England in 1736, became prominent among a group
there called the Shaking Quakers, named for their ecstatic behavior
in worship services. The group emerged amid the religious revivals
that occurred on both sides of the Atlantic in the mid-18th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Only after immigrating to America with a few fellow believers in
1774, and settling near Albany, N.Y., did Mother Ann Lee, as she
was called, achieve the status of a visionary leader. She laid the
basis for what became the United Society of Believers in Christ's
Second Appearing, the Shakers' formal name, through a series of
preaching tours that culminated in 1783, the year before her death.
</P>
<P>
   Through conversions, the society grew remarkably, to 6,000
people in the 1830s and '40s. They were gathered in 19 rural
communities from Maine to Kentucky. But after the Civil War, their
numbers began a steep decline.
</P>
<P>
   Getting from New York to the last living Shaker settlement, the
Sabbathday Lake Shaker Village, which lies within the town of New
Gloucester, is not difficult. It takes about an hour to fly into
Portland's airport, a few minutes from the city center. We arrived
late one Friday evening, picked up a rental car and drove to the
residential West End, where we checked into the Danforth, a
bed-and-breakfast inn in a three-story brick house built for a
merchant 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   We planned to go to Sabbathday Lake the next morning. The Shaker
community lives there year round, but the grounds are open to
visitors only between Memorial Day and Columbus Day.
</P>
<P>
   After a few miles of uninteresting countryside on Route 26, a
busy two-lane stretch of asphalt that links the coast with Canada,
a roadside sign appears, announcing the Sabbathday Lake Shaker
community. The site includes more than a dozen white-painted wooden
buildings clustered around an imposing brick house, the community's
home, called the Dwelling House.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who arrives expecting the likes of Plimouth Plantation or
Colonial Williamsburg, with people in antique costumes going about
picturesque chores, risks great disappointment. During our visit,
the place was dead quiet; the only visible activity was the labors
of a dog named Habukkuk, herding sheep in a pasture. Our guide, a
non-Shaker, said the community's living quarters were
(appropriately) off limits.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview later, Leonard Brooks, director of the
Shaker Museum and Shaker Library at Sabbathday Lake, said it would
be unusual for visitors to have any contact with community members.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're at work in the workshops and the Dwelling House,'' he
said. ``They meet for prayer three times a day. So there's not a
lot of time to meet the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbathday Lake's attraction is more subtle, centering on the
value of entering a place where a highly distinctive American group
continues to live out its history. To enhance a visit, I'd
recommend a little reading. Some books are available in the small
and tasteful museum shop inside a building that houses displays
about life in the community as it once was. You have to stop there
anyway for a $5 tour ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shaker Experience in America'' (Yale, 1992), by Stephen J.
Stein, is an excellent, thorough history that describes the
successes and failures, as well as leading personalities, of the
sect's two centuries. It warns, too, against the temptation to
glamorize the Shakers. ``The United Society has an unusual, even
remarkable, record of achievements,'' Stein writes. ``It does not
need to be sentimentalized or romanticized.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
