<HEADER>
A0859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-SHAKERS-2NDTAKE     07-30 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-SHAKERS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: or romanticized.''   &HT;    There were no other visitors when we arrived, so we wound up
with a private tour. Our guide, a knowledgeable local woman, said
the Sabbathday Lake property encompassed 1,900 acres, on which the
Shakers raise culinary herbs for sale. They can be purchased in the
museum shop or the Shaker store or by mail order.
 &HT;    The community now consists of four women and two men, ranging in
age from 30-something to 80-something. All live and dine in the
48-room Dwelling House, which dates to 1883. At mealtimes they are
segregated by sex.
 &HT;    When we visited in June, seven people were living there. But in
a poignant illustration of Shaker demographic trends, the community
has since decreased by one, as a third ``brother'' left Sabbathday
Lake.
 &HT;    Across from the Dwelling House sits the community's most
interesting structure, the Meetinghouse, first used on April 19,
1794. It is a satisfyingly austere place of white walls and
blue-painted ceiling beams, illuminated by the light from clear
glass windows. Worshipers sit on facing benches, the men and the
women separately.
 &HT;    A utilitarian building, the Meetinghouse contains an upper floor
arranged to show Shaker living and working space. Examples of the
famous chairs can be seen, along with other evidence of Shaker
industriousness, like a workbench for making flat brooms for sale.
 &HT;    The believers, the guide said, have a history as an
entrepreneurial people whose products and innovations, like the
circular saw, the clothespin and the flat broom, provided financial
support to the communities.
 &HT;    Our tour also took in the Ministry's Shop next door, set up to
show how the community's governing elders and eldresses lived and
worked. It also shows the evolution in Shaker dress and home styles
during the later 19th century, as business dealings brought
believers closer to outside society. The walls are adorned with
pictures, while bedsheets bear monograms, a sign of individualism
emerging among a communal people.
 &HT;    As Stein makes clear in his book, the Shakers never shunned
modern technology, using the railroads to ship their products to
market and later buying cars. But their insistence on redefining
the idea of the family by requiring celibacy and communal living
made them distinct, and in the 19th century subject to rumors,
accusations and even physical attack by neighbors.
 &HT;    If the Shaker commitment to celibacy seems merely peculiar,
rather than the razor-sharp dividing line from a sinful world,
consider what James Whittaker, a Shaker leader, wrote to relatives
in 1785: ``I hate your fleshly lives, and your fleshly generation,
and increasing, as I hate the smoke of the bottomless pit.''
 &HT;    These days, the sort of vehemence with which the earliest
Shakers expressed their commitment to religious separatism belongs
to the distant past. When we left Sabbathday Lake, it was with
thoughts of the creativity and durability of this community.
 &HT;    We returned to Portland by way of Yarmouth, a coastal town where
we paused for lunch at the Royal River Cannery. A window near our
table looked out on half a dozen small sailboats; on one, a man
worked away, swabbing his deck.
 &HT;    The scene made us want to get closer to the water, a desire
Portland can fulfill, with a ride on a Casco Bay Lines ferry to one
of the harbor islands.
 &HT;    At the terminal, we asked a man behind the counter to recommend
a see-the-basics cruise. He sold us round-trip tickets to Peaks
Island, a 20-minute ride that gave us time to gaze on distant
wooded shores and enjoy the play of sunlight and cloud shadow on
the bay.
 &HT;    Rather than disembark with the other passengers, we stayed
aboard for the return. We met a couple who had gone over earlier
and walked clear around the residential island, a brisk 90-minute
journey, they said.
 &HT;    We saved our walking for downtown Portland and its Old Port
area, a place of shops and restaurants behind the waterfront. At
our request, the Danforth made reservations for us both nights we
were in town, sending us the first evening to Perfetto, a place of
hardwood floors, brick walls and a menu that runs from filet mignon
to a good haddock with risotto.
 &HT;    The restaurant won our gratitude for taking us in with no fuss,
even though we arrived several minutes past the time when it
normally stops seating diners. We returned to the area the next
night, to Street &AMP; Company, a seafood restaurant on cobblestoned
Wharf Street.
 &HT;    One caveat worth mentioning about this area, however, is that as
the evening progresses, a just-postcollegiate crowd rolls in, bound
for local bars. The resulting hilarity, it seems, can reach rather
high decibels.
 &HT;    Although the Old Port reverts to calm in the daylight, we
decided to put the city behind us on Sunday, driving along the
coast below Brunswick. A guidebook recommended Route 123, which
runs down a finger of land in Casco Bay. We found country houses,
white-steepled churches and glimpses of the water.
 &HT;    It was a pretty enough landscape, on a road that allowed us to
stop at a tiny beach where we could stroll beside sun-sparkled
water. But the surroundings did not make the impression of
Sabbathday Lake.
 &HT;    Once the village was the most northerly outpost of a farflung
network of believers. Now it is a singular place in America's
religious landscape.
 &HT;    The first Shakers gathered there while Ann Lee was still alive.
That a community remains, in its third century, offers a fragile
testimony to the power of her vision.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MAKING THE VISIT
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is information about places mentioned in the article about
Portland, Me., and the Sabbathday Lake Shaker Village. There is a
Web site at www.shaker.lib.me.us for more information on the
Shakers.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   THE DANFORTH, 163 Danforth St., Portland, (207) 879-8755.
Weekend room rates based on double occupancy range from $165 for a
standard room to $225 for a two-room suite, all with Continental
breakfast buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   THE ROYAL RIVER CANNERY, Lower Falls Landing, Yarmouth, (207)
846-1226. Seafood. Open year round.
</P>
<P>
   PERFETTO, 28 Exchange St., Portland, (207) 828-0001.
Mediterranean cuisine. Open year round.
</P>
<P>
   STREET &AMP; COMPANY, 33 Wharf St., Portland, (207) 775-0887.
Seafood and pasta. Open year round.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   SABBATHDAY LAKE SHAKER VILLAGE, 707 Shaker Road, New Gloucester,
(207) 926-4597. The community is open for guided tours from
Memorial Day to Columbus Day, Mondays through Saturdays from 10
a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Admission is $5 for adults and $2 for children.
To get there, take Interstate 495 north from Portland, exit at
Gray, head north on Route 26 and look for signs.
</P>
<P>
   CASCO BAY LINES FERRY, terminal at 56 Commercial St., Portland,
(207) 774-7871. Operates ferries and cruise boats to the bay's
numerous islands. The Peaks Island ferry leaves hourly and costs
$5.25, round trip. Round-trip tickets to other islands _ including
Great Diamond, Long Island, Cliff and Great Chebeague _ range from
$8 to $13.75 for adults, with discounts for children and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   How to Get There
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR: From Manhattan, take Interstate 95 North, passing
through Connecticut, Rhode Island and Massachusetts. The distance
to Portland, Maine, is about 310 miles.
</P>
<P>
   BY PLANE: Continental Airlines operates five direct flights
daily from Newark International Airport to Portland. Round-trip
fares range from $135 for tickets purchased more than 21 days in
advance to $393 for tickets purchased within seven days of travel.
Information: (718) 565-1100.
</P>
<P>
   BY BUS: Greyhound buses to Portland leave from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal, Eighth Avenue and 42nd Street, Manhattan.
The trip takes six to eight hours, and the round-trip fare is $67
for adults and $33.50 for children 11 and under. Information: (800)
231-2222.
</P>
</TEXT>
