<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-30 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTHY BUT TRANSITORY ENTERPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Some enterprises, though worthy, have transitory lives
On Beaver Creek _ I once traveled down this valley on foot, canteen
empty and with a ferocious thirst.
</P>
<P>
   The topographic map gave no hint of a spring to water from. But
it did show a town ahead _ a place with the hopeful name of Tigris,
mother of civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   I stumbled out upon a road, ascended it around a bend and came
upon the place, only to find that Tigris had perished unremembered
years before.
</P>
<P>
   No drink was to be found there, but I made these notes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALS)The door of the John Allen Store, General Mdse., is
nailed shut and further guarded by wicked canes of blackberry that
have forced the rotting porch boards and grown up to make a thicket
on a stage.
</P>
<P>
   Just across is the livery stable, broken by a tree and dragged
down by wild grape. Garage &AMP; Welding _ dead too, fastened with a
rusted padlock. The tomato cannery, of galvanized sheeting, chimes
impassively under the blows of clenched fists.
</P>
<P>
   On the hill behind are the remains of a dwelling, home of the
master of Tigris overlooking his fief, consumed on a winter night
by some accident with the flue. A mansion it was, judging by the
size of the footings. Hugely the offending furnace looms,
embarrassed to have survived.(END ITALS)
</P>
<P>
   From Tigris, the road led on to the town of Ava, and beyond
there, a gravel lane descended into a different valley.
</P>
<P>
   I built my fire and spread my blanket that night in a grassy
little glade, beside a bluff where a rivulet of clear, sweet water
spouted from a pipe driven into a cleft in the rock face.
</P>
<P>
   The next day I continued on down that valley's brook to its
joining with larger Bryant Creek. And, rounding one of Bryant's
bends in the blue light of evening, was astonished to hear the
day's last prayer song, in Latin, spreading sweet and melancholy
through the forested solitude of Shingle Hollow.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd come upon was a community of Trappist monks _ 20-some
of them, supporting themselves by the manufacture of cement
building blocks and the making of jellies.
</P>
<P>
   More notes:
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALS)Theirs is the silent order, so they are generous
with everything but talk. They have forsaken the pleasures and
temptations of the world for the simplicity of bread and milk, hard
work and early rising.(END ITALS)
</P>
<P>
   All that was 35 years ago. On a recent day I passed through that
Ozark country again, this time by car.
</P>
<P>
   In Tigris, no sign of the livery stable could be found. John
Allen's establishment, like the man himself, also had disappeared
entirely. The name on the metal sheeting of the cannery's front has
faded, and the ruin of the mansion is lost among the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Trappists of Shingle Hollow have moved to new quarters on
the hill above. Nothing remains of the old monastery down by Bryant
Creek, or of the hard disciplines of that monastic order. For the
rules have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The monks speak freely now, their services no longer are sung in
Latin. There's even a female among them _ a woman of the town
brought in to help with office matters.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently the young find the contemplative vocation less
attractive than in previous times, for the community is in
inexorable decline. Every year the brothers are older and fewer _
now only 12 regular and two hermit monks, several of them ailing.
</P>
<P>
   Another day, in a different piece of country to the east, we
stopped on a ridge where there'd been a mill for making barrel
staves. Trees had reclaimed the denuded land, and except for the
concrete slab upon which it had stood, the mill itself was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Along that ridge there'd been rough cabins _ 30 or maybe more of
them _ for the timber workers and their families. But all that
could be found of those were a few stone footings and, close to
those, the stubborn perennials a woman's hand had transplanted
there from some other forgotten camp.
</P>
<P>
   In all these places, I was struck by how faint and fragile is
the print of some men's works upon the land. Yet the endeavors of
others _ even inauspiciously begun _ can have a durable life.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the difference between them?
</P>
<P>
   (Sunday: How enterprises last.) -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
