<SLUG> BC-ABORT-GIRLS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF 12-YEAR-OLD SEEKING ABORTION ISN'T AS RARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY L. THOMAS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The case of a pregnant 12-year-old Michigan girl
seeking an abortion in Wichita, Kan., isn't as rare as many might
think.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of young girls nationwide are getting abortions. Last
year, 48 Kansas girls ages 14 and under underwent the procedure, as
did 121 Missouri girls, in their respective states.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 12 months, we've probably done about ten
12-year-olds, and maybe another ten 13-year-olds,'' said Patty
Brous, president of Planned Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri.
``I think we've also had one 10-year-old in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the numbers are small in comparison to the total number
of abortions performed nationwide _ around 1.2 million _ those on
both sides of the issue say they are a major concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every abortion is a tragedy,'' said Dave Gittrich, executive
director of Kansans for Life, the state's largest anti-abortion
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is very, very troubling,'' said Susan Tew,
spokeswoman for the Alan Guttmacher Institute, an organization that
researches reproductive issues.
</P>
<P>
   The figures also highlight another disturbing issue: rape and
incest of young girls. Those who specialize in the treatment of
adolescents say that most pregnancies in girls 13 and under are the
result of rape and incest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very high percentage of the very young teens who did
not voluntarily have intercourse,'' said Paula J. Adams Hillard,
professor of obstetrics and gynecology and pediatrics in the
College of Medicine at the University of Cincinnati. ``We see it
all the time. That's something nobody likes to think about, but it
is really, really important to note.''
</P>
<P>
   Brous said she'd seen similar cases at Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our experience with the 12- and 13-year-olds, more often
than not the pregnancy is a result of coercion, usually by an older
male, often a family member or a close friend of the family,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really illustrates the crying need in this country for
comprehensive sexuality education that is age-appropriate, from
early childhood through high school and college.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has attracted national attention since a Michigan
judge on Friday cleared the way for the parents of a 12-year-old
girl to take her out of the state for a late-term abortion. The
girl, who allegedly was impregnated by her 17-year-old brother, is
about 28 weeks pregnant. A typical pregnancy lasts 40 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Wichita physician George Tiller, who operates Women's Health
Care Services, is one of a handful of doctors who performs
late-term abortions. Abortion is illegal in Michigan after the 24th
week unless the girl or woman's life is endangered. Kansas law
permits it under a few other circumstances, although the law is
currently being challenged by Tiller.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tiller nor his clinic administrator would comment on the
case Wednesday. Clinic officials have neither confirmed nor denied
that the girl is getting an abortion there.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Bowman, spokeswoman for the Women's Freedom Project and
former spokeswoman for Tiller, said she was aware of girls as young
as 9 having abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I know that it happens to 10-, 11- and 12-year-olds,''
Bowman said. ``The issue of how often it happens is immaterial. If
it happens to you and your family, it is a tragedy. And the fact
that it happens at all is indicative of the enormous abuse going on
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many girls in the 10- to 12-year-old
range get abortions each year. The Alan Guttmacher Institute, an
organization that compiles abortion statistics, reports that in
1994 _ the most current year data are available _ 12,150 abortions
were performed on girls ages 14 and under in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   About the same number of births were reported _ 12,901, and
about 3,800 miscarriages. That means there were roughly 28,851
pregnancies in girls ages 14 and under. The figures, however,
aren't broken down into more specific age groups.
</P>
<P>
   Figures compiled by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention show in 1995 that 5,903 abortions were performed on
girls ages 14 and under in 42 states and New York City. Not all
states, however, report their abortion figures to the CDC. Among
those not included are heavily populated states such as California,
Florida and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether young girls should be delivering babies is
a hotly contested one.
</P>
<P>
   Hillard said most studies suggest that teens who are older than
15 don't run much more risk of medical complications than do older
women. But the studies indicate that younger teens probably do face
increased risks, in part because they don't seek prenatal care
until later in their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies also show that younger teens are not yet
biologically mature enough to deliver, Hillard said.
</P>
<P>
   Many abortion opponents believe otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's not easy if you're 12 years old,'' said
Kansans for Life's Gittrich. ``But the rule of thumb has always
been that if you can conceive, you can deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't necessarily the case, Hillard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ignoring the fact that it may not have been voluntarily
that she got pregnant in the first place, it's ignoring all of the
developmental issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that arises in dealing with young girls getting
pregnant is late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is very, very complicated, and you'll find many
physicians who are not truly supportive,'' Hillard said. ``There's
just not a good choice in those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do the girls wait so long to seek an abortion?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, they don't know,'' Hillard said. ``Menstrual
periods are frequently irregular for teens, and they don't keep
track of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are not developmentally mature, certainly not at age 12,
and even not at age 15,'' Hillard said. ``They're not thinking
about the consequences of their actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons young girls wait so long, Hillard said, are
because they are afraid of disappointing their families and because
of a lack of familiarity with the medical system.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are just completely lost, they may not have good
problem-solving skills, and they don't know to go to some other
adult if they can't go to a parent, especially if one is the father
of the child,'' she said. ``They're just completely floundering,
and it's so very, very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes argue that though the cases are tragic, abortion
is not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is abortion going to solve?'' Gittrich said. ``Is it
going to make them an `unvictim' of an incest? Is it going to make
them feel better about being incested? It's just not going to do a
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to be just as traumatized as she was before the
abortion. The only problem is she's going to have to deal with the
fact that the baby she's felt kicking and moving and living in her
womb is now going to be killed. All we're doing is compounding the
problems and killing the child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
