<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVERNESS-FILM-REVIEW     07-30 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVERNESS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'THE GOVERNESS': CAPTURING IMAGES AND PASSION IN A TURBULENT
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our world is so overrun with photographic images that it's
amazing to realize that the art of photography is barely 150 years
old. Who would have thought, until it had been done, that it was
possible to capture and freeze a moment of time on a piece of
paper?
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Goldbacher's ravishingly handsome film ``The Governess''
takes us back to the spooky moment when the pioneers of photography
discovered how to create a lasting photographic image. That the
inventors in her film _ a gentleman scientist named Charles
Cavendish and his daughter's governess, Rosina da Silva (Minnie
Driver) _ are fictional characters gives her a metaphoric license
that sticking to the facts couldn't have allowed.
</P>
<P>
   When Charles and Rosina stumble on the idea of ``salt fixed''
prints (it's actually Rosina's idea, although Charles, her tutor in
photography, later takes credit for it), they are conducting a
secret, wildly passionate affair, and many of the first photographs
they take are of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The saucy Rosina poses for a series in which she plays Salome
doing the dance of the seven veils. While Charles, a skittish
Victorian Scot, is asleep, she takes a picture of him lying naked.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes of these photo sessions, in which a single eye is
shown peering feverishly through a lens, resonate long after the
film has ended, because of the poignancy with which they evoke the
difference between stop-time and real time.
</P>
<P>
   If Rosina's photograph of the naked Charles will last forever,
his tempestuous passion for her is evanescent and fraught with
guilt and betrayal. Because the cinematography of ``The Governess''
is so richly panoramic, the movie forces you to contemplate the
emotional power exerted by film, which is, after all just a series
of flickering photographic images flashed on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about trusting the truth of the frozen image in a
universe of ceaseless change aren't the only ideas that the movie
tosses around with the same spirited abandon exhibited by its
central character, Rosina.
</P>
<P>
   A rebellious life-hungry sensualist, Rosina grows up in an
affluent Sephardic Jewish household in London. Her world suddenly
shatters in the early 1840s when her father, a successful fish
merchant, is murdered on the street and the family is plunged into
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting an arranged marriage with an older man, Rosina
determines to disguise her Jewishness (the movie makes much of
virulent anti-Semitism in her world), and find a job. Posing as
Mary Blackchurch, a Protestant of partly Italian descent, she takes
a job as a governess to the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish
island.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rosina carries off the charade, the movie makes a major
point of showing the gap between 19th-century Christian and Jewish
cultures. Rosina may be a rebel, but she remains unshakably rooted
to her Jewish faith.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamy flashbacks in which she hungers for the life she left
behind are steeped in Jewish ritual and chant, and she secretly
continues to observe Passover. At the same time, she must observe
Christian rituals in the Cavendish family chapel.
</P>
<P>
   But it is her affair with the head of the household that reveals
the most profound and painful differences between the two
traditions. Where Charles rails about sin and hellfire and being
``consumed'' by his passion, Rosina pursues their relationship with
free-spirited determination.
</P>
<P>
   She has little comprehension of what Charles is going through
and not much sympathy. Were Charles to learn she was Jewish, he
would probably denounce her as a witch. Although Ms. Goldbacher is
sympathetic to both characters, she is clearly on the side of
Rosina, who emerges as a proto-feminist hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Governess'' is a wonderful showcase for Ms. Driver, whose
Rosina is a complicated, intimidating character. She pursues an
adulterous affair with the same stubborn feistiness she shows in
her dealings with Clementina (Florence Hoath), the mischievous,
morbidly inclined little monster in her charge.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Driver's performance is strong, it is less than great,
because her face lacks the transparency of expression that would
transport us inside her character's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wilkinson's Charles is a harrowingly effective portrait of a
guarded, puritanical man swept off his feet and nearly unstrung by
a passion he resists with all his will. Harriet Walter is equally
impressive as his idle, snobbish wife who wonders out loud in a
sweetly curdled voice if it's possible to die of disappointment and
boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Rhys Meyers is touching as the Cavendish's emotionally
unstable son, Henry, who develops an obsessive infatuation with
Rosina.
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes some missteps. Rosina's ability to support her
family in luxurious style from her earnings as a governess is
implausible. The screenplay includes some glaring lapses into
contemporary slang. And dramatically, the movie peters out in its
disappointingly perfunctory final scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Governess,'' which opens Friday in New York City,
still leaves a lasting after-image. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``The Governess'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has nudity and sexual
situations.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNESS
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Sandra Goldbacher; director of
photography, Ashley Rowe; edited by Isabel Lorente; music by Edward
Shearmur; production designer, Sarah Greenwood; produced by Sarah
Curtis; released by Sony Pictures Classics. At the Loews Paris Fine
Arts Theater, 4 West 58th Street, Manhattan. Running time: 114
minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Minnie Driver (Rosina), Tom Wilkinson (Cavendish), Harriet
Walter (Mrs. Cavendish), Florence Hoath (Clementina), Bruce Myers
(Rosina's Father) and Jonathan Rhys Meyers (Henry). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
