<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAR AND CIVILIZATION:' BATTLES AND BLOODSHED OVER MILLENNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Keegan, the popular British military historian, lends
scholarship to ``War and Civilization,'' the eight-part history of
mayhem that begins Sunday at 9 p.m. on the Learning Channel. Walter
Cronkite, America's narrator for all occasions, lends his
portentous baritone. And the producers lay on plenty of effects _
smoke, bodies, slow motion, fleeting images _ intended to represent
the most momentous clashes of the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The program, a busy mix of lecture room and legend, costume
drama and technical information, carries us from the Greek city
states to the Chinese empire, from the fall of Rome to the fall of
Constantinople, from the English civil war to the American Civil
War, from World War I to Hiroshima, right up to yesterday's carnage
in Rwanda and Bosnia, with many other cruel stops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Attention is steadily directed at innovations of weaponry,
tactics, logistics and other elements that have accounted for
triumph by slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's opening hour pays a mixed tribute to the Greeks of
3,000 years ago, crediting that fount of democracy with creating a
``Western way of war,'' which was ``deadly and decisive.'' You will
learn about the effectiveness of the armor that the hoplites, or
yeoman farmers, wore (about 70 pounds each) and the power of their
massed phalanxes. Military analysis helps explain the Greek
strategy on land and sea that turned back the Persians at the
battles that Herodotus made famous.
</P>
<P>
   The particular attraction of the series lies in the details,
how, for example, Philip of Macedon's shifts to longer spears and
smaller shields, along with the addition of horsemen and archers,
made his standing army the most formidable of their time. His son
and heir, Alexander the Great, whose empire covered all of the
known world, is crowned the ``father of modern logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent episodes give credit to the horse, which bore Attila
and Genghis Khan into Europe and China; to the long bow, which, in
the 14th century, enabled the British to topple the French knights
in their bulky armor; to the gunpowder that blasted away notions of
gallantry along with castle walls; to the arrival of the tank and
the airplane and, yes, to the sudden appearance of nuclear weapons,
which were heralded as changing everything but have not in fact
done much to stop nationalist, ethnic, religious and tribal clashes
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite's script poses the question, ``Can there be a future
without war?'' Perhaps influenced by the Cold War's resolution
without cataclysm, Keegan is mildly optimistic. He notes that with
the cost of all-out war now so high, both in blood and treasure,
the world's great armies have perforce become peace-keepers.
</P>
<P>
   But smaller forces keep busy. Since World War II, we are
reminded, most war casualties have been inflicted by second-hand
small arms, notably the Kalashnikov assault rifle, which even
impoverished nations can afford.
</P>
<P>
   With due regard for the many technical and tactical achievements
recorded here that have transformed warfare through the ages, every
day's headlines confirm that old-fashioned hatred is still managing
to cause misery and crush hope around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WAR AND CIVILIZATION'
</P>
<P>
   Learning Channel, Sunday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   ``War and Civilization'' is produced for the Learning Channel by
Worldview Pictures Ltd. For Worldview Pictures: Stephen Trombley,
executive producer and director; Bruce Eadie, series producer; Tony
Bulley, director. For the Learning Channel: Sandra Gregory,
executive producer; John Ford, executive in charge of production.
John Keegan, consultant; Walter Cronkite, narrator. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
