r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-LABOR-HNS &LR;      07-30 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LOBBYING OF CITY GOES UNREPORTED DESPITE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The interest group considered to be the
strongest and most effective at getting its way at City Hall,
organized labor, doesn't disclose its lobbying of city officials,
despite a decade-old law aimed at eliminating back-room
deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   Union influence on policy under Mayor Willie Brown is on the
rise and labor representatives have been particularly busy
advocates this year on health care legislation, the city budget and
on proposed rules for municipal contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But labor has never filed the quarterly disclosures required of
all paid advocates, businesses and organizations under San
Francisco's 1988 lobbyist disclosure ordinance, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Vida, executive director of the Ethics Commission, said
notices would be sent to the unions advising them that if they meet
the threshold of lobbying activity that triggers the ordinance,
``they need to register and report.''
</P>
<P>
   The required reports identify who is lobbying and on whose
behalf; how much they are being paid for the work; the names of the
city officials with whom they are meeting; and the topics they
discuss.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are a way for the public to track the efforts of
interest groups to influence public policy and spending.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of unions to register and report their lobbying
activity came to the attention of Ethics Commission staff members
recently as they prepared a series of amendments to the disclosure
law.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's belated attempt to force compliance by the
unions, particularly the Service Employees International Union, the
city's largest, has already sparked controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Union representatives contend they were unaware the measure
applied to them. They also argue it is wrong to lump them in with
lobbyists for corporate interests, whose influence in City Hall
provided the original impetus for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Boileau, vice president of the San Francisco Labor Council,
said the unions already disclose plenty of their political activity
by complying with state and local laws on reporting of campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the unions would resist city efforts to force them to
make similar disclosures under the lobbying ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists who regularly report their activities and elected
officials who have been critical of union influence at City Hall
disagreed with Boileau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I took office in 1993,'' said Board of Supervisors
President Barbara Kaufman, ``the unions have been the strongest
lobbying force and the most effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they should be treated any different from
private developers or other advocacy groups. They are very good at
what they do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got more money on the line than any other single
interest group,'' said Mark Mosher, of the Committee on Jobs, an
association of the city's biggest corporate employers.
</P>
<P>
   Activity directly tied to contract negotiations or matters
pertaining to workplace issues and grievance procedures are
exempted from the lobbying issue, according to a 1993 report from
the city attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   But if a union ``communicates with city officials for the
purpose of influencing legislative or administrative actions...,''
wrote Deputy City Attorney Randy Riddle, ``the organization is a
lobbyist within the meaning of the ordinance.''
</P>
<P>
   Disclosures are due quarterly, and a $1,000 fine could be levied
for each violation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTA     07-30 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Sharon Stone (Maslin).  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,' starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon, Tom
Sizemore, Jeremy Davies, Edward Burns and Adam Goldberg. Directed
by Steven Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly
magnificent new film is the finest war movie of our time. Turning
back the clock to restore passion and meaning to the genre, he
works in a spirit of urgent communication to look at war as if it
had not been looked at before. Tour-de-force battle scenes are
frank without sensationalism, and the same great storyteller who
made you believe there was an extraterrestrial hiding in the closet
has made this an irresistibly vibrant, gripping tale. Hanks
continues to astonish with admirable modesty, and the rest of the
casting is comparably inspired. As he did with ``Schindler's
List,'' Spielberg has made a landmark film of devastating power
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SMALL SOLDIERS,' starring Gregory Smith, Kirsten Dunst, Dennis
Leary and Phil Hartman. Directed by Joe Dante (PG-13, 105 minutes).
This ably animated film about action-figure toys who virtually come
to life should have been a sure thing. There are innocent echoes of
``Toy Story'' and darker ones of the director's own ``Gremlins''
pictures, which had the witty balance of mischief and horror that
``Small Soldiers'' strangely lacks. The voice talent here is
extraordinary, with the casts of ``The Dirty Dozen'' and ``This Is
Spinal Tap'' playing rival toy factions, and Tommy Lee Jones and
Frank Langella as their respective commanders. But the story
remains unfocused and grows too wan for horror, too creepy for
lighthearted fun. Another reason not to laugh is Hartman's
performance in the fatuous role that was his last (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE SPANISH PRISONER,' starring Campbell Scott, Rebecca
Pidgeon, Ben Gazzara and Steve Martin. Written and directed by
David Mamet (PG, 112 minutes). The most engaging of Mamet's
cinematic puzzles begins with an X-ray at an airport security
check. And the audience will wish it had a similar device for
reading the characters' sneaky minds. No such luck: the mystery
here, in a handsome and Hitchcockian film named for an elaborate
con game, stays tricky to the very end. Scott plays the inventor of
a lucrative, stealable scientific process, with Gazzara as the boss
who's in no hurry to compensate him for it. In an ensemble cast
working entirely on the calculating Mamet wavelength, Martin plays
a rich, debonair mystery man who tells the inventor all about his
pretty young sister. In her performance as a pert, unaccountably
off-kilter secretary, Ms. Pidgeon perfectly embodies the film's
sleight of hand (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,' starring Cameron Diaz, Ben
Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (R,
119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter. Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a
cruel, cruel zipper, this paean to low humor works ridiculously
well because it never stoops to being mean-spirited or (despite all
appearances) authentically inane. The principal cast is bright and
appealing, with Ms. Diaz at her most beautiful and blithe. Do note
that this film strives hard for something to offend everyone, and
that tolerance for the Farrellys' zit jokes is unfortunately
required (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TITANIC,' starring Leonardo DiCaprio, Kate Winslet and Gloria
Stuart. Directed by James Cameron (PG-13, 197 minutes). For once, a
much-touted event movie is exactly that: a glorious throwback to
the days when epic storytelling really filled the screen. Despite
the astonishing technological advances behind Cameron's great
visual spectacle, gimmicks are never allowed to intrude on the
film's central illusion, that the audience is drawn back into the
Gilded Age and intimately involved in the fateful voyage. For all
its painstaking historical detail, this ``Titanic'' proves anything
but quaint, thanks to the phenomenal immediacy of its sights and
the pure Hollywood hokum of its story. As two young lovers whose
romance is skillfully interwoven with historical detail, Ms.
Winslet and DiCaprio are a duo with serious chemistry. With his
``Gone With the Wind''-caliber ambitions, Cameron dared to dream of
the impossible and came up with the movie of the year (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE TRUMAN SHOW,' starring Jim Carrey, Laura Linney and Ed
Harris. Directed by Peter Weir and written by Andrew Niccol (PG,
104 minutes). The ultimate in high-concept ingenuity. Hosannas and
cartwheels for this ingenious media-age fantasy are over the top,
but by comparison with Hollywood's usual notion of summer movie
fare, it's definitely a dazzler. Carrey, refreshingly free of
shtick, gives an instantly iconic performance as a guinea pig for
an entertainment-happy nation, a man whose whole life is a fraud
contrived by Harris' so-called ``televisionary.'' Carrey's innate
edge of volatility gives the material, from a screenplay of
transfixing sci-fi intensity, its trace of danger. Ms. Linney, as
the actress playing a wife whose bluff could be called at any
moment, is the story's spookiest character as well as its perkiest.
Weir unifies the story's many nuances with great finesse (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   FILM SERIES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOOKING BACK, MOVING ON: CELEBRATING PHILIPPINE CINEMA.' In
observance of the 100th anniversary of the independence of the
Philippines from Spain, the Film Society of Lincoln Center Friday
begins a three-week survey of classic and contemporary Philippine
filmmaking. The series of 28 films, subtitled in English, opens
Friday with Marilou Diaz-Abaya's ``Rizal'' (1998), about the
19th-century author, poet, physician and nationalist Jose Rizal,
whose martyrdom inspired a rebellion against Spanish rule. The
series includes Cesar Gallardo's ``Gerry the Tramp'' (1964),
starring Joseph Estrada, now president of the Philippines, as an
illiterate man of unknown parentage who becomes a champion of the
downtrodden. Among other directors represented in the series is
Lino Brocka, who opposed the censorship of the Marcos dictatorship,
achieved international renown and helped to reinvigorate the
Philippine film industry in a 20-year career that began in the
1970's. The series continues through Aug. 20 at the Walter Reade
Theater, at New York's Lincoln Center. Admission: $8.50; $5 for
Film Society members; $4.50 for the elderly at weekday matinees.
Information: (212) 875-5600 (Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
