<HEADLINE>
STATE ETHICS RULES WOULD HAMPER FEDERAL PROSECUTORS, FISHER SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pending legislation to hold federal attorneys to
various state ethics rules rather than one national standard would
make it impossible to prosecute terrorists, telemarketers and child
abusers, a Justice Department spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Attorney General Ray Fisher said prosecutors would be
severely hampered making cases against criminals who operate in
several states if they had to meet ``a haphazard patchwork of 50
sets of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Clever defense lawyers could ``throw up roadblocks'' to
prosecutions by claiming Justice Department attorneys violated a
state ethics rule during a nationwide investigation of illicit
conduct, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects of this provision could be disastrous,'' Fisher
said, noting that department lawyers often appear in more than 10
states annually. ``Quite simply, it might prevent federal
prosecutors from bringing some of our most important multistate
cases, such as those involving large-scale conspiracies,
telemarketing fraud, child sexual abuse, exploitation on the
Internet and terrorist attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversial measure would create a seven-member
``Misconduct Review Board'' to review allegations of misbehavior by
Justice Department attorneys. The president would appoint the
panel's three voting members, and congressional leaders would name
the board's four advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The panel could subpoena information about an attorney's
conduct, including documents from a criminal investigation. The
board also could impose punishment, including the attorney's
dismissal, and refer the lawyer for criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the panel, ostensibly designed to rein in
overzealous prosecutors, could undermine even the most ethical of
prosecutions, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board would be able to intervene in a case on the basis of
vague allegations against department attorneys and would enable the
targets of investigations and their attorneys to obtain access to
all of the evidence obtained by the government, including the
identities of potential witnesses or confidential informants,''
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Rep. Joseph McDade, R-Pa., the measure's chief
sponsor, objected to Fisher's assessment. Calling the controversial
ethics provision ``very important,'' Jake O'Donnell said the
Justice Department's internal system for disciplining its lawyers
does not provide an adequate check on prosecutors' misconduct and
that an oversight panel would be a better safeguard.
</P>
<P>
   McDade's measure is part of a bill the House will consider next
week to provide $18.3 billion to the Justice Department for fiscal
year 1999, which begins Oct. 1. A Senate-passed measure to give
$17.8 billion to the department does not contain the controversial
provision.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno's opposition is so strong she would
take the unusual step of urging President Clinton to veto
legislation to fund her agency if the funding bill contains the
ethics measure, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is truly unnecessary,'' he said, noting that
federal lawyers who act unethically are already subject to
discipline from U.S. judges and the Justice Department's Office of
Professional Responsibility. ``We recognize the need for mechanisms
to deal with the occasional misconduct when it occurs, but this
proposal is fatally flawed,'' Fisher said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
