<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will be heavy for a time from eastern
New England to northern Middle Atlantic coast, particularly Friday
morning, as a disturbance skirts the coast. However, skies will
brighten by late Friday afternoon as the low moves quickly out to
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will be mixed with cumulus clouds across the interior
Northeast and eastern Ohio Valley, as a cool, dry air mass arrives.
Daytime highs will be close to normal, though nights will be cool
for the season. Meanwhile, high pressure, marking the center of the
refreshing air mass, will sponsor ample sun across the Great Lakes
states.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will percolate near a stalling cold
front from the southern Middle Atlantic states to the southern
Plains. Some storms will be locally heavy, though a significant
outbreak of severe weather is highly unlikely. Meanwhile, scattered
thundershowers will erupt near the eastern Gulf coast where cooler
air from sea breezes penetrate inland.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon thunderstorms will develop over the Rockies in
response to a persistent monsoon circulation. The Northwest will be
much cooler than recent days, while clouds and fog linger much of
the day at the coast. California will be sunny and seasonable,
though the day will dawn with fog and low clouds at the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Alex strengthened Thursday, as thunderstorms
increased in both number and intensity near the storm's center.
Further strengthening is expected Friday, as Tropical Storm Alex
continues to churn westward east of the Lesser Antilles.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hot Houston
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures soared to 100 degrees at Houston on Wednesday,
marking the 11th time this month with triple-digit readings. The
total represents Houston's second greatest number of 100-degree
days in July since records began. The number of 100-degree days for
the summer rose to 13, third on the all-time list behind the record
31 days in 1980. Temperatures of 100 degrees are not common in
Houston, given the clockwork afternoon cumulus and storms that
billow in conjunction with sultry winds from the Gulf of Mexico.
But steadfast high pressure aloft has suppressed clouds this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
