<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-HAPPINESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR HAPPINESS? LOOK AT YOURSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    At a firemen's convention the fire chiefs told stories about
their men's heroism. Afterward, a veteran fireman asked, ``Why are
we spending all our time running to put out fires, when we should
be looking for the arsonist who is starting them?''
 &HT;    Sure enough, an investigation led to an arsonist, and the fires
abated.
 &HT;    This story comes to mind when I think about how people deal with
their emotional needs. Some are always busy putting out emotional
fires while others search for the cause, thus not allowing the
fires to start.
 &HT;    By looking inward, we can live emotionally healthier and happier
lives.
 &HT;    But for many, adventure seems to be the tool for measuring
emotional health and happiness.
 &HT;    Let's look at some of the ways society enlists the help of the
arts to portray happiness.
 &HT;    I had a teacher who said, ``If you want to know what people are
thinking about, check the best-seller list.'' When reviewing
current best-sellers, we find many books that are sad.
 &HT;    ``Angela's Ashes'' has been on the list for 86 weeks. It is a
memoir of misery -- family neglect, childhood suffering and total
abuse.
 &HT;    I prefer a best-seller that is down to earth, dealing with
reality and attainable goals for fulfillment. For me the Bible has
reality and wonderful goals. It has been on the best-seller list
for centuries. It has plenty of adventure but no fantasy.
 &HT;    Let's see what society offers in the way of adventure. If you
have a couple thousand dollars and you don't mind possibly dying,
you can try climbing Mt. McKinley. It's a most exciting trek but 91
climbers have died since 1932.
 &HT;    If you do come back alive and your fellow climber doesn't, you
can get a book out of it. If you are stranded on the mountain and
resort to cannibalism, it might even mean a movie. At this time
there is a waiting list to challenge the mountain.
 &HT;    What else does society offer in entertainment? We have at least
three films depicting how Mother Earth is going to pieces. Whether
it is ``Godzilla,'' the fearful monster tearing up New York City,
or ``Deep Impact,'' with a threat from asteroids, they don't come
close to the newest film, ``Armageddon.'' There Bruce Willis and
his boys save the world.
 &HT;    Sadly, Willis finds it easier to save the earth than his
marriage to Demi Moore.
 &HT;    What may be happening to society is the refusal to look at
ourselves and take responsibility for our actions. After all, it is
not easy to recognize and correct personal limitations and
obligations.
 &HT;    Instead, we continue to search for new and exciting things to
do. By dealing with fantasies we deflect the real self.
 &HT;    We do so by reading books of sorrow, or viewing movies of saving
the world or by climbing mountains. We deny ourselves the
inevitable fact that we are responsible for our deeds and when we
act responsibly, we really feel good.
 &HT;    In the fantasy world we put our true feelings on hold. It's more
exciting to go to the theater and see Bruce Willis save the world.
 &HT;    That is much easier than coming home to face your family and
save your marriage. But easier is not always better.
 &HT;    A story is told about a sad, sad king. All the physicians had
despaired of curing him. As a last resort the healer offered him a
remedy: If the king would put on the shirt of a person who was
absolutely happy, then the king would be healed.
 &HT;    Riders were dispatched all over the country to look for a person
who was absolutely happy and bring back the shirt to the king.
 &HT;    First they went to the richest person in the country. They asked
him, ``Are you happy?'' He answered: ``Of course. I am the richest
person in the country.''
 &HT;    ``But are you absolutely happy?'' He began to hesitate.
``Absolute is a difficult term. I always have to protect my
position. I've had a setback or two recently ...''
 &HT;    The messengers left him in the middle of his thoughts. Then they
met the country's leading educational figure. ``Are you happy?''
they asked him. ``Yes,'' he answered.
 &HT;    ``Absolutely happy?'' And there he began to hem and haw.
 &HT;    On their way home they heard a joyous melody. A person was
singing freely, and they sensed that he was really happy. They saw
a drunken man, reeling back and forth with a huge smile on his
face. ``Are you happy?'' they asked him. ``I am the happiest person
in the world,'' he answered.
 &HT;    ``Absolutely happy?'' ``Yes. I have not a care on my mind.''
``Sir, we need your shirt. The king is sick, but the healer said
that if he puts on the shirt of a happy man, he will be healed.
Lend us your shirt for a short while. We promise that you will be
amply rewarded.''
 &HT;    The man replied, ``I would be happy to help the king, and I do
not need his rewards. But there is one problem. I do not own a
shirt.'' In his pursuit of happiness he had lost his family,
friends and all his possessions.
 &HT;    That man's happiness was not what the king needed. I believe
that a person who wants to be happy and fulfilled must be ready to
give up something.
 &HT;    The Jewish sage Ben Zoma had a saying, ``Who is rich? He who is
happy with his lot.'' One must recognize when fantasy becomes
destructive. By escaping into fantasies, we fool ourselves. We need
to be in touch with the real self.
 &HT;    As in the king's story, one needs to recognize that you cannot
have it all and be happy all the time. Remember, by chasing your
fantasy -- you may lose more than your shirt.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1998 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
