<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE SHRINKING AS DRUG SANCTIONS HIT HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEUCHATEL, Switzerland _ Slightly deflated, but not yet
defeated, the Tour de France rolls on. But even though it left
behind its host country for a few hours Thursday afternoon, it
didn't leave behind all its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Only 101 cyclists lined up at the beginning of the race's
fourth-to-last stage before it ends in Paris Sunday. That's little
more than half of the 189 who started the race almost three weeks
ago, attrition due in large part to riders who were banished after
drug investigations or dropped out because they felt harassed by
the probes and media coverage they feel have overshadowed the race.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining riders gathered in Aix les Bains at 11 in the
morning with their numbers once again pinned on their jerseys _
they had stripped them off in protest Wednesday, when they merely
rode instead of raced, causing the stage to be nullified _ and they
were ready to compete. But the mood was anything but joyful.
</P>
<P>
   In the village where sponsors gather before the race, reporters
speculated about what might happen, team officials walked around
talking on cell phones, and French racer Luc Leblanc _ wearing
street clothes instead of his racing uniform _ did interviews with
television stations about why he decided to pull out of the race
the night before (to show ``solidarity,'' he said, with countryman
Laurent Jalabert, whose Spanish-based team dropped out Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   Other no-shows were the two Spanish teams, Vitalico, and the
Kelme team, of which fourth-place Fernando Escartin is a member.
</P>
<P>
   Also absent was Rodolfo Massi, who was detained by police
Wednesday night along with Marc Madiot, the director of the
Francaise des Jeux team, and an unidentified doctor, judicial
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press also reported that police searched vehicles
and hotel rooms Wednesday night belonging to the teams from
Francaise des Jeux, ONCE, and Casino, and that no illegal
substances were found among medication seized Tuesday by customs
officers from the Bigmat team.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the clear blue skies, a black cloud hung over the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Jemison of Salt Lake City, a rider for the US Postal
Service team, said morale was down Wednesday night and was still
low Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said. ``That can change, but I mean, who's
going to raise their arms today and feel good about it?''
</P>
<P>
   The 136-mile ride ventured over the French border into
Switzerland on its final full day in the Alps. And even though it
lacked the straight up-and-down mountain passes that marked the
past three days, Jemison said the stage was anything but easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this is not flat,'' he said, displaying the small
profile of the stage that he keeps in his jersey. ``This is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jemison and the remaining riders appeared to be back in
racing form as they covered the countryside at a clip that averaged
28 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The flat finish was made for sprinters, and it seemed Germany's
Erik Zabel was poised to cross the line first as he furiousily spun
his wheels and sped along to the front. But another ace sprinter,
Tom Steels of Belgium, made clear that it was not to be. He rushed
up right next to Zabel's wheel, then surged just inches ahead as he
crossed the line in 4 hours 53 minutes 27 seconds. It was the third
stage win for Steels, who is in 81st place overall.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the pack rolled into town en masse, and the overall
standings didn't change.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Marco Pantani is in first place, with an almost
six-minute lead over Bobby Julich of the United States, who leads
defending champion Jan Ullrich by just 14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass., finished 54th Thursday, 4
minutes 8 seconds back, and is in 52d place overall with a 1-hour
37-minute 30-second deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he gets to the podium in Paris Sunday, Julich realizes
his finish might be tainted by the scandals that have surrounded
the Tour..
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there may be a little asterisk by my name in the
results,'' Julich said, ``but I know what I know, and Laurent
Jalabert dropping out doesn't take any of the prestige away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think regardless if it's just me or 10 guys crossing the
line, when we all were there in the race and when all the riders
were givng 100 percent, I was still there. I was one of the best
riders, and that's what I'm going to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tour heads back to France today but, the riders hope, not
back to more problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
