<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US LOSES TO LITHUANIA, 84,82, AT THE BUZZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ We've now officially gone back to the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's just like it was in the pre-Dream Team days, when the
United States would go to an international basketball tournament
and find itself in a shark pool. The US entry in the world
championships here discovered just how vulnerable it was Thursday
when it fell behind Lithuania by 16 points and wound up losing,
84-82, when Jimmy Oliver's great look at a potential game-winning
3-pointer rattled in and out at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Lithunania is not even considered one of the favorites.
Lithuania is missing its two best players, Arvydas Sabonis and
Zadrunas Ilgauskas. A couple of its players look as if they need _
I mean really need _ a good meal. But more than a few of these guys
played a superb game against the Americans. If Oliver's shot had
gone down, it would have been a painful, and more than likely
incomprehensible, loss for the Lithuanians, who took the lead at
13-12 and never gave it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy we can come back and play (Friday) and not have
to wait three or four days,'' said point guard Michael Hawkins, who
packed 11 of his 16 points into a stretch drive that almost
resulted in a tremendous American comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's opponent is South Korea. Trust me when I tell you that
your US team will have no trouble beating South Korea. The loss
Thursday will have little effect on the US chances of winning the
gold medal, other than to boost the confidence of the teams
considered true contenders.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no big surprise to learn that the Lithuanian
player who bullied America's team the most was the most
Americanized player they've got. I am speaking of ex-Seton Hall
star Arturas Karnisovas, whose 29 points, accumulated via an
impressive all-around display of offensive virtuosity, looked and
felt more like 129. He did not make baskets as much as he threw
daggers. He pretty much did whatever he felt like doing, and none
of Rudy Tomajanovich's players came close to stopping him.
</P>
<P>
   This is interesting because at the Goodwill Games, Karnisovas
was the team offensive millstone. The Lithuanians shot 52 percent
as a team despite his 38 percent bricklaying.
</P>
<P>
   But it just so happens that this game was played at Peace and
Friendship Arena, where Karnisovas played a full season for
Olympiakos in the Greek League. ``When the bus pulled up, I started
thinking about the good games I had here for Olympiakos,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had three or four games over 30 in this building and 15
or 20 more over 20,'' pointed out Hawkins, an Olympiakos teammate.
``So he felt real comfortable in this gym.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans looked distinctly uncomfortable in the first half.
Oliver hit two quick shots, but that was it. For most of the half,
it was Boulder Central. Worse yet, the US couldn't figure out what
was going on when Lithuania had the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The scouting report harped on Lithuania's shooting ability. The
Lithuanians responded with obvious trickery. They began taking it
to the hoop and they never stopped. They also got into transition
every chance they got, and no one had said anything about that,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the Americans play Brazil,'' said Karnisovas.
``Brazil was aggressive at the start. They were getting to the line
and they were running. Then they slowed down. They looked unsure of
themselves. They lost their leverage. We decided we would run the
ball and stay aggressive, and we also said we had to be as physical
as they were.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we didn't think they could run,'' said assistant
coach Del Harris. ``We just thought we could contain them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they did that to us,'' fumed Oliver. ``We
spend a lot of time working on defensive transition. I think they
came out more aggressively and tried to put it to us from the
get-go. They put us back on our heels. Looking at the films, they
were a shooting team. They turned out to be a driving team.''
</P>
<P>
   The US is still trying to find out exactly what it is. Brazil is
no longer the Brazil of old. That was perhaps a deceptively easy
opener. Anyone watching the tape of this one will come away with
all kinds of ideas about how to beat this US team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My state of mind, and I will pass this on, is that we simply
can't go out there and have another bad start against Korea,'' said
Oliver. ``We must do whatever it takes, starting right there in the
locker room, to get off to a better start.''
</P>
<P>
   The US remains confident, but not ridiculously so. The European
players among them certainly respect the competition. What this
game reminded everyone is that the US isn't good enough to dig big
holes and assume that the extrication effort will be successful.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of you folks hated the Dream Team and its successors. You
wanted competition. This game serves as ample enough evidence that
you've got it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
