<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS &LR;      07-30 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE GOP CONFIDENT OF PREVAILING ON MANAGED CARE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Noting that Senate debate on reining in managed
care has been put off until after the August recess, Republican
lawmakers said Thursday they won't compromise on one of the key
sticking points _ patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a key architects of the Senate
Republican managed care bill introduced last month, accused
Democrats of stalling and creating the delay in considering the GOP
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not going too far to say the Democrats are
beginning to jeopardize the possibility of passing a bill,
period,'' Gramm said at a news conference. ``Their unwillingness to
bring this bill up is beginning to threaten the whole concept of
passing a bill this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pushing for their own patients-rights measure,
which they say goes further than the GOP measure to control the
cost-conscious health plans that closely monitor patient treatment
to make sure it is medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said the Republicans who dominate the Senate have
``reached a consensus. And the consensus is we want to defeat the
(Democrats') bill and we want to adopt our bill. That's the
consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   With Election Day a little more than three months away, managed
care has become a hot-button issue, with both parties jockeying to
win voter favor as the champion of controlling health plans.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans approved a managed care bill July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans were anxious to bring up their version of the
bill this week. But on Wednesday, Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., put it off after Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., refused to go along with the GOP plan to limit the number
of amendments Democrats could offer.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the Senate floor Thursday, Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., co-author of the Democrats' patients-rights bill,
accused Republicans of squelching open debate and a vote on each
legislative issue for fear that it would show that ``their plan is
more loophole than law.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans ``believe that the less the American people
know about their sham proposals, the better they will be able to
protect their friends in the health insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   At the GOP news conference, Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., said
Democrats fear that a vote on the Republican bill would take away
one of their prime 1998 campaign issues. ``It seems to me they're
more interested in playing politics ... than they are in trying to
legislate seriously on this matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republican and Democratic bills would require health plans
to compensate patients for most emergency room care at hospitals
not in the plans' hospital networks. Both would lift ``gag'' rules
that prevent doctors from talking about treatment options that
individual plans do not cover.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican bill would cover only the 48 million people
whose plans are exempted by federal law from state regulation. The
Democratic bill would cover all 160 million or so enrolled in
managed care health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill would set up appeal routes inside and
outside health plans when patients disagree with their plan's
denial of coverage. The Democrats also would permit patients to sue
their health plan for compensatory and punitive damages when the
denial results in further injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill also would set up an internal and external
appeals route. Patients would be able to go to court after the
appeals route is exhausted, but only in limited circumstances. If
the external appeals body rules in the patient's favor and the plan
still does not provide the treatment, the patient could obtain a
court-ordered penalty of $100 a day for each day the plan refuses
to comply.
</P>
<P>
   If the appeals body turns thumbs down, the patient still could
go to court but only to recover the cost of the denied benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill also contains a provision to expand a small
federal trial program of medical savings accounts (MSAs), which
offer tax deductions to individuals who set the accounts to save
for out-of-pocket expenses incurred when they purchase
high-deductible medical insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and their supporters have condemned MSAs as sops to
the rich and healthy that would, in effect, draw them out of the
insurance risk pool and cause rates to rise for the poorer and less
healthy who remain behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, a staunch MSA advocate, said he could not compromise on
these accounts in order to get a bill passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical savings accounts are not controversial,'' he insisted.
``They're only controversial with people who deep in their heart
want the government to run the health care system. They know if we
get medical savings accounts and empower the consumer, they will
never. ever have their dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   A compromise bill authored by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., is aimed
at bridging the gap between the two parties. Joined by Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., Sen. Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., and Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., the Chafee proposal includes
many of the common points of the Democratic and Republican plans,
such as internal and external appeals, and easier access to
emergency room care.
</P>
<P>
   But it avoids the political pitfalls such as the lawsuit
provision in the Democrats' bill and expanded medical savings
accounts in the Republicans' measure.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the Chafee bill contains fewer protections than the
Democrats' bill, but its existence proves ``that the wall of
opposition by Senate Republicans to genuine reform is continuing to
crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, however, dismissed the Chafee effort, calling it ``a
compromise looking for a constituency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
