<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SUMMER, NOISE MATTERS  
 TV'S OK WITH DAVID KELLEY  
 HOLLYWOOD SUCCESS STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ If there is one outstanding feature of the movies
released this summer, especially the big special-effects pictures,
it is that they are among the noisiest films ever made.
``Armageddon'' and ``Godzilla,'' and even the serious drama
``Saving Private Ryan,'' have cranked up the aural effects, leaving
some people thrilled and others with headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the response, many experts say movie sound _ even if it
is sometimes characterized as just ``technical'' _ is entering a
more sophisticated era, partly as a result of better sound
production in the studios, and partly as a result of movie
theaters' installing digital sound systems. And the change is
having a big impact on how audiences experience films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound has become a much more important tool in terms of
putting the audience in a mood and a place,'' said Wylie Stateman,
a co-founder of Soundelux Entertainment, a large sound production
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sound tells the story,'' he continued. ``It's not responsible
just to make it louder. What you can do is create a time and a
place, create weight and velocity. You can put a helicopter over
the audience's head and move it all around.''
</P>
<P>
   Stateman has worked on effects from the screech of Godzilla,
produced with a mix of elements ranging from a trumpet to lion and
camel roars, to the sounds in ``Flubber,'' ``Air Force One'' and
``Jerry Maguire.'' He is also creating the effects for the voice of
God for the animated feature ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jenkins, the president of Todd-AO Studios, the largest
sound production company in Hollywood, said, ``The technical
improvements have always gone in small increments, but in the last
three to five years they have grown in great leaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who worked on ``Lost in Space'' and ``Six Days, Seven
Nights,'' among other films, added: ``What this is about is
contrast and subtlety. We can be much more subtle now. A whisper is
as important as an explosion as far as we're concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Jenkins and Stateman emphasized that the new equipment and
techniques have clarified soundtracks, making each element more
distinct, removing background noise and allowing for subtle mixes
that give the audience a sense that the images on the screen are at
varying distances.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the digital electronic advances, many techniques
are still quite prosaic. Stateman said that a head of lettuce is
still torn in half to create ripping sounds, and that coconut
shells are still knocked together to produce the sound of horses'
hooves, just as in radio days. But now the horses can seem to walk
around the viewer, and even behind.
</P>
<P>
   Stateman said one of the greatest and most satisfying challenges
was taking the relatively flat images of animation and making them
come to life through sound.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that movie sound would increasingly be used to
create a sense of total immersion in the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll go back to smell-o-rama,'' he said, ``but
using new digital standards will put you completely in the
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in addition to filling the entire theater with
sounds, seats might be made to vibrate to add to the sense of
realism.
</P>
<P>
   Just a Break From TV
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Hollywood hierarchy has looked something like
this: You did theater to get into television, and television to get
into movies, then went back to television only when you got too old
for the movies or hit a creative slump.
</P>
<P>
   By those standards, David Kelley, television's most prolific
writer-producer, would seem to have finally gotten his break.
Kelley created ``Picket Fences,'' ``Chicago Hope,'' ``The
Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal'' for television, and his shows just
garnered 14 Emmy nominations. He is a meticulous craftsman who
wrote every episode of ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice'' last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But at long last his movie career appears to be taking off.
Earlier, he wrote ``From the Hip'' and ``To Gillian on Her 37th
Birthday,'' both of which did not fare well in the theaters. Now he
has two films under way: ``Lake Placid,'' the tale of a 35-foot
crocodile that makes its way into a remote lake in Maine, and
``Mystery Alaska,'' about a small-town hockey team whose pride is
suddenly put on the line when it gets an opportunity to play the
New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelley said he viewed these projects as modest asides, to
fill his time between television seasons, not as an opportunity to
climb the Hollywood ladder: ``You still hear people say: `You're a
pretty good writer. Why are you still doing television?' It always
surprises me. The sugar plums that dance around in peoples' heads
here come from features. But both of these movies were done during
the hiatus in the television season. It really was just that. I
consider myself to be in television. I just had a few good ideas
that didn't lend themselves to television treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said that given the quality of much television today and
the amounts of money that could be made, the medium had gained
somewhat in stature, but for emphasis, he added, ``This is not a
segue into features.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery Alaska,'' which is being released by Disney's
Hollywood Pictures and on which Kelley was a writer and a producer,
has just finished shooting and is expected in theaters early next
year. It stars Russell Crowe, Hank Azaria, Mary McCormack, Lolita
Davidovich and Burt Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Placid,'' which Kelley wrote and is a producer on, is
about to begin production and is being released by Phoenix
Pictures, 20th Century Fox, Canal Plus and Pioneer. It stars Bill
Pullman, Bridget Fonda, Oliver Platt and Brendan Gleeson. Kelley
said the film had grown out of a childhood ``obsession'' with
crocodiles.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said he was disappointed in some ways that he had done
the hockey story as a feature rather than a television series
because he had grown to like the characters and wished he had had
the opportunity to explore them further.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said that he and his wife, actress Michelle Pfeiffer,
tried to go to the movies every Saturday night, and that he enjoyed
the entertainment, but that he preferred writing for television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make an argument that television is better than
features these days, but the best feature is something to behold,''
Kelley said. ``But it's just always been more fun for me to write
for existing characters. I'm content to stay in television, for
now.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Daydream Come True
</P>
<P>
   You spend years producing and directing promotional spots for
television shows, but you dream of making a feature-length movie.
You have a script, written with your wife. You even get a small
production company interested, and all you need is an actor or two
with just a bit of a reputation. And then you suddenly find
yourself with two Oscar winners eager to play roles.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Valerio admitted that that was, at one time anyway, his
daydream, but that it had now come true, much like an old-fashioned
Hollywood tale, as he was preparing to direct his first feature
film, ``Carlo's Wake,'' with Martin Landau and Rita Moreno. The
movie is being produced by Triple Axel Productions.
</P>
<P>
   Though the project has been years in the making, Valerio, 40,
admitted to a frisson of delight that he was finally moving ahead.
He said he was concentrating on how to make the oddball comedy seem
fresh, and especially on how to make it a movie rather than a
two-hour sitcom, a common pitfall for directors who come from
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlo's Wake'' began as a play written by Valerio's wife,
Rosie Taravella, and based on real experiences. The play was a
poignant and humorous account of her father's wake; the colorful
members of the extended family who attended the event and the woman
who did not, Carlo's estranged wife, Angela. Lies, secrets and,
eventually, truths about the family spill out as its members take
account of Carlo's life and joust with each other over his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   What the audience must come to terms with, Valerio said, is
whether ultimately Carlo's wife was justified in running off with
her husband's brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlo is a bit of a scoundrel, so it's a dark-edged comedy,''
Valerio said. ``But what happens is the children all see the dead
man differently. It's like they're talking about a different man.
The audience doesn't know what to think because they only know what
they're told by the characters. It's not a gross-out comedy like
some of the ones that are popular now. It's darker.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's budget is $2.5 million, which is a reasonably hefty
sum for a small, independent film with an ensemble cast, and it
will be shot in Santa Monica. It's a big step for Valerio, who at
one time directed what he described as a porno puppet show for the
Playboy channel before focusing on promotional spots for television
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 10 years, I directed most of the best actors in
television,'' he said. ``It was just for a short time for each
promotion, but I worked with everyone from Dick Van Dyke to Cheech
Marin. You learn a lot working with people like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
