<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Love sweeter than any gift costing a mint
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of my grandsons is getting married to a darling,
dark-haired, bookish young girl, and I've brooded over how to help
with the celebration and what to give them.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, parents and grandparents could deed over a
spread of land. Before that, when more land wasn't to be had, they
would give a mule or a milk cow. In the house, the womenfolk busied
around getting together feather beds and quilts for them. Many
young couples started marriage with a brace of ducks, a couple of
setting hens and a setting of eggs.
</P>
<P>
   I knew an old lady who always gave Bibles for wedding presents,
and a gentle, kind old bachelor who had a wonderful library and
invited the nuptial couple to take their choice of his books.
Starting them off with a library of their own was the richest gift
he had at his disposal, and I dallied with the idea of giving my
grandson and his bride books.
</P>
<P>
   But they give me books. Ted left two boxes of books in my
basement and said, ``Help yourself.'' They are all things I want to
read, but no self-help book that will tell me what to give them for
a wedding present.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a grandmother will bestow a new car on the marrying
ones. I don't have one to give, and I can't afford to buy them one.
Besides, they have cars and probably strong ideas about what they
will buy for themselves when they are able. I know a rich lady in
Mobile(Ala.) who sends the bridal couple around the world on their
honeymoon. I might finance a trip to Ludowici, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The old custom of registering their wants with a department
store is not as prevalent with brides-to-be as it used to be. I
remember going to Rich's and being taken in hand by 'Cile Butts,
who would take you on a tour of the china, crystal and silver
departments, detouring by linens and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Computer no help
</P>
<P>
   I tried that at the one store where our bride is registered.
There was no 'Cile Butts to be warm and welcoming. You talked to a
computer. I was so discouraged by the answers I got, I turned off
the machine and started wandering. There were many pretty things,
but would she want any of them? What does she have already? What
have her friends and relatives contributed?
</P>
<P>
   So I went home and started thinking about the custom of handing
down. To one bride, I handed down the remains of my mother's
silver, which happened to be her own chosen pattern. To another, I
gave two old serving pieces that had belonged to her
great-grandmother on the other side. What is left for this couple?
I searched the cabin and came up with nothing. An old platter?
Crackled and stained and in use for 100 years ... what modern girl
would want that? I looked at quilts and pictures. They mean a lot
to me, but absolutely nothing to this pretty newcomer in our
family.
</P>
<P>
   The day approaches, and I am out of ideas. Or I was until I
remembered a card I read years ago. It said, ``What can I give
thee? I can give thee love.''
</P>
<P>
   And I do. I wish them a long and happy marriage, independent of
things. I send them a heartful of love going back to when the
husband-to-be was a newborn baby and I drove down Piedmont Avenue
with an iron bed tied to the top of my car. I send them memories _
his first haircut, his grammar school play, our walks to the river,
our talks about books. Worrying about a present would detract from
the day, so I won't. I send them love.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
