<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trip-hopping Tricky in a feel-good mood
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brace yourself, Tricky fans.
</P>
<P>
   The moody genius behind the trip-hop masterpiece ``Maxinquaye''
and the dense, difficult new effort ``Angels With Dirty Faces'' is
about to throw the wildest curveball of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He is getting happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Mr. Positive!'' gushes the 30-year-old British
artist in an expletive-riddled phone interview from his home in New
York. Those who know the man's work and reputation will find that
hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Born Adrian Thaws, Tricky got his nickname as a teenager. (In
the July issue of Details magazine, he says it was because he was
thought to be ``unreliable.'') He rose to prominence in the early
'90s as part of a clique of artists experimenting with
``trip-hop,'' a downbeat, murky-sounding form of electronic dance
music. His 1995 debut, ``Maxinquaye,'' made many critics' year-end
best-of lists, and such pop hipsters as Bjork and Neneh Cherry
queued up to collaborate with him.
</P>
<P>
   As Tricky's career grew, so did his reputation for being
temperamental. In interviews he could be uncooperative, refusing to
discuss past efforts. By his own admission, he could be difficult
with colleagues. ``People I had been working with told me they
couldn't work with me anymore,'' he says. ``I knew there was
something wrong.'' He tried tai chi to calm his nerves and sought
the opinions of several doctors, but, he says, ``I went to see the
wrong ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, earlier this year, he went to see a nutritionist who
diagnosed him with candidiasis, a yeastlike fungus that some say
infects the intestinal and respiratory tracts. Controversy
surrounds the condition and its treatment, which includes
restricting sugar and wheat in the patient's diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether such a thing as candidiasis exists is still in
question,'' says Chris Rosenbloom, an associate professor of
nutrition at Georgia State University. ``The whole area is still
not well-known. In terms of its treatment, restricting someone's
sugar intake makes sense theoretically. But no one has ever shown
that it actually clears it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after several months of being on such a diet,
Tricky says, ``I feel so much better. I've written some new songs
that I am loving. They're not nearly as tense and paranoid as the
old stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the masses respond to the new, feel-good Tricky? ``I can
see a lot more people getting into (the new songs),'' he says. Not
that mainstream success is necessarily the main goal. ``Only if I
can do it my way,'' Tricky insists. ``It would be beautiful to do
it without compromising.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
