<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On-target `Negotiator' fights fire with fire
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this crisply acted thriller, Samuel L. Jackson plays a
hostage negotiator for the Chicago police department who is framed
for embezzlement and murder. Desperate to clear his name, he takes
four members of the department hostage, then asks another
negotiator (Kevin Spacey) to act as a mediator between himself and
his fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's main kick is the engrossing duel of bluffs and
counterbluffs between Spacey and Jackson. They make us believe in
the high stakes of the situation. And director F. Gary Gray (``Set
It Off'') remembers the meat and potatoes of the genre, throwing in
tense action sequences that make the film resemble a cousin of
``Die Hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negotiator''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey. Directed by F. Gary
Gray. Rated R for violence, language. At metro theaters. 2 hours,
15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Takes no hostages with its blend of tense action
and terrific acting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
