<TEXT>
<P>
   An updated `Trap' sticks to tried, true
</P>
<P>
   By Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   The people behind this remake have wisely deviated little from
the plot of the 1961 Disney movie that made 15-year-old Hayley
Mills a top star. This time, redheaded Lindsay Lohan plays the dual
role of separated-practically-at-birth identical twins who meet at
camp and switch identities in the hope of reuniting their divorced
parents. Much of what's different about this ``Trap'' involves
updating _ fax machines and ``Leo'' DiCaprio references dot a
modernized tale, which includes a mother who works and (in one
scene) gets a little tipsy. Young kids may fidget at the length and
several kissing scenes. But they should enjoy the high-jinks-filled
camp sequence and Atlanta's Elaine Hendrix as Dad's coldly
calculating fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parent Trap''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Natasha Richardson, Dennis Quaid and Lindsay Lohan.
Directed by Nancy Meyers. Rated PG for mild profanity and alcohol
use. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A ``Trap'' to get caught up in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
