<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Henry Fool' keeps emotional distance
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've never been a fool for director Hal Hartley's work
(``Trust,'' ``Amateur''), and ``Henry Fool'' does little to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which won the best screenplay prize at Cannes earlier
this year, is an ambitious fable of friendship, fame, art, commerce
and the ever-shifting phenomenon known as the eye of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   The aptly named Simon Grim (James Urbaniak) is a nerdy, put-upon
garbage man who is generally regarded as retarded by everyone in
his Queens neighborhood, including his slatternly sister (Parker
Posey, doing her usual wild-child slut act). Then, one day, Henry
Fool (Thomas Jay Ryan) moves into the Grim basement and takes over
Simon's life.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is as grandiose and overbearing as Simon is withdrawn and
unsure. He's also a self-styled writer, working on a personal opus
that he calls his ``Confession.'' Noting his new friend's
difficulty in expressing himself, Henry hands him a notebook and
some advice: ``Ever feel like you've got something to say and can't
get it out, stop and write it down.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll grant Hartley intelligence, wit, a love for language and a
certain eccentric world vision, all nice attributes for any
filmmaker. But his determinedly removed style keeps us at a
distance, and without any emotional investment in the characters,
it's difficult to be drawn into the picture's central conflict: the
sacredness of friendship vs. the integrity of the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Henry Fool'' just seems to go on and on and on,
bogged down by the director's insufferable self-indulgence and a
fatally bad performance in the title role. Urbaniak is fine as
Simon; his constricted conciseness of gesture and air of unblinking
alienation suggest a heavily medicated Lyle Lovett. But his
co-star, Ryan, has none of the innate charisma and self-serving
bravura of a natural-born poseur. Hartley gives him a particularly
distasteful secret which, when revealed, is supposed to make us
reconsider our attraction to this colorful scoundrel. But because
he's more boring than colorful, our ``attraction'' isn't really at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
