A0984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-POLISH-COX     07-30 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-POLISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family _ the tie that binds
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, it's so rare to see an independent film about a
family that's not dysfunctional that that fact alone makes this
debut feature by Theresa Connelly something of a welcome surprise.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that her bustling clan of working-class
Polish-Americans, the Pzoniaks, doesn't have its share of problems.
To begin with, the sultry, iron-willed matriarch, Jadzia (Lena
Olin), is having an affair. Her sad-eyed husband, Bolek (Gabriel
Byrne), who works the graveyard shift at the neighborhood bakery,
has his suspicions. After all, every time he has a night off, his
wife has a meeting of the Polish Women's Auxiliary. (Watching Olin
march off to her illicit assignations in pseudomilitary garb is a
great sight gag.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, their beautiful daughter, Hala (Claire Danes), is a
headstrong bundle of raging hormones who routinely sneaks out after
dark. One night, she comes home pregnant. The icing on the cake:
She's just been chosen to play the Virgin Mary in their church's
annual procession.
</P>
<P>
   Objectively speaking, ``Polish Wedding'' is a stubbornly un-P.C.
movie. Essentially, it endorses a teenager's dropping out of high
school, getting knocked up and forcing the baby's father to marry
her, regardless of consequences down the road. The film never
really examines this kind of thinking, and yet that's part of its
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's script may be shaky and cliched, but her cast so
expertly creates this insular, blue-collar, first-generation
community that choices such as adoption, abortion and contraception
don't seem relevant. You even swallow, with barely a grimace, the
film's Old World assertion that women's true vocation is, in
Jadzia's words, ``making life and making love.''
</P>
<P>
   Olin, last seen putting a lethal leg-lock on Gary Oldman in
``Romeo Is Bleeding,'' is a commanding, sensual and complex woman,
firmly committed to her family yet risking all for a fling. Danes
is her ever-radiant self, just a little sneakier and
self-assertive. Best of all is Byrne, who effortlessly translates
his trademark Irish soulfulness into soulful Polishness.
</P>
<P>
   What all this adds up to is a warning of sorts: This movie may
be playing the art-house circuit, but it's more like a wobbly
``Moonstruck'' wannabe than anything Parker Posey or Christina
Ricci has been in recently. Thus, ``Polish Wedding'' may be too
square for the typically hip independent-film audience. Ironically,
that same lack of chic is what makes it so refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polish Wedding''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Claire Danes, Lena Olin and Gabriel Byrne. Directed by
Theresa Connelly. Rated PG-13 for sex. At Tara. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A strong cast transforms a trite script.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
