<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHENANDOAH-FRONTIER-C     07-30 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHENANDOAH-FRONTIER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shenandoah Valley: Walk into the lives of the early settlers
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Staunton, Va. -- In the early 18th century, the Shenandoah
Valley was still wilderness _ America's western frontier. Its
earliest settlers were farmers from Germany, Northern Ireland and
England who came in search of religious freedom and land to call
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of American Frontier Culture tells their story. A
walking tour through this remarkable outdoor living history museum
takes visitors to the three European farms and finally to the
American frontier farm that represents the melding of the Old World
traditions of these three ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The farms are not replicas but buildings that were dismantled,
shipped to Virginia and reassembled on site. Each farmhouse is
outfitted with period-appropriate furniture, household items and
farm implements. Even the crops in the fields and the livestock in
the barns are antique breeds typical of the countries represented.
Costumed interpreters demonstrate farm skills. At each home, tables
have been laid with typical foods of the time and place.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop on the loop trail is the timber-frame German farm
built between 1688 and 1730 in the village of Hordt by the Rhine
River in Rhineland-Palatinate. You'll likely be greeted by a
gregarious flock of feather-crowned German silver spitzhaubens,
once common barnyard chickens. Inside, a man spins wool into yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the Ulster farm, typical of those leased from a landlord
by the Scottish-Irish in Northern Ireland. The three thatch-roofed
buildings stood near the village of Drumquin, County Tyrone. A
woman in a straw hat hoes the field as another woman tends to
household chores inside. Farther down the path a blacksmith is at
work at the forge moved from County Fermanaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The English farm was the home of a yeoman (a small landowner) in
the late 17th century. The meat on the table along with the
vegetables attest to his relative prosperity. The two-story
timber-frame house was moved from Hartlebury Parish,
Worcestershire, in the West Midland area. Its windows are lead
glass and the roof clay tile.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the American log farmhouse and outbuildings were found
near the town of Eagle Rock in Botetourt County in the southern
part of the valley. During a visit earlier this summer, a group of
schoolchildren watched as an interpreter quilted on the front
porch.
</P>
<P>
   Plan to spend a full morning or afternoon to see the
introductory video and exhibits in the visitor center and explore
the farms.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: 9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily. $8 adults; $7.50 senior
citizens; $4 ages 6-12. Take I-81 Exit 222 to U.S. 250 west;
entrance half mile on the left. 540-332-7850.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
