<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shenandoah Valley: If you go
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Trasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   Nonstop flights to Washington-Dulles and Richmond leave
frequently on a daily basis at a major airport near you. Usually a
14 day advance purchase is required.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   540-740-3132 (Shenandoah Valley Travel Association; call for a
free travel guide and calendar of events, or check the Web site at
www.svta.org). Also, 1-800-847-4882 (Virginia Division of Tourism)
for a statewide travel guide.
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   -- Sunday lecture series at Stonewall Jackson Museum: Aug. 16:
Historian Gary Eclebarger discusses his book ``We Are In for It,''
about the first battle of Kernstown. Sept. 13: ``Cedar Creek
Revisited,'' a discussion of the pivotal battle by former U.S. Army
historian Col. Joe Whitehorne. Oct. 11: ``Battlefield Ghosts'' by
Gettysburg National Battlefield guide Keith Toney. 3 p.m. Free with
admission. 540-465-5884.
</P>
<P>
   -- Museum of American Frontier Culture, Staunton: ``Expressions
of Faith _ Presbyterian Traditions'' program, Aug. 9; ``Flax to
Linen'' program Aug. 29 (advance ticket required); Frontier
Festival, Sept. 12-13; American Picnic and Barn Dance, Oct. 4
(advance ticket required); American Revolution Battle Re-enactment,
Oct. 17-18. 540-332-7850.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shenandoah Valley Music Festival, Orkney Springs: Jazz
weekend, Aug. 14-15; folk festival featuring Tom Paxton, Sept. 5;
big band concert, Sept. 6. Orkney Springs Hotel. 1-800-459-3396 or
www.musicfest.org
</P>
<P>
   -- Green Valley Book Fair, Mount Crawford: More than 500,000 new
books offered at 60 percent to 90 percent off retail. Aug. 8-16,
Oct. 10-18 and Nov. 27-Dec. 6. 1-800-385-0099.
</P>
<P>
   -- Virginia Quilt Museum, Harrisonburg: Through Sept. 24:
``Beyer and Bowie: Retrospective of Two Virginia Quilters.'' Sept.
19-Feb. 1: ``Celestial Treasures,'' antique and contemporary quilts
in star and sunburst and related designs. 540-433-3818.
</P>
<P>
   -- Blue Ridge Theatre Festival, Harrisonburg: Aug. 6-22: the
musical ``Starting Here, Starting Now.'' Sept. 10-26: the comedy
``Grace and Glory.'' Oct. 8-24: the musical ``Shenandoah.''
Rockingham Theatre at Market Place on Court Square. 540-564-1988.
</P>
<P>
   -- Wayside Theatre, Middletown: Professional theater for 37
years. Through Aug. 8: the comedy ``Perfect Wedding.'' Aug.
13-Sept. 5: the musical ``Quilters.'' Oct. 1-25: the mystery
``Mousetrap.'' 1-800-951-1776.
</P>
<P>
   -- Luray Caverns ``Inchiversary,'' Luray, Aug. 13: Special
events, including a Grand Illumination, commemorate the caverns'
discovery Aug. 13, 1878, and the 1-inch growth of its stalactites
and stalagmites in the past 120 years. 540-743-6551, Ext. 223, or
www.luraycaverns.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rockingham County Fair, Harrisonburg, Aug. 17-22:
Agricultural fair with exhibits in homemaking, farm crops,
horticulture, poultry, rabbits and cattle along with country,
gospel and bluegrass music. 540-434-0005.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rockbridge Community Festival, Lexington, Aug. 29: Street
fair features arts and crafts, food and music on Main Street.
540-464-9463.
</P>
<P>
   -- Antiques Show and Sale, Middletown, Sept. 5-6: Quality
antique vendors sell their wares at historic Belle Grove
Plantation. 540-869-2028.
</P>
<P>
   -- Edinburg Ole Time Festival, Edinburg, Sept. 18-20: Music,
clogging, food, parade and rubber duck race on the Shenandoah
River, plus antique tractors, engines and motorcycles.
540-984-8521.
</P>
<P>
   -- 10th Annual African-American Heritage Festival, Staunton,
Sept. 19-20: Music, dance, food, arts, books and history.
540-332-3972.
</P>
<P>
   -- Apple Harvest Arts and Crafts Festival, Winchester, Sept.
19-20: Arts and crafts, food, live entertainment and lots of
apples. 1-800-662-1360.
</P>
