</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHENANDOAH-TOUR-COX     07-30 1934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHENANDOAH-TOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stonewall's Shenandoah: In the General's footsteps
 &HT;    (EMBARGOEDC UNTIL AUGUST 2: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The distance from Lexington, Va., in the southern reaches of the
Shenandoah Valley, north to Winchester is about 130 miles _ a
three-hour drive through small towns along U.S. 11, somewhat less
if you zoom along I-81. But why rush?
</P>
<P>
   We spent six days in the valley earlier this summer and almost
missed our flight home from Richmond because there was so much to
take in _ so many interesting detours.
</P>
<P>
   So many sites related to Lt. Gen. Thomas J. ``Stonewall''
Jackson, we started to feel like instant Stonewall scholars. Here's
a little of the history we learned:
</P>
<P>
   Lexington
</P>
<P>
   -- Stonewall Jackson Home: The modest green-shuttered red brick
house on East Washington Street, just up hill from the Lexington
Visitors Center, is the only residence Jackson ever owned. By all
accounts, he spent his happiest years here with his wife, Anna,
while teaching at Virginia Military Institute, from early 1859
until he rode off to war April 21, 1861, never to return.
</P>
<P>
   A tour of the National Historic Landmark house documents the
life of the bearded, tight-lipped Jackson _ a man hard to imagine
with a smile on his face. But in this domestic setting, the
brilliant military leader comes to life as a professor, devout
Christian, church leader, businessman and loving husband. You'll
see the study where Jackson stood to prepare his lessons at an
upright desk, the dining room where he conducted Bible study and
prayer before breakfast each morning and the parlor where he
visited with his wife by the fire at night. The neat-as-a-pin house
and carefully tended garden in the back reflect Jackson's desire
for order. After his death, Anna and their daughter left Lexington
and returned to her native North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, 1-5 p.m. Sundays. 540-463-2552.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stonewall Jackson Memorial Cemetery: Don't be surprised if
you see lemons scattered around the Stonewall Jackson Monument and
Jackson's grave. A wreath of lemons was placed at the grave on
Memorial Day. His admirers honor him with the fruit because it
seems Jackson frequently sucked lemons to relieve a cronic stomach
ailment _ even on the battlefield. The bronze statue of Jackson was
erected in 1891 atop a granite base. Jackson's tomb is beneath the
monument, surrounded by a six-chambered burial vault containing
family members.
</P>
<P>
   540-463-2552.
</P>
<P>
   -- VMI Museum: On the lower level of Jackson Memorial Hall on
the VMI campus, where he taught for a decade before the war, is
where you'll find his preserved horse. ``Little Sorrel is central
to the museum _ both figuratively and physically,'' says director
Keith Gibson. ``It compresses history for folks when they think
that horse was an eyewitness to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally named Fancy, the dumpy, rather homely little horse
was anything but. Yet, the calm, easy-gaited beast with remarkable
stamina served Jackson well. Little Sorrel died in 1886, at age 36,
at the Robert E. Lee Camp for Confederate Veterans in Richmond,
having been exhibited at countless Southern fairs in his postwar
years. After preparation by a taxidermist, Sorrel was initially
displayed at Lee Camp but moved to VMI in 1948 when the camp
closed. A janitor, assigned to place a bucket of water in the glass
case where Sorrel was originally housed to maintain humidity,
reportedly quipped he was the only man in the world whose job it
was to water a dead horse.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jackson items include the blue wool VMI faculty uniform he
sported at the First Battle of Manassas on July 21, 1861; the
bullet-pierced raincoat he wore when he was mortally wounded while
sitting atop his horse at Chancellorsville; the slouch hat he
favored over the standard-issue caps; and the field desk he used
throughout the war. These and other exhibits at Virginia's oldest
museum tell the story of the nation's first state-supported
military college, founded in 1839.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, 2-5 p.m. Sundays. Free.
540-464-7232.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Stonewall Country'': Jackson's life before and during the
Civil War, recalled with battle scenes, stories and music, has been
the centerpiece at Theater at Lime Kiln in Lexington for 14 years.
Unfortunately, the show was not in production when we visited. But
we bought tickets to a Sunday night concert with Nathan and the
Zydeco Cha Chas just to experience the rough-hewn ambience of the
amphitheater built amid the stone ruins of an old lime kiln, with
bare earth for a stage and the fragrance of honeysuckle in the air.
</P>
<P>
   $11 Tuesdays-Thursdays; $16 Fridays and Saturdays. Through Aug.
15. The Sunday night concert series continues through Sept. 6.
540-463-3074 (Web site is www.cfw.com/limekiln).
</P>
<P>
   Dayton
</P>
<P>
   -- Shenandoah Valley Folk Art &AMP; Heritage Center: Somewhat off
the beaten path, this museum in Dayton, south of Harrisonburg, is
worth finding _ not only for its exhibits on the folk art and
culture of the valley but for the electric floor-to-ceiling map
that lights up to pinpoint Jackson's moves during the Valley
Campaign as a 20-minute taped narration details the action. The map
provides a graphic overview of Jackson's ``mislead and surprise''
strategy that kept Union forces on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: If you're in the area on a Thursday, Friday or Saturday,
drop by the Dayton Farmers Market on Va. 42. It's a vast emporium
filled with locally grown produce and fresh meats and seafood,
handcrafted gifts, baked goods, cheeses, gourmet coffees and a
country restaurant (540-879-9885).
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays and Wednesdays-Saturdays, 1-5 p.m.
Sundays. $4. Take I-81 Exit 245, then west on Port Republic Road,
left on Va. 42 and right on County Road 732. 540-879-
</P>
<P>
   2681.
</P>
<P>
   New Market
</P>
<P>
   -- New Market Battlefield Military Museum: Although Jackson was
dead by the time of the May 15, 1864, Battle of New Market _ during
which the outnumbered Confederate army and VMI cadets defeated
Union troops _ his earlier defense of the valley help lay the
groundwork for victory. Plan to spend at least an hour winding
through the labyrinthian exhibit hall past 130 illuminated and
well-organized displays highlighting not only the Battle of New
Market but the entire Civil War and American military history from
1750 to the present. A Jackson family Bible and a piece of the
uniform the general was wearing when he was mortally wounded are
among the more than 3,000 artifacts assembled by Civil War
collector John Bracken. Catch the half-hour film on the Civil War
and take the self-guided battlefield tour that begins on the museum
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned by Bracken (``I personally chased all these
things down,'' he says), this 10-year-old museum is not affiliated
with the close-by state historical park and the Hall of Valor,
although both are on the battle site.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily through Dec. 15. $6. Follow signs from I-81,
Exit 264. 540-
</P>
<P>
   740-8065.
</P>
<P>
   -- New Market Battlefield State Historical Park and Virginia
Military Insitute Hall of Valor Civil War Museum: Don't miss the
film ``Stonewall's Valley,'' depicting the daring 1862 campaign
that spared the valley and saved Richmond from occupation by
Federal troops. Exhibits include dioramas, photo murals and
artifacts. Admission includes the 19th century Bushong farmstead,
used as a hospital after the Bushong's orchard was turned into a
battlefield. Scenic pathways lead to bluffs high above the
Shenandoah River.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily. $5 adults; $2 ages 6-15; 5 and under free.
Follow signs all the way to the end of County Road 305 from I-81
Exit 264. 540-740-3101.
</P>
<P>
   Stratsburg
</P>
<P>
   -- Stonewall Jackson Museum at Hupp's Hill Battlefield Park: The
original section of the rustic museum is a 1750s split log
structure that was part of the George F. Hupp estate on the
outskirts of Strasburg. From outside the museum, note the trenches
from the 1864 Battle of Cedar Creek and fabulous views of the town,
Massanutten Mountain and the valley. Inside, immerse yourself in
the brilliant military strategist who ``won simply because he would
not lose,'' says director Patrick Heelen. ``Failure was not an
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's victorious 1862 campaign _ spurred by what Heelan
calls ``an overriding sense of duty and purpose'' _ is explored
through a wonderful jumble of artifacts, more than 100 photographs
of Jackson and interpretive materials that depict him as a devout
Christian and staunch patriot. While not as polished as the New
Market museums, it successfully chronicles Jackson's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's emphasis on interactive learning also sets it
apart. Visitors can handle reproductions of Civil War weapons,
uniforms, saddles and toys. Children can visit a hands-on room
where they can try on period costumes, climb into a soldier's tent,
hop on wooden horses complete with cavalry saddles and bridles, and
dig through ``Discovery Boxes'' filled with games, puzzles and
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, noon-5 p.m. Sundays. $3
adults; $2 for seniors and children; free for children under 6.
33229 Old Valley Pike. 540-465-
</P>
<P>
   5884.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester
</P>
<P>
   -- Stonewall Jackson's Headquarters Museum: Actress Mary Tyler
Moore's great-grandfather owned the striking 1854 Hudson River
Gothic Revival-style house on Braddock Street in Winchester _ but
that's not its primary claim to fame. Lt. Col. Lewis T. Moore's
house served as Jackson's headquarters in Winchester during the
winter of 1861-62. Restored and furnished by the local historical
society, the house contains artifacts from Jackson, calvary officer
Gen. Turner Ashby, mapmaker Jedediah Hotchkiss and other
Confederates. Among the memorabilia is Ashby's revolver and
Jackson's prayer book _ he was a Presbyterian _ and camp table.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, noon-4 p.m. Sundays. Through
October. $3.50 adults; $1.75 children. 415 N. Braddock St.
540-667-3242.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shenandoah Valley Civil War Center: The center's permanent
exhibition, ``Shenandoah: Crossroads of the Confederacy, The Role
of Virginia's Valley 1861-1865,'' provides an excellent orientation
to the region's Civil War history. Located in the Kurtz building in
the heart of Old Winchester, the center offers an overview of 15
military engagements and a summary of Jackson's campaign. This is
also a good place to stock up on brochures on Civil War sites and
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, noon-5 p.m. Sundays. Free. N.
Cameron St. 540-722-6367.
</P>
<P>
   Epilogue
</P>
<P>
   -- Stonewall's Arm: The general's amputated left arm didn't come
home to the Shenandoah Valley for burial with the rest of his body.
The limb is interred at a farm 15 miles west of Fredericksburg.
Jackson's chaplain, the Rev. Beverly Tucker Lacy, claimed the arm
and buried it in the cemetery at Ellwood, his family's home. The
granite marker at the grave reads ``Arm of Stonewall Jackson. May
3, 1863.'' Upon hearing of his trusted lieutenant's grave injury,
Gen. Robert E. Lee is quoted as saying, ``He has lost his left arm;
but I have lost my right arm.'' Jackson died of pneumonia seven
days later.
</P>
<P>
   Open daily. From Fredericksburg, take Va. 3 west through
Chancellorsville, then left on County Road 20, and look for gravel
road on left that leads to Ellwood. 540-373-6122 (National Park
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
