<HEADER>
A0990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANHALEN-COX     07-30 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANHALEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Van Halen III
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA-- These are the times that try the souls of Van Halen
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ones who, after a long and blustery 11 years _ an epoch
in rock 'n' roll time _ had finally gotten used to Sammy Hagar, the
band's iron-tonsiled Big Kahuna, the guy who couldn't ``drive 55''
(as his signature tune declared), yet surprisingly sustained the
group after the 1985 departure of its original vocalist, David Lee
Roth. The foppish ``Diamond Dave'' had given this quintessential
1970s L.A. hard-rock act an outrageously animated visual presence
to match guitarist Eddie Van Halen's innovative, and much emulated,
``hammer-on'' technique. But his ego and the lure of an initially
promising solo career dispatched him on a path that eventually led
to ... uh, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hagar, too, is back in solo-land. And like one of those
former Soviet states that retires the party bosses and summons
fresh blood to the seat of power, Van Halen has a new lead singer _
Gary Cherone, of the popular (and now defunct) ``hair'' band
Extreme _ and some controversy on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   Behold! There is much wailing and gnashing of teeth among the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave was awesome because he was a showman and a rocker,'' fan
Mike Schlenk opines on his Web site, ``Mike Schlenk's Personal Van
Halen Memorium'' (http://www.qni.com
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)schlenk/vh/), a page devoted both to Schlenk's VH
obsession (``It's a religion to me'') and his disappointment at the
band's latest edition. ``VH then matured a little with Sammy but it
continued to rock. Sammy is a ... rock star (despite his latest
album). He sang about female body parts and sandy beaches, but he
could be honest and heartfelt too. This latest album (``Van Halen
III,'' as in Mach 3) makes me think maybe the boys are
concentrating on being mature rather than being crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Van Halen couldn't give a flip. Which is, after all, how
it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a gas; the shows are great!'' says the
43-year-old guitarist, who joins the band tonight at Lakewood
Amphitheatre for a concert that will flaunt Cherone's new status
but will also survey Roth-era tunes unheard in a decade of tours.
``All the skeptical naysayers, after they see us live, they're not
thinking of Roth or Sammy after the show. There were some hard-core
Roth fans that even said, `Boy, was I wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   Van Halen's confidence persists despite not-so-great record
sales of the March release of ``III,'' which the musician happily
admits was a departure for the 24-year-old act. ``It starts off
with a waltz and ends up with me singing! To me, that's what rock
'n' roll has always been about,'' Van Halen says in his gruff,
early-afternoon voice.
</P>
<P>
   The band's audience, however, has been slow to acknowledge this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, fans face an interesting challenge,'' says Gene
Romano, national director of rock programming for Jacor
Communications, which owns more than 200 radio stations nationwide,
of which 40 are rock stations (including Atlanta's WKLS-FM). ``The
band is perceptibly competing against past band-singer
permutations. Early listener reaction has not been terrific. It may
take awhile for fans to warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   Although two tracks from the album promoted for radio play
achieved brief Top 20 playlist status, and a third _ ``One I Want''
_ is on the way, the tunes aren't bulldozing the airwaves as in Van
Halen's previous incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio in L.A. won't even play us,'' Van Halen says. ``After 20
years! There's not one radio station in our hometown that will play
us. We don't fit their format. We're a rock 'n' roll band, a little
square peg trying to fit into this Spice pothole.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Eddie bitter? Heck, no! He's bemused.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you be, too? If you were married to actress Valerie
Bertinelli and your 7-year-old boy Wolfgang (a.k.a. ``Wolfie'') was
already getting some whammy out of the custom-made miniature guitar
you gave him? If you got to spend every summer, like, totally
rocking America? And, for once, with a hassle-free front man?
</P>
<P>
   ``The (other) three of us were always arguing with the singer,''
Van Halen says. ``I used to wonder, are all singers like this?
What's the deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed reviews and middle age have done nothing to temper the
guitarist's enthusiasm. ``I swear I don't feel it,'' he says.
``It's all frame of mind, too. Last tour, I was on crutches with my
hip. I haven't had the operation yet (for a condition called
vascular necrosis) and I'm jumping around like a maniac. The top of
my hip joint is dead bone and, this is very rare, it's coming back
to life. I cut out the booze, I'm eating healthy, working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me all the time,'' he says, about the band's rowdy
reputation in the '70s, ``and I say it's 99 percent the way it is
now as when we were the so-called `America's premier party band.'
We got pigeonholed.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Guns N' Roses came along to fill the slot in the 1980s
_ right?
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the biggest thing since sliced bread,'' Van Halen
says, reflecting on a group that now consists of its lead singer _
Axl Rose _ and hasn't released a new album in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess bread beat 'em out.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The new set list:
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually had to go out and buy our first record and learn
`I'm the One.' I hadn't played it in 20 years. `Hot for Teacher,'
`Dance the Night Away,' `Romeo Delight,' `Jamie's Crying' ...''
</P>
<P>
   -- The hyper-drive school of guitar: ``I play kind of weird;
it's just the way I play. A lot of people still think that I want
to do a guitar record. Just guitar. If I actually did a solo
record, people would really freak because there probably wouldn't
be guitar on it. There'd be piano, cello. I love playing cello, and
rhythmic stuff. I'm actually more of a rhythm guitarist than I am a
soloist.''
</P>
<P>
   -- His favorite album: ``I love Peter Gabriel. The last record I
bought was `So.' I don't know how long ago that was. The guy moves
me. Gives me goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Musical choices: ``Roth used to say, `Nobody wants to see you
playing piano; you're a guitar hero.' I said, `If I want to play
tuba, I'll damn well do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   -- Why he's not a guitar hero: ``I don't wear a mask. I don't
have a cape. What is that? I take it as a compliment, but it's
pretty funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
