<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIPHOP-GUIDE-COX     07-30 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-GUIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hip Hop: The evolution of a genre
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though the artist known as Tricky rejects the label, the term
``trip-hop'' has been applied not only to his rumbling,
post-apocalyptic update of the blues, but to nearly anything coming
out of his hometown of Bristol, England.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, when the musical collective Massive Attack formed in
that western English city, the genre has been freely evolving. Its
soundscapes, whether complex or stripped raw, draw on several
sources:
</P>
<P>
   -- The American hip-hop culture.
</P>
<P>
   -- The longer tradition of Jamaican ``sound systems'' _ marathon
parties with dozens of performers, including DJs, rappers,
vocalists, turntables and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   -- And the reggae variant known as dub, often eccentric or
extreme instrumental remixes of songs that can be at once hermetic
and psychedelic (putting the ``trip'' in trip-hop).
</P>
<P>
   Massive Attack's 1991 album ``Blue Lines'' established the genre
and introduced listeners to Tricky, Geoff Barrow (who later founded
the band Portishead) and Nellee Hooper (probably best known for
production work on Madonna's ``Bedtime Stories''). The current
edition of the group is touring behind a new album, ``Mezzanine,''
and plays Sept. 6 at the Roxy.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky's breakthrough was the 1995 album ``Maxinquaye,'' named
after his late mother, Maxine Quaye. The album's dense, congested
sound is a Tricky signature, as are convoluted nods to rap
inspirations (an inside-out remake of Public Enemy's ``Black Steel
in the Hour of Chaos,'' for instance).
</P>
<P>
   Portishead is the only trip-hop-affiliated act to come close to
a commercial hit in the United States. ``Sour Times (Nobody Loves
Me),'' from its 1994 debut ``Dummy,'' with its somnambulant vibe
and spy movie motifs, was an ideal mope-fest for coffeehouse
melancholics everywhere. Vocalist Beth Gibbons conveyed a raw
soulfulness, however, that stirred emotion beneath the song's hip
veneer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BUFFALO-COX     07-30 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BUFFALO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Buffalo' roams but remains lost
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills and Buffalo-born Billy Brown (Vincent Gallo)
have more in common than a hometown. Billy's whole life has been
shaped by the football team. He was born the day the Bills played a
crucial game, something for which his fanatical Bills-loving mother
(Anjelica Huston) has never forgiven him. As a young adult, he made
a foolish, losing bet on the Bills. Unable to pay off his bookie
(Mickey Rourke), he was forced to confess to a crime he didn't
commit, thus landing in prison for five years.
</P>
<P>
   If all of ``Buffalo 66'' worked on this level of insistent,
loopy absurdity, it would be terrific. Unfortunately, Gallo _ a
former Calvin Klein underwear model and sometime actor, making his
writing-directing debut _ doesn't just want us to laugh at Billy's
predicament. He wants us to feel for Billy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we meet our skanky, bedraggled protagonist the day he gets
out of prison. For reasons never made clear _ or, perhaps, never
made credible _ he decides to visit his parents (Huston and Ben
Gazzara), zoned-out suburbanites who barely gave him the time of
day when they were raising him. En route, he drops by a tap-dancing
class and abducts a voluptuous blond teenager (Christina Ricci).
Her assignment: to pose as his wife during the visit.
</P>
<P>
   So far, not so bad. Huston and Gazzara are chillingly zany, she
with her outsized Bills obsession, he with his lounge-singer
fantasies. But once the young pair leave home, they have nowhere to
go. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66'' is all over the place. It's self-pitying and
sardonic, arty and maudlin. Gallo's appeal on-screen is a matter of
personal taste. Apparently he's something of a hipster's darling,
but he struck me as whiningly one-note. Still, give him credit for
recognizing talent in others. Gazzara and Huston create
etched-in-acid, quick-sketch caricatures. Ricci, meanwhile, takes
full command of a role that's not just underwritten, but unwritten.
A mournful little tap dance in a deserted bowling alley makes no
sense whatsoever in Gallo's script, but it makes all kinds of sense
in Ricci's capable hands (and feet).
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vincent Gallo and Christina Ricci. Directed by Gallo.
Not rated, but contains strong language, graphic violence and
nudity. At Tara. 1 hour, 46 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Don't shuffle off to this ``Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BASE-COX     07-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BASE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to have a ball, `South Park' style
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big lizard and the giant asteroid let us down. So thank
heaven for the rude boys of summer. In the wake of the Farrelly
brothers and ``There's Something About Mary,'' here come ``South
Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone in another zesty,
disgusting, laugh-out-loud comedy.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``BASEketball,'' and though the guys didn't write
it, their anarchic, tacky spirit comes through in every scene.
That's because it's directed and co-written by David Zucker, who
paved the way for anything-goes, taste-defying humor with
``Airplane!'' and the ``Naked Gun'' flicks back when Parker and
Stone were still pooping their pants. (Given their sense of humor,
that might not have been so long ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone play Coop and Remer, two slackers who invent a
hybrid of baseball and basketball in their driveway. Basically,
it's designed to be as un-strenuous as possible. Five years later,
it's a national sport, complete with mock-up garage-front playing
field and barely dressed cheerleaders. The rules: Score base runs
by shooting hoops. When the other team is up, the challenge is to
psych out rival players to make them flub their shots. (Prime
psych-outs include I-slept-with-your-mama jokes, or putting a
player to sleep by playing a books-on-tape parody of ``The Horse
Whisperer.'')
</P>
<P>
   As the boys play around the country, the movie takes swipes at
various cities. In San Francisco, for instance, the cheerleaders
are buff, shirtless men. Here, Parker parodies a Foster's beer
commercial, climaxing with a bared rear, and yells, ``That wasn't a
gay joke, that was an Australian joke!''
</P>
<P>
   That's debatable. ``BASEketball'' manages to be racist, sexist,
homophobic and just about everything else. But it does so in a way
that kiddingly tweaks the very notion of political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Take Yasmine Bleeth, who plays the guys' dream girl and the
director of the Dream Come True foundation. Instead of calling her
kids ``terminally ill,'' she prefers ``health-challenged and
survival-impaired.'' One little boy with liver disease takes the
place of ``Mary's'' little dog as the target of extreme slapstick
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   So does ``Squeak'' (Dian Bachar), the fellows' diminutive pal,
also known as ``Little Bitch.'' Tossed around nearly as much as the
titular ball, Bachar gets a prime moment in ``BASEketball's''
gleeful spoof of movie cliches: When Coop and Remer have their
inevitable falling-out, Squeak gives them a hackneyed lecture about
sportsmanship ... while dressed as a giant pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, if it matters, has the boys struggling to keep
ownership of their team (the Beers) away from an evil businessman
(Robert Vaughn) and the sexpot widow (Jenny McCarthy) of the
original owner (Ernest Borgnine). Like much else in the movie, the
conflict is just a chance to throw in sight gags and allow Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, Bob Costas, Al Michaels and Robert Stack to tweak
their own images. And if you wonder what Kato Kaelin has been doing
lately, you'll find an answer here.
</P>
<P>
   ``BASEketball'' lives up to its title. It is base. It's also a
ball. But if you can live without the sight of male lactation, you
may want to sit this game out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
