<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUFFDADDY-COX     07-30 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUFFDADDY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Puff Daddy heads fest that also features R&AMP;B at the Georgia Dome
</P>
<P>
   By Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Two of the biggest names in pop music last year
finally make it to Atlanta this Saturday: Puffy and Missy.
</P>
<P>
   That's short for Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs and Missy
``Misdemeanor'' Elliott, both longtime million-selling producers
who made it to the top of the charts in 1997 when they finally
debuted as rappers. They are among the most anticipated performers
in the 10-act Budweiser Superfest at the Georgia Dome, which is
expected to last at least six hours and draw tens of thousands of
fans.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Puffy and Missy are no longer on every other song
you hear and in just about every video you see _ a slam that was
thrown Puffy's way at one point. But they continue to be major
influences in pop music and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   While Combs has had the No. 1 rap single nationally for the past
month _ ``Come With Me,'' a song from the ``Godzilla'' soundtrack
featuring Jimmy Page _ it gets little airplay on Atlanta's urban
radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   The song probably isn't in heavy rotation on R&AMP;B and rap
stations because of its rock backdrop, says Jermaine Dupri, Atlanta
producer, rapper and label president and Combs' friend and peer.
``But Puffy himself is kind of cooling out now, doing his thing
behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes scenes in an untitled Oliver Stone movie in which
Combs, 28, will make his film debut as a football player. Filming
for the project, which will include Al Pacino, begins in September.
(Combs supposedly got his nickname when he was a high school
football player; teammates said the thin teenager would often
``puff out'' his chest to look bigger.)
</P>
<P>
   Combs also has plans for Atlanta. He and LaFace Records
co-President Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid plan to open Justin's, a
Caribbean-themed restaurant, in mid-September in the former Coco
Pazzo location on Peachtree Road. It will be the second spot Combs
has launched and named for his 4-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to call me a rapper or whatever, but I consider
myself an entertainer, and I want to be involved in all of the
various forms of entertainment,'' said Combs, whose manager, Benny
Medina, helped guide Will Smith from music to movies as well.
``Atlanta is like home for me,'' continues Combs, a Harlem native,
who did not bring his ``No Way Out'' tour to Atlanta last year
because the city lacked a suitable venue. (The Omni had been
demolished and the Hawks monopolized the Dome.) His decision to
skip Atlanta prompted local radio stations V-103 and Hot 97.5 to
circulate petitions to bring the tour here. The effort failed, but
it didn't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's some love, man,'' Combs remarked. ``And I can't wait to
get back onstage and return that love to my fans in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's first public performance here, meanwhile, will be one
of the last she'll do anywhere for some time. The 25-year-old has
spent the first half of her summer as the lone hip-hop act on the
Lilith Fair tour. That was time the lyricist (for Mariah Carey,
Aaliyah and SWV) could have spent on projects for Whitney Houston,
R&AMP;B trio Total, the ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?'' soundtrack and
her own new label, Gold Mind Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad she's got my project out of the way,'' said Nicole
Wray (``Make It Hot''), 17, the first artist on Elliott's roster.
``Because she's got so much on her plate now I'd have to think I
would be standing in line behind Whitney or Scary Spice,'' with
whom Elliott has recorded the first ``Fools'' single.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missy is like my idol,'' added Da Brat, the first female
rapper to sell a million records. ``I mean she just keeps coming
with the hits, for herself, and whoever can afford her these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Budweiser Superfest
</P>
<P>
   With Puff Daddy, Mase, Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott, LSG and
others.
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. Saturday. Georgia Dome, 1 Georgia Dome Drive N.W. $40.75,
$45.75 and $52.75.
</P>
<P>
   The Budweiser Superfest rounds up some of today's most popular
rap and rhythm-and-blues acts. A rundown:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sean ``Puffy'' Combs: Producer, rapper and two-time Grammy
Award winner. Has two singles on Billboard's rap Top 10: ``Come
With Me'' (at No. 1 for the fifth week) and ``Lookin' at Me,'' with
the million-selling rapper Mase.
</P>
<P>
   -- Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott: The mass appeal of this
producer-rapper's hits for herself (``The Rain'') and others has
made her a Gap and Sprite spokeswoman and put her in Whitney
Houston's stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dru Hill: The quartet (``In My Bed'') that has stepped in as
the gospel-tinged, gritty R&AMP;B act while Jodeci is away.
</P>
<P>
   -- Montell Jordan: Just when the R&AMP;B singer thought ``This Is
How We Do It'' would be his biggest single, ``Let's Ride,'' with
Master P, put him back on the road to No. 1 status.
</P>
<P>
   -- K-Ci and Jo Jo: Jodeci's lead singers venture out on their
own and away from the previous R&AMP;B act's more promiscuous lyrics
(``All My Life'').
</P>
<P>
   -- Lil' Kim: Rap's million-selling equivalent to Madonna back
when the Material Girl was posing naked for ``Sex'' and wearing
bras as tops.
</P>
<P>
   -- LSG: Established crooners Gerald Levert, Keith Sweat and
Johnny Gill succeed at appealing to the young.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mase: Monotone, slow-talking rapper made his way quickly into
prominence alongside Puff Daddy (``Can't Nobody Hold Me Down'').
</P>
<P>
   -- 112: Atlanta quartet touted as the gentlemen on the Bad Boy
label. Best known for their vulnerable ballads (``Cupid'').
</P>
<P>
   -- Timbaland: One of urban music's most forward-thinking
producers. Tim ``Timbaland'' Mosely often sets Missy's lyrics to
music.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
