<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER31-COX     07-30 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visual ``Lolita'' not as good as the book
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some books are just good at being books. They aren't cut out for
synergy. Vladimir Nabokov's ``Lolita'' is a masterpiece _ it ranked
fourth on the Modern Library's recent list of this century's 100
best English language novels. A satiric, self-aware, lushly playful
roadtrip through the mind of a 37-year-old Englishman obsessed with
a 12-year-old American nymphet, Nabokov's ``Lolita'' spins its
tawdry subject into provocative art.
</P>
<P>
   The $58 million movie adaptation that arrives on pay cable's
Showtime (9 p.m. EDT Sunday) doesn't manage the same trick.
Directed by Adrian Lyne (``Fatal Attraction,'' ``9 1/2 Weeks''),
with Jeremy Irons as the obsessed Humbert, this ``Lolita'' is
smart, gorgeous, tastefully brave (sexy without any real sex) _but
finally a payoff-free crawl through a world a little too creepy to
take the time to watch.
</P>
<P>
   As a novel, ``Lolita's'' forbidden eroticism isn't always front
and center. What Nabokov's masterly hands created wasn't just a
voyeur's kick _ when the book was finally published in the U.S. in
1958 (four years after its Paris printing), those who thumbed
through it for the juicy parts quickly found themselves tangled in
the bramble of Nabokov's inspired alliteration.
</P>
<P>
   But this movie adaptation (which itself took two years to reach
wide U.S. distribution from Europe) keeps our eyes, like Humbert's,
always lurking for the chance peek: the bare midriff, the legs
bicycling in bed, the dress lifted just to there. It makes us
Humbert's accomplice, rather than the rapt listener we are in the
novel. It's ... creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Irons is practically perfect; with his lipless mouth and
eyelids that blink a half-moment after his every pathetic thought,
he totes a comic air of self-rebuke. A post-World War Two
continental, Humbert arrives at a New England town the summer
before he begins teaching at a college. He's soon greeted at the
house with a room for rent by Charlotte Haze (Melanie Griffith), a
man-hunting widow who runs it.
</P>
<P>
   Humbert is about to sprint from Charlotte _ or is it the
cartoon-like Griffith? _ when he spots her daughter Lolita
(15-year-old unknown Dominque Swain), who's getting nice and wet
under a lawn sprinkler. He stays.
</P>
<P>
   Swain is practically perfect herself. She's all antsy, random
hormones _ one minute a languid, sashaying coquette, the next
sticking gum under a dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   It's when ``Lolita'' turns on its own inherent unsavoriness that
watching it almost seems worthwhile. Like the moment early on when
Lolita bends over the back of a chair, in a classic Vargas girlie
pose, and leans in close to the pinned-to-his-seat Humbert. As he
holds his breath in agonized expectancy, Lolita purrs, ``Am I
getting a zit?''
</P>
<P>
   But as the movie takes its sweet time moving along, we feel less
and less like sharing in Humbert's fetish. When Lolita also catches
the perverted eye of Clare Quilty (Frank Langella), a kiddie-porn
lovin' playwright, we, like Lolita, are given a choice between
Creep and Creepier.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a movie this well done, not much of a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon, Cartoon
</P>
<P>
   Cartoon Network's viewership is on the rise. Nielsen ratings
between June 29 and July 26 show that the average number of
nationwide households tuned in to the channel all day jumped 42
percent to 581,000. And the number of kids age 6-11 watching in
prime time rose 69 percent to 327,000. Cartoon Network has been
airing its popular 'toons ``Dexter's Laboratory'' and ``Cow and
Chicken'' five nights a week. Both recently got Emmy nominations
for best animated series and will compete against ``The Simpsons''
and ``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   And the host is. . .
</P>
<P>
   There she is: Meredith Vieira, a moderator of ABC's daytime
talker ``The View,'' will co-host the Miss America pageant telecast
Sept. 19 on ABC. Her partner for the broadcast is football star
Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Bob Longino, Charles Haddad
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
