<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-COX     07-30 2066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When D-DAY hit home
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bedford, Va. -- What Lucille Boggess remembers most clearly
about D-Day is this: ``The dog howled all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggess was 15 on June 6, 1944, and the radio had been blaring
reports that thousands of Allied troops had stormed the beaches of
Normandy in faraway France.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents began to worry from the moment they learned that the
long-awaited invasion was on. They knew her two eldest brothers,
Bedford, 30, and Raymond Hoback, 24, were in Company A of the 116th
Regiment of the 29th Infantry Division. And in England.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents suspected, Boggess says today, that her brothers
were taking part in the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   They were. What the family wouldn't know until a month after
D-Day was that both had been killed within 15 minutes of hitting
the beach. And so had 19 other Bedford boys in Company A of the
116th, a federalized Virginia National Guard regiment.
</P>
<P>
   Boggess, now 69, believes her family's dog somehow sensed her
parents' fears. Whatever the cause, the plaintive cries certainly
marked an end to her easygoing, fun-loving way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford, then a bucolic village of 3,200 souls nestled beside
the Blue Ridge Mountains, would become synonymous with sacrifice.
Per capita, this picturesque burg lost more men on the beaches of
Normandy on D-Day than any other American village, town or city.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years later, many who remember the invasion have
died, and others have moved in. Yet World War II is still very much
a presence, and so Steven Spielberg's horrific D-Day saga, ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' is particularly resonant.
</P>
<P>
   The movie depicts the chaos and carnage among the 29th Division,
the first wave to hit what was code-named ``Omaha Beach.'' For
Boggess, it was hard to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sort of tried to insulate myself,'' she says. ``I
couldn't think of my brothers in something so terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggess, longtime revenue commissioner, serves on the board of
the National D-Day Memorial Foundation, created by Congress to
erect a $12 million memorial in Bedford to honor the 1,200
Americans who died in the invasion that day. The foundation relies
on donations; to date only about half the money has been collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the movie raises interest that will help raise money
for the D-Day monument,'' she says. ``I don't like war movies, but
this one may do some good. Spielberg will reach people who never
would have known.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the consensus around Bedford, a town too small
for a movie theater, where people have been talking about ``Private
Ryan'' and in some cases traveling the 30 miles west to Roanoke to
see it.
</P>
<P>
   One who did last Friday, in a special viewing for D-Day vets,
was Ray Nance, 84. As a first lieutenant in Company A, Nance was
wounded three times on Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie will be a good thing,'' he says, showing a visitor
French money and a $5 bill signed by some buddies on his landing
craft. ``The movie was the most realistic I've ever seen, but
still, nothing can come close to the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Stevens, 78, the only other living member of the 116th in
Bedford, went to the movie because he knew he'd be asked about it
and also to ``get people thinking about D-Day, before we're all
gone. People still go to Appomattox, and they should always
remember D-Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' twin brother, Ray, was one of the Bedford boys lost
that day. Stevens found out four days later, when he saw a cross
with dog tags tacked to it in a temporary graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had Ray's name on it,'' he says. ``Losing my twin, that was
terrible. I still think of him, but I don't dote. He's buried over
here at Longwood Cemetery. I don't think about it much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Many D-Day veterans echo that sentiment, but some say it's time
to speak, because their generation is disappearing fast. Of 5,000
men who landed with the 116th Regiment _ the successor to Stonewall
Jackson's fabled Civil War unit _ only about 200 are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Boggess says there are good reasons many WWII vets haven't
talked much about the war. Like the fictional Ryan, they wrestle
with the knowledge that many others died while they were saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of guilt,'' she says. ``So many died.
Those who lived felt funny, no matter how brave they were. And
people who stayed at home felt funny. Especially in Bedford. It
really wasn't until about 1984, the 40th anniversary, that D-Day
began to come into focus in this community, even though we had the
big 10-year anniversary event.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, 1954, thousands came for the dedication of a modest
D-Day monument made of granite carved from the caves of
Vierville-sur-mer, France, near where Company A went ashore. A
bronze plaque bears the names of the 21 Bedford men of Company A
who died, plus two in other units. The monument's significance is
evident in its prominent location _ directly in front of the town's
Confederate memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Boggess says the community seems split between those who know
about Bedford's sacrifice and those who don't know or don't care.
The reason: For years, it just wasn't discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people, just like the men, felt they had done what they
had to do, what anybody would do. It was only when we had the
anniversaries that people realized what an incredible price this
little tiny town paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the silence, she says, Bedford still hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a generation,'' she says, gesturing toward the 1954
monument. ``You can't take so many young men out of a town the size
of Bedford and not change it. It's hard to comprehend the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother felt that, she says, ``everyone needed to die a
little after losing her two boys. A part of her died when they did.
She sobbed and cried. My dad would go out to the barn and cry
alone. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom didn't want to go on outings again. Our outings
stopped. We stopped having fun. It was almost like she didn't want
life to continue, that it wasn't fair for us to have fun. It's
never been like it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph Gaston, pastor of Bedford Presbyterian Church,
found out fast that many Bedfordians seem deeply scarred by D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here a few years ago, I knew I needed to understand
the community,`` says Gaston, 39. ``I was sitting there with a
longtime member, and tears started streaming down her face when she
described what it was like when the rash of telegrams started
coming in. It was so terrible to her still, she said the greatest
thing to her was to go to a Presbyterian camp, where there were no
reminders. You could almost sense her own guilt that she felt good
to have a chance to get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a cloud hanging over the community when 50
years later, people still cry about it,'' Gaston says, looking at a
D-Day poster in the city museum. ``The town is healing, but it's
not quite healed.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggess hopes the movie may help with the healing and that the
dedication of the national memorial, planned for June 6, 2000, will
too. Both can help older residents come to terms with the memories.
</P>
<P>
   Both can also educate younger people about the community's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a generation, mine, that was profoundly affected,''
Boggess says. ``Then we had a generation that grew up in the shadow
of it. And a lot of people in the younger group now don't know much
about it at all. That's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Saunders, a 17-year-old college freshman, complains he
hasn't been taught much about World War II, let alone Bedford's
sacrifice at D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense I have to learn about D-Day in a
movie,'' he says. ``It was talk all my life about Vietnam. My dad's
generation wanted to forget World War II because of Vietnam, to
forget about war.''
</P>
<P>
   Bedford Museum director Ellen Wandrei, 50, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd bet you'd find that most kids here are clueless about
D-Day,'' says the former teacher and mother of two grown sons, one
a member of the 116th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an adult before I learned one of my uncles helped
liberate Dachau. He didn't talk about things and people didn't ask.
My peers had Vietnam and people didn't want to think about war.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gross, 61, Bedford's city manager, says there's always been
a kind of gentleman's agreement not to dwell on Bedford's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some level, it's always been on people's minds,'' he says.
``I don't think Bedford has gotten over it. It's like the red soil,
it's just there _ D-Day. It's like it's just below the surface. It
hurts too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Teass, 75, knew almost all the Bedford boys who died.
As the town's telegraph operator, she got the first word of the
D-Day disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from Roanoke _ `casualties coming.' I don't know how
many it was, maybe five or seven at first. And then they just kept
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   After that muggy summer, she muses, Bedford changed. ``People
didn't talk as much on the streets. It became a calm, quiet, sad
town. Everything was different. It's mighty sad when a community so
small gets hit so hard. I hope it never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggess says she's gotten over the hurt as much as she ever
will, but she'll never forget the dreadful summer of '44.
</P>
<P>
   She was a teenager, anticipating seeing her friends at Sunday
church services, when the county sheriff pulled into the driveway
of her family's farmhouse five weeks after D-Day. The sheriff
delivered the telegram that said her brother Bedford had been
killed at D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, it seemed, all of Center Point Methodist
Church, right across the street, was in our front yard,'' she
recalls. ``Everybody was crying and hugging.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, the sheriff returned. This time he handed her
parents a telegram saying that her brother Raymond had disappeared
at Omaha Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some men later told me he was shot,'' she says. ``He got shot
at low tide. They said his wounds weren't mortal, but at high tide
he washed out to sea, and his body was never found.''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to visit brother Bedford's grave in September when
about 40 local folks travel to Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   Nance won't be going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll go sometime, by myself, with my family,'' he
ponders, staring at a yard-long faded photo of Company A hanging on
a hallway wall. ``I'd want to see where I went in, where I looked
up at that church steeple. But I don't want to go with a crowd.
It's too personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nance's combat career began and ended on D-Day. His wounds, just
below his lip near his throat, in his right foot and his trigger
finger, took months to mend, and the war ended before he could be
shipped to the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   He and other surviving members of the 116th Regiment often talk
in the present tense about their experiences, instantly recalling
names of men they haven't seen since 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Nance points to a faded photo in his hallway. ``There, that's
John Wilkes. He was killed. Leslie Abbot there was klled. And
Elmere Wright was killed. John D. Clifton. Frank Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's Overstreet. He made it. Jack Powers was killed.
Gillaspie, Nick I think it was, got it. Here I am. I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Stevens, who flies Old Glory in his front yard every day,
hasn't decided yet if he's going to France with the Bedford group.
He last saw his brother Ray early on the morning of D-Day when the
two men, both platoon leaders, headed for separate landing craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray stuck his hand out, wanting me to shake it, and I reminded
him we'd agreed to meet on the beach,'' Stevens said. ``But that
didn't happen. He'd told me a couple of times he didn't think he'd
make it. Maybe he knew. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A medic told me Ray was shot with machine-gun fire. I didn't
believe it. I couldn't believe it. We'd bought 136 acres and were
going to farm it together. I farm it now, but he never got the
chance. He never had kids and grandkids like me and never had a
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The war ended for Stevens on June 30, when he was hit by
shrapnel a few miles away from the beach at Ste.-Lo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain,'' he says. ``I miss Ray. Always have. But
I'm not bitter like I was at first. I liked to got killed trying to
get revenge for Ray. But you can't. You just have to go on. Ray and
I had big plans. It just didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom has its cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
