A1010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-ELECTION-NYT     07-30 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUN SEN SAYS KING SIHANOUK HAS APPROVED COALITION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ Cambodia's leader, Hun Sen, offered
Thursday to form a three-way coalition government with his chief
rivals as additional returns in the parliamentary election on
Sunday appeared to confirm his predictions of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen spoke after meeting with King Norodom Sihanouk in the
ancient capital of Siem Reap and said the king had approved his
plan to share power with Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who is the
king's son, and Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
   The two men said it was premature to talk of coalitions. Both
have filed official protests contending that Hun Sen stole the
election and both have threatened to boycott the new Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Both are also bitter enemies of Hun Sen, who staged a coup a
year ago and ousted Ranariddh, leader of the FUNCINPEC royalist
party, as his partner in a previous coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy charges that Hun Sen was trying to kill him in March
1996 when four grenades were thrown at a rally he was holding,
killing 16 people and wounding more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   Although most foreign election monitors coordinated by the
United Nations endorsed the conduct of the election, reports began
accumulating Thursday that supporters of the opposition were facing
threats and intimidation now that the election was over and foreign
observers were leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations and an independent monitoring group
called the Asian Network for Free Elections reported that dozens of
opposition members had fled to the capital from provincial towns
and villages where they were being threatened with reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Thomas Hammarberg, the U.N. human
rights envoy to Cambodia, voiced concern. ``It is very important
that the political leadership make very clear they will take a
strong stance against attempts to settle scores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen, who heads the Cambodian People's Party, is leading in
the slow vote count. But it appears certain that he will need to
form a coalition with at least one of his rivals in order to reach
the two-thirds of Parliament's 122 seats that are needed to create
a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spoke to his majesty the king about the possibility of
having a coalition government between the CPP, FUNCINPEC and Sam
Rainsy,'' Hun Sen said as he left Siem Reap for Phnom Penh. ``His
majesty the king was pleased with the idea and would like to see
cooperation between the three parties in a coalition government,
giving a favorable atmosphere for national reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading independent poll-watch group, the Committee for Free
and Fair Elections, projected Thursday that the Cambodian People's
Party would win 59 seats, while FUNCINPEC was projected to win 45.
Sam Rainsy's party, which bears the name of the candidate, was
projected to win 18.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary official results were not expected until this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we have not yet received the result we cannot say
anything about a coalition,'' Ranariddh said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the coalition offer ``premature,'' Sam Rainsy's party
issued a statement saying, ``If reports of irregularities and
electoral fraud are resolved, and the results of the elections are
shown to be valid, then we will accept those results and consider
our position on the formation of a coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   One Western diplomat was skeptical that a three-way coalition
could survive the stresses of the personal animosities and clashing
ambitions of the men involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is precisely the volatility of Hun Sen, the fickleness of
the prince and the provocativeness of Sam Rainsy that would make
this difficult to sustain,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen's offer laid out his bargaining position for a possible
coalition, reserving the political plums for himself. ``I can say
clearly that as prime minister I have the right to choose five
important ministries for the CPP _ defense, interior, justice,
finance and foreign affairs,'' he said. He also proposed that Chea
Sim, the president of his own party, remain as chairman of the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy could become deputy
prime ministers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
