<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLESSI-ART-REVIEW-520     07-30 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLESSI-ART-REVIEW-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FABRIZIO PLESSI': A LIVELY BEGINNING TO A NEW SERIES ON MEDIA ART
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Exhibition notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Using the pompous title ``European Perspectives on
the Media Arts,'' the Guggenheim Museum's SoHo branch has ushered
in a series of shows that focus on ``media art practices'' in
Europe, exploring the work of key artists in the field. Fabrizio
Plessi, an Italian known for his large video installations,
inaugurates this new series, and this show is his New York debut as
well. Despite the unpromisingly academic title of the series,
Plessi gets it off to a lively start.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, he has provided four big installations for the
Guggenheim SoHo's ground-floor galleries, each given its own room.
If there's a common theme to them, it's the clever theatrical play
of video imagery with real substances and situations: water, stone,
metal, architectural elements and the like. Starting out in the
1970s, Plessi was involved with performance and Conceptual Art,
eventually turning from the use of video for recording such work to
exploring its potential as installation art in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Today he uses the technology to enhance and interpret the
mysterious realms of nature and history, mixing the virtual with
the real, so to speak. (He is professor of the humanization of
technologies at the Academy of Media Arts in Cologne, Germany.)
Take, for instance, the show's most impressive piece, ``Baroque
Cathodic Movements'' (1996), in which three ominous-looking wooden
structures, painted black and echoing 17th-century architectural
motifs, gyrate from the ceiling in slow, asynchronous rotations.
Each resembles a sort of furnace whose maw contains amazingly
real-looking video flames that appear to be consuming the ancient
architecture with a fierce roar. Ultratheatrical, a ballet in
themselves, they suggest coffins for the past while conveying a
shivery sense of hellfire and brimstone.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Plessi has been especially taken with the
movement of water, a preoccupation evident in two other works here.
In ``Rome II'' (1988), video monitors pave the rim of a large ring
built up of travertine marble pieces. Each of the monitors is alive
with the image and sounds of a turbulent patch of the Tiber River.
The images are identical, but each seems to move from one monitor
to the next, giving the sense of a rhythmical, relentless flow. The
water and the endless ring are intended to invoke the spirit of
Rome as the Eternal City, but even apart from these connotations
the piece has a hypnotic presence.
</P>
<P>
   A less successful work is ``Liquid Crystals'' (1993), inspired
by the canals and, I suppose, the ancient tradition of glassmaking
in Venice, where Plessi mainly lives and works. Five hundred empty
glasses are suspended upside down from the ceiling of this enclosed
piece, poised over 14 zinc buckets of bubbling water. The water in
the buckets looks very real, yet it's created by images on video
monitors concealed in each bucket, accompanied by appropriate
watery plops and squooshes. While intended as a metaphorical
reference to Venice, the work comes off instead as not much more
than a glitzy piece of decor. (It was commissioned by the Caffe
Florian in Venice for display there.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That can't be said of ``Bronx,'' a piece done for the 1986
Venice Biennale, which perhaps is surprising because it refers to a
turf that, while alive to New Yorkers, presumably doesn't have much
vibrancy overseas. Yet the Bronx does, apparently, resonate with
Plessi, if only as a state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing it less as a place than a condition of ``separation and
isolation,'' as he says in a catalog note about the work, he evokes
the borough with a lineup of 26 video monitors, each with a
workman's shovel seemingly stuck into the middle of a screen that
reflects it in a fiery orange glow. If the piece suggests more the
past history of, say, Pittsburgh than the Bronx, never mind. In his
statement, Plessi holds that the work does not attempt to describe,
but to generate ``strong signals.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in technical brilliance and imagination, Plessi's work
scores high. As video shows go, his is one of the real _ not
virtual _ events of the year.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FABRIZIO PLESSI'
</P>
<P>
   The show remains at the Guggenheim Museum SoHo, 575 Broadway, at
Prince Street, through Sept. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
