<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNMARRIED-FATHERS-HNS     07-30 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNMARRIED-FATHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS URGED TO PROTECT PROGRAM FOR UNMARRIED FATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unmarried fathers told House lawmakers Thursday
that a federal program that helps them remain actively involved
with their children works and should be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, introduced earlier this year by Rep. E. Clay Shaw
Jr., R-Fla., would provide $2 billion to states over five years to
help pay for projects where fathers would learn how to actively
support their children.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 4 of every 10 children in America are growing up without
a father in their home, according to a 1996 Census Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we must move beyond simply helping mothers work,''
Shaw, chairman of the Ways and Means subcommittee on human
resources, said in a prepared statement. ``We must take the next
step by doing everything we can to increase the number of our
nation's children being raised in two-parent families.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Downing, 29, of Baltimore told the subcommittee that
Healthy Start, a Baltimore-based private, nonprofit group that
promotes child care, helped him get off of drugs and find a job.
</P>
<P>
   Downing took his son 12-year-old son, Victor Jr., to the
subcommittee hearing. Downing said he admired the men he saw in the
Healthy Start group. It took him a long time to join, he testified,
but the people at Healthy Start ``never gave up on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Downing, who said he has been off cocaine and heroin for seven
months, said he was getting into fights over drugs in the streets
before he finally joined the program.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the benefits has been a closer relationship with
his son, who is now in the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his testimony, Downing nodded at his son and said,
``That's my best friend there.''
</P>
<P>
   Healthy Start receives $5 million from the Department of Health
and Human Services, but that money will be cut in half starting in
October. Supporters of the program, and about 50 others like it in
the nation, are urging Congress to restore the money and protect
programs for fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Another Baltimore man, Paul Hope, told lawmakers he also broke a
drug addiction with the help of Healthy Start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't joined the group, by now I would be dead or in
prison for life,'' Hope, 25, said.
</P>
<P>
   Hope said the program changed the way he looks at life. He no
longer carries a firearm, he said, and his two children and their
mothers have been off welfare since he joined the program five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Current support programs for fathers work, said Joseph Jones,
director of services for men at Healthy Start.
</P>
<P>
   The main Healthy Start program was founded to reduce infant
mortality by finding pregnant mothers and providing support. The
program for men, which has about 200 participants, grew out of the
mother's program. Jones said counselors try to contact the men who
fathered the babies, and then work with them to find jobs and set
up support groups to help them understand the role of a father.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, himself a former drug addict and now a married father of
three, said most men at Healthy Start are on welfare and have an
average education level of ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just not enough (role) models'' in the inner city,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The programs like Healthy Start are not expensive, according to
Jones, and the benefits outweigh the costs. The project uses less
than $2,000 a year per person, which is a ``drop in the bucket''
compared to the costs of time in prison, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A man can come in unprepared for responsibility, Jones said, but
after participating in the program, ``he becomes a candidate for
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   A provision in the legislation also requires the programs to
promote marriage and two-parent families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
