<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  ing:IntersectingStoriesB $13.Ma   07-30 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
ing: Intersecting Stories By Alice Mattison. Quill/Morrow, $13.
Many of the New Haven teachers, lawyers and social workers who
populate these whimsical tales are domestic but hardly
domesticated, as they squirm in the intellectual and social shadow
cast by Yale. `` Mattison is a charmer,'' Dwight Garner said last
year in the Book Review. ''It's a joy to tune into her characters'
thoughts.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women
</P>
<P>
   By Hilton Als. Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $11. Three
quirky, highly personal portraits explore the themes of racial and
sexual identity by mixing memoir, literary criticism and
reflections on politics and psychology. The subjects are the
author's spirited mother, who moved to Brooklyn from Barbados;
Dorothy Dean, a brilliant but self-destructive fixture in New
York's gay scene in the 60's and 70's; and the Harlem poet and
dramatist Owen Dodson, who was Hilton Als's mentor and lover. In
1997 our reviewer, Andrea Lee, admired the ''almost magical
cohesiveness'' of these ''truly original'' essays, calling this ''a
book to read several times, noting how its application grows
broader and broader upon consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Good Brother
</P>
<P>
   By Chris Offutt. Scribner, $12. After his brother is killed,
Virgil Caudill tries to escape a blood feud in his Kentucky hill
town by fleeing to Montana, but he can't shake the past or the
psychological pull of his homeland. Last year in these pages, Jo
Ann Kiser called this ''a fine first novel by a fierce writer.''
</P>
<P>
   T. Rex and the Crater of Doom
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Alvarez. Vintage, $13. A geologist describes how the
discovery of a giant 65-million-year-old crater in Yucatan helped
advance the once scandalous theory that a comet or asteroid killed
off the dinosaurs (and nine-tenths of the planet's species at the
time). Last year our reviewer, Timothy Ferris, called this a ''deft
and readable . . . account from the world's leading authority on
death from above.'' In Dinosaur Lives: Unearthing an Evolutionary
Saga, by John R. Horner and Edwin Dobb (Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$13), a leading paleontologist and bone collector explains his
craft and uses the fossil record to offer fascinating ideas about
how dinosaurs lived and evolved. ''We can't all study dinosaurs,
but books like this mean we can all enjoy the process and the
results,'' Philip Gingerich wrote here in 1997. Back in the
Holocene, the creatures described in The Modern Ark. The Story of
Zoos: Past, Present and Future, by Vicki Croke (Bard/Avon, $12),
benefit from the author's close-up observation of their lives in
captivity. Combining history with vivid accounts of maulings, this
is an ''absorbing, provocative book,'' Carol Peace Robins said here
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornerstone
</P>
<P>
   By Zoe Oldenbourg. Translated by Edward Hyams. Carroll &AMP; Graf,
$14.95. The title of this somber historical novel, which has just
been restored to print, refers to Christianity in 13th-century
France and the struggle among the members of a landowning family in
Champagne to build spiritual values in the squalid, bloody age of
chivalry. The result, Elizabeth Janeway said here in 1955, is ''a
vital book, and a rich one'' by an author of ''very substantial
talent.'' Three hundred years later in the New World, the events of
Aztec Autumn, by Gary Jennings (Tor/ Tom Doherty, $6.99), unfold
during another brutal time, in the years after the invasion of
Mexico by the conquistadors. The hero is a young Aztec who plots
revenge after witnessing the death of his father at the hands of
the Spaniards. ''Jennings's fascinating if often gory novel is
guided by exhaustive research,'' Charles Salzberg said here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Woe Is I: The Grammarphobe's Guide to Better English in Plain
English
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia T. O'Conner. Riverhead, $11. With chapter titles
like ''Death Sentence: Do Clich s Deserve to Die?'' and ''Comma
Sutra: The Joy of Punctuation,'' it's fair to assume that this
grammar book, written by a former editor at The New York Times Book
Review, is irreverent and reader-friendly. But it's also
surprisingly useful. In 1996 our reviewer, Daniel Pinkwater, called
the guide ''lighthearted and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Geronimo Rex
</P>
<P>
   By Barry Hannah. Grove, $12. The author's audacious first novel
follows the larger-than-life comic exploits of Harriman Monroe as
he romps through the South in the 1950's and 60's. When it was
first published in 1972, our reviewer, Jim Harrison, called this
''a stunning piece of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungry Ghosts: Mao's Secret Famine
</P>
<P>
   By Jasper Becker. Owl/Holt, $14.95. A journalist re-creates in
chilling detail the 1959-61 famine that killed up to 30 million
Chinese, a calamity caused by the obstinacy of the nation's
ruthless, ideologically driven leaders. The book, with a new
afterword on the current famine in North Korea, is ''powerful and
important,'' Nicholas Eberstadt wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Exiles: Three Short Novels
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Caputo. Vintage Contemporaries, $13. Whether in
Micronesia, suburban Connecticut or Vietnam, the misfit heroes in
this collection are outsiders whose defects lead them into trouble.
Last year in these pages, David Haward Bain said two of three
stories displayed the author's ''extraordinary eye for the exotica
of locale and behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Veale...end
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
