<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-REVIE     07-30 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILHARMONIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEIGHBORHOOD OUTING WITH FANFARE AND CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The second leg of the New York Philharmonic's tour of
parks in and around New York City got under way on Tuesday evening
at Van Cortlandt Park, in the Bronx. Kurt Masur has ceded the
podium of the traveling Carlos Moseley Pavilion to a newcomer,
Roberto Minczuk, a young Brazilian conductor, whose calling cards
included some fluff (John Williams' ``Summon the Heroes''), a dash
of Brazilian color (Lorenzo Fernandez's ``Batuque'') and two more
substantial works (Tchaikovsky's Serenade and Dvorak's Eighth
Symphony).
</P>
<P>
   The audience, estimated at 7,500, was less than a tenth the size
of the crowd that attended the series opener in Central Park a week
earlier. There was a subtle difference in atmosphere as well. As in
Manhattan, concertgoers brought picnics, blankets and fold-up
chairs, and settled in for an evening's entertainment that included
a Grucci fireworks display. But if the size of the crowd in Central
Park, the skyline on the park's borders and the slightly pressured
atmosphere gave last week's concert a festive glow, the Bronx
concert had more of a homespun charm, the sense of being a
neighborhood outing rather than a huge event.
</P>
<P>
   Minczuk was making his conducting debut with the Philharmonic,
but he has performed with the orchestra in another guise. In 1984,
when he was a 16-year-old student at the Juilliard School, he was
the soloist in Mozart's Horn Concerto No. 2 at one of the
orchestra's Young People's Concerts. He began conducting in the
late 1980s, and on Tuesday evening he showed that he has both
technique and interpretive flexibility going for him. His gestures
were broad and clear, and in the Tchaikovsky and Dvorak works, his
pacing was both personalized and tasteful, and magnified the
music's impulses nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to those works, however, meant wading through two
curtain raisers, which is at least one too many. Williams' ``Summon
the Heroes,'' composed for the 1996 Olympics, is a brassy,
predictable fanfare that sounded custom made to accompany
slow-motion video of athletes running, jumping, sweating and
exulting. Still, the Philharmonic's brass reveled in the spotlight,
and played brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
   They also made strong contributions to the Fernandez work, in
which the brass lines include bent notes that superimpose a sultry
jazz sensibility upon a rhythmically vital and characteristically
Brazilian backdrop. But this movement, excerpted from an orchestral
suite, is too fleeting to give much of an impression of the
Brazilian folk style in which it is rooted.
</P>
<P>
   In its way, Tchaikovsky's Serenade for Strings is as
manipulative as Williams' piece; the fanfare is meant to be
stirring, the serenade wears its heart on its sleeve. Minczuk took
a natural approach to the Tchaikovsky, looking into its emotional
core but respecting the boundary between emotional and maudlin. The
Philharmonic's strings responded with what may have been a lush
sound on the stage; through the Moseley Pavilion's speakers, it
sounded edgy.
</P>
<P>
   The sound was better in the Dvorak, and Minczuk found an almost
ideally balanced approach to the conflicting currents of
brawniness, stateliness and folksy charm that Dvorak demands.
</P>
<P>
   Minczuk brings the same program to Miller Field, Gateway
National Recreation Center on Staten Island, Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
