A1075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWELL-SUIT-NYT &LR;      07-30 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWELL-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD JEWELL'S MOTHER SUES FBI AGENTS, FORMER PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barbara Jewell, whose son, Richard, became the focus
of a federal investigation into the 1996 Summer Olympics bombing
but was later cleared, has filed a lawsuit against six FBI agents
and a former federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jewell is claiming that the officials intentionally
violated her Fourth Amendment rights by using misleading and false
statements by investigators to get a warrant to search her home,
said her lawyer, Watson Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Jewell, the security guard who spotted the bomb in
Centennial Park before it exploded on July 27, 1996, was hailed as
a hero before word of the investigation was leaked and a media
frenzy ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said the lawsuit, which he filed on Wednesday in U.S.
District Court in Atlanta, was ``a matter of principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Alleging ``real and emotional distress,'' the lawsuit says the
FBI agents searched everything from Mrs. Jewell's underwear drawer
to her Tupperware containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about 30 or 40 strange men pawing through your clothes,
your medicine cabinet, emptying out pill bottles, emptying out your
Tupperware to make sure nothing is hidden in your sugar, salt and
flour,'' said Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Some items were taken, including a ``Mary Poppins'' video, and
not returned until two months later.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the bombing, Jewell lived with his mother in her
apartment on the Buford Highway in Atlanta. She was humiliated in
front of her friends and neighbors, Bryant said, as investigators
and news media camped outside her door. It was October before he
was finally cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also laid the groundwork to sue not just former U.S.
Attorney Kent Alexander and the individual FBI agents named in the
suit, but to seek damages from the Justice Department and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant on Wednesday filed an administrative action against the
FBI and Justice Department, seeking $475,000. If that action is not
resolved in six months, he will add those agencies to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the FBI and U.S. Attorney's Office had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell, a former police officer, was working as a security guard
at the park in the early morning of July 27, 1996, when he spotted
a suspicious looking backpack that contained the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   While security guards and police tried to clear the area of
people, the bomb exploded, killing one woman and injuring more than
100 others.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell's actions were applauded after the blast by public
officials, who said he may have saved the lives of others, but he
quickly went from hero to suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell, who claimed that some members of the news media
mistreated him in their coverage, has since obtained settlements
from CNN and NBC and is suing The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
which first reported that he was the focus of an investigation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
