<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD TIGHTEN FEDERAL LAWS AGAINST 'DATE RAPE' DRUGS
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The night that Hillory Farias returned home to La
Porte, Texas, from a volleyball camp, she went to a dance club with
friends. Later that night, she complained of a severe headache and
went to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Hillory's grandmother found her dead.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days shy of the second anniversary of her death, Raul
Farias relayed his niece's story at a House Judiciary subcommittee
hearing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillory will never get the scholarship she dreamed of, she'll
never go to the prom. ... She'll never graduate,'' Farias said in a
shaky voice.
</P>
<P>
   It took two months for the medical examiner's office to figure
out what killed the 17-year-old high school senior who had hoped to
attend the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a colorless, odorless drug called GHB that had been
dropped into the girl's Sprite _ a drug that law enforcement
officials say is the hottest ``date rape'' drug on the club scene
in Texas, Florida and many other states.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, introduced legislation
Thursday that would allow federal prosecution of the possession of
GHB and a similar drug called ketamine. The bill would allow
prosecution even when those who make the drugs change the formula
slightly. Some states, including Georgia, already regulate GHB.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence against women is a social evil we must address,''
said Jackson Lee. Her bill, named after Hillory, would also direct
the attorney general to educate the nation's youngsters about the
harmful effects of these drugs.
</P>
<P>
   GHB can appear as clear liquid or a white powder, and brings on
such effects as euphoria and intense sexual pleasure. Like other
date rape drugs, it interferes with memory and may even cause
amnesia, which makes it difficult to document a sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, the drug is known as ``liquid ecstasy,''
``scoop'' or even ``easy lay.'' Its chemical name is gamma hydroxy
butyrate, a depressant of the central nervous system that can cause
dizziness, heart rate problems, seizures and death.
</P>
<P>
   GHB was banned by the Food and Drug Administration in 1990, when
it was sold in health food stores.
</P>
<P>
   The major source today is cheap kits obtained over the Internet,
said Paul Doering, a pharmacy professor at the University of
Florida in Gainesville. As a result, ``non-chemists'' create GHB
from flawed and incomplete recipes that lead to unknown potency,
Doering said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's no way to tell the strength of home-made GHB,
what might be a safe dose today could produce a toxic dose
tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stevens, a drug enforcement detective for the Orlando
Police Department, called GHB the most popular drug in club culture
in Central Florida, where minors use it to mimic the effects of
alcohol. The drug is also used calm highs obtained earlier from
hours of partying.
</P>
<P>
   GHB cannot be detected in routine drug screens. It took repeated
drug tests over two months to find the drug attributed to Hillory's
death, said Joye Carter, chief medical examiner for Harris County
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
