<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY CASE CONTINUES TO CREATE LEGAL QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been a little more than six months since
allegations about a sexual relationship President Clinton and
Monica S. Lewinsky first surfaced, and the questions and legal
issues continue to pile up.
</P>
<P>
   With the news this week that Lewinsky has agreed to testify
before the grand jury in exchange for full immunity, and of
Clinton's agreement to videotape his testimony at the White House
on Aug. 17, here is an attempt at answers to some of the persistent
questions:
</P>
<P>
   Q. News reports refer confidently to what Lewinsky will say
about the alleged relationship and whether Clinton asked her to lie
about it under oath. How is it known what Lewinsky will testify to?
</P>
<P>
   A. It isn't, really. What has been widely reported is that
anonymous ``legal sources'' say Lewinsky will admit she had an
affair with Clinton, contradicting her sworn affidavit in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment case that she did not have sex with the
president. Lewinsky, again according to various accounts, will say
no one at the White House helped her write the ``talking points''
that instructed her one-time friend, Linda R. Tripp, to say she saw
the president do nothing inappropriate. (Tripp denies any such
role.)
</P>
<P>
   Those in the best position to know what Lewinsky offered to say
include her own lawyers, and officials in independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's office. But there are other possibilities and most
news reports provide little guidance on this score.
</P>
<P>
   As White House press secretary Michael D. McCurry noted this
week, no one except Lewinsky, her lawyers and other confidants
really knows what she will tell the grand jury. Media reports about
her testimony have varied widely, with conflicting accounts of
whether the two agreed to lie about an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, meanwhile, has yet to talk publicly, and the general
description of her testimony doesn't take into account the
inevitable nuances that will arise when she actually is questioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. After Lewinsky has testified, will Clinton know what she has
said, and, if so, how?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lewinsky's testimony to the grand jury is given in secret.
The prosecutors, the grand jurors, and the court personnel are not
allowed to discuss the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   However, a witness is not bound by that rule, so Lewinsky is
free to discuss her testimony with her lawyers afterward, and they
are allowed to convey that information to the president's lawyers
or _ more likely _ leak it to the press. Clinton also will learn
much about the nature of her testimony as he is asked questions by
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Given that Clinton appears to be in the extraordinary
position of being part of a criminal investigation, why didn't he
contest the subpoena to testify before the grand jury all the way
to the Supreme Court?
</P>
<P>
   A. Clinton for months has employed a strategy of remaining quiet
and appealing every legal action that could harm him. Some members
of Clinton's legal team wanted to continue this strategy and fight
the subpoena. But with Lewinsky's agreement to testify, and with
the investigation apparently drawing near a close, Clinton's
political advisers were adamant that he fulfill his initial pledge
to cooperate. The political aides believed that the
silence-and-delay strategy was beginning to hurt him in the polls,
and that a refusal to answer a subpoena would make it appear that
Clinton was being uncooperative and trying to cover things up.
</P>
<P>
   There was a also a risk that the Supreme Court would have ruled
against Clinton's refusal to testify, which would have been
politically embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Clinton has already testified in the Jones case that he did
not have sex with Lewinsky. If he now admits in his grand jury
testimony that he did, how serious an offense would that be?
</P>
<P>
   A. The prospect that Clinton lied in the Jones deposition, while
a potential felony, is an offense that is rarely prosecuted for
civil cases. Lying alone is not perjury. The lie also has to be
``material.'' In the Jones case, the judge ruled the Lewinsky
evidence was irrelevant and later dismissed the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lewinsky investigation is not a typical legal case. Most
legal experts say Starr does not have the option of indicting a
sitting president. Instead, Starr will deliver a report to
Congress, which will decide whether to begin impeachment
proceedings. Thus, it also becomes a political decision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What if Clinton lies in his videotaped testimony for the
grand jury?
</P>
<P>
   A. That would be very serious, explained former federal
prosecutor Bruce Yannett. ``Courts view lying to a grand jury as a
very serious offense, and it is routinely prosecuted,'' he said.
``Congress and the American public would take it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a precedent for Clinton changing, or at least
modifying, his story. During the 1992 campaign, Clinton denied
having an affair with Gennifer Flowers. But during his deposition
in the Jones case, he admitted having sex with her once. While
White House officials said this was not a contradiction of
Clinton's denials of an affair, the impression was the president
was being careful not to be caught in a lie during a legal
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that Clinton would admit to some kind of
relationship with Lewinsky but say it was not what he considers to
be a sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What role can Clinton's lawyer play during the president's
testimony?
</P>
<P>
   A. Normally, a grand jury witness testifies before a prosecutor
and the jurors without having a lawyer present. The witness can
consult his or her lawyer, who usually is standing outside the
grand jury room, before answering a question.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, Starr agreed to let the president be
questioned in videotaped testimony at the White House instead of
appearing before the grand jury at the federal courthouse. In
addition, Starr will allow the president's lawyers to be present
during the questioning. Starr, who had subpoenaed Clinton to
testify, agreed to withdraw the subpoena in exchange for Clinton's
voluntary agreement to this time and arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is known about a dress that Lewinsky supposedly has
turned over to Starr's office?
</P>
<P>
   A. It has been reported for months that Lewinsky may have a
dress that contains forensic evidence that could prove Clinton had
a sexual relationship with her. But when investigators examined
dresses from Lewinsky's Washington apartment, they found no such
evidence, leading critics to say the report had been false.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, Lewinsky reportedly acknowledged that the
dress in question was kept at her mother's New York City apartment.
While that dress reportedly has been turned over to investigators,
there has been no confirmation so far that it contains evidence
proving that Clinton had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky. If
forensic evidence is found, then investigators would have to obtain
a DNA sample from the president to determine whether there is a
match; a swab of saliva would suffice, Yannett said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Before Lewinsky and her mother, Marcia K. Lewis, reached an
immunity agreement with Starr this week, where they vulnerable to
criminal charges?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lewinsky's attorneys were concerned she could have faced
charges of perjury, suborning perjury, or obstruction of justice.
Perjury could stem from contradicting her sworn statement that she
did not have a sexual relationship with the president. Suborning
perjury could relate to any efforts to get others to lie in the
case. Obstruction of justice could relate to the possibility that
Lewinsky conspired with Clinton or others to coverup their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who had many conversations with her daughter, apparently
kept the dress that investigators had been seeking and suggested
ways for Lewinsky and Tripp to avoid testifying in the Jones case.
So Lewis may have been concerned about facing charges of
obstructing justice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
