<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-QUOTAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SCANNING NEW BOSTON LATIN ADMISSION POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The revised admissions policy for Boston's most
prestigious public school, Boston Latin, is now in the hands of a
federal appeals court, which must decide if it passes
constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a federal district judge court judge in Boston ruled
that it was constitutional, prompting an appeal by the attorney for
a white ninth-grader who was not admitted, Sarah Wessmann.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Wessmann's attorney, Michael C. McLaughlin, argued
before a panel of the US Court of Appeals for the First Circuit
that diversity is not a legally defensible basis for an admissions
policy that admits half of Latin students based purely on merit,
half of students on a combination of race and merit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal courts, he argued, including the US Supreme Court, have
not held that ``diversity'' serves a compelling government interest
-- the legal standard for taking factors such as race into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Boston School department attorney Frances Cohen argued that
courts, including the Supreme Court, have traditionally given local
school authorities broad discretion in balancing any number of
interests and issues, from religious freedom to students' free
speech rights. Thus, school districts should be ones to decide how
best to prepare students ``to become citizens in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   But McLaughlin argued that the Supreme Court in a 1995 case
involving set-asides for minority contractors said the only time
race can be used is as a remedy for a constitutional violation --
and only if there is no other, less restrictive alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no claim that there is a constitutional right to
diversity,'' said McLaughlin. ``There is no case for diversity as a
compelling government interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Bruce Selya, a member of the appeals court panel, noted
the uniqueness of Boston Latin School, which he said makes the case
``terribly difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all aware that a student who is denied admission to
Boston Latin School solely because of this policy cannot get a
comparable education anywhere else in the city of Boston,'' Selya
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen disagreed, saying that Wessmann is getting a similar
education at Boston Latin Academy, where she takes Latin and honors
math. ``It's a comparable education,'' Cohen said, ``but not her
first-choice education.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the revised admissions policy for Boston Latin
School, which admits 50 percent of students based solely on grades
and entrance exam scores, and the other half of the class based on
grades, test scores and on the proportion of applicants from their
racial group.
</P>
<P>
   Wessmann, who was not admitted, scored higher than 10 minorities
who were admitted to Latin.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin had successfully challenged an earlier admissions
policy on behalf of his daughter, Julia. That policy, which was
dropped because of questions about its constitutionality, set aside
35 percent of seats for blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Chief US District Court Judge Joseph L. Tauro found that
the revised policy was constitutional, ruling that it was not
``just another paternalistic affirmative action program'' like
those previously struck down by the Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
