<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, August 31. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SAFETY (Washington) _ The Transportation Department says
that a rule it adopted three years ago to make cars safer was in
fact making cars more dangerous by preventing automakers from
introducing new technology that could save hundreds of lives a
year. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   SANCTIONS-DEBATE (Washington) _ Congress and the Clinton
administration are rethinking the use of economic sanctions, a
foreign policy tool of choice for decades, as the penalties
increasingly prove ineffective or backfire. But it'll be hard: More
than 75 countries are now under sanctions or the threat of
penalties. By Eric Schmitt. With graphic. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   POWERBALL (Westerville, Ohio) _ On the trail of the winners of
the big jackpot. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMO-REACT (Piqua, Ohio) _ For the elderly and disabled
people of this city, Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield's Medicare
HMO was a godsend. It provided exactly the kind of aggressive,
benefit-laden and prevention-oriented care that Congress envisioned
when they decided to open up the 33-year-old Medicare program to
HMOs and other forms of managed care. But Anthem got over-extended
as it hustled to lock up the Medicare market and recently announced
it was discontinuing its Medicare HMO in 19 Ohio counties. The
anger, dislocation and confusion among its elderly beneficiaries
says a lot about the dangers to come as more and more managed care
companies break into the Medicare market. By Peter T. Kilborn.
1,650 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEFTHANDED-DNA (Undated) _ One of the mysteries of DNA is
why it is always ``lefthanded.'' Now, scientists are ready to link
that explanation to the way dust clouds are polarized in the same
direction. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   Possible reefers:
</P>
<P>
   MASS-TAXCUT (Boston) _ The governor signs into law the biggest
tax cut in Massachusetts history. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM-DRUG (Undated) _ A drug widely available in Europe
that may reduce the urge to drink is being tested in the United
States, which has 13.7 million alcoholics. Its French maker hopes
to have it on the U.S. market in 2000. Many experts on dependency
say the drug _ acamprosate, which would be sold in the United
States as Campral _ is badly needed. Only two other medications can
treat alcoholism, and both can have unpleasant or potentially
dangerous side effects. But others in the medical community argue
that alcoholics should be treated with counseling alone. By David
J. Morrow. 1,600 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
