<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGED TO HELP `PROTECT OUR YOUTH' AGAINST DATE RAPE
DRUGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Texas man shared his grief with a House committee
Thursday over the ``date rape'' drug death of his 17-year-old niece
two years ago, as he pleaded with lawmakers to outlaw substances
that could be used to render women defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a House Judiciary subcommittee considering
several bills, Raul Farias of the Houston-area city of La Porte
recounted how his niece Hillory Farias died after drinking a soda
that was laced with gamma y-hydroxybutyrate, better known as GHB.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the young high school volleyball player attracted
national attention in August of 1996 after authorities, who were at
first perplexed by her death, discovered that someone had slipped
GHB into her soft drink during an evening out with friends. The
crime remains unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to be a willing participant of drug use. But
it's another when you are participating unwillingly or
unknowingly,'' said Farias, who called on lawmakers to help
``protect our youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Farias called for passage of a bill sponsored by Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee, D-Texas, that would place the drugs GHB and Ketamine
on the Food and Drug Administration's list of controlled
substances. The bill and several similar pending proposals would
also make it a federal crime to use drugs ``to render a woman
helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow Ketamine and GHB to be used as a tool for date
rape by individuals who prey on unsuspecting teen-age girls and
women,'' Jackson Lee, who serves on the Judiciary Committee, told
her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Calling violence against women ``a social evil that we must
address,'' Jackson Lee said Congress should ``send a message loud
and clear that if you commit date rape by using GHB or Ketamine you
become an inmate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee's bill would also instruct the attorney general to
establish programs to distribute materials to high school and
college students about the use of drugs in sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hillory Farias, there have been at least 15 other
deaths attributed to GHB use across the country. But Jackson Lee
said the drug is probably responsible for many more deaths since it
is not normally covered in standard toxicology screens.
</P>
<P>
   The congress member said the drug, which is produced outside the
United States, has been responsible for at least 60 admissions to
Houston-area hospitals during the past six months. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
