</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: `WHAT DID YOU DO TO US?' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago an editor on The New York Times, decently
paid and with a good future, diverted money from the newspaper to
himself _ less than $1,000. He did it in a way that made it
inevitable that the paper would soon find out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was heading the news department. The first words I said to him
after I was told were: ``What did you do to us?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You, me, the newsroom. He knew what I meant; we read each
other's unhappy eyes. I was saying I had to fire him immediately.
Otherwise the paper could no longer operate with assumption of
honor _ impossible to contemplate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What has the president done to us, the country? An adulterer
knows always that, if discovered, he will damage his family. Both
the act and consequences, in our society, are considered the
business of the adulterer and the few people he puts at risk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if Bill Clinton committed adultery in the White House, he
also committed putting the presidency at reckless, selfish risk.
That's why it sticks in my own gullet.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency does not belong to any president. It is his to
guard, not to put in jeopardy, to throw on the table like a
one-dollar chip. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether Americans in President John F. Kennedy's time cared
about presidential adultery, or knew, or whether foreign presidents
have no worries about sex does not matter. This is America NOW, not
the Kennedy era, and we vote only for our own president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, adultery would knowingly be a particularly grave
risk of the presidency, given his pre-White House record and
reputation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently most Americans do not want him to lose the presidency
for adultery, even for perjury about adultery. But the risk to the
presidency is not any lesser, nor the price to the country. Nobody
can be a fully functioning president and month after month a
full-time defendant.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration also passes on to future presidents
the entirely reasonable fear that the law will deprive him of the
confidentiality, and self-confidence, of people close to him. The
restrictions were imposed not by the special prosecutor himself but
by the courts that upheld him.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To me, the idea of Secret Service agents having to testify about
what they saw or heard because protecting the president's life put
them within range is shocking. But there it is, a souvenir of the
Clinton era. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have been trying falteringly to write this column in tenses
hinting I believe that perhaps Clinton might not have done as his
accuser is ready to testify. But I am a little embarrassed because
I do not believe that at all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Non-jurors are entitled to form opinions about innocence or
guilt before any trial. But all these years I have written, edited
and believed in innocent until proven guilty, juror or not.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accuser is a young person with no known accomplishment
beyond grabbing hold of the lowest bureaucratic rung. The accused
was twice elected president of the United States. Why is it that
the American majority, including his supporters, believe her when
she says she had sex with him, not him when he says denies it.
</P>
<P>
   Because: He takes himself with himself throughout his life, as
do we all. He has lied before, about his sex life before he became
president. I gave him an easy pass on that, as did the country on
Election Day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But since then, he has become a man whose word on matters of
world importance is doubted. Naturally, he gets no benefit of the
doubt on non-global matters, like adultery.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During his first presidential campaign, for instance, he said he
would struggle for oppressed Chinese and Tibetans. Now he is the
world's ace promoter of the Chinese Communist regime that kills and
tortures them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I had believed that America's trust in its leader would depend
on an ear tuned to the dungeons, not just an eye fixed on the Dow.
I was wrong. But maybe the disbelief now in Clinton's word, in his
own country, is a little payoff time from those dungeons. I like
thinking so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, I do not long for another president to be driven out of
office. But surely I do not know what will come of all this. Maybe,
if he has not told the utter, complete truth, he will tell it now,
for congressional amnesty? Maybe Monica would testify it was all an
erotic dream? I suppose not.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance. Probably we will just live with a dishonored
presidency _ our cost for his risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
