<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DIPLOMATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROTESTS DETENTION OF DIPLOMATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An American diplomat told the government here
Thursday that military attaches from the U.S. Embassy are free to
travel where they want in Mexico. The firm reminder followed the
detention of the two envoys by villagers in the southern state of
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the government of Mexico's concern for the
safety of our staff,'' the embassy official said on customary
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, as was explained to the Mexican foreign ministry's
representatives, as diplomats we have the freedom to travel
anywhere in Mexico without giving prior notice,'' the official
said. ``At the same time, Mexican diplomats in the United States
are free to travel to anyplace they want without advising us.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident involving the military aides had newly arrived U.S.
Ambassador Jeffrey Davidow facing his first diplomatic flap even
before he could present his credentials to President Ernesto
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Two American defense attaches from the embassy were detained for
nearly 10 hours last weekend by villagers in Chiapas. The incident
set off a chain of events that included a dressing down of the
deputy chief of mission Charles Brayshaw by the Mexican Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Brayshaw is acting in Davidow's place until the new ambassador
is fully accredited.
</P>
<P>
   Brayshaw was summoned to the Foreign Ministry to explain what
Thomas Gillen and Elizabeth Kruger were doing in the village of Los
Platanos when they reportedly refused to allow villagers to search
boxes in their automobile.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-government villagers demanded to know who Gillen and
Kruger were and what they were doing in Los Platanos, about 50
miles north of the colonial city of San Cristobal de las Casas. The
villagers blocked the road for about 10 hours before Chiapas state
officials negotiated their release.
</P>
<P>
   Published reports said Gillen and Kruger claimed diplomatic
immunity and refused to let the villagers open the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry officials told Brayshaw of their concern about
``risks and consequences that could accompany visiting certain
villages in the state of Chiapas to obtain information,'' the
ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas is a sensitive issue in Mexico. A brief but bloody
insurrection erupted there in 1994, with a band rebels demanding
democracy and rights for Indians. Since then, violence has flared
periodically and the southern state has drawn increasing scrutiny
from foreign rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Accredited defense and military attaches from all countries
regularly travel anywhere they want, except to areas specifically
prohibited for reasons of national security, the American embassy
official said.
</P>
<P>
   When possible, the official said, ``in recognition of the joint
concern for the safety of staff,'' informal notice will be given
before travel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
