u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-SMITH-BOS &LR;      07-30 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-SMITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO BOB SMITH, 80; `VOICE AND EGO' OF HOWDY DOODY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buffalo Bob Smith, the television pioneer whose question ``Say
kids! What time is it?'' was greeted with the joyous ``It's Howdy
Doody time!'' during 13 years of live broadcasts, died Thursday of
cancer in a Hendersonville, N.C., hospital near his Flat Rock home.
He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was ``literally the voice and ego'' of the freckle-faced
marionette Howdy Doody, television producer Burt DuBrow, a friend
and colleague of Smith's, said Thursday. ``A lot of people didn't
know he was Howdy's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith made his mark on pop culture by creating the show that is
often credited with establishing television as an entertainment
medium. The show drove the sales of TV sets and was considered the
first popular children's show on television, possibly because, when
it began in 1947, there was literally nothing else on the air
except test patterns until its daily 5:30 p.m. broadcast on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The show's phenomenal appeal and popularity were said to have
influenced Milton Berle and other performers to forsake the
established medium of radio and take their chances on the newer and
untested television. The show's occasionally broad slapstick was a
far remove from comedian Fred Allen's depiction of TV on small
screens: ``A collection of passport photos.''
</P>
<P>
   The show ran for 2,343 performances before succumbing in 1960 to
the more sophisticated ``Mickey Mouse Club.'' During its peak
years, the show had a viewing audience of 10 million, most children
ranging in age from two to 11 years old. Broadcast live, Smith
interacted with a studio audience of children called the Peanut
Gallery. He also showed film shorts (``Gumby'' started there and
was spun off into its own show) and sang a song or two.
</P>
<P>
   DuBrow called the show, which had a continuing story set in
Doodyville that ended on Fridays, ``the first soap opera for
kids.'' The show's ensemble included an irascible mute clown
Clarabell, once played by Bob Keeshan, who would go on to become
TV's ``Captain Kangaroo.'' Others in the ensemble were a winsome
Indian princess named Summerfall Winterspring, Phineas T. Bluster,
Dilly Dally, Chief Thunderthud, Trapper John and Flubadub.
</P>
<P>
   DuBrow said Smith was the same powerful but reassuring presence
on- and off-camera. ``What you saw you got. He had an incredible
presence. When he looked at you, you thought you were the most
important person in the world. We looked up to him as a hero. It
wasn't like today when a hero is a cartoon or a Teenage Mutant
Ninja Turtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith got his start on the radio and his nickname in his
hometown, Buffalo, N.Y. ``I did just about everything you could do
on the radio when I was 15,'' he said. Two years later, singer Kate
Smith came to Buffalo. Smith joined her vaudeville act, playing the
piano at times and other times playing master of ceremonies. He was
back working successfully in radio when NBC was looking for someone
in 1947 to be host of a children's television show.
</P>
<P>
   That was the birth of ``The Howdy Doody Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970-71, during the Vietnam era, he and DuBrow staged a
successful tour of colleges thronged by students who'd grown up
with Howdy Doody. He continued to make hundreds of appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show was loved for much of its 13 years, it without
its critics. Stephen Davis, author of the 1987 book ``Say Kids!
What Time Is It?'' said then that Howdy Doody became an
extraordinarily lucrative merchandising machine in his time.
``Buffalo Bob would break off a conversation ... to look into the
camera and say, `Hey, kids, did you know Wonder Bread builds strong
bodies 12 ways?' Nobody held a stopwatch on advertising in those
days.'' Smith was television's first spokesman, with his wholesome
image also selling Campbell Soup and Twinkies. Smith would later
buy three radio stations and dabble in real estate. For 43 summers,
Smith vacationed at Grand Lakes Stream, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   DuBrow described Smith as a ``religious, spiritual man'' who
signed off his shows ``telling the kids not to forget to go to
church or their place of worship. He played 15 to 20 instruments,
including the piano and the organ at church.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Smith's Howdy Doody was ``Proustian, as familiar as
the sound and sense of the cooking in the kitchen. It reminds
Yuppies of our mothers puttering around in the kitchen between 5
and 6 in the afternoon. It gave us the warm glow of childhood, the
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife of 57 years, Mildred, Smith is survived by his
three sons, Robin, Ronald, and Christopher and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1924EDT &QL; 
