<P>
   CABLE-ALLEN (Seattle) Software billionaire Paul Allen morphed
himself into a cable TV mogul yesterday, announcing he would spent
$4.5 billion to buy Charter Communications and combine it with
Marcus Cable (which he bought a couple of months ago) to become the
nation's seventh-largest cable operator. The deals give him
high-speed access into about 2.5 million homes and a platform he
can use to deliver a wealth of cool stuff _ interactive television,
convenient electronic commerce, lightning-fast Internet access,
local and long-distance telephone service and eventually video on
demand _ he envisions in the ``wired world'' of the ever-nearer
future. The Charter purchase is Allen's largest personal investment
so far and the latest in a string of deals that signify a growing
belief in the business world that the TV cable is the best way to
deliver tons of digital data to the home.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
