<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-FUNERALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNERAL HELD FOR CAPITOL SHOOTING VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK   AND ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ John Michael Gibson, one of two officers killed
last week protecting the Capitol, was remembered as he was laid to
rest next to other American heroes at Arlington National Cemetery
Thursday as a man who lived to help others.
</P>
<P>
   His widow, Evelyn, wept as she and their children, Daniel, 14,
Jack, 15, and Kristen, 17, each placed a long-stemmed red rose on
Gibson's mahogany casket. They embraced one another, and Evelyn
Gibson wiped tears from her daughter's face.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, a 42-year-old &UR;  &LR; Capitol Police detective, &UR;  &LR; was given full
police honors, including a fly-over by police helicopters and a
21-gun, three-volley salute, at a service attended by family
members from Massachusetts, busloads of congressmen, and police
officers from Canada to California.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mourners was the family of Capitol Police Officer
Jacob J. Chestnut, who also died last Friday when Russell Weston
Jr., a diagnosed paranoid schizophrenic, allegedly stormed the
Capitol. Gibson's family plans to attend Friday's services for
Chestnut, 58, an Air Force veteran, who will be buried at Arlington
with full military honors.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and Chestnut are the first Capitol Police officers to die
in the line of duty in the more than 100-year history of the force.
Gibson died just hours before his family was scheduled to leave on
vacation. The Capitol shooting was believed to be the first time he
ever had to draw his weapon in his 18 years with the force.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Gibson was to have been best man at the wedding of
his brother, Charles, an Air Force sergeant based at the American
Embassy in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now John, you'll have the best seat in the house,'' said Jack
De Wolfe, supervisor of special agents for the Capitol Police, who
gave Gibson's eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral at St. Elizabeth Ann Seton Church in suburban
Lake Ridge, a motorcade of more than 1,000 police motorcycles and
cruisers stretched for 15 miles along Interstate 95, according to
the Military District of Washington. The route was lined by many
families with children who held American flags and stood in silent
tribute to the slain detective.
</P>
<P>
   Special congressional permission was granted for Gibson, who did
not serve in the military, to be buried at Arlington. His grave, on
a grassy knoll beneath red maple trees, is just a short walk from
the gravesite of President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   De Wolfe, who was Gibson's best friend and immediate supervisor,
delivered an emotional, and sometimes humorous, eulogy, remembering
his fellow Massachusetts native as a man who never lost his
enthusiasm for police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``John enjoyed helping people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When they joined the Capitol force as rookies in 1980, DeWolfe
said another Massachusetts native, John Morrissey, asked if Gibson
could join their car pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another guy who liked the Red Sox and Bruins and Celtics,''
recalled DeWolfe during the service. ``How could I go wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   On their first assignment as plainclothes detectives, a local
police official in the Midwest asked if either of them ``spoke
English,'' De Wolfe said with a distinctive Massachusetts accent
that drew laughter from the mourners.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gibson, a bodyguard for House Republican whip Tom DeLay
of Texas, never failed to stop at an accident scene to provide
assistance when they drove into Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never met an individual who loved his profession as much as
John,'' said DeWolfe.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gibson, who delighted in his motorcycle training, was
happiest on motorcycle rounds on Capitol Hill. De Wolfe said Gibson
inherited his driving skills from his father, Charles, and his
ability to tell a joke from his mother, Eleanor. His parents still
live in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and Moakley family members were at the services Thursday.
Evelyn Gibson is the daughter of Robert Moakley, the brother of
Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a South Boston Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
