<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIRETTE-THEATER-REVIE     07-30 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRETTE-THEATER-REVIEW-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIRETTE': A CASE OF PLUCK TURNING INTO LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HADDAM, Conn. _ What is it about the Goodspeed Opera House
and musicals involving plucky, pint-size redheads who melt hearts
and minister to troubled adults? From the theater where ``Annie''
was born 22 years ago now comes ``Mirette,'' with music and lyrics
by ``The Fantasticks'' team of Harvey Schmidt and Tom Jones. It is
adapted from the prize-winning children's book ``Mirette on the
High Wire,'' the story of a little girl's dream of becoming a
tightrope walker.
</P>
<P>
   Goodspeed, that riverside Victorian doll house, is about as
hospitable a backdrop as could be furnished for a musical about
childish wishes. And the theater's latest offering, aided greatly
by Schmidt's jaunty melodies and Cassandra Kubinski's unaffected
performance in the title role, strives mightily to take the
audience along into the upper atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Mirette,'' originally produced in Goodspeed's smaller,
workshop-oriented space, never really finds its footing on the
theater's main stage. The expansion and embellishment of Emily
Arnold McCully's delightful book proves too burdensome an exercise
for so slender a narrative. To get to the not-all-that climactic
moment in which Mirette finally walks the tightrope, we sit through
an entire symphony when a simple drumroll would do.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCully's illustrated book, published in 1992, tells the
sweetly wistful story of the awakening of Mirette's unlikely
ambition when a celebrated tightrope walker checks into the
vivacious Parisian boardinghouse run by her mother, Madame Gateau.
The performer, Bellini, has fled the circus after developing a
sudden fear of heights; in teaching Mirette his craft he finds the
strength to conquer his own phobia.
</P>
<P>
   You can see why Schmidt's and Jones' curiosity was piqued. In
subjects ranging from first love (``The Fantasticks'') to wedded
bliss (``I Do! I Do!'') the venerable partnership has often been
attracted to tales with a bedtime-story shimmer to them. Their best
work here, in ``Learning Who You Are,'' a duet for Mirette and
Bellini, reflects their penchant for finding the music in fairy
tale pairings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's difficult, however, to present a full-blown musical on the
promise of sparkle. Ms. Diggs, the show's book writer, does her
best to broaden the plot by filling Madame Gateau's boardinghouse
with an assortment of aspiring jugglers, opera singers and
tumblers. But they're standard-issue secondary characters, lifeless
and charmless.
</P>
<P>
   Director Andre Ernotte displays no particular warmth for this
material. The pantherlike Mellon certainly looks as if he could
walk the high wire, but his menacing manner makes his Bellini less
likely as a mentor for an impressionable girl than as a candidate
for special scrutiny by the neighborhood watch committee.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Kubinski, though, is a sturdy and unspoiled presence. She's
the sturdy center of a show that isn't quite the confection it's
meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `MIRETTE'
</P>
<P>
   Book by Elizabeth Diggs; music by Harvey Schmidt; lyrics by Tom
Jones, based on the book ``Mirette on the High Wire,'' by Emily
Arnold McCully; directed by Andre Ernotte; musical direction by
Michael O'Flaherty; choreography by Janet Watson; sets by Neil
Patel; costumes by Suzy Benzinger; lighting by Timothy Hunter;
orchestrations by Larry Moore; vocal arrangements by Gary Adler;
assistant musical director, Christopher Jahnke; production manager,
R. Glen Grusmark; stage manager, Donna Cooper Hilton; artistic
associate, John Pike; associate producer, Sue Frost, general
manager, Howard Sherman; produced by Michael Price. Presented by
the Goodspeed Opera House, East Haddam, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jason Wooten (Tabac), Marsha Bagwell (Madame
Rouspenskaya), Paul Blankenship (Clouk), Leslie Ann Hendricks
(Claire), Amanda Watkins (Gaby), Steve Pudenz (Camembert),
Cassandra Kubinski (Mirette), Anne Allgood (Madame Gateau), James
Mellon (Bellini) and Michael Hayward-Jones (Max).
</P>
</TEXT>
