<HEADLINE>
COYOTE SIGHTINGS ON THE RISE IN SOUTHEASTERN MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With Coyote-Attack)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ABBY FUNG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrolman David Malcolmson said he had never even heard the word
coyote mentioned around quiet Sandwich, Mass. five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last three weeks, residents of the small Cape Cod
town have inundated the police and animal-control departments with
18 calls of coyote sightings _ all before four-year-old Daniel Neal
was attacked by a coyote while playing in his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials say this is the first documented coyote
attack on a human in Massachusetts, and that attacks are rare,
usually prompted only by rabies or if the animal has been fed by
humans.
</P>
<P>
   But the proliferation of coyotes in the state _ and particularly
into its eastern and southern regions _ has been a long time
coming, since the first of the animals began migrating to
Massachusetts 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Langlois, a wildlife biologist with the state Division of
Fisheries and Wildlife, said reports of coyote sightings have been
``steadily increasing,'' with some fluctuations, from 81 in 1990 to
137 in 1996. The slight dip last year, to 105, was due to the fact
that the animals are now so common in some places that people have
stopped reporting them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people, after their third years of seeing coyotes,
who just don't report it anymore,'' Langlois said. ``The Cape is
the newest territory for the coyote to expand to. It's not
commonplace to see a coyote yet, so you might get the increase in
the number of calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Chatham officials hired a federal
sharpshooter to kill two coyotes who had supposedly been plaguing
the town's population of endangered piping plovers.
</P>
<P>
   Langlois said the first sighting of the coyote in southern and
eastern Massachusetts occurred during the 1970s, after coyotes had
migrated down from the Canadian border in the 1940s and 1950s into
Massachusetts' northern and western regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only place they don't exist yet is Nantucket and the
Vineyard,'' Langlois said. ``Whatever habitat is available to them,
they'll adapt to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cocca of the Massachusetts Audubon Society in Lincoln,
Mass. agrees. When she first started working for the society 10
years ago, Cocca said, she received only one call a month about
coyotes. Now she receives about three or four calls a month, and
from places which are farther south and east.
</P>
<P>
   The state coyote population, which is around 3,000, is
increasing because coyotes are highly adaptable, and can live off
brush piles, compost piles, trash bins, or scraps of food left for
them by people, wildlife officials say.
</P>
<P>
   They rarely attack people, but when they do, the attacks can be
deadly. In Los Angeles, one person was killed and nine were
attacked by coyotes between 1975 and 1981: Six of the nine were
children younger than five.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
