<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WHY31-COX     07-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WHY31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WEIGHED LAW AND POLITICS IN GRAND JURY DECISION
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With one eye on the justice system and another on
the court of public opinion, President Clinton has staked his
presidency on his belief that the political risk of fighting Ken
Starr far outweighs the legal risk of cooperating with him.
</P>
<P>
   He's betting that whatever the independent counsel reports to
Congress, lawmakers will be reluctant to impeach a popular
president weeks before all House members and a third of the Senate
must face voters back home.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to Clinton, however, is that his Aug. 17 grand jury
testimony will damage public trust in him, or that Starr will give
Congress evidence that the president had lied under oath or
obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   Any of those outcomes, analysts say, could erode Clinton's
public popularity, perhaps his greatest insurance against moves by
a Republican-led Congress to impeach and convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Congress will not get too far ahead of the public,'' said
Michael Genovese, a political science professor at Loyola Marymount
University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, said Genovese, ''Clinton really has to be
careful of how this plays in Peoria _ even more than how it plays
in court.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Clinton's playing very well in the heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the legal tide appeared to turn this week against
Clinton, an NBC News poll taken Wednesday showed 68 percent of
Americans approving of the way Clinton is doing his job, up five
percentage points from a month ago. The poll showed 27 percent of
Americans disapproving, with 5 percent unsure. The telephone survey
had a margin of error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   After six months of probing allegations that Clinton had an
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and then
urged her to lie about it under oath _ charges the president has
denied _ Starr obtained a court order requiring Clinton to answer
questions before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena was withdrawn after Clinton agreed instead to
voluntarily give his testimony by videotape from the White House
with his lawyers present.
</P>
<P>
   He did so even though many legal experts believe Starr could not
have forced Clinton to honor the court order.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a strong argument that he can't, on the grounds that
he's in a unique position _ there's only one president,'' said
Thomas Sargentich, professor of constitutional law and presidential
powers at American University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Having one branch of the American government, the judiciary,
dictate terms to another, the president, could be argued to be
unconstitutional, a matter that Clinton's attorneys could have
taken to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a fairly strong constitutional argument, and it would
not be a bad thing for the president to assert it,'' said
Sargentich.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stakes are much greater than this particular president's
future,'' said Sargentich. ''The question is one of preserving the
power and the dignity of the office of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's political advisers, however, counseled against taking
a stand that might make it appear that the president was primarily
concerned with saving his own skin.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats, fighting to regain the House in the
November elections, warned that they would not support Clinton if
he resisted testifying.
</P>
<P>
   There were fears, moreover, that Clinton might not prevail in
the Supreme Court. Other presidents, including George Bush, Ronald
Reagan and even Thomas Jefferson, have given testimony to grand
juries considering criminal charges against third parties. Some
legal experts contend that the Supreme Court might well have leaned
on those cases as precedent, then ruled that testimony from Clinton
in a case focusing on him was comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to testify also reflects a set of
calculations as yet inscrutable to the public.
</P>
<P>
   While Lewinsky is reportedly prepared to testify that she had an
affair with Clinton, reversing an earlier sworn statement in which
she said the opposite, the public has been offered no proof that
such an affair took place.
</P>
<P>
   If it didn't, then Clinton could simply elaborate in his
testimony on his now famous January claim that he never had sex
with ''that woman _ Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's later shown that an affair did take place, however,
Clinton's credibility, already a liability to him, could slip
further, posing a potential threat to his public support.
</P>
<P>
   ''Politically, what you do (with the testimony) is you make it
look like you're cooperating, you make it look like you're the
victim, you make it look like Ken Starr is out to get you,'' said
Genovese.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk is, if he did lie under oath, then Congress would
consider that an impeachable offense,'' Genovese said. ''That would
cross a legal line that could give the Republicans credibility
...It opens a door that right now is not open.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another possibility is that Clinton might admit to
wrongdoing and ask the nation to forgive him, and try to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Clinton ultimately tells Starr and his team on Aug. 17,
it's certain that the president will look, as he has throughout his
career, to his personal powers of persuasion and his political
instincts to put the best possible face on the matter, in the hope
that he'll be embraced by the jury he knows best _ in the court of
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
