<SLUG> BC-GA-POWERBALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery chief stands by Powerball decision
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia Lottery President Rebecca Paul said Thursday
she doesn't regret her decision nearly two years ago to bail out of
Powerball and join The Big Game, a more conservative, multi-state
jackpot game.
</P>
<P>
   That move kept Georgians on the sidelines this week while many
parts of the nation were gripped in Powerball mania over a $295.7
million jackpot that was finally claimed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said such mammoth jackpots cause short-term surges in
lottery ticket sales in the 20 Powerball states but don't
necessarily boost those lotteries' sales in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   She said Powerball jackpots of $195 million and $295 million in
recent months may cause ``jackpot fatigue,'' where players decide
to postpone ticket buying until jackpots reach very high levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you continue to raise the bar higher and higher, the long
term impact is negative for raising money for programs you fund,''
Paul said. The Georgia lottery funds HOPE college scholarships,
pre-kindergarten and technical programs for schools.
</P>
<P>
   Paul said the Georgia Lottery pulled out of Powerball in the
late summer of 1996 due to concerns about Georgia's liability for
other new games Powerball states _ all considerably smaller than
Georgia _ planned to launch.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Lottery didn't want to join one particular new game
run by the Multi-State Lottery Association, which also runs
Powerball. But attorneys warned that Georgia might not be able to
escape liability for the new game as long as it remained a member
of the association, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia quit Powerball before the new game began. Meanwhile, six
states similar in size to Georgia were beginning The Big Game. At
the time, odds for winning the Big Game were 52 million to 1,
slightly better than Powerball's 54 million to 1.
</P>
<P>
   But after Georgia departed, Powerball lengthened its odds to 80
million to 1, greatly increasing the chances that its jackpots
would roll over, creating bigger payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given Georgians the opportunity to play for $60-$70
million jackpots,'' Paul said. ``And we've had several winners.''
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia ticket sales volume for The Big Game since late 1996
haven't matched Powerball ticket sales through August 1996 when it
was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Big Game sales failed to reach the $1 million mark on 30 percent
of the draws in the past six months, while Powerball failed to
reach that mark on only 4 percent of draws during the same period
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   However, daily sales for both games were highly sensitive to
jackpot levels at the time. For example, while $1.2 million
Powerball tickets were sold on April 3, 1996, when the jackpot was
$5 million, $5.6 million Big Game tickets were sold on April 3,
1998, when its jackpot was $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
