<SLUG> BC-SINCLAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sinclair Community College offers distance learning courses
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- Sinclair Community College has joined with seven
other community colleges across the country to offer
distance-learning courses to students starting this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Community College Distance Learning Network will make as
many as 500 courses available in a variety of ways, including
video, audio, Internet and CD-ROM, according to Peggy Falkenstein,
Sinclair's dean of distance learning. The venture is designed to
make it easier for potential students to gain access to a college
education, and it also could boost enrollment and tuition revenue
for Sinclair, Falkenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair has offered such distance-learning courses since the
early 1980s, and currently has 59 courses available on the Internet
and 73 on video. The collaboration with other colleges will greatly
increase the profile of Sinclair's offerings: The colleges are
preparing an advertising campaign for the Yahoo! web site and
national newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The courses will be open to students anywhere who pay the
tuition to the college providing the instruction, Falkenstein said.
Sinclair will offer the courses for $31 per credit hour to
Montgomery County residents, $50 per credit hour to out-of-county
Ohio residents and $83 per credit hour to out-of-state students.
Montgomery County residents pay the least because they support
Sinclair through a countywide tax and through their state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration will also make full use of Sinclair's newly
constructed Center for Interactive Learning, a technology-rich
building in the heart of the downtown Dayton campus that is poised
to open Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
