A1131 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     07-30 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS OF DRESS, TAPES RAISE NEW QUESTIONS IN CLINTON
INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reports that Monica Lewinsky is turning a dress and
an answering-machine tape over to special counsel Kenneth Starr
raised new legal questions _ and White House angst _ Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The items could hold tell-tale evidence of an intimate
relationship between Lewinsky and President Clinton, who has denied
under oath and in public statements having sex with the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Unclear was whether the tape could bear on Lewinsky's expected
testimony to a federal grand jury that she and Clinton agreed to
deny having sex during her repeated visits to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Also uncertain was how Starr intends to seek samples, such as
blood, saliva or hair, from Clinton for DNA matching tests with any
residue on the dress. A request for such samples could set off
another legal wrangle between the president's lawyers and the
special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The White House refused comment on ``any of these rumors'' about
Lewinsky producing material evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A dress, supposedly semen stained, figured in the early days of
the investigation last winter because of reports that Lewinsky
talked about the garment with Linda Tripp, a former White House
aide who taped their conversations. William Ginsburg, one of
Lewinsky's original lawyers who has since left the case, said in
January a dress existed that ``might be forensically important in
terms of DNA evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents, under a court-ordered search warrant, removed
several garments from Lewinsky's Watergate apartment, but
reportedly no evidence incriminating to Clinton was found. The
dress reportedly turned over to Starr on Wednesday was given to
Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, for safekeeping, according to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky took the dress and tape with her when she went to her
lawyers' office to sign papers relating to the immunity deal,
sources said. In broadcast tape of Lewinsky en route to her lawyers
office, she is holding a carryall bag, which reportedly contained
items to be given to Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern has been granted immunity from
prosecution for any action in the case _ except for lying to the
grand jury in her upcoming testimony. She swore in the Paula Jones
harassment case that she had not had a sexual relationship with the
president but is now reported ready to recant.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the official silence at the White House, the possibility
that the special counsel has physical evidence to back up
Lewinsky's claim of a sexual relationship sent a shudder through
the Clinton administration on the day after the president agreed to
be questioned by Starr's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not good news for the president,'' said a senior
administration official. ``Despite legal questions that can be
fought out (between the White House and Starr's office), this
intensifies the need for Clinton to be absolutely, unequivocally
truthful'' in his videotaped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Among the future legal battlegrounds could be the issue of
whether the president can be forced to provide DNA samples to be
compared with any residue from the dress.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who specialize in criminal cases said a demand by Starr
for sample of Clinton's blood, saliva or hair could lead to a legal
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years of case law is on Starr's side, said David Baugh, a
former assistant U.S. attorney in Texas and Virginia. ``It
shouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Courts freely order (such samples) on the basis of potential
relevance'' in routine cases, said Edward Millett, a criminal
defense lawyer in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Hollander of Albuquerque, N.M., a specialist in Fourth
Amendment search-and-seizure cases, said ``the rules seem to be
different in this case'' and predicted another deal based on
negotiations between Clinton's lawyers and Starr's office. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; National polls published Thursday indicated that while the
public continues to approve of Clinton's handling of his job, there
is increasing concern about whether he committed perjury in denying
a sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   A Wall Street Journal-NBC survey found that by 64 percent to 30
percent respondents approved of Clinton's job performance _ a
continuation of his strong ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But there was some erosion on the issue of whether perjury about
his relationship with Lewinsky is grounds for Congress to begin
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Journal-NBC survey found that 57 percent to 39
percent of respondents did not believe perjury about sex was
serious enough to warrant an impeachment inquiry, but in the most
recent sampling the margin had closed to six points, 51 percent to
45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum has switched in another direction,'' said Peter
Hart, a Democratic pollster who with a Republican analyst oversees
the poll.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Thursday, Starr called a group of Secret
Service personnel before grand juries, apparently probing for
information on what the protective force may have seen during
Lewinsky's more than three-dozen visits to the White House during
and after her internship.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, accompanied by Secret Service attorney Mike Leibig,
made no comment as they arrived at the federal courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
