<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRATION31-COX     07-30 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PANEL VOTES TO SPLIT IMMIGRATION AGENCY
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House immigration subcommittee voted Thursday
to create a new law-enforcement agency that would operate the
Border Patrol and handle deportations and other anti-crime
functions currently performed by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Like the FBI, the new Bureau of Enforcement and Border Affairs
would be a separate division of the Justice Department. The INS,
already part of the Justice Department, would be responsible solely
for the citizenship process.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was introduced two weeks ago by Rep. Harold
Rogers, R-Ky., and its swift approval by the immigration
subcommittee reflects growing impatience among both Republicans and
Democrats for improvements in the performance of the INS,
particularly in processing a nationwide backlog of 1.9 million
applications for citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this separation will improve both immigration
service and enforcement operations,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas, chairman of the immigration subcommittee. Smith offered a
litany of complaints about the failure of the INS to respond to
requests from both Congress and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In one example, Smith said a couple waited more than a year for
INS approval of their adoption of an orphan from India: ``They sent
a written inquiry, only to receive a terse written reply that ...
such inquiries take away from the time the INS has to process
applications.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration recognizes the weaknesses in the INS,
but opposes dividing the agency's responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do acknowledge and agree there needs to be some management
improvement there,'' Associate Attorney General Ray Fisher said
Thursday. ``That has already been undertaken in great measure by
(INS Commissioner) Doris Meissner and the INS. We oppose the
proposal to split the agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus, who met two weeks
ago with Vice President Al Gore to complain about the citizenship
backlog, were wary Thursday of the legislation that would divide
the agency in charge of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we believe reform of the INS is vital, we are concerned
... (that) this legislation does not address one of the priorities
of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus _ immigrant services,'' 13
caucus members said in a letter to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate immigration subcommittee, led by Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., is still examining possible solutions to INS
problems and plans the third of three hearings on the subject in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a very slow approach,'' said Abraham's
spokesman, Joe McMonigle. ``We're going to ... look at all the
functions of INS, then use next year to start on legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
