<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIG-BLACKSTONE-325&AMP;AD     07-30 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-BLACKSTONE-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURER AIG TO INVEST IN MERCHANT BANK BLACKSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American International Group Inc. said Thursday that
it would invest $1.35 billion in the Blackstone Group, the private
New York merchant bank, raising the prospect of considerable future
cooperation between the two companies as the traditional barriers
between insurance and investment banking continue to erode.
</P>
<P>
   The big insurance group is paying $150 million of this money to
acquire a 7 percent limited partnership stake in Blackstone, while
the remainder, an estimated $1.2 billion, would be invested in
Blackstone's private equity partnerships, real estate funds and
other ventures.
</P>
<P>
   In a relationship that both companies see continuing for many
years, AIG is also committing to reinvesting this money with
Blackstone along with at least half of its after-tax profits,
Blackstone president and chief executive Stephen Schwarzman said in
an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely therefore that the money AIG is agreeing to invest
could grow to $2 billion to $3 billion or more within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   AIG's 7 percent stake in Blackstone replaces $100 million that
Nikko Securities Inc. of Japan had invested in the New York
merchant bank in 1988. That stake now makes less sense for Nikko,
after the Japanese securities company _ responding to the
continuing deregulation of Tokyo's financial markets _ a few weeks
ago entered into a worldwide partnership with the Travelers Group
and its Salomon Smith Barney investment banking subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement of AIG's investment also reflects the
continuing convergence of Wall Street businesses, analysts said.
``AIG would at one point have been viewed as a traditional
insurance company,'' said John Keefe, an independent New York
financial analyst. ``Not now. This shows that the barriers between
the different sectors of U.S. finance _ banking, insurance and
investment banking _ are wearing away. This makes AIG look more
like a merchant bank or an investment bank.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   AIG's financial strength has many analysts speculating about its
future strategy. In 1997, the company was the most profitable among
insurance and financial services companies with headquarters in the
United States. Its $3.33 billion net profit in 1997 on revenue of
$30.6 billion represented a record for the company and the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting investment with a number of fascinating
sideline possibilities,'' said Michael Lewis, an insurance analyst
at Warburg Dillon Read. ``AIG is viewed more and more as an
acquirer and part of the consolidation of the financial services
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of Blackstone and AIG, which are both based in New
York City, have worked together for many years. AIG chairman and
chief executive Maurice Greenberg has been on Blackstone's advisory
board since 1989. But Thursday's announcement represents a
considerable deepening of the existing business relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been an investor in Blackstone funds for a number of
years,'' Greenberg said, adding that AIG has in the past invested
$300 million in Blackstone funds. Speaking from Switzerland, where
he is on vacation, Greenberg praised Blackstone's returns as among
the best in the investment banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Thursday that the Blackstone Capital
Partners II fund had returned an average of 68 percent a year since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the relationship between AIG and
Blackstone will grow further, particularly as there has long been
speculation that the big insurance group might seek to grow by
acquiring, or merging with, a Wall Street firm. Greenberg, however,
seemed wary of compromising Blackstone's independence. ``I have
known Pete Peterson and Steve Schwarzman for many years,'' he said
Thursday. ``It's a long relationship. The thing that makes them
good is their independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The payment of $150 million for 7 percent of Blackstone would
imply a valuation of $2.14 billion for the entire company.
Schwarzman cautioned that this, however, would represent a
``minimum notional value'' for the firm as Blackstone is not a
publicly quoted company.
</P>
<P>
   Blackstone chairman Peter Peterson and Schwarzman teamed up at
Lehman Brothers, where Peterson was chairman and Schwarzman was his
deputy. In 1985, they founded Blackstone to focus on private equity
investing, real estate investment, asset management, and advising
on mergers and acquisitions and restructurings.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzman said AIG and Blackstone would explore cooperation
``on an ad hoc basis in a variety of areas,'' but he declined to
comment on what the two firms might do together in Asia, where AIG
has huge existing businesses, but where many companies might
welcome Blackstone with its track record for advice on
restructurings.
</P>
</TEXT>
