<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-PACIFIC-COX     07-30 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PACIFIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific: Asia crisis forces 2 plant closings
 &HT;    By Kristi E. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia-Pacific Corp. was forced to trim 25 percent
of its pulp-making production because of a decline in Asian orders
and weaker foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second-largest paper and wood-products company said
Thursday it's closing market pulp production at plants in Ashdown,
Ark., and Port Hudson, La. They produce almost 25 percent of
Georgia-Pacific pulp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been apparent that this isn't a viable product,''
Georgia-Pacific spokesman Ken Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ashdown plant has 1,300 workers, and the Port Hudson plant
has 875 workers. About 30 people at each plant are being laid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we do not anticipate a turnaround in this market for
at least two years, we are acting sooner rather than later to
mothball these operations,'' Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
A.D. ``Pete'' Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   The workers might be eligible to transfer to other jobs or
plants, depending upon their union contracts, Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   Market pulp is sold on the open market. Most hardwood pulp is
sold overseas. The pulp is combined with other fibers to make
paper.
</P>
<P>
   The paper-producing industry anticipates further declines in
sales in the third quarter because of the weakness in Asian
currencies, said Matt Berler, an analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs will occur over the next month, Haldin said. The
paper manufacturing operations _ which make copy, bond, offset
printing and writing paper _ will remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
