<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-ONE-COX     07-30 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-ONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rumors swirl, but MediaOne denies sale
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Is MediaOne Group, the parent of Atlanta's largest
single cable system, for sale?
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based cable operator has topped Wall Street's
speculative list of prime takeover targets for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill cranked into action again Thursday when Ray Katz,
a prominent media analyst at Bear Stearns, suggested investors were
accumulating MediaOne shares amid speculation the company would be
bought and divided among several cable operators, including Time
Warner and Atlanta-based Cox Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications declined comment on the speculation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has already said it is not interested in MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for us to get bigger,'' said Time Warner
Chairman Gerald Levin last week. ``We're going to build out our
current systems, not add new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Time Warner's 12 million subscribers are 50,000 in
northwest Atlanta, where the company owns a system. That system is
currently being upgraded to handle digital services such as cable
modems and high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   While uninterested himself, Levin has the power to block the
sale of MediaOne to anyone. This right of first refusal is part of
an agreement that controls most of the company's entertainment
assets. MediaOne owns about a quarter of that partnership.
</P>
<P>
   As for MediaOne, its top executives say the company is not for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd never say never,'' says MediaOne Chief Executive Jan
Peters, ``but we're absolutely not for sale. We're happy with our
assets and our strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has 540,000 subscribers in metro Atlanta and is
rebuilding the system to provide digital television, telephone
service and high-speed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
