<HEADER>
A1143 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-ECON-ART-690(2     07-30 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ECON-ART-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY MEXICO'S BANK BAILOUT HELPS THE WEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ If there is anyone who personifies what Mexicans
distrust about their banking system, he is Angel Isidoro Rodriguez
Saez.
</P>
<P>
   For four years when Rodriguez headed a large bank, Mexican
regulators say, he made illegal loans to himself and his family
worth $400 million. When the government seized the bank in 1995,
its bailout program absorbed the huge portfolio of rotten loans
that Rodriguez had left. So far he is facing charges of fraud and
tax evasion covering at least $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans are outraged that Rodriguez, a playboy whose
nickname is The Divine, is out of jail, attending society parties,
appearing on talk shows and going about his new business of running
beachside resorts.
</P>
<P>
   So when the government asked Congress to rescue the program that
rescued Rodriguez's bank, among others, it was met with a revolt. A
newly emboldened opposition in control of the lower house has
seized on Rodriguez's case to open an intense debate over the sins
of the economic elite.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has denied that he committed fraud, promised to pay
his debts and contended that his role in the banking problem had
been overblown.
</P>
<P>
   But that has hardly soothed everyday Mexicans, besieged by high
interest rates and laboring to meet their own debts. Many of those
people say they are convinced that the government is asking them to
bail out Rodriguez and other high-living tycoons who danced away
from their own debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich are being favored, being let off from their debts,
even though they can pay them, while we, the people who suffer in
paying, have to pay,'' said Luis Corona Rodriguez, 49, a bus driver
here, who last weekend joined a small but vociferous demonstration
against the bailout.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy was ignited in March, when finance officials
admitted for the first time that the bailout program had quietly
gone about the business of cleaning up the country's banks by
taking over $62 billion of bad loans. That figure is about 16
percent of what Mexico produces in an entire year, and it was far
higher than experts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The arcane, even tedious legislative discussion that officials
had expected on refinancing the program never occurred. Instead the
government is confronting the question of who should pay for the
errors.
</P>
<P>
   As never before, top officials are being called on the carpet to
account for recurrent economic calamities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the premier moral dilemma Mexico is facing right
now,'' an anti-government social critic, Carlos Monsivais, said.
``We are looking at debts left behind by past official failures.
This government wants to charge the Mexican people infinite sums to
pay for the incompetence of a handful of functionaries and
bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, cobbled together in 1995 in the midst of an
economic cataclysm, brought the banks back from the brink of
collapse to a stable but fragile health. Now that the economy as a
whole is thriving, finance officials are seeking to put the program
on firm footing.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Ministry is asking Congress to allocate millions of
pesos to pay the interest on the loans in the fund and to transfer
those liabilities from the fund to the overall public debt. That
move could increase the public debt, from 26 percent to 42 percent
of the annual gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal turned into a severe political test for Finance
Minister Angel Gurria, revealing the financial acumen and weak
lobbying skills of a man who is often mentioned as a possible
presidential candidate in 2000. Gurria is a charismatic technocrat
who is used to operating in an era, now past, when the opposition
was powerless and the word of a top official was as good as law.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a technocratic fix the government's proposal makes a lot of
sense,'' Manuel Pastor, an economist who specializes in Latin
America at the University of California at Santa Cruz, said. ``Up
to now the technocrats have been the masters of the universe. But
the public is asking for the first time: `What are we getting for
our money? A better financial system or some subsidy to the
wealthy?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even members of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party
have balked at moving the bailout sums to the nation's debt. The
left-leaning Party of the Democratic Revolution has said the fund
is illegal, because Congress never authorized it. The party is
organizing a nationwide referendum on the bailout and calling for a
program to help debtors instead of banks.
</P>
<P>
   No party has suggested that the government should default on the
bailout debts, a move that could imperil the entire banking system.
But after four months of debate the issue has reached an angry
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are finance officials, including Gurria and
Guillermo Ortiz, head of the Banco de Mexico, the central bank, who
have won the trust of the markets for their expertise. Ortiz
initiated the rescue in 1995, when he was finance minister, to help
foundering banks recapitalize and protect Mexicans' deposits.
Investors lauded it as a smart alternative to a financial collapse,
which seemed imminent after a peso devaluation in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the worst moments of the crisis,'' Ortiz recalled in
an interview, ``we never had people lining up to take their money
out of the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are people like Luis Rodriguez, the bus
driver. His family's finances were wiped out when interest rates on
a bank loan topped 100 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come here today because I feel so powerless,''
Rodriguez said. ``It was my young daughter's birthday yesterday,
and what did I give her? I couldn't afford to give her anything but
a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, the Fund for Bank Savings Protection, the
government helped weak banks by buying bad loan portfolios while
requiring investors to inject fresh capital. The government paid
the banks with 10-year Treasury notes that cannot trade on the
markets now and that pay no interest until they come due. The
program protected 100 percent of Mexicans' bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every bank participated. The Treasury notes now amount
to 30 percent of the banking system's assets, far more than the
banks' total capital, according to the Mexican Bankers Association.
The government's latest proposal would let the banks exchange the
notes for a security that could trade for cash.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, 12 of the 19 banks have failed despite government
assistance, and their major stockholders lost all their
investments, an estimated $1.5 billion. Even so, most Mexicans say
they do not believe official statements that the bailout was
enacted to protect their deposits, not bankers' fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Documents released by the bailout agency to Congress show that
604 multimillion-dollar loans that banks made to rich investors,
including Angel Rodriguez, account for nearly half the agency's
debts. The documents suggest that the agency may have
indiscriminately bought questionable or even fraudulent loans to
favor well-known entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also reluctant to hand taxpayers debts to pay down
over 30 years that would cut directly into federal social spending.
Outlays for social spending have dropped 40 percent since 1994,
according to a Congressional study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to accept the government's never-ending
efforts to distribute losses among the Mexican people and
concentrate profits and opportunities among a few of its friends,''
said Alfonso Ramirez Cuellar, a deputy from the Party of the
Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Gurria hit lawmakers with the $62 billion
takeover figure with no prior negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress retaliated by ordering exhaustive audits of the
bailout agency. Despite warnings from finance officials that delays
could undermine investor confidence, the lawmakers delayed action
on the government proposals until after the audits have been
completed, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators have also summoned many current and former
officials who were thought to have been untouchable to testify at
hearings, including former Finance Minister Pedro Aspe.
</P>
<P>
   Among government officials, Ortiz is the most politically
vulnerable. Before becoming finance minister in late 1994, he was
chairman of the committee that sold state-owned banks to private
bankers, including the one that Rodriguez bought.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders have called for Ortiz's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   PRI deputies stormed out of meetings last week in a failed
effort to prevent the opposition from forcing Ortiz to testify. But
Ortiz pointed out that not even President Ernesto Zedillo can
remove him from the bank, which has recently been fortified with
new autonomous powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever accused me of any inappropriate transaction,
of favoring political interests or even of doing political
favors,'' Ortiz said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, whose nickname The Divine comes from a family
restaurant with that name, has become the government's worst
political nightmare. He was arrested in 1996 in Spain while sunning
on his yacht in the Mediterranean. After a two-year legal battle,
Mexico succeeded in extraditing him.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as he returned on 1 June, Mexico's lenient financial
fraud laws allowed him to post bail. Because of outdated bankruptcy
laws, his personal wealth remains untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez acknowledged in an interview that he owed $120 million
to his former bank and others. The loans are languishing in the
bailout fund.
</P>
<P>
   He protested that the officials were exaggerating his
malfeasance. ``The government is trying to make me into a legend,''
Rodriguez said, ``to make it appear that I am a major cause of all
the troubles of the bank bailout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABOR-COSTS-ART-600&AMP;A     07-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-COSTS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGES, BENEFITS SHOW FASTER RATE OF INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite signs that economic growth is slowing sharply, wages and
benefits are climbing a bit faster than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's employment cost index _ a broad gauge of
compensation trends closely watched by the Federal Reserve
chairman, Alan Greenspan, and other policy-makers _ rose
nine-tenths of 1 percent this spring, slightly more than the
seven-tenths of 1 percent increase in the winter. For the 12 months
ended in June, pay for all civilian workers, including government
workers, rose 3.5 percent, up from 2.8 percent in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup in labor costs reflects one of the tightest peacetime
labor markets in memory. Even as the Asian crisis, the recently
settled General Motors strike and a lull in inventory additions
have combined to drag down growth in recent months, unemployment is
well below 5 percent, as it has been for a year, hiring plans have
remained robust and thousands of jobs in industries from high
technology to hotels have gone begging.
</P>
<P>
   The acceleration in wage inflation is of the creeping, rather
than galloping, variety: Pay and benefits are rising just one
percentage point faster than at the low-point for such cost
increases nearly three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the latest reading is not likely to provoke Greenspan,
who only a week ago reiterated how closely he watches the index, to
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't moved into new territory,'' said Nicholas Perna,
chief economist at Fleet Financial Group in Boston. ``This report
reduces the odds that the Fed will tighten.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since unemployment first slipped below the level that most
economists regard as consistent with steady inflation, the Federal
Reserve has been on the lookout for any hint that wage pressures
are getting out of hand. But now that the economy seems to be
slowing on its own, the modest pickup in pay may well show up in
slimmer profit margins rather than in higher prices for consumers.
Investors, in any case, seemed to take that view. Bond prices rose
after the report's release, and the stock market closed higher
ahead of Thursday's much anticipated report on economic growth for
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are getting a better deal than the raw numbers imply.
Thanks to a minuscule 1.6 percent rise in the cost of living over
the last year, relatively restrained nominal pay increases are
being translated into relatively robust real gains. Real pay is up
nearly 2 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the employment cost index, though widely regarded
as the broadest and most reliable gauge of employers' labor costs,
may understate just how well workers are doing. It does not include
one-time payments like signing bonuses and bounties, which
businesses are increasingly relying on to fill vacancies without
raising their entire pay structure. It also does not take account
of another widespread phenomenon: promotions that are given purely
to raise a worker's pay or promotions that workers give themselves
by switching to better-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One sign that these factors may add up is that another
Department of Labor measure, compensation per hour, has risen about
a percentage point more in the last year than the employment cost
index. ``We're seeing some dramatic wage inflation'' in some job
categories, says Maury Hanigan, a human resources consultant in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Wages and salaries grew nine-tenths of 1 percent, not much more
than the eight-tenths of 1 percent growth in the winter. But
benefit costs jumped sharply to eight-tenths of 1 percent, twice as
fast as they had risen in the previous quarter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Part of the pickup in benefit costs is probably temporary; it
reflects commissions and bonuses being paid on Wall Street and
elsewhere in the financial industry, where compensation has risen
by 7 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But at least half of the benefits, including Social Security
payments and vacation pay, are tied directly to wages. And
one-fifth consist of health benefits, which are once again marching
higher. ``Health insurance costs are picking up for the first time
in three and a half years,'' said Wayne Shelly, an economist at the
Bureau of Labor Statistics, which issued the report.
</P>
<P>
   Wage pressures may not fade. Some of the forces holding down
living costs are clearly temporary. As Asia struggles back, oil
prices are apt to firm. And the strong dollar, which has made many
imports a bargain, could weaken.
</P>
<P>
   More important, even if the economy settles down to a growth
rate of 2 percent or 2.5 percent over the next year or so _ as
Greenspan and other forecasters expect _ it will not be slow enough
to loosen up the labor market much. ``The unemployment rate stays
exactly where it is,'' Perna predicted. ``The overall degree of
tightness stays exactly where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other reports made public Thursday suggest that this is the
case right now. The Conference Board reported that its help-wanted
advertising index rose to 91 in June from 90 in May and 88 a year
ago. And new claims for unemployment insurance dropped to 304,000
last week from 317,000 the week before, the Labor Department said.
That's the lowest level since the beginning of April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
