<P>
   WELLPOINT-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ WellPoint Health Networks
shares fell 16 percent after the managed health-care company said
it took charges of $108.6 million that resulted in a second-quarter
loss. WellPoint shares fell 10 5/8 to 61 in midmorning trading of
1.38 million, more than four times its three-month daily average,
earlier hitting 60 1/2. California's second-largest health insurer
said it will sell its money-losing workers' compensation unit and
write off an investment in troubled physician-practice manager FPA
Medical Management Inc. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FREEWAY-SHOOTERS (Los Angeles) _ In the fourth freeway shooting
in two weeks, three gunman wounded a motorist shortly before dawn
near Griffith Park. Three men with shaved heads in a green Honda
Civic were northbound on Interstate 5 near the Colorado Boulevard
off-ramp when they fired several rounds at the victim's car. By
Alex Roth. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   FIREFIGHTER-GIVEBACK (Los Angeles) _ Glendale firefighter Bill
Jensen is recovered and back working, but in a new way. On Thursday
Jensen, one of two Glendale firefighters seriously injured in the
Calabasas-Malibu wildfires in 1996, gave $25,000 he raised in June
to the Sherman Oaks Burn Center and the Firefighters Quest for Burn
Survivors. Jensen was burned over more than 75 percent of his body
and endured more than 15 surgeries during his long recovery.
Jensen's left arm is still in a sling, but said he is hopeful that
future surgeries will help him regain use of his left hand and arm.
Now, he's turned it around and is raising funds for other burn
survivors. By Lee Condon. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   NFL-TO-LA (Los Angeles) _ Should Los Angeles be home to another
football team, and what comes next in its bid to be a gridiron
city? The Los Angeles Sports and Entertainment Commission will
attempt to answer these and other questions during a day-long
conference on football. Jerry Richardson, owner of the Carolina
Panthers and chairman of the NFL Stadium Committee is the keynote.
By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California, ``a'' national
and ``s'' sports files.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
