<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, GORE STRESS ENVIRONMENTAL RECORD IN NORTH CAROLINA
CEREMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHE COUNTY, N.C. _ Seeking to polish the administration's
environmental credentials, President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore traveled to the bucolic southwest corner of this state to
confer special status on one of the oldest rivers in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony on the banks of the New River, Clinton designated
the waterway one of 14 American Heritage Rivers, which will make it
easier for local officials to receive federal help for
environmental cleanup and preservation of cultural landmarks along
its path.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ancient river has flowed through the heart of this land
for millions of years,'' Clinton told the crowd that endured humid
heat and a brief rain to catch a glimpse of the present.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Gore unveiled the list of 14 rivers that won
the national competition for the special designation. The rivers
include the Rio Grande in Texas, the Potomac in Washington, D.C.,
and the Hudson in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The New River, which flows northward from North Carolina,
through Virginia to West Virginia, is estimated to be about 320
million years old. In the 1960s, residents of this largely rural
mountainous region successfully fought a plan to build a dam across
the river, a victory that was alluded to several times during the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Clinton tried to stress that their environmental agenda
has not come at the cost of jobs, a criticism often leveled at
environmentalists by conservatives. Gore noted that river
renaissances across the country have served as a ``catapult to
create jobs.'' And Clinton said that the American Heritage River
program did not include federal mandates or restrictions on
property holders' rights.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton praised bipartisan support for the river program,
he chided the Republican leadership in Congress for blocking his
other environmental initiatives, including clean water funding and
money for land purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some folks in Congress are no longer committed to bipartisan
progress,'' he said, adding ``they want to put off for another
day'' work on environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Clinton flew to Raleigh to attend a
fund-raiser and rally for John Edwards, the Democratic Senate
candidate who is opposing incumbent Republican Sen. Lauch
Faircloth. The fund-raiser cost $5,000 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat ceremony next to the serene river stood in stark
contrast to the turbulent politics of Washington where Clinton is
facing increasing pressure from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr,
who this week granted immunity to Monica Lewinsky to tell about her
alleged affair with the president. Clinton also has agreed to
provide videotaped testimony to Starr's grand jury to avoid being
subpoenaed by the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But those interviewed in the supportive crowd did not appear
terribly concerned about the recent developments, with several
saying they didn't care about the president's private life and
others speculating that Lewinsky had ulterior motives for making
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's just in it for the fame and money,'' said Betty
Lou Houck, 50, of Ashe County, who was waiting for the president to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica is out for Monica. We got other things to worry about
without this dirt,'' said Amy Craig, a 42-year old single mother
who said she wanted to tell the president how she got off welfare
and escaped an abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Craig said she hoped that Clinton was telling the
truth when he vowed that he never had an affair with the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Winebarger said she didn't condone the president's conduct
if he did have the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he should have done it. After all he is a public
figure,'' said the 37-year old nursing home worker. But Winebarger
said, ``It's between him, Hillary and God.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Vicky Glenn, 32, said she didn't care about the
president's private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as long as he takes care of the world's business,'' the
factory worker said. Glenn also admitted she hasn't been following
the scandal story and said she didn't know who independent counsel
Starr is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
