<HEADER>
A1175 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-HMO-REACT-AR     07-30 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMO-REACT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO SENIORS DISTRAUGHT BY MEDICARE HMO THAT CAME AND WENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Calif., S.C., Utah)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIQUA, Ohio _ For the elderly and disabled people of this weary
looking city surrounded by cornfields, Anthem Blue Cross &AMP; Blue
Shield's Medicare health maintenance organization was a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   It bought a motorized scooter for Ronnie Hines, who has diabetes
and multiple sclerosis. It diagnosed Dorothy Kloecker's shallow
breathing disorder, after many tests, and helped her to control it
with daily two-hour walks through the hilly cemetery. It removed
the benign but disconcerting lump in Rosie Stelzner's jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem provided exactly the kind of aggressive
prevention-oriented care that Congress and other health planners
envisioned when they opened up the 33-year-old Medicare program to
HMOs and other forms of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not last long. In late May, just a year and a half
after it started its Medicare HMO here, Anthem announced that it
was discontinuing the service as of Dec. 31 in 19 Ohio counties and
parts of three others. The decision affected 18,235 elderly
clients, including many in Piqua (pronounced pick-wah and less
often pick-way).
</P>
<P>
   Becky Howe, 50, who has a degenerative joint disease, expressed
the view of many of the elderly subscribers when she said:``They
gave us life. Now they're trying to suck that life out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Two subscribers have filed a class-action suit in an effort to
stop Anthem from pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem officials said their company, which has successfully
operated a Medicare HMO around Cincinnati, about 75 miles south,
for three years, found itself over-extended, over-subscribed and
under-paid by the federal government when it expanded. Its
experience highlights the difficulties managed care companies face
as they try to extend service to Medicare clients outside the
bigger cities _ and the upheaval that results when these companies
stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem's retreat, like those of other HMOs recently from 10
counties in California, 10 in South Carolina and the whole state of
Utah, also casts a shadow over the decision by Congress and the
Clinton administration, as part of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act, to
steer more of the nation's retirees into managed care.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to slow the 10 percent annual increases in federal
spending for Medicare and the even sharper increases some expect as
the baby-boom generation retires. Encouraging competition among
managed care companies for Medicare beneficiaries, they reasoned,
would mean more benefits for the elderly and lower costs for the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Here, however, managed care for the elderly and disabled is
going, not coming, and in the process it is doing exactly what many
critics feared: Building expectations among the elderly, then
dashing them, leaving the subscribers angry and confused.
</P>
<P>
   Until just a few months ago, three commercial television
channels carried commercials for Anthem Senior Advantage, the
Medicare HMO. The benefits over traditional Medicare were clear:
Prescriptions would cost just $5 to $15; doctor visits $5; there
would be no deductibles, no premiums and no charges at all for
hospitalization, and there would be free screenings and free
preventive care.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, by contrast, charges patients 20 percent of doctors'
bills and $760 of their initial hospital expenses. It does not
cover preventive care or most medicine or screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the number,'' said Mrs. Kloecker, 77, and signed up
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kloecker told Mrs. Stelzner, 73, who also called. ``I asked
them, `Is my doctor in this?''' Mrs. Stelzner said. Assured that he
was, she signed up, too.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the television commercials, Anthem sent a sales agent
around. He knocked on Dolly Floss' door. Mrs. Floss, 58, is
diabetic and has been disabled and unemployable since a patient she
was treating as a nurse's aide fell on her back and shattered four
disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you think this is too good to be true, wait till
you see the other things coming along,''' she said. `` `Eyeglasses,
hearing aides, dental.' I could get my testing strips. I'm supposed
to test my blood sugar eight times a day.'' The strips cost $48 for
a box of 50, so she had been testing just four or five times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Then the cancellation notice arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Hirsch, 69, who lives in a 25-year-old mobile home on a
Social Security check of $906 a month after losing two husbands to
death, said: ``I called Anthem. I was very upset. They said,
`Nothing is guaranteed.' I had great faith in Blue Cross &AMP; Blue
Shield. But that went down the drain. They had never done anything
as underhanded as this.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are just as peeved. Ohio Gov. George Voinovich, a
Republican candidate for the Senate seat being vacated by Sen. John
Glenn, a Democrat, has publicly rebuked the company and ordered an
investigation. The state Legislature sharply questioned Anthem
officials at a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told people, `As long as Medicare is around, we're going
to be around,' '' said state Rep. David Hobson, a Republican whose
distract includes four counties that have lost Anthem's Medicare
HMO.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Keller, spokeswoman for the Ohio office of the American
Association of Retired Persons in Columbus, noted that managed care
had been widely proclaimed as the salvation of the Medicare
program, and argued that the Anthem experience should trouble
Congress on two counts.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it erode the elderly's confidence in managed care,
Ms. Keller said, but it can also disrupt their treatment, pushing
them back into traditional fee-for-service medicine without the
preventative care that many HMOs promise.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 18,235 subscribers affected, 6,500 live in Miami County,
which includes Piqua, and five other counties where they are left
with no HMO at all. Many of Anthem's HMO subscribers have incomes
of $10,000 or $15,000 a year, mostly from Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Piqua's retirees had Medigap insurance to cover the 20
percent of doctors' fees that Medicare does not, and they gave it
up. Mrs. Stelzner expects to get hers back, at a cost of $238.60
every two months. But that will not be possible for everyone
affected, and some others whose whose health has deteriorated might
have to pay more for it.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the elderly accuse Anthem of discrimination. They point
out that the company has offered the Senior Advantage program in
Dayton, a half-hour away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're redlining,'' said Bruce Knisley, whose wife is
confined to their home by multiple sclerosis. ``It's like being
told you can't have a mortgage because of your age and where you
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthem, with headquarters in a new granite and glass suburban
office building just north of Cincinnati, acknowledges excesses in
trying to enroll Medicare recipients, in part to capture them
before competitors did.
</P>
<P>
   Having offered its Senior Advantage program successfully in
seven counties in and around Cincinnati for three years, Anthem
began expanding to 37 more counties at the start of last year. By
the end of the year, enrollment had leaped to 56,000 from 16,000,
and it is now up to 63,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what hit us, we were growing so fast,'' said
Lynne Gross, Anthem's vice president for government programs. ``We
didn't predict the high sales in rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The more beneficiaries Anthem enrolled, the more money it lost,
in part because of the Balanced Budget Act, which restrains
spending for Medicare. In an analysis of last year's results, Ms.
Gross said the company discovered that in urban areas it collected
an average of $389 a month in Medicare reimbursements for each
subscriber and spent $345, for a profit of $44. But in rural areas,
it collected $325 and spent $361, losing $36, with the lower
reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem also discovered that conventional Medicare, with its
traditional fee-for-service copayments and deductibles, was a
luxury that relatively poor retirees in places like Miami County
often shunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people saying for the first time, `I'm beginning to
live!''' Ms. Gross said. ``Fee-for-service wasn't meeting the needs
of these folks. I think managed care in rural communities may have
created a demand for care where there wasn't any care before.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pradip Vyas, an internist and primary care physician for
many of Anthem's Miami County subscribers, said the company
improved their health. Now Vyas asks: ``How will I convince my
patients to continue preventive medicine? They will have to pay out
of pocket, and many do not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there are cautionary lessons in Ohio for federal
health planners. Congress' new Medicare program greatly expands
upon more than a decade of efforts to encourage the 33.5 million
elderly and 5 million disabled beneficiaries to enroll in managed
care.
</P>
<P>
   Called Medicare Plus Choice, the new program still allows people
to choose regular Medicare. But it also lets them choose among a
variety of alternatives, primarily several forms of managed care
plans.
</P>
<P>
   For each subscriber, the Health Care Financing Administration
pays HMOs 95 percent of the average that the agency spends each
year for people who use Medicare's fee-for-service care.
</P>
<P>
   The base rates vary widely by county, from less than $400 a
month in rural areas to almost $800 in New York City. To make the
lower-rate areas more appealing to HMOs, Congress set up a formula
to shrink the variations, but so far it has not enhanced the
economic appeal of rural areas for HMOs. In addition, Congress
limited increases in most reimbursement rates to just 2 percent _
less than the rise in health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   So now, with their reimbursements squeezed, more HMOs are
charging subscribers premiums and reducing free benefits, and in
rural areas, they have begun closing their doors. Others are
scaling back plans to move into the areas..
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, ``that Anthem
made some monumental mistakes and over-promised what they could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeWine added: ``It would not shock me if Anthem is just the
beginning of this. The preliminary evidence would indicate that
there is a bigger issue than Anthem making bad business
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, DeWine said, ``one of the goals has been more
choice for Medicare recipients. That's one thing my constituents
tell me they want, and that's been a legitimate object of what we
should strive for. Choice is vitally important.''
</P>
<P>
   It was vitally important to Dolly Floss, who with Anthem's
departure is losing her free testing strips. ``I don't have a
choice,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
