<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: St. Louis Cardinals
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight at 7:40 p.m., Saturday at 1:15 p.m., Sunday at
1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: Fox Sports South will telecast tonight, WAGA will
telecast Saturday, and TBS Sunday. 750-AM will broadcast all three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, RHP Greg Maddux (14-4,
1.59; 17-13, 2.40 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs. RHP Todd Stottlemyre
(9-9, 3.51; 0-0, 3.00 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday, LHP Tom
Glavine (14-4, 2.68; 11-4, 3.85 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs. LHP
Kent Mercker (6-8, 5.94; 0-2, 6.35). Sunday, RHP Kevin Millwood
(11-6, 4.39; 0-0, 5.06 lifetime vs. Cardinals) vs. RHP Kent
Bottenfield (3-5, 4.73; 1-1, 2.25).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: Atlanta trails the all-time series 181-218 but
has lost just one season series to the Cardinals since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves swept a two-game series at St. Louis
on May 13-14, setting the league record for consecutive games with
home runs at 25 the first night and scoring seven times in the
eighth inning the second night in a 7-3 victory. John Rocker got
his first major-league victory.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: The Cardinals are 9-11 since the All-Star break,
entering Thursday night's game with Milwaukee. Although St. Louis
is sixth in the league in runs scored (4.9 per game), the club has
been undone by pitching troubles all season. Injuries to Alan
Benes, Matt Morris and Donovan Osborne made a shambles of the
rotation from Opening Day, and the team has tried 13 starters along
the way. The bullpen's ERA (4.78) is the third-highest in the
league, and Cardinals' relievers have been forced into the NL's
heaviest workload (363.1 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: Ray Lankford is hitting .351 since the All-Star
break. John Mabry has had two-hit games in four of his last eight
starts. Rookie reliever Rick Croushore has converted seven-of-eight
save chances, with 37 strikeouts in 37 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: Tom Pagnozzi is 4-for-21 (.190) since the break.
Willie McGee is hitting .242 on the road. Reliever John Frascatore,
who leads the team in appearances, has a 4.41 ERA with 70 hits and
28 walks allowed in 69 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
