A1181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGWIRE-COMPUTE-COX     07-30 0209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGWIRE-COMPUTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Against the Hall
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution wanted to know how its Hall of
Fame rotation _ Tom Seaver, Ferguson Jenkins, Gaylord Perry and
Warren Spahn _ would match up against Mark McGwire on a computer.
So Diamond Mind Software (www.diamond-mind.com), which correctly
predicted the outcome of every game in the big series between the
Braves and Yankees in June, was called on once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' everyday lineup, with McGwire hitting third,
faced each of the Hall of Fame pitchers, with Rollie Fingers coming
on in relief. The computer company used numbers from the pitchers'
best seasons: 1981 for Fingers, 1974 for Jenkins, 1972 for Perry,
1969 for Seaver and 1953 for Spahn. The results were not good for
Big Mac. He went 2-for-16 with one home run and four strikeouts
against the Hall of Famers. He was 0-for-4 against Jenkins with one
strikeout; 1-for-4 against Perry with a double and run scored;
0-for-3 against Seaver with two strikeouts; and 1-for-4 against
Spahn with a homer and strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   He faced Fingers once, hitting into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
