<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGWIRE-COX     07-30 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGWIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to retire McGWIRE
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Perhaps the pitchers of today should take a hint from
an old master when it comes to pitching to Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would try to keep McGwire in the park, 314-game
winner Gaylord Perry smiled _ and licked his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Perry's infamous spitball is the ticket; nothing seems to
be working for today's pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has 45 home runs in 105 games, hitting one home run
every 7.3 at-bats. He has walked 110 times, once every four plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   His homers have gone an estimated total of 18,884 feet, or 3.58
miles. And it's not even August yet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when the Braves and Cardinals begin a three-game series
at Turner Field, McGwire will hit against arguably the best
pitching staff in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the perfect swing right now,'' San Diego pitching coach
Merv Rettenmond said. ``He sees the ball better now than he used
to, and he's much stronger. He's matured as a person, and he's had
the desire to get better as a player. He's the ultimate power
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pitchers have had success, none more than Toronto's Roger
Clemens, who used to feed the 6-foot-5, 250-pound McGwire a steady
diet of fastballs inside on his hands. Clemens felt that McGwire's
biceps and quadriceps were so big that he wouldn't be able to get
his bat around quickly enough to hit a hard inside pitch. Perhaps
he was right; the result was four hits (two of them home runs) in
47 at-bats against Clemens, a future member of the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The game's other top pitching staffs have not been so fortunate.
In short, they have been pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one dream staff McGwire has not faced. And will not
face. Call it The Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff. The starters
are overpowering right-handers Tom Seaver and Ferguson Jenkins;
Perry, the spitball pitcher; and crafty left-hander Warren Spahn.
Rollie Fingers is the relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   This Hall of Fame rotation won 1,272 games, struck out 12,949
batters, won seven Cy Youngs and threw four no-hitters. Fingers had
341 saves and was the first reliever to win a Cy Young Award and
the Most Valuable Player in the same year (1981).
</P>
<P>
   Batter up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has weaknesses; I don't care who you are,'' Seaver
said. ``Obviously, (if) you put something in on his hands, it's
going to be tough on him. But I can see that it can be difficult to
throw to him inside. He is so big that he makes the strike zone
look much smaller when you are standing on the mound. Plus, if you
make a mistake and leave that ball out over the plate, he is so
quick (that) he is going to hit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe people are afraid to pitch him inside,'' Seaver said.
``I would keep going inside on him and not worry if I walked him. I
think I could get him out, because he is right-handed. I always had
a lot of success against hitters like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appears McGwire has made adjustments and is doing a
better job of hitting pitches on his hands. His swing has become
more compact.
</P>
<P>
   Astros catcher Brad Ausmus thought his pitchers could attack
McGwire on the hands. Left-hander Pete Schourek tried. McGwire hit
one pitch into the third deck in the Astrodome but just foul.
Ausmus called for the same pitch again later in the series. McGwire
homered to left off Jose Lima.
</P>
<P>
   So Jenkins said he would use a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would go with a hard slider away,'' Jenkins said.
``I would make him reach out well over the plate, which should take
away some of his power. But I wouldn't walk him. I never walked
guys like that when I played. I always tried to challenge them, see
if I could get them out. I don't know if pitchers today challenge
like they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jenkins pitched there were plenty of power hitters,
including Hank Aaron, Willie Mays and Harmon Killebrew. But he says
McGwire reminds him of 6-foot-6, 210-pound Dave Kingman, an earlier
intimidating figure in the batter's box. Jenkins said there's one
big difference: ``Mark is a much more selective hitter than Dave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave was scary-looking in that box, and I imagine so is
Mark,'' Jenkins said. ``But Dave struck out (1,816 times, fifth
all-time). Look at the number of walks Mark has. That's pretty
impressive. So you really can't get him to go looking for a bad
pitch. You're going to have to give him something in the strike
zone if you're not going to walk him. I like something hard on the
outside corner.''
</P>
<P>
   It would need to be close on the corner. McGwire is a
disciplined hitter. But as the chase gets down to cases, pitchers
will begin nibbling at the corners in an effort to turn off the
power.
</P>
<P>
   Spahn was one of the best at nibbling. He had an excellent
curveball and pitched on the corners, much as Greg Maddux does
today. Spahn would prefer to keep McGwire off-balance, by mixing up
his pitches, a strategy often used on big sluggers by working the
ball inside and outside. ``I'd pitch him inside, but I'd also throw
something down and away.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry agreed. ``You can't get in a pattern against a hitter like
that,'' he said. ``I really think he likes fastballs up and in. I
would probably throw a slider down and away.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perry also would use another strategy: ``I would work awful
hard on trying to get out the other players around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fingers said he would use one pitch for McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would throw him a slider outside,'' he said. ``That's the
hardest pitch in the world to hit. If you don't get him to hit your
pitch, then you walk him and shouldn't be embarrassed about it.
Make guys like that hit your pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   So different pitchers have different answers. Hard and inside.
Down and away. A slider outside. Nibble the corners.
</P>
<P>
   The one constant is respect. McGwire, 34, has 432 homers in his
career and is the second-fastest to reach 400. Depending on how
many more he hits this year, if he averages about 42 homers during
the next five years, he will pass Mays (660) and finish behind only
Aaron (755) and Babe Ruth (714).
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps Perry is right. Maybe finding a way to doctor the
ball is the only way to get McGwire out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's so good,'' Perry said, ``he would probably hit that,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
