<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rose's advice: Enjoy the ride
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Pete Rose has chased all kinds of baseball records.
</P>
<P>
   So he knows exactly how Mark McGwire feels about all the
attention from the media, fans and company representatives with
endorsement possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have fun with it,'' Rose advised last week during an interview
in Cooperstown, N.Y., where he was signing autographs during the
Hall of Fame weekend. ``He has to be having fun hitting all those
home runs with his little kid standing there as a bat boy. And
that's what I like about McGwire. Whenever they show him playing,
he is smiling. So, just have fun. It's got to be a blast what he is
going through. He is chasing a great record and has a good chance
of breaking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose also offered advice on how to deal with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't fight them,'' Rose said. ``Deal with the media and don't
try to ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was going through the (44-game) hitting streak and then
going after Ty Cobb's record, I used to have a press conference
before the game and after it. That way the rest of my teammates
weren't bothered, because the media knew where they could get me. I
liked talking to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is not as accessible, and at times he has become
impatient and terse with the media. The Cardinals have set limits
on his accessibility during the home run chase, holding a press
conference before the first game of a series. McGwire can be
interviewed after games, but he usually get upsets if he is asked
about his home runs, especially if the Cardinals lose.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about home run No. 45 after a 13-10 loss to Milwaukee
on Tuesday night, McGwire told the reporter, ``That's a stupid
question.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions will increase as McGwire approaches Roger Maris'
record of 61. When Rose was chasing Cobb's all-time hits record, he
became infatuated with Cobb. He spent hours reading about him. But
Rose points out that there was a difference between his pursuit of
Cobb and McGwire's pursuit of Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to eventually break that mark,'' Rose said.
``It was just a matter of time. Mark has only a certain amount of
games to hit 61.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose also has another suggestion for McGwire, one that might
help him when he steps on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just relax when you are not in the batter's box,'' Rose said.
``The only time you have to concentrate on the pitcher is when you
get in the batter's box. You don't have to concentrate on the
pitcher when you are in the dugout, the clubhouse, the on-deck
circle. You can't hit it then. So save your concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
