<SLUG> BC-DEEP-ART-REVIEW-620(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEEP STORAGE': COLLECTORS WHO SEEK THE INNATE ORDER OF CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)   (Eds.: Exhibition notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The instinct to preserve, strong in most people, can
run especially deep in artists. Their desire to leave a record of
their beliefs, lives, times or inner states has been in effect at
least since the time of the Lascaux cave paintings, to the great
benefit of the world's cultures.
</P>
<P>
   In modern times, the artist's instinct to preserve has sometimes
crossed wires with a more institutional expression of that drive:
the museum or archive. The motivations have been many. Some artists
have been inspired by the museum's encyclopedic example or by a
desire to subvert and satirize its esthetic assumptions and vast
storehouses of art. Others have felt compelled to confront the
deluge of images, objects and events that press upon us all,
attempting to reveal their underlying order or chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of new recording tools, from the camera to the
computer, has played a role, as have the influences of recent art
movements. These include Minimalism's emphasis on serialism and
repetition; Conceptual Art's fascination with randomness, vast
systems outside art and pure fact, and performance art's inherent
dependence on documentation. In recent years, the artist as
collector, archivist, curator or documentarian has become a
familiar figure.
</P>
<P>
   Early precedents for the artist-as-archivist include the
projects of Eugene Atget and August Sander, who at the turn of the
century set out to photographically record, respectively, the city
of Paris and the German people, with extraordinary results.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the focus has been far narrower: Marcel Duchamp's
``Green Box,'' containing drawings, notes and reproductions,
documents and annotates the creation of his masterpiece ``The Large
Glass'' and is itself a work of art. Somewhere in between is Claes
Oldenburg's ``Mouse Museum,'' a collection of 385 small objects _
found, altered or made by the artist _ that comment on American
popular culture and consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   With Duchamp's ``Green Box'' among its jumping off points,
``Deep Storage: Collecting, Storing and Archiving in Art'' at the
PS 1 Contemporary Art Center in Long Island City sets out to
document the urge to document in recent art. This exhibition of
more than 100 works by nearly 40 American and European artists is
terrific in spots and predictable in others. But it taps into an
important strain of contemporary art and confirms once again that
the most successful group exhibitions of the moment are based on
shared ideas, not visual styles.
</P>
<P>
   In this case the idea originated in an essay by the critic
Ingrid Shaffner and eventually expanded to involve five curators
and a thick, handsome catalog with essays by 15 writers. Sponsored
by the Siemens Cultural Program, it was first shown at the Haus der
Kunst in Munich last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moving between artists of different generations, sensibilities
and media, the show covers a lot of ground, sometimes sketchily, if
only because some monumental works, including Oldenburg's ``Mouse
Museum'' and Gerhard Richter's ``Atlas,'' which were included in
Munich, are not here.
</P>
<P>
   But particularly memorable is the opening gallery, on the
center's third floor, where the visitor is confronted by Jason
Rhoades' towering ``Great See Battles of Wilhelm Schurmann,'' a
compartmentalized structure that takes the boxed artwork to
monumental extremes. Part steamer trunk, part altar, part
collector's cabinet, it contains an elaborate installation work
that recapitulates the complex life of Schurmann, a well-known
German photography collector. To either side are the wryly memorial
paintings of David Deutsch, each depicting part of an enormous
basilicalike dome lined with indistinct portraits _ a pantheon of
patriarchal fuzziness.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Arranged around the gallery are different expressions of the
collecting or storing impulse, which echo throughout the
exhibition. Douglas Blau's ``All of Tomorrow's Parties No. 2'' is a
moveable picture archive that features dozens of found images of
social gatherings, gleaned from stage, screen and art history.
Museum practices are variously sent up by H.C. Westermann's
``Second Shotgun,'' which comes with its own beautifully made
shipping-crate pedestal, and Louise Lawler's laconic photographs of
actual museum storerooms, where odd assortments of art objects
forlornly reflect vast holdings rarely exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   What might be called the bean-counter approach achieves grand
and pure heights in ``1,000,000 Years Past'' and ``1,000,000 Years
Future,'' by the well-known Conceptualist On Kawara. Each consists
of 10 thick, leather-bound volumes that count out a million years,
year by year. (Related but more elliptical are a series of poems by
David Bunn, each consisting of consecutive titles in the card
catalog of the Los Angeles Public Library.) Thomas Virnich's
``Weltkugel,'' a giant rough globe made from a mulch of maps and
atlases, is one of several works in which material and concept
collide in amusing ways.
</P>
<P>
   The show includes suspects both usual and not, and often
obscures the line between art and archive. Marcel Broodthaers and
Joseph Beuys are predictably present, as is an example of Edward
Ruscha's 1966 fold-out book, ``Every Building on the Sunset
Strip.''
</P>
<P>
   But the curators have also included the boxlike assemblages of
Hannelore Baron and five of the 106 ``Time Capsules'' that Andy
Warhol, an obsessive collector, assembled and preserved. The
contents of one capsule, including mail, magazine and exhibition
announcements, line the bottom of a large vitrine. Downstairs, a
little-known German artist, Karsten Bott, achieves an even more
obsessive effect with ``One of Each,'' a wall-to-wall display of
thousands of carefully ordered small objects that is viewed from a
raised walkway. This piece is but one selection in a 10-year
project titled ``Archive of Everyday History.''
</P>
<P>
   Another entry in the less-than-familiar column is Joseph
Cornell's ``Crystal Cage (Portrait of Bernice),'' a 20-year
accumulation of images that document the life of an imaginary
little girl. And one of the show's most fascinating surprises is a
small selection from ``Atlas of Memory,'' a display of art
reproductions, often rephotographed in thematic groupings, that
were amassed by the art historian Aby Warburg.
</P>
<P>
   The implicit chaos of Nam June Paik's ``Box for Zen
(Serenade),'' a jumble of objects in a suitcase, which figured in
the artist's early Fluxus performances, contrasts strikingly with
the handsome, strictly categorized photographs of the German
artists Bernd and Hilla Becher, who have spent more than three
decades documenting the massive industrial structures of 19th- and
20th-century Germany and America.
</P>
<P>
   In a downstairs gallery, the Bechers' project is poignantly yet
powerfully echoed in one of the show's high points: ``Detonation
Deutschland,'' a carefully orchestrated video installation by Piero
Steinle and Julian Rosenfeldt of Munich. In a darkened, mirrored
hall, seven screens periodically erupt with the sights and sounds
of old or bomb-damaged buildings being blown up during the
rebuilding of Germany after World War II. An archive in motion, the
work converts the march of progress into a bombardment of
mesmerizing beauty, inflected with violence, tragedy and human
folly.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DEEP STORAGE: COLLECTING, STORING AND ARCHIVING IN ART'
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is at the PS 1 Contemporary Art Center, 22-25
Jackson Ave. at 46th Avenue, Long Island City, Queens, through Aug.
30. It will be shown at the Henry Art Gallery in Seattle from Nov.
5 to Jan. 31. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
