<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAS ONE MORE CHANCE TO COME CLEAN  
 (THIS EDITORIAL IS APPEARING IN FRIDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time and again, President Clinton has demonstrated he is an
accomplished performer before the camera. He has wriggled and
charmed his way out of any number of scrapes and embarrassing
messes. On Aug. 17, in what may be a defining moment of his
presidency, Clinton will have an opportunity to go before a camera
and tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the embattled president, flanked by his lawyers,
will submit to questioning by Independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
The interrogation will be videotaped in the White House for Starr's
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   With or without Clinton's full cooperation, Starr's six-month
investigation into allegations of perjury, witness tampering and
obstruction of justice stemming from charges of an affair between
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky will move, mercifully, close to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Congress would like to wash its hands of the whole
tawdry matter. Based on Starr's findings, members of the House must
decide whether to hold impeachment proceedings. Given enough
evidence, Congress has no choice but to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   The public has had its fill of this sordid chapter, in between
being titillated and repulsed as each episode has been reported.
Clinton's charm and a booming economy have served as a buffer
against a concerted public outcry, but even his most ardent
supporters have grown weary and impatient with a man who seems
perfectly incapable of telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to allow Clinton to have lawyers present at the
videotaping, Starr provided an important concession. That is a
privilege, as we have pointed out, not enjoyed by other witnesses.
However, Clinton, and the nation, will be spared the embarrassing
spectacle of a president heading into a courthouse to testify in a
case in which he is the prime target.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clinton come clean and tell the truth in a few weeks? Given
his powers of persuasion, Clinton could go before the country
today, tomorrow, and confess to having a sexual relationship with
`that woman,'' and many would likely forgive and move on.
</P>
<P>
   But some speculate that Clinton will adhere to the strategy of
dissembling and denying an affair with Lewinsky. Of course, in
weighing his options, Clinton must deal with the testimony of
Lewinsky, Linda Tripp and Secret Service agents, among others. And
then there is the dress. News reports have raised anew the
possbility of a dress stained from an encounter between Clinton and
Lewinsky. Such physical evidence would be impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has an opportunity, yet one more time, to be open with
the American public and tell the truth. Judging from an
increasingly weary public, that door is closing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
