<HEADLINE>
UNSER JR. HAS BITTERSWEET RETURN TO INDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ His last hot laps around the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway earned Al Unser Jr. an embarrassing DNQ.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Did Not Qualify'' still haunts Little Al, who was the
reigning Indianapolis 500 champion when he failed to crack the
33-car starting lineup in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent split between the Indy Racing League and
Championship Auto Racing Teams has kept Unser and team owner Roger
Penske _ a couple of card-carrying CART loyalists _ out of Gasoline
Alley for three years. But Unser's exile at Indy is scheduled to
end today, in the finale of the True Value International Race of
Champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have mixed feelings. I'd be remiss if I said I didn't,''
said Unser, one of 12 drivers from various forms of motorsports
scheduled to run the 100-mile sprint in identically prepared
Pontiac Firebirds. The full-fendered IROC Firebirds making their
first racing appearances at the Speedway have nothing in common
with the rear-engined rockets Unser Jr. has been driving since
1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely want to come back here and race in a
single-seat, open-wheeled car in the month of May,'' said Unser,
the Indy 500 champion in 1992 and 1994. ``But yes, it's going to
ease the pain a little bit. The main thing is it gives me an
opportunity to get back out there _ between those walls _ and
relive some of the moments that I've had there in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of four-time Indy 500 champion Al Unser and nephew of
three-time race-winner Bobby Unser, Little Al admittedly grew up
with the notion of racing at the Speedway as his birthright. His
first victory here in May 1992 produced the then-closest finish in
the race's history, 0.043-seconds in front of Scott Goodyear.
Victory No. 2 in May 1994 was one of eight races Unser won in 16
starts en route to his second CART PPG Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Even in defeat, Unser has been cast as a modern-day gladiator.
His late-race tangle and backward crash into the Turn 3 concrete
wall during the 1989 race led to Emerson Fittipaldi's first Indy
victory _ and a macho thumbs-up salute from Unser. After that race,
Unser announced that in case anybody had not figured it out,
winning the Indy 500 meant more to him than life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not racing at Indy really does play on Al's mind an awful lot
because of his family heritage,'' said Shelley Unser, Al's wife of
17 years. Shelley accompanied her husband to the Speedway during
Indy 500 qualifications in May, where they rooted for aspiring IRL
drivers Johnny and Robby Unser, Al's cousins.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of Unser Jr., both made the big race. And he was
warmly received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what to expect with the crowd at an IRL race,''
Unser Jr. said. ``I didn't know if they would boo me or what. The
crowd showed me a lot of heart. They clapped. They said they missed
me. It almost brought a tear to my eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Unser said the impromptu show of support overwhelmed
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Elvis had come back to life,'' she said. ``I think
this \RIROC\S race is going to feel awkward for Al _ that this
isn't right. But it's a race car and he's a race car driver, so he
might just want to kick some butt on the NASCAR boys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
