<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSS PRIZE TO A SCOT  
 WORKS BY MAGRITTE'S FRIEND  
 MIRAGE'S WYNN BETTING ON ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 C.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Douglas Gordon, the 32-year-old film and video artist
from Glasgow, Scotland, who won the prestigious Turner Prize two
years ago, has captured another award. Wednesday night, the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum announced that Gordon was this year's winner
of the Hugo Boss Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year-old $50,000 prize is sponsored by the museum and
the men's wear company. It is given for significant contribution in
contemporary art, and artists of all nationalities are eligible. By
contrast, the $32,000 Turner Prize, awarded by the Tate Gallery in
London, is given to a contemporary British artist for a body of
work over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   An international jury of arts professionals chose Gordon from a
short list that included five others: William Kentridge, a South
African filmmaker; Lee Bul, a South Korean installation and
performance artist; Pipilotti Rist, a Swiss video artist; Lorna
Simpson, an American photographer and filmmaker, and Huang Yong
Ping, a Chinese installation artist. The work of all the finalists
is in a show at the Guggenheim's SoHo branch that runs until Sept.
20.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury took into consideration that he'd won the Turner
Prize, but they didn't want to penalize him for it,'' said Nancy
Spector of the Guggenheim, who organized the show of the finalists'
work and who has been involved in the prize since its inception.
``Although I was not on this year's jury, I know they were looking
for someone with a promise for the future, and Douglas has an
amazing capacity and vision for invention.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon first gained public attention for his slow-motion version
of the Hitchcock film ``Psycho,'' which was shown at the Hayward
Gallery in London two years ago. The Boss Prize exhibition includes
his ``Hysterical'' (1995), a film installation made from an early
medical film that shows a masked woman being treated for a
psychiatric disorder by two doctors. The action is projected onto
two giant free-standing screens: at normal speed on one, slowed
down and reversed on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Douglas is someone working in the '90s whose relationship to
film is new and fresh,'' Ms. Spector said. ``Much of his work
centers on the idea of polar opposites: good and evil, sacred and
profane.''
</P>
<P>
   Magritte's Friend
</P>
<P>
   It's an auction house's dream to sell works of art from their
source, or at least as close to the source as possible. Christie's
in New York will be realizing that dream in November when it
auctions a group of 54 paintings and drawings from the collection
of Harry Torczyner, a Belgian-born writer, scholar and collector
who was Magritte's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, which is estimated to be worth about $15
million, was formed over 50 years. Twenty-five of the works are
paintings, drawings and gouaches by Magritte; also for sale is one
of his rare painted bottles. In addition, the collection includes
works by Francis Bacon, George Segal, Max Ernst, Christo and Paul
Klee.
</P>
<P>
   Torczyner, who died in March, was a friend and adviser to
Magritte. He commissioned works from the artist, wrote several
books and articles about him, arranged exhibitions of his work and
donated Magritte works to the Museum of Modern Art in New York and
the Israel Museum in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Torczyner was also the subject of one of Magritte's most famous
portraits, ``Justice Has Been Done,'' from 1958. It shows the
lawyer in a toga with a hot-air balloon above his head. Just before
he died, Torczyner gave the painting to the Royal Museum of Fine
Arts of Belgium in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Magritte works to be sold are ``Personal Values,'' a
1952 painting considered iconic. It is a play on scale, showing an
oversized comb standing upright on a bed, a giant match lying on
the floor, a green wine goblet, an enormous pill and a
shaving-cream brush, all trapped in a bedroom with sky painted
walls. It is estimated to sell for $2 million to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the auction is perhaps the most widely recognized
Magritte painting, ``Son of Man'' (1964), which shows a man in a
bowler hat with a green apple obscuring his face. It is expected to
fetch $2 million to $3 million. ``In every medium, he got the pick
and the best,'' said Franck Giraud, who runs Christie's 19th- and
20th-century departments. ``This collection has the largest and the
greatest selection of Magrittes in the world. Most of them are well
known because they have been extensively published and exhibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Bids on the work are expected, Giraud said, from museums in the
United States and abroad, and from the small but passionate group
of Magritte collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on Art
</P>
<P>
   Mirage Resorts chairman Stephen Wynn has sought advice from top
experts since he began buying important Impressionist, modern and
contemporary art seriously two years ago, both for himself and for
Bellagio, his new resort that is scheduled to open in Las Vegas in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, William Acquavella, the Manhattan dealer, has
been his main adviser, representing Wynn at auctions. But though
Wynn said Acquavella will still be working with him, he has
recently hired Edmund P. Pillsbury, who resigned in January as
director of the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, Texas. Pillsbury
will be involved in the Bellagio Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a full art gallery with everything from an
Acoustiguide to a catalog,'' Wynn said in a recent telephone
interview. ``These days enthusiasm isn't enough. This is a very
serious, first-rate effort, and Ted knows exactly what he's talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to love art; it's another thing to know the
business and to anticipate public needs,'' Wynn added. ``Ted will
be involved in everything from making the space user-friendly to
ticketing to conservation. He will also help put together the
catalog, which will have essays by scholars.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Feldman, spokesman for Mirage, said Pillsbury was traveling
abroad and could not be reached for comment. Wynn said that while
Pillsbury visits the Las Vegas resort regularly, he will still be
based in Fort Worth.
</P>
</TEXT>
