<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADE-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE WINDS BLOW HOT, COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trading away Wilson Alvarez and Sammy Sosa for Harold Baines in
July 1989 still haunts the Rangers. But the St. Louis Cardinals
rejoice at getting Mark McGwire last July for three minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Midseason trades are a double-edged sword. Teams who think they
can win now often gamble by trading top minor-league prospects for
immediate help. Sometimes they win. Sometimes the past can haunt
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major-league team is still your No. 1 priority,'' Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin said. ``But you have to balance that
against the long-term interests of the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at some of the more significant midseason deals from the
past three years:
Rick Aguilera for Frankie Rodriguez July 6, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, 37-28, needed a reliever to reinforce their drive
to an American League Eastern Division title. The Twins thought
Rodriguez, a second-round pick in the 1990 draft, had the talent to
be a No. 1 starter. Aguilera saved 20 games and the Red Sox won the
division. Rodriguez, 25, has been a bust for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Boston
Cone for minor-leaguers July 28, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees strengthened their bid for the wild-card
playoff spot by acquiring David Cone from the Toronto Blue Jays for
minor-league pitchers Marty Janzen, Jason Jarvis and Mike Gordon.
Cone, who won the Cy Young Award in 1994, went 9-2 down the
stretch. The Blue Jays have received almost nothing from the three
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Yankees
Scott Erickson for Scott Klingenbeck July 7, 1995
</P>
<P>
   Klingenbeck was the Orioles' fifth pick in the 1992 draft, but
they traded him to the Twins for Scott Erickson. Erickson was 4-6
with a 5.95 earned-run average at the time of the trade but is
49-31 since then for the Orioles. Klingenbeck won one game for the
Twins before being given away to the Reds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Orioles
Bobby Bonilla for Alex Ochoa, Damon Buford July 28, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles insisted Ochoa, rated the eighth-best minor-league
prospect in baseball, was untouchable. But when they heard the
Yankees had acquired Cone, they traded him and Buford to the New
York Mets for Bonilla. Ochoa never fulfilled his promise and is a
part-timer now with the Twins. Buford is a defensive specialist.
Bonilla had a big year with Baltimore in 1996 before moving on to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Orioles
Ken Hill for minor-leaguers July 27, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, on their way to a 100-44 record, picked
up Hill from the St. Louis Cardinals, mainly as a fourth starter in
postseason, while giving up infielder David Bell, pitcher Rick
Heiserman and catcher Pepe McNeal. Hill won a big game in the AL
Championship Series before leaving as a free agent. The Cardinals
got almost nothing from the three minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Indians
Jim Abbott for minor-leaguers July 27, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, trying to hold on in the AL West, reacquired Abbott,
their former No. 1 draft pick, from the Chicago White Sox for
minor-league pitchers Bill Simas, Andrew Lorraine and John Snyder,
and outfielder McKay Christenson. Lorraine, another No. 1 pick, was
supposed to be the key to the deal but was a bust. Simas, however,
has been a serviceable reliever, and Snyder is getting a shot right
now in the White Sox rotation. The Angels didn't win in 1995 and
Abbott went 2-18 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: White Sox
Cecil Fielder for Sierra-Drews July 31, 1996
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees fortified their 1996 world championship team when
they acquired Fielder from the Detroit Tigers, who were willing to
accept Ruben Sierra's big contract to get minor-league pitcher Matt
Drews. Drews, a hard thrower, was the key to the deal but is
currently struggling at Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Yankees
Denny Neagle for Schmidt-Wright Aug. 28, 1996
</P>
<P>
   The Braves improved the best rotation in baseball when they
traded pitcher Jason Schmidt and first baseman Ron Wright to the
Pirates for Denny Neagle, a 20-game winner last year. Schmidt has
the talent to be a No. 1 starter, but Wright, once considered a
premier power prospect, struggles in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Braves
John Burkett for Helling-Dempster Aug. 8, 1996
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would have not won a division title in 1996 without
acquiring pitcher John Burkett from the Florida Marlins for
pitchers Rick Helling and Ryan Dempster. They even got Helling back
last year for Ed Vosberg. But Dempster still has a chance to be a
good major-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Rangers
White Sox surrender July 31, 1997
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox ran up the white flag last year when they
traded pitchers Roberto Hernandez, Wilson Alvarez and Danny Darwin
to San Francisco for minor-league pitchers Keith Foulke, Lorenzo
Barcelo, Bobby Howry and Kev Vining, infielder Mike Caruso and
outfielder Brian Manning. The Giants got a division title out of
the deal; the White Sox were crucified. But the White Sox received
a front-line shortstop in Caruso while Foulke and Howry, a future
closer, are contributing in the bullpen. Alvarez and Hernandez left
as free agents after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Both did well
Jose Cruz for Spoljaric-Timlin July 31, 1997
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners traded Cruz to the Blue Jays for relievers Paul
Spoljaric and Mike Timlin. The two pitchers did little to help the
Mariners' bullpen. Cruz got off to a bad start with the Blue Jays
this year and is back in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: It all depends on Cruz. Mark McGwire for three
pitchers July 31, 1997
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris took a twist last year when
Oakland traded him to the Cardinals for pitchers T.J. Mathews, Eric
Ludwick and Blake Stein. McGwire has been a huge hit in St. Louis
but the Cardinals, through Tuesday, are 71-89 since the trade.
Mathews and Ludwick did little to help the Athletics. Stein could
develop into a front-line starter.
</P>
<P>
   Trade winner: Cardinals
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
