<SLUG> BC-KENYA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION DISPUTE DOMINATES KENYAN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The head of Kenya's new anti-corruption
authority has been suspended from office after a disagreement with
the finance minister in a case that underscores just how difficult
it is to root out graft here.
</P>
<P>
   President Daniel arap Moi suspended the official, John Harun
Mwau, on Wednesday, just four days after Mwau had filed charges
against four high-ranking Treasury Department officials, accusing
them of a scheme to evade $3.9 million in import duties on wheat
and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The president's actions came after the finance minister, Simeon
Nyachae, in a spirited defense of his accused subordinates,
attacked Mwau in public, accusing him of starting a witch hunt. He
defended the officials, who are accused of corrupt business
dealings, maintaining that not only did they act within the law,
but with the full approval of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Played out on the front pages of newspapers here, the
disagreement has undermined the credibility of Moi's efforts to
stamp out corruption, once again putting Kenya's shaky relations
with international lenders in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not helpful,'' said one diplomat, insisting on
anonymity. ``This is an unfortunate development, distracting from
the central issues this country faces. This is all a distraction, a
sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   When the International Monetary Fund suspended aid to Kenya last
year, one of its principal complaints was that the government had
done little or nothing to rein in rampant official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, corrupt schemes have seeped into almost every
level of government here, from bribes that traffic officers solicit
from motorists to elaborate land grabs and import-duty scams
involving Cabinet members, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   In response to pressure from the IMF, Moi set up the Kenya
Anti-Corruption Authority last December and put Mwau, a former
police officer and an opposition gadfly, in charge.
</P>
<P>
   But Mwau's decision to prosecute the four treasury officials as
his first high-profile case has raised questions about his
sincerity and the viability of his authority, diplomats and
financial officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the charges were leveled, the four accused officials were
seen as part of a progressive, reform-minded wing of the governing
party, a group led by Nyachae that stands firmly behind efforts to
stamp out corruption.
</P>
<P>
   While diplomats and officials at international lending
institutions said they could not say whether the charges were true,
they did say they came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a feeling that these people who were to be arrested
were doing their jobs and we have no reason to believe they were
corrupt,'' one banking official said, speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the charges are true, several diplomats said the
public contretemps was not likely to persuade the IMF and World
Bank to resume aid to shore up Kenya's shattered economy, which is
reeling from a steep drop in tourism.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of the capital, meanwhile, speculation has grown
that Mwau purposely took aim at pro-reform officials first, instead
of other officials suspected of corruption, in order to take the
wind out of the pro-reform movement's sails.
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon in Wednesday's Daily Nation newspaper showed Mwau and
Nyachae as puppets, their strings being pulled by hands
recognizable as the president's.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the president's office said Moi would appoint a
tribunal to ``inquire into the proper performance'' of the
corruption authority. The statement said Mwau would be suspended
until the tribunal had finished its inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mwau has fiercely defended the charges against the
four officials and has said he will resign if they are not proved
true in court. It is highly unlikely the case will ever be heard,
however, since the attorney general has dropped the charges. The
accused officials are Joseph Kinyua, Njeru Kirira, John Msafari and
Samuel Chebii.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nyachae has accused Mwau of pressing the
charges only to divert attention from the fact that he himself is
under investigation by the Kenya Revenue Authority for evading duty
on the import of automobile tires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
