<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE FANS CAN FIND LUXURY OR LAID-BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some horse-racing fans planning an August vacation face a
decision as difficult as any maze of handicapping variables.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga or Del Mar?
</P>
<P>
   For traveling horseplayers who have the financial means _ or a
generous expense account _ it is impossible to go wrong at either
place. A losing day at Saratoga and Del Mar beats a winning day at
most other tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The best horses in the country congregate annually at the two
tracks, running for daily purses twice as high as at Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   But the similarities end there. Located on opposite sides of the
country, the tracks are equally far apart in style and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Race Course is tucked away in the middle of Saratoga
Springs, N.Y., a small tourist community less than a half-hour from
Albany, N.Y., in a picturesque setting of mountains, trees and
lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The track has been in business since the mid-1800s, and the
quaint wooden grandstand and country-fair atmosphere are throwbacks
to a time when ladies wore hoop dresses to the track and gentlemen
were attired in top hats.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Saratoga has always been a summer showplace for
old-money aristocrats from New York, such as the Vanderbilts and
Whitneys. They still cram the August calendar with concertos,
charity balls and dog shows.
</P>
<P>
   Although coats and ties and sun dresses remain the standard in
the grandstand, the track is also a popular weekend getaway for
tailgaters from Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Vermont. Clad
mostly in shorts and T-shirts, they arrive in the morning armed
with blankets, armchairs and coolers and wait in line to stake out
a spot in the track's vast grassy backyard. There they have access
to betting windows, TV monitors, concession tents and kiosks _ and
even shade trees, a foreign phenomenon at racetracks in this part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   After the races, many fans go next door to Siro's, a popular
restaurant with a block-sized beer garden whose cash flow could
support the economies of some Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   Properly planned, an afternoon at Saratoga is delightful.
Unfortunately, it can also be very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Springs has only about 40,000 permanent residents, and
a hotel shortage drives in-town lodging prices to exorbitant levels
during the racing season, even for spartan accommodations _
assuming you find a room at all. Many have to stay overnight in a
surrounding city and make the short drive to Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar, on the other hand, is in a beach community of the same
name just down the road from San Diego along the Pacific Coast
Highway. Built in 1937 as the brainchild of crooner Bing Crosby,
the Del Mar track is adjacent to the ocean, thus its trademark
slogan of ``Where the Surf Meets the Turf.''
</P>
<P>
   The Del Mar grandstand has a Mission-style architecture, but it
was recently remodeled and modernized.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to the more traditional air of Saratoga, it is not
unusual to see bikinis on the track apron at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat the environment, either. After racing hours, the
Del Mar and La Jolla areas offer outstanding restaurants, shopping
and night life. Temperatures seldom rise above 85 on sunny days
because of cool ocean breezes, and swimmers cavort alongside seals
in water so cold that wetsuits can be worn in the middle of summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a typical laid-back Southern California beach town, with
bicyclists, rollerbladers and skateboarders who sometimes seem to
outnumber motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Living in such a paradise isn't cheap, with modest homes selling
in the $1 million range. Fortunately, hotel rooms are easier to
obtain around Del Mar than in Saratoga and are more comfortable and
more realistically priced.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even at these tracks, the handicapping variables can
be just as tough to decipher as they are at Louisiana Downs or
Remington Park or Retama Park. And bad rides can happen there, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when the horses don't run according to plan at Saratoga and
Del Mar, it's much easier to shrug your shoulders and smile.
The Buzz
Still in the saddle Kent Desormeaux apparently is keeping the mount
on Real Quiet, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux has been penciled in as the rider of Real Quiet for
the Aug. 9 Buick Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park in
Oceanport, N.J., because jockey Gary Stevens has instead opted to
ride archrival Victory Gallop in the same race.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop finished second to Real Quiet in the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness Stakes, then defeated him by a nose in the
Belmont Stakes to spoil the Triple Crown bid.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens reached a verbal agreement with trainer Bob Baffert
earlier this summer, allowing Stevens to ride any of Baffert's
horses. But in deciding to ride Victory Gallop and not Real Quiet
in the Haskell, Stevens' agent, Ron Anderson, cited a long-standing
relationship between Stevens and Houston-owned Prestonwood Farm,
which races the Belmont and Arkansas Derby winner.
The dirt on the dirt Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie's dirt surface
should look considerably different next spring, and possibly even
for the quarter-horse season this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Track consultant Dennis Moore _ whose brother, Ron, is in charge
of day-to-day maintenance of the racing strips at Lone Star _ was
in town this week to examine the surfaces and reportedly
recommended some changes.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt track was kinder to horses in 1998 than 1997, but it
still isn't where the Moores would like it. So the surface will be
retooled, perhaps along the lines of Louisiana Downs, where a
pine-bark additive recommended by Dennis Moore has helped transform
that once-maligned surface into one praised by horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make some changes,'' promised Lone Star general
manager Corey Johnsen, who said more details should be forthcoming
in a few weeks.
Hoofbeats
Fast but frail Hit hard again by illness, Silver Charm could miss
the Breeders' Cup Classic and most of this year's racing schedule,
trainer Bob Baffert said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Silver Charm trailed the field in the five-horse
San Diego Handicap, finishing an astonishing 27 lengths behind
winner Mud Route.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said afterward that the 4-year-old Kentucky Derby winner
had bled internally during the race and soon would be put back into
training. But a few days later, he reversed himself and said Silver
Charm probably won't run again until the Santa Anita meeting begins
shortly after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he believes Silver Charm is still suffering the
effects of the virus and subsequent antibiotic treatments that kept
the colt from participating in last month's Hollywood Gold Cup.
A bit ouchy Undefeated 2-year-old filly Arrested Dreams came out of
Lone Star Park's July 18 Silver Spur Stakes with a sore right shin
and is being given some time off, said owner and trainer Louis
Roussel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's at Louisiana Downs, and we just put a little blister on
her shin,'' Roussel said. ``We're just trying to get the soreness
out. Hopefully, we can make a race in September and maybe another
in October.''
</P>
<P>
   If Arrested Dreams returns to her best form and proves talented
enough, Roussel said he might still run her in the Nov. 7 Breeders'
Cup Juvenile Fillies at Churchill Downs. The daughter of Dehere has
won convincingly in her three starts, all at Lone Star.
Et cetera Houston furniture magnate Jim McIngvale has signed up to
sponsor the major 3-year-old prep race at Turfway Park in Florence,
Ky., which will now be called the Gallery Furniture.Com Stakes. Jim
Beam, the longtime supporter of the race, withdrew its sponsorship
earlier this year. If things go wrong, can Mattress Mac fire
Turfway Park? ... The Aug. 15 Pacific Classic at Del Mar has a
tentative lineup that includes Gentlemen, Touch Gold, Free House
and Mud Route, for a $1 million purse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
