<SLUG> BC-CABLE-COMPETE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION BILL IRES CABLE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cable television industry lashed out Thursday at newly
proposed federal legislation designed to increase competition and
protect the nation's 67 million cable subscribers from
price-gouging after regulation of monthly rates expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Representatives Edward Markey (D-Mass.), the
ranking Democrat on the House Telecommunications subcommitee, and
Billy Tauzin (R-La.), the panel's chairman, introduced a bill that
requires cable operators to offer a basic low-cost package of local
broadcast channels and bars cable companies from locking up
exclusive programming deals at the expense of a rival broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would give communities the chance to control local
rates after deregulation if the community determines that a cable
operator does not offer an acceptable range of programming choices.
Cable rates are currently set by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether there are sufficient protections for cable
subscribers when rates are deregulated on April 1, 1999, as called
for under the Telecommunications Act of 1996. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While long-distance phone rates have dropped because of
increased competition, cable TV and local phone markets have
remained largely under monopoly control and have not seen lower
prices. In fact, cable rates nationwide rose 7.3 perent over the
last year, while the inflation rate was &UR;  &LR; only 1.7 percent, said
Markey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Nationally, the average rate for a package of cable programs
rose from $24.43 a month just before passage of the 1996
Telecommunications Act to more than $31 a month earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have anything remotely close to a competitive cable
marketplace today. Yet unless Congress acts, the regulation of
cable monopolies will end early next year and there will be no
competitive check on price gouging in most of our communities,''
said Markey, although he added that he doesn't expect the bill to
pass this session.
</P>
<P>
   Cable industry officials were quick to criticize the
Markey-Tauzin bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will harm, not help consumers,'' said
Bartlett Leber, vice president and corporate counsel for MediaOne
in New England, which has 850,000 cable subscribers in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Leber and other cable executives say they face rising
programming costs _ particularly to purchase shows from &UR;  &LR; various
sports channels such as ESPN _ which are responsible for many of
the recent rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne increased monthly rates about 10 percent this year.
Leber said 60 percent of the price rise was due to higher
programming fees. The other 40 percent was for maintaining and
expanding the company's broadband network.
</P>
<P>
   Cable officials asserted that introducing more regulations now
would defeat the purpose of the telecom act. ``We meet the
requirements, why do we need new legislation to micromanage us?''
asked Leber.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents of the legislation maintain that communities
will unduly control programming. The bill could ``empower thousands
of city councils to dictate TV program lineups,'' said Decker
Anstrom president of the national Cable Television Association, a
Washington trade group. ``It's more government where less
government is necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
