<SLUG> BC-NC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON KEEPS TO BUSY SCHEDULE OF PUBLIC APPEARANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ President Clinton appeared Thursday before
friendly crowds in North Carolina, never mentioning the sex and
perjury inquiries as he pressed his environmental programs and
helped raise money for John Edwards, a Democratic candidate for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In Boggs, along the banks of the New River, Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore joined local politicians to declare the river an
American Heritage River, a move that encourages federal and local
agencies to preserve the river's environment and stimulate economic
activities in its watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand North Carolinians cheered enthusiastically, and
Clinton's luck was good enough that a drenching rain held off until
moments after his speech ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support you, Mr. President!'' one woman hollered from the
crowd, and she beamed as he gestured at her and said, ``Thank you,
ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has kept Clinton on a schedule of public
events, like Thursday's, as a grand jury in Washington prepares to
hear testimony from Monica Lewinsky, perhaps as early as next week.
In an immunity deal with prosecutors, Ms. Lewinsky, a former White
House intern, has said she had a sexual relationship with the
president and that they discussed ways to hide it. Clinton has
denied any such relationship.
</P>
<P>
   As he usually does at appearances with an environmental theme,
Clinton said the Republican-controlled Congress was loading
spending bills with provisions that would roll back environmental
protections.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Congress to release about $700 million that has
already been set aside for buying conservation lands and to finance
clean water programs in his budget request for fiscal year 1999,
which begins on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heritage Rivers program was established by a White
House executive order last year, and communities all over the
country have competed for the designation. Among the 14 waterways
that were selected this week to receive the special status were the
Hudson River, the Potomac River, the Rio Grande and the Connecticut
River.
</P>
<P>
   The New River, where Clinton spoke, is poorly named: Geologists
say it has been here for 350 million years, even before the
Appalachian Mountains rose. Two decades ago, conservationists
fought off efforts to dam a big stretch of the river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1216 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS DODGES LEWINSKY MATTER, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ariz., Calif., Conn., Texas, Okla., N.J.)   (See also: CLINTON-STARR CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives begins its session
most days with a period for one-minute speeches that members can
devote to any topic they please. Often, representatives use these
speeches to address the news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the one-minute speeches involved issues like
gambling, education and campaign finance. No one mentioned
President Clinton's decision to testify before the grand jury in
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to questions about the president, Republican
representatives repeated, almost like a mantra, that they were
concentrating on legislation and the needs of their constituents
and were relying on the Judiciary Committee and its chairman, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to decide how to deal with the investigation of
the president. The Judiciary Committee has jurisdiction over
impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Typical was this response from Republican Rep. J.D. Hayworth:
``My job is to represent the 6th District of Arizona and to work on
those issues I'm here for. I'm content to leave Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky to Henry Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, a senior Republican from California, said
party leaders had advised the backbenchers to take that
noncommittal stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Dreier said, ``for us to engage in
Clinton-bashing now is not the wisest thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain why, Dreier replied, ``His popularity is high,
and we still need to work with him on issues like trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in the House also responded to inquiries in more or
less the same way. They are glad the president is going to testify,
they said, and hope this will bring the investigations to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we can get through with this and get to the
important issues,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hyde, he was courteous in an interview but said little of
substance. ``I think it's good that he's going to testify,'' he
said. ``Let's wait and hear what he's going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   When does he expect a report from Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel? Sometime after Aug. 17, the date scheduled for
the president's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be a lame-duck session after the November election
during which his committee would conduct an investigation? He is
not ruling it out.
</P>
<P>
   Is he looking forward to receiving Starr's report and possibly
conducting an inquiry? ``This is onerous duty,'' but somebody has
to do it, Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Is perjury an impeachable offense? ``To consider the
impeachability of any act, you have to look at it in context,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has authorization to hire a staff of 14 investigators and
lawyers to consider the question of impeachment, and most of those
slots are filled. Democrats on the panel have authorization for a
staff of four. Two lawyers have been hired, and interviews are
under way for the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Senators did not go out of their way either to comment on the
news of the president's plans to testify. On the wall of the Senate
press gallery, where the senators leave press releases with
quotations they hope will make the papers, none of the dozens of
releases posted Thursday dealt with the president and his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the matter, Republican senators were more
forthcoming than their counterparts in the House. Sen. Phil Gramm
of Texas declared: ``Well, where I'm from, if you were mayor of
College Station and you were accused of this, and you looked the
people in the face and said, `I didn't do it,' and you did it, you
couldn't stay mayor of College Station. If he did do it, it's going
to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issue was clearly not at the forefront of the senators'
minds. Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant Republican
leader, said he thought that the Lewinsky matter was important but
that campaign finance abuses were much more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators seemed reluctant to say much about the
subject. ``It's still in a state of flux,'' said Sen. Frank
Lautenberg of New Jersey. ``We don't know what the responses can
be. If you look at it strictly on what you're hearing, it has a
superficial specter that is rather foreboding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
