<HEADLINE>
U.S. GOVERNMENT EYES $420 MILLION DEAL TO REPLENISH CRUDE RESERVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
and HILLARY DURGIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just months after announcing plans to sell oil from
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve at ``fire sale prices,'' the
federal government is now contemplating buying $420 million worth
of crude.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, in a surprise maneuver late Wednesday night,
attached an ``emergency'' measure to an unrelated appropriations
bill that would authorize the Energy Department to purchase about
28 million barrels of crude for the government's emergency oil
stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate took up the 1999 Treasury-Postal Appropriations Bill
_ legislation designed to fund government services ranging from the
White House to the Internal Revenue Service _ on Thursday, but the
bill got bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   And while lawmakers could still take up the issue Friday, the
vote may be postponed until September.
</P>
<P>
   Authored by Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., the bill is designed to
replenish crude sold from the reserve over the last three years to
help balance the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has repeatedly used the Strategic Petroleum Reserve
as a cash machine in recent years, selling oil to pay for unrelated
programs and depressing the price of oil by as much as 50 cents a
barrel,'' Bingaman said. ``The purchase will get excess oil off the
market and will help restore some of the security the reserve is
intended to provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers anticipate the Energy Department would pay an average
of $15 per barrel for the crude. That's a far cry from the average
$27.14-a-barrel the government spent building up the reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The petroleum reserve has about 563 million barrels of crude oil
in storage caverns located along the Gulf Coast in Texas and
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   By declaring the provision an ``emergency,'' lawmakers are
circumventing budget rules that otherwise would require them to
find other spending to cut to pay for the oil purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjusted for inflation, oil prices are lower today than during
the Depression,'' Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, chairman of the
Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee, said in a written
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``While that is good for the consumer, it is a nightmare for our
small domestic producers,'' Murkowski said. ``The very survival of
our ability to produce oil within the United States is at risk ...
I call that an `emergency.'''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal gave oil prices a boost. They jumped 39 cents in
early trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Light, sweet
crude for delivery in September ended the day at $14.21, up 12
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Unleaded gasoline for August delivery settled at 40.97 cents a
gallon, down 0.14 cent. Home heating oil for August delivery was
35.31 cents a gallon, down 0.02 cent.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas prices were lower, with contracts for delivery in
September settling at $1.906 per thousand cubic feet, off 2.7
cents.
</P>
<P>
   In London, North Sea Brent crude oil for September delivery
settled at $13.08 per barrel, up 2 cents, on the International
Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Sharief, director of energy research for Hornsby &AMP; Co., a
Houston-based energy risk management firm, said the amount of oil
being discussed was not enough to really affect the markets. ``I
was really surprised there was a blip,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Independent Petroleum Association of
America, representing the nation's smaller producers, hailed the
oil purchase plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Removing 28 million barrels of oil from a saturated market
would help stabilize oil prices,'' the trade group said in a letter
to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   George Yates, a Roswell, N.M.-based producer and chairman of the
trade group, said that if government officials agreed to purchase
crude they would be ``sending the signal that they recognize not
only the opportunities brought about by low oil prices but also ...
that they would like to retain a domestic oil industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to purchase crude for the reserve comes less than
four months after then-Energy Secretary Federico Pea raised the
alarm about a congressional mandate that would have forced the
Energy Department to sell 21 million barrels of crude from the
reserve to raise $207.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pea feared the government would fetch prices ranging from $10 to
$15 a barrel, and thus cost American taxpayers $175 million or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed to postpone any further oil sales. Earlier this
week, Bingaman raised the idea of buying crude with President
Clinton, while the two were aboard Air Force One flying from
Albuquerque, N.M., to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials were generally supportive of
the measure Thursday, noting that with oil prices so low it would
be reasonable to purchase crude at this time. They noted, however,
that they want to first examine the budget rules to determine if
they would agree that no other spending cuts will be required.
</P>
</TEXT>
