<HEADLINE>
STURGES CENTENNIAL: REELING BACK  
 NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STURGES CENTENNIAL: In the early and middle 1940s, Preston
Sturges wrote and directed a string of perhaps the wittiest, most
sophisticated comedies ever made for the American screen. In the
late '30s, though, he wrote before he directed. ``This is him
seeing what directors were doing and saying to himself, `Wait a
minute, I can do that,''' said his son Tom Sturges.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, retrospectives of Sturges films as a director, from
``The Great McGinty'' (1940) to ``Hail the Conquering Hero''
(1944), in Los Angeles and at the Film Forum in New York City (July
24-Aug. 6) commemorate his 100th birthday. Many of the major titles
have recently been reissued on video by Universal, and Tuesday the
studio will add four films written or partly written by Sturges but
directed by others: the drama ``Imitation of Life'' (1934), the
comedy ``Easy Living'' (1937), the adventure-comedy ``If I Were
King'' (1938) and the comedy ``Never Say Die'' (1939).
</P>
<P>
   The last film, a marital imbroglio starring Bob Hope and Martha
Raye, was written with others. ``Writers then were like piano
movers,'' Tom Sturges said. ``They worked in teams. One guy wrote
women's dialogue and one the men's. Another would write chase
scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sturges, now the general manager of Twism Records, a company
partly owned by Shaquille O'Neal, was 3 when his father died in
1959. Besides encouraging the restoration of his father's films, he
has gathered many of the scripts into bound volumes, published by
the University of California Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy Living,'' a riotous comedy directed by Mitchell Leisen,
is about a feisty banker (Edward Arnold) who chases his profligate
wife (Mary Nash) to a rooftop and flings her $58,000 fur coat off a
balcony, the young woman on whom the coat lands (Jean Arthur) and
the banker's debonair son (Ray Milland), with whom Ms. Arthur
begins a romance.
</P>
<P>
   Sturges was never entirely comfortable with his scripts in the
hands of others. `` `Easy Living' goes about 40 miles per hour,''
Tom Sturges said. ``My dad would have made it go 60.'' Preston
Sturges also frequently made deals to direct dialogue, possibly the
strongest attribute of all his films. ``My father liked getting two
people in a room and seeing what they could say to each other,''
Tom Sturges said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four films, he added, Sturges would have preferred
directing ``If I Were King,'' based on a play by Justin Huntly
McCarthy. Basil Rathbone is the ruthless and often hilarious Louis
XI, who is holed up in a 15th-century Paris under siege by the Duke
of Burgundy. Ronald Colman is the poet and rabble-rouser Francois
Villon.
</P>
<P>
   In Sturges' rendering of the situation, the cunning and
loquacious Louis, a born palace psychologist and obsessive
conniver, is more taken with courtly manipulation than he is
worried by the threat outside his walls. Villon remains in good
humor despite being under the constant threat of execution. Sturges
translated the poetry himself, adding the occasional embellishment.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admire a man who, while presumably being led to the
gallows, is asked to say something humorous to cheer a tearful
woman friend, responds, ``His neck at last shall have the chance to
weigh the tonnage of his pants.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   JACKIE BROWN
</P>
<P>
   1997. Miramax. 154 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date:
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With his hipness in high gear, Quentin Tarantino adapts Elmore
Leonard's ``Rum Punch.'' Jackie (Pam Grier), an airline attendant,
ferries money from Mexico for the gun runner Ordell Robbie (Samuel
L. Jackson). That gets her in trouble with the government and
introduces her to the sympathetic bail bondsman Max Cherry (Robert
Forster). Tarantino indulges his gift for catchy gab, but a problem
arises with convoluted plotting in a film that, Janet Maslin wrote
in The New York Times, ``isn't sharp enough to sustain all the time
it wastes on small talk, long drives, trips to the mall and
favorite songs played on car radios.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE GINGERBREAD MAN
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram . $102.96. 115 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Altman becomes the latest name director to adapt a John
Grisham mystery (Francis Ford Coppola's ``Rain Maker'' was released
on tape in April). It all has to do with a lawyer, of course.
During a rainstorm in an evocatively depicted Savannah, the
divorced legal hotshot Rick Magruder (Kenneth Branagh) meets a
mysterious woman in fishnet stockings (Embeth Davidtz). Before he
knows it she's peeling off those wet clothes, and he's easing into
hot water he'd be better off avoiding, like how to deal with her
crazed father (Robert Duvall). Particularly well-suited to Altman's
atmospheric style, the film is his ``best genre piece since `The
Long Goodbye.''' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE MEN
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $19.94. 98 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   In Rodney Gibbons' adaptation of Louisa May Alcott's novel, Jo
Bhaer (Mariel Hemingway) of ``Little Women'' is now grown up and
the headmistress of Plumfield, a Massachusetts boarding school that
she runs with her husband, the professor (Chris Sarandon). With
cows grazing in pastures by the lovely woods, grace said before
meals and Saturday nights enlivened by pillow fights, all is
idyllic until the arrival of Dan (Ben Cook), a bad boy from the
city whose rude ways become a burden for all. But while Alcott is
full of life, here ``everyone seems to be just imitating 1930s
movies about the 19th century and false notes abound'' (Anita
Gates).
</P>
<P>
   HARD RAIN
</P>
<P>
   1998. Paramount. $102.56. Laser disk, $34.95. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dark and stormy night in Huntingburg, Ind., as a security
guard (Christian Slater) tries to salvage $3 million from an
armored car that is the target of a gang of thieves led by Jim
(Morgan Freeman). Jim sure would like that money to retire on, but
in his way are a dam that is about to burst, a disgruntled sheriff
(Randy Quaid) and other stumbling blocks in a film for which ``deep
waters and shallow characters tell the story'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK CLOSE: A PORTRAIT IN PROGRESS. The artist renders a
self-portrait and holds forth on his work _ paintings derived from
Polaroid head shots of family, friends and fellow artists _ his
methods and the meaning of his technique. 1998. Home Vision.
$29.95. 57 minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   WOVEN BY THE GRANDMOTHERS and LEGACY OF GENERATIONS. Two videos
explore, respectively, Navajo weaving and Southwestern American
Indian pottery making. 1998. Home Vision. $19.95 each or $29.95 for
the set. 30 minutes each.
</P>
<P>
   THE VERY BEST OF ST. ELSEWHERE. ``Elsewhere'' was the name hung
on St. Eligius, the rundown and besieged Boston hospital in the
gritty television series (1982-88) that set a standard for realism
and gave rise to some of the best writing in television. New Video.
A boxed set of four cassettes with two 60-minute episodes each.
$59.95.
</P>
<P>
   SLAPSTICK ENCYCLOPEDIA, Volumes V-VIII. The second wave in
Kino's silent series includes ``The Rink'' and ``A Night in the
Show'' by Charlie Chaplin, films by Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy
from Hal Roach Studios, madhouse fire drills from Max Sennett and a
half-dozen other slapstick favorites. Four cassettes. $24.95 each;
$89.95 for the set. Each volume runs 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A SELF-MADE HERO. In Jacques Audiard's film, a French
noncombatant in World War II comes up with an imaginatively valiant
background for himself, earning honor and admiration but not for
long. 1997. New Yorker Video. $89.95. 105 minutes. French with
English subtitles. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
