<HEADLINE>
MANY THINK CLINTON LIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As people around American see it, anyone in Bill
Clinton's position would have lied, even under oath.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Most believe former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and
the occupant of the Oval Office had sex of some sort. They also
believe Clinton responded as any guilty husband and father might.
</P>
<P>
   He lied, they said. Maybe he told her to lie, too. That's
unfortunate, they said, even offensive. But few of the dozens of
men and women, Republicans and Democrats, interviewed said Clinton
should face impeachment proceedings for falsely answering a
question he should not have been asked in the first place. The
economy is humming, the nation is not at war, and that's what
matters most to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, really, who cares?'' said Nancy Miranda, a schoolteacher
from Brooklyn, N.Y. ``What is it lying about? There's no state
secrets. He didn't lie about the Bay of Pigs. (The investigation)
is such a waste of time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Damion Young, music director at a Los Angeles radio
station, ``He's done some good for the country, and if he did
something with this woman, then that's his business. He should be
judged on the things he's done as a professional and not what
happens on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Regina Jordan, executive director of the Chamber of
Commerce in Douglas, Ariz., put it, ``I just don't see the point of
any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that every voter thought Clinton should go
unpunished. Lori Murphy, who was visiting the Capitol from
Cookville, Tenn., said she was saddened that the American people
seem not to care that Clinton is ``a liar and a cheat.'' She is,
she added, as disappointed in them as she is in her president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that our nation is not more concerned with the
morality of our leaders,'' said Joann Creamer, who lives in
Arlington, Texas. ``People think if he's handling the country it's
OK. But if you don't have moral character in small decisions, you
don't in big decisions either.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Billy Mariani, a Chicago computer consultant who believes
Lewinsky is lying and Clinton is telling the truth, ``If it were
true, he lied under oath. You'd definitely have to bring forth
impeachment hearings. You can't let something like that go
unexcused.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, however, were more ambivalent about the impact of
Clinton's personal character on public issues as well as the
outcome of a sex scandal that has transfixed Washington but had
little impact on the day-to-day lives of average Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a terrific diplomat,'' said Anthony Papandrea, a Brooklyn
butcher. ``As good as he snows women, he snows other politicians.
He's one of those men who have that charisma where, no matter how
this turns out, people will like him.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Think about Nixon and Watergate. That was breaking
and entering. This is about infidelity to your wife. Totally
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Some did say Clinton should face the same penalty for perjury as
any other person, although not until he leaves office. A half-dozen
also wanted Clinton impeached, especially if it is proven that the
president specifically asked Lewinsky to lie to prosecutors. Still,
most added, it would depend how and when Clinton made that request,
if he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not see a sitting president impeached for something
like this,'' said Marv Marlowe, an insurance agent in Santa Monica,
Calif. ``Lying is lying, of course, but let the punishment fit the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Vicky Erhart, a community outreach coordinator in Phoenix:
``I can't imagine someone not lying about something like that, to
be honest with you. Probably he should be punished if it was
obstruction of justice. But that would depend. I mean, if afterward
he just said, `Don't tell anyone,' then no, he shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Erhart, many people also said they were not absolutely
certain that Lewinsky was now telling the truth. When first
approached, Lewinsky, like Clinton, denied any relationship of a
sexual nature. This week, six months after independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr launched his investigation, she was granted
immunity from prosecution, and reportedly will tell a grand jury
that she had a sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most were inclined to believe Lewinsky, saying too many
women have come forward too many times to dismiss them all as
liars. As many noted, Clinton also initially denied an affair with
cabaret singer Jennifer Flowers while he was governor of Arkansas.
He later admitted to having sex with her once or twice; she
maintains their affair lasted 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm something of an expert on cheating husbands, having had
three myself,'' said Monica Williams, a bartender from Kissimmee,
Fla. ``Let me tell you something _ if a man is innocent, he can
prove it, and that's what he's going to do, right from the start,
because he knows he has to. If he says it's his word against hers,
he's a dog, and that's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sue Crosthwait, a paralegal in Oklahoma City, ``If I had to
say one way or the other, I'd say the women are probably telling
the truth. I hate to say that because I voted for him and I like
him as our president. But I do think it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many citizens, Consuela Ivy, a receptionist in Chicago,
said she would like to believe Clinton is telling the truth. Either
way, though, it doesn't much matter to her. The president, she
said, was elected to run the country well, not his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hillary's not bashing him over the head, I'm not going to
bash him over the head,'' Ivy said. ``I don't have to roll over and
look at him at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gary Thelen of Des Moines, Iowa, ``I'd prefer the whole
thing go away. People have been indiscreet for all of history. Why
is it now a big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   That's the stance many men and particularly women took when all
Clinton was facing were charges that he had had a relationship with
a woman who technically worked for him and who was young enough to
be his daughter. When news of their alleged relationship first
broke, polls in fact showed that Clinton's support among women
rose.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, many women also said they would not stand by the
president if it was proven that he had asked Lewinsky to lie or had
simply lied himself. Thursday they appeared to back off those
claims. Again and again, they stressed that Clinton was too smart
and too savvy a politician to have made such a request, which would
have been an attempt to obstruct and that it will ultimately be her
word against his.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to make a mistake like that,'' said Cathy
Perkins, who sells Mary Kay cosmetics in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Perkins and other voters said they wished Clinton had
been upfront with the American people from the start. In a nation
known for embracing celebrities who admit their sins, they said he
would have been forgiven, the entire matter forgotten. Now the
president must testify before the grand jury via videotape on Aug.
17, though many feel the story has dragged on too long already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows he did it, and they've already made up their
minds about whether they think it matters. I'm just glad it's
coming to an end,'' said Jamie Gordon, a physical therapist in
Orlando, Fla. ``It is coming to an end, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Globe staff reporter Fred Kaplan and correspondents Louise D.
Palmer, Stephen J. Siegel and Brad Liston contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
