<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-PILOTS-270&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS STALL BETWEEN NORTHWEST AIRLINES AND ITS PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (js) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal mediators have declared an impasse in contract
negotiations between Northwest Airlines and its pilots, setting the
stage for a possible strike as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board, which has been presiding over
negotiations between Northwest and its 6,300 pilots since July
1997, declared the impasse on Wednesday and asked both sides to
submit to binding arbitration. Northwest agreed, but the pilots did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the issues are too important and too complex to give
to an outside party,'' Paul Omodt, a spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association, said. ``The pilots who fly the airplanes and
know the schedules and the managers who run the airline are in the
best position to make these decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Railway Labor Act, the Mediation Board's declaration
triggers a 30-day cooling off period before a strike. The earliest
that the pilots could walk out is Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are expected to continue and both Northwest and the
union expressed confidence that a strike can be averted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to prevent the inconvenience to passengers and the
severe economic disruption that a strike would cause,'' Ben Hirst,
Northwest's lead negotiator, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest, which is the country's fourth-largest carrier and is
based in St. Paul, Minn., is currently negotiating with six
different unions representing about 90 percent of its 50,000
workers. Many of the airline's flights were disrupted in April and
May when machinists staged slowdowns and wildcat strikes to protest
the slow pace of the contract negotiations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The combination of the disruptions and the weak economy in Asia,
where Northwest has a large presence, caused the airline's
second-quarter earnings to plunge 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This week, 27,000 members of the International Association of
Machinists, which represents a wide range of workers from mechanics
to secretaries, voted on a series of tentative contracts with the
airline. The results will not be announced until next Tuesday, but
a spokesman for the union said that it now appeared that the
contracts would be rejected, which would send the union and the
airline back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   The airline and the pilots have agreed on 22 of 29 sections of a
new contract. Issues still outstanding include job security, pay
increases, retirement benefits and approval of Northwest's proposed
alliance with Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said that it would continue to fly its full schedule
over the next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
