<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta beats Reds 13-3 and trades for Colbrunn
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ In a deft sequence that would make any rotisserie
player proud, the Atlanta Braves in a few choice hours on Thursday
body-slammed Cincinnati, pulled off a trade and flew back home to
joust with mighty Mark McGwire and his St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves dispensed with Cincinnati 13-3 and then regained Greg
Colbrunn, the reserve first baseman who played a valuable role with
the club last year but was not re-signed. Atlanta obtained him from
Colorado, where he was hitting .311 with two home runs and 13 RBIs
in 62 games. Of more interest to the club, he is 9-for-26 (.346) as
a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough out,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``He can give Cat
(Andres Galarraga) a day off, if he needs the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, he bolsters the right-handed capability off
the bench. In return, Atlanta sent the Rockies minor-league
relievers David Cortes (Class AA Richmond) and Mike Porzio (Class A
Danville). The club needs to open a roster spot for Colbrunn. That
decision will be made after Cox and general manager John Schuerholz
discuss plans for moves before tonight's trading deadline.
Outfielder Danny Bautista appears at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pounded the Reds for 16 more hits, including two
homers by Gerald Williams and Andruw Jones, to take three of four
games from the Reds and finish their road trip at 7-2. From the
fifth inning of Wednesday night's game, Atlanta scored 24 times in
16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of went two or three games there where we didn't swing
so well,'' Chipper Jones said, ``so I guess you could say we were
due. From the fifth inning on (Wednesday) night, we swung extremely
well, took our walks and made them pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the game brought forth another quality performance by
Denny Neagle (11-9), who appears to be shaking out of a 1-3 slump
as he recovers his change-up. He allowed two runs on five hits in
eight innings, giving the bullpen a much needed breather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any (change-up) cutting back over the middle
of the plate,'' Neagle said. ``If anything, I missed low and away.
That's what I want to do with that pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves return home to greet the biggest story of the year in
McGwire and one of the most startling home-run rushes in history.
Greg Maddux, who faces Todd Stottlemyre and the Cardinals in the
first of three games, considered whether he would enjoy facing the
challenge of McGwire at the height of his prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. Would you?'' Maddux replied. ``Why would you enjoy facing
a guy who can hit the Coke bottle (above left field)? I enjoy
facing the singles hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
