<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-GAY-CONGRESS-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        HOUSE DEMS REGROUP DURING CALM IN STORM OF ANTI-GAY RIGHTS
LEGISLATION
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 30 -- House gay rights advocates had a chance
to regroup Thursday, thanks to a last-minute schedule change.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the House passed a measure that jeopardizes
millions of dollars of federal housing funds to San Francisco
unless it repeals a domestic partner ordinance. And Thursday, the
House was supposed to consider a proposal by Rep. Joel Hefley,
R-Colorado Springs, that would block President Clinton's executive
order making homosexuals a ``protected group'' against
discrimination in federal employment.
</P>
<P>
   But a delay in debate on a larger spending bill, to which Hefley
was going to attach his amendment, provided a temporary calm in
what critics consider a storm of anti-gay rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to fight because we are right,'' said Rep.
Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif. ``The very idea that (the Hefley amendment)
is coming to the floor -- that it's even being considered by this
body -- shows what we're up against in getting gay rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hefley said the intention of both measures were
misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of it causing this much of a stir,'' said
Hefley. ``It's become in some people's mind a big gay issue, which
is not what it is at all.''
</P>
<P>
   His amendment, which he intends to attach to the House spending
plan for the Departments of Commerce, Justice and State, is simply
``to prevent the president from carving out another protected
class,'' Hefley said, something he believes is a unnecessary and
would bog down the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wednesday's measure by Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., ``That
is a different issue in that, no, we won't let a local municipality
blackmail their contractors with our money,'' said Hefley.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley was referring to the city ordinance forcing companies
doing business with San Francisco to provide benefits to employees'
domestic partners. The Riggs amendment would prevent San Francisco
from using any federal housing money ``to implement'' that
ordinance, something that could cost the city $65 million dollars,
according to Pelosi.
</P>
<P>
   The Riggs amendment passed by a 214-212 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democrats said Thursday that both bills are about one
thing: discriminating against gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the millennium, we are still hung up on who to
discriminate against,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., who, as the
only Holocaust survivor to be elected to Congress, said the issue
of discrimination ``touches the very core of my being.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a hundred years ago, we had slavery on the basis of
pigmentation,'' said Lantos, adding: ``Are we still not grown up
enough to realize that discrimination... is an outrage?''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the bills are part of a GOP assault on gay rights,
which has included Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
equating homosexuality to alcoholism and kleptomania, and the
Senate holding up the nomination of gay philanthropist James Hormel
as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., the only openly gay Democrat in the
House, said the measures are really election bellwethers for the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're setting up here is a test for November,'' said
Frank. ``The right wing, to its credit, will vote. Too many
moderates and liberals... will just denounce politics, or vote
Green, making sure the Republicans win.''
</P>
<P>
   The only open gay GOP Congressman, Jim Kolbe of Arizona, was
among 35 Republicans who voted against the Riggs amendment. Kolbe
did not return a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley's amendment was originally going to be attached to the
Treasury and Postal Service spending bill, until House leaders
realized that Kolbe was managing that debate, and delayed the
Hefley amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment is expected to be introduced early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, House Democrats said they will be making sure they
have enough votes to defeat it. Hefley said he does not know how
many votes his measure will get.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also said they will try to ensure that the Riggs
measure does not make it into the yet-to-be-passed Senate version
of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Hefley amendment, Frank said he is confident the
proposal will be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this one will lose,'' said Frank. ``I think they've
clearly over reached on this one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
