<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      07-30 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESS APPROACHING LEWINSKY INQUIRY A LITTLE MORE CAUTIOUSLY SECOND
TIME AROUND
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-PERJURY) 
(sw) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The period of press hand-wringing and soul-searching is long
past. The harsh critique of the news media in Brill's Content is by
now old news. And the Monica Lewinsky story is back with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, news organizations are proceeding as usual:
plastering their front pages and leading their television reports
with news about developments in the case. But news executives say
they are doing things differently this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all being a bit more cautious in making sure
that we get things in perspective,'' said Walter Isaacson, managing
editor of Time magazine. ``But I'm really not sure that there were
any major transgressions made the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Steven Brill, who harshly criticized coverage of the
Lewinsky case as irresponsible in his magazine on the news media,
said he had noticed a slight change in approach on the part of
several news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being a little more careful about identifying
sources,'' Brill said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike, the White House press secretary, said: ``As the chum
in the water, I can attest it's the same feeding frenzy. The press
has but one speed on this story and it's fast forward with too few
editors who press the pause button.''
</P>
<P>
   While many newspaper, magazine and television journalists have
defended their initial coverage as appropriate, some news
executives say the accusations of Brill and other critics prompted
a healthy self-examination about reliable sourcing and getting too
far ahead of the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do my level best to make sure everything we
publish feels very solid and is based on our reporting, not on
second- or third-hand reporting,'' said Stephen Smith, who recently
resigned as editor of National Journal to become editor of U.S.
News &AMP; World Report. ``Watching the big press, which got so
competitive on this story, was a real lesson for me. You could see
people pushing the story further than it really wanted to go
because they were so locked into being first.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Wolinsky, managing editor for news at The Los Angeles Times,
said criticism of the press had forced his newspaper to try to
provide better context and to winnow out gratuitous, salacious
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make sure these stories have material that
says to the public, `This is why it's important,''' Wolinsky said.
``There has been a real focusing on what the real story is _ Is
there suborning of perjury? Are there crimes that would affect the
future of the presidency? _ as opposed to details of sex lives.''
</P>
<P>
   One element complicating the coverage, Wolinsky said, is that
news organizations are getting conflicting information from
different sources. As a result, he said, journalists from one news
organization at times wind up reporting what other news
organizations are saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are constantly leaking and spinning,'' Wolinsky said.
``Trying to get corroboration _ to not use gossip _ is much more
difficult on a story like this than it would be on any other story.
We're trying not to go out on a limb that might be sawed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, news organizations continue to rely heavily on anonymous
sources, making it difficult for the public to evaluate where the
information is coming from and why. In addition, with a scarcity of
concrete developments to cover and an abundance of air time to
fill, several television programs have continued to speculate about
impeachment and compare Clinton's predicament at this point to that
of President Richard Nixon after disclosure of the contents of the
Watergate tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a danger of lowest-common-denominator journalism,''
said James Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House counsel. ``In
an effort to avoid being scooped, often journalists will all try to
match the latest salacious story. When you're reduced to reporting
what other people are reporting, then you've abandoned your own
standards and adopted the other organizations' standards and I
think that's a dangerous path to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some news executives say, much of what they
reported in the early days of the story has proved accurate. ``In
many ways it's remarkable how the evidence in January is the
evidence today,'' Isaacson of Time said. ``It's not like, `Oh, that
was totally wrong. There were no tapes; there were no dresses.'''
</P>
<P>
   News organizations have been in retreat about the ``talking
points,'' intended to coach Linda Tripp on possible testimony about
Clinton. While there had been rampant speculation in the news media
about who in the Clinton administration might have written them,
Ms. Lewinsky herself has apparently claimed authorship.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather, the CBS News anchor, said he subscribed to the view
``Better to be last than to be wrong'' but said news organizations
were operating in an increasingly crowded marketplace, which can
cloud judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive pit is much larger, much fiercer,'' Rather
said. ``One news organization will report something and the
pressure is immediate and immense to match it. But that's not an
excuse. ``There is no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Kovach, curator of the Nieman Foundation Journalism
Fellowships at Harvard University, said that however important the
story might be, coverage of it had been premature _ covering leaks,
not actual news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still crystal clear that the press is being used by
sources to an extent that really raises questions about just how
independent the press is,'' Kovach said. ``If I were an editor, I
would try to avoid publishing conclusionary statements about what
people are going to testify, because we don't know what they're
going to testify.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
