<SLUG> BC-GM-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM BOARD HAS DIFFICULT MEETING COMING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The board of General Motors faces an unusually
difficult meeting on Monday because the company's management raised
Wall Street's expectations this summer for a drastic cost-cutting
move only to conclude a strike settlement this week that calls for
closer cooperation with the United Automobile Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Board members will have a wide range of options at their
regularly scheduled meeting. Most auto analysts were predicting
Thursday that the company would choose limited moves that might not
offend the UAW but also might not do much to improve the company's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials declined to speculate on the outcome of the board's
deliberations, which will also include meetings of some board
committees on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Possible limited moves include proceeding with a long-expected
initial public offering of a 20 percent stake in GM's auto parts
division; reshuffling some vice presidents, and eliminating the
production of some unprofitable car models and assigning workers to
other models.
</P>
<P>
   The board may also decide to combine the vehicle distribution
and marketing staffs of divisions like Chevrolet, Buick and
Cadillac, creating instead regional marketing offices that would
handle all cars and trucks. This might reduce nonunion,
white-collar employment slightly but would have little effect on
the public because the names of cars and dealerships would not
change.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hackworth, GM's group vice president for North American
car operations, said several times during the nearly eight-week
strike at two parts factories in Flint, Mich., that the automaker
was reconsidering the viability of various models and factories.
While the UAW has long tolerated changes in what models GM builds,
it has fought factory closings.
</P>
<P>
   Auto analysts said Thursday that they were trying to lower
institutional investors' hopes for any big moves, such as the
closing of unprofitable factories or layoffs of tens of thousands
of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for North American
personnel, said late Tuesday that company and union officials would
begin meeting more regularly to discuss problems before they turn
into strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
the same day that GM had not raised the possibility of factory
closings during strike-settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   David Bradley, an auto analyst with J.P. Morgan, said that those
comments made it unlikely that the GM board would take any big
steps on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been closing factories and reducing its work force
through attrition since the late 1970s as its American market share
has diminished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
