r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OPENER-TE     07-30 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OPENER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY GOES ON PUBLIC VIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Even exuberant Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin
can't remember the last time he got excited about a preseason
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, the 11-year veteran can barely remember even playing in
one.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin brings almost rookie-like emotion into tonight's
exhibition matchup against the Seattle Seahawks, set for 8 o'clock
at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bet we are going to be in there longer than we are
used to,'' Irvin said of the Cowboys' first team. ``We are ready to
line up against somebody else and see what this offense looks like
against another team. Because of that, we are looking forward to
playing. ''
</P>
<P>
   Several changes after last season's 6-10 campaign, highlighted
by the addition of coach Chan Gailey and his new offense, the 1998
preseason might be far different from any of the past several
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, the offensive coordinator at Pittsburgh last season,
will make his inaugural walk into Texas Stadium as head coach. The
shotgun will make a Cowboys appearance for the first time in seven
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will also get a first look at top draft pick Greg Ellis,
newly acquired free-agent running back Chris Warren, a slimmed-down
Nate Newton, the position battles at free safety and No. 2
receiver, fullback Daryl Johnston in game action after neck
surgery, and a revamped defense scheme, featuring a ``3-4'' look.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey acknowledged that the environment surrounding the
preseason opener is unusual and therefore isn't surprised that
veterans like Irvin and quarterback Troy Aikman are excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are excited about it just like I think all of us are
excited about playing a game with a new offense and a new
defense,'' Gailey said. ``And \Rwe're excited about\S seeing how
some things turn out to make an evaluation of where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The area drawing the most anticipation is the offense, where the
power running and precision passing scheme of years past gives way
to Gailey's power-running, high-octane attack, that will feature
the shotgun and five-receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who will play about a quarter, along with the rest of
the first team, said he wants to play as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play as much as possible because it's a new
offense,'' Aikman said. ``We need to get a feel for it in a
game-type situation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Aikman warned that the offense might not look too
smooth the first time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want perfect execution,'' he said. ``But more likely, it
will look a little rough and we know that. We know there's going to
be some mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of offense, the game is also a spotlight for Gailey and
his coaching staff, including seven new assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps the coaches,'' Gailey said. ``We have a new warmup
procedure, new people on the phone, new people upstairs in the
coaching booth, new people downstairs on the sideline. It helps our
game-day management procedures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
