<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTE-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTE ATTACKS CAPE COD TOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With sidebar, Coyote-Sightings)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ A coyote sprang from the woods and attacked a
3-year-old boy Wednesday evening as he played on his backyard
swingset here, the first documented case of a coyote attacking a
human in Massachusetts and one of only a dozen cases nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was rescued when his mother kicked and punched the
coyote, wresting her bleeding son from its clutches. The animal
then began growling at the boy's five-year-old sister, who was at
the top of the swingset, before police officers arrived and killed
it.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Neal was treated and released early Thursday morning at
Children's Hospital in Boston for bites to the head, arm, chest and
back. As a precaution, he was given the first battery of shots for
rabies.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, officials began trying to solve the mystery of what
prompted the coyote _ one of a burgeoning number of coyotes in
heavily populated Massachusetts towns _ to become violent.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Deblinger, the state's assistant director for wildlife, said
he douted the animal had rabies. More likely, he said, the coyote
had gotten accustomed to being around humans from either being fed
by them or eating food they had put out for their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it's cute to get close to wildlife,'' Deblinger
said. ``But when wild animals get used to handouts and their
feeding gets interrupted, that's when we get problems like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes are normally skittish around humans, but this one had
become so aggressive over the last several days that local police
were actually hunting it when the attack occurred about 6:30 p.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel and his 5-year-old sister Elena were playing on the
swingset in their back yard, which borders the Massachusetts
Military Reservation in the Forestdale section of Sandwich. Daniel
was on the glider while his sister was climbing on a section of the
set next to her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the coyote pulled Daniel off the swingset and dragged
him about 10 feet closer to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Audra Neal, who was in the kitchen, heard the commotion and ran
out and started kicking and punching the coyote. She then rushed
him inside, telling her daughter to stay up on the swingset. She
came back outside, staying between her daughter and the coyote
until her daughter was safely inside. She then called police.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwich Police officer Michael F. Hoadley had been hunting the
coyote for several days, as sightings had increased and its
behavior became more aggressive. At nearby Camp Good News, local
officials said, the same coyote had pulled a child in a sleeping
bag out of his tent. It had scratched another camper and come face
to face with a third.
</P>
<P>
   Hoadley said he had spotted the coyote Wednesday morning but it
ran off before he could get a safe shot at it. He took a run later
in the day after work, listening to Van Halen on his headset. A
driver pulled up alongside him as he jogged and pointed behind him.
There was the coyote again, loping along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coyote was on my heels,'' Hoadley said. ``He must have
known I was coming for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the coyote ran into the woods. About two hours later, at
about 6:50, Audra Neal's call to police came in. Arriving at the
Neal home, Hoadley said, he could hear the mother and child
screaming inside the house and then spotted the coyote out back. It
took three shots to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home Thursday, Daniel Neal seemed in good spirits
after waking up from a nap Thursday afternoon. His mother, sitting
with him on their home's back deck, said: ``I only did what I had
to.''
</P>
<P>
   The coyote was a relatively young female, weighing an estimated
50 to 55 pounds. Rabies tests are expected to be concluded sometime
late today, but rabies is almost unknown on the Cape, in large part
because of a program begun three years ago to drop food for
raccoons from helicopters. The food contains the rabies vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   In every instance where a coyote has attacked a human, Deblinger
said, ``it was a fed coyote that attacked someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Chapman, the animal control officer in Sandwich, said
officials also are investigating whether the animal had distemper,
which he said could also cause aggressive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Chapman said, he had always told people nervous
about coyotes to just make a lot of noise and they will take off.
``Now with this incident,'' he said, ``it's hard to tell them
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
