<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Business disinterest may KO Holyfield bout
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Evander Holyfield's last scheduled fight was voided
because of an opponent's positive hepatitis B test. His next
proposed bout might be floored because the host city has tested
negative for cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's desire to fight in the Georgia Dome on Sept. 19,
with Vaughn Bean as the probable opponent, appeared unlikely
Thursday because the Atlanta business community has not guaranteed
the financial support that the heavyweight champion and his
attorney, Jim Thomas, had hoped for or expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people keep telling you, `I need more time,' I lose
faith,'' Thomas said. ``People's words begin to ring hollow. The
other day, I thought this was a done deal. Now I'm pretty
discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who has resumed training in Houston, said, ``It's
hard for me to understand why nobody has been able to pull this
thing together. People have to understand that this isn't (my
fault). I want to do this. I'm taking considerably less money to
fight in Atlanta. I want to give kids the opportunity to say, 'I
saw the three-time heavyweight champion of the world fight.' If it
doesn't happen, it's because the (business) people didn't show
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's camp is seeking Atlanta businesses to guarantee the
$2 million to $3 million that promoter Don King believes is
necessary to help cover the promotional cost. The boxing card also
might include a concert.
</P>
<P>
   King also would like to receive financial concessions from the
state, which operates the Dome, and from local hotels to house
boxers, officials and Showtime employees.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime would carry the fight on its cable network or as a
pay-per-view offering.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield intended to make available thousands of moderately
priced tickets, hoping to draw as many as 50,000 people to the
Dome, which never has held boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he updated King on the lack of progress. ``He didn't
seem surprised,'' Thomas said. ``He said he never believes it until
he sees the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The next logical site for a Holyfield-Bean fight is Las Vegas,
but an alternative date probably would be sought because of the
Oscar De La Hoya-Julio Cesar Chavez rematch Sept. 18 at Caesars
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the option of trying to reschedule the mandatory
defense against Henry Akinwande in Las Vegas. Doctors believe
Akinwande no longer is infectious with the hepatitis B virus, but
the New York State Athletic Commission, which canceled the June 6
bout with Holyfield, has a zero-tolerance rule, and Akinwande's
blood continues to show traces of antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield never thought opponents would be that hard to come by.
His master plan was to get the WBA and IBF mandatory bouts behind
him so he could concentrate on unifying the three major belts with
a Lennox Lewis fight in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thinks Atlanta-based companies that might financially
back
</P>
</TEXT>
