<P>
   TECH-LOBBYING _ WASHINGTON _ Last fall, the high-tech industry
lost a legislative skirmish in its multi-year battle with the FBI
and U.S. spy agencies over who will control encryption of messages
on the Internet. Scared and enraged by a loss that threatened the
growth of their industry's profits, high-tech rivals stopped
dissing each other long enough to chip in more than $5 million to
form a lobbying coaltion called Americans for Computer Privacy and
convince a lot of their customers, suppliers and sympathizers to
sign up. Launched in March, the $5 million lobbying alliance of
more than 90 companies and 40 associations already has won some
early rounds in its fight against the FBI and U.S. spy agencies.
Who formed Americans for Computer Privacy, why, how they grew it,
how they run it, and what it does. (Mollison).
</P>
<P>
   With art and data for a graphic showing the founding, inner
circle and rank-and-file companies and associations in the
coalition, together with lobbying and political expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ENCRYPTION WASHINGTON _ What the coalition wants and why
its foes don't want to give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Thursday for release Sunday, Aug. 2.
