<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXFORD-MARKETPLACE-57     07-30 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXFORD-MARKETPLACE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: A HEALTH PLAN'S RELAPSING STOCK TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is it time for investors to stick a toe in? The stock
of Oxford Health Plans, the troubled managed-care company, has long
been down and out, after plunging last year when the company told
investors to expect an enormous loss. Now, the stock has again
fallen precipitously, losing nearly half its sharply reduced value
in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It closed on Nasdaq Thursday at $8.4325, after touching a new
low of $7.375 during the previous day's trading.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's shares traded above $20 earlier this year, buoyed by
takeover speculation and the news that the fund group run by
Michael F. Price, the renowned value investor, had bought the
stock. Texas Pacific, a savvy private investment group led by David
Bonderman, also rode to Oxford's rescue with badly needed capital.
</P>
<P>
   But following that smart money has not led the average investor
to more riches, and the stock does not strike many as a bargain
even at its low, low levels today. Price's group, Franklin Mutual
Advisers, which bought about 4.2 million shares late last year, has
apparently seen the value of its investment dwindle, and it
declined to say whether it still owned that stake.
</P>
<P>
   The other big shareholders, Texas Pacific and Dr. Norman C.
Payson, Oxford's new chief executive, are well insulated from the
effects of any bad news when the company reports its second-quarter
results in mid-August. Under the deal struck by Texas Pacific, the
price of its stake depends on the stock's price next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Payson, who plunked down $10 million of his hard-earned
money for Oxford's stock _ at $15.52 a share _ stands to get
options on 1 million shares based on the price at the time of the
company's annual meeting in late August. His options on 2 million
more shares can be exercised at $15.52.
</P>
<P>
   These investors have an advantage over someone who might wade in
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a better piece of paper,'' said Larry Feinberg of
Oracle Partners, a hedge fund that specializes in health care and
who is not buying the stock.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be driving the share price down in recent days is
the growing anxiety of investors over the company's financial
results, which are expected during the week of Aug. 10. Oxford is
keeping mum, and some stock analysts fear a sizable loss _ at least
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it's anyone's guess. ``Given Oxford's lack of communication
with the investment community, it is difficult, if not impossible,
to form realistic earnings expectations,'' Roberta L. Walter, a
Merrill Lynch analyst, recently said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are also concerned about the consequences of the
company's turnaround plan, outlined in a letter sent to doctors
last week. In the letter, Payson warned that the health care
provider, which is still losing money, would be cutting fees to
doctors and raising premiums to return to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Frazier, an analyst with Bear Stearns, like most of his
brethren on Wall Street, is not recommending the stock. ``Oxford is
not going to be the Oxford of old and the Oxford for everyone,'' he
aid.
</P>
<P>
   The health care provider's popularity with patients _ it still
has more than 2 million customers _ has been built on the promise
of an affordable health plan that allows consumers to go to a
doctor of their choice. No one knows if the plan will remain a
crowd-pleaser if premiums go up sharply or if doctors, unhappy with
lower fees, start leaving the network.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the share price hitting new lows, even investors with a
reputation for sniffing out bargains look like daredevils.
</P>
<P>
   According to Technimetrics, a New York investor-relations
research company that studies quarterly filings of stock ownership,
the Franklin fund group picked up its Oxford shares late last year,
when they were trading in the mid-teen's or higher. Next month,
investors will find out if Franklin still owned the shares at the
end of June. If Franklin is selling now, it will not be disclosed
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Such big questions leave other buyers of the common shares with
little to go on. Even if they are not concerned with how much
Oxford may have lost for the quarter, information is scant about
the company's progress in sorting out the extensive systems
problems that caused it to lose track of its costs. Oxford may
still not know how much it costs to deliver care, making it
difficult to decide how much to charge its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Additional losses, especially if they are sizable, would also
eat into capital, a danger for a company that must adhere to
certain state requirements. ``If losses persist,'' Ms. Walter of
Merrill Lynch said, ``Oxford might have to raise additional capital
to meet statutory reserve requirements,'' further diluting existing
shares. The company secured $710 million in financing earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   One hope, of course, is that the company will prove to be an
attractive takeover candidate for a competitor wanting a strong
market position in the New York area. But it is unclear just how
many members Oxford will have once the dust settles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the franchise is predicated on an underpriced business, how
good is the franchise?'' wondered one analyst, who spoke in
exchange for anonymity. Just as investors seem to be holding off,
potential acquirers might want to wait until Oxford's business
position is clearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the next three months that will change the
fate of the stock,'' said Kenneth Abramowitz, an analyst with
Sanford C. Bernstein, who thinks that the company could be a great
value for an investor with the patience to stick it out for a year
or two.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Oxford's stock has hit bottom, investors may want to
wait until its earnings come out before they go fishing. The water
looks awfully muddy right now, and some investors have better bait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
