<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALCONS-NOTES31-COX     07-30 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 BC- FALCONS-NOTES31-COX &HT;    For some, the answer to injury is play hurt
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Falcons' list of walking wounded didn't
grow any shorter Thursday as three players missed the morning
practice and four missed the afternoon session on the seventh day
of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Being injured means different things for different players.
</P>
<P>
   For backup guard Scott Adams, who has been with eight teams in
eight years, including the Falcons twice, it means unless your leg
has fallen off, you practice. The former Georgia standout has a
strained hamstring and a badly sprained ankle. But he has missed no
time, hobbling through practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like me, who's always been concerned just with making
the team ... hey, I'm going to be out there,'' said Adams, who has
been to 10 training camps on rosters in Dallas, Atlanta, Minnesota,
New Orleans, Chicago, Tampa Bay, Denver and Atlanta again. ``Maybe
if you're an All-Pro you don't take any chances. Not me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, that means convincing the medical or training staff
you're all right when you're really not. ``I've told my share of
lies, but none recently,'' said Adams, who also played for the
Barcelona Dragons of the World League in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran cornerback Randy Fuller, who has missed six straight
practices _ or half of camp _ also has a badly sprained ankle. But
his situation is different from Adams'. If Fuller goes out and
tries to play, it can only do harm for him to stumble around as
receiver blow past. Then again, if the graduate of Spencer High in
Columbus doesn't come back soon and show what he can do, that won't
help either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting very antsy,'' said Fuller, a four-year veteran who
played the last three seasons in Pittsburgh. ``It hurts me because
this is the most crucial point in training camp ... when you're
learning all the defenses. Every day I miss, I fall further behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're only as good as your last play, and ... mine was in
Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will practice at 9 this morning, and after meetings
this afternoon, fly to Jacksonville for Saturday's 8:15 and 2:15
scrimmage-practices. The team will be off Sunday, other than
evening meetings, and practice twice Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Turning up the heat
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon was the hottest yet: 92 degrees with 60
percent humidity, producing a heat index between 100 and 105
degrees. It was 93 one afternoon last week, but the humidity was
below 50 percent. Players were pleased there was no conditioning
after the afternoon practice, a first this camp, but most of them
had lifting scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   QB watch
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what's going on with the quarterbacks:
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler _ Worked all day with the first unit, and threw
his share of drills. Connected of 5-of-6 passes in the hurry-up
drill at the end of two-hour afternoon practice with Tony Martin,
Terance Mathis and Todd Kinchen as receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graziani _ Ditto, except with the second unit. Threw better
than a day earlier, but was 0-for-3 in hurry-up drill with Mercury
Hayes, Jammi German and Kevin Thornal as receivers. Also had
placement duties with kickers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve DeBerg _ Ditto, but with third unit, no hurry-up drill.
Threw an interception (Jessie Tuggle) in the afternoon when there
was no receiver within 10 yards in 11-on-11s. Also had placement
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brennan _ Used in drills all day, and then he got one snap
with the No. 1 unit in the 11-on-11s near the end of the afternoon
practice. His job was to throw an interception. He missed when a
cornerback went the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   The good, bad, and ugly
</P>
<P>
   Good: In afternoon 11-on-11s (minus tackling), while the
third-string offense was going against the No. 3 defense,
linebackers Ben Talley and Ruffin Hamilton sniffed out a screen
pass to Ken Oxendine and arrived in the backfield at the same time
as the pass from DeBerg.
</P>
<P>
   Bad: In the hurry-up drill at the end of afternoon practice,
Graziani threw deep down the right sideline to German, who was in
double coverage. It didn't matter, though, because German broke off
the route.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly: Chandler let a pass get away in the morning 11-on-11s, and
it went straight to defensive end Lester Archambeau, who found
himself all alone in rare pass coverage. Ugly II: Archambeau
dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   What they said
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie's popping it in the slot every time. It's really nice
to have a good, solid snap over and over.'' _ Chandler, on the
center-quarterback exchange between converted guard Robbie Tobeck
and himself.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons water their three practice fields with giant
sprinklers, the water is drawn from the lake/pond next to
headquarters. It takes about 80,000 gallons each time, and the
water stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Home cooking
</P>
<P>
   Undrafted free agent receiver Corey Allen of Georgia doesn't get
a lot of chances to show his stuff, but got more than usual
Thursday. In the afternoon practice, he got open on a flag route
deep down the middle, catching a perfect pass from Graziani. Later,
in 11-on-11s, he ran a nice curl route of about 12 yards, caught
the ball, and fumbled it away.
</P>
<P>
   Run over him, and smile
</P>
<P>
   With receivers coach Rennie Simmons and defensive backs coach
Ron Meeks tutoring and head coach Dan Reeves observing, there was a
drill in the morning that had receivers trying to get off the line
of scrimmage, and DBs trying to jam them. There were two lines at
once, causing Reeves to tell them to alternate, and ``wait until
the (video) camera is on you.'' The Falcons videotape nearly every
aspect of practice, most of it from one of two tall, portable,
telescoping towers. Meaning: Even if coaches didn't see players
mess up on the field, they'll probably catch it later.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Instead of 1-on-1 drills where defensive linemen go against
offensive linemen, Thursday afternoon it was 2-on-2, and sometimes
2-on-3 (offensive linemen) as defenders occasionally stunted. ...
Shawn Swayda and Esera Tuaolo, who've been working at backup right
and left defensive tackle, respectively, switched for some reps in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Fumble!
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons spend 5-10 minutes in almost every practice working
on turnovers, doing different drills each day. Thursday morning,
running backs worked on protecting the ball as they tried to strip
each other from behind, wide receivers worked on recovering fumbles
on the run, and offensive linemen worked on recovering fumbles,
period. Defensive backs worked on recovering onsides kicks,
linebackers worked on recovering fumbles before they squirted out
of bounds (after being rolled toward the sideline by LB coach Don
Blackmon), and the defensive line worked on recovering fumbles.
Most days, they do a drill where DBs run up behind WRs and try to
strip the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
