<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers won't go to minors
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Mark Wohlers has no interest in returning to
Richmond. If the Braves were hoping the struggling reliever might
retreat to Class AAA for another optional assignment, they better
get another plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staying here,'' Wohlers said after Thursday's game. ``Even
if I strike out every hitter I face, it's got to be at the
big-league level. I'm aware of the circumstances. I understand my
playoff spot on the roster is in jeopardy. But if I got down there
and pitched great, then come back here and have two bad outings,
I'm in jeopardy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching at AAA is irrelevant. That's how I feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the club had not formally suggested that Wohlers take
another assignment _ he was away from the team for 22 games in June
and July _ officials were hopeful he might be persuaded to return
to Richmond, based on his struggles since returning. In his six
appearances since being recalled, Wohlers has given up 13 runs on
five hits and 14 walks in just 3 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had discussed the matter with manager Bobby Cox,
Wohlers replied: ``You know what? The last time, I got in a whole
lot of trouble when I had a conversation with Bobby. If he wants to
speak about it, I hope he feels free to talk about it. But I'm just
trying to make things less chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said Wohlers' situation would be discussed in his meeting
with general manager John Schuerholz this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do what's best for him,'' Cox said. ``But I also
have to do what's best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye to Cortes
</P>
<P>
   Last season, David Cortes was the talk of the low end of the
Braves' farm system, saving 23 games and striking out 55 in 48
appearances as he jumped from Class A Macon to Class A Durham to
Class AA Greenville. In the first two months of the season, when
the Atlanta bullpen was teetering, the club considered calling up
Cortes from Class AAA Richmond, where the 24-year-old right-hander
began the season.
</P>
<P>
   But he never got his chance because of shoulder trouble that put
him on the DL. And now he is gone, dealt to Colorado, along with
left-handed pitcher Mike Porzio (3-2, 2.51 ERA, two saves in 26
games) of Class A Danville (Carolina League).
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you've got to give something to get something,'' Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cortes' numbers were not as strong at Richmond, but he was still
a strong prospect in a system pushed for relievers. He was 3-3 with
17 saves and a 2.82 ERA in 29 appearances. The International League
was hitting .227 against him, and he had struck out 46 in 44 2/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   No maximum John
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz is not in a suspendable mood. Still incredulous the
day after he was ejected by rookie umpire Hunter Wendelstedt when
the ump stepped on his foot, Smoltz said he would fight any fine or
suspension the National League might send down. He remains adamant
that Wendelstedt mishandled the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing the replay, I don't think there's any
questionable doubt at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
