<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Heritage time again
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As a continuation of last year's elaborate Jackie
Robinson celebration, the Atlanta Braves will recognize cultural
diversity in baseball in the second annual ``Heritage Salute'' this
weekend at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will wear the uniforms of the 1940 Atlanta Black
Crackers of the Negro League in their games Saturday and Sunday
against the St. Louis Cardinals, who will wear the gear of the 1928
St. Louis Stars of the Negro League.
</P>
<P>
   Video memories from Hank Aaron, Willie Mays, Dennis Martinez and
Juan Marichal, among many others, will be featured during the
games. There also will be a trivia contest on African-American and
Hispanic players.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, there will be on-field ceremonies with the likes
of Jackie Robinson's daughter, Sharon Robinson, and former Negro
League players Joe Black and Buck O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a Major League Baseball/Negro League exhibit will be on
display in the Hank Aaron Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the quality of the events, and we're
excited about continuing to acknowledge these players who have
given so much to the game,'' said Dexter Santos, the Braves'
director of community relations and fan development.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have scheduled a Heritage Festival for Saturday
afternoon at Grant Park for 3,000 area youths, who also will be
invited to attend Sunday's game and participate in a pregame
parade, led by the New Orleans-based band Coolbone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
