<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-SKATE-COX     07-30 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-SKATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nagano runner-up still achieving
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Figure skater Michelle Kwan is so popular that
10 days after her ``Mulan'' special on ice aired last month on ABC,
the network squeezed it back into the prime-time schedule on short
notice.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be shown yet again Saturday morning _ even the
``Seinfeld'' finale got only two airings _ and then Kwan will
appear live that night on TBS in the Goodwill Games. ``When I was
13, people told me I would be burned out by the time I was 18, but
here I am,'' said Kwan, who celebrated her 18th birthday on July 7
with a surprise party during a 59-city, 3 1/2-month skating tour.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a silver lining in being Olympic runner-up, Kwan has
found it. And she doesn't even consider her loss to Tara Lipinski
at the 1998 Olympics a dark cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things I could've done better, maybe,'' said
Kwan, who admitted to being overwhelmed by all of the fuss in
Nagano. But she added, ``I don't feel depressed about it. I'm proud
of what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan saw room for improvement in her speed and jumps as she
reviewed the Olympic videotape before the Goodwill Games, where
she's skating the same programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a smile on my face while I was watching it,'' Kwan said.
``At the end of my program (in Nagano), I couldn't believe I had
done it. ... But when I was watching it, I was saying to myself,
'Push Michelle, push. You can do it.' I needed a little more oomph
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The public couldn't have been more moved by Kwan's graciousness
in defeat. She has received thousands of letters, and a soap
endorsement fit in perfectly with her squeaky-clean image.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one lady, probably in her 70s, wrote that she had some
kind of disease and she was holding on for me until 2002,'' Kwan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan is determined to compete that year in the Salt Lake City
Olympics, although she says that she misses skating against
Lipinski, who was turning pro while Kwan was winning her second
world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much what's out there. It's what I want inside. I
love competing. I love the challenge. That's what keeps me going. I
don't feel that I'll be that old, either. 21? I mean, please,'' she
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan says that staying eligible for the Olympics will allow more
people to see her skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like to share my skating with them and put them into
a trance, sort of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the perception that the Olympic silver medalist has
gotten more attention than the gold medalist, she pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I skate, it's always good sportsmanship,'' said Kwan, the
most introspective female skater of this decade. ``I believe that
competition's only a competition, and it only goes so far. If
things don't go your way, you just have to keep your head up high
and keep on going.''
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, she conceded, ``I thought if I didn't
win, my life would be over.''
</P>
<P>
   And now? ``The gold medal may be great, but I feel that there's
more to accomplish than just the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   She wants to begin practicing her triple-triple combinations,
now that her fractured toe has stopped hurting. And then there is
``landing that triple axel I've been talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Her coach, Frank Carroll, said she's a young lady in charge of
her life. One day, he said, she was in ``a little bit of a funk''
and wasn't skating well. He offered to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to say and do nothing,'' Kwan told him. ``This
isn't your problem; this is my problem. Give me two or three
minutes and I'll be over it, and we'll be fine, but I'm the one who
has to snap out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes passed, Carroll said, ``And she was marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan's maturation also is visible in her glamorous look. She
appears at news conferences immaculately dressed, usually in black
linen or leather.
</P>
<P>
   Her ``Mulan'' special gave her the opportunity to do love scenes
with French heartthrob Philippe Candeloro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of retakes,'' she said. ``We'd have to be very
serious and in love. ... You know how we're just goofballs. We
looked into each other's eyes and, with the camera right next to
us, we'd bust out laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Games, Kwan will stay in New York City with her
sister, Karen, who's interning with designer Vera Wang. She'll
shop, see some Broadway shows and study for her final exams in
August before winging off to Hawaii. She will put off applying to
colleges until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   She's considered Harvard, but that would mean leaving Carroll
and Lake Arrowhead, Calif., where she will begin work soon on next
season's skating programs.
</P>
<P>
   And if she can't compete at the standard she has set for
herself? Kwan may skip next year's national and world
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to come out,'' she said, ``having the same old
Michelle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
