<HEADER>
A1276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEC-FOOTBALL-COX     07-30 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-FOOTBALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll favors Gators over Tennessee
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Tennessee football fans are a proud bunch and
over the past five seasons they have good reason to be:
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Tennessee has posted a 50-11 record. Only one school
in the SEC has won more games _ Florida with 55.
</P>
<P>
   In that same span, Tennessee has averaged 10 wins per year. Only
Florida has been better, averaging 11 wins.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five seasons, Tennessee is 33-7 in SEC games.
Florida is 36-4 with four SEC titles to Tennessee's one.
</P>
<P>
   Are we detecting a pattern here? Tennessee fans have had a great
deal to celebrate lately, including the Vols' 1997 SEC
championship, being ranked in the Top 10 for 35 of the last 36
polls and the coming and going of the great Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who bleed Big Orange, who make the righteous trek
to Neyland Stadium on Saturdays each fall, there is something
missing. In all that success, in all that football glory, there
still is no win over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has won five straight over the Volunteers, and on
Thursday the Gators were picked to win the SEC championship again,
in a poll of sportswriters and broadcasters. Those same voters, by
a 41-4 vote, chose Florida over Tennessee in the league's Eastern
Division. In other words, few people here think the Vols will win
when they host Florida at Neyland Stadium in a nationally televised
(8 p.m., CBS) game on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   It is a theme that became familiar to coach Phillip Fulmer as he
toured the Tennessee booster clubs this spring. It was said in many
different ways, but the message was the same: ``Coach, we love you,
and we're glad you won the SEC. But when are we finally going to
beat Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it bothers me,'' Fulmer said. ``Everybody has their own
goals and their own ego. We've accomplished an awful lot of good
things. But (beating Florida is) a hump we haven't gotten over
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee should feel good about its chances on Sept. 19.
Despite the loss of Manning, the Vols are expected to be very good
on offense again. The defense has a few holes to fill, but there is
plenty of talent. And they get to play at home before 107,000 fans,
the largest crowd in college football.
</P>
<P>
   But the size of Thursday's vote in favor of Florida spoke
volumes about who has the psychological edge in this series.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem for Tennessee is that beating Florida has
become a major cause for celebration. LSU's fans stormed the field
and tore down the goalposts. Georgia, which beat the Gators in
November after seven straight losses, put out a video. Goodness
knows what Tennessee's fans will do if Florida falls in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice compliment watching how those teams react after
beating us,'' Florida coach Steve Spurrier said. ``But as I recall,
both of those teams lost their next game. Shoot, we like being up
there and having folks take their shot. That's what makes it fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's team has taken its cue from Spurrier on the Tennessee
game. They remain confident without being overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won them all lately, but it's always a dogfight,'' said
Terry Jackson, Florida's senior running back. ``We expect the same
up there.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the two teams will take different routes to the game.
Florida will play The Citadel and Northeast Louisiana in what
Spurrier called a couple of ``warm-up'' games. Tennessee, on the
other hand, opens Sept. 5 at Syracuse in what will be a noisy and
difficult task. The Vols take the next week off and then entertain
the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's losing streak, plus the fact that the Vols will be
without Manning, who never beat Florida, will make for an
intriguing prime-time event.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past few years, it was always the Peyton Manning game.
Everybody wondered if he could beat us,'' Florida defensive end
Jevon Kearse said. ``Now, they have another group of guys who are
ready to take their shot. It could be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
