<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPLELEAF-HOLLYWOOD-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIGHTS, CAMERA _ CANADA!'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This ``entertaining'' 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from
the International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general, ``e'' entertainment and ``f'' financial news
files.)  
  
 By RICHARD COVINGTON  
 c.1998 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASTIGOUCHE, QUEBEC _ Stripped to the waist, wearing long braids
and deerskin moccasins, Pierce Brosnan is no James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Brosnan, who recently portrayed that Hollywood staple, Agent
007, in ``Tomorrow Never Dies,'' has come to this wilderness camp
two hours north of Montreal to shoot one of the feature films that
is turning Canada into Hollywood North.
</P>
<P>
   He plays Grey Owl, the Indian trapper turned celebrity
conservationist, in Lord Richard Attenborough's coming film of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn by a lucrative mix of tax credits, enthusiastic, less
costly local crews and a depressed Canadian dollar, now worth about
68 U.S. cents, foreign investment has turned the Canadian film and
television industry into one of the busiest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Added to these financial incentives, a number of bilateral
treaties make Canadian co-productions a convenient way to sidestep
local quotas on imported films and television programs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of treaties with some 40 countries, notably
excluding the United States, foreign co-productions also qualify
for a range of subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   A French-Canadian production, for example, is considered French
in France and Canadian in Canada, gaining access to government
subsidies in both countries and bypassing restrictions on imported
productions.
</P>
<P>
   Last autumn, the Canadian government sweetened production deals
still further, giving tax credits amounting to 11 percent of labor
costs. This is on top of similar credits offered by the various
provincial authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto is now the third busiest production center in the world,
after Los Angeles and New York, according to industry sources.
Vancouver, where ``The X-Files'' and other American television
series are shot, is fourth.
</P>
<P>
   In Ontario alone, a third of film and television programs
generated last year _ 56 out of 161 _ were foreign productions,
according to the Ontario Film Development Corp. Other provinces
recorded a similar proportion of foreign to domestic production.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, total production amounted to $1.25 billion in the
three most active provinces, Ontario, British Columbia and Quebec,
according to statistics compiled by provincial film authorities, a
rise of $250 million over 1996 figures.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment accounted for $540 million, or slightly less
than half the 1997 total production budgets within the three
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Even Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and tiny Prince Edward Island
are getting in on the act, with a rising number of feature films
and made-for-TV movies being shot in these eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
   All told, some 65,000 people work in film and television
production in Canada, according to the local film boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers save around 15 percent making a film in Canada over
making the same film in the U.S.,'' said Jake Eberts, a veteran
Canadian producer whose film credits include ``Gandhi,'' ``A River
Runs Through It'' and ``Grey Owl.''
</P>
<P>
   As a British-Canadian co-production, the Attenborough-Brosnan
film qualifies for tax breaks in both countries, amounting to
around $5 million to $6 million of the $30 million budget,
according to Eberts.
</P>
<P>
   Subsidies for television productions are even higher, as much as
a third of production costs.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Paddington Bear,'' an animated series co-produced by the
Canadian company Cinar and the French television network TF1, 20
percent of the $9.3 million budget comes from Canadian subsidies
and a further 10 percent from French subsidies, according to Ronald
Weinberg, president and chief operating officer of Cinar. The
proportions reflect the amount spent on production in the two
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eberts and other filmmakers say they also appreciate the
chameleon quality of Canadian locations, with parts of Montreal
able to double for Liverpool in the 1930s and parts of Quebec City
standing in for a European city in the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen Paris a million times, London a gazillion times,
but we haven't seen Quebec that often,'' Eberts said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others point to the ready availability of experienced
crew members as another advantage to Canada. ``The crews are also
very good at doing things with not very much money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian director Norman Jewison, who filmed ``Agnes of
God,'' ``Moonstruck'' and other films largely in Ontario, said that
there had been a quantum leap in film production in Canada in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost impossible to make a feature film in Canada 20
years ago,'' Jewison said. He was one of the first to set up shop
in Toronto in 1978, converting an abandoned warehouse into a sound
stage and editing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Toronto is teeming with film activity, with the Canadian
Film Center celebrating its 10th anniversary promoting local
productions and talent and at least four studios churning out
special effects and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Animators graduating from Sheridan College in Toronto are being
snapped up by Walt Disney Co., Warner Brothers and other Hollywood
companies, according to Jewison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadian talent that used to automatically head for Los
Angeles and New York is staying in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Attracted by this growing pool of skills, even Hollywood
productions are relying on Canadian filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to suffer from the `coffee-boy syndrome,' where the
Americans brought in everyone but go-fers to fetch coffee,'' said
Alan King, president of the Directors Guild of Canada. Now programs
like ``The X-Files'' hire Canadian directors, some of whom, such as
Atom Egoyan and David Cronenberg, have achieved international
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the surge in Canadian production, films in
Canadian cinemas are overwhelmingly American. Only 1 percent of
films shown in English-speaking provinces and 3 percent in
French-speaking provinces are Canadian, King said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 950-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
New York Times Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in
Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
