<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-DICKERSON-NYT     07-30 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-DICKERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WOUNDED AT CAPITOL SHOOTOUT PRAISES SLAIN OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See related article, CAPITOL-SHOOTING)  
 (af)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angela Dickerson, who was wounded in last week's
shootings at the Capitol, said Thursday that she would carry no
deep scars, except perhaps emotional ones.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickerson, who turned 24 Thursday, appeared astonishingly
sound and serene for someone who was hit in the shoulder by a
.38-caliber bullet and wounded in the face by a bullet fragment six
days ago. But beneath the surface, she said, the shootings left her
afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more paranoid than I was before,'' she said. ``You never
know who's going to have a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would be able to identify the gunman when called as
a witness in the case. But precisely because she will be a witness,
her lawyer limited what she could say Thursday about the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickerson had no trouble describing what she felt as the
Capitol's corridors exploded with gunfire: ``It was extremely
terrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was seeing some of the sights of Washington for the
first time last Friday. ``I experienced a lot of `firsts,' '' she
said. ``Not only was it my first time to the Capitol, it was my
first time being shot.''
</P>
<P>
   One bullet passed cleanly through her shoulder, leaving only a
small scar. ``The bullet from my shoulder entered and exited, so
there was no need for surgery; just stitches to help the wound heal
with minimal scarring,'' Mrs. Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether that bullet was fired by Russell Weston
Jr., 41, who is charged in the attack, or by John Gibson, a
detective on the Capitol Police who was guarding the office of Rep.
Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip, and was one of two
police officers killed in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   A fragment from a second bullet lodged just below Mrs.
Dickerson's right eye. A fraction of an inch of difference would
have cost her the vision in that eye, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickerson expressed concern for Weston's family, and a
deeper emotion for the slain officers, Jacob Chestnut, 58, and
Gibson, 42, and their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to their families and friends for having to
experience such a terrible tragedy,'' she said at a news conference
in her lawyer's office. ``If Officer Chestnut and Special Agent
Gibson could hear me now, I'd tell them: `Thank you for doing such
a wonderful job and for protecting and saving so many lives. I only
wish that there were three surviving victims instead of me. May God
bless you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She had high praise for the ambulance workers and emergency
medical personnel, and for the staff at George Washington Hospital,
where she was treated. And she said she had received ``a ton of
flowers'' at her home, as well as a telephone call from President
Clinton on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickerson, a decorator for Ethan Allen, and her husband,
Stephen, a sales manager for Sears, Roebuck and Co., live in
Chantilly, Va., a suburb of Washington. She said she would be back
to work next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0420 </DOCNO>
