<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN CAPITOL HILL DETECTIVE IS BURIED AT ARLINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., N.Y., Ill.)  (See also CAPITOL-DICKERSON) 
(ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ After a funeral procession 15 miles long
journeyed from his hometown in rural Virginia to the nation's
Capitol and along the parade route of presidents, John Gibson was
buried here at the nation's cemetery Thursday with full military
honors.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 police cruisers from across the country
accompanied the black hearse bearing his body as the cortege rolled
north up Interstate 95 into Washington under the midday sun.
Traffic came to a standstill as hundreds of drivers stopped their
cars on overpasses and side roads to glimpse the procession.
</P>
<P>
   Once it passed the Capitol _ where Gibson, a Capitol Hill
detective, was killed in a shootout six days ago _ the procession
wove past the federal courthouse where lawyers for the suspected
gunman were meeting with a judge. It then crawled past the Lincoln
Memorial and across the Potomac River, where a dozen officers from
the U.S. Park Service Police, mounted on horseback, guarded the
gateway to Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the lead 260 officers in the motorcade peeled
off, lined their motorcycles along the length of Memorial Drive and
raised their hands in a final salute.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the day for police officers to honor Gibson, and
they showed up in force, from the California Highway Patrol to the
Minneapolis Police Department to the Nassau County (N.Y.) Police
Department. Gibson's mahogany coffin, glinting in the sun, was
borne to the grave by uniformed officers as two dozen members of
the Pipe and Drum Corps of the Emerald Society of the Chicago
Police Department played ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief ceremony, Gibson's wife and three children placed red
roses on the coffin. Accompanying them was the family of a second
officer, Jacob Chestnut, who was also killed in the gunfire and who
is to receive a similar ceremony here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two men will not be buried next to each other. Cemetery
officials said that Chestnut is to be interred elsewhere on the
612-acre grounds because 21 other funerals are scheduled for
Friday, some in the area where Gibson was laid to rest Thursday,
and they did not want the expected public outpouring for Chestnut
to conflict with those services.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Chestnut, who served in Vietnam, Gibson was not a
military veteran. But the secretary of the Army granted permission
for him to buried at Arlington, where more than 250,000 people are
interred beneath identical white stone markers. Arlington is the
second-largest national cemetery in the country after the Long
Island National Cemetery in Farmingdale, N.Y., where more than
300,000 people are buried.
</P>
<P>
   After Gibson's coffin was lowered onto a platform by nine
uniformed pallbearers, three police helicopters flew overhead and
seven riflemen fired three volleys of gunfire over the grave.
Cemetery officials said this was not a 21-gun salute, which is
reserved for heads of state. Rather, the volleys are an old war
tradition, in which each army would fire three shots to indicate
that they had removed their dead from the battlefield and were
ready to resume fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Many officers wore their dress uniforms, which are made of wool,
and in the sticky afternoon heat, at least a dozen collapsed from
heatstroke, medics said. A handful of people _ a former Capitol
Hill officer, a current officer on disability, the mother of an
officer and a bicycle messenger _ stayed after the service to watch
the coffin be lowered into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be here through the end,'' said the woman
whose son works on the Capitol force. ``When I'm with my son from
now on, I'll know this was painful, and I just came to feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   George Culberath, the bicycle messenger, said he delivered
packages to the Capitol and knew the officers. ``I just feel a
loss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Formal tributes were paid earlier at Gibson's home church, St.
Elizabeth Ann Seton Catholic Church in Lake Ridge, Va., about 35
miles from Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Hamilton said the best way to honor Gibson, who
served in the protective detail guarding Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
would be for Congress to pass laws that eliminate violence.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Dewolse, Gibson's best friend, said that Gibson was hoping
to be part of the protective detail assigned to guard the many
members of Congress who plan on accompanying Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, to Florida in October for his second trip into space.
</P>
<P>
   He said to his absent friend: ``Now, John, you'll have the best
seat in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the suspected gunman, Russell Weston Jr., was still
recuperating in a nearby hospital and remained under heavy police
guard. His lawyers said he should be well enough by Aug. 18 to
appear in court. Magistrate Deborah Robinson authorized four mental
health experts to examine Weston in the hospital. He has been
charged with murder in the killing of a federal law enforcement
officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
