<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BERRIES-LABOR-A     07-30 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BERRIES-LABOR-ART-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNION VOTE SOWS BITTERNESS IN STRAWBERRY FIELDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATSONVILLE, Calif. _ Tension and fear hover over the strawberry
fields of the Coastal Berry Company here like the morning fog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, the lush fields outside of this small
city 70 miles south of San Francisco have become a battle ground in
an increasingly nasty and nationally significant
two-and-a-half-year struggle by the United Farm Workers to unionize
the men and women who pick the sweet red berries, often for short
pay and long hours: their backs bent, their heads down, their hopes
low. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since July 1, there have been threats, arrests, beatings of UFW
supporters, a disputed union election that a rival group won, a
one-day strike to protest the election and a hearing at the state
Capitol on Tuesday on the entire bitter harvest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disturbed about what I heard,'' said state Sen.
Hilda Solis, D-Los Angeles, the co-chairwoman of the hearing.
``There's violence in the fields, intimidation. A union vote should
never have been taken in that kind of environment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the UFW said it would file legal papers with the
California Agricultural Labor Relations Board, seeking to have the
results of the union vote at Coastal Berry, the largest strawberry
grower in the country, thrown out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The UFW maintains that the election on July 23 was unfair and
was held in a climate of violence and fear; it refused to
participate in the vote. The union also contends that the group
that won the election, the Coastal Berry Farm Workers Committee, is
a ``sham union,'' a front for the company and the powerful Western
Grower's Association, a farming industry organization in Irvine,
Calif., which has long opposed the union's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are so high that all of agri-business has come
together to stop us,'' said Dolores Huerta, the co-founder of the
UFW. There are 20,000 strawberry pickers in California, where 80
percent of the nation's strawberries are grown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both the company nd the association deny they had anything to
do with the election or its results.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply,'' said Doug Kerr, general counsel for the
association, ``the UFW is lashing out at anyone they can over their
frustration at being unable to organize the Coastal Berry
employees.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The UFW tried to stop the election but the labor board allowed
the vote to go forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Coastal Berry Farm Workers Committee, a group that did not
exist a few weeks ago, won the right to represent the company's
more than 900 field workers with 54 percent of the vote, even
though the committee had no agenda, no list of demands on behalf of
the workers and no organizing strategy beyond defeating the UFW. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Coastal Berry President David Smith conceded that the
workers' committee had a limited purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have structure,'' Smith said of the new union.
``They don't have management. They don't want to collect dues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the leaders of the group, a 22-year-old truck driver,
Jose Fernandez, was arrested and charged with assaulting a police
officer who interceded in a confrontation between members of the
workers' committee and UFW supporters in the fields on July 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of tension for the last couple of years,''
the president of the UFW, Arturo Rodriguez, said. ``But we never
expected they would just openly rush a field and beat up workers
loyal to the union.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three workers were sent to the hospital, where they were treated
and released, but Smith said the violence was relatively minor:
rocks, fists and boxes of strawberries were thrown, in one case
hitting a frightened woman in the face. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the Agricultural Labor Relations Board tried to investigate
the incident before the union election, Coastal Berry refused to
cooperate, citing a fear of more violence, the labor board's
general counsel, Paul Richardson, said at Tuesday's joint hearing
of the state's Senate Committee on Industrial Relations and the
Assembly Committee on Labor and Employment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the board wanted to investigate the incident to
determine if the election should go forward, but without the
company's cooperation it decided to proceed with the voting, partly
to avoid any more trouble in the fields. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the ALRB,'' Richardson said, ``is to vote now,
litigate later.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That statement and several others from labor board officials
seemed to inflame state Assemblyman Richard Floyd, D-Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, the co-chairman of the hearing, said the board was
``absolutely condoning'' the violence when it refused to block the
election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither the growers' association, the Coastal Berry Company or
its new union appeared at the hearing, although each group was
invited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During an interview, Smith said Coastal Berry was now
cooperating with labor board investigators and that he did not care
what union if any represented his workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We would negotiate with the UFW,'' he said. ``They have done
some good things for their workers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the UFW was picking on the wrong company, because
Coastal Berry provides some of the highest wages and best benefits
in the $600 million a year strawberry industry, which is known for
its low wages and poor benefits. Smith said workers earn a base pay
of $6.50 an hour, which can increase to $10 or $11 in the peak
picking season, depending on how much a worker picks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The union said that during the peak season, the base pay goes
down and the amount of money the pickers earn per box of
strawberries goes up from about 35 cents per tray to 75 cents per
tray. An average worker picks about four to six trays an hour.
``It's back-breaking work,'' said Lupe Lara, a picker for 15 years,
who said he was dismissed last Monday after participating in a
one-day strike to protest the election. ``But I want my job back. I
have no choice. I have six children.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodriquez, the UFW president, and several workers, agreed that
conditions in the fields ``have improved dramatically.'' But they
credit that to the union's efforts to organize, not the policies of
Coastal Berry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the union campaign began, said Jesus Anaya, 46, a picker
for years, conditions were poor. ``Now the company is giving us
health insurance,'' he said, ``because of the union.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, after nearly three years of effort and considerable help
from the AFL-CIO, the UFW has not been able to gain a solid
foothold in the strawberry fields of Watsonville. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said that at first, the goal of his group was to keep
the UFW and any other unions out of the fields. It was only after
it was determined to be more effective for the group to represent
itself as a union that the workers' committee was formed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said the UFW has failed because ``we got tired of them
harassing us to join the union at our homes, after work, before
work, at the park, on the street.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for his new union, Fernandez said he is not sure what it will
ask for at the bargaining table, if the committee ever gets that
far. ``Maybe we'll try to get some bonuses,'' he said. ``We don't
promise nothing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for the hearts and minds of the strawberry pickers
is far from over. Ms. Solis said she planned to hold another
hearing about the election and intended to review the labor board's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in 14 years we're actually having an
oversight hearing of the ALRB,'' the senator said. ``It won't be
the last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
