<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECHOLS-COX     07-30 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECHOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Post office honors 50-year employee, former pitcher
 &HT;    By Delbert Ellerton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- One-hundred-fifty years of service.
</P>
<P>
   That's what 83-year-old Melvin Echols Sr. wants for his family.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Echols, a still-working 50-year U.S. Postal Service
employee and a former Negro Leagues pitcher who once struck out 22
players in a baseball game, inched closer to that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Echols' service was honored by management at an employee
appreciation celebration held at the main Atlanta Post Office on
Crown Road.
</P>
<P>
   Echols, who is a custodian and also has worked as a postal
service guard, has two sons who are letter carriers.
</P>
<P>
   As a family, the Echolses have a combined 109 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going when I get ready to go,'' Echols said when asked if
he had any plans for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark-blue work uniform topped with an Atlanta Black
Crackers baseball cap, Echols stood before a crowd of co-workers,
microphone in hand, thanking God and introducing his older son,
Melvin Jr., 51. Echols' younger son, Michael, 49, could not make
the celebration. Melvin Jr. has worked for the postal service for
31 years, and Michael has been on the job for 29 years. During his
playing days with the Atlanta Black Crackers, the Atlanta White Sox
and other Negro League teams, Echols was known as Sunny Jim Echols.
An Atlanta Daily World sportswriter nicknamed him ``Sunny'' while
writing an article, and his grandmother had nicknamed him Jim years
before.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he found success as a baseball player, Echols never
encouraged his sons to be athletes. Instead he pushed them toward
music and careers with the postal service.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his dream, to get us here, to come to the post office
and work,'' said Melvin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
