<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA MAY MIRE MCGWIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ITAL)``I don't want to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ St. Louis' Mark McGwire on Tuesday night after he hit his 45th
home run but suffered through the Cardinals' 13-10 loss.(END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   Is Mark McGwire's high-wire act finally getting to him? Is the
media pressure going to make him topple? Who will he blame if he
lands in the safety net a few knocks short of Roger Maris'
single-season home run record?
</P>
<P>
   In order, the answers are sort of, no and probably himself.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's surliness toward the media in recent weeks appears to
have been magnified as he gets closer to saving the game of
baseball ... rather, hitting another bushel of tape-measure blasts
in the final 50-odd games he'll play in to break the Maris
standard.
</P>
<P>
   Not as much has been written or said about similar
media-perceived pressure put on Seattle's Ken Griffey or Chicago's
Sammy Sosa on the same chase _ maybe because they've trailed
McGwire from the beginning, maybe because the intensity hasn't been
as severe.
</P>
<P>
   That the unending focus is on McGwire, the former USC star with
the bulging biceps and devilish goatee, is something he'll have to
somehow deal with for the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   From Sports Illustrated cover stories (current issue, check out
the media swarm on page 43) to the daily graphics on the sports
pages tracking his every swing, it's only going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of June, the Cardinals' media-relations staff has
invoked the ``McGwire Rules'' as far as interviews go. During
Cardinals road trips, where the new flock of writers and TV crews
are sent out to report on every move by this out-of-town sensation,
the only time the media can talk to him about his chase is in a
30-minute session 3{ hours before the first game of each series.
The rules are a bit more lax during home series. And after every
game, he can decide whether he'll make himself available to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   If he hits a home run, he'll usually talk. But then again,
there's not much to say in the case of earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think he's having fun and wants to break the record
more than anyone knows _ yet _ but he's been so agitated with the
way the team has underachieved that it's taken a lot of the luster
off it,'' said Joe Buck, the Cardinals' TV play-by-play man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more frustrated by the team than the media attention.
Look at Tuesday: I'll guarantee you 40,000 people left Busch
Stadium satisfied even though the team blows the game on a
ninth-inning grand slam given up by a rookie closer. They still saw
McGwire's 45th homer. It's very strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if he wouldn't trade some of this personal glory
in just for the team to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's trade to the Cardinals in the middle of last season
was precipitated by him wanting to get out of Oakland because the
Athletics, where he played on a World Championship club in 1988,
are in the process of rebuilding. The Cards had designs on the NL
Central title entering the season but aren't even in the wild-card
race in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Personal glory was something that drove a player like Reggie
Jackson during his chase of Maris' record in 1969, when he had 37
homers at the All-Star break and hit only 10 the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really regret the fact that the media attention bothered me
so much in 1969 that I couldn't get that record,'' Jackson said
recently. ``I hope the same thing doesn't happen to these players
this year because, trust me, you don't want to be in a position to
say 30 years later that it was the media that bothered you. The
media isn't as important as hitting 62 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the Washington Post, McGwire was quoted as saying:
``I'm getting tired of seeing my mug on TV and in the paper.
Sometimes you just don't want to know. The newspaper... I just pick
it up and throw in the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   You do what you've got to do to keep your sanity. That's
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   You also do what you have to do to keep yourself from feeling
you're letting the entire sport down if you don't achieve this
milestone. McGwire might not have figured out how to deal with that
yet, although you won't find many (unlike when Maris competed with
teammate Mickey Mantle for Babe Ruth's record) who are rooting
against him. Even the media, whose members aren't supposed to be
openly rooting for anything, are in this case privately enjoying it
as much as the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say he's going to crack, but I don't see the media
attention as a factor,'' said Buck, who has a chance to make the
record-breaking call on TV at the same time his father, Hall of
Famer Jack Buck, is doing it on the Cardinals' radio broadcast.
``He's a guy who can separate the circus from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything that's going to distract him, it'll be his
want to not disappoint the fans. He's into this chase more than he
lets on. When he breaks it, he won't be able to contain himself.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the question is: Will the media be able to contain
itself?
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST PICTURE SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Get a good mental image of Steve Mason and John Ireland, because
as of today, their 6 a.m.-to-9 a.m. ``Big Show'' has ceased
simulcasting between KXTA-AM (1150) on radio and Fox Sports West 2
on TV as it has been for the last 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   The call was made by those who run the radio side _ and,
incidentally, pay the guys' salaries. Fox, which sold a sponsorship
package for the TV show but had no other financial stake, isn't
thrilled to have to replace it with fitness shows and more Fox
Sports News. But the Jacor execs didn't feel as if the quality of
the show should be compromised just for the cross-promotion on TV.
</P>
<P>
   So  &UR; !ital! &LR; sayonara to waking up to that vision of Shoshona,
boys.
</P>
<P>
   LISTEN UP
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rome's ``Last Word'' on Fox Sports Net continues to be taped
at the Fox studios in Century City, and an audience will watch it
live from the All Star Cafe in New York. The New Yorkers will be
able to ask questions of Rome and the guests. It all starts
Monday....
</P>
<P>
   Irv Kaze's show tonight _ on KIEV-AM (870), which recently
changed ownership _ focuses on probably the two best role models
for women involved in athletics today: Donna DeVarona, the former
Olympic swimmer and ABC broadcaster who chairs the FIFA women's
world soccer championships that will be in the U.S. next year, and
Anita DeFrantz, the head of the Amateur Athletic Foundation of Los
Angeles recently elected vice president of the IOC....
</P>
<P>
   The 3.7 rating NBC received for Sunday's final round of the U.S.
Senior Open at Riviera was the only sports program that did better
than a 3.0 for the weekend. It is a 32 percent jump over the 2.8
the tournament received on the final day last year.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Al Michaels' and Bob Costas' appearances
``as themself'' in TV's ``Arli$$'' and the cinema's
``BASEketball,'' which comes out today. In the former, the intended
comedy is so putrid that the sports-broadcasting icons look like
nothing more than cheap props. In the latter, the fact Costas can
scream _ and make a risque reference to how excited he is _ and
Michaels can gaze at some voluptuous cheerleaders and remember when
they were schoolgirls, is not just closer to the pure definition of
parody. It's just funnier, which is something Robert Wuhl's guys
might learn from David Zucker's.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   How much slack do we give Fox Sports Net's Lauren Sanchez before
she ends up hanging herself? There's an apparent in-studio contest
between her and Brad Goode!arrow! for most blunders per show by a
news reader (using the term literally) without any idea of what
they just said. If credibility is what FSN wants in its competition
with ESPN's cast of SWM (Single White Male) clones, start by hiring
more qualified folks who not only look pretty (which mostly applies
in Goode's case) but also are a little clued in on what they're
feeding the viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
