<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, TINSELTOWN BRINGS DOWN THE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ The big Tudor house on the corner wasn't
exactly the old Granville place in ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' and
the man who lived there for nearly 50 years until he died last
summer was named James Stewart, not George Bailey. But 918 N.
Roxbury Drive, with its towering trees, wide lawn and walled
English garden, was a landmark on a leafy street where the
neighbors included Lucille Ball, Jack Benny and Ira Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
   Now the house, which was sold in the spring for $5.6 million, is
gone, demolished over the last three weeks by its new owner to make
way for an Italian-style villa twice as big, and all that remains
is a hole in the ground. It is just one of the latest casualties in
that affluent Tinseltown tradition, the ``teardown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm haunted by the knowledge that this house will be torn down
the minute I die,'' said the Stewarts' next door neighbor, Albert
Moxie, an 86-year-old retired history professor from the University
of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The latest demolition was no surprise to Moxie, who has lived on
Roxbury Drive since 1929. The house on the other side of his was
torn down after its owner, Pandro Berman, who produced the Fred
Astaire-Ginger Rogers musicals at RKO, died two years ago, and a
new house is just being finished there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In good economic times, people are willing to do teardowns
because they say, `I want exactly what I want, and I don't want
anything less,''' said Fred Sands, a leading luxury real estate
broker here. ``During a recession, people will do some remodeling.
But for many people now, it's simply the price of admission: you
buy it, and you tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sands should know. Last year he sold O.J. Simpson's old house in
Brentwood for nearly $4 million, after the bank that foreclosed on
it had spent $200,000 on elaborate renovations to make it more
attractive. This week the new owner, an investment banker named
Kenneth Abdalla, sent in bulldozers to reduce it to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is it was somewhat dated, and it was still subpar
for a $4 million house,'' Sands said. ``The second-story master
suite wasn't what it should be for today's environment. The buyer
brought in the architect and talked about gutting the second floor
but then decided he might as well take the whole thing down.''
</P>
<P>
   In most markets, spending $4 million or $5 million on a dwelling
only to demolish it would be unheard of. But in affluent areas like
Beverly Hills or Silicon Valley, where land is precious and parcels
like the Stewart family's 1.4-acre plot almost never come on the
market, the lure is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trend in major metropolitan markets where the land is
in acute short supply and the prices are high,'' said Gopal
Ahluwalia, director of research for the National Association of
Homebuilders in Washington. ``It was much more common five or 10
years back, and then land prices diminished somewhat, and now
they're on the upswing again. It's the culture of this country.
Here people move pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of Simpson's former neighbors were distraught at the demise
of his house at 360 N. Rockingham Ave. It had been a magnet for
curious tourists since he was arrested there four years ago and
charged with the murder of his former wife Nicole Brown Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   But on Stewart's old stretch of Roxbury Drive, neighbors like
Rosemary Clooney, who since 1953 has lived just up the street in
the house where the Gershwin brothers wrote ``Our Love Is Here to
Stay,'' mourned the end of an era. Ms. Clooney and her husband,
Dante DiPaolo, returned from an out-of-town trip a couple of weeks
ago to find the Stewart house flattened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only we'd known,'' she said. ``We'd have taken a brick or
something.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Greg Field, the lawyer for the Stewart estate, said, ``I think
it's fair to say the family's preference would have been to leave
the house standing and perhaps renovate it in some fashion, but
they fully understood that the buyer had the absolute right to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The property's new owner, Steven Wallace, who founded Pacific
Brokerage Services, an online discount brokerage that he sold to
Mellon Bank last summer, was unsentimental about his acquisition,
which was built in 1928 by director King Vidor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house was just a dump,'' Wallace said in a telephone
interview. ``How he could have lived there, I don't know. There
were cracks everywhere. The gardens were magnificent, but when I
looked at it, I said: `Why buy it? It's a total teardown.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the large corner lot that seduced Wallace,
who already lives on the street, just up the block from Ms.
Clooney, but wanted a bigger place. He plans a 12,800-square-foot
house with a three-car garage to replace the old 6,300-square-foot
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be kind of an Italian villa,'' said Wallace, who has
hired the Stewarts' longtime maid as his own. ``It'll look old, but
be new.''
</P>
<P>
   The twist is that Wallace can build so big a house only because
more than 30 years ago Stewart himself doubled the size of his
property by buying the house next door and tearing it down to build
his beloved garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all relative,'' Wallace said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
