<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING OLD, SOMETHING NEW IN PRIME MINISTER'S CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Keizo Obuchi took office on Thursday as prime minister
and named a cabinet which, while it largely reflects his loyalty to
factions of the governing Liberal Democratic Party that insured his
election, also made a nod to younger members pushing for change.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi became prime minister because his party colleagues defied
the wishes of their constituents, who overwhelmingly preferred his
rivals and who have already voiced their displeasure with the
ruling party by voting it out of power in the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will he have to satisfy voters at home, he will have to
prove to a world clamoring for action to right the Japanese economy
that he can abandon the cautious consensus-building that brought
him to power and make bold, even daring moves.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was not the choice of the upper house, which chose Naoto
Kan, head of the largest opposition party, the Democrats, as prime
minister. But in such a split the candidate chosen by the more
powerful lower house gets the job. The division will mean, however,
that Obuchi will be working overtime to curry the favor of Japan's
splintered opposition parties if he wants to push through
controversial legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet will have to address major issues including rising
unemployment, a banking crisis and global fears of a surge in
Japanese exports helped by a weak yen.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi turned responsibility for the powerful Ministry of Posts
and Telecommunications, which controls a big chunk of Japan's vast
pool of private savings, over to a woman, Seiko Noda, and appointed
a highly regarded academic, Akito Arima, as education minister.
</P>
<P>
   And he entrusted Japan's sick economy and fragile financial
system to Kiichi Miyazawa, a former prime minister and party
veteran who has a long record in international economic
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   While Obuchi's cabinet reflected the factional power within the
governing party, commentators suggested that in some cases he had
made his own selections from among faction members rather than
allowing the faction leaders to choose.
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets withheld judgment of the new cabinet,
which was not officially announced until after many Asian markets
closed, although the new cabinet members' names were circulating on
Thursday morning. The yen held steady against the dollar in Tokyo
but fell in New York on Thursday after Miyazawa indicated he might
not move to prop up the currency or the stock market as past
governments have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting it very simply, whether it is the yen or stocks, we
should rely on the markets to move on their own,'' he said. The
Nikkei basically shrugged its shoulders, rising 43.51 points to
16,201.60.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa, 78, has been involved in crafting policies to deal
with Japan's banking crisis, and his global reputation for
financial savvy goes some way toward dispelling doubts in world
capitals about Obuchi's ability and commitment to aggressively
address that problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have serious worries about the current economic
situation,'' Miyazawa said during a news conference with other
appointees. ``I think tackling it speedily is the most important
thing we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For foreign minister, the position Obuchi held before becoming
prime minister, he selected Masahiko Komura, who served as his
right hand in the Foreign Ministry since 1996. Komura, 56, is
considered an expert on Japan's relations with Russia, which Obuchi
has emphasized as a focus of his administration. He, like Ms. Noda,
is a member of the Komoto faction, the smallest segment of the
Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In giving two prime Cabinet seats to such a politically
insignificant faction, Obuchi could have been making an attempt to
avoid reflecting internal party politics in the national
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Noda's appointment, however, could also be construed as an
olive branch to Seiroku Kajiyama, one of the two men who challenged
Obuchi for the party president's job, as well as to younger members
of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Noda, whose grandfather was a ranking Liberal Democratic
politician, supported Kajiyama. She has in the past openly worried
about the Liberal Democrats' ability to win the affections of
voters.
</P>
<P>
   One of five women currently sitting in the lower house and the
youngest Cabinet minister in postwar history, Ms. Noda, 37,
emphasized that in her position she can be instrumental in
developing new industries and jobs for Japan in telecommunications
and information services.
</P>
<P>
   Arima, the new education minister, is a nuclear physicist who
was president of Tokyo University from 1989 to 1993. He is a
political novice, having won his first term in the upper house
during the recent election.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the job at a time when Japan is agonizing over its
educational system, which has been rocked by a series of knifings
in schools and by concerns that its rigidity stunts creative
thinking that the country needs in a competitive global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan's future in the international community depends on how
well we can raise powerful and vivid young people,'' he said on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
