</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LEFTHANDED-DNA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY LINKS RADIATION TO MOLECULES THAT LED TO LIFE ON EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The left-handed molecules that led to the beginning of life on
earth may have been singled out for their eventual role in biology
by a type of radiation that astronomers have discovered in a
star-forming cloud some 1,500 light years away.
</P>
<P>
   A team of astronomers in Australia reported in the issue of
Science magazine published Friday that they detected strongly
polarized radiation from a celestial cloud of hot dust and infant
stars in the constellation Orion. Its discoverers believe that
similar radiation could account for the uniform twist of key
molecules in living creatures and help explain how life arose.
</P>
<P>
   The form of infrared radiation they found is said to be
circularly polarized _ that is, the crests and troughs of its waves
follow corkscrew paths as they travel through space.
</P>
<P>
   Using a large, specially equipped telescope on Siding Spring
Mountain in Australia, the scientists detected the corkscrew rays
streaming from a bright nebula known as M42 in the constellation
Orion. This vast, luminous cloud is known to be a stellar nursery,
where thousands of new stars are condensing from the surrounding
gas and dust, probably along with new planetary systems that might
one day support life.
</P>
<P>
   In their report, Dr. Jeremy Bailey of the Anglo-Australian
Observatory and his collaborators from Britain, France and Japan
say that their discovery supports the view that such radiation can
help concentrate the molecules vital to life.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said in a interview this week that the discovery came as
a complete surprise. He said that members of his group had intended
merely to investigate the composition and distribution of dust in
the Orion nebula and had not expected to see the high levels of
circular polarization they detected.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery may shed light on the chirality _ or handedness _
of terrestrial biology.
</P>
<P>
   In 1848, Louis Pasteur discovered that some carbon-based
molecules come in two mirror-image forms, matched with each other
just as pairs of gloves are matched. One of the molecular types in
such chiral, or handed, partnerships rotates beams of light to the
right, and the other rotates light to the left.
</P>
<P>
   After Pasteur's discovery, other scientists found that the
building blocks of life themselves _ amino acids and sugars _ are
also chiral.
</P>
<P>
   When chemists synthesize amino acids in the laboratory, the
result is a mixture of roughly equal amounts of the left-handed and
right-handed forms. Scientist call such mixtures ``racemic.'' But
living creatures, including humans, are assembled exclusively from
left-handed amino acids and right-handed sugars.
</P>
<P>
   Why and how this should be so are among the central mysteries of
the origin of life, and such questions have prompted much
scientific investigation and debate.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: single-handedness, or homochirality, is an
essential property of the amino acids and sugars incorporated into
living organisms. This is because mixtures of left-handed and
right-handed types would create molecular mismatches. Animals and
plants cannot build coherent peptides and proteins from mixed pairs
of amino acids, or mixed pairs of such sugars as ribose and
deoxyribose _ the corkscrew backbones of genetic RNA and DNA. It
would be like trying to put a left glove on a right hand.
</P>
<P>
   But how the gift of homochirality was bestowed on earth as a
mold for life is an unsolved mystery; single-handedness had either
to arise on the earth itself, or to arrive from outer space, but
which? Scientists also wonder why biological amino acids happen to
be left handed rather than right handed, which would be just as
suitable for life; was the choice decided by random chance, or was
there some physical influence favoring left-handedness?
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report from Australia lends weight to a growing body of
evidence that homochirality is extraterrestrial in origin.
</P>
<P>
   One theory consistent with this idea is based on the fact that
amino acids tend to decompose when they absorb ultraviolet
radiation. Laboratory experiments have demonstrated that if this
radiation happens to be circularly polarized, it preferentially
decomposes either the left-handed or the right-handed amino acid
type, depending on the direction of the beam's corkscrew rotation.
</P>
<P>
   If the ultraviolet preferentially decomposes right-handed amino
acids floating through interstellar space, this would leave an
excess of left-handed ones. Such an imbalance, Bailey and others
say, could have started amino acids out on the homochiral road to
life. Left-handed amino acids and other chiral molecules, selected
by the action of polarized radiation, could have been swept up and
carried to earth on comets, meteoritic dust or asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey acknowledged in the interview that although his group
found circularly polarized infrared in the Orion nebula, this did
not prove that circularly-polarized ultraviolet was also present.
But the same process that produced the infrared polarization,
possibly the scattering of light by magnetically aligned dust
particles, is likely to have produced circularly polarized
ultraviolet as well, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultraviolet radiation from distant sources does not penetrate
interstellar dust clouds or even the earth's atmosphere to an
appreciable extent, and it therefore cannot be detected with
earth-based instruments. But Bailey said he hoped that ultraviolet
detectors capable of measuring polarization would someday be sent
into orbit above the atmosphere. An orbiting instrument of this
kind could perhaps find a window through the dust shrouding much of
the Orion nebula and measure ultraviolet polarization directly.
</P>
<P>
   Some investigators concluded that the meteorite's amino acids
could be explained in terms of terrestrial contamination by
bacteria and other biological sources. Others argued that the amino
acids were extraterrestrial in origin.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Dr. John Cronin and Dr. Sandra Pizzarello of
Arizona State University completed tests that all but settled the
debate. They found a pronounced excess of left-handed amino acids
in the meteorite _ not only amino acids found in life, but amino
acids unknown in living organisms. The latter are therefore likely
to be extraterrestrial in origin.
</P>
<P>
   The latest observations from Australia may demonstrate the
mechanism that imprinted a preponderance of left-handed amino acids
in the Murchison meteorite _ and perhaps on those in earth's
creatures as well.
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists remain skeptical of all theories of
extraterrestrial sources of the attributes of life. Among them is
Dr. Stanley Miller of the University of California in San Diego,
whose experiments beginning in the 1950s showed that amino acids
could be created from simple mixtures of terrestrial gases exposed
to heat or artificial lightning bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has contended over the years that life probably
originated on the earth itself, without help from the depths of
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report by Jeremy Bailey and his colleagues shows that
their work was very carefully done,'' Miller said in an interview,
``but I'm very skeptical of the inferences they draw. For the
moment, let's concede that circularly polarized ultraviolet can
preferentially decompose either left-handed or right-handed amino
acids.
</P>
<P>
   ``This radiation from a star gets polarized by scattering it
from the dust in the vicinity of the star. The direction of twist
of the polarized ultraviolet will depend on where the dust grains
lie with respect to the star. Dust grains north of the star might
scatter radiation with a left-handed twist, while grains south of
it would give the radiation the opposite twist. The effects would
cancel out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey said that the excess of left-handed amino acids need
not be large. It might start out as small and become amplified by
some physical process. Either way, he said, ``the ultimate source
is likely to be extraterrestrial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
