<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS     07-30 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   East meets West Coast in brotherhood of basketball
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ Theirs is a relationship that has spanned cultures
and eras, jumped borders and survived political ideologies,
bouncing along like the ball in the game that is in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Small world, this ever-shrinking basketball planet from which
Donn Nelson and Sarunas Marciulionis have come from opposite sides
to be more than blood brothers. They are friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend asked me to do him a favor, and I obliged,'' said
Nelson, giving the simplest response to a question about how an
American-born hoop junkie of Swedish and German descent came to sit
on the bench as an assistant coach for the Lithuanian national
team, which defeated the United States 84-82 on Thursday at the
World Championship of Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The story began a decade ago, when Nelson, the son of Dallas
Mavericks coach and general manager Don, traveled through Europe
and became familiar with a hard-nosed guard who played for the
former Soviet Union. That guard, Marciulionis, became one of the
first highly recruited foreign-born players by the NBA and wound up
at Golden State, playing for Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   In Donn Nelson and Marciulionis, East met West Coast, and the
pair who spoke the language of the game forged a bond that would
grow deep enough so that when the Soviet Union crumbled in 1991,
one friend could ask another to devote himself to a cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 50 years, Lithuania has always had a passion _
basketball _ that made it different from the rest of Europe,''
Nelson said. ``It wasn't soccer. It was always basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was the tiny republic that produced most of the greatest
players on the Soviet Big Red Machine that won the gold medal at
the 1988 Olympics. Marciulionis played with Arvydas Sabonis and a
handful of others, and even though it was the Soviet national
anthem they heard as they received their medals, those proud
players _ and the rest of the Soviet Union _ were aware who made up
the heart of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``During 40 years of being held captive by this dark political
force, basketball was always the way for the Lithuanians to thumb
their noses at the Soviets,'' Nelson said. ``They'd take their team
into Moscow and whip the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that sense of national pride for which Marciulionis
appealed to his American buddy Nelson when he wanted to prepare
Lithuania for its first Olympic appearance in 1992. That was the
year the first U.S. Dream Team dominated the headlines and the
games. But who expected different from a team that included Michael
Jordan, Magic Johnson, Larry Bird and Charles Barkley?
</P>
<P>
   But Lithuania, led by the feisty veteran guard Marciulionis and
the young American assistant coach, that achieved the real Olympic
dream, winning the bronze medal, beating none other than Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The jubilant Lithuanians jumped up and down on the victory stand
wearing their tie-dyed warm-up shirts provided by the Grateful
Dead. While the U.S. team bickered over corporate logos in
Barcelona, Marciulionis and his countrymen wore the Deadheads' rock
'n' roll skeleton and partied.
</P>
<P>
   They hugged in the locker room. They doused the then-president
of their country, Vytautas Landsbergis, with champagne and cried
when they sang the Lithuanian national anthem, Nelson included.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the single proudest moment of my life,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Proud for what he had contributed. Prouder for a friend whose
country finally was free.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, Lithuania has added an Olympic bronze and a
silver at the World Championship. Marciulionis has retired as a
player and runs the Lithuanian pro league.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could call him the godfather of basketball in his
country,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   But the godfather has not had to make Nelson an offer he can't
refuse to keep helping. Nelson says he's committed to his adopted
country for the long haul, even in two years when he is under
contract to succeed his father as Mavs coach.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, like Marciulionis, is excited about the play of the
young Lithuanian team (2-0) but admits disappointment over the
absence of the NBA stars for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand all sides of the argument,'' he said. ``But I
believe that when your country asks you to serve, whether it's war,
sports or anything, you do it. Through these people, through
Sarunas, I have learned how deep patriotism can run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing their champagne, their hugs, their tears.
</P>
<P>
   For Nelson and Marciulionis, what a long, strange trip
friendship has been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
