<HEADLINE>
FOR 101 RIDERS, THE TOUR DE FRANCE WILL CARRY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SAMUEL ABT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEUCHATEL, Switzerland _ The Tour de France continued without
incident Thursday as the 101 remaining riders yielded to the
enormous implications of aborting the bicycle race for the first
time since it began in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   The riders staged two sit-down protests on Wednesday and
threatened not to start if police persisted in what the riders
regarded as brutal methods of questioning them in a widening drug
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   French police did check four teams at their hotels after
Wednesday's finish and took a leading rider, a coach and a team
doctor into custody, but the racers decided that their rights had
not been violated and set off Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Many teams with riders high in the overall standing and with a
chance at prestige and a share of the $2.2 million prize list are
happy to keep racing until the end in Paris on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams, like the U.S. Postal Service, which is adamant
against doping, remained ``for the glory of the sport and because
this is the focus of our entire season,'' as Dan Osipow, the team's
director of operations, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Another major factor in the continuation was that such firebrand
teams as ONCE, led by Laurent Jalabert, the world's top-ranked
rider and one of the leading protesters, pulled out Wednesday and
did not participate in the discussion the riders had Thursday as
they rolled together at the start.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, too, how many favors were called in by the organizers
and how many deals were struck by them with the coaches of the 15
teams still in the race. Twenty-one teams and 198 riders began the
three-week Tour in Dublin on July 11.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal over illegal performance-enhancing drugs originally
embroiled the Festina team from France, which was expelled from the
Tour, but has since spread to TVM from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion has also fallen on Big Mat-Auber from France and the
four teams whose hotels were searched Wednesday night: ONCE from
Spain, Casino from France, La Francaise des Jeux from France and
Polti from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The rider taken into custody, Rodolfo Massi, an Italian with
Casino and the leader in the climbing competition, was still being
held, as was Nicolas Terrados, the doctor for the ONCE team. The
coach of Francaise des Jeux, Marc Madiot, was released too late to
make the start.
</P>
<P>
   Four teams withdrew Wednesday and one pulled out Thursday before
the start of the 18th of 21 daily stages, 136 miles from Aix les
Bains, France, to Neuchatel, Switzerland, as cowbells rang out to
celebrate the racers' brief incursion.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds in France were more reserved, with spectators expressing
disappointment over the annulled stage Wednesday but not anger
toward the protesting riders. In many conversations with fans, they
voiced indifference to the doping scandal and cited the special
role that the Tour has in French life and culture.
</P>
<P>
   In sunny and hot weather Thursday, the winner of the mass sprint
was Tom Steels, a Belgian with Mapei. Erik Zabel, a German with
Telekom, was second and Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with Gan, was
third. They, and 42 other members of the pack, finished in 4 hours
53 minutes 27 seconds, a speed above 27 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Pantani, an Italian with Mercatone Uno, continued to wear
the leader's yellow jersey by 5:42 over Bobby Julich, an American
with Cofidis, and by 5:56 over Jan Ullrich, a German with Telekom
and the defending Tour champion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The previous fourth-place rider, Fernando Escartin, a Spaniard
with Kelme, was stricken from the rolls when his team joined the
three others from Spain and withdrew Thursday. Massi, the rider in
custody, had been in seventh place over all.
</P>
<P>
   Over their breakfasts of pasta mixed with eggs and wheat germ,
Julich and another American with Cofidis, Kevin Livingston, talked
about their feelings at the conduct of the race, confessing anger,
sorrow and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty by association is not the correct way of doing
things,'' Julich said. ``Just because a friend of yours steals a
car doesn't mean that you're a car thief. The problem here is being
publicly ridiculed and physically violated by the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Julich and Livingston both worried about the reaction in the
United States. American riders are known for their aversion to
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a sport where we're constantly pushing ourselves
to the limit and vitamins and daily recuperation are a must,''
Julich said. ``That's why our doctors are here. There's no reason
other than that. It's a tough sport that we do, 200 kilometers a
day, day after day, and recovery is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said: ``Not too many people understand what's going
on, including us. But if it goes on like this, there won't be any
sport. It can't go on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Julich agreed. ``We're killing the sport in the most beautiful
race in the world,'' he said. ``Riders like myself have peaked
their season around this three-week period. For all this to happen
now takes away from all the hard work and sacrifices we've made.''
</P>
<P>
   As the second-place rider, Julich also worried that if he stood
on the one-two-three final victory podium in Paris, his triumph
would be devalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've worked for my whole career and it takes a
little away when, 10 years down the line, you may see an asterisk
by the result. I hope that isn't the case. I hope I've gained
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, it's only a bike race. I was looking through the
newspaper and on the page after all the stuff about the Tour de
France, there's a picture of a starving kid in Sudan.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
