<HEADLINE>
PAUL ALLEN EXPANDS CABLE HOLDINGS BY AGREEING TO BUY CHARTER
COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Mo., Ill.)   (af)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The billionaire investor Paul Allen on Thursday expanded his
holdings in the cable business by agreeing to buy more than 90
percent of Charter Communications, the nation's 10th largest cable
operator, for $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's company, Vulcan Ventures, already owns Marcus Cable.
Combining the two, each with about 1.2 million subscribers, would
make Allen the owner of nation's seventh-largest cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   William Savoy, the president of Vulcan, said Thursday it was
paying roughly 14 times Charter's projected cash flow. That is a
relatively high multiple in an industry in which buyers had been
paying about 12 times cash flow. Allen paid $2.8 billion for Marcus
Cable last April _ about 12.4 times cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of AT&AMP;T's deal to purchase of
Tele-Communications Inc., validating the importance of cable as a
means of delivering telephone and interactive data services to
homes, prices for cable systems have been escalating, said Sharon
Armbrust, senior analyst at Paul Kagan Associates, a media
consulting firm. ``There seems to be a certain urgency as people
pair up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who amassed his wealth as co-founder of the Microsoft
Corp., already has other major media investments including 24
percent of Dreamworks, the film, television and record company and
a holding in USA Networks, the home shopping and television
production company. He also owns the Seattle Seahawks football team
and the Portland Trailblazers basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Thursday, Savoy said he was very
bullish on the revenue that cable operators can potentially
generate from alliances with other service providers in the near
future _ in banking and shopping, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Armbrust said, ``The tickler is Paul Allen's expectation of
transactional revenue if you are looking for a handle in
understanding why he is paying these multiples.''
</P>
<P>
   Savoy continued: ``Our investment strategy has been a
recognition that low-cost computing power is a very dramatic
paradigm shift from the communications chances people have had
historically. Our investment has been communications-centric, in
spite of the fact that there are some sports franchises, the bulk
of the portfolio is companies that participate in this convergence
of broadband and computer.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company's stake in Dreamworks was somewhat separate,
but that Allen's stake in USA Networks was related since it is in
electronic communications and offers the opportunity for
transactions on line.
</P>
<P>
   Savoy made it clear that Allen's company was still interested in
acquiring more cable operations. It is already rumored to be
interested in Century Communications, another cable operator.
</P>
<P>
   Savoy also said he was convinced there would be ``a new class of
service that consumers are willing to pay for it.'' He added, ``I
can justify these values for cable because scale is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter is a privately owned cable operator founded by Barry L.
Babcock, Jerald L. Kent and Howard L. Wood, along with the
investors Ed Gaylord of Gaylord Entertainment Co., Charterhouse
Group International and Kelso &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Although exact terms of the deal were not disclosed, Gaylord
said Thursday that it expected to receive $370 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kent said Charter had considered going public in order to let
its financial investors cash in on their investment, but chose
instead to sell.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles market, Charter and Marcus combined reach
400,000 subscribers. If Allen bought Century, that would add
800,000 subscribers in that market.
</P>
<P>
   Charter and Marcus also have systems in Dallas, and Charter has
systems in Missouri and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus will serve as chairman of the combined cable company and
Kent will become president.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's discussions with Charter were reported Wednesday by
Broadcasting and Cable magazine. News of his purchase Thursday
strengthened the shares of publicly traded cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision Systems Inc. rose $3.375, to $82.75; Comcast Corp.
increased $1.9375, to $46.8125; Cox Communications Inc. gained
$2.3125, to $49.375, and Adelphia Communications Corp. soared
$6.125, to $39.625.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
