<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-430&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      07-30 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET GAINS REVERSE SUMMER SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rose sharply Thursday, ending a two-day
losing streak and pushing the Dow Jones industrial average back
above 9,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gains came with heavy trading volume and reversed a volatile
summer slump that in the last weeks had seen most of the major
indexes fall more than 4 percent from all-time highs set earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Dow rose 111.99 points, or 1.26 percent, to
9,026.95, leaving the blue-chip barometer about 300 points below
its all-time high of 9,337.97, which was set on July 17. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also gained sharply, climbing
17.74 points, or 1.58 percent, to 1,142.95.
</P>
<P>
   Although investors continue to be jittery about signs that
profit growth is slowing, Wall Street analysts said prices had been
beaten down too sharply in the last few weeks and that share prices
were ripe for a recovery Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a rubber-band situation,'' said Larry Wachtel, a
market strategist at Prudential Securities. ``We took the Dow down
about 500 points. But this is the biggest and best bull market in
history. It doesn't just go away on a random day in July.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel and other analysts said that although earnings had been
less than spectacular, there had been some bright spots. On
Thursday, for example, Clorox, one of the largest consumer products
companies, said its fiscal fourth-quarter profit soared 32 percent,
well above analysts' expectations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, profit growth in the second quarter has been anemic. With
reports in from about 80 percent of the companies that make up the
S&AMP; P 500, operating profits have risen just 1.7 percent from the
period a year earlier. In the first quarter, profit growth was
equally meager, at 1.3 percent, according to IBES International,
which tracks corporate earnings.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The result has been the weakest profit growth in the first half
since 1991. Expectations for the third quarter are also being
trimmed, and that has many investors worried.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot, however, is a healthy economy with low interest
rates and strong retail sales, which are helping offset the sharp
economic downturn in Asia. Many investors are also betting that
profit growth will recover later this year or next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Joseph Cohen, the widely followed market strategist at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., said in her weekly report this week that the
most serious concerns revolve around Asia, but that she expected
the economies in that region to stabilize and to see U.S. corporate
profits re-accelerate in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen views the current sluggishness in the U.S. stock
market as part of a ``choppy trading range'' that has persisted
since April. As for second-quarter earnings, she said, ``So far, so
good,'' noting that most companies have reported results that
exceed consensus estimates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, some of the biggest gainers were technology stocks,
which have been clobbered in recent days, following sharp gains in
the early part of the summer. The Nasdaq composite index, which is
heavy with high-tech stocks, soared 38.09 points, gaining more than
2 percent Thursday, to 1,919.58. Microsoft, Intel, Dell Computer
and Cisco Systems all rose sharply. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Taylor, the chief investment strategist at United
States Trust Co., said investors had soured on many stocks in
recent weeks, and that it was simply time for them to start buying
again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Things had become so negative,'' he said. ``And when there's a
consensus on the negative side, people start moving to buy again.
That's how the market works technically.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
