director for the Healthworks health club in Boston's Back Bay.
``Aerobics has really changed,'' says Finan, who is also the
national competitive step-aerobics champion, and trains as hard for
her sport as any professional athlete. ``It's nothing like it used
to be.'' Finan is currently ranked third in the world for amateur
competitive aerobics. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- July 30, 1998 --
ADOPTION-SECRET-BOS, 7-30 -- Rita Nakashima Brock, 48, runs the
Bunting Institute at Radcliffe College. 15 years ago, she found out
the secret that everyone else seemed to already know. ``Oh, my
God!'' Brock remembers saying loudly. ``I'm adopted!'' Even now,
Ms. Brock still seems startled by the discovery that her mother's
husband, the man who had taught her how to tune the engine of a car
and had taken her fishing and camping so many times, was not her
biological father. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- July 30, 1998 -- CASTIRON-AZR-2,
7-30 -- Chef Robert McGrath of the Roaring Fork in Scottsdale,
Ariz. is an expert with cast-iron cookware. Cast iron cookware has
many advantages. It wears well, it's inexpensive and you can buy a
skillet for $15 or so and use it throughout the rest of your
culinary life. ``I grew up camping,'' explains McGrath who's vast
experience with cast iron started around campfires. (Mark
Henle/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- July 30, 1998 -- CASTIRON-AZR-1,
7-30 -- Chef Robert McGrath of the Roaring Fork in Scottsdale cooks
dishes in cast-iron cauldrons heated on a grill. Specialties
include seasoned boneless trout fillets, bottom front, and
vegetables such as corn on the cob, onions and chile peppers. (Mark
Henle/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) COLTS NECK, N.J. -- July 30, 1998 -- GROUP-BIKING, 7-30
-- Members of the Jersey Shore Touring Society on a Cranberry Sauce
Lite Route. In a group, you have a responsibility to keep up, to
prize safety and assist fellow riders and do the right thing.
Brazenly trying to beat a motorist at an intersection is bad karma.
Wearing a hard-shell helmet is a safety must. (Dith Pran/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NALERIGU, Ghana -- July 30, 1998 -- GHANA-SIDE-AZR, 7-30
-- On their way to class, members of a village sewing school
balance their Singer sewing machines on their heads. In addition to
sewing machines, women of this village, transport huge earthenware
jugs of water on their heads back to common storage tanks in the
village, making several trips a day. (Randy Reid/Arizona Republic
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NALERIGU, Ghana -- July 30, 1998 -- GHANA-AZR-2, 7-30 --
Bhamata, is the mother of Sule Issifu, the chief of the Mamprusi
Tribe. As one of the wives of the previous chief and the mother of
the current one, Bhamata is viewed as the matriarch of the family
and of the village. (Randy Reid/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NALERIGU, Ghana -- July 30, 1998 -- GHANA-AZR-1, 7-30 --
Sule Issifu, a prince of the Mamprusi Tribe, holds court inside his
family compound. As the eldest son of Mamprusi Chief Issifu
Tampuri, Sule Issifu had inherited the title of chief after his
father's death last year at 89. By this tradition, the younger
Issifu was expected to rule the Mamprusis as his father had for
more than half a century. (Randy Reid/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
WOMEN-COMPOSERS, 7-30 -- Helen Taafe Zwilich in front of her piano.
Ms. Zwilich, a Pulitzer Prize- winning composer of large-scale
instrumental works, points out that opera and the bigger forms of
``serious music'' require both practical experience and real
opportunity to learn (and earn) from performance. It has been
easier for women to compose pop. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2 --
RYAN-FILM-VIOLENCE, 7-30 -- A plain-clothes officer running past
the scene of last week's shooting at the Capitol. The shooting at
the Capitol conformed so well to movie-style terrorism that it
became all the more shocking. The level of violence portrayed in
Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan'' has forced many critics
to look closely at the violent scenes and senarios appearing in
today's movies. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 2
--VIEWPOINTS-DANCE, 7-30 -- The director Anne Bogart, left, and
students at a New York University conference on the acting
technique Viewpoints. ``It's a post-modern way to train actors,''
says Ms. Bogart, who has used Viewpoints in work as diverse as
Bertolt Brecht's ``Baal,'' Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``South
Pacific'' and Tennessee Williams's ``Streetcar Named Desire.''
(Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
