<P>
   (NYT23) AMAGANSETT, N.Y. -- July 30, 1998 -- CLINTON-HAMPTONS,
7-30 -- Harold Bennett, left, and Joe Holmes in the bar at the
American Legion in Amagansett. ``Hey, he's my President and I'm
happy to see him here,'' says Bennett, a retired ironworker. ``All
we're gonna do is make him welcome. And they're gonna raise a ton
of money.'' His drinking partner and childhood friend agrees.
``It's all for the bucks, no doubt,'' says Holmes, a disaffected
Democrat now running for local office on the Independent Party
ticket. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1998 -- SEX-COLUMNIST-PROFILE, 7-30
-- Candace Bushnell, the sex columnist, at home but not relaxing.
Her writing has spawned what this summer has become one of HBO's
best-rated sitcoms: ``Sex and the City,'' starring Sarah Jessica
Parker, a journey into Ms. Bushnell's 1990s Manhattan demimonde of
models, investment bankers, designer G-strings and threesomes. ``I
would spend a week, I swear to God, working on a paragraph about
mascara,'' she says. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PIQUA, Ohio -- July 30, 1998 -- MEDICARE-HMO-REACT, 7-30
-- The Medicare HMO is leaving Piqua, Ohio, affecting many like
Ronnie Hines, in wheelchair, and, from left, Dorothy Kloecker,
Becky Howe, Rosie Stelzner, Miyako Francis, Virginia Hirsch and
Dolly Floss. ``They gave us life,'' says Ms. Howe. ``Now they're
trying to suck that life out of us.'' (Mark Lyons/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WATSONVILLE, Calif. -- July 30, 1998 --
CALIF-BERRIES-LABOR-2, 7-30 -- The United Farm Workers is
continuing its fight to represent strawberry pickers in California
after losing a vote to an avowed anti-union group. Arturo
Rodriguez, president of the United Farm Workers, testifies at a
hearing on the election. (Ed Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WATSONVILLE, Calif. -- July 30, 1998 --
CALIF-BERRIES-LABOR-1, 7-30 -- The United Farm Workers is
continuing its fight to represent strawberry pickers in California
after losing a vote to an avowed anti-union group. The UFW said
Thursday it would file legal papers with the California
Agricultural Labor Relations Board, seeking to throw out the
results of the union vote at Coastal Berry, the nation's largest
strawberry grower. (Ed Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- July 30, 1998 -- CALIF-TEARDOWNS, 7-30 --
An empty dirt lot and a construction trailer is all that's left of
Jimmy Stewart's old house on North Roxbury Drive in Beverly Hills.
``The house was just a dump. How he could have lived there, I don't
know,'' says Steven Wallace, brokerage executive, who razed Jimmy
Stewart's house in Beverly Hills after paying $5.6 million for it.
``There were cracks everywhere. The gardens were magnificent, but
when I looked at it, I said, 'Why buy it? It's a total teardown.'
`` (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LAKE RIDGE, Va. -- July 30, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING-2,
7-30 -- A Capitol police officer weeps during funeral services for
Detective John Gibson at Elizabeth Ann Seton Church in Lake Ridge
on Thursday. Gibson was buried at Arlington National Cemetery after
a procession of police vehicles that stretched for miles along the
route from the funeral. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1998 -- NY-SCULPTURE-FLOATER, 7-30
-- With the Brooklyn Bridge as backdrop, Symone Kenton sits on a
steel sculpture by Eric Jean-Marie at the Empire-Fulton Ferry State
Park in Brooklyn. The sculpture, which is supposed to represent the
tail of a scorpion, is part of a show called ``Between the
Bridges,'' sponsored by New York State and the Brooklyn Waterfront
Artists Coalition. (Carrie Boretz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- July 30, 1998 -- OBIT-BUFFALOBOB-B&AMP;W, 7-30 --
Buffalo Bob Smith with his puppet sidekick on the television show
``Howdy Doody and Friends'' in 1972. Smith, a singing piano player
and chatty radio disk jockey who created Howdy Doody and then
teamed up with the puppet on one of early television's most
enduring children's shows, died Thursday at a hospital in
Hendersonville, N.C. The cause was cancer, said his family. Smith
was 80 and lived in Flatrock, N.C. (New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- July 31, 1998 --
REAGAN-RANCH-2, 7-31 -- Ronald and Nancy Reagan used to unwind from
Washington by paddling about in a canoe on ``Lake Lucky'' outside
Rancho Del Cielo, the 106-year-old adobe Ronald Reagan Ranch house
in Santa Barbara. The new owners, who bought the ranch April 21,
want to eventually give visitors unprecedented access to the ranch,
to offer insights about Reagan's lifestyle. So far, they have
invited a few reporters to take a peek. (Steve Malone/Santa Barbara
News-Press Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- July 31, 1998 --
REAGAN-RANCH-1, 7-31 -- The living room in Rancho Del Cielo, the
106-year-old adobe Ronald Reagan Ranch house in Santa Barbara. The
home looks as if the former president could walk in at any moment,
sore from chopping wood by the barn, although he hasn't set foot at
the ranch since late 1994. (Steve Malone/Santa Barbara News-Press
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 1998 -- CAPITOL-SHOOTING, 7-30 --
The hearse carrying Special Agent John Gibson passes the Capitol
building Thursday. Gibson was buried at Arlington National Cemetery
after a procession of police vehicles that stretched for miles
along the route from the funeral in Lake Ridge, Va. The procession
slowly wound past the Capitol, where the flags were still at
half-staff, before moving on to Arlington. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
