<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPHICS-FILES-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a listing of the New York Times News Service Macintosh
graphics files that moved Thursday, 07/30/98. Included is the
corresponding story slug and the size. All graphics have been
posted on PressLink, NewsCom and the Wieck Photo Database.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO/Bank Bailout -- 1X4 5/8 -- MEXICO-ECON
</P>
<P>
   SANCTIONS/U.S. Foreign Policy Map-- 3X6 -- SANCTIONS-DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON/Hamptons Itinerary -- 1X7 3/4 -- CLINTON-HAMPTONS
</P>
<P>
   GROUP-BIKING/N.Y. Metro Region-- 1X4 1/8 -- GROUP-BIKING
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE/Piqua, Ohio Map -- 1X2 1/4 -- MEDICARE-HMO
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM/Drug, Success -- 14pX3 1/4 -- ALCOHOLISM-DRUG
</P>
<P>
   LABOR/Employer Costs, Wages -- 1X3 1/8 -- LABOR-COSTS
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD/Stock 7-31 -- 14p6X3 1/8 -- OXFORD-MARKETPLACE
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ALCOHOLISM-DRUG-ART     07-30 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ALCOHOLISM-DRUG-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: their drinking.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some patients, acamprosate has worked well. Diagnosed with
breast cancer in 1981, Gudrum Hellinger, a 57-year-old school
secretary who lives near Munich, Germany, began sipping wine and
Champagne to cheer her mood. Ms. Hellinger gradually became a heavy
drinker and tried repeatedly to quit, always failing within about
two months. In 1995, she became suicidal and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took acamprosate for six months,'' Ms. Hellinger said.
``I've been sober for three years. I just didn't want a drink
anymore when I was on acamprosate. I don't think I could have given
up drinking without it. But you need more than the drug to do it.
I'm still in counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors, however, noting that only two other medications
for alcoholism have been introduced here since 1951, have renewed
their criticism of the pharmaceutical industry for not developing
more drugs to help addicts through withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The captains of large drug companies won't spend money on
medications to treat alcoholism, doctors say, because addicts
frequently do not take their drugs. Other patients simply make
better customers. As evidence, doctors note that while only 1.8
million American men were treated for erectile dysfunction last
year, according to IMS Health, an industry consultant, six new
treatments are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly as many Americans were treated for alcoholism last year _
1.4 million, according to addiction experts _ but only two drugs,
including acamprosate, were being developed to aid withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies ``wouldn't get their money back from these
drugs,'' said Dr. Herbert Kleber, medical director of the Center on
Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   For acamprosate's advocates, the strangest twist in the
controversy is that the debate exists at all. Alcoholism, after
all, is a devastating illness, one that tears families apart, ruins
careers and kills tens of thousands of people a year. A study by
the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism found that
alcoholism and its treatment cost U.S. businesses $67.7 billion in
lost productivity in 1992, the latest statistics available.
Treatment is not cheap, either: a two-week stay in a clinic can
easily cost $450 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen percent of the U.S. population will be dependent on
alcohol at one time in their lives,'' said Barbara Mason, director
of the Division of Substance Abuse at the University of Miami
School of Medicine and the principal investigator of the nation's
clinical trials on acamprosate.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts call the synthetic drug a therapeutic breakthrough.
Invented by Lipha in 1980, acamprosate, also known as calcium
acetylhomotaurine, is thought to work by restoring normal activity
on certain neurotransmitters in the brain that become overexcited
by the withdrawal of alcohol. This hyperactivity can last a year,
experts say, leaving the alcoholic prone to relapse.
</P>
<P>
   But in the European studies, the drug remained somewhat
effective over time. The percentage of patients who took
acamprosate and abstained from drinking fell to 35 percent after
six months and 33 percent after a year. The number of people who
took placebos yet still stayed off alcohol declined to 23 percent
after six months and 21 percent after a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the higher success rate for those taking the drug is
encouraging. Lipha officials are confident that acamprosate will be
profitable in the United States despite a limited market. Sales of
alcohol withdrawal drugs in the United States totaled a modest $21
million last year, according to IMS Health, largely because of the
side effects of available drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big potential market,'' said Dr. Sylvie Chabac,
international strategic product manager for Lipha.
</P>
<P>
   For some researchers, acamprosate is more than just a promising
treatment _ it is an important new weapon in the arsenal against a
double addiction of alcohol and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, research has shown a strong link between heavy
smoking and drinking. An 11-year study by the Mayo Clinic showed
that those with a dual addiction were far more likely to die from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``A leading cause of death among alcoholics who smoke is lung
cancer,'' said Dr. David Lewis, director of the Center for Alcohol
and Addiction Studies at Brown University in Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Even with acamprosate's benefits, no one is passing it off as a
magic bullet. Experts insist that patients should also undergo
counseling and maintain it long after they are sober. Critics also
note that the drug is of no use in detoxification and that it has
never been proved to reduce a craving for alcohol, even though
patients repeatedly contend that it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a stigma that alcoholism is a moral weakness,''
said Dr. Richard Fuller, director of clinical and prevention
research at the alcoholism institute. ``I find it very distressing.
Alcoholism has a biological basis like hypertension. We treat that
with medications. Why can't you treat alcoholism the same way?''
</P>
<P>
   That argument, however, does not sit well with some clinicians.
``Alcoholics should not be given drugs, unless it is to treat an
organic illness like diabetes,'' said Dr. Joseph Pursch, who is
best known for treating Betty Ford and Billy Carter for alcoholism.
``All these drugs _ Xanax, Valium _ that doctors prescribe for
alcoholics can be addicting. What good is it to switch dependence
from one drug to another?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, an import from France may be alcoholics' best hope for a
new medication. A 1995 report by the Institute of Medicine found
that U.S. drug and biotech companies avoided developing drugs for
addictions.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasons: Many doctors would probably refuse to prescribe
them, many patients would probably decline to take them and
insurers might balk at reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   The drug industry denies that it has neglected drugs for
addictions, noting that 19 such medications are under development,
including one for alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kleber, an author of the Institute of Medicine report, said
he was frustrated by the industry's inertia. ``I'm just glad we may
get acamprosate,'' he said. ``God knows we have a gazillion
antidepressants. Now at least we'll have more than one drug to
treat alcoholism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
