<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-DRESS-BOS &LR;      07-30 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-DRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY DRESS TO BE TESTED FOR DNA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Probe-Dilemma)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth Starr turned over a
dress owned by Monica Lewinsky to the FBI Thursday, with the
expectation that laboratory analysts would search for DNA evidence
that might provide proof of a sexual encounter between President
Clinton and the former White House intern, a source close to
Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has told Starr the dress contains a stain caused by
Clinton that could prove that she engaged in a sexual relationship
with the president, the source said. Lewinsky has saved the dress
for months without cleaning the stain, the source said, thus
preserving proof of at least one sexual encounter.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the dress, which had been previously reported,
then denied, then long rumored, took on renewed importance Thursday
as the possible tie-breaking evidence in what many observers
believe will become a classic he said/she said showdown between
Clinton and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky spent part of Thursday meeting with prosecutors from
Starr's office, providing greater details of her likely testimony
when she appears before the federal grand jury, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with her testimony said Lewinsky could appear
before the grand jury as early as next week, but more likely the
following week. She was given a sweeping form of immunity on
Tuesday, and as part of that arrangement with Starr, she turned the
dress over to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky also gave prosecutors some tape-recorded telephone
messages from Clinton that are not expected to be particularly
incriminating, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   As the FBI took possession of the dress, Clinton was touring
North Carolina, unveiling an environmental initiative involving
river preservation. He ignored reporters' shouted questions on his
own testimony and the Lewinsky immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are low level rumblings in the White House about
the possibility of Clinton making a public statement after
providing his secret grand jury testimony on August 17. Some
Clinton aides believe it is essential that Clinton tell the nation
the details of his testimony, if only because his chief nemesis,
Starr, will have the opportunity to do exactly that when he files a
report to the Congress on his findings in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   However, in prior proceedings when Clinton has supplied
testimony from the White House his aides usually release a one-line
statement simply acknowledging the event. For now, aides said,
there is no immediate plan to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If past is prologue, and it usually is, he won't be saying
anything,'' said Paul Begala. ``But that's still 18 days away.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the dress, as well as Clinton's upcoming testimony,
seemed to raise the stakes in the unwinding investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that after six months of silent strategizing,
Clinton is now left with just two options: Repeat his denial of a
sexual relationship with Lewinsky to the grand jury, or admit to an
affair and, in effect, confess to the federal crime of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Those analysts and his own advisers said the absolute worst
political and legal strategy Clinton could pursue would be to
compound a prior lie about his relationship with Lewinsky with a
fresh one before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The venue of the grand jury, analysts said, is far more serious
than any civil proceeding, especially a suit which has since been
dismissed as the Paula Jones sexual harassment case was. The
penalty for such a lie, analysts added, would be far more severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors take perjury in a grand jury much more seriously
than in a civil deposition,'' said Bob Ullman, a partner at the
Boston law firm of Nutter McClennen &AMP; Fish and a former federal
prosecutor. ``In my experience, perjury in a civil case is rarely
prosecuted. And prosecuting perjury in a dismissed civil case is
unheard of. Prosecuting perjury in a grand jury is done every
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal advisers are sending out initial signals that
the president does not plan to deviate from his adamant denial in
January, when he told Jones lawyers he did not have an affair with
Lewinsky, then declared to the public, ``I did not have sexual
relations with that woman.'' It is the truth, his advisers say, and
it will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the dress, there is also the expectation of reams of
circumstantial evidence gleaned from White House visitor logs and
testimony from the likes of Clinton's personal secretary, his close
friends, including Washington lawyer Vernon Jordan, and the Secret
Service agents assigned to watch him all day and all night. And
there will also be the testimony of Lewinsky herself, who
reportedly plans to tell the grand jurors that she carried on a
lengthy affair with the president and discussed ways with him to
keep it a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Among Clinton allies on the inside and outside of the White
House, there is a general sense of jubilation that he has agreed to
testify to the grand jury and hastened the completion of the Starr
investigation, which has virtually rendered their domestic policy
agenda dormant for the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those allies, speaking on a not-for-attribution basis, said that
even if Clinton admits to a lie in the Jones deposition and says he
had a sexual affair or an encounter with Lewinsky, he will survive
both politically and legally. The public, they said, has already
accepted the possibility Clinton has lied.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are well aware of the latest wave of poll
results which seem to provide a foundation to this belief. Fully
two-thirds of those asked in a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll released
Thursday said they believe it was definitely or probably true that
Clinton had some form of sexual relations with Lewinsky. Only 24
percent of those polled believed that if Clinton had tried to
obstruct justice, it would be a matter serious enough for Congress
to consider impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the poll gave Clinton a 65 percent approval
rating -- a remarkly high figure for a second term president facing
what his critics have said is a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   If he admits wrongdoing, some advisers inside and outside the
White House said, he would have to address the nation, apologize
for his indiscretions and vow to return to the business of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   At least part of that view, coupled with a queasiness over the
sexual nature of the probe, was echoed widely on Capitol Hill,
among Republicans and Democrats alike, who have said repeatedly
they do not want to be presented with a case solely about the
president's sexual indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Republicans are looking forward to a Judiciary
Committee hearing on the president's sex life,'' said Rep. Martin
Meehan of Massachusetts, a member of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   All along, critics have said that the far more serious charge
that can be levied against Clinton will be obstruction of justice.
But legal analysts said that even if the dress does reveal DNA
evidence, obstruction charges will be difficult, at best, to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly has told Starr's prosecutors that she
discussed with the president possible scenarios about keeping their
affair secret. In addition, Clinton seemed to take great pains to
help Lewinsky land a job in New York City, even involving Jordan
and the US ambassador to the United Nations, Bill Richardson, in
the search.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Washington lawyer Stanley Brand, ``It's very hard
making an obstruction case. It's usually in the mafia, and it's an
explicit, `I'll break your legs' kind of thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
