<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ATHLETICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX DEAL, GET DEALT A LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ As zero hour nears for the trading deadline,
Steve Avery knows the clock could be approaching midnight for him,
too.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight start, the Red Sox lefthander failed to
make it past the third inning, this time in a 6-5 loss to Oakland
Thursday that simultaneously ended a four-game Boston winning
streak and a nine-game A's losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Avery had little choice but to acknowledge that
if general manager Dan Duquette deals for another pitcher, he could
lose his spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that helps the team is great,'' said Avery, who
walked four and gave up four hits in 2 2/3 innings before being
yanked with Oakland leading, 4-1, and well on the way to its first
win against Boston in eight meetings. ``I think I've done a pretty
fair job until the last couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much leeway I'll get, but I'm not happy that
I've lost a couple of times while the team has been playing some
good ball. I'm going to do everything I can to change it and keep
hoping that I'll get the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams wasn't prepared to say Avery could be
dropped from the rotation, even though he has yielded 15 runs (13
earned) in his last three starts, but it is not Williams's style to
tip anything off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other pitchers have gone through the same thing,'' Williams
said. ``I'm sure Cy Young went through it, too, though I don't
remember. There isn't a pitcher who hasn't gone through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Avery isn't Williams's only concern. The lefthander
might have been spared his fourth loss against seven wins,
especially after the Red Sox scored three times in the eighth, two
runs coming on Nomar Garciaparra's fourth home run in the last five
games and 21st of the season. But by then, Rich Garces had given up
his third tape-measure homer in barely a week, Matt Stairs taking
El Guapo over the center-field fence for a two-run shot that made
it 6-2 in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Garces has bone chips in his right elbow that will require
surgery after the season and keep him from pitching in back-to-back
games. But he has now been scored upon in each of his last five
appearances, which raises questions about how much he can
contribute down the stretch after playing such a valuable role to
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' Garces said, continuing to downplay his condition.
``I was so worried about the runner on first base (Mike Neill),
keeping him from stealing a base, that I left the pitch up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a split-fingered pitch that didn't break until it cleared
the wall. The home run by ex-Sox substitute Stairs was his
team-leading 16th of the season, but it was runner-up for longest
home run of the day.
</P>
<P>
   That distinctionbelonged to Billy Ashley, the peroxide giant
who is seen less often than Wally the Green Monster and may become
even less visible now that the Red Sox are bringing back Mike
Stanley to serve as the righthanded DH.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley, who has had only 24 at-bats in the five weeks since he
was promoted after the Jim Leyritz trade, cleared the left-field
bleachers in the fifth with his third homer, meaning he homers
almost as frequently as the Great McGwire. But Ashley also whiffed
twice against lefty starter Kenny Rogers, giving him 11 strikeouts,
or virtually one every two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   And in the ninth inning, when the game could have been tied with
one swing of the bat, Ashley was lifted for a pinch hitter, Darren
Bragg, who lined out to shortstop against righthander Billy Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley could be headed for a return trip to Pawtucket, though he
would seem to have some usefulness as a righthanded pinch hitter,
with Keith Mitchell sent back to the PawSox instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crossed my mind,'' Ashley said when asked whether he
thought his days with Boston were numbered. ``Whether via trade,
though I haven't heard that anybody's interested, I don't know
where this leaves me. I'd love to stay and contribute. These guys
are great, and we still have a very good chance of being in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I wasn't able to do more for myself to get in
on a more frequent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, it's on to Anaheim for a reunion with Stanley and a
three-game set with the Angels, a possible playoff opponent. All
the while, the Sox will be keeping an eye on the scoreboard,
because the Orioles Thursday won for the 17th time in 20 games and
have shaved their wild-card deficit from 15 1/2 to eight games in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez, Red Sox Nation turns its lonely eyes to you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
