<HEADLINE>
TURF STARS' SCHEDULE TO SEE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When it comes to turf-course racing, California
grass is usually best. Of the past 18 national champions in the
male and female turf divisions, 12 won major stakes in the state
where grass is green year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The local circuit's turf-stakes schedule is in for some changes
because of the cancellation of the 1998 Arlington Million (which is
gone for good if Arlington International racetrack doesn't reopen
in '99) and the addition of a fillies-and-mares turf race to the
Breeders' Cup program (starting in '99).
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the Million, which has been run in late August,
might prompt Del Mar to move the Eddie Read Handicap to the end of
the summer season or raise the purse for the Del Mar Invitational
Handicap. Either change could only help the track by keeping local
stars in town.
</P>
<P>
   The Breeders' Cup change will force changes in two major
late-season stakes for fillies and mares. The Yellow Ribbon Stakes
will have to move from the end to the beginning of the autumn Oak
Tree meeting at Santa Anita, where it would serve as a
steppingstone to the Breeders' Cup race. The Matriarch, at
Hollywood Park in November, will shorten up to 1[ miles from 1\
miles, the distance of the Breeders' Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the local effect of the Arlington Million's absence
is likely to be seen in a stronger-than-usual field for the
$250,000 Del Mar Invitational on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be seen in the $300,000 Eddie Read Handicap on Sunday,
which combines with the $300,000 Ramona Handicap for fillies and
mares on Saturday to form one of Del Mar's biggest weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Among the challengers for top-weighted Labeeb (121 pounds) and
Hawksley Hill (120) is only one out-of-towner, Subordination (117),
the New York 4-year-old who won the Hollywood Derby in November.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Drysdale trains both Labeeb and Hawksley Hill. Drysdale
could have a huge weekend.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Fiji, the nation's top-ranked turf filly, in the
Ramona and it appears he'll let her run despite being unhappy with
the weight assignments under which Fiji's 125 is seven more than
next-highest Different.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Legal dance: &LR;  Laws prohibit the California Horse Racing Board
from identifying trainers suspected of medication violations until
an investigation is complete, but not from announcing Thursday that
accusations are being drafted against seven trainers whose horses
tested positive for clenbuterol.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers are being told privately that follow-up tests of
urine samples confirmed initial results, and no timetable has been
set for making the names public, the CHRB said. However, state
agents are known to have searched the barns of Bruce Headley,
Robert Marshall, Darrell Vienna and Ted West.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 20 horses tested positive for the drug, which aids
breathing and thus can improve performance, following races at
Hollywood Park, Golden Gate Fields and Cal-Expo in Sacramento
between May 16 and July 11, the CHRB said.
</P>
<P>
   Clenbuterol became legal this year under FDA regulations,
meaning it may be used in training. But it's still prohibited in
post-race samples, and improved tests can find left-over traces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Seasons change: &LR;  Last summer, when Kent Desormeaux won the Del
Mar riding title, he gave credit to leading trainer Bob Baffert,
for whom Desormeaux was the regular jockey.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gary Stevens has first call in the Baffert barn, and
Desormeaux has been feeling the effects. He needed 21 tries to ring
up his first Del Mar winner on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Baffert hasn't been doing much better. He won once
with 11 starters last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More 'Mo: &LR;  The good news for Desormeaux is that he'll keep
riding Real Quiet while Stevens sticks with Victory Gallop for the
Aug. 9 Haskell Invitational at Saratoga. It was up to Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet was assigned 126 pounds for the Haskell. Victory
Gallop, who nosed him out of the Triple Crown in the Belmont
Stakes, gets 125. Coronado's Quest gets 124.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More Baffert: &LR;  The latest on Silver Charm is that he'll stay in
light training while Baffert looks for signs that he's ready to
race again. But the Aug. 15 Pacific Classic at Del Mar is
definitely out.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm finished last on Saturday in the San Diego Handicap
won by Mud Route. A post-race exam showed a mild case of
respiratory bleeding. Baffert thought the trouble might stem from
the colt's fever and antibiotics treatment the week he pulled out
of the Hollywood Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Another thought: Silver Charm is only the latest horse who seems
to not be quite the same after making the long trip to the $4
million Dubai World Cup. He won the race against some of the
world's best in March.
</P>
<P>
   Might trainers think twice before sending their horses halfway
around the globe in the future?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sit on it: &LR;  The Kentucky Derby prep race formerly known as the
Jim Beam Stakes has a new sponsor and a clumsy new name for at
least the next three years. It's the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Turfway Park in Florence, Ky., announced a deal under which the
Houston-based furniture company will put up $500,000 of the
$750,000 purse. Gallery is owned by James McIngvale, a horse owner
who made his shaky reputation in the sport by capriciously firing a
series of trainers last spring.
</P>
<P>
   If McIngvale expects people to walk around saying, ``I love a
horse in the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes,'' he's got another thing
.coming. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
