<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS SEEK GENETIC TESTING OF LEWINSKY'S DRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-PERJURY) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors are seeking genetic testing of a dress
belonging to Monica Lewinsky that she says contains physical
evidence of a sexual encounter with President Clinton, according to
lawyers close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky turned over the dress to the office of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr on Wednesday, lawyers said. It had been kept
for the past seven months in the New York apartment of Ms.
Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, putting her in jeopardy of an
obstruction of justice charge for concealing evidence that
prosecutors had sought on a search of Ms. Lewinsky's Watergate
apartment earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs. Lewis were given broad grants of immunity
from prosecution this week in exchange for providing full accounts
of Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the president. They also agreed
to turn over evidence, including the dress and answering machine
tapes containing messages to Ms. Lewinsky from the president, the
lawyers said..
</P>
<P>
   The messages were innocuous, according to a lawyer who has heard
them. In one, just before Christmas last year, the president told
Ms. Lewinsky that the brother of his private secretary, Betty
Currie, had died. In another, the lawyer said, Clinton said, ``Hey,
it's me. Sorry I missed you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky met for several hours with prosecutors at an
undisclosed location on Thursday afternoon in preparation for her
grand jury testimony, which could begin as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   The president has maintained a resolute silence on the Lewinsky
matter since late January, when he vehemently denied a sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and said that he had not told anyone
to lie under oath. Since then, the White House strategy has been to
delay the investigation with as many legal roadblocks as could be
constructed while seeking to undermine the legitimacy and fairness
of Starr's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision to submit to grand jury questioning
came after numerous requests from Starr over a period of months,
culminating in a subpoena issued on July 17. Many of the
president's advisers urged him to resist or ignore the subpoena,
but he decided that giving testimony now was the quickest way to
bring the investigation to a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the grand jury will hear Clinton's explanation
two weeks from Monday, there is no sign that the president is
prepared to speak to the American people on the matter any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no reference to the Lewinsky matter on a trip to
North Carolina on Thursday, ignoring shouted questions and not
addressing the issue in a speech on the environment and later at a
political fund-raising dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman, said the president is
scheduled to make an announcement on the economy Friday in the
White House Rose Garden and may take questions from reporters that
would almost certainly concern the revelations of the past several
days.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president would decide whether to answer
questions ``depending on how hot it is out there.'' He was not
referring to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry said that Clinton had no intention of speaking to
the news media or the American public in any detail in the next two
weeks about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky or about any of the
other questions arising from the months-long perjury and
obstruction-of-justice investigation being conducted by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all talked about it,'' McCurry said. ``He clearly has to
testify and he has to stay focused on that. Until we know what the
testimony is, none of us is in a position to give advice on what he
should say publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on what Ms. Lewinsky tells the grand jury when she
testifies and whether other testimony and physical evidence
supports her story.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's dress may be sent to an FBI forensics lab to
determine whether there is a stain containing Clinton's semen, as
lawyers familiar with the case say that Ms. Lewinsky has asserted.
Such a stain would retain DNA material for many years, unless the
dress has been cleaned with detergents, according to experts in DNA
testing. Dry cleaning alone would not remove it, nor would storage
under poor conditions, they said.
</P>
<P>
   If semen is found on the dress, prosecutors then would likely
seek a saliva or blood sample from the president to determine
whether it matched. The tests are extremely reliable, according to
prosecutors and defense lawyers who use DNA testing in trials.
</P>
<P>
   With modern instruments and computers, matching could be
completed in a matter of days, according to Barry Scheck, a
prominent New York defense attorney and an expert on genetic
testing. He served as a consultant for the defense in the O.J.
Simpson murder case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no sperm on the dress, that's the end of the
hysteria,'' Scheck said. ``If there is, there is no legal basis for
the president to resist giving a DNA sample, a simple swab from the
inside his cheek.'' The entire process could be completed in 72
hours, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To keep the results secret until Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony to
set a ``perjury trap'' for the president would be unfair to Clinton
and bad for the nation, Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, stung by accusations that his office leaked sensitive
grand jury material to the media, issued a two-sentence statement
on Thursday with Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers denying that they were the
source of news accounts this week about Ms. Lewinsky's proposed
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported this week that Ms. Lewinsky told members of
the independent counsel's office that she had had a sexual
relationship with Clinton, despite both of their denials under oath
in the sexual harassment lawsuit filed by Paula Jones against
Clinton. It has also been disclosed that Ms. Lewinsky is willing to
testify that she and Clinton agreed they would deny the
relationship to keep it private.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky's lawyers, Jacob A. Stein and Plato Cacheris,
and the Office of Independent Counsel met for the specific and
mutually shared purpose of preventing the dissemination of
speculative information concerning the OIC's investigation and its
dealings with Ms. Lewinsky,'' the statement said. ``Suggestions in
the media that Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers or the OIC are the source of
such information are untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   The procession of witnesses before the grand jury continued on
Thursday, with seven Secret Service officers appearing before two
separate panels at the federal courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has sought the officers' testimony to determine whether or
when Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky were alone together in the White
House or whom else she might have seen during her 37 White House
visits after she left her job there in April 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
