<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCCLINTON-COX     07-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCCLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political riptide washes away in N.C.
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST JEFFERSON, N.C._ Along a pastoral stretch of the ancient
New River overflowing with Democrats, bluegrass music and the
excitement of a first-time presidential visit, President Clinton
escaped Thursday from the political uproar rising from his
relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd vote for you again, Bill,'' a young woman yelled from the
crowd of several thousand who crammed a narrow spit of farmland
next to the South Fork of the New River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you,'' another shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, smiling and brushing a hand through his thick silver
hair, ignored those calls. But he acknowledged others with waves
and brisk salutes amid the kind of hooting and hollering that these
mountain folk typically reserve for fine fiddle playing.
</P>
<P>
   In this traditionally Democratic corner of North Carolina that
bumps against Virginia and Tennessee, people seemed mildly offended
by the mention of Lewinsky on this historic day for their revered
river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people hear about all that trash, the more they like
him,'' said Nancy Vannoy, 71, who traveled with her husband, Fred,
from the nearby Todd community. ``They're plumb disgusted with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, White House Chief of Staff
Erskine Bowles and North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt arrived by
helicopter to honor the New River, which begins as the South Fork
and North Fork in northwestern North Carolina. In a geological
oddity for a North American river, it flows northward rather than
southward, through Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's motorcade arrived in a rush of rock music blaring from
speakers and flashing lights atop police cars. Clinton remained in
his vehicle for a few minutes, as security agents and dogs searched
a grove of trees on a hill overlooking the speaking platform. Then
the president arrived on stage dressed casually in two shades of
green.
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of a spell of speeches that went on so long
that some old-timers grew faint in the muggy heat, Clinton signed a
document declaring the New River and 13 other U.S. waterways as the
country's first American Heritage Rivers. The rivers are now
eligible for federal money for further environmental protection and
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ancient river has flowed through this and for millions of
years, hundreds of millions of years,'' said Clinton, predicting
generations from now people will fish and paddle on the same gently
flowing waters as the Cherokees did centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   A cool breeze moved across the lush ridge on the other side of
the river, bringing a burst of rain that began falling just as
Clinton and his entourage disappeared from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Childress, 43, of Jefferson, praised Clinton for his
efforts to improve education, health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing his job, and as long as he is doing it well, leave
the poor guy alone,'' she said. ``It's a shame that people can't
leave his private life alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe McKenzie, 70, chairman of the Democratic Party in Sullivan
County, Tenn., reached back 24 summers to explain why he believes
Clinton's opponents are hoping to catch the president in a lie
about his relationship with the young White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans cannot forget about Nixon, and they want to
get even,'' said McKenzie, wearing a red badge endorsing Gore for
president in 2000. In 1974, President Nixon resigned rather than
face impeachment proceedings for his involvement in the Watergate
scandal. Back in West Jefferson, standing along the roadside where
they thought Clinton's motorcade would pass, two men held a
hand-painted banner. It read, ``America turn back! God must turn
his back_ or say sorry to Sodom!''
</P>
<P>
   ``This pretty much tells you how we feel about the Monica
Lewinsky scandal and the other things that President Clinton has
done,'' said Michael J. Woodman, the bishop of El Shechinah
Churches International, a Christian denomination based in Roanoke,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, along the president's route, elementary school teacher
Linda Ball decorated the doorway of her granite home in red, white
and blue letters spelling, ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is coming to honor the oldest river,'' said
Ball, who invited friends and family members to watch the motorcade
in lawn chairs in her shady yard.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the children were eager to talk about what they knew
about the Lewinsky matter, but before they had a chance, a mother
scolded, ``Keep quiet, Seth.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
