<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-GOODWILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGIZED AS TEACHER, COACH AND CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST MEADOW, N.Y. _ At 27, Lea Loveless Maurer is a
world-champion swimmer. A high school teacher and coach. A wife.
And happy with the entire package.
</P>
<P>
   In the world championships in Australia in January, she won the
100-meter backstroke. She teaches freshman and sophomore English at
Lake Forest High School outside Chicago and coaches its boys' and
girls' swimming teams. She gets coaching help from her husband,
Erik, whom she met at Stanford when both were collegiate champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erik knows I'm still swimming as part of my life, not as my
whole life,'' Maurer said. ``He understands the balance I have. He
knows I need to be flexible. But I have no expectations. I do this
one step at a time. I don't know when it will end. Sooner or later,
I won't have the energy to do what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, at the Nassau County Goodwill Games Swimming and Diving
Center, she has had plenty of energy. She is a co-captain of the
United States women's team. In the novel four-team dual-meet
format, she helped the Americans rout China, 88-34, on Tuesday
night and swam against the World All-Stars Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   When she started at 9, Lea (pronounced Lee) Loveless became a
swimming prodigy from Crestwood. Her career was honed in the
50-yard pool of the Badger Swim Club in New Rochelle, where Coach
John Collins put the 13-year-old in the same practice lane as a
male backstroker, Rick Carey, who won three gold medals in the 1984
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would lap me twice over 400 meters,'' she recalled. ``But I
was very young and he taught me a lot of stuff. He taught me to
keep aware of what I do well and what I want to do the most. He
taught me to swim hard every day, read a lot, keep on top of my
academics.''
</P>
<P>
   She learned. She has won seven national titles. She won a gold
medal and a bronze medal in the 1992 Olympics. But she did not make
the United States team for the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1996 Olympic trials were probably the worst meet of my
life,'' she said, ``and when they ended I asked myself: Do I teach?
Do I coach? Do I have a baby? Have I been swimming because I want
American records, or do I like the sport? I think I was doing it
for the right reasons. I like to race.''
</P>
<P>
   She kept racing, and in this year's world championships she
shocked herself by setting an American record of 1 minute 1.16
seconds for the 100-meter backstroke. She wants to be the first
woman to break one minute (the world record is 1:00.16).
</P>
<P>
   So she is still swimming, still looking forward to the daily
drudgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have everything I want now _ a great career, a great
husband,'' Maurer said. ``I can walk away from swimming. But my
career has been unusual, and I don't recommend that anyone follow
my footsteps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
