<DOCNO> NYT19980730.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRAWLEY-JURY-2TAKE     07-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-JURY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE ISSUE PERMEATED BRAWLEY CASE, SOME JURORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON) 
(bl) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON and DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ They were six people thrust together by
chance and lawyers' calculations.
</P>
<P>
   One was a white woman who had never heard of the Rev. Al
Sharpton before last November. Another, a postal worker originally
from the Bronx, was the jury's sole black woman and nearly came to
blows with a white man a day before the verdict. A third, a black
man who grew up in Arizona, said he had not been raised in ``the
black community'' but learned much about it during the course of
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated from the rest of the world, the jurors in the Tawana
Brawley defamation trial said they tried to decide the case only on
the evidence. But called upon to resolve one of the most
contentious racial cases in New York's history, they found that
race often intruded in the jury room.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the jury of two blacks and four whites awarded just
$345,000 in damages to Steven Pagones, the white former prosecutor
who sued for defamation after Miss Brawley's advisers said he raped
and kidnapped Miss Brawley, a black woman, in 1987, when she was
15. Some of the white jurors had pressed for a much higher number.
One said he had in mind $1.5 million but compromised, he said, to
try to win unanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with four of the jurors after Wednesday's verdict
showed that they viewed the voluminous evidence presented to them
through the prism of race. There were sometimes emotional
confrontations based on racial differences. They were, after all,
``six different people from six different worlds,'' said Patrick
Cody, the foreman.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors needed each other, another juror said, because no one
else understood what they were going through. They were ``like
survivors of a shipwreck,'' he said. Several jurors said they had
formed enduring relationships. An alternate and a juror, newly
single, have a date to go to the zoo this week.
</P>
<P>
   As in any jury deliberation, their work was often a balancing
act. The jurors decided, for example, that the Rev. Al Sharpton was
less culpable than the other two Brawley advisers, C. Vernon Mason
and Alton Maddox, because they were lawyers and he was not.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors said they were often able to bridge racial gaps, for
example, by focusing on literal facts of the trial, like the
precise wording of statements Pagones said were defamatory. But
when racial divisions surfaced, they served as a reminder of the
volatility of the case. Several jurors said that a pivotal conflict
developed between L. Williams, the black woman, and Mark Urbin, 37,
a white toolmaker at a manufacturing company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams, a postal clerk, declined repeated requests for an
extensive interview. In a brief conversation, she denied that she
was motivated by race, but several jurors said she appeared to feel
most intensely the pressure that could come from scrutiny of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believed in Tawana; all the rest of the jurors believed in
the evidence,'' Urbin said. Other jurors said Urbin was the most
aloof member of the panel and seemed least sympathetic to Miss
Brawley's three black advisers. He acknowledged that Ms. Williams
at one point asked him to put himself in one of the black
defendants' shoes. He refused. ``I didn't do it,'' he said. ``I
needed to look at the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-simmering tensions between Ms. Williams and Urbin
erupted Tuesday, as the jurors were beginning to consider what
damages to assess after the eight-month trial. Urbin said he was
one of the jurors pressing for a heavy damage award. ``She said she
felt I was using race in the discussion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other people who were there said the two were yelling at each
other. Ms. Williams exploded in anger, jabbing a pen toward Urbin's
face. A court officer entered the jury room, and deliberations were
suspended for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams, 40, had attracted wide public notice when she
refused to sign the verdict sheet July 13 that declared the
advisers had defamed Pagones 10 times. In news accounts, there had
been speculation that she was isolated as a dissident on the jury.
But in the interviews, other jurors said her position within the
panel was far more subtle. She had participated in the
deliberations and had voted with the majority more than half the
time, two jurors said.
</P>
<P>
   But, other jurors said, she seemed to grow concerned about how
her role as a black juror would be portrayed publicly. Glen
Heinsohn, 45, a white man who moved here 12 years ago from the
Bronx, said he and Ms. Williams became close friends, sharing
memories of the Bronx and praying together.
</P>
<P>
   Heinsohn said it was obvious that Ms. Williams felt great
pressure because of her race. He said he would not betray her
confidence. But, he said, ``maybe one of the instincts is
self-preservation.'' Heinsohn, who works at a school for autistic
children, said he had wanted to assess $1.5 million but relented to
encourage Ms. Williams to participate in the deliberations. She did
and voted for the damage award. But then, when the jury was polled
in the courtroom, she surprised the others on the panel by saying
that she did not approve of the $345,000 verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hypothetically,'' Heinsohn said, ``you're a black female,
you're going to leave this process, maybe you're already getting
flak. You're hearing this. You've got a family to think of.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The other black juror was James Boone, 45, an engineer at IBM,
whose perspective was very different from Ms. Williams'. He had
grown up among whites in Tucson, Ariz. In an interview Thursday he
said that shaped his view of the world, and he noted that he is
married to a white woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't raised in the black community, so, culturalwise, I
didn't know a lot about it,'' he said. ``I've learned a lot about
it during this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors said Boone tended to see the case much as they
did. ``Jimmy looked at all the evidence,'' said Urbin, ``and when
he wasn't sure, we'd show him the evidence and he'd change his
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams, however, could not be so easily swayed. She often
talked about the oppression of blackpeople in American history when
others wanted to talk about such details as the wording of one of
the defamatory statements.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams said she understood the importance of the advisers'
work more keenly than the four white jurors or even Boone possibly
could. Boone recalled her explanation: ``Althea always said, `Hey,
I grew up in New York City. I've seen other people who wanted for
things and had no way to get them except through people like Al
Sharpton.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For all the jurors, the length of the trial and the fact they
were more or less trapped in a room with the defendants meant that
they all experienced what one of the jurors likened to ``Stockholm
syndrome,'' the process of identifying with one's captors.
</P>
<P>
   But the underside to that, several of the jurors said, was that
they were prisoners in their own lives. Heinsohn, who lives alone,
said that even though he does not drink, he often went to a bar and
nursed club sodas just to hear people talk about life outside the
Brawley case.
</P>
<P>
   An alternate said she sometimes took a mental break by talking
to salesmen on the telephone. Even the jurors with spouses and
children often talked to each other on the telephone at night
because they found they could not find solace with people who were
living outside their tightly contained world.
</P>
<P>
   When they were deliberating the first phase of the case, the
judge, S. Barrett Hickman, asked the jurors if they wanted to be
sequestered. Most of them said no. A day later, that changed. In
the interviews, the jurors said they simply could not bear the
feeling of estrangement from everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like loneliness in a crowd of people,'' said Heinsohn.
``It's like we were survivors of a shipwreck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the phase devoted to determining the size of the monetary
award to Pagones, the jurors said they had widely divergent ideas
about how much to assess. ``We all had numbers in own heads,'' said
Cody, 32, a warehouseman who was the foreman. ``So we decide to
divide it up,'' averaging the amounts proposed by each juror as a
starting point for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their efforts to keep their deliberations
dispassionate, the jurors' perspectives on race almost always
returned as a subtext. In apportioning damages among the three
defendants, the jurors ultimately penalized Mason and Maddox more
heavily than Sharpton. They said that was partly because, as
lawyers, they had ``the rule book'' about what was permissible in
making accusations, and Sharpton did not.
</P>
<P>
   But in the interviews, the white jurors appeared more accepting
of Sharpton generally than they were of Mason and Maddox, partly
because Sharpton's efforts to enter the political mainstream in New
York made him seem more appealing. ``He's a likable guy,'' said
Heinsohn. ``I've heard him on the Imus show.''
</P>
<P>
   As they haggled over what damages to assess, a pattern emerged.
The four white jurors were pressing for higher damages. Ms.
Williams was arguing to keep the damages to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   On the fence was Boone, who says he identifies himself as
racially mixed. But as the deliberations grew more intense, he
said, he found himself feeling pressured to vote a certain way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among those who perceive me as black,'' he said, ``they would
look at me and say, `You have to do things based on your black
culture.'''
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle, Boone says, he sided with Ms. Williams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
