<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-SHARPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON CLAIMS VICTORY, BUT MAY STILL APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BRAWLEY-JURY) 
(bl) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rev. Al Sharpton claimed victory Thursday, a day
after a Dutchess County jury ordered him to pay $65,000 to a white
former prosecutor whom he had accused of kidnapping and raping a
black teen-ager 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said that he would appeal the decision, and he
suggested that his appeal might revolve around something a jury
member said Wednesday after the decision on damages _ that Sharpton
may have been duped by C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox, the two
other advisers to the teen-ager, Tawana Brawley, and so under the
law he should not have been held liable for defamation.
</P>
<P>
   Former prosecutor Steven Pagones had sought $395 million from
the three advisers to Ms. Brawley, whose story of being attacked
was later found by a grand jury to be a hoax. The judge will
determine what damages she owes at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief news conference Thursday, Sharpton said that the low
damages were a victory in a case that was always ``about the right
of advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, Pagones' lawyer, William Stanton, had
said that the defamation trial was about holding the advisers
accountable for self-serving distortions and falsehoods that
injured his client's good name.
</P>
<P>
   After the closing arguments, which ended an eight-month trial
that revisited the racially divisive case, a jury decided that
Pagones was defamed when the three advisers to the Brawley family
made public statements linking him to the attack.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, that jury awarded Pagones $345,000 in compensatory
and punitive damages. They set Sharpton's total damages at $65,000,
Maddox's at $95,000 and Mason's at $185,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton and his lawyer, Michael Hardy, said they were
encouraged by juror comments that suggested Sharpton had believed
Ms. Brawley's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said of the damages and whether he had enough money to
pay them: ``I've said that if it was $1 or a million, I was going
to appeal. Its certainly going to cost more to appeal, which is
important to clear my name.''
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, Maddox, who represented himself, and Stephen
Jackson, the lawyer for Mason, said they still believed that
Pagones had attacked Ms. Brawley. Hardy walked a fine line, never
saying whether he believed that Pagones was guilty. Instead, Hardy
argued that Sharpton, as the spokesman for the Brawley family, had
a duty to represent them zealously.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sharpton evaded lingering questions about whether
he still believed Ms. Brawley's story and whether he believed that
Pagones was involved in the attack. When asked whether he still
believed the story, Sharpton would say only, ``Ms. Brawley says he
was among her attackers'' and ``surely, here today, I believe there
was enough evidence for Steven Pagones to be prosecuted like anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the jury's decision on damages _ after calls from
Pagones' lawyers that jurors bankrupt the advisers _ a victory
against ``the political forces that were trying to use a civil case
to stop Al Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton refused to say he made a mistake in championing Ms.
Brawley's cause, saying, ``I've tried over the last 10 years to do
what is right, and with each case I try to do it better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
