<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-30 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPREWELL'S SUIT AGAINST NBA IS TOSSED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million civil suit Latrell Sprewell filed in an attempt
to make the National Basketball Association and the Golden State
Warriors pay for punishing him after he attacked his coach, P.J.
Carlesimo, was dismissed by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker in
San Francisco on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's suit challenged the suspension he received and
alleged that his civil rights and racial discrimination laws had
been violated. The suit also alleged that he was punished twice _
by the team and the league _ for choking Carlesimo. Walker said the
suit had ``manifold deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell assaulted Carlesimo during a Dec. 1 practice session,
which led the Warriors to terminate his $24 million contract and
the NBA to suspend him for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case that should have never been brought,'' said
Jeffrey Mishkin, the NBA's chief legal officer. ``It is entirely
baseless, and we are, of course, very pleased with Judge Walker's
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The league was not successful at all on another legal front
Thursday. In U.S. District Court in New York City, Judge Barbara
Jones denied the NBA's motion to stay a jurisdictional hearing by
John Feerick regarding a request for arbitration filed by the union
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Feerick listened to arguments for just over an
hour concerning whether he had jurisdiction to arbitrate a
grievance filed by the union on behalf of players whose contracts
call for them to be paid during the NBA's owner-imposed lockout.
Once Feerick decides the jurisdictional issue, which could take a
day or two, a hearing on the merits of the case will be scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the union's request for arbitration, the NBA sued
the union, contending that the league should not have to pay
players during the lockout and that it should not have to go to
arbitration. The league also asked for Feerick to be removed as
arbitrator on the grounds that his term had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Feerick's name is known all too well within the league. In
March, Feerick ruled that the termination and suspension Sprewell
received were excessive. He ordered that Sprewell be reinstated by
the Warriors and that the suspension be reduced. But Sprewell did
miss 68 games without pay because of the part of the suspension
that was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Walker gave Sprewell the opportunity to re-submit the complaint
but urged him to consider dropping the matter completely.
</P>
<P>
   WOOING JORDAN FROM A DISTANCE
</P>
<P>
   Tim Floyd, the Bulls' coach-to-be, has been unabashed in his
effort to woo Michael Jordan and prevent himself from being known
as the man who forced the superstar out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's monthlong lockout has prevented Floyd from contacting
Jordan directly, but he has become cozy with Buzz Peterson,
Jordan's roommate at the University of North Carolina. The two have
talked repeatedly about Jordan, and messages have been relayed.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest that Floyd may try to lure Peterson from his
coaching job at Appalachian State and make him a well-paid
assistant in order to please Jordan. But Floyd's efforts may be
futile.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's decision to come back may have more to do with Scottie
Pippen's future than with Phil Jackson's departure from the Bulls
and with Floyd's arrival. Pippen will be a free agent when the
lockout ends, but his market value may be diminished after his back
surgery this week. Phoenix may think twice about offering $60
million to a player who has been through so much wear and tear as
he nears 33.
</P>
<P>
   This could help the Bulls' bargaining position. If Jerry
Reinsdorf, the Bulls' owner, is willing to pay his star forward
enough to lessen the friction Pippen has for General Manager Jerry
Krause, there might be a way of keeping Pippen and Jordan on the
floor together with Floyd as the coach.
</P>
<P>
   With or without Pippen and Jordan, Floyd will be the coach
despite the transparent attempt by Reinsdorf to announce Floyd as
Jackson's successor last week by installing a surprise twist to his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to wipe his fingerprints off any plan that might
force Jordan out, Reinsdorf said Floyd would be kept as director of
basketball operations if Jackson wanted to return and coach Jordan
again.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was puttering around on a motorcycle, feeling the wind
nip at his tie-dyed T-shirt when he had to put the brakes on. He
stopped to tell reporters, who had gathered at his summer home in
Flathead Lake, Mont., that he was not going to return to the Bulls
as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect I'd have to re-retire,'' Jackson said. ``But I
guess it's important that I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   OAKLEY'S ADVICE FOR KNICKS
</P>
<P>
   Players and teams are not allowed to talk during the lockout,
not even former players and teams. But Charles Oakley, who was
traded to Toronto for Marcus Camby on the night of the NBA draft,
did squeeze in a conversation or two with the Knicks' team
president, Ernie Grunfeld, after the trade and before the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most who buy into the theory that the Knicks' point guard
position needs a makeover with a big trade, Oakley was campaigning
for the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Ernie to re-sign Charlie Ward,'' Oakley said. ``But
that's up to them. They shouldn't short-change him. He's a starting
point guard, so you've got to treat him like one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
