<SLUG> BC-BRICKYARD-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brickyard good to Irvan again
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Ernie Irvan was first out in qualifying Thursday
for Saturday's Brickyard 400, then put a record 179.394 miles per
hour lap on the board to win the pole for the second consecutive
year.
</P>
<P>
   It was Irvan's first pole of the year, his winning speed two
miles an hour faster than last year's 177.376 mph lap.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, the 1996 Brickyard champion, joins Irvan on the
front row with a speed of 178.596 miles per hour. Jeff Gordon,
178.324 mph, and rookie Kenny Irwin, 178.260 mph, make up row two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we got to figure out how to win this race,'' said Irvan,
who gave his Skittles team their first career pole. ``I don't know
how I could have gotten a better lap. The car did everything we
expected it to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to start on the pole is a definite plus. I knew the
Pontiacs could run with the Fords in qualifying, and when we get it
ready to race, we'll find out how it stacks up in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had been fastest in prequalifying practice and took his
best shot at Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with that, I wasn't at all disappointed,'' Gordon
said. ``I've got everything going. I'm starting to see 1994 (when
he won) come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Buckshot Jones surprised himself with a 15th place
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal just to make this race,'' Jones said, ``but a
real big deal to make it in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody was in such a good mood. Defending champion Ricky
Rudd qualified 27th; 1995 winner Dale Earnhardt was 23rd and Bill
Elliott, the only driver with four top 10 finishes here, slipped
all the way to 37th.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip, making his debut with his new Tyler Jet team,
got off to a bad start, qualifying 42nd in the Tabasco Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   On Hold
</P>
<P>
   A gold watch that was to be presented to Gordon honoring his
Driver of the Year Award was part of a shipment from Switzerland
being held in New York by U.S. Customs agents. The Chopard watch
had not arrived because other watches in the shipment had bands
made from skins of endangered species of lizards or snakes.
Gordon's watch has a leather band and should clear Customs today.
</P>
<P>
   Tight rookie race
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin takes a 22 point lead over Jerry Nadeau into today's
Brickyard, while Kevin Lepage is only 39 behind. Steve Park likely
will not be a factor, having missed most of the season with a
broken leg suffered in Atlanta in March.
</P>
<P>
   Unser return
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr. is at the Brickyard this week to participate in
today's IROC event. It's his first visit since 1994 when he won the
Indianapolis 500. He failed to make the field a year later and in
'96 the series split into two factions _ Indy Racing League and
Championship Auto Racing Teams. ``It was very special of the
Speedway to invite IROC here,'' Unser said. ``I had kind of mixed
emotions about it. I'm glad I'm here, but I wish it was in a
different kind of car.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank business
</P>
<P>
   The No. 46 SABCO team has made a couple of midseason
adjustments. The Money Store becomes the primary sponsor, First
Union the associate sponsor and Jeff Green the driver for the
remainder of the season, with the exception of next week's event at
Watkins Glen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
