<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON NAMES BOB JEFFREY AS PRESIDENT OF ITS NEW YORK OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bob Jeffrey describes himself as someone who ``loves
challenges.'' He has certainly come to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey is the new president of the flagship New York office of
J. Walter Thompson USA, part of the J. Walter Thompson unit of WPP
Group PLC. He was hired in March by Chris Jones, chief executive at
Thompson, from Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS, where he had been executive
vice president and managing director of the San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey's mission is formidable: to help Thompson New York wipe
away the tarnish put on its reputation by almost two years of
turnover in accounts, shortfalls in several high-profile reviews
and turmoil in the top executive ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong agency that needed to be kick-started back to
life,'' said Jones, who, since becoming chief executive last year,
has also changed the leadership at other offices, including those
in Chicago and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jeffrey, 45, had no experience running a big agency like
Thompson New York, which has $847 million in estimated billings and
440 employees, he is praised for his skills in the care and feeding
of large clients as well as his ability to stoke the fires of new
business.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, three months after his arrival, Thompson New York
emerged victorious in one of the biggest, most closely watched
reviews so far this year, landing the $85 million account of
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Objectively, it was great,'' Jeffrey said, ``but
psychologically it was also great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning Merrill Lynch was an important achievement that really
defines how JWT New York will go forward in a new era,'' he added.
``I really believe we're on a new track.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jeffrey, a 20-year veteran of Madison Avenue, faces
daunting difficulties in reviving Thompson New York. In an
interview last week, he acknowledged what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``JWT is a great brand name, and New York has great accounts,''
he said, ``but it needs resuscitation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told people that a year from now, I want the image of the
agency to be significantly transformed inside and outside,'' he
added. ``The existing perception is neutral to negative, that it's
a sleepy agency without a lot of excitement. I want it to be an
exciting agency doing new things, and not just creatively.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There's an amazing amount of talent'' at Thompson New York,
Jeffrey said, ``a lot of young and middle-level people who want to
transform the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just looking for the leadership to do it,'' he added.
``And one key thing is that you have to get people to communicate
with each other. I believe if you have the right leadership, the
right people and better communication, there's no reason why a New
York office can't do great work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey's remarks recall some of the problems that were said to
plague Thompson New York under his predecessor, Susan Gianinno, who
departed abruptly in October.
</P>
<P>
   There had been widespread complaints, as reported by the trade
publication Adweek, that Ms. Gianinno _ who subsequently took an
important post at the D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications
unit of MacManus Group in New York _ had not been inspiring enough
to employees because of a reluctance to delegate that discouraged
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had not been a focus on getting everyone to work as a
team,'' Jones said. ``In the end, the agency business is like team
sports. Agencies need team players, and Bob really wants to play on
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Merrill Lynch pitch was arduous and drawn out,'' he said,
``but the agency came together fantastically. And Bob had a big
part in that.''
</P>
<P>
   A question that arose when Jeffrey was hired for Thompson New
York after 18 months at Lowe _ part of the Lowe Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Cos. _ was whether an outsider could win the
confidence of longtime staff members, something he would need to
remake the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency has that old boy network reputation,'' Jeffrey
said, ``but when I started meeting people, I didn't find them
close-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on all the tsouris they experienced,'' he added, ``they
were open to new people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``I had been very public, since the time Susan went,
that I wanted to go outside for her successor. The agency was not
only prepared for it, but everyone felt it was the right thing to
do, for new blood and fresh leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, Jones observed that ``if an outsider comes in
and behaves like an outsider, he or she is likely to be treated as
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bob has amazingly impressed everyone,'' he added, ``and
has been welcomed with open arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey said that the Merrill Lynch pitch gave him a glimpse of
how well Thompson New York could perform when everyone cooperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of commitment and a lot of passion,'' Jeffrey
said, ``and I'm a big believer in the passion factor in this
business because if you don't have people aiming high, with passion
and excitement, where's the satisfaction?''
</P>
<P>
   As for what's next, Jeffrey said, he is sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, how many opportunities do you get to do
something like this?'' he asked. ``I excel in an underdog
situation; it's basically my nature. I have a lot of optimism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
