<SLUG> BC-FALCONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons counting on Dronett
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Shane Dronett likes to talk about ``getting skinny,''
but he has to come up big this season for the Atlanta Falcons, and
he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 1/2, 300-pound defensive tackle backed up starters
Travis Hall and Dan Owens last year and did a good job, with 40
tackles and four sacks. He also blocked two field goals and knocked
down five passes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the team needs more. Owens is with the Detroit Lions,
and Dronett will start at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big deal for a guy with one career start at the
position after being drafted by Denver in the second round as a
defensive end in 1992, the last year Falcons coach Dan Reeves was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest difference in being a starter is the
responsibility,'' said Dronett, who was first team All-America in
1991 as a junior at Texas before leaving school early. ``Guys are
counting on me.''
</P>
<P>
   You might recognize Dronett, who wears No. 75, from Falcons ads
showing him, Hall and end Chuck Smith trying to block a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett has seven career blocks, four short of the NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about getting skinny, which isn't easy when you're
300,'' he said. ``You're thinner when you turn sideways ... at the
line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do it as fast as you can at the snap, before (offensive
linemen) get their pads together and form a wall. You get in the
crack, drive and get your hands up. My height is a big factor
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dronett's height also has helped him knock down 21 passes in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   In his first three seasons in Denver, he had 165 tackles, 19
sacks, 15 passes deflected and four field goals blocked while
playing end. But knee surgery and a change to tackle in 1995 added
up to a poor season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta signed him as a free agent before the '96 season, but he
asked to be released five games into the season. Detroit signed him
but cut him at the end of training camp in '97. The Falcons brought
him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the preseason against us last year, he made some really
good plays at tackle,'' Reeves said. ``(Defensive line coach) Bill
(Kollar) had him before and really didn't like what he'd seen. But
I had him look at some more film ... and we felt like he was a guy
we needed to bring in.''
</P>
<P>
   When Owens didn't play against New Orleans in November, Dronett
got his only career start at tackle. He responded with six tackles,
two sacks, a blocked field goal and a deflected pass. He was player
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dronett added 10 pounds in the offseason but still has work to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to work real hard at keeping my pads down (and
staying low),'' he said. ``I've had to change my stance a lot, but
I'm starting to feel powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are counting on it. They signed Dronett to a
two-year, $1.6 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very good pickup,'' Reeves said. ``About the only
thing he needs to work on is keeping his pads down. He's got
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
