<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HAMPTONS-ART-     07-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HAMPTONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS TO ADD A LITTLE STAR POWER TO HAMPTONS WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic/map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. _ No one here begrudges President Clinton a
weekend getaway, what with that nettlesome Lewinsky matter back in
Washington. But of all places, why would he choose a Long Island
town that becomes a parking lot in the summer for people who
consider themselves plugged-in and beautiful, as well as for those
who attend to their many needs?
</P>
<P>
   Why seek shelter in a cell-phone storm?
</P>
<P>
   Harold Bennett, a retired ironworker, knew why and needed no
words to convey the answer. Inside the Amagansett American Legion
hall, perhaps the last redoubt for native sons and daughters _ who
call themselves ``bubbies'' and just about everyone else
``carpetbaggers'' _ he raised a hand stained with paint and rubbed
forefinger and thumb together in a universal gesture that means
money.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is where cottages rent for $10,000 a month,
where a 15-ounce box of Cheerios costs $5, where year-round
residents swap stories about being cut off by stretch limousines.
This is where the entertainment executives from Los Angeles, the
Wall Street titans from New York and millionaires from just about
everywhere else come to play and preen.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his presidential entourage are expected to descend
upon East Hampton early Friday afternoon and leave sometime Sunday
afternoon. In the span of those 50-odd hours, he is scheduled to
attend three fund-raising events: a $25,000-a-couple soiree on
Friday night, a $5,000-a-person luncheon on Saturday afternoon and
a more proletarian gathering on the expansive lawn at the home of
Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger, for which tickets start at $250.
When Air Force One departs this easternmost spit of New York State,
the Democratic National Committee will be some $2 million richer.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to East Hampton is not so easily measured. Some welcome
Clinton, crowing that it will be the first time this century that a
sitting president has visited the island's South Fork; others sniff
that he is just another celebrity, whose sole contribution to the
community will be adding some Secret Service sedans to the traffic
nightmare that is Route 27.
</P>
<P>
   The debate plays out in microcosm at the American Legion bar,
where people address concerns about endangered species with bumper
stickers on their cars that say, ``Piping Plover Tastes Like
Chicken.'' With suspenders stretched over a T-shirt stained with
sweat, Harold Bennett may not dress like Alec Baldwin, but he is a
proud Democrat _ so proud, in fact, that he will be among the
volunteers working to make the Baldwin-Basinger event a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, he's my president and I'm happy to see him here,''
Bennett said. ``All we're gonna do is make him welcome. And they're
gonna raise a ton of money.''
</P>
<P>
   His drinking partner and childhood friend, Joe Holmes,
courteously removed a toothpick from his mouth to speak. A
disaffected Democrat now running for local office on the
Independent Party ticket, he muttered that he would like to take
Clinton out on his clam boat with him. ``Make a man of him,'' he
said. Holmes noted that it took him 27 years to earn $30,000 as a
mailman. The idea of spending $25,000 on anything, much less a
one-night date with the upper crust, left him speechless _ almost:
``It's all for the bucks, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   While Holmes rakes the harbor bed for littleneck clams,
politicians traditionally rake the East Hampton summer scene in
another way. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., was out
here last weekend for a fund-raising event, and New York's GOP Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato might as well be an honorary resident.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, not only has he hit the fund-raising
trifecta, but he is also said to be staying at a fortress of an
estate owned by filmmaker Stephen Spielberg. The neighbors this
week are complaining about helicopters, not mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Puff Daddy,'' said Judith Hope, state Democratic
chairwoman and full-time East Hampton resident, by way of Arkansas.
``This is not movie stars or show people descending on the East End
this weekend. This is the commander in chief. Maybe some cynical
New Yorkers scoff at that. But to a lot of local East Enders, it's
a privilege and an honor to have the president in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hope, who was once the town supervisor for East Hampton,
said that she had been overwhelmed by requests for the
Baldwin-Basinger affair and by an outpouring of support from local
residents. ``There are some very touching stories,'' she added.
``Senior citizens have gone to the bank with their passbooks and
drawn $250 to buy a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Down at the East Hampton Senior Citizens Center on Fireplace
Road, none of the staff members could think of anyone who had
bought a ticket to any of the Clinton functions. They pondered the
very idea as they cleaned up after the day's lunch of breaded fish,
vegetables and oatmeal cookies. ``I wouldn't pay to see any
celebrity,'' said Ida Smith, the office assistant, pausing for a
moment from the task of rolling quarters. ``Plus, the traffic here
is horrible to begin with, and he'll be the only one able to get on
the road and move around.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ann Mack, the office assistant, argued that the presidential
moment was worth some inconvenience. ``If I could afford the $250,
I would go,'' she said. ``It's going to be a historic event for
East Hampton and when I look back, I could say I saw the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Jack Rudin, a retired schoolteacher and a Democrat,
walked in. He cited recent developments in Washington _
particularly Monica S. Lewinsky's decision to cooperate with
prosecutors investigating the president _ as evidence that Clinton
had demeaned the office and therefore was not worth a moment of
anyone's free time or a penny of anyone's savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind his visit so much if he was coming here to
better the community,'' Rudin said. ``But to destroy a town for
partisan purposes? That's the only reason he's coming here: to
raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton will do anything presidential _ between raising
money and playing a round or two of golf _ was of as much interest
as the effect his visit will have on traffic. Some people hope,
even expect, that he or his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, will
appear at one of the apolitical fund-raising events taking place
around town.
</P>
<P>
   In his fantasy, said Rossetti Perchik, an architect who runs the
annual sand castle contest to benefit community projects, the
president stops by to add his support; in reality, he said, one of
his judges dropped out to attend a Clinton fund-raiser. Richard
Rosenthal, who runs the town's disabilities office, has invited the
president to a $6-a-plate dinner at Whalebone Village, a subsidized
housing complex; although it conflicts with the Baldwin-Basinger
party, Rosenthal said, ``I'd expect him to find an hour or two to
be the president for all of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dawn Zimmerman, the director of the Child Development
Center, a school for disabled children, extended an invitation to
the president and the first lady for a fund-raiser on Sunday
afternoon. So far, she said, the invitation has not been accepted
or declined. But a few days ago a man from Washington _ she was not
sure whether he was from the White House _ visited the school. ``He
came to check it out, and actually had a good time with the kids,''
she said. ``But he didn't say much.''
</P>
<P>
   That air of mystery, created by a continuing vacuum of
information about the president's visit, has also brought some
giddiness and sense of the historic to a town that takes pride in
its egalitarian distribution of parking tickets to Porsches and
pickups alike.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy DeSanti, the owner of Dreesen's Market, plans to serve 750
doughnuts _ cinnamon, powdered sugar and plain _ at the
Baldwin-Basinger gathering. And for this contribution he and two
helpers had to undergo a Secret Service background check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do our job and leave,'' he said, sounding almost
patriotic.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bennett of the American Legion is looking forward to the
Saturday night event. Tonight he and dozens of other volunteers
were to gather under the billowing white tent on the
Baldwin-Basinger estate to be given their assignments. But there's
only so far a ``bub'' will go for a ``carpetbagger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't cuttin' no grass,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
