<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUMAURIER-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING SHOOTS 8-UNDER-PAR 64, LEADS DU MAURIER CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ Betsy King joined the LPGA Tour in 1977, the
year that Se Ri Pak was born.
</P>
<P>
   More than two decades later, King is still on the tour,
competing against Pak, Annika Sorenstam, Karrie Webb and other
young stars. The future may belong to the talented 20-something
set. But Thursday's best round in the du Maurier Classic _ one of
the tour's majors _ belonged to King.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting an 8-under-par 64, and finishing with back-to-back
birdies, King held a 1-stroke lead over Meg Mallon and Wendy Doolan
after the first round at Essex Golf and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who is trying to win her third consecutive major as a
20-year-old rookie, shot a 69 to remain within striking distance,
tied with 19 others for 30th place, 5 strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tammie Green, Lisa Hackney, Chris Johnson, Emilee Klein and
Dottie Pepper were in a five-way tie for fourth place, at 66.
</P>
<P>
   For King, who will turn 43 next month, Thursday's round was
another statement that she remains a formidable player. Taking
advantage of favorable conditions _ virtually no wind, coupled with
overcast skies that kept the greens soft _ King put together a
machinelike round, hitting every green in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   King had eight birdies without a bogey, and she ended the day in
style, with birdies on Nos. 17 and 18. Can King keep it up? She was
eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely the best round I've played this year,'' said
King, whose most recent victory was in last year's Nabisco Dinah
Shore. ``I got off to a good start, and for me that's really key.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When King lists her accomplishments in golf, the resume is
impressive. She is a member of the LPGA Hall of Fame. She has won
31 tournaments. And she has won six majors, including two U.S.
Women's Open championships.
</P>
<P>
   But King has never won the du Maurier, the only women's major
that has eluded her. That will motivate King this week, and she is
also trying to secure a spot on the U.S. Solheim Cup team that will
compete against Europe in September.
</P>
<P>
   As the LPGA's all-time leading money winner, with more than $6
million, King has the financial security to retire whenever she
wishes. However, quitting is something she rarely thinks about. She
still hits 245-yard drives, her short game has actually improved
over the past five years and Thursday she made four birdie putts of
15 feet or longer, including 20-footers on No. 17 and No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stay out here as long as I can,'' she said. ``The
money keeps getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   While King breezed through her round, Pak struggled early,
standing at 1 over par through six holes. However, a 13-foot putt
for a birdie on No. 7 changed the momentum in Pak's favor. Then she
took advantage of her length at the par-5, 450-yard No. 9, reaching
the green in two shots, then two-putting from 25 feet for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 10, Pak birdied again, hitting a 3-iron approach shot to
within three feet of the cup. Pak's final birdie came at the par 5,
490-yard No. 14, when she reached the green in two shots again,
then two-putted from 25 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Pak was pleased with her position, although she felt
some pain in her left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK, a little sore, just from playing golf and
practicing,'' said Pak, who was followed throughout her round by at
least 15 photographers from her native South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``My driving and my irons weren't that sharp, so at 3 under par
I'm happy. I'm surprised to see such low scores, but everything is
perfect _ good greens, good conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pak-Sorenstam-Webb threesome drew the largest gallery of the
day, around 1,000 people at its peak. Sorenstam won their personal
battle, shooting a 4-under-par 68, while Webb shot a 69 to tie Pak.
</P>
<P>
   There were a number of Koreans in Pak's gallery, urging her on,
and she appreciated the support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised, because the Korean economy is not that
good,'' Pak said. ``But they want to come see me. It makes me want
to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   The fever surrounding Pak reminded King of the enthusiasm
generated by Nancy Lopez in 1978, when she won five consecutive
tournaments and attracted many more fans to women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Se Ri is bringing more attention than Nancy did,''
King said. ``Se Ri has worked hard to learn English and endear
herself. I see great things in the future for Se Ri and the LPGA.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, nobody was better than King. She has come close to
winning the du Maurier before, losing to Brandie Burton in 1993 on
the first hole of a sudden-death playoff in London, Ontario. This
time, she hoped for a different outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, at 42, still able to compete, so yes, I feel
good,'' King said. ``You don't get tired of winning. I'm going to
give it my best shot.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
