<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-AZR &LR;      07-30 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WANT ANSWERS ABOUT DEATHS, NEAR ABORTION OF FULL-TERM
BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A select committee of lawmakers will meet next month
to ask Arizona state regulators to explain the bleeding deaths of
two women and the near abortion of a full-term baby at a Phoenix
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   A-Z Women's Center was apparently able to operate unlicensed
because state law requires no license for clinics owned by doctors
who neither keep patients overnight nor administer general
anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to discipline the clinic after the first woman
bled to death in 1995 might indicate that state laws are inadequate
or not enforced, said House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly are some questions about what the Board of
Medical Examiners has been doing,'' he said, ``and what the Arizona
Department of Health Services has been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The board, which regulates doctors, has suspended the license of
Dr. John Biskind, the doctor involved in the three incidents. But
Brad Christensen, spokesman for the state Health Department, said
state law exempts the clinic from licensing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exemptions from licensure are drawn up by the Legislature,''
Christensen said. He added that the department does license more
than 500 outpatient centers that treat everything from arthritis to
heart trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost said he will be co-chairman of the 10-member committee.
The speaker and the other co-chairman, Sen. David Petersen, R-Mesa,
are foes of abortion. But Groscost said patient safety will be the
focus and that political views on a woman's right to choose will be
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Miller, executive director of Arizona Right to Choose, was
not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exploitation of an unfortunate medical situation,''
Miller said. ``The problem is really the Board of Medical
Examiners. The speaker, the Senate president and the governor could
have fixed this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Miller predicted that a committee dominated by abortion
opponents will embark on a ``thinly veiled attempt to chip away at
a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Members opposed to abortion are Reps. Marilyn Jarrett, R-Mesa;
Linda Aguirre, D-southwest Phoenix; and Sens. Ed Cirillo, R-Sun
City West; and Mary Hartley, D-west Phoenix. Those who support
abortion rights are Sens. Ann Day, R-Tucson; and Victor Soltero,
D-Tucson; and Reps. Susan Gerard, R-central Phoenix; and Debora
Norris, D-Sells.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost acknowledged that media coverage of the incidents at
A-Z Women's Center prompted the legislative probe. And he said he
expected legislators to propose abortion limits outside the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Groscost and Senate President Brenda Burns insisted that the
panel would hold hearings only on regulation of outpatient clinic
staff and operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're pro-life or pro-choice,'' Groscost
said. ``It's abhorrent that you've had two ladies die in that
clinic. We are going to hold agencies accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Howard, president of Planned Parenthood of Central and
Northern Arizona, said he would accept Groscost's word that the
legislative inquiry is aimed at clinic operations and not abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' Howard said, ``the Arizona Legislature for the past
two sessions has been fertile ground for anti-choice initiatives.
We're watching carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to hold at least two hearings
beginning next month, dates to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   The June 30 abortion procedure that turned into a delivery and
the April bleeding death of LouAnne Heron, 33, are under
investigation by a Maricopa County grand jury. &QL; 
Mike McCloy can be reached at 444-8111 or at mike.mccloy(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
