</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WELFARE-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REFORMING WELFARE WITH EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 31:
</P>
<P>
   An important amendment approved by the Senate to the bill
reauthorizing the Higher Education Act would give states the option
of allowing welfare recipients to enroll in postsecondary education
or vocational training for two years without losing their welfare
benefits. The provision, sponsored by Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.,
should be retained in the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing welfare recipients the opportunity to gain real skills
is the most promising approach to getting families off welfare.
Recipients who have more education are more likely to find
higher-paying jobs that offer economic self-sufficiency. But
current law allows education or vocational training to count as a
work activity for only 12 months, after which the student must work
20 hours a week to continue getting benefits. For many recipients,
that requirement means dropping out of school.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-month limit is particularly constraining for people who
need English-language classes in addition to vocational courses.
Even among English-speakers the need for more education is
substantial. Some 40 percent of all recipients lack a high school
diploma. More than 60 percent of those who have been on welfare for
five years or more have no diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The education gap may also be contributing to racial shifts in
the welfare population. As recently reported in The New York Times,
blacks and Hispanics are less likely than whites to have a high
school diploma and the skills to find a job. That fact is one
reason minorities are having a harder time leaving welfare than
whites.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare law is too tilted toward short-term work activity,
allowing little attention to skills development. The current law
also sets a cap on the percentage of the welfare population that
can be enrolled in educational or vocational training at any one
time. By 2000, all teen-age parents pursuing high school diplomas
would be counted under the educational cap, thus reducing the
number of adults who can enroll in training and still receive
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Wellstone amendment would prevent teen-age parents from
being counted in the educational cap. Republicans are resisting
these sensible changes, fearing they amount to backsliding on
welfare reform. On the contrary, letting states encourage education
is the best investment the nation can make toward a long-term
welfare solution. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
