<SLUG> BC-STOCK-MANIPULATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKER RUNS AFOUL OF SEC IN SHARE MANIPULATION CASEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas)   (af)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rafi M. Khan, a stock promoter, was accused by federal
regulators Thursday of manipulating the shares of two companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles, the
Securities and Exchange Commission accused Khan, 47, a stock broker
and promoter, of using a variety of schemes to manipulate the
shares of the two little-known companies in an effort to drive up
the prices of those shares and reap huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   While Khan had been accused in several lawsuits of being
involved in stock manipulation in the early 1990s, Thursday's
complaint is the first time that federal regulators have accused
Khan of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a guy who has been reputed in the past to have been
involved in questionable activities and here are two cases where we
have good evidence he manipulated two stocks,'' Ronald E. Wood, an
assistant regional director at the SEC office in Los Angeles, said
Thursday. ``He used multiple schemes to get the price of those
stocks up.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is seeking to have Khan repay $552,500 in illegal
profits, along with other fines and penalties. The commission also
charged Timothy Tyrrell, who regulators say acted as a trader for
Khan at Reynolds Kendricks &AMP; Stratton in Beverly Hills, Calif.,
whose parent company is now J.B. Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   The commission contends that Tyrrell co-conspired in
manipulating the shares of the two companies. The commission is
seeking to have Tyrrell repay $224,800 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to Khan's lawyer, Bernard L. Burton in Melville,
N.Y., were not returned. Efforts to reach Tyrrell, whose home
telephone number is unlisted, were also unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Khan and Tyrrell are accused by regulators of manipulating the
shares of Future Communications Inc., a cable television
programming company in Dallas that went bankrupt in 1993, and the
shares of the L.L. Knickerbocker Co. in California, which sells
collectible dolls and teddy bears that have been endorsed by
celebrities like Marie Osmond and Annette Funicello.
</P>
<P>
   The manipulations, regulators said, resulted in huge runups and
then great falls. Shares of Future rose from $6.50 to $27.25 on the
Nasdaq stock market in a two-month period before collapsing in
1993. And in just over a month in 1995, shares of Knickerbocker
climbed from $6 to $52 on the Nasdaq market before plummeting,
according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Khan, the commission said, orchestrated an elaborate scheme to
drive up the prices of those two stocks, including buying up a
substantial share of the available stock, restricting access to the
stock, ``parking stock'' in the names of fictitious accounts and
creating demand for the stock by ``making misleading statements and
touting wildly exaggerated earnings projections.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Khan was also accused of promoting the stock of
Future on the expectations of growing viewership of Billy Bob's
Country Countdown, a one-hour music television show, and MSTV, a
cable network, even though he knew, according to regulators, that
the owners of those two outlets had said they were not affiliated
with Future Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Khan earlier made headlines in 1993, when he became embroiled in
a nasty proxy battle with Milan Panic, the former prime minister of
Yugoslavia and chairman of ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc. in Costa Mesa,
Calif., and eight other board members over control of the company.
ICN and Khan have been locked in a legal battle over whether Khan
used insider information to try to gain control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a federal judge blocked Khan's proxy fight and
suggested Khan may have perjured himself in sworn testimony. In
ordering an injunction, The judge, John Sprizzo of the federal
district court in Manhattan, said that he would ask federal
prosecutors to investigate Khan.
</P>
<P>
   Sprizzo said that Khan had concealed information about his past,
which included an investigation by British authorities into Khan's
involvement in British Gas, the subject of another securities fraud
case.
</P>
<P>
   Khan, whom some investors and portfolio managers considered a
stock wizard, managed to convince mutual fund companies like
Fidelity Investments and the Invesco Fund Group to buy into his
stock picks in the early 1990s. Invesco, for example, bought a
large stake in ICN Pharmaceuticals in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Khan, a former stock broker for Reynolds Kendrick Stratton (with
Tyrrell) and later at Shamrock Partners, was also sued in the early
1990s by investors who accused him of manipulating the stock of
Future Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
