</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVAN'S `SECRET' FORMULA WINS BRICKYARD POLE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It's no secret that Ernie Irvan has found the
fast lane around the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. But don't expect
Irvan to divulge the magic setup that for the past two summers has
produced record-setting pole runs for the Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a secret, I wouldn't tell you. And I don't think I
do,'' said Irvan, who earned the No. 1 qualifying spot for
Saturday's NASCAR Winston Cup race with a hot lap at 179.394 mph
yesterday evening. ``It just goes to show you I get around the Indy
racetrack fairly good. You can't do it without an awesome car and
an awesome lap. You have to put 100 percent dedication to get your
line perfect, and have a car capable of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   And under unsettled weather conditions like yesterday's, it also
helps to get out first and get it over with. Qualifying to lock in
the first 25 of 43 available positions was scheduled to begin at
1:30 p.m. But a rainstorm delayed the start until 5:14, when Irvan
was first out on a green track _ one devoid of rubber laid down
during two days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going first might have set the precedent to run that fast,''
said Irvan, a former Daytona 500 champion who is in his first
season of driving the No. 36 Skittles Pontiac Grand Prix for Read
Morton. ``A lot of times when the racetrack is green, that's when
it sticks the best. Our car seemed to handle perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Irvan toured the 2.5-mile IMS layout at a stock car
record of 50.637 seconds/177.736 mph in the No. 28 Texaco Havoline
Ford Thunderbird.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Irvan clipped off a lap in 50.169 seconds/179.394 mph
to claim his first Bud Pole with crew chief Ryan Pemberton. The
pole _ a first for Pontiac at this event _ was the 20th of Irvan's
Cup career in 281 starts and made him the second driver to win two
series poles at IMS. Reigning Cup champion Jeff Gordon, winner of
the inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994, started from the pole in 1995
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, it was Gordon who had the last shot at knocking Irvan
off the point.
</P>
<P>
   The 47th of 50 cars to make a qualifying attempt, Gordon ran off
a lap at 178.324 mph that placed the No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Refinishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo third and inside on the two-car
second row.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan was joined in the front row by Dale Jarrett, the 1996
race-winner and Irvan's former Robert Yates Racing teammate.
Jarrett, who beat Irvan to the finish line after a no-team-orders
brawl here in 1996, lapped yesterday at 178.596 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an incredible lap Ernie put up there, especially
being the first car out,'' said Jarrett, driver of the No. 88
Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``But we've got a good
race car and I was happy to get that in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's No. 2 start is a career-best at IMS, topping his
third-place effort in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing the pole, Gordon now has qualified on the front
row in nine of the past 10 races this season _ and won two of the
last three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to see 1994 again,'' said Gordon, who has a
62-point lead on Mark Martin after 18 of 33 races. ``We qualified
third (that year) and had one of the fastest cars in practice. We
qualified third here today. I hope we get the same results on
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kenny Irwin Jr. _ who was introduced as Irvan's
replacement here one year ago _ nailed the No. 4 qualifying slot at
178.260 mph in the No. 28 Taurus. He and fifth-place qualifier Jeff
Green, introduced yesterday as the newest full-time driver of the
newly responsored No. 46 The Money Store Chevy,
</P>
<P>
   were the last drivers to break Irvan's former qualifying record.
Green ran 177.915 mph, and will be joined in Row 3 by Gordon's
Hendrick Motorsports teammate, Ricky Craven, at 177.701 mph in the
No. 50 Bud Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Among those failing to qualify was defending race-winner Ricky
Rudd, who stood 27th at 175.750 mph in the No. 10 Tide Taurus. He
was trailed by seven-time Cup champion and Daytona 500 winner Dale
Earnhardt at 175.668 mph in the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus
Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-first-round qualifiers were separated by 1.027 seconds.
Second-round qualifying is scheduled for this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
