<HEADLINE>
HARRIED MARKETSPAN CHAIRMAN IS SAID TO PLAN RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Amid mounting pressure from stockholders,
public officials and board members, the embattled chairman of the
newly formed Marketspan energy company, Dr. William Catacosinos, is
negotiating the terms of his resignation, company officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking official with close ties Catacosinos said the
chairman's resignation could be announced as early as Friday, when
the company's board meets in Manhattan to discuss, among other
things, the controversy over Catacosinos' compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos' resignation would end a brief but stormy reign at
the company that was formed in part from the remnants of Long
Island Lighting Co., which Catacosinos had led since 1984. In
recent weeks, he has been harshly criticized over the $42 million
in severance that the LILCO awarded him as its chairman just before
he took over his new post at Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's public relations office declined to comment on
Catacosinos' fate except to say that any decisions would be made by
a three-member committee that the directors designated to review
the situation with the advice of an outside law firm, Simpson
Thacher &AMP; Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   But one company official said he thought it unlikely that there
would be another large severance package for Catacosinos. All the
top officials at Marketspan are working without contracts, and his
guarantees for severance payments came from his previous LILCO
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations for Catacosinos' resignation have lasted several
days, company officials said. An agreement was nearly reached, but
Catacosinos backed away, according to those same officials. But
now, they say, a deal is close at hand.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The resignation preparations came amid a crisis atmosphere on
the eve of Friday's crucial board meeting. The meeting's location
was switched at the last minute from the company's Long Island
headquarters to Simpson Thacher's office in Manhattan. The
directors face a struggle for control of the company and demands
from Gov. George Pataki for Catacosinos' ouster.
</P>
<P>
   As rumors swirled about Catacosinos' departure, his supporters
on Wall Street complained of political interference with the
company. One leading investor demanded a special meeting of
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan was formed barely two months ago when the Brooklyn
Union Gas group merged with what was left of LILCO after New York
state bought most of LILCO's electricity service amid fanfare and
high hopes. But the ensuing dispute over Catacosinos' severance,
plus $25 million paid to 25 other LILCO executives, rapidly
escalated into full-blown corporate warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who engineered the state takeover of LILCO's electricity
service to enable a 20 percent cut in Long Island's electricity
rates, had accused Catacosinos of ``a secret act of greed'' and
charged that the payments violated state agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos' departure would be a big coup for the governor, who
is running for re-election. He could claim credit for reducing
electric bills and getting rid of both LILCO and Catacosinos, a
lightning rod for public resentment when Long Islanders were paying
the highest rates in the continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that Mr. Catacosinos must resign, and the
sooner he does, the better off Marketspan is, the better off LIPA
is and the better off Long Island is,'' said Richard Kessel, the
governor's appointee as chairman of the Long Island Power
Authority, the state agency that took over LILCO's electricity
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians have also been clamoring for Catacosinos'
removal, some specifying that they wanted Robert Catell, formerly
Brooklyn Union's chairman and now Marketspan's president, to
succeed Catacosinos as chairman, or one of their own members or
someone else from the outside. Since Catacosinos served as both
chairman and chief executive, the board could also split his titles
between two people.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is control of Marketspan's board and management, the
fate of its highest executives, its mission and strategy _ even its
existence, according to company officials and industry analysts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
