<SLUG> BC-PEARSON-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARSON FACES NEW SCRUTINY IN ITS SIMON &AMP; SCHUSTER BID
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British media group Pearson PLC is facing a new round of
scrutiny from U.S. antitrust regulators in its bid to become the
world's biggest educational publisher with the purchase of most of
Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, the Justice Department extended its examination
of the competitive impact of Pearson's purchase of Simon &AMP;
Schuster's educational, professional and reference publishing
business from Viacom Inc. But a Pearson spokesman in London said
Thursday that this phase _ known as a second request review _ was
not unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought there would be a second request,'' the
Pearson spokesman said. ``Back in May, we said that we expected to
complete this transaction in the second half of 1998, basically by
the end of this year. And we have no reason to revise that view.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson agreed in May to buy Simon &AMP; Schuster's operations for
$4.6 billion, striking a revised deal to sell the reference unit to
the American buyout firm Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst for $860
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, the Justice Department's regulators have
demanded additional information from a handful of other publishers
specializing in the science, medical and legal fields. In those
cases, the reviews did not prevent the mergers. It remains rare,
however, for companies to face this more intensive review. Last
year, more than 3,700 companies filed notices in connection with
mergers, but of those only 120 were subjected to the second level
of review.
</P>
<P>
   Gina Talamona, a spokeswoman for the Justice Department,
confirmed that a review was taking place, but declined to comment
about any other aspect of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson declined to disclose what information the Justice
Department is seeking, although a person who has been briefed on
the review said regulators were examining the merger's impact on
the diversity of textbooks for students in the kindergarten through
high school market and the potential concentration in the college
market in textbooks for chemistry, biology, math and physics.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Authors Guild, which unsuccessfully
challenged Bertelsmann's merger with Random House, said that it
approached the Justice Department last week with an offer to
provide information about potential concentrations in the
educational market.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our concerns _ which parents and educators should share
_ is that eliminating competition in textbook publishing could lead
to higher costs, less diversity of opinion and a lower incentive to
improve texts,'' said Paul Aiken, executive director of the guild,
which represents published authors.
</P>
<P>
   Aiken said that Pearson might have expected the new level of
review, but ``one may go to the dentist expecting a root canal and
that doesn't make it any more pleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a company enters the second phase, the investigative
process could take from four weeks to eight months, according to a
Washington lawyer specializing in antitrust matters. The lawyer
said that federal regulators had tended to demand more narrow
information from publishers about competing titles.
</P>
<P>
   At Simon &AMP; Schuster last week, employees received a reassuring
newsletter that described the additional review and predicted a
merger in the fall, noting that typically companies ``find a
mutually acceptable way to address the regulator's concerns in a
way that allows the transaction to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Greco, associate professor at the business school at
Fordham University, said the new round of examination was
significant for Pearson because it could raise the prospect of
reshaping the merged companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would anticipate some problems,'' said Greco, who has
studied publishing industry consolidation. ``To wrap it up, they
may have to consider divesting some properties. And someone in
Washington might say you have to get rid of certain titles, certain
imprints.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
