<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FERRARO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO PLAYS THE GENDER CARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Asserting that Congress has suffered because of the
scarcity of women in its ranks, Geraldine Ferraro said Thursday
that she should be elected to the Senate because she could, as a
woman, bring a perspective to a variety of issues, from child care
to the economy, that her male competitors could not match.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro played what her advisers believe may be her strongest
political card _ she is the only woman in the New York Senate race
_ as she spoke in Manhattan to an audience of women who own
businesses. She described herself as ``a woman with a national
profile'' who would bring ``a kind of suasion without parallel'' to
the male-dominated world of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, a Democrat, said there was a ``need for women in
leadership positions'' because ``we bring another dimension to the
political process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roles as caretakers, nurturers and mothers cannot help but
give us a different perspective,'' she said, looking straight into
the camera and blinding lights that her campaign had set up to tape
the speech for use in a television advertisement. ``It's not
necessarily better. But it is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said that she was not ``putting down men'' in making
what was a notably undisguised appeal for votes based on sex. But
she approvingly cited Carol Gilligan, a psychologist from Harvard
University, in describing characteristics that Ferraro said were
particular to women and in short supply in the government today.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to Dr. Gilligan, instead of engaging in
confrontation, women are more apt to negotiate,'' Ferraro said.
``Instead of looking at short-term solutions to problems, women are
more apt to think in terms of generations to come. Instead of
thinking in win-lose terms, women are more apt to see the gray
areas in between.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Ferraro seemed to put at least a temporary end to
what has been a fallow period in her campaign. The presence of the
camera crew at her speech, along with the fact that her aides
encouraged coverage of it, suggested that Ferraro will try to do
what a number of women running for office have tried to do without
success in New York over the last decade: turn their identities as
women to their political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, a former candidate for vice president, is facing two
men in the Democratic primary who are seeking to challenge Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, a Republican, this fall: Mark Green, the public
advocate for New York City, and Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal to the women's vote has been a constant if, until
Thursday, subliminal theme in all the statewide races this year.
Female voters are certain to be critical to the outcome of the
Sept. 15 primaries and the general election in November. There are
also women running in the Democratic primaries for governor,
attorney general and lieutenant governor. And candidates from both
parties have been paying particular attention to the kind of issues
_ like day care and health care _ that polls indicate are of
particular concern to women.
</P>
<P>
   What was unusual about Ferraro was the directness of her appeal,
which she made in a breakfast speech to about two dozen members of
the National Association of Women Business Owners. Later in the
day, both Green and Schumer questioned her remarks, each contending
that his positions and record were more significant than his sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing for a candidate to run based largely on
appeals to gender, ethnicity or religion,'' Green said by telephone
from Buffalo, where he was campaigning. ``My grandma said I was a
nice Jewish boy, but I wouldn't dream of seeking voters purely, or
largely, on that basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer pointed to legislation he has sponsored in Congress that
is of particular interest to women, like allowing abortion clinics
to sue protesters who block their buildings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
