<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TILLINGHAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES TILLINGHAST, 87, TWA CHAIRMAN, BROWN CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., R.I., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles C. Tillinghast Jr., a lawyer, businessman and investment
banker, who was chairman of Trans World Airlines and a former
chancellor of Brown University, died July 25 at his summer home in
Little Compton, R.I. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   He died of heart disease, a spokesman for the family said.
</P>
<P>
   Tillinghast, who built his career as a law partner at the New
York firm of Hughes, Hubbard, Blair &AMP; Reed, went on to play a
leading role in a handful of America's best-known companies,
including Bendix Corp., TWA and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   As TWA's chairman, Tillinghast steered the airline through
considerable turbulence, including the oil crisis of 1973-74,
winning credit for saving the airline from a disastrous combination
of fast-rising fuel prices and falling ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the late Charles C. and Adelaide Shaw Tillinghast,
Charles Carpenter Tillinghast Jr. was born in Saxtons River, Vt.,
on Jan. 30, 1911. He attended the Horace Mann School in Riverdale,
where his father was headmaster and from which he graduated in
1928. Four years later, Tillinghast graduated from Brown
University, where he played center on the football team.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Columbia Law School in 1935, he spent
three years as a Wall Street lawyer, and then worked for two years
for the Manhattan district attorney at the time, Thomas E. Dewey,
before returning to Hughes, Hubbard, Blair &AMP; Reed. He became a
partner in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Tillinghast's law practice provided the foundation for a
substantial business career. In 1957, he was appointed vice
president and a director of Bendix Corp., the Detroit auto parts
company that would eventually become part of the Allied Signal
Corp. Four years later, he was named president and chief executive
of TWA, later becoming chairman. His management during a period of
falling demand for air travel brought Tillinghast praise and the
public eye, and his picture appeared on the cover of Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from TWA in 1976, he became vice chairman of
White, Weld &AMP; Company, an investment banker that was acquired by
Merrill Lynch in 1978. The acquisition led to Tillinghast's
becoming a vice chairman of Merrill Lynch, a post he held until his
retirement in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Tillinghast became a trustee of Brown University in 1954, and
its 15th chancellor in 1967. Brown awarded him an honorary degree
in 1967 and the Susan Colver Rosenberger Medal in 1982. In the last
two years, two professorships were established there in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Tillinghast is survived by his wife, Lisette Micoleau
Tillinghast; a son, Charles C. Tillinghast 3d of La Jolla, Calif.;
three daughters, Elizabeth Nadeau of Rochester, Jane Roberts of
Stowe, Vt., and Anne Tillinghast of Providence, R.I.; two brothers,
John A. Tillinghast of Exeter, N.H., and David R. Tillinghast of
New York City; 12 grandchildren, and 11 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
