<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WORLDS-HNS &LR;      07-30 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WORLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lithuania 
gets past 
U.S. team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATHENS, Greece _ In case they were getting full of themselves,
these young Americans who want to rule the basketball world found
out the hard way Thursday that reputation won't get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Any strut the Americans had is gone after Lithuania outplayed
them, survived an impressive U.S. rally topped by a missed
3-pointer at the buzzer, and won 84-82 at Peace and Friendship
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Lithuanians rolled up a 16-point lead with former Seton Hall
standout Arturas Karnisovas throwing in 29 points. But the United
States stormed back with a barrage of 3-pointers and would have
pulled out an unlikely, probably undeserved win if Jimmy Oliver's
open-look 28-footer at the buzzer had not been a fraction of an
inch long, careening off the back rim, then the front rim and
bouncing out of the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the United States to 1-1 in the opening round
of the FIBA World Championship of Basketball. It was the first loss
by a U.S. men's international team since the semifinals in the 1990
World Championship. Since then, the United States had won 26
consecutive games with NBA players leading each team in the
Olympics (1992 and '96) and the World Championship ('94).
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we weren't invincible,'' said David Wood, who had a
key 3-pointer during the comeback. ``After Italy (in an exhibition)
and Brazil (in the tournament opener) played us close in the first
halves of those games, we knew that. It was pretty high intensity
when we were getting our rears kicked in the first half. It was
like, `What's going on here?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird feeling having a United States jersey on and not
be winning by 40 points. But they played very well in the first
half, and we made an excellent comeback. We made a lot of clutch
shots. We just came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point in this tournament, the Americans expected to be
in a do-or-die situation. They just didn't expect it to come this
quickly. If the wrong scenario pops up today, they could be one of
only four teams that do not qualify for the second round.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. team can't beat South Korea, and if Brazil were to
beat Lithuania, the Americans would finish last in Group C and be
left to fight it out with the last-place finishers of the other
three groups for 13th place in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Lithuania beat South Korea by 41 points, so the U.S. team will
be favored. Still, it's never fun to be in a must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday, Rudy Tomjanovich's team has nobody to blame but
itself for being in a tough situation in the first round. And its
defense disappeared long enough in the first half to give Lithuania
an insurmountable head start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was a very disappointing game for us,''
Tomjanovich said. ``They really dictated the tempo. They had us
backpedaling from the start. To their credit, they made some real
big plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some big plays also, but I thought it was amazing the
way the game was going that we had a chance to win the game at the
buzzer. I'll put my money on Jimmy Oliver to make that shot every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had fallen behind by a double-digit margin because
their defense was outsmarted by the Lithuanians. The U.S. defense
was horrible in the opening 20 minutes. Lithuania shot 54 percent
in the half but went 11-for-12 in a stretch when it turned a 10-7
deficit into a 34-20 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not playing good defense early,'' Tomjanovich said.
``They were just running by us.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trailed by 12 with seven minutes to play but scored on
seven consecutive possessions, the last on Wood's 3-pointer with
3:54 to go, to pull within 76-73.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and Michael Hawkins hit 3-pointers as the U.S. kept up
the pressure. Down just 83-81 after Oliver's trey with 13 seconds
left, the Americans fouled Karnisovas, who made just the second of
two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Needing a 3-pointer to tie, the U.S. instead was sent to the
free-throw line as Hawkins was fouled with 2.5 seconds left. He
made the first, then intentionally missed the second and the ball
was batted out of bounds by the Lithuanians with 0.5 seconds
showing.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough time to catch and shoot, which is what Oliver does
best. He popped out and was wide-open, but the shot refused to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the circumstances, I think I had a great look at
the basket,'' Oliver said. ``It just rattled in and came out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was surprising Oliver ended up alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally screwed up their assignments,'' Wood said. ``It
was an unbelievable screwup on their part. It was a gift, an
unbelievable gift that we didn't quite receive. What a great win
that would have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will be chalked up as a wake-up call for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should affect us, and I want it to affect us _ in a
very positive way,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I told our team when we
started in Chicago that we had to become better as we get
experience. We have to learn from lessons like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I told our guys (after the game) was that the test of a
good team, a real team, is how you handle disappointments and
obstacles. We felt that it was going to be a tough tournament all
along. I feel like we did a pretty good job of letting this team
know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Miller, who led the United States with seven rebounds, said
the team lacked the confidence it displayed in the opening blowout
of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come with that attitude, and I don't think we
showed that attitude on the court,'' Miller said. ``We just kind of
showed up with the reputation. We started out a little sluggish.
You get down so much, and it's not the points, it's that the other
team has the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tomjanovich said: ``They had a very aggressive offensive
game, and by the time we got them under control, it was too late.
Their team was a little better than our team was today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
