<SLUG> BC-NY-TRUMP-CONGRESS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BARS FUNDS TO IMPROVE LAND NEAR TRUMP PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a slight to Donald Trump, the House of Representatives voted
late Wednesday against the use of federal highway funds to move a
stretch of a New York City roadway that is next to Trump's luxury
condominium project, now being built on Manhattan's Upper West
Side.
</P>
<P>
   But Trump responded that the road suits him fine where it is.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice vote, the House approved a one-sentence amendment to
its transportation appropriation bill for the next fiscal year that
bars the use of any of the money for improvements to the stretch of
the West Side Highway near Trump's project, Riverside South.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was proposed by an opponent to Trump's plan, Rep.
Jerrold Nadler, a Democrat from the Upper West Side. He said the
highway relocation was an effort by Trump to ``subvert hundreds of
millions of dollars of taxpayer funds'' for his personal benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler failed to kill a $6 million study of the project that
Congress approved earlier this year as part of the largest
public-works program in the nation's history. The study is to
include an examination of design and engineering options for moving
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the highway would clear the way for a 21.5-acre park to
be included in Riverside South.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler said that moving the highway would enhance the view of
the Hudson River from the project's apartments and condominiums,
allowing Trump to charge higher prices and arrange more favorable
financing for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is also controversial because the part of the
highway that would have been moved was just renovated about three
years ago at a cost of $80 million, and has an estimated life of at
least 35 years, according to Nadler's office.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the federal government denied Trump's application for
government mortgage insurance for the next phase of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, Trump declared victory after learning
about the latest vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is a much simpler one for me if we leave the highway
in place,'' he said. ``It's not a highway issue. It's a park
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump said the highway would not affect the view from his
high-rise condominium project, and said he is getting fabulous
rents for the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Nadler is my best friend, economically,'' Trump said.
``He's played right into my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadler replied that Trump's response is belied by his efforts to
get federal funds for the project. But he acknowledged that Trump
and his supporters could seek funds again in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sue Kelly, R-N.Y., had requested the funds for the study
project and said Thursday that moving the highway continues to
enjoy ``broad support among local civic, labor, environmental and
business groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The amendment will be reviewed later this year by the conference
committee that will reconcile the House and Senate transportation
bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
