<SLUG> BC-NJ-OPEN-SPACE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. LEGISLATORS APPROVE OPEN-SPACE BALLOT MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ In one of the nation's most ambitious efforts to
preserve vanishing farmland and woodlands, the New Jersey
Legislature passed a ballot measure Thursday that will ask voters
in November to approve borrowing $1 billion to protect half of the
state's remaining 2 million acres of undeveloped land over the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a major political triumph for Gov. Christie
Whitman, who had made preserving 1 million acres of open space the
top priority of her second term. It came just days after members of
her own party dealt her a major blow by rejecting her other top
priority: an increase of 4 cents a gallon in the gasoline tax, to
be phased in over three years, for mass transit and highway
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman outlined her proposal to preserve open space in her
inaugural speech in January to address mounting concern from
residents and local officials about the impact of rapid development
on the state's landscape and the quality of life in fast-growing
towns.
</P>
<P>
   She said she realized that dramatic steps had to be taken
because, traveling around the state in her first term, she could
see that much of the state's rural character was quickly
disappearing because of development pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal officials across New Jersey had embraced development
for years, mainly to expand their property tax bases. But now a
growing number of local officials are finding that unchecked growth
is driving up local property taxes and causing traffic congestion
and overcrowded public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people see what is happening around them,'' said Michael
Catania, executive director of the Nature Conservancy of New
Jersey, a nonprofit organization that has helped protect
environmentally sensitive lands from development for more than a
decade. ``They see what is being lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Although New Jersey voters have strongly supported open-space
bond referendums in the past, Whitman said that she would campaign
aggressively during the next several months to win voter approval
for this measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the bill unanimously; the General Assembly
voted 70-3 in favor, with little debate. Supporters in the
Legislature described the resolution as one of the most important
initiatives for the state's future.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Republican leaders rejected Whitman's initial
proposal to pay for the preservation of 1 million acres with a
gasoline tax increase of 2 cents a gallon. Whitman agreed instead
to push for legislative approval of a bond referendum that asked
voters to consider the $1 billion borrowing plan.
</P>
<P>
   But she continued to fight for a 4-cents-a-gallon gasoline tax
increase for transportation projects until Republican legislative
leaders in the Assembly canceled a scheduled vote on it this week
because it lacked bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Democrats, who had banded together on Monday to oppose
the gasoline tax, considered trying to block the open space
legislation Thursday to hand Whitman yet another setback. But
statewide polls have consistently shown that protecting the
environment and open space has ranked high among New Jersey voters'
priorities, making the bill politically impossible for most
Democrats to dismiss. Democrats, in the end, voted overwhelmingly
in both houses for the measure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since 1961, New Jersey voters have approved nine bond
referendums that have raised $1.39 billion to help protect more
than 400,000 acres of farmland and other land from development.
Also, 53 New Jersey towns and 13 counties have approved tax
increases that range from 1 to 5 cents on each $100 of assessed
property value to protect undeveloped land.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the state has permanently preserved 922,000
acres from development out of a total of 4.8 million acres of land
in New Jersey. Preserving an additional million acres of open
space, including 500,000 acres of farmland, would mean that almost
2 million acres statewide _ two-fifths of the state _ would be
protected from development.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are looking to provide matching funds to towns
and counties that come forward with plans to protect farmland or
turn other undeveloped land into parks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the state would spend the proceeds from the
$1 billion bond issue, along with $450 million from sales tax
revenue, to preserve 1 million acres of open space over the next 10
years. The referendum would not increase the sales tax, but would
dedicate sales tax revenue for the land acquisition and for
repayment of the borrowing costs. It would take 30 years to repay
the debt, which with interest is estimated to total between $2.5
billion and $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's open space proposal, and her renewed commitment to a
statewide master plan, have caused some concern among developers
who point out that they are building residential developments in
outlying areas in response to market demand.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick O'Keefe, head of the New Jersey Builders Association,
said that the association had no position on the resolution adopted
by the Legislature Thursday. He pointed out that the association
had supported smaller bond referendums for open-space protection in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at some point,'' O'Keefe said, ``the administration will
have to take out a map and show us which million acres they are
talking about, and I think at that point, it will be a much more
meaningful discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Council on New Jersey Outdoors, which recommended
to Whitman late last year that the state protect a million acres,
has suggested that the state preserve 500,000 acres of farmland,
200,000 acres of open space for recreation, 100,000 acres for
watershed protection and 200,000 acres for greenways, trails and
corridors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-98 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
