<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLISEUM-APPRAISAL     07-30 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLISEUM-APPRAISAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPRAISAL: CHANGING VISIONS OF PUBLIC ARCHITECTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More jazz, please. Less Colossi of Memnon. With less
reverence toward history and more susceptibility to rhythm, the new
plan to develop the Coliseum site on Columbus Circle could become
the architectural breakthrough New York has been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by David Childs of Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill, the plan
is a thoroughly reworked version of the scheme Childs prepared in
the 1980s for the original developer of the Coliseum site, Mortimer
Zuckerman. That plan, which aroused opposition from civic groups
because of its size, was an explicit homage to the Century and the
Majestic, Irwin Chanin's great twin-towered apartment buildings on
Central Park West.
</P>
<P>
   Childs' new design retains the old version's basic Art Deco
silhouette. But instead of sheathing the project's two towers with
masonry, the architect now proposes to dress them in glass. This is
a major improvement, one that will open up this potentially hulking
project to reflections of sky, light and space.
</P>
<P>
   This plan was chosen for financial, not esthetic, reasons. With
Time Warner pledged to come in as the building's major commercial
tenant, the Related Companies offered the most substantial deal to
develop the site. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani deserves major credit for
the decision to create a theater in the building's base that will
be the permanent home for Jazz at Lincoln Center. It's not possible
to imagine a better site to build a place for jazz. Chistopher
Columbus, when he sailed west, may not have known that he was
venturing forth to discover jazz. Four centuries later, we are
somewhat more informed. We know that jazz is one of this
continent's greatest gifts to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is the essential art form of a modern democratic society.
Jazz is urban, ethnically diverse, collaborative and mutable. It
will be fantastic to enter a jazz hall beneath the pillar with
Columbus standing on top. This guy insisted that Europeans explore
new worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Above the Jazz Theater will rise a base dedicated to shops,
movie theaters, restaurants and other commercial uses. Time Warner
will occupy the next highest level in this stacked, vertical city.
The two towers, rising to a relatively discreet height of 750 feet,
have been planned for residential use: apartments and a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is much building going on in New York City these
days, there is little evidence of daring. When did New York
architecture become the screen for the projections of fearful
people? Decision makers who sit on boards like the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority and the New York City Planning Commission
seem to envision themselves as bunny rabbits scuttling around in
small cages of their own making. Evidently, the best we can hope
for from such people is a quality that they take to be dignity but
the rest of us recognize as failure of nerve.
</P>
<P>
   A design like this one happens not because an architect
genuinely believes in it, but because somebody thinks that this is
something that somebody else wants. Since this project is not, in
fact, a genuine public work, but a private enterprise that will
occupy a publicly conspicuous site, there is enormous pressure to
make the architecture strive for an approximation of dignity. The
result is a design that will play no role in the cultural life of
New York or the history of architecture. It is skillful, earnest
and devoid of meaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
