<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES--NYT </SLUG>
  
 METS LOSE TO PADRES IN 10th, 3-1  
(mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine did everything he could to get Bobby
Jones a victory. The Mets' manager even let his starting pitcher
bat for himself leading off the eighth inning of a 1-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much Jones deserved something better than a
no-decision, the Mets' hitters could not help their starter. And,
after Dennis Cook allowed a two-out, two-run double to pinch-hitter
Carlos Hernandez in the top of the 10th inning, the Mets had not
only lost, 3-1, to the San Diego Padres at Shea Stadium Thursday
night, they had also squandered an opportunity to pull back to
within two games of the Chicago Cubs in the National League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Cook created his own jam when he hit the former Yankee Jim
Leyritz with a pitch with one out in the 10th. One out later, Chris
Gomez moved the pinch-runner Andy Sheets to third with a single,
his third hit of the game. And then Hernandez drilled a 3-2 pitch
to the gap in left-center for what proved to be the winning runs,
as the Mets fell to 3-7 in extra innings this season. Trevor
Hoffman pitched a 1-2-3 10th for his 34th save.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was just the third in the last 11 games for the Mets
(56-49), who could have completed a three-game sweep of the NL
West-leading Padres if they could have scored just one more run for
Jones after Mike Piazza's second-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has now won only three of his last 17 starts at Shea,
dating to June 1997. And he has not won at all since July 2.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night the right-hander deserved better than his
third consecutive no-decision. He pitched nine dominant innings
with perhaps his best curve of the season, and he still left with
nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   The only run Jones allowed was in the third, on Gomez's leadoff
double and Quilvio Veras' one-out single to right, which kicked off
the heel of Butch Huskey's glove as he charged the ball and
prepared to throw home. That tied the score at 1-1, and negated the
472-foot home run Piazza hit to left to lead off the bottom of the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Jones allowed only four other hits. Two were to Tony Gwynn, one
was to Leyritz and the other was to Gomez, leading off the eighth
of what was still a 1-1 game. Piazza, however, threw out Gomez on
what looked to be a botched hit-and-run attempt with San Diego
starter Sterling Hitchcock at the plate. Luis Lopez, who was
starting at short again for the injured Rey Ordonez _ Ordonez came
in as a defensive replacement in the 10th _ made a sensational
short-hop pick of the throw and then tagged out Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who at one point had struck out five Padres in a row,
then struck out Hitchcock swinging and Veras looking for his ninth
and 10th strikeouts of the game to tie his career high.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine let Jones bat for himself to lead off the bottom of
the eighth. The Mets' offense was sputtering against Hitchcock, who
proceeded to set the Mets down in order for the fourth time, as the
teams headed into the ninth still tied.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock had basically matched Jones pitch for pitch. Aside
from Piazza's second mammoth homer in as many nights, Hitchcock
stifled the Mets. Their only hits through eight innings were a pair
of two-out singles by Carlos Baerga (one in the second and one in
the seventh), and a two-out fourth-inning double by Butch Huskey,
whom Hitchcock left stranded on second after striking out Bernard
Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock finally departed after allowing a lead-off single to
John Olerud to open the bottom of the ninth. The hit extended
Olerud's hitting streak to 13 games, currently the longest in the
National League. But reliever Dan Miceli came on and struck out
Piazza and Huskey in succession, before retiring Gilkey on a
harmless grounder to third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
