<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-30 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Series veterans 
show rare form 
against Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It's possible to count on both hands the number of players
remaining from the Florida Marlins' World Series championship team
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Astros, Livan Hernandez and Cliff Floyd
are among them.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez pitched a five-hitter and Floyd smacked a three-run
homer Thursday afternoon as the Marlins avoided a sweep with a 4-3
victory over the Astros in front of a crowd of 33,303 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The broomsticks remained in the closet, as the Astros could not
complete their first sweep of a four-game series in more than a
year. The last time the Astros swept a four-game series was July
24-27, 1997, against the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to lose a close game; it always is,'' said
manager Larry Dierker, whose club dropped to 18-13 in one-run games
this season. ``You can think of a lot of things that could put you
in the winner's column.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez (9-7), the Most Valuable Player of last year's World
Series, had a lot to do with that. The righthander retired the
first six batters before Tony Eusebio hit his first home run of the
season on a 2-0 pitch to start the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez struck out seven and walked three in his sixth
complete game, third-most in the National League, in shutting down
an Astros offense that had outscored the Marlins 35-14 in five wins
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The top five spots in the Astros' batting order went a combined
1-for-17 with one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have to give Hernandez a lot of credit,'' Dierker
said. ``That guy was tough. The way we had been swinging the bat,
to hold us to five hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is 2-1 with a 2.24 ERA in three career starts against
the Astros, allowing only six earned runs in 24 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very difficult and good team,'' said Hernandez, who
struck out Ricky Gutierrez with runners on first and second to end
the game. ``I was just trying to change my pitches, change speeds
and keep him (Astros left fielder Moises Alou) from hitting home
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who entered the game batting .556 against his former team
this season, was 0-for-2 with two walks and had his streak of
consecutive games with a home run snapped at four, one shy of the
club record.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Shane Reynolds (12-7) spotted the Marlins a
3-0 lead in the first inning before many in the Astrodome had found
their seats. Edgar Renteria singled with one out and stole second,
and after Mark Kotsay struck out, Todd Zeile walked. Cliff Floyd's
15th home run of the season, which came on an 0-2 pitch, gave the
Marlins a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After the Marlins' quick start, Reynolds retired 10 batters in a
row until Craig Counsell's leadoff single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with (my performance), but I kept the team close
and gave them some innings,'' said Reynolds, who after winning five
straight decisions has lost his past two. ``It's tough to beat them
four straight games and tough to go against their best.''
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio's solo homer pulled the Astros within 3-1. It also
snapped the longest homerless drought on the club _ a string of 191
at-bats for Eusebio dating to June 6, 1997, against San Diego's
Fernando Valenzuela.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point of the game came in the fifth inning. Counsell
beat out an infield hit when his grounder to first base was fielded
by Jeff Bagwell, who had no chance to complete the play as Reynolds
was slow off the mound to cover the base.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, it was downhill from there. Second baseman Craig
Biggio committed his 11th error of the season (he had 10 or fewer
in three of the past four seasons) when he couldn't handle a throw
from Gutierrez for what likely would have been a double play. Todd
Dunwoody sent a double to left field that Alou dropped as he
approached the wall, scoring Counsell from second base to make it
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What hurt the most was not covering first base,'' Dierker
said. ``That's something we start on the first day of spring
training. That could have saved us a run or at least put us in a
tie situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett added his 11th home run of the season in the fifth,
and Bill Spiers doubled and scored on Bagwell's sacrifice fly to
center field in the sixth to trim the Marlins' lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, one of only eight Marlins remaining from last year's
club, allowed only one hit over the final three innings and worked
out of a jam in the ninth after walking Alou and allowing Eusebio's
infield hit. He ended the game by getting a called third strike on
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Hernandez) had his best stuff, but he did what
he had to do,'' Everett said. ``We didn't take advantage of all the
hangers he threw. So you give him credit because he continued to do
it, and we continued not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida ended its 10-game road trip 2-8. A year after winning
the World Series, the Marlins are on pace to lose the most games by
a defending champion in major-league history. The 70 losses by the
Marlins match their total from all of last season, when they
finished 92-70 to clinch the NL's wild-card spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
