<HEADER>
A1632 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      07-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big-time gamble &QL; 
always entails risk
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HIS bag was on the bus, but Gerry Hunsicker lugged it off. There's
enough of a chance the Astros can pull off a trade today that the
general manager decided to stay here and work the phones from his
office, rather than try to juggle dozens of calls from a Pittsburgh
hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker's U-turn of sorts doesn't mean anything involving
Roger Clemens, Todd Stottlemyre or the Big Unit himself, Randy
Johnson, et al., is imminent, but it does mean hope springs eternal
in the GM's breast.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good. Because it definitely continues to spring in the
Astros' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros let one get away to the mealy Marlins on Thursday
afternoon, and Francisco Cordova, against whom they didn't hit a
lick last season, will throw for the Pirates tonight. Hence, there
seemed to be just a pinch more urgency in the voices of the veteran
Astros regarding Hunsicker's doing of a meaningful deal before the
clock strikes midnight in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Craig Biggios and the Jeff Bagwells are realists. They know
the Astros as they are presently constituted, no matter how well
they have performed to stay atop the Central Division for most of
the season, are teetering along on a tightrope. Particularly with
their two established arms _ Shane Reynolds' right one and Mike
Hampton's left _ having been underwhelming of late.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with the Braves
</P>
<P>
   There's minimal margin for error as far as reaching the playoffs
is concerned, and once into October, the Astros can hardly be
judged the equal of Atlanta or San Diego in a best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've both got the three horses,'' Biggio said of the
Padres' and the Braves' starting rotations.
</P>
<P>
   So somehow, some way, the Astros must reel in a pitcher of the
caliber of the aforementioned. M-U-S-T.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years of this franchise,'' Biggio said, ``they've
hung only three (division-championship) banners from that roof.
Sometimes, when you've got a chance to win _ and this team does _
you just have to roll the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hunsicker can't, or won't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably say, `damn,''' Biggio admitted. ``Sure, I'll be
disappointed. I really don't want to hear about losing prospects
for the future. I want to win now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry does, too. The GM doesn't need his bifocals to see the
window of opportunity the Astros have opened for themselves with
one of baseball's fiercest every-day lineups. But he's quick to
remind how trading under the gun of the deadline is ``high-stakes
poker,'' and sometimes you do lose your shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Plus a Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, everybody who's willing to chat with the Astros
brings up Elarton, the organization's ranking whiz kid, and Richard
Hidalgo pretty quickly in the conversation. Yet who's to say
Johnson or Clemens or Stottlemyre will come in and help deliver the
Astros unto the World Series, the only goal worth shooting for?
</P>
<P>
   Remember how badly Stottlemyre stunk up things in the playoffs a
couple of years ago? And how about Johnson's feeble efforts against
Baltimore? And what, pray tell, has Clemens accomplished in the
postseason?
</P>
<P>
   These are not easy decisions. But I'm with Biggio. If there's a
deal that's doable for a high-impact pitcher _ no, Pete Harnisch
doesn't qualify _ it's imperative it gets done.
</P>
<P>
   Randy, Rocket or Todd?
</P>
<P>
   Clemens would be my first choice for a number of no-brainer
reasons, not the least of which is his contract doesn't expire at
the end of the season. And his returning to Houston would almost
match the magnitude of Nolan Ryan's long-ago homecoming. Just
because Doug Drabek and Greg Swindell failed to pay pennant-winning
dividends doesn't mean homeboys must forever be spurned.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Toronto isn't aggressively shopping the Rocket as
the Mariners are Johnson, who is desperately unhappy in Seattle and
counting the hours until he gains his freedom. He would be a
short-term hired gun, nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   The short term is all we're guaranteed, though. Elarton, as
stout as he appears, is no sure thing. He's a pitcher, for cripes'
sake. Stuff happens to pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a solid-enough ballclub to win our division with the
players we have,'' manager Larry Dierker said when asked for his
two-cents' worth. ``If we don't win it, it will be our fault. But
obviously, I'd like to see us do something if the price is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Except the price is never right in these situations. The team
with the commodity sits there smugly while the team badly needing
same fusses, fidgets and sweats. At least the rich clubs can afford
to gamble and lose. They can throw money at the problem next season
to fix it. But if the Astros do the wrong thing, if their costly
``savior'' isn't one, there's no mulligan. The damage stays done.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Hunsicker stayed home. That hotel room might have
gotten pretty lonely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
