<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-30 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-VETO-NYT &LR;      07-30 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-VETO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI VETOES BILL BACKED BY VALLONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A centerpiece of Peter Vallone's campaign for
governor, a bill allowing New York cities to give preference to
in-state contractors over those from other states, has been vetoed
by Gov. George Pataki, whom Vallone hopes to oppose in November.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said in his veto message, dated Wednesday and made public
Thursday, that while he commended the bill's aim of promoting
business in New York state, it would actually hurt in-state
businesses by triggering a trade war with other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since New York state businesses are net exporters of goods and
services,'' the governor wrote, ``this bill will have a negative
impact on New York businesses seeking to contract in other states
and engender results contrary to the bill's stated purpose of
promoting economic development in New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vallone, the Democratic speaker of the New York City
Council, said the Republican governor's motivations were political.
``This is a case of, if I say yes, the governor is going to say
no,'' he said. ``And you have a governor who wants to run for
president, and he's not going to do anything to upset business
people in other states who would oppose this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who left Thursday on a three-day fund-raising trip to
Colorado and California, was not available for comment. But a
spokesman, Charles Deister, said that Vallone ``doesn't have a
basic grasp on the facts,'' adding that the bill ``will cost jobs,
instead of creating jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the bill illustrates a broad theme of this
race: Pataki says that after three and a half years under him, the
state is doing well economically, while his four Democratic rivals
assert that New York continues to lag far behind the national boom
and that drastic policy changes are needed. The other Democrats in
the race are Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross, Brooklyn District
Attorney Charles Hynes and James Larocca, a former state
commissioner of energy and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The veto is more significant in the wake of a ruling early this
month by the Court of Appeals, New York's highest court, striking
down a provision in the New York City Charter that allows the city
to bypass the usual rule requiring that government contracts go to
the lowest responsible bidder.
</P>
<P>
   New York City has for years given preference to contractors
based in the city, a policy that Vallone contends adds $1 billion a
year to the city's economy. The court decision outlawed that
practice, but the bill passed by the Legislature in June would have
effectively resurrected it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, passed with broad bipartisan support, would have
allowed a local government to bypass an out-of-state contractor who
submitted the low bid, and instead choose an in-state contractor,
as long as the New York company submitted a bid no more than 5
percent higher than the low bid.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Vallone has made the contracting preference a
prominent part of his economic plan, saying that as governor, he
would make it state policy. Meanwhile, he sought to make an
in-state preference city policy.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone had planned to have the Council pass a bill next Tuesday
taking advantage of the new state law, to make it city policy.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, opposed the plan and would
have vetoed it, but Vallone clearly had the votes to override a
veto.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Vallone appeared at the site of a planned bridge
across the Niagara River linking Buffalo and the Canadian city of
Fort Erie, to call on Pataki to give preference to New York
contractors in the bidding to build the span.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's try to do it in Buffalo, hire a Buffalo contractor, keep
the jobs in Buffalo,'' he said in an interview, after the event.
``I never believed that the governor would veto this. It's putting
the state at such a disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Business Council of New York State, the state's largest
large-business group, opposed the bill for the same reason given by
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's veto message also said that the bill was poorly
written, failing to make it clear that when an out-of-state bidder
is bypassed, a contract must go to the lowest in-state bidder. He
also contended that the bill was in conflict with federal law,
which requires that any project built with federal money go to the
lowest responsible bidder.
</P>
</TEXT>
